<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLPEN COLLAPSES, SO POSADA AND MARTINEZ SAVE YANKS
</HEADLINE>
  By RAFAEL HERMOSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three previous times on this homestand, the New York
Yankees watched their bullpen squander late leads and produce the
demoralizing losses that come with blown saves.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees witnessed a fourth failure Wednesday night. For a
change, they rallied back.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton and Jeff Nelson laid the groundwork for a demise,
but Jorge Posada hit a tying two-run homer in the eighth inning and
Tino Martinez delivered a ninth-inning single that produced a 10-9
victory over the Texas Rangers at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Polonia led off the ninth with a single off Tim Crabtree
and Jose Vizcaino grounded a single past the drawn-in third baseman
Mike Lamb when he swung away at a 1-1 pitch. Vizcaino had squared
to bunt on the first two pitches. Jose Canseco grounded into an
apparent double play, but Luis Alicea's throw pulled Frank
Catalanotto off first base.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander Mike Venafro entered to face Martinez, who
grounded an 0-1 pitch just inside the first-base line and into
right field.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have struggled on this homestand, splitting the
previous six games, and manager Joe Torre has been frustrated
because he has sensed the team was ready to go on a long winning
streak several times. The Yanks gave their manager more cause for
worry Wednesday night as the baffling bullpen continued showing the
inability to close games.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in the past week, Yankees relievers blew a
sizeable lead and wasted a strong outing by a starter. Mariano
Rivera was responsible Friday, when he couldn't hold an 8-4 lead in
the ninth inning. Wednesday night, he worked out of a ninth-inning
jam for the victory after allowing a leadoff double.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, pitching on his fourth straight day, had a shouting
match with Torre on Sunday over not being allowed to work out of
his own jams. But he could blame no one but himself for Wednesday
night's performance. Stanton had already allowed Ricky Ledee's
three- run homer in the eighth inning. That wiped out a 7-4 lead
Roger Clemens helped to build.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson came in and Bill Haselman hit a squibber to the right of
the mound. Nelson ran over and reached down but couldn't grip the
ball. Haselman reached first on the error and Lamb tried to bunt
him over, but Posada nearly replicated Nelson's mistake by not
gripping the ball.
</P>
<P>
   A routine bunt then moved the runners to second and third before
Alicea grounded a single up the middle, ending Nelson's night.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens overcame his own rough start to pitch six innings. He
allowed four runs, but none after the third inning when he appeared
to rediscover his fastball. He struck out the side in the fifth
inning and finished with nine strikeouts and four walks.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' outfield alignment, meanwhile, could have caused
rubber necking. By the late innings, it featured Polonia in left
field, Clay Bellinger in center and Scott Brosius in right field.
Brosius, who won a Gold Glove award at third base last season, had
made one appearance in right field since joining the Yankees in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had been dominant since losing to the Mets June 9 at
Shea Stadium, posting a 2.54 ERA in his 10 starts leading into
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored twice off Clemens in the first inning, on a
double by Gabe Kapler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
