<SLUG> BC-PROP-BLAZE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZE GUTS HOME OF BUDWEISER FROGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The business that made those toylike Budweiser
frogs and chatty Foster Farms chickens for TV ads was gutted by a
swift-moving fire Wednesday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty firefighters battled the intense blaze at The Character
Shop for 75 minutes, struggling against flames feeding on resins,
acetone, spray paint and compressed gas used to create animated
figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had everything that firefighters dread. It was extremely
dangerous because of its toxicity,'' said Capt. Steve Ruda of the
Los Angeles Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   The chemicals and materials created heavy black smoke and
intense heat that partially collapsed the roof and a wall at the
business, fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Two firefighters and a worker from the shop were treated for
minor smoke inhalation injuries. Five LAPD officers and six
civilians were treated at the scene for minor smoke inhalation,
said Bob Collis, an LAFD spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a matter of about five minutes, it had already consumed
everything inside and gone through the roof,'' said Battalion Fire
Chief Thomas Brennan.
</P>
<P>
   The shop is known in the film and television industry for its
special effects, puppets, animatronics and prosthetics.
</P>
<P>
   Among its creations was the 8,000-pound pachyderm in the Disney
film ``Operation Dumbo Drop,'' according to firefighters and
business owners.
</P>
<P>
   Both the elephant and Foster Farms chickens were damaged in the
blaze, firefighters said. The cause of the fire was under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A life-size cow was among the few creations still intact among a
charred mess of metal that stretched about 100 feet across and 75
feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze started near the famed elephant, as employees worked
around flammable liquids, firefighters said. The employees tried to
knock down the blaze by using fire extinguishers, Brennan said, but
the flames overwhelmed them.
</P>
<P>
   The Character Shop's owner and employees declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said flames shot 40 feet above the shop's rooftop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was surprising how fast the flames came through,'' said Ben
Griffiths, a warehouse supervisor in one of four adjoining business
saved by firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Haren, who co-owns Architectural Security Products, two
doors from the gutted building, praised firefighters for keeping
flames away from his shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I drove up and realized where the flames were coming
from, my heart just stopped. I was thinking it was the end of my
business and my mom just died, and I didn't want another thing like
this to happen,'' Haren said. ``They did a great job, incredible.
They saved our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Haren's and three other businesses had some water and smoke
damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
