<SLUG> BC-TEN-HAMLET-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPARING FOR OPEN, NORMAN WINS MATCH
</HEADLINE>
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMACK, N.Y. _ After winning his first hardcourt title as an
unseeded player in last year's Hamlet Cup, Magnus Norman reached
the fourth round of the U.S. Open before a back injury forced him
to withdraw. It was his best showing in a Grand Slam event to that
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so confident coming from a win here, I was hitting so
well, it was a shame I had to withdraw,'' Norman said on Wednesday
after dispatching Jonas Bjorkman, 6-4, 6-1, in the Hamlet Cup.
``But I think I'm a better player this year. I'm much better in big
tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman, a 24-year-old Swede who is ranked No. 3 in the world and
seeded third for the Open, has won three titles this year: at
Auckland, New Zealand, Rome, and Bastad, Sweden. He also reached
the semifinals of the Australian Open and the final of the French
Open, where he lost to Gustavo Kuerten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think about that,'' Norman said. ``I got off to a
slow start in the French, going down, 0-2, after an hour. But after
that I played well. I think my results this year have been the
result of a lot of hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday he took just 1 hour 12 minutes to get past
Bjorkman, his fellow Swede, dominating throughout as he won 20 of
24 first-serve points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my best match so far this year,'' Norman said. ``I'm
moving good, feeling good. I'm going to work hard this weekend. I'm
definitely ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could not be said of No. 2-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov of
Russia, who was eliminated in straight sets, 6-1, 6-3, by Karol
Kucera of the Czech Republic in another second-round match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to win every match,'' Kafelnikov said. ``Maybe
in the back of my mind I'm trying to save energy for the Grand
Slam. I'm sure I'll be ready for the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   In the only other match completed before a rain delay, Fernando
Meligeni, a qualifier from Brazil, upset ninth-seeded Albert Costa
of Spain, 3-6, 6-3, 6-2. Arnaud Clement, seeded 15th, was leading
George Bastl in the third set and No. 5 Cedric Pioline was down a
set to Andrei Pavel before play was interrupted.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
