<HEADER>
A0704 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ASTHMA-AZR &LR;      08-24 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTHMA-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-ASTHMA-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    EXPOSURE TO GERMS MAY HELP AVERT ASTHMA(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KETTY FEHR-SNYDER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Babies who swap germs in day care or with siblings
are roughly half as likely to develop asthma later in life, says a
sweeping new study, furthering the idea that Americans are becoming
too clean for their own good.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Arizona findings, appearing today in the
(beginitalic)New England Journal of Medicine(enditalic), are part
of the world's longest-running study of childhood respiratory
illnesses and support recent studies showing that children benefit
from minor colds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It now appears (children) need to get messages from microbes
in their environment to develop healthy immune systems,'' said
Thomas Ball, a pediatrician and the lead author of the UA study.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 20 years, UA researchers have been following more
than 1,000 children born healthy in Tucson to study what triggers
allergies or asthma later in life. Known as the Tucson Children's
Respiratory Study, the project previously has linked cigarette
smoking by adults to asthma in children, and bottle feeding with
ear infections.
</P>
<P>
   Today's study of 1,035 children analyzed asthma rates of babies
who spent time in day care or around older siblings. Researchers
found children were 40 percent more likely to develop asthma if
they were not exposed in their first six to 12 months of life to
other kids in day care, play groups or even brothers or sisters in
their own families. The study didn't surprise the UA researchers,
especially Ball, who recently spent a year in rural Africa and
realized that none of the children there had asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``That got me thinking about the whole `hygiene hypothesis,'''
Ball said.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is a growing problem worldwide, especially in developed
countries. More than 17 million Americans, including 316,000 in
Arizona, are afflicted with the respiratory disease.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe the ailment is partially inherited and
partially caused by environmental factors. Although the findings
mesh with two recent German studies, they also seem to contradict
other evidence that asthma is growing among inner-city poor
children raised in dirty environments with cockroaches, dust mites
and other allergens.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Wright, one of the study's authors, said the contradiction
lies in the fact that not all bacteria are created equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complex picture, but when we talk about
cleanliness, we mean a lot of different things,'' she said. Germs
from cockroaches, for example, are not considered ``gram-negative
bacteria'' like those found in feces, livestock and other organisms
that seem to protect children from asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past 100 years, we have fundamentally changed our
relationship with microorganisms,'' Wright said, noting the demise
of the family farm, rural life and the growth of antibacterial
products. ``It looks like day care is kind of making up for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the findings seem to suggest babies not currently in
day care should be enrolled to bolster their immune system, the
researchers stopped short of recommending such a move in all cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a pediatrician, I cannot make a generic recommendation for
every child,'' Ball said. But in some cases, putting small children
in day care ``might actually be beneficial to them for preventing
allergies and asthma later on.''
</P>
<P>
   They also said the findings suggest it may not be so bad to keep
a messy house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is what is clean?'' Wright said. ``Maybe we don't
have to worry so much about hygiene. Maybe we've gone overboard
with our anti-bacterial soap.''
</P>
<P>
   James Lee, a prominent asthma researcher at the Mayo Clinic in
Scottsdale, agrees with the study findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exposure to organisms should have the effect of the immune
system revving up to deal with other pathogens in the world,'' said
Lee, who is studying the genetic component of asthma.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that the UA study doesn't explain the entire
asthma picture.
</P>
<P>
   The study, paid for by the non-profit National Heart, Lung and
Blood Institute, also did little to convince one mother that she
should have put her asthmatic son in day care as a baby.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she regretted keeping 6-year-old Matthew out of
day care, Lavonda Session of Phoenix said, ``Not at all, because
kids in day care are always getting sick.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
