<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC FRESHMAN HOLMES WILL PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ Eight true freshmen will accompany USC to the
Kickoff Classic to play Penn State, and none is more excited than
tight end Alex Holmes of Harvard-Westlake High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm unbelievably excited. I can't wait,'' said Holmes, who
will play a central part in USC's double-tight end offense. ``I am
bursting at the seams.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, who was primarily a pass-catcher at Harvard-Westlake,
has become a more-versatile player during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm much more prepared than when I played in high
school,'' Holmes said. ``I learned to block in camp. I didn't
really have to do that before.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, though, Holmes' forte is receiving. It's the primary
role he'll have whenever he is used as the Trojans' second tight
end, and he is expected to be a viable part of the offense in the
season-opener.
</P>
<P>
   Another pass-catching tight end, true freshman Gregg Guenther of
Taft, said his sore back has recovered and he is available to play
against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Malik gets start: The defensive line has been an area with
some of USC's toughest competition, but senior Sultan Abdul-Malik
has edged out junior Lonnie Ford for a starting position against
Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Ford could split time equally with Abdul-Malik, though, because
the Trojans will rotate linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Another player who has made a move is tackle Bobby DeMars of
Westlake High. DeMars is the fourth tackle, the highest he has been
on the depth chart, and will probably see some action against Penn
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves his chance,'' defensive line coach Ed Orgeron
said.
</P>
<P>
   Early payday: USC will clear more than $700,000 from the Kickoff
Classic, which is about the same amount the Trojans made from the
1996 game.
</P>
<P>
   Trading places: Hackett said tailbacks Sultan McCullough and
Malaefou MacKenzie would probably alternate series against Penn
State, although McCullough is expected to start.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Feeling good:!off! The Trojans were in high spirits as
they finally broke camp Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the work ethic and work level was outstanding,''
Hackett said. ``From what we've demanded from them, they gave us
what we wanted. It's a very confident team that leaves camp.''
</P>
<P>
   It was USC's longest stay in Irvine (2 weeks), and the Trojans
were thrilled to be leaving and heading back to campus Wednesday
night, before leaving for New Jersey today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been here a little too long,'' quarterback Carson Palmer
said. ``We're ready to get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   It's official: Ending what was the worst-kept secret of training
camp, Hackett officially announced that junior David Newbury would
handle place-kicking duties, beating out senior David Bell and
freshman John Wall of Birmingham High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (Newbury) I'm not going to make a change, you go do
it,'' Hackett said. ``I feel good. He's ready to have a strong
year. I don't imagine we'll be trying 50-yard field goals, so he
keeps his confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell will still handle kickoffs for the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   On the plane: Senior offensive guard Trevor Roberts (strained
foot) will not suit up but will attend the Penn State game. He is
tentatively scheduled to return for the Colorado game on Sept. 9,
but it is possible he won't play until the Sept. 23 contest with
San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   Practice schedule: Hackett said the Trojans would probably
practice only 30 minutes in New Jersey on Friday, and one hour
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to do much,'' he said. ``We've got to polish
up. We need to keep our legs fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Walk-ons honored: Wide receiver Matt Nickels and linebacker Ryan
Shapiro were awarded scholarships by Hackett, in his tradition of
giving at least one walk-on a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Nickels, a senior and former teammate of Palmer at Santa
Margarita, is currently considered the Trojans' No. 3 receiver,
although sophomore Steve Stevenson and freshman Keary Colbert are
likely to be used just as much against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro is a senior who played at Carson High.
</P>
</TEXT>
