<HEADLINE>
REGIS HAWKS NEW LINE OF SHIRTS, TIES IN VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ America's No. 1 pop culture icon dazzled Wednesday
with his million-dollar smile, twinkling eyes and untiring
sincerity as he basked in the adoration of his fans young and old.
</P>
<P>
   Some chanted, ``Regis ... Regis ... Regis ... you're our man!''
while others screamed and applauded as Regis Philbin, host of ``Who
Wants To Be A Millionaire'' pitched a new line of Van Heusen shirts
and ties that bear his name.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 people already were lined up in Macy's at the Sherman
Oaks Fashion Square when the store opened at 10 a.m., three hours
before Philbin arrived.
</P>
<P>
   There was Elma Wallace of Bel-Air who boasted she was first to
arrive at 9 a.m. and 85-year-old Betty Salomon of Sherman Oaks who
wore head-to-toe-pink to meet Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says it's my best color,'' she said, ``and you know,
there's only one Reege. He's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Another early bird was 67-year-old Marie Nolan of Northridge,
who said she's been a fan since 1977.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've brought pictures of him from his early days, plus I
bought a new Regis tie for him to sign,'' Nolan said.
</P>
<P>
   When Philbin, 65, looked at her photo collection, he shouted,
``Oh my God,'' and held the pictures from his pre-icon years up to
his face as fans snapped photos.
</P>
<P>
   Once an NBC page seating guests on Steve Allen's ``Tonight
Show'' nearly 50 years ago, Philbin has been a sportscaster, news
anchor, late-show personality and ``The Morning Show'' host with
Kathie Lee Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   He clearly relished his new role as superstar posing with young
mothers with their babies and a little boy dressed like him in a
blue shirt and tie, shaking hands with businessmen buying into the
Regis look and autographing a pair of black ties for 15-year-old
Agoura Hills residents Daniel Steinman and Lauren Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not square. He's smarter, more sophisticated than other
game show hosts and he dresses really well,'' Steinman said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Goldstein: ``I don't see Regis as old and I love his
'final answer' quote, but also like his morning show. I saw Darva
Conger try out for Kathie Lee's job and I think she'd be good for
Regis.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Byrd, 54, of Bellflower explained why she's been a fan for
16 years. ``He's very natural, not afraid to speak out, and would
do well to pick Marie Osmond for his next co-host.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, like 41-year-old Misak Balyan of Pasadena, made the
celeb's personal appearance a family outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all love the 'Millionaire' show, so I surprised the
children by bringing them,'' Balyan said.
</P>
<P>
   His 10-year-old daughter, Mari, said she liked Regis because
``he's nice to the contestants even when they don't know the
answer,'' while her brother Artashes, 8, said he liked the game
show host's laugh. And also the Pokeman questions that he was able
to answer.
</P>
<P>
   During the long wait, fans shopped for shirts and ties, while
friends held their place in line. Macy's reported the silvery color
combo worn by Philbin that day was the bestseller, followed by an
eggplant number and Philbin's favorite, a navy blue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
