<SLUG> BC-EDWARDS-CLOSINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS FILES FOR BANKRUPTCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Edwards Theatres Circuit Inc. filed for bankruptcy
protection Wednesday and moved to close four of its outdated movie
houses amid mounting industry concern that the glut of multiplexes
far outstrips demand.
</P>
<P>
   The Newport Beach-based company said it will leave untouched its
remaining 70 theaters, including ones in Calabasas, Camarillo, Simi
Valley and Santa Clarita.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' move comes just two weeks after one of the nation's top
multiplex owners _ Carmike Cinemas Inc. of Columbus, Ga., with
about 2,750 screens _ also filed under Chapter 11.
</P>
<P>
   At least two other major chains are scrambling to restructure
their assets in a market that, analysts say, has built up to 50
percent more screens than the public can sustain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There became a fervor to do this and now the whole industry
has backed off, realizing that we probably went too fast,'' said
Stephen Coffey, president of Edwards Theatres, the nation's
11th-biggest chain, with 739 total screens.
</P>
<P>
   The industry added more than 3,000 screens to the U.S. market in
1999 alone, sharply accelerating the multiplex building boom that
started four years earlier. The industry believes multiplexes are
what the public wants _ theaters with 10, sometimes 20 or more
screens under one roof, Coffey said.
</P>
<P>
   The nation now has 37,185 screens, according to the National
Association of Theatre Owners in North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But by industry estimates, there is only enough business for
25,000 to 30,000 screens, Coffey said.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid expansion in multiplex construction over the past five
years coincided with a steady rise in average ticket prices and
movie admissions, although the latter dripped by 1 percent last
year after growing 6.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the industry added nearly 10,000 new screens from 1995
to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards Theatres helped pioneer the multiplex concept, opening
one of the nation's first such theaters in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The four Edwards Theatres being closed are in Stanton, San
Diego, Temecula and Rancho Cucamonga. Each was losing business to
newer theaters with more modern seating, sound and screens, company
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards Theatres, which also operates in Idaho and Texas, filed
voluntary petitions for reorganization under Chapter 11 as part of
a strategic restructuring of its debt and operations, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reviewing the various alternatives available, we
concluded that utilizing the Chapter 11 process to complete our
restructuring is in the best long-term interests of the company and
its constituents,'' said Chief Executive Office W. James Edwards
III.
</P>
<P>
   Coffey said the company had no immediate plans to close any
other theaters, but would inevitably do so as newer ones are built
to replace the aging movie houses.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, operations and movie screenings will continue
without interruption. The company plans to seek court approval to
honor policies regarding gift certificates, movie passes and other
customer programs.
</P>
<P>
   The voluntary petitions were filed in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in
Santa Ana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
