<HEADLINE>
AUGUST DOG DAYS CHALLENGING BUSH CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The campaign of Texas Gov. George W. Bush has long
predicted that the presidential race would tighten after the
summer's political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few people expected the dog days of August to be this cruel
to the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   In the six days since Vice President Al Gore accepted his
party's presidential nomination, Bush has lost his lead in seven
national polls, an advantage he had enjoyed since winter.
</P>
<P>
   On the hustings, Bush stepped into a hard-to-win dispute with
the only Republican member of the Clinton administration over the
readiness of the military, and acknowledged that he needs to ``do a
better job'' explaining the virtues of his signature $1.3 trillion
tax-cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   Never known for his verbal fluidity, Bush has had more
difficulty than usual with syntax and word choice, declaring in one
speech that ``Nothing can be further than the truth,'' mistaking
``hostile'' for ``hostage'' and ``terrors'' for ``tariffs'' and
suggesting that President Clinton had been in office for four years
rather than eight.
</P>
<P>
   And just Wednesday, Bush campaign officials stepped in at the
last minute to kill a Republican TV ad criticizing Gore for
defending President Clinton's honor _ a line of attack that has
backfired on every Republican who has tried it.
</P>
<P>
   There is no outward sign of alarm in Bush's Austin, Texas,
headquarters, where aides talk about the ebb and flow of campaigns.
Yet, as independent pollster Ken Warren observed from the Midwest
battleground state of Missouri: ``You'd better believe that some
Bush people are shaking in their boots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No question that Republicans have a lot more reason to be
concerned than they did a month ago,'' said Warren, who teaches
political science at St. Louis University. ``The worst-case
scenario for Republicans has come true.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Bush saw a comfortable lead slip away, he was
battling Sen. John McCain for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor regained his footing by appealing to his
party's conservative core and deploying his vast advantage over
McCain in money and organization.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, battling an increasingly populist vice
president, those options are simply not available.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the primaries, the battleground over the next 10 weeks
will be for swing and independent voters _ and each campaign has
roughly the same size war chest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, still a novice on the national political stage, faces the
daunting task of riding out a wave of unfavorable publicity and
re-establishing his image as a natural leader to win over voters
who say they are more closely aligned with Gore on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of patience'' said GOP strategist Rich
Galen. ``In any sport, the other guy gets the ball every once in a
while. Sometimes they score. It doesn't mean they are going to win
the game. The Bush campaign has to just keep plowing ahead, step by
step.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Bush is that Gore's lead is very small,
falling within the statistical margin of error in several polls.
</P>
<P>
   And history shows that the bounce a candidate receives after his
convention often doesn't last very long.
</P>
<P>
   President Carter jumped 10 points in the polls after the 1980
convention in New York before losing to Ronald Reagan. Four years
later, Walter Mondale jumped to within 2 percentage points of
Reagan after the Democratic gathering in San Francisco, only to
suffer the most lopsided electoral rout in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Warren said the polls that come out in late September should be
viewed far more seriously. While many candidates have lost
elections after strong conventions, only Harry Truman in 1948 came
back to win after trailing in late September.
</P>
<P>
   Bush embarks Thursday on a campaign swing that will take him to
Florida, where Republicans had thought they had a strong advantage.
Not only will Bush find Gore already stumping in the state, he may
get a firsthand glimpse of dark clouds even more ominous than those
some say are gathering over his campaign _ Tropical Storm Debby is
on course to hit the Florida coast by tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has been knocked down on a number of fronts,'' Warren
said. ``Now is when most people are paying attention. Now is when
he has to re-establish himself as a leader.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
