<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-LAST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 `SURVIVOR' KING RICHARD: HE'S TOUGH, HE'S RICH, HE NEEDS A SHOWER  &HT;     By JOHN CARMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In the words of one of the losing contestants, the snake ate the
rat Wednesday night in the conclusion of the summer TV phenomenon,
``Survivor.''
<P>
   Richard Hatch, a 39-year-old corporate trainer from Newport,
R.I., won the million-dollar grand prize in the show's two-hour
finale on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch won a 4-to-3 vote among the last seven contestants voted
off the island, defeating Nevada river guide Kelly Wiglesworth, 23.
</P>
<P>
   The show ended with hugs and handshakes around the ``tribal
council'' fire, and perhaps with gasps of surprise in living rooms
across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's victory seemed an upset. Though Hatch said in his final
plea to the jury that ``I think I played as ethically as is humanly
possible,'' he was the architect of the alliance that ousted most
of the players who went on to decide the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the jurors thought of Hatch the same way Martin Balsam's
character thought of Holly Golightly in the 1961 film ``Breakfast
at Tiffany's.'' ``She's a phony,'' Balsam said, ``but she's a  &UR; real
 &LR; phony.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch had barely survived ``tribal council'' balloting in the
program's eighth installment, when three players voted to eliminate
him.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch and his fellow castaways were in Los Angeles last night
for a live CBS ``town hall'' special after the finale.
</P>
<P>
   The last hour of ``Survivor'' was marked by sharp acrimony,
especially when Wisconsin truck driver Susan Hawk, 38, the first of
the four finalists voted out of the competition last night,
unloaded on her former friend Wiglesworth.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the other jurors and in the presence of the two
final competitors, Hawk said Hatch was ``a bit of a loser in
life,'' but then called Wiglesworth ``two-faced and manipulative.''
</P>
<P>
   If she encountered Wiglesworth dying of thirst, Hawk said,
glaring at Wiglesworth, ``I would not give you a drink of water.
I'd leave you to the vultures.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawk added that Pulau Tiga, the Malaysian island where the
series was filmed last spring, was ``pretty much full of only two
things, snakes and rats.'' She described Hatch as a snake and
Wiglesworth as a rat, and said that ``the snake eats the rat.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently stunned by Hawk's remarks, Wiglesworth argued that
``I don't think anybody in this game is without faults.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting as jurors, expelled players Hawk, Rudy Boesch, Sean
Kenniff and Greg Buis voted in favor of Hatch. Gervase Peterson,
Jenna Lewis and Colleen Haskell voted to award the million-dollar
prize to Wiglesworth.
</P>
<P>
   Wiglesworth won $100,000 for finishing second among the 16
contestants who swam to the island at the game's outset.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, who is gay and an avowed nudist, seemed most to embody
the scheming that characterized the reality show in its 13-week
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``My approach to the game was one of strategy from the
beginning. ... For me, instead of who's the better person, it is
about who played the game better,'' Hatch said in his argument to
the jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Casting his vote for Hatch, Kenniff said that ``Survivor'' had
become ``a contest of who's least objectionable'' and that Hatch
was ``just an out-and-out scoundrel, but I like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the four finalists, Hawk was voted out first on last
night's show after Wiglesworth won an ``immunity challenge'' that
involved recalling details about players who had lost earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Wiglesworth also won a second ``immunity challenge'' by walking
across a fire pit and then keeping a hand on a totem pole for four
hours and 11 minutes. She outlasted Hatch and the 72-year-old
Boesch in that contest.
</P>
<P>
   The victory and her resulting immunity enabled Wiglesworth to
choose between Hatch and Boesch. She voted to eliminate Boesch, who
later blamed his defeat on momentarily losing his grip on the pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have nothing to say to these two,'' Boesch, a retired
Navy SEAL, said at the final tribal council the next day. ``I just
want everybody to know how dumb I feel about a mistake I made
yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   The finale of executive producer Mark Burnett's real-life
amorality play was projected to attract the biggest television
audience of the summer, perhaps upward of 40 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after a hit Swedish television series, ``Survivor'' has
triggered an avalanche of reality concepts bought by U.S. networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' will return in January for a new round of shows,
set in the Australian outback.
</P>
<P>
   But first, CBS is expected to repeat the original 13 episodes in
September, as a counter-programming move against the Olympic Games
from Sydney, Australia, on NBC.
</P>
</TEXT>
