<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ENOUGH FALLOUT IN THIS WINDFALL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Eighty-eight million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   I know what I'd do with $88 million. If I were Nita and Tommy
Colla, who took their California lottery winnings in a lump sum,
paid taxes and wound up with $29 million, I'd hire a detective to
find out what happened to my other $59 million.
</P>
<P>
   The government lures you into their gambling scheme, which has
odds that make Vegas look like Santa Claus, then they slice and
dice away two-thirds of your winnings.
</P>
<P>
   Where is that compassionate conservative tax-the-poor agenda
when you really need it?
</P>
<P>
   I tell you, $88 million ain't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   The Collas immediately hired a financial adviser. Me, I'd ask
for the money in one-dollar bills and hire a forklift operator.
</P>
<P>
   And for the heck of it, I'd pick up a cherry '88 Oldsmobile
Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   I would also hire advisers. Financial advisers, technical
advisers, foreign-policy advisers. You can never have too many
advisers. And spokespeople.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; No, Mr. Donaldson, what Mr. Ostler MEANT to say was... &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE PROBLEM, though: With $88 mil, how would you deal with
all your new friends?
</P>
<P>
   Do they like you for you or for your money?
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Barbieri, star of radio KNBR, told me he once interviewed
Herb Caen for a magazine story.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph asked, ``Everywhere you go, Herb, people are glad to see
you, they're nice to you, they buy you drinks, they laugh at your
jokes. But how do you know whether they like you for yourself or
because you're a famous columnist?''
</P>
<P>
   And of course Herb said, ``Who gives a s_?''
</P>
<P>
   BURIED TREASURE? The Friends &AMP; Foundation of the Library people
don't exactly promise you'll find hidden riches at their big book
sale Sept. 7-9, but they drop hints.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's sale, they tell me, one reader bought a book and
found that it had been hollowed out. Inside were five very large,
gold-capped teeth. Yes, a book you can sink your teeth into.
</P>
<P>
   Another hollow book contained an out-of-circulation $100 bill
and three rings.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is all donated books, no library rejects.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the 100,000 books at Herbst Pavilion at Fort Mason, only
a small percentage is likely to contain cash and jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Every last book, though, contains riches for the mind, if you're
into that sort of materialism.
</P>
<P>
   Running shoes are recommended. Last year an elderly volunteer
holding back the first-day crowd before the nine o'clock opening
bell was almost trampled when someone in the crowd shouted ``Go!''
a minute early.
</P>
<P>
   Unruly louts, those book junkies.
</P>
<P>
   THE DREADED dot-commers are forcing the mass exodus of medical
people from the 450 Sutter building, which means that those same
dot-commers will have no place to go for Botox shots and ski-injury
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   And the place will need a new nickname. Tom Sweeney tells me
that the big medical building has long been known to locals as 450
Suffer.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE WAY, as William Thomas Quick is quick to point out, the
company that now owns 450 Suffer and is jacking up rents about 400
percent is ... Harsh Investment Properties.
</P>
<P>
   I'M WITH reader Tex when he says, ``Thank goodness there are no
Firestone blimps flying overhead.''
</P>
<P>
   A Firestone rep told Tex's friend, who lives near Redding, that
she would have to drive to Sacramento to turn in her faulty
Flintstone _ I mean Firestone _ tires.
</P>
<P>
   That's a long ride over red-hot pavement, so Tex figures the
Firestone slogan should be, ``No guts, no glory.''
</P>
<P>
   JANET RENO, with a name like that she should have been a
gambler. But anyway, Lou Bristol notices that the attorney general
said Tuesday, in response to a question about Gore's fund raising,
``I don't comment on conversations I have with attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess that would narrow the possible questions down to: ``Ms.
Attorney General, what does your hairstylist say about Al Gore's
fund-raising shenanigans?''
</P>
<P>
   FORGET ABOUT the polls. What George W. Bush should be worried
about losing points in is not the polls, but his IQ tests.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to explain his fiscal plan, W sounds like me trying to
balance my checkbook with three margaritas. He bumbles and rambles,
misplacing and realigning trillions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush vows not to let ``terrorists or rogue nations hold our
nation hostile or hold our allies hostile ...''
</P>
<P>
   The man has some charm, and all the charisma money can buy, but
he's going to have to hire an interpreter to stand next to him at
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe W just needs more speech practice. Like standing at the
seashore with marbles in his mouth, saying over and over,
``Inclusion illusion confusion,'' and ``The hostile hostage ate the
sausage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
