<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBRYO-RESEARCH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSY ERUPTS OVER GUIDELINES FOR EMBRYO RESEARCH
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Medical researchers hailed the government's new guidelines on
federal funding for human embryo cell research Wednesday, while
anti-abortion forces promptly denounced the move as condoning
murder and vowed a legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   At no time in the history of medical science have researchers
been so convinced that the tiny cells, contained within human
embryos shortly after fertilization, can offer a path to
breakthroughs in the fight against dozens of major disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have discovered that during the earliest days after
fertilization, the tiny clusters of embryonic cells contain within
them pluripotent stem cells that can be guided to develop into all
sorts of other cells: muscle, heart, nerves, blood, bone and many
others.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines announced by the National Institutes of Health
Wednesday after more than a year of public debate will create a
high-level scientific review group that must approve every proposal
seeking federal funds for research into the cells.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines also insist that federal research be conducted
only on cells that would otherwise be discarded after women have
become pregnant through in vitro fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   In such fertilization efforts, clusters of embryonic cells
normally are produced in a laboratory dish. After two or more
clusters of the embryonic cells are returned to the womb and the
woman becomes pregnant, the remaining surplus cells are destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   While allowing federal funds for the human embryonic stem cell
research under strict controls _ including a requirement for
``informed consent'' by any woman permitting her surplus cells to
be used _ the new guidelines explicitly ban any experiments on the
embryos themselves.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton himself hailed the new NIH guidelines at a
press conference Wednesday and said the research offers
``potentially staggering benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we cannot walk away from the potential to save lives
and improve lives, to help people literally get up and walk, to do
all kinds of things we could never have imagined, as long as we
meet rigorous, ethical standards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is certain to be taken up by Congress and is
likely to spill over into the presidential campaign because it is
so closely linked to the hot-button abortion issue. Several
Republicans threatened new legislation reversing the guidelines and
banning any research with human stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush made
clear his opposition to the administration's guidelines. ``The
governor opposes federal funding for stem cell research that
involves destroying a living human embryo,'' said campaign
spokesman Ray Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Catholic leaders also weighed in. Douglas Johnson,
legislative director of the National Right to Life Committee,
declared: ``You have to kill a human embryo to get (stem cells).
There will be a legal challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, leading scientists predicted that speeding the
research with federal funds could yield the first clinical trials
to treat specific diseases within three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Berg, a Stanford University biochemist and Nobel
laureate, said he is constantly puzzled by outcries against the
research because the cells to be used come from embryonic tissue
that would otherwise be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it more ethical to destroy these embryo cells or to
preserve them for enormous human benefit?'' Berg asked. ``To me
it's a no-brainer. We have the moral imperative to save human life
and improve human health, and I can't understand how one small
minority can hold up the work by imposing their view of morality or
ethics on the rest of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
