<SLUG> BC-ETRADE-PROBE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 E-TRADE'S MARKETING PROBED  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Regulators have begun investigating the
marketing practices of E-Trade Group and have forced the online
broker to get advance approval of all advertising materials,
according to a document filed by the company.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade is best known for edgy, offbeat ads that make light of
investor lust for money and have helped propel the firm to the No.
2 spot among online brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Menlo Park, Calif.'s E-Trade said in a quarterly report filed
last week with the Securities and Exchange Commission that NASD
Regulation, the National Association of Securities Dealers
affiliate that polices the industry, and the SEC had opened formal
investigations of its ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we have voluntarily agreed to prefile all
advertising 10 days prior to first use for (NASD Regulation's)
review and comment,'' E-Trade noted. The prefiling requirement
began June 12 and ends on Sept. 12, the firm said.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade has already been sanctioned twice this year by NASD
Regulation for failing to comply with security industry rules. The
company has said its violations were unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   NASD Regulation and the SEC declined to elaborate on the matter.
E-Trade is ``fully cooperating with the NASD'' but can't comment
further ``until that investigation is completed,'' E-Trade
spokesman Patrick Di Chiro said.
</P>
<P>
   One source close to E-Trade said NASD Regulation is insisting on
reviewing anything that can broadly be construed as marketing
material, including such items as press releases, hampering the
firm's ability to quickly gear up promotional campaigns. If E-Trade
runs afoul of its rules, the agency has threatened to extend the
review period for a full year, the source noted.
</P>
<P>
   The probes of E-Trade come more than a year after government and
industry leaders sharply criticized the online brokerage industry
for advertising that implied trading on the Internet was a fast and
easy way to get rich.
</P>
<P>
   In a May 1999 speech, SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt slammed
Internet brokers for ads that ``more closely resemble commercials
for the lottery than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   He specifically cited an ad by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter (then
known as Discover Brokerage) featuring a tow truck driver who buys
an island with his stock market winnings and an Ameritrade ad that
shows a woman returning to her computer after a morning jog,
bragging that she had just made $1,700 on a biotechnology stock.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued last year, NASD Regulation promised
more-vigorous oversight of online brokerage advertising, citing its
concern about ads that seem ``to unfairly portray the benefits of
the trading online, without disclosing the risks associated with
online investing.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency said it has stepped up enforcement by forcing brokers
to change and, in some cases, stop running commercials. ``Members
that repeatedly have issues regarding their compliance with the
advertising rules will be subject to greater sanctions,'' it
warned.
</P>
<P>
   NASD Regulation can censure brokers, fine them, force them to
halt advertising or, ultimately, expel them from the association,
effectively putting them out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, brokers pay heed to the agency. Ameritrade
stopped running its jogger commercial after NASD Regulation
questioned it, said Donna Kush, a spokeswoman for the Nebraska
firm. Ameritrade isn't being investigated by the agency, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear which E-Trade ads caught the eyes of NASD
Regulation and the SEC. But the firm has also used television
commercials and billboards that dangle riches in front of
prospective customers.
</P>
<P>
   During the past few years, E-Trade has been one of the
industry's most aggressive, creative and successful advertisers,
building one of the industry's best-recognized brand names. During
the nine months ended June 30, the firm spent $422 million on
marketing, one of the biggest budgets in financial services.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade's ads have ``been extremely effective,'' said
SalomonSmithBarney analyst Matthew Vetto. ``They have generated
tremendous growth in accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm's television, print and billboard ads, created by
superstar San Francisco agency Goodby, Silverstein, have garnered a
slew of awards. One of the most outlandish was a Super Bowl
commercial showing a chimpanzee lip-synching the song ``La
Cucaracha,'' followed by the tag line: ``Well, we just wasted two
million bucks. What are you doing with your money?''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
