<SLUG> BC-PUC-CONFLICT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA PUC COMMISSIONER OFF CASE AFTER CONFLICT COMPLAINT  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California Public Utilities Commissioner Henry
Duque, under fire for investing $10,000 in a cellular phone company
his agency regulates, was dropped from a PUC case last month amid
complaints he had a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, a Santa Cruz, Calif., lawyer asked PUC President
Loretta Lynch to consider removing Duque from overseeing a case
involving mobile-home parks because he owned $81,000 in stock in
Chateau Communities, which owns five mobile-home parks in
California.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeding could determine whether apartment buildings and
mobile-home parks _ including Chateau's _ can resell water to
tenants at a profit and whether the PUC can set the rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such financial holdings raise the appearance of a conflict,''
wrote Benjamin Scharf, an attorney representing mobile-home owners.
</P>
<P>
   Duque, however, said the PUC's lawyers advised him the
investment didn't pose a problem. The PUC's top lawyer, Peter Arth,
declined to confirm that statement.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Duque said he decided to sell his stock and remove
himself from the case after a reporter asked him about the
complaints. The Santa Cruz Sentinel ran a story about the
allegations on July 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, OK, discretion is the better part of valor,'' Duque
said. ``It's really nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But a commission official said the PUC lawyers recommended he be
moved off the case. The case was transferred on July 18 to Lynch,
but the order does not indicate who requested the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it is not clear that Duque violated the law in the
mobile-home case but complain that Duque hasn't done enough to
avoid the appearance of a conflict of interest in his role at the
PUC.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, The Chronicle reported that Duque bought stock in
Nextel Communications, the country's fifth-largest wireless firm,
despite state regulations barring commissioners from investing in
companies regulated by the PUC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is going to be increasing pressure for him to
vacate his seat,'' said Michael Shames, executive director of the
Utility Consumers' Action Network. ``There's a compounding effect.
It makes the (Nextel) violation even that much more egregious.``
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Duque never tried to hide the investments. In forms
filed with the PUC in February, Duque reported he invested at least
$460,000 in 46 companies, ranging from telecommunications to
semiconductors to real estate.
</P>
<P>
   And even consumer watchdogs who differ sharply with Duque
politically do not question his honesty. ``Duque is an honorable
man, and he would not do anything to put himself in this position
deliberately,'' said Paul Stein, a lawyer with The Utility Reform
Network, a San Francisco consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   But Stein added: ``Duque needs to be more careful, and the PUC
legal staff needs to take a more active role in identifying
potential conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   PUC lawyers review only the financial filings if the
commissioners ask them for advice. In an earlier interview, Arth
said it is up to the individuals to follow the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duque is taking action to make sure the problem doesn't
occur again. He retained a lawyer Wednesday who specializes in
election law to review his investments and identify potential
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing his best,'' said Joseph Remcho of San Francisco.
``He hired me to set up a procedure so that inadvertent errors that
may cause an appearance of a conflict do not happen in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that Duque seemed unfamiliar with some of his
investments.
</P>
<P>
   In the mobile-home case, for instance, Duque said he didn't
realize Chateau owned any mobile-home parks until an attorney in
the case complained that he had a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But Chateau's Web site touts it as ``the largest owner/manager
of manufactured (or mobile) home communities in the nation.''
Indeed, that is almost all Chateau does.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just calls his investment adviser, and his investment
adviser says `Buy that' and (Duque) says `OK,' '' Remcho said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it seems clear that Duque broke state rules in the
Nextel case but not necessarily in the mobile-home situation.
</P>
<P>
   Scharf, who represents mobile-home tenants in the Golden State
Mobilehome Owners League, said he believes the Public Utilities
Code bars commissioners from owning stock in any company subject to
regulation by the commission _ including mobile-homes parks.
</P>
<P>
   But Duque notes that mobile parks are regulated by the PUC only
in rare instances.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
