<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-AUTOSALES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AMAZON GIVES GREEN LIGHT TO ONLINE CAR SALES  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It may be difficult to visualize dropping a
2,000-pound Ford Explorer into your ``shopping cart,'' but
Amazon.com is asking customers to do just that as the leading
e-tailer begins selling new automobiles online Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   To the likely relief of stockholders in the money-losing
e-tailer, Amazon isn't actually buying cars from manufacturers and
setting up a delivery system. Instead, the Seattle company is
leasing space on its Web site to Livermore, Calif.'s
Greenlight.com, which sells new cars online and arranges their
delivery through 1,500 local dealerships in 27 states, including
several Bay Area chains.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jupiter Communications' rosy forecasts of a $30 billion
online car market by 2004, selling new cars online has so far
proved difficult. CarOrder.com, based in Austin, Texas, shut down
its Web site Friday, and other car-sales sites have seen their
stock prices sink in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   However, this agreement is a low-risk way for Amazon to test the
online car-sales market, said Heath Terry, a financial analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody can sell (cars online), Amazon can, but it's going
to take awhile before direct car sales on the Internet are going to
become a big thing,'' said Terry of Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a category we want to be in,'' said Amazon Chief
Executive Officer Jeff Bezos. ``It is completely clear that over
the long term, online is going to have a lot to do with car
buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike books, home-improvement tools or other items Amazon
sells, automobiles are subject to state laws designed to protect
the current dealership system and supported by powerful dealer
lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   State franchise laws make it illegal to sell new cars without
going through a dealer, so most car sites _ including Greenlight _
depend on commissions from dealers for revenues. (Greenlight also
gets some revenue from financing, trade-in fees and other sources.
The closely held firm won't disclose details about its revenues.)
New cars carry a profit margin of only 1 to 2 percent, leaving
little for an Internet company to pick up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selling cars over the Internet just doesn't work,'' said
Jonathan Lawrence, an auto e-commerce analyst with Dain Rauscher
Wessels.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos' response to such doubts: ``Five years ago, they were
telling me the same thing about books.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenlight will pay Amazon $15.25 million during the two-year
contract in exchange for access to the popular site's 23 million
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon agreed in January to acquire 5 percent of Greenlight and
has the option to buy more shares at a fixed rate. Industry sources
say Amazon has warrants for up to 30 percent of the company. In
addition, Amazon contributed less than $5 million to the $39
million round of funding Greenlight raised Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The new Greenlight page is integrated into Amazon's site. Amazon
terminated a similar arrangement with furniture seller Living.com _
in which it held an 18 percent stake _ last week, when the company
went out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon also holds minority shares of Webvan and Pets.com, and
analyst Terry said these companies are potential candidates for
similar partnerships, should Amazon decide to start selling
groceries or pet supplies. Bezos has said he eventually wants every
product under the sun to be available at Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon received warrants to buy 5 percent of ToysRUs.com two
weeks ago in exchange for taking on the responsibility of running
the toy seller's troubled Web operation. Under the 10-year
agreement, Amazon will receive fixed payments as well as a
percentage of each toy sale.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon shares closed at $38.81 Wednesday, up $2.31. The stock
has lost about 60 percent of its value this year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
