<HEADER>
A0739 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-EMBRYO-RESEARCH-1     08-24 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EMBRYO-RESEARCH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO ALLOW ITS RESEARCHERS TO WORK ON EMBRYONIC STEM CELLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan.)   (CHANGES ``believe'' to ``say'' in 2nd graf; ADDS time frame to 6th
graf)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health issued long-awaited rules
Wednesday that would permit federally financed researchers to work
on human embryonic stem cells, cells derived from the very early
embryo.
</P>
<P>
   Because of these cells' ability to form every tissue of the
body, scientists say they hold great promise in treating many
diseases, particularly the degenerative maladies of age.
</P>
<P>
   The rules permit federally financed researchers to use cell
lines that are derived from frozen human embryos due to be
discarded by fertility clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of abortion have objected to federal approval of the
research because the embryos, which they consider to be capable of
life, are destroyed in the process.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to sidestep the abortion issue, the National
Institutes of Health will allow its researchers to use only cells
that have been obtained by private firms. The agency's researchers
will not be allowed themselves to extract and culture the cells
from discarded embryos.
</P>
<P>
   The cells, which were first cul- tured two years ago, may be
legally derived by anyone who does not receive federal funding.
Human embryos are created by mixing eggs and sperm in fertility
clinics. Those that are not used are often frozen, stored for many
years, and eventually abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was welcomed by scientific groups like the
Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology, and
President Clinton referred in a press conference Wednesday to the
``potentially staggering benefits of this research.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we cannot walk away from the potential to save lives
and improve lives, to help people literally get up and walk, to do
all kinds of things we could never have imagined,'' Clinton said,
``as long as we meet rigorous, ethical standards.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as rigorous ethical standards are met, he said, ``I
think we cannot walk away from the potential to save lives and
improve lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lana Skirboll, director of science policy at the National
Institutes of Health, said that the agency's special review
committee for embryonic stem cells would hold its first meeting
next month and that the first research grants could be awarded
before the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., the Senate's leading critic of the
agency's policy, said in a statement Wednesday that human embryonic
stem cell research was ``illegal, immoral and unnecessary.''
Brownback said the research was prohibited by a congressional ban
on financing research that led to the destruction of human embryos,
sought to benefit by taking human life and would lead to treatments
that could be developed by other means: the use of adult stem
cells.
</P>
<P>
   The initial draft of the agency's guidelines, issued in
December, drew criticism as morally inconsistent from anti-abortion
groups and even the National Bioethics Advisory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In their final form, the guidelines have been made more
stringent, by the addition of a new level of review. Biologists
seeking federal funds to work on human embryonic stem cells will
have to win approval from four separate bodies _ their university's
in-house review group and three panels within the N.I.H. _ before
receiving their money.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines include several provisions designed to discourage
anyone from donating embryos for profit or for the medical benefit
of relatives. The new version also allows the donor of the
embryonic cells to be identified, since the immunological makeup of
the cells may be important if they are transplanted into patients.
</P>
<P>
   The extra reviews required by the new rules should not delay
research because they will take place within the agency's normal
reviewing cycle, Skirboll said.
</P>
<P>
   One new issue that has been raised in recent months comes from
the finding that a different kind of stem cells found in the organs
of adults are far more versatile than supposed. The opponents of
funding embryonic stem cells have argued that the promised health
benefits can be obtained just as well as from a patient's own adult
stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   The argument is not without substance. Most organs seem to have
a small reservoir of stem cells that generate new cells, among them
the bone marrow stem cells that daily replenish the red and white
blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   Adult stem cells are less versatile than embryonic stem cells
but they now appear to be less tissue-specific than thought; recent
experiments have shown that the blood-making stem cells can also be
coaxed to make muscle cells and even nerve cells.
</P>
<P>
   Blood-making stem cells are quite accessible and could perhaps
be converted into dopamine-secreting brain cells, the type lost in
Parkinson's disease. Use of a patient's own stem cells would avoid
both the ethical problems of embryonic stem cells and the threat of
immunological rejection.
</P>
<P>
   But embryonic stem cells grow much more prolifically than adult
stem cells and biologists have in mind several ways of handling the
problem of immune rejection. In short, no one yet knows which type
of stem cell will prove more suitable for clinical use, and
researchers want to try both.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is bad public policy for politicians to say
which cells should be studied,'' said Daniel Perry, chairman of the
Patients' Coalition for Urgent Research. ``we think all of them
should be studied.''
</P>
<P>
   Embryonic stem cells are taken from the embryo at a stage when
it is a hollow sphere consisting of a thousand or so cells. Inside
the sphere is a blob known as the inner cell mass, which contains
the stem cells. The cells can form any tissue of the body except
the placenta.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a scientific committee recommended to the British
government that researchers should be allowed to embark on
therapeutic cloning, in which an ordinary body cell is taken from a
patient and inserted into a human egg cell whose own nucleus has
been removed.
</P>
<P>
   Through mechanisms that are not yet understood, the egg's
interior contents or cytoplasm can reprogram the introduced nucleus
and enable it to regain its full potential; instead of operating
just as the nucleus of a skin cell, say, it can make any tissue of
the body.
</P>
<P>
   In principle the inserted nucleus can then direct the egg to
grow into an entire adult organism. This is the process that was
used to clone Dolly the sheep, the nucleus being taken from an
adult mammary gland cell.
</P>
<P>
   A human egg cell with an introduced adult cell nucleus would
presumably be a viable embryo, but inserting it into a uterus would
be a criminal offense in Britain. For therapeutic cloning, the egg
would instead be cultured in laboratory glassware and exposed to
signals that would convert it into the type of tissue that the
patient needed to have replaced. The concept has been demonstrated
in repairing heart tissue in mice and is considered to have
enormous clinical promise.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, therapeutic cloning could legally be
undertaken by private researchers but no one is known to have done
so, Skirboll said. Therapeutic cloning is specifically prohibited
for federally financed researchers by the guidelines issued
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Skirboll said the N.I.H.'s special review committee for
embryonic stem cells would hold its first meeting next month, and
that the first research grants could be awarded before the end of
next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
