r f BC-JUKEBOX-HIGHTECH-SFCH     08-24 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUKEBOX-HIGHTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 JUKE JOINTS JUMP WITH HIGH-TECH TUNES  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You're at your favorite bar. You amble up to the
new Internet-connected jukebox and punch up your favorite tune. In
moments, the jukebox downloads the song, plays it and asks if you
want to buy the CD.
</P>
<P>
   Then you notice the jukebox displaying the live video feed of an
attractive patron sitting in a bar 3,000 miles away. In seconds,
you've e-mailed a hopeful message: ``Can I buy you a song and a
drink?''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this is not your father's jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the bubble-tubed, Art Deco mechanical machines that
have survived for a century as an American music icon are about to
be transformed by the Internet music revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Little-known startups such as Ecast Inc. of San Francisco as
well as long-established jukeboxmaker Wurlitzer are rolling out
online, computer-powered digital jukeboxes that they hope will
supplant an estimated 250,000 machines that spin vinyl 45 rpm
records or plastic CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the new ``downloadable'' jukeboxes promise a
virtually limitless selection of songs _ nearly enough to make a
Napster junkie happy _ but analysts say it is a concept that could
also make e-commerce transactions like buying a CD palatable for
the millions of people who don't use computers at home or work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is kind of a `duh' idea,'' said Edward Bevilacqua,
chief executive of Fun e-Business Inc., a San Diego County company
that designed the technology inside a new computerized jukebox that
Wurlitzer Jukebox Co. of Chicago plans to roll out later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jukebox is a multigenerational product that people feel
good about,'' Bevilacqua said.
</P>
<P>
   A deal that Ecast announced earlier this week is the biggest
signal to date that digital music is beginning to transform the
$2-billion-a-year jukebox industry.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe International Inc., the world's biggest manufacturer of
jukeboxes, said it will build new downloadable jukeboxes using
Ecast's Internet technology, called the Siren Entertainment System.
</P>
<P>
   The Rowe-Ecast jukeboxes will be able to tap into a library of
thousands of songs from major and independent record labels. Each
box can store up to 400 discs on a local hard drive. For payment,
the boxes will also accept credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Because Rowe International of Grand Rapids, Mich., claims about
70 percent of the North American jukebox market, its alliance with
Ecast will get the attention of traditional jukebox operators who
historically have been skeptical about switching to new technology,
said Marcus Webb, editor of the industry publication RePlay
Magazine, based in Tarzana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leading jukebox factory has made this very close alliance
with a firm making downloading-music technology,'' said Webb, who
has followed the jukebox industry for 15 years. ``That is going to
send a really big signal to the operators who buy these
jukeboxes.''
</P>
<P>
   One company, TouchTunes Music Corp. of Montreal, has already
leased about 2,000 of its Genesis digital jukeboxes around the
country. The TouchTunes jukebox can store 750 downloaded songs.
</P>
<P>
   According to jukebox historians, the first commercial
``coin-operated phonograph'' made its premiere on Nov. 23, 1889, in
San Francisco's Palais Royal restaurant on Sutter Street. Inventor
Louis Glass affixed a coin slot to an Edison gramophone, which
played sound for two minutes on a nickel.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 20th century, jukeboxes became cabinets that played
songs from a small collection of vinyl records stored inside. For
example, the first Wurlitzer jukebox, the Debutante, which
premiered in 1933, had 10 songs. The company now has a model that
holds 120 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, Wurlitzer plans to roll out a model that looks
like an old-fashioned rainbow-colored jukebox on the outside but
replaces the mechanical CD or record changer on the inside with an
off-the-shelf computer.
</P>
<P>
   The jukebox can store 10,000 songs in digital form on a hard
drive and, through a high-speed DSL connection, access and download
music from a virtual library of 200,000 songs, using Liquid Audio
Inc.'s digital audio format.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, mechanical jukeboxes have to be manually
updated to add the latest top hits. That means jukebox distributors
typically have to go to each unit and replace the 100 CDs with new
ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem you have with CD jukeboxes is that only
one to three songs out of 12 (on a CD) are being played by the
jukebox patron,'' said Joe Pankus, chief executive officer of
Wurlitzer USA.
</P>
<P>
   However, with Internet-connected jukeboxes, ``you have all the
hits,'' Pankus said.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Ecast chief executive and founder Mouli Cohen said his system
also has the ability to link to a site that sells CDs. And the
system is designed to deliver other forms of entertainment, like
video games, film and cartoons. Cohen also envisions a time when
the jukeboxes could be used to buy and print concert or sports
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   And imagine a day, Cohen said, when a jukebox network includes
screens that show people in other taverns around the country. ``If
you're in a bar in San Francisco and see someone in New York,'' he
said, ``I can buy him or her a drink or a song from the location
where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   While that scenario is still too futuristic, the Ecast jukeboxes
are becoming a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Ecast has demonstration models set up in about 50 U.S.
locations, such as Kennedy's Irish Pub Curry House on Columbus
Avenue in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The company earlier this year signed a deal with England's
Leisure Link Group Ltd., the world's biggest electronic amusement
game operator, to deploy Ecast technology in about 20,000
Leisure-made jukeboxes in the United Kingdom during the next
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe the downloadable jukeboxes will catch on
quickly. According to a report by Dataquest analyst Van Baker, the
Ecast business model ``is so compelling at all levels of the supply
chain that it is bound to have a profound impact on the traditional
jukebox industry. ... This is clearly a potential change-or-die
scenario for the operators.''
</P>
<P>
   That could bring sweet music to an industry that has been slowly
shrinking due to competition from the new forms of digital
entertainment, from video games to the home computer.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that jukeboxes remain a staple in bars but
practically disappeared since the late 1980s from restaurants, said
Jim Hayes, chairman of the jukebox committee for the Amusement &AMP;
Music Operators Association, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to find them in other places besides bars, like ice
cream parlors and pizza places,'' Hayes said. Downloadable
jukeboxes ``gives our industry a chance to gain back some market
share in some of the venues we used to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Rufus Connell, an analyst with Frost &AMP; Sullivan, a San Jose
company that tracks Web-connected kiosks, said music will only be
the first step toward introducing non-Web-savvy consumers to
Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, retailers may be able to use the jukebox
to sell products to restaurant customers who are playing music and
waiting for their food to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of providing music through an Internet jukebox is a
neat idea,'' Connell said. ``This is a great way to provide revenue
streams.''
</P>
<P>
   But Webb, the editor at RePlay, said persuading the thousands of
bar and restaurant owners to install downloadable jukeboxes could
be a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same group that waited until 10 years after CDs were
introduced _ and five years after CDs had replaced vinyl albums as
the dominant music media _ to start replacing the old vinyl-playing
jukeboxes with ones that played CDs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a new, but still-unreleased jukebox industry survey by
the University of New Orleans shows 19.6 percent of the commercial
jukeboxes still in use play vinyl 45 rpm records.
</P>
<P>
   And although 41 percent say downloadable jukeboxes will
eventually replace the old technology, 43 percent say the new
machines will have no effect, according to the survey commissioned
by the amusement operators association.
</P>
<P>
   ``American operators are coming to the reluctant conclusion that
the technology that they were 10 years behind the rest of the
country in embracing _ CDs _ may eventually have to be replaced by
downloading music,'' Webb said. ``But they're not eager to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
