 POWER-MISER MICROCHIPS GENEROUS TO HANDHELD DEVICES  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Even as it pushes to bring its new Pentium 4 and
Itanium chips to market, Intel announced plans Wednesday for yet
another processor design, this one intended not for PCs but for
Web-capable mobile phones, handheld computers and networking
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Officially called the XScale Microarchitecture, the new
technology will be the foundation of a series of products Intel
will begin announcing this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Because these chips will deliver high performance on very little
power, devices incorporating them will be capable of carrying out
demanding tasks such as videoconferencing while running on just a
single AA battery, according to Ron Smith, vice president and
general manager of Intel's Wireless Computing and Communications
Group in Folsom, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Chips based on the architecture will be capable of operating at
variable voltages and performance levels. In a demonstration
Wednesday at the Intel Developer Forum in San Jose, Calif., Smith
and the chief Intel engineer on the project, Jay Heath, cranked up
a prototype to a speed of 1 gigahertz _ 1 billion cycles per second
_ by increasing its power to 1.75 volts.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Intel's latest Pentium III chip, running at 1.13
gigahertz, can consume up to 35.5 watts, according to Intel
technical documents.
</P>
<P>
   When Smith and Heath dialed the power going into the XScale
prototype down to 0.7 volt, the chip ran at 200 megahertz. At that
level, it would consume only about 50 milliwatts, or 0.05 watt.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Smith said, the chip could operate on as little as 10
milliwatts, running at 50 megahertz. Application programs will be
able to tell XScale-based devices how much power and performance
they require, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a multimedia player running on a personal digital
assistant with an XScale chip could set the voltage to a high level
so the chip could handle a heavy-duty chore like decoding an MPEG2
video stream. But when the user switched to, say, an appointment
calendar, which needs much less processing performance, the program
would tell the device to drop to a lower power mode to preserve
battery life.
</P>
<P>
   This power-conservation scheme bears some resemblance to the
LongRun technology used in the Crusoe chips announced earlier this
year by Transmeta, a secretive Santa Clara, Calif., startup. The
Crusoe chips, however, adjust voltage levels on the fly, depending
on the chip's current workload, without waiting for instructions
from software applications.
</P>
<P>
   The XScale architecture is an enhanced derivative of the
StrongARM, a family of chips Intel acquired in 1998 as part of the
settlement of a patent dispute with the former Digital Equipment
Corp. Digital in turn had developed the chips around technology
licensed from a British chip design company called Advanced RISC
Machines (ARM).
</P>
<P>
   Intel said it would incorporate the new chips into its own
networking products but declined to identify prospective outside
customers. Currently, the StrongARM chip powers the iPAQ Pocket PC,
a hot-selling new handheld computer from Compaq, and Palm Inc. has
said it plans to adopt ARM chips in future version of its handheld
organizers. (Palm today uses a Motorola chip called the
Dragonball.)
</P>
<P>
   Already the largest supplier of flash memory chips for mobile
phones, Intel hopes the new chips will also find a home in that
burgeoning market. Aside from their communications chips, today's
phones have only rudimentary processors, but as phonemakers add
features such as color screens, Web access and MP3 music
capabilities, they will require the combination of high performance
and low power XScale is designed to deliver, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Intel closed Wednesday at a 52-week high of $74.63, up
$2.50.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of INTEL24 (10454 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
