<SLUG> BC-LANE-ORACLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FORMER ORACLE PRESIDENT LANE JOINS VENTURE FIRM  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Oracle's former No. 2 executive, Ray Lane, who
left the database software giant last month after he was stripped
of his duties, resurfaced Wednesday as a general partner at one of
Silicon Valley's most prestigious venture-capital firms.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, 53, will become a general partner at Kleiner Perkins
Caufield &AMP; Byers, one of the early investors in ``new economy''
titans America Online and Amazon.com, where he said he hopes to
help Fortune 1000 companies found startups harnessing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the shakeout in dot-coms, venture-capital success is
about how well you can pick CEOs, build management teams and choose
acquisitions _ I've done that,'' Lane said in an interview,
referring to his pre-Oracle job at business consulting firm
Booz-Allen &AMP; Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Lane also said the job's flexible hours and the proximity of
Kleiner Perkins' Menlo Park, Calif., headquarters to his home in
Atherton, Calif., will let him spend more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another operations role would put me on the 18-hour-a-day
circuit with a lot of travel. This is an industry and a firm that
structurally fits my life,'' he said, adding that he considers
Kleiner Perkins ``the New York Yankees of the venture-capital
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane's decision answers a much-asked question in Silicon Valley
and beyond. Since his abrupt departure from Redwood Shores,
Calif.'s Oracle last month, many have wondered where the highly
respected Lane would turn up.
</P>
<P>
   Although some analysts said Lane was particularly talented at
running the day-to-day minutiae of a large high-tech company,
others said Lane will have a wider-ranging impact on the industry
in his role at Kleiner Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lets Ray play an active role in incubating and
germinating and fertilizing smaller companies as they embark on
aggressive growth paths,'' said Wendell Laidley, an analyst at
Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At Oracle, Lane was considered a buttoned-down counterbalance to
chief executive Larry Ellison's flamboyance.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Ellison often made brash promises to the marketplace and
media, Lane, during eight years as Oracle's president and chief
operating officer, forged strong bonds with customers and revamped
the company's overly aggressive sales practices, according to one
analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Oracle has assessed what they lost in Ray
Lane,'' said Giga Information Group analyst Terilyn Palanca.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, the mercurial Ellison unexpectedly reassigned
Lane's duties, from decisions about ``every PC the company bought,
to every person the company hired,'' Lane told The Chronicle in the
first published interview after his departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in the interest of the company to distribute his
functions more broadly among up-and-coming senior managers,''
Ellison said in an interview at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Lane resigned a newly minted billionaire by way of Oracle's
soaring stock and several weeks later said he would not seek
another executive post, though that hasn't stopped firms from
trying to recruit him.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks after his break with Oracle, Lane said at least 50
firms called with offers of chief executive or director slots. Some
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, Lane joined the board of Sheer Networks, a
Sunnyvale, Calif., firm that creates software to manage
telecommunications networks. In addition to Sheer Networks and
Oracle, Lane sits on the boards of Marimba, C-bridge Internet
Solutions and Software Technologies Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Lane is the latest in a string of high-tech defectors to Kleiner
Perkins. John Doerr joined Kleiner from Intel Corp., Floyd Kvamme
came from Apple Computer Inc. and Thomas Jermoluk moved to the firm
from ExciteAtHome Corp. in May.
</P>
<P>
   William R. Hearst III, a board member of Hearst Corp., which
owns The Chronicle, is also a partner with Kleiner Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was founded in 1972, Kleiner Perkins has invested more
than $1.2 billion in more than 100 companies that have since sold
shares in initial public offerings. The firm has become one of the
most sought-after venture capitalists for young technology
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
