<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-EINSTEIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Computing Q&AMP;A: E-Books Aren't Quite Ready to Make a Move  &HT;     By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I've been hearing a lot about e-books. Exactly what are they,
anyway? Do I need special hardware or software to read them, and
what makes them different from any other document I can view on my
PC?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: It's a good thing I don't charge by the question or you would be
in trouble. E-books _ or electronic books _ are actual books, like
novels, textbooks and classics, that have been digitized and
formatted in a way that makes them appear on a computer screen
exactly as they do in print. You can read e-books on a PC, but the
goal is to put them on portable devices like specially designed
handheld readers or personal digital assistants, so you can read
them while you are on a bus, train or plane.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, e-books are in their infancy. The primary software
formats for them are the Microsoft Reader and the Glassbook Reader.
Both are free downloads _ from  &LR; www.microsoft.com/reader &LR;  and
 &LR; www.glassbook.com &LR;  _ that you can load onto your PC or notebook
computer. The Microsoft reader also comes loaded on new Pocket PC
handheld computers from companies including Hewlett-Packard and
Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   A few e-book devices also are available, including the $600
SoftBook Reader from SoftBook Press and the $269 Rocket eBook from
NuvoMedia.
</P>
<P>
   So far, more titles are available for the Microsoft Reader than
for other formats. But it probably won't be long before most
e-books are released in all available formats. Right now, expect to
pay about the same price for an e-book that you would for a
discounted regular book.
</P>
<P>
   For a lot more information on e-books, go to
 &LR; www.barnesandnoble.com &LR;  or to  &LR; www.ipublish.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Cleaning Up Temp Files
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I have collected about 48 megabytes of temporary files on my
hard drive. Is it safe to delete them?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: In general, the answer is yes. Any file ending in ``.tmp'' is a
temporary file that your computer can live without very nicely.
Many programs create temporary files while you work.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, temporary files are automatically deleted
when you close a program or reboot your PC, but because it isn't a
perfect world, you will always have some temp files hanging around.
The first place to look for temporary files is in the TEMP folder
inside the Windows folder. You can also use the Find function in
the Windows Start menu to search for ``.tmp,'' which will reveal
the location of all your temp files.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; By the way, don't confuse temporary system files with
``temporary Internet files'' that Microsoft's Internet Explorer Web
browser stores on your disk. Those are useful, because they make it
possible to load Web pages faster. Netscape also uses such files,
but refers to them as ``cache'' files.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Loading MSN Messenger
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: Do you need an Internet account with MSN to use its Messenger
service? If you do not have to be a subscriber, how do you go about
getting MSN Messenger?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Internet message services like MSN Messenger and America
Online's Instant Messenger are free to anyone, not just people who
get their Internet access via MSN and AOL.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, all you have to do is sign up online at
 &LR; www.msn.com &LR;  or  &LR; www.aol.com &LR; , and download a small software
program if it isn't already on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   You should bear in mind that MSN Messenger users can't
communicate with AOL Instant Messenger users. The two companies
hate each other too much to cooperate. So you may have to use both
services to keep in touch with all your friends.
</P>
<P>
   NICE WORDS FOR ATHOME: During the past couple of years, I have
taken a shot or two at AtHome, mostly because of the slow service I
have received when my Internet cable went down. Recently, however,
I had a really good experience. After rebuilding a PC, I called
AtHome for some help configuring the service with a new internal
network card. I got a tech support fellow on the phone right away,
and he walked me through the procedure in five minutes. Couldn't
have been easier.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK: If you find yourself printing a lot of stuff _
draft versions of documents, notes or information from the
Internet, for example _ don't waste your money on expensive typing
paper. Instead, buy a box of copy machine or multi-use paper. For
less than $20, you should be able to get 10 reams _ that's 5,000
sheets.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David einstein at  &LR; computers(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
