<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PUC _ &LR;  California Public Utilities Commissioner Henry Duque, under
fire for investing $10,000 in a cellular phone company his agency
regulates, dropped out of a case last month after receiving
complaints he had a conflict of interest.  &UR; BY TODD &LR; 
 &UR; WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; JUKEBOX _ &LR;  You're at your favorite bar. You amble up to the new
Internet-connected jukebox and punch up your favorite tune. In
moments, the jukebox downloads the song, plays it and asks if you
want to buy the CD.
</P>
<P>
   Then you notice the jukebox displaying the live video feed of an
attractive patron sitting in a bar 3,000 miles away. In seconds,
you've e-mailed a hopeful message: ``Can I buy you a song and a
drink?''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this is not your father's jukebox.  &UR; BY BENNY &LR; 
 &UR; EVANGELISTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; COMPUTING (Q&AMP;A COLUMN) _ &LR;  Q: I've been hearing a lot about e-books.
Exactly what are they, anyway? Do I need special hardware or
software to read them, and what makes them different from any other
document I can view on my PC?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a good thing I don't charge by the question or you would
be in trouble. E-books _ or electronic books _ are actual books,
like novels, textbooks and classics, that have been digitized and
formatted in a way that makes them appear on a computer screen
exactly as they do in print.  &UR; COLUMN BY DAVID EINSTEIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ETRADE _ &LR;  Regulators have begun investigating the marketing
practices of E-Trade Group and have forced the online broker to get
advance approval of all advertising materials, according to a
document filed by the company.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade is best known for edgy, offbeat ads that make light of
investor lust for money and have helped propel the firm to the No.
2 spot among online brokers.  &UR; BY SAM ZUCKERMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; AMAZON _ &LR;  It may be hard to visualize dropping a 2,000-pound Ford
Explorer into your ``shopping cart,'' but Amazon.com is asking
customers to do just that as the leading e-tailer begins selling
new automobiles online Thursday.  &UR; BY CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; INTEL _ &LR;  Even as it pushes to bring its new Pentium 4 and Itanium
chips to market, Intel on Wednesday announced plans for yet another
processor design, this one intended not for PCs but for Web-capable
mobile phones, handheld computers and networking equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Officially called the XScale Microarchitecture, the new
technology will be the foundation of a series of products Intel
will begin announcing this fall.  &UR; BY HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; LANE _ &LR;  Oracle's former No. 2 executive, Ray Lane, who left the
database software giant last month after he was stripped of his
duties, resurfaced yesterday as a general partner at one of Silicon
Valley's most prestigious venture capital firms.  &UR; BY KELLY &LR; 
 &UR; ZITO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NOTE _ &LR;  There is no Dan Fost / Media Bytes column this week.
</P>
