<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGAL-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Clinton legal fund raises $8 million  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Supporters of President Clinton have raised $8
million to help pay his legal bills from investigations of
Whitewater, the Paula Jones sexual harassment case and the Monica
Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the Clinton Legal Expense Trust gave their
semiannual update on the fund to reporters Wednesday, saying the
number of contributors is increasing as the end of Clinton's
presidency nears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased that the results of our efforts have been
steady over the past year,'' said Anthony F. Essaye, executive
director of the trust. Most of the money is raised by sending
letters to potential contributors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trust raised $950,000 in the first six months of this year
from about 16,000 contributors, an average of about $59 each. There
were 187 contributions from Missouri residents and 87 from Kansas,
none more than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the television and movie industry gave to the
Clinton fund, including producer Norman Lear, $10,000, and director
Rob Reiner, $1,000. Other contributors of $1,000 included Clinton
friend Vernon E. Jordan, former senator and Democratic vice
presidential nominee Lloyd M. Bentsen of Texas, and Caroline
Kennedy's husband, Edwin A. Schlossberg of New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months of 1999, the trust raised $800,000. The
goal is to pay as much of an estimated $11 million in legal
expenses as possible before Clinton leaves office Jan. 20. The
trust is expected to cease raising money at that time, Essaye said.
</P>
<P>
   Essaye said he could not gauge what the effect on fund raising
or legal bills would be as a result of last week's report that
independent counsel Robert Ray has called a grand jury to consider
indicting Clinton after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens there is beyond our control,'' Essaye said. ``Our
objective is to raise as much money as we can.'' So far the fund
has paid $6.5 million in legal expenses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The $8 million has been raised since the trust was formed in
February 1998. Contributions are capped at $10,000 each and are
only taken from individuals. No lobbyists, corporations, or
executive branch employees may give.
</P>
<P>
   The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton have been
under investigation for most of the last eight years for their
Whitewater real estate dealings in Arkansas. Clinton was impeached
by the House in 1998 for alleged perjury and obstruction of justice
stemming from the Jones and Lewinsky cases. The Senate acquitted
him.
</P>
<P>
   Although critics of Clinton said his legal troubles were his own
making, the fund-raising drive is a legitimate way for supporters
to help relieve the Clintons of legal bills they cannot afford to
pay, Essaye said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really feel there should be an opportunity for the public,
if they wish, to enable a first family to leave office without an
enormous financial burden incurred while they are serving the
country,'' Essaye said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 0110EDT &QL; 
