<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFF-KAN </SLUG>
  
 All should be aware of e-policy  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every day across America, workers are fired for using their
companies' computer systems as their personal electronic
playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Chemical Co. confirmed earlier this week that it was letting
about 40 employees go because they allegedly violated corporate
e-mail policy. A routine review of company e-mail accounts in
Houston discovered the violations, described as violent or sexually
explicit content. Fifty others were fired earlier this year at Dow
headquarters in Michigan for similar reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Dow is hardly the only employer to come down hard. In June,
American Century Investments in Kansas City fired 16 workers who
were accused of violating user policies on its e-mail and Web-based
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically have a zero tolerance rule,'' said Chris Doyle,
American Century's director of corporate public relations. ``We
have clear-cut guidelines, and when we discovered what we felt were
violations during routine server maintenance, we acted swiftly.''
</P>
<P>
   In case any corporate computer user has been sleeping through
the e-mail and Web explosion of the 1990s, here's the deal:
</P>
<P>
   Three out of four employers told the American Management
Association this year that they use electronic surveillance or
otherwise monitor their employees' Internet and e-mail use.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City lawyer Irv Belzer, who advises clients on e-mail
policies, emphasizes that employers own the information on their
computer systems and have the right to review it. They also can and
do take disciplinary action when they find violations of use
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, companies need to make their policies known. There
should be no lack of awareness or confusion among workers. A union
official, speaking about the dismissed Dow workers, contended this
week that some were unaware of the company's policy and others
didn't take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Know it. Believe it. People lose jobs because of random checks,
routine maintenance and co-worker complaints.
</P>
<P>
   And remember: Hitting the delete key alone doesn't protect
users. Computer experts can find files that users think they've
deleted.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of pornography, dirty jokes, excessive Internet
surfing or e-mailing, and unauthorized distribution of proprietary
information have all led to pink slips.
</P>
<P>
   Every wired company should have a written policy that every
employee signs. At minimum, the e-policy should say:
</P>
<P>
   The company owns the system and has the right to monitor its
use.
</P>
<P>
   No employee should consider his or her messages or files to be
confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the delete key does not remove material from the entire
system.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail and Web access should not be used to exchange messages or
view files that co-workers may consider pornographic, lewd,
harassing, exploitative or embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail and Web access should not be used to solicit,
proselytize, promote or engage in any non-job-related causes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the policy should clearly lay out the disciplinary
process that will follow the discovery of violations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
