r a BC-PCS-KAN &LR;      08-24 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT PCS UNVEILS UPGRADES TO WIRELESS WEB SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Sprint PCS on Wednesday announced a series of
business-oriented upgrades to its Wireless Web service that speed
up Internet access and link mobile workers to corporate computer
networks through their wireless phones.
</P>
<P>
   Called Wireless Web for Business, the enhanced services include
a single price for unlimited wireless Internet access and a series
of network-based computer software applications that link workers
to corporate e-mail, sales and service records, corporate
directories and other areas.
</P>
<P>
   The new service, scheduled to be available next month, is
expected to give Sprint a leg up on the competition for highly
sought wireless corporate customers. That market is expected to
grow 1,000 percent in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year ago, we led the industry with the nationwide launch
of Sprint PCS Wireless Web,'' said Ronald T. LeMay, interim
president of Sprint PCS. ``Since that time, our national business
accounts have grown 285 percent. Now we're excited to build on the
tremendous consumer success of the Wireless Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the service and some computer programs already used by
some large companies, mobile workers will be able to access
customer records and phone logs, send and receive company e-mail,
make airline travel reservations and do other tasks that usually
would have to wait until they were back in the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view of this is that it's a great day for the road
warrior,'' said Paul Reddick, vice president for Sprint PCS product
management and development.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Sprint is improving Internet speed by using
software that compresses data. Currently, the company offers
service that runs at about one-quarter the speed of a
56-kilobit-per-second modem. Using new software and compression,
the system gives users the equivalent of 56K service, Reddick said.
</P>
<P>
   The service also makes it easier for laptop computer users to
connect to the Internet using their Sprint PCS phones and Sprint's
Wireless Web service, Reddick said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the program, Sprint PCS is offering a new pricing
plan for wireless Internet service _ $40 a month for unlimited
wireless Internet access for mid- and high-use phone customers. The
existing $10-a-month plan that allows customers to use their
regular monthly voice minutes for Internet use will remain for
consumers and other business users, Reddick said.
</P>
<P>
   The new service is a result of partnerships with some big
software companies: Lotus, Siebel Systems, Sabre Holdings Corp. and
others.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless Internet market is expected to reach about 885,000
business users by the end of this year. The Yankee Group, a Boston
telecommunications research firm, is projecting that the market
will grow almost tenfold _ to 8.2 million business users _ by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer wireless Internet market is expected to grow even
faster _ although it doesn't generate as much high-usage revenue.
According to the Yankee Group, about 390,000 consumers now use
wireless Internet service. That number is expected to reach 9.5
million in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The wireless Internet market is still new, but corporations are
just about ready to dive in, said Roberta Wiggins, director of
wireless data research for the Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wireless is moving up the line on the list of corporate
priorities,'' she said. ``They're very aware of the opportunities
and the benefits of connecting mobile workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improving software to speed up access will help draw more
customers by improving the customer experience.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of June, Sprint PCS had about 7.9 million customers.
The company has projected 10 million customers by Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, listed on the New York Exchange as PCS,
closed Wednesday at $47.88 a share, down $1.13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
