<SLUG> BC-PRICE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE CANDY CO.'S REMAINING ASSETS SOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Price Candy Co., a local institution for 87 years,
has melted into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Richmond factory and its assets were auctioned off
last week to pay off delinquent loans to Commerce Bank of Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce foreclosed on the factory in late April. Price Candy
closed its office and distribution center in Hunt Midwest
SubTropolis the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Among the assets auctioned off were Price Candy's trademarks,
real estate, inventory, packaging equipment and kitchen equipment.
An official with the auction company, Rabin Brothers of San
Francisco, called it ``a very good sale,'' although he was unable
to say how much the sale yielded.
</P>
<P>
   The sale marked the demise of a company founded by Charles Price
in 1913 in the old Jones Store building downtown. The company was
later owned by Price's son, Charles Price II, who became the U.S.
ambassador to the Court of St. James's in London during the Reagan
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Price II was out of town this week and not available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Price Candy went through a succession of owners in the past two
decades, remaining modestly profitable until the late 1990s. In
1982, Charles Price II sold it to a company run by Minnesota Twins
owner Carl Pohlad. Eight years later, Pohlad sold it to
Glico-Harmony Foods Corp. of Santa Cruz, Calif., a subsidiary of
Japanese confectioner Ezaki Glico.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Glico-Harmony sold Price Candy to four New York
investors involved in the food industry. The four sought to change
Price Candy's marketing strategy, with apparently disastrous
results.
</P>
<P>
   Previously a small, boxed-chocolate manufacturer with sales
around $20 million, Price Candy under its new owners sought to
compete in the mass market and began distributing other
confectioners' products. The mass merchandising effort failed, and
starting two years ago the company began hemorrhaging red ink.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, Price Candy employed 150 workers at area
facilities. The company also had sales representatives in Chicago
and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The company made candy under three brand names: Price's Fine
Chocolates, Blum's of San Francisco and The House of Bauer. It was
also the exclusive importer and distributor of the Les Cygnes line
of Belgian chocolates and a distributor of the Guylian line of
Belgian chocolate shells.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 0114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
