<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEITER GIVES WEARY METS JUST WHAT THEY NEED
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ When the New York Mets lost by 15 runs on Tuesday
and had to summon an outfielder to pitch, they knew their bullpen
would be depleted the next day. Speaking after that game, Al Leiter
seemed puzzled when asked if he would have to pitch any
differently, to conserve pitches to last deep into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's expression seemed to ask if his questioner had noticed
what he has done all year. Leiter, the Mets left-hander, has been
consistently durable and effective; of course he would not deviate
from that pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter worked eight innings in a 4-1 victory over the San Diego
Padres, allowing three hits and one run and matching a season high
with 12 strikeouts. When the Qualcomm Stadium public-address system
played The Cars' ``Just What I Needed'' in the seventh inning, it
seemed an appropriate anthem for what Leiter had given the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter improved to 14-5, and he lasted long enough that the Mets
had to use only one reliever, Armando Benitez, who recorded his
34th save. The Mets have an off-day Thursday, and they should have
a completely rested bullpen when they begin a three-game series
with the Arizona Diamondbacks at Shea Stadium on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of Leiter's first seven pitches was a strike, and the
eighth, to Damian Jackson, wound up over the fence in left-center
for a home run. The bases were empty when he hit it, because Leiter
had picked off the leadoff hitter, Eric Owens, after walking him.
Leiter has nine pickoffs, tied with Arizona's Brian Anderson for
the major league lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Jackson's home run, Leiter set down the next 14 Padres.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were thin in the bullpen after Tuesday's 16-1 loss,
which robbed them of their dignity _ outfielder Derek Bell gave up
the final five runs _ and their bullpen depth. They considered
promoting a pitcher as protection against a short start by Leiter,
but they have only one reserve with options, Joe McEwing.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Mets sent McEwing down, they could not have brought him
back for 10 days. ``McEwing is a pretty important part of the
group,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said, but he added,
``Hopefully, I won't regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   He would not. In Leiter, the Mets had the right pitcher to give
a lengthy outing. Leiter is third in the National League in pitches
per start, averaging 112, and he is having a season that rivals
that of any other pitcher in the league besides Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   If only Leiter could hit. He is batting .063, and twice he came
up with the bases loaded. In the fourth, he came up after Mike
Bordick grounded a single under the glove of the diving third
baseman, Phil Nevin, to drive in the Mets' first run. Had Leiter
simply struck out, Lenny Harris would have come up. But Leiter
bounced into a double play, ending the inning and keeping the score
tied, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had started to get to Matt Clement, the 26-year-old
right-hander who had baffled them twice this year. They went down
in the fifth, one-two-three, but two of those outs came on
highlight-worthy catches by Padres outfielders. And if the Mets
were not hitting Clement, they were laying off his sharp breaking
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Mike Piazza and Darryl Hamilton drew leadoff
walks. After an out, Benny Agbayani singled to load the bases, then
Clement hit Bordick, the second batter he hit with a pitch in the
game. The go-ahead run scored, and Leiter came up, chopping a bunt
back to Clement, who flipped home for a forceout. Catcher Wiki
Gonzalez threw to first and nearly doubled up Leiter, but the throw
hit Leiter and another run scored.
</P>
<P>
   Harris singled in another run, putting the Mets ahead, 4-1, and
Carlos Almanzar came in for Clement. He retired Bell on a pop-up,
ending the inning and extending a lengthy slump by Bell. In 50
at-bats since his dramatic, game-tying homer at Houston on Aug. 7,
Bell has five hits, a .100 average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
