<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S FOLLOW RHODES TO RUIN AGAINST TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Apparently, there are still a few bugs in the system.
</P>
<P>
   Far from Tuesday's victory putting to rest whatever it is that
ails the Mariners, the club came out Wednesday night and showed
that the dog days of August are still barking up a storm.
</P>
<P>
   The night started with hordes of flying ants, then smaller
gnats, swarming the field and sending the fans at Comerica Park
running for cover. The night ended, for all practical purposes, in
the seventh inning, when the Tigers' offense swarmed the Mariners'
bullpen, every bit as pesky and every bit as nasty as the bugs of
sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Rhodes, the most reliable of the Mariners' relievers, was
dissected with precision once again by the Tigers. This time
Detroit got four consecutive hits off him, including a game-tying
triple by Juan Encarnacion that swung the momentum of the game
firmly in the Tigers' direction.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 6-5 Tigers win and Seattle's ninth loss in 10
games. Things seemed to have regained some level of normalcy for
the Mariners when starter Paul Abbott pitched six strong innings as
a follow-up to Tuesday's 8-4 Seattle win. But Rhodes' implosion
changed all that.
</P>
<P>
   Or was it Rhodes?
</P>
<P>
   ``That was all my fault, not Arthur's,'' catcher Dan Wilson
said. ``He had good stuff. It's my job to call the pitches. It was
bad pitch selection on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   Fastballs are Rhodes' stock in trade, and fastballs are what
Wilson asked for. With the fastball crackling, Rhodes got ahead of
three of the four batters he faced with two quick strikes. Getting
that third strike _ or anything else resembling an out _ didn't
happen.
</P>
<P>
   So while the rest of his teammates were getting a bite to eat or
grabbing a shower, Wilson sat slumped in front of his locker in
game gray pants and a sweat-soaked, dark blue T-shirt. Based on
body language, you would have thought a pitch Wilson called for
cost the Mariners the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was all my fault,'' Wilson repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Well, no. As is the case with the Mariners' 70 wins this season,
it is a shared experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about this whole 1-9 stretch is that we've hung
together,'' Abbott said. ``We've won with 25 guys, and we've lost
with 25 guys. Tonight we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Mariners lost was no reflection on Abbott, who carried
a 4-1 lead into the seventh inning. But Deivi Cruz doubled and took
third on a Brad Ausmus fly ball. That's when manager Lou Piniella
motioned for Rhodes, who had been ineffective in two recent games
against the Tigers. Wednesday night, he took ineffective to a new
plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes got two strikes against Jose Macias, who then ripped an
RBI single on a 1-2 pitch. Wendell Magee singled and, after falling
behind 0-2, Encarnacion tripled, tying the game. Bobby Higginson
singled, giving the Tigers their first lead of the game. Later,
Jose Mesa would surrender a sacrifice fly that capped the five-run
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I be frustrated?'' Rhodes said. ``I've been
throwing good all year. I've been effective all year. I threw some
good pitches tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``''I wasn't out of my pattern. I was going with my catcher
(Wilson). I can't be frustrated because of one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Rhodes predicted a long night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one won't go away quickly,'' he said. ``This one will eat
at me all night, until tomorrow morning until I wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   One could guess that Wilson would feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Rhodes) got to 0-2 a lot,'' the manager said. ``He just
didn't put the hitters away.''
</P>
<P>
   But at one level, at least, Wilson said this loss was different
from any of the eight that comprised the losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't like any of those,'' Rhodes said. ``It was a
completely different feeling. We played well tonight. We just lost.
And that's a totally different feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, no different on the scoreboard. The Mariners
lost a chance to gain a game on Oakland, a 7-5 loser at Cleveland.
And giving away an opportunity to put ground between themselves and
Oakland gnawed at the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Even Abbott, who would have been justified at being upset at
seeing a win slip away from him, wasn't thinking along those lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being completely honest here,'' he said. ``I would have
been just as happy if we'd come back and won the game. That would
have been great with me, even if it means I don't get the win.
Oakland lost, and we had a chance to put some ground between us and
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Edgar Martinez was on the same wavelength. He
set a new career high with his 30th homer, a solo shot in the third
inning, but it seemed to mean little to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not anyone in this clubhouse that is thinking about
personal numbers now,'' Martinez said. ``The statistics don't
count.''
</P>
<P>
   One statistic does _ wins. And that statistic has been
frustratingly elusive for the Mariners of late.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
