<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOCHER'S INJURY COULD BE COSTLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ken Kocher, the 311-pound anchor of the defensive
line, sprained his left ankle in practice Tuesday and it took less
than 24 hours for the Bruins to feel his pain.
</P>
<P>
   Kocher, on crutches with his leg in a walking boot, was
conspicuous by his absence during Wednesday's scrimmage at the Rose
Bowl. The Bruins' second-team offense caved in defensive tackles
Rodney Leisle and Anthony Fletcher, creating huge holes for
third-string tailback Akil Harris, as it marched easily down the
field in its only crack at the first-team unit.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how much it will hurt if Kocher is on the sidelines in
the season opener against No. 3-ranked Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   While Kocher is holding out hope of playing against the Crimson
Tide in 10 days, coach Bob Toledo expects him to be out from two to
four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he finds a faith healer he may play,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Kocher might not be the only person who needs one.
</P>
<P>
   The junior is one of the best defensive tackles in the
conference and was certain to draw double teams. Now, Fletcher and
Leisle, who were sharing the other tackle spot, are on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll find out Saturday how they get moved out,'' Toledo said
of Fletcher and Leisle, who will be backed up by Steve Morgan and
Sean Phillips. ``There's a reason why (Kocher) is first string. The
second string guys have to pick it up, but any time you lose key
people, it's going to hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Kocher said the injury occurred on the final play of practice
Tuesday when a teammate rolled on his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it sort of pop,'' he said. ``I tried to walk it off.
I'm not ruling out playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-a-days done: The two-hour scrimmage, which didn't pit the
first- team units against one another, concluded two-a-day
practices and the Bruins will now begin to prepare in earnest for
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The fact the second-team defense gave up fewer big plays than in
Saturday's scrimmage at Drake Stadium was an encouraging sign.
</P>
<P>
   The scrimmage was held at the Rose Bowl to help the Bruins get
ready for the season opener. They worked on substitution
situations, the two-minute drill, kicking and punting, and had
coaches stationed in the press box and the sideline. The only thing
missing was the crowd and the emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody in the stands,'' Toledo said. ``They're sore,
beat up, tired, their legs aren't there and they're thinking about
moving out of the dorms today. I think we're ahead of last year,
but we've got a ways to go. How much better we'll be I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury report: Also missing from the first-team defense were end
Rusty Williams (thigh) and linebacker Ryan Nece (shoulder), the
latter participating in non-tackling situations. Tight end Gabe
Crecion (thigh) and receiver Brian Poli-Dixon (thigh) also saw
limited action.
</P>
<P>
   Bama names Zow: Alabama coach Mike DuBose announced that
incumbent Andrew Zow has won the starting quarterback job. However,
both Zow, a junior, and sophomore Tyler Watts will play against
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Williams returning?: Cornerback Julius Williams, who flunked out
of school this summer, said he will take extension classes this
fall and hopes to re-enroll in school for the winter quarter and
rejoin the team next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put myself and the team in an awkward situation,'' said
Williams, a junior who was expected to back up Jason Bell. ``I
messed up. I just feel bad that I put the team in a bad
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams must re-apply for admission. If he's accepted to
school, Toledo said he would consider accepting Williams back on
the team but noted that Williams ``dug himself a deep hole''
academically.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
