<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-EXPOS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN LOOKS LIKE GOLD FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For six innings Wednesday night, Kevin Brown made
Los Angeles Dodgers fans forget where they were.
</P>
<P>
   On a cool August night in a season that is slipping away, Brown
had everyone on their feet believing when he retired the first 18
batters he faced in a 5-1 victory over the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the ace who has struggled the past month like the rest of
the team, shook off getting hit on the right index finger on a bunt
attempt in the fifth inning and looked like he might, just might,
throw the Dodger's first perfect game since Sandy Koufax 35 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought it was going to happen with the way he was
rolling,'' second baseman Mark Grudzielanek said. ``It would have
been great for all of us with how badly everything has gone this
year. It would have been something to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the victory, the Dodgers remain eight games back in
the National League West with 37 to play. But on this night, all
that mattered was Brown (11-5) did not allow a batter to reach base
until former Dodgers farmhand Peter Bergeron opened the seventh
with a sharp liner off the glove of third baseman Adrian Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to go out there and get a hit,'' Bergeron
said. ``Everyone knew he had a no-hitter. He was going right after
people, throwing strikes and getting ground balls.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos went on to score after doubles by Jose Vidro and Lee
Stevens, but it didn't stop the crowd of 31,337 from a standing
ovation. Brown, who pitched a no-hitter in 1997 at San Francisco
when he played for the Florida Marlins, left after allowing the
first two batters to reach base in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stay in the game, but my finger had started to
swell up the past few innings,'' said Brown, who had not won in
five starts. ``But I'm not going to blame that. You just go out
there every game trying to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The result Wednesday was eye popping, but Brown's catcher said
nothing surprises him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of guy who could throw a no-hitter every time he
goes out,'' catcher Todd Hundley said of Brown. ``I've never caught
a no-hitter. I went 8 three times, with David Cone, Bret Saberhagen
and Frank Tanana. It would have taken a spectacular play by Beltre
to catch that ball. But that is the kind of play you need to have a
no-hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Dodgers got all the runs they needed in the
fourth off right-hander Mark Thurman (3-4), who actually retired
the first 10 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored three times in the fourth and two unearned
runs in the fifth after a throwing error by Thurman. But it was
Thurman's pitch that inning that struck Brown on the right hand
that almost ended the no hitter.
</P>
<P>
   On the same play back in May against the Mets, Brown suffered a
fractured right pinkie and spent two weeks on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson, who underwent surgery on his left
rotator cuff Tuesday, rushed to Brown behind home plate. But Brown
remained in the game and walked to first to begin another rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared because of what had happened before,'' Brown
said. ``It turned out OK.''
</P>
<P>
   If fans thought they saw this game before, they were right. Only
the names and uniforms have been changed.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 10, 1998, Brown, then a member of the San Diego Padres,
threw six perfect innings against the Dodgers at Qualcomm Stadium.
Eric Young then opened the seventh by reaching on an error,
Trenidad Hubbard walked and Eric Karros reached on an infield
single.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers wound up scoring four runs, two each on RBI singles
by Bobby Bonilla and Grudzielanek. Brown retired the final seven
batters, but lost 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the game-winning hit in that game didn't I?''
Grudzielanek said. ``When Brownie is pitching like he did tonight,
he is the only one you remember.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
