<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0770 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-ANALYSIS-LADN     08-24 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC HOPES IT HAS THE ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC flies to New Jersey today, with 17 days of
football practice behind it, but on the eve of the Trojans' season
opener against Penn State, there still seem to be nearly as many
questions as when they opened training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, the Trojans are drawing plenty of praise,
certainly enough to warrant being ranked 15th in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Carson Palmer is back. Tailback Sultan McCullough
gained 154 yards in a scrimmage last week. Wide receiver Kareem
Kelly has continued where he left off as the Pacific-10 Freshman of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, with nine starters returning, is formidable at
nearly every position. Along the defensive line, there's a healthy
Ennis Davis for the first time in two years. Linebackers Zeke
Moreno and Markus Steele are poised for dominating seasons. And the
secondary, despite missing Antuan Simmons, will have plenty of
experience.
</P>
<P>
   But what do the sum of all these better-than-average parts add
up to?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question that not even USC coaches can answer, and one
reason the Trojans are so eager to start their season in the
Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things we need to find out. What's the
chemistry of this team when it gets behind? Or when they get ahead
by 21 points?'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``After the first two
or three games, we'll get a better feeling for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   At least USC will know more Sunday night than it did a year ago
at this time. Its 62-7 victory over Hawaii only raised expectations
for what turned out to be a disappointing 6-6 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we beat Hawaii last year, it was not the measure of us as
a team,'' Hackett said. ``We'll know (this year) after two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not stopping the preseason publications from going crazy,
with one already proclaiming USC will finish 12-0. As ridiculous as
that sounds, you could make an equally strong case that even with a
relatively easy schedule, a couple slip-ups and the Trojans are 8-4
or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, how many really thought they would be 6-6 last season?
Palmer's broken collarbone aside, USC blew a pair of 21-point leads
that helped send the season into a spiral.
</P>
<P>
   So here are the main concerns as the Trojans prepare to meet the
Nittany Lions on national television?
</P>
<P>
   1. Do they have a kicker? Has this glaring weakness been fixed?
Uh, maybe. Who knows? Junior David Newbury won the job, but he was
only 11 of 20 last season, and has had good-and-bad moments in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hackett believes Newbury has improved, there will be
lots of nervous expressions on the USC sideline when Newbury lines
up for his first field goal against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Just to make sure he doesn't lose confidence early, don't expect
any 53-yard attempts in the Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   2. Can they run?: The coaching staff has been heartened by
McCullough's improvement, but like Newbury, it's only a hunch until
the season starts. There's also legitimate questions about whether
the other tailbacks - Malaefou MacKenzie, Petros Papadakis - will
remain injury free.
</P>
<P>
   3. Can they stop the run? This wasn't supposed to be a question
mark, with an experienced defense, but last week's shaky moments in
the scrimmage have made this a slightly worrisome issue.
</P>
<P>
   4. Are the Trojans mentally tough? Last year, USC blew a pair of
21-point leads, the third time that has happened in two seasons
under Hackett. With Palmer healthy, and a veteran leadership, it
shouldn't happen this season. But that's what everyone thought last
year.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. Players have been on the same page during
training camp, without the usual ego problems that have been
present in previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did in training camp was amazing in terms of intensity
and focus,'' Palmer said. ``It really surprised me.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Has the offensive line improved? This has been a problem area
for four years running, but is supposed to better this year. As
long as you erase the six false starts in the first scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   But more importantly, the Trojans seem solid at nearly every
position, without a true weak link. Left guard Zach Wilson could
become a dominant player, and it eased some concerns that Faasea
Mailo nailed down the right tackle spot, because he started several
games there in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else concerning this team, however, none of it
will really make a difference until the team starts performing at a
high level in an actual game.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the coaches are just hoping that the signs of
improvement they think they saw in training camp will actually
translate into success on the field. Or at least a well-fought
effort against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, what's important is to play well,'' Hackett said. ``We
need to set the standard for our season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
