<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 03:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0774 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-REDSOX-LAD     08-24 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-REDSOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE VAUGHN, ANGELS END TRIP WITH LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mo Vaughn hit his first home run in Fenway Park since
he left after the 1998 season, but it was the only run the Anaheim
Angels could muster against five Boston Red Sox pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 3-1 Angels loss Wednesday in the final game of
a nine-game East Coast road trip.
</P>
<P>
   The evening started with a three-hour, one-minute rain delay and
finished with the loss that left the Angels at 4-5 on the trip. But
they remain in a pennant race, trailing the American League
West-leading Mariners by 5 games and the wild card-leading Indians
by 3 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look back at the road trip as a block of games,''
Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``Tonight we had a chance to win
the ballgame and we didn't get it done. Historically, going back
East we know we're in for some tough ballgames. We played three
tough teams and those teams don't give an inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we went one game under .500, but we know one
twist or turn and it could have been better.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn went 5 for 13 in the series and had three of the Angels'
eight hits Wednesday. They had chances, but went 0 for 5 with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of opportunities to score and couldn't get the
key hit,'' Scioscia said. ``And obviously, they did.''
</P>
<P>
   All three Red Sox runs came in on two-out hits, but they didn't
score after the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of offense spoiled a solid outing by starter Ramon
Ortiz (4-4). Ortiz gave up three runs and five hits in 7 innings,
the fourth time in his past five starts he has pitched at least
seven innings. But he still is being watched by Scioscia and
pitching coach Bud Black.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz can get overly excited, which often works against him. He
gets fidgety on the mound, reflected by his four balks, second most
in the league despite pitching most of the season in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked with Ramon between starts again,'' Scioscia said.
``His composure is very important as it correlates with his
success. He understands the importance of it. An asset for him is
going hard every pitch. But with that intensity, he has to temper
it, find a middle ground and get the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox scored an unearned run in the first inning, getting
a little help from the wet grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Daubach was on first base with two outs when Carl Everett
singled to center. But the ball skipped on the wet grass past
center fielder Garret Anderson for an error, allowing Daubach to
score and Everett to reach second.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox scored two more in the third, both runs scoring with
two outs. Daubach singled home Jose Offerman and Everett followed
with a single, moving Daubach to third. Troy O'Leary then made it
three consecutive singles, knocking home Daubach for a 3-0 Red Sox
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the game things didn't go right for him, with the
errors, but he settled down and pitched a terrific ballgame,''
Scioscia said. ``It was the kind of outing we're looking for from
Ramon. As he gets more experience that's the kind of outing he'll
give us more consistently.'' Vaughn's homer leading off the fourth
inning was a tape-measure blast to center estimated at 430 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit a lot of balls like that in this ballpark, to dead
center field,'' Vaughn said. ``That's the only thing I remember,
it's not meaningful because it came against Boston. It's just, I've
seen that trajectory before.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox starter Tomo Ohka lasted only 5 innings, but allowed
only the homer by Vaughn and four other meaningless hits.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Beck, Rheal Cormier and Rich Garces set up Derek Lowe, who
pitched the ninth for his 29th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a solid road trip,'' Vaughn said. ``We're still
right there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
