<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 08:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0789 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-FOX-AZR &LR;      08-24 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOX-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-FOX-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    FOX IS `BREATH OF FRESH AIR,' BUT FEW EXPECTING MUCH(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By TESSIE BORDEN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Activists on both sides of the immigration fence are
referring to the U.S. visit by Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox
Quesada as a golden opportunity for a new dialogue. But few expect
any real developments.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, the first opposition candidate to wrest the Mexican
presidency from the long-entrenched Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, today comes to Washington to meet with President
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Fox will go to Dallas to meet with Republican
presidential nominee George W. Bush. He spent the early part of the
week in Canada, where he met with Prime Minister Jean Chretien, as
well as bankers and entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of the visits, Fox revealed more details of proposed
immigration and development plans to reporters in Mexico. The
initiatives included gradually opening the U.S.-Mexican border,
establishing a fund through the North American Free Trade Agreement
that would resemble the European Union's $35 billion-a-year
development fund and allowing Mexican drug-trafficking suspects to
be extradited to the United States for trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to say he's a breath of fresh air,'' said Frank
Sharry, executive director of the National Immigration Forum, a
policy think tank. ``We've had some excellent people working on
these issues through the years, but they always seem to get pushed
to the side by the trade discussion. Fox is going to elevate the
migration debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Isabel Garcia, of the Tucson-based, pro-immigrant Coalicion de
Derechos Humanos, agreed. But she is wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, when we began to hear some of the things he was
saying throughout the campaign we were pretty shocked,'' Garcia
said. ``They're some of the things we've been saying all along. I'm
happy Fox is engaged in this kind of discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Garcia said her group's optimism and support for Fox is
not unqualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where we sit we blame both governments for the lack of
progress on this issue through the years,'' she said, adding that
Mexico did little for emigrating workers under the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want tighter immigration controls welcome that Fox is
pushing the issue to the forefront, but say his agenda conflicts
with U.S. goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a good opportunity,'' said David Ray, spokesman
for the Federation for American Immigration Reform. ``But Mr. Fox
seems to think we have a common interest in immigration. While
Mexico thinks that more immigration is in its best interests, most
Americans think that less immigration would be a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said Mexico needs to get a handle on its endemic corruption
problems before talking about economic development.
</P>
<P>
   His Arizona counterpart, Bob Park, was more combative, saying
Fox was ``way, way, way out of line'' in his visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should simply butt out,'' Park said. ``Fox doesn't need to
come up here to tell us what our immigration agenda should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Park also was pessimistic about prospects for reform in a
government many consider corrupt to the core and expressed doubts
about Fox's ability to deal with Mexican drug-trafficking cartels
or even to finish his term.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much power and too much money involved in the
drugs,'' Park said. ``He'd have to make some drastic and dramatic
changes, and I don't think he'll live long enough to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox last week outlined several initiatives in news conferences
and interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be better friends, we must be better neighbors, we
must be better partners,'' he said about the often-troubled
relationship between the two nations. ``By building up walls, by
putting up armies, by dedicating billions of dollars like every
border state is doing to avoid migration, is not the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the ideas he advanced was the prospect of someday
abandoning the borders separating all three North American nations,
a prospect that alarmed Washington pundits and activists alike.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox hinged the proposal on a platform of greater economic
parity between the United States and Mexico and suggested
establishing a development fund to first ramp up Mexican economic
growth so both nations would be on more even ground. A similar fund
helped cut immigrant flows from poor to rich countries of the EU,
Fox contended.
</P>
<P>
   About 150,000 Mexicans emigrate illegally to the United States
each year, and about 3 million of the 7.1million Mexicans in the
United States live here illegally, according to figures from the
Center for Immigration Studies.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects Fox's visit to lead to any major policy moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that we're on the verge of our own elections and our own
change of national leadership, there's probably a sense of `let's
see what the next president and the next Congress believes,''' said
Arturo Vargas, of the National Association of Latino Elected
Officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 0801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0792 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV27-C     08-24 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE COMING CELLULAR CRUNCH
 &HT;    Moving in the (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Aug. 27.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once the knock on Southern California was too much
bad air and not enough water. But soon crowded Californians, among
others, could suffer even more from a scarcity of spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated visitors to the Democratic National Convention got a
glimpse of the future when they sought, in large numbers, to use
their ``roaming'' cell phones in Los Angeles. What they often got
was the cellular equivalent of freeway gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Spectrum governs the wireless world. The federal government
gives it away to TV and radio licensees. The feds also gobble up
huge chunks for military communications, satellite services and the
like.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Federal Communications Commission has
auctioned off pieces of available spectrum, seeking to earn
billions of dollars for the taxpayers. Unhappily, some buyers
overpaid and went broke. These dormant allocations, now tied up in
Congress and in the courts, are like fallow fields reclaimed by the
bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Come September, the FCC plans to try again, putting up for bid
some of the sweetest spectrum around. At one time, the regulators
hoped to raise $50 billion from the coming sale, which would match
the current record, raised by the German government this month.
</P>
<P>
   Such a choice parcel of wireless real estate is just what's
needed to build out what the telecoms call 3G networks. These
third-generation mobile systems already enjoy a firm grip on the
airwaves in Europe and parts of Asia. They enable cell phones to
surf the Internet at high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a hitch. In most large markets, these wavelengths
are already in use. In regulatory jargon, the FCC sale is ``on the
encumbered basis.''
</P>
<P>
   That means winning bidders must find ways to coax the TV
stations that occupy those slices of the UHF band (channels 60 to
69) to give up their frequencies.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Congress nor the FCC, knowing where their political
bread is buttered, show any interest in getting the broadcasters to
move elsewhere or to go off the air. Unhappily, the pickings on the
remainder of the band have become a lot slimmer after Congress in
1996 reserved the remaining (14 to 59) UHF slots for digital
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   In the Washington-Baltimore region, down a notch from the
largest urban markets, 34 of these 45 UHF channels are already
allotted. All major stations here transmit separate VHF and UHF
signals, usually airing identical fare. And nobody seems in a hurry
to give the VHF channels back to the feds by 2006, as called for
under the original deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have led the telecommunications revolution in the world
because we encouraged innovation and competition,'' says Reed
Hundt, a former FCC chairman. ``The spectrum shortage,'' he adds,
``threatens that policy when it comes to wireless.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 85 percent of U.S. households watch UHF stations on either
cable or satellite, lawmakers could ease the crunch by letting
broadcasters go off the air but still retain their current local
``must carry'' cable rights.
</P>
<P>
   A more likely result: nobody budges, the new FCC auction proves
a bust and Europeans surge even further ahead of Americans on the
mobile phone front.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
