<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE COMING CELLULAR CRUNCH
 &HT;    Moving in the (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Aug. 27.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once the knock on Southern California was too much
bad air and not enough water. But soon crowded Californians, among
others, could suffer even more from a scarcity of spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated visitors to the Democratic National Convention got a
glimpse of the future when they sought, in large numbers, to use
their ``roaming'' cell phones in Los Angeles. What they often got
was the cellular equivalent of freeway gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Spectrum governs the wireless world. The federal government
gives it away to TV and radio licensees. The feds also gobble up
huge chunks for military communications, satellite services and the
like.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Federal Communications Commission has
auctioned off pieces of available spectrum, seeking to earn
billions of dollars for the taxpayers. Unhappily, some buyers
overpaid and went broke. These dormant allocations, now tied up in
Congress and in the courts, are like fallow fields reclaimed by the
bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Come September, the FCC plans to try again, putting up for bid
some of the sweetest spectrum around. Athe VHF channels back to the
feds by 2006, as called for under the original deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have led the telecommunications revolution in the world
because we encouraged innovation and competition,'' says Reed
Hundt, a former FCC chairman. ``The spectrum shortage,'' he adds,
``threatens that policy when it comes to wireless.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 85 percent of U.S. households watch UHF stations on either
cable or satellite, lawmakers could ease the crunch by letting
broadcasters go off the air but still retain their current local
``must carry'' cable rights.
</P>
<P>
   A more likely result: nobody budges, the new FCC auction proves
a bust and Europeans surge even further ahead of Americans on the
mobile phone front.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
