<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN27-COX     08-24 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Cohen brings sanity to Defense debate
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen has brought a welcome moment of
sanity to a presidential campaign shouting match about miliary
spending and readiness that was threatening to get wildly out of
hand. With luck, Cohen's comments will discipline the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The issues are legitimate and, anyway, inevitable. Defense has
figured in every presidential campaign since World War II. (And
before, for that matter, when an isolationist Congress was
resisting President Franklin Roosevelt's efforts to prepare for the
inevitable.)
</P>
<P>
   The partisan wrangling has as often distorted as it has
illuminated the issues. John Kennedy was elected on fear-mongering
claims of a missile gap between us and the Soviets that didn't
exist. Richard Nixon tried to panic the nation over the fate of two
meaningless islands _ Quemoy and Matsu _ off the China coast. Jimmy
Carter was denied re-election as supposedly the wimp of the western
world when in fact his administration began development of many of
the gee-whiz weapons that would star in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan played the defense issue like a master fiddler
with a Stradivarius, to mixed results. His anything-goes military
budgets helped to spend a decaying Soviet economic system and its
stressed military into deserved oblivion but left us with record
deficits we'll be decades paying off, if we ever do.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has picked up Reagan's old Strad but he's no
Reagan. He's sawing out squeaks with his claims that the U.S.
military is in such sorry shape that two of its divisions couldn't
even be deployed should the need arise and that the armed services
are a sink of lousy morale.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military is the world's most richly funded. It has no
close competitor in skill, technology or firepower. The Joint
Chiefs of Staff say all the divisions are ready. And now Cohen has
weighed in, though reluctantly as a Republican himself and
carefully, in ways to keep his office and the Pentagon politically
neutral.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense secretary notes that military budget declines began
with Reagan and continued _ and were at their steepest _ under
President Bush. Military spending has turned up in recent years,
and President Clinton approved the biggest military pay increase in
a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has supported, at Vice President Gore's specific urging,
a $127 billion increase over 10 years. Re-enlistments have turned
around and are rising again.
</P>
<P>
   A fair argument can be made that the Clinton administration was
slow to sober up from the heady days when both parties were living
it up on the post-Cold War ``peace dividend.'' Cohen and the joint
chiefs, although acknowledging the upturn, argue that still more is
needed to meet our increasingly complex superpower obligations.
</P>
<P>
   There's room aplenty there for candidate Bush to challenge the
Clinton administration record, without partisan overkill that
misleads voters and, perhaps dangerously, rattles our allies and
heartens our enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
