<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN27-CO     08-24 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Sitting in anticipation of a Big One
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Aug. 27, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Jack's in San Francisco; I'm down here, at the appendage
of the United States. We talk often, about earthquakes and
hurricanes. I always tell my West coast friend that living in an
earthquake-prone area is more comfortable than being in a
hurricane-prone one because earthquakes don't visibly creep up on
you, day-by-day, mile-by-mile.
</P>
<P>
   With an earthquake, it's BOOM!, and that's it (except for the
aftershocks.)
</P>
<P>
   While an earthquake always is on his mind, a hurricane not only
haunts me but is made more disturbing by the fact that today's
technology can spot one slipping off the African coast, thereby
initiating a day-by-day, hour-by-hour tracking that consumes and
escalates several weeks of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't come with an earthquake. Certainly there's
anticipation of both, but you can see the hurricane working its way
toward you.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when weather forecasters didn't have satellites
to find embryonic zephyrs of wind and rain below the Azores. Now
they pipe that information to rabid TV news departments that begin
immediate tracking and remind people to stock up on batteries,
water, tuna fish and the like _ even before they have any idea of
whether the storm will reach the western hemisphere, or toddle off
toward Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   People deal with hurricanes in one of two ways: wisely and not
so wisely.
</P>
<P>
   When then Hurricane Debby began approaching Hispaniola and Cuba,
it appeared a sure shot that she eventually would take a slap at
South Florida. Then, the people who are not so wise flooded
supermarkets and building supply stores looking for bottles of
water, canisters of propane, plywood -- anything that is necessary
to protect life and property during and after a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   The lines were immense and the pickings slim.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who, like the wise little piggy who built his house
of bricks, did our hurricane supply purchasing at the very start of
hurricane season, June 1, sat back and observed the frustration and
dismay of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm off to the store,'' a daughter-in-law called in,
``anything I can get for you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a thing my dear, I did my Christmas shopping early.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Debby jilted the Miami area (on the eighth anniversary of
the day the monster Hurricane Andrew jolted it) and the lines have
subsided. Debby could become someone else's problem but, now, even
the Miami procrastinators are stocked up in case an Ernesto,
Florence, Gordon or Helene comes along.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Ernesto will start up somewhere, maybe in the Atlantic,
perhaps in the Caribbean, and we will begin the hour-by-hour
tracking, tuning to our weather telecasters who tell us not to
panic but to go out and get that canned tuna fish. Well, we all
have it now.
</P>
<P>
   Jack, over in San Francisco, doesn't have to deal with this,
doesn't have an earthquake season, just has to sit and wait for
something sudden to whack him and his property.
</P>
<P>
   We wonder which is worse. As a Hurricane Andrew victim, I
believe watching these monster storms descend upon us is as
terrible as it can get. Jack, a 1989 earthquake survivor, feels the
other way. He doesn't like the idea of his house coming down on him
suddenly, without warning.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose there's argument for both and there's certainly fear
of both. But at least earthquake-prone citizens don't have to
listen to rabid local TV anchors who, when a tropical depression
off Africa's west coast is still closer to Cairo than it is to
Miami, proclaim as their opening news headline: ``Alberto inches
closer to South Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Alberto, by the way, is the one that got closer to Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
