<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-OLYMPICS-$ADV27     08-24 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-OLYMPICS-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OLYMPIC DREAMS FOR CHINA'S WOMEN WEIGHLIFTERS GOES BEYOND
WINNING THE GOLD
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Ding Meiyuan likes to go out in a nice dress and feel
pretty, but those thoughts will have to wait at least another
month. She is preparing for the Olympics, and at 227 pounds, her
biggest concern is that she'll lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me now, eating is first; training is second,'' she said
after a workout one afternoon recently.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old fisherman's daughter is the women's
weightlifting world champion in the super-heavyweight division, 75
kilograms and over. Some say that makes her the world's strongest
woman. But she is not the heaviest.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the slimmest of all her competitors,'' said Wei Di, who
heads the weightlifting program. ``The rest of them weigh at least
265 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's weightlifting will make its debut as an Olympic sport
next month at Sydney. With world records in four of the seven
weight classes, China's team is heavily favored to win several gold
medals.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the women on China's national team come from peasant
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese women are good at enduring hardships,'' Wei said.
``For those from the countryside, this is a path to a better
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ding grew up in a fishing village near the port city of Dalian
in northeastern China. Like many on the team, she started training
when she was just 12, after a coach decided she had the right body
type and convinced her to enroll in a state-run sports school,
which is where almost all Chinese Olympic athletes are trained.
</P>
<P>
   After a few years on the Liaoning provincial team, she moved up
to the national team at age 15. At 19, she won three gold medals
and broke two world records at the 1998 Asian Games in Bangkok.
Last November, she won the world championship in Athens, Greece.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't the only Chinese woman picking up medals in Bangkok.
She and her teammates won all seven weightlifting gold medals and
broke world records seven days in a row.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Liaoning Daily newspaper, the women's
weightlifting team has not shown its true strength in international
competitions for fear of dominating the sport too heavily and
jeopardizing the chances of it becoming an Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   Ding's strongest rival is Agata Wrobel, the 19-year-old world
record-holder from Poland.
</P>
<P>
   As for the American team, ``there's one kid who's pretty good,''
said Zhang Wenxi, the women's weightlifting coach.
</P>
<P>
   At 17 and 300 pounds, Cheryl Haworth of Savannah, Ga., is the
U.S. national champion and America's best chance for a women's
weightlifting medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she can maybe get a bronze,'' Zhang added.
</P>
<P>
   Since China has been allotted just four slots for women's
weightlifting, Zhang and Wei say they are still deciding on the
final line-up, which will be announced August 27. Everything from
competitors' performances to menstrual cycles are being factored
into the equation.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on the team to win gold has been building. With
recent injuries and doping scandals in swimming, diving and track
and field _ high-profile events for which China had high Olympic
hopes _ women's weightlifting is one of the few events China feels
confident about.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese state-run media have been talking about a gold medal
sweep for all four women. Zhang says he feels secure about at least
three golds.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic medals also come with financial rewards in China's
state-sponsored sports system. Gold medalists will receive 80,000
yuan, or almost US$10,000, which is the equivalent of 20 years'
income for many farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But sports is starting to get commercial sponsorship too. For
example, all athletes who win medals will be required to wear
clothing from Chinese manufacturer Li Ning during the medal
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The weightlifting team, so far has not attracted much corporate
backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are not very interested in weightlifting,'' Wei
said. ``We hope after these Olympics we'll get more support.''
</P>
<P>
   But first, they have to get the gold.
</P>
<P>
   The women's team works out three to five hours a day at a
Beijing gym. Ranging in age from 19 to 26, they repeatedly hoist
barbells to their chests and over their heads. For several hours
each week, they also do mental exercises, which Zhang says involves
deep breathing and recalling their best performances from the past.
</P>
<P>
   The team has experts in Chinese medicine monitoring each athlete
and giving them pills made of ginseng and deer antler to enrich
their blood and energy levels.
</P>
<P>
   On average, Ding lifts more than 30,000 pounds a day. To sustain
her, she eats four meals a day and snacks as much as she wants to.
Her arms are big, but her thighs are massive.
</P>
<P>
   At first, building bulk was hard on her psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be skinny,'' she said. ``I weighed only 40 kilograms
(88 pounds).''
</P>
<P>
   After getting big, ``I didn't like to go outside because I
thought I was too fat. I felt like everyone was looking at me,''
she said. ``But now, doing this sport, I have to be like this.
After I stop training I'll lose weight.''
</P>
<P>
   One thought keeps her going when she longs to be thin again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about when I'm in Australia getting my medal,
listening to China's anthem, how other girls won't be able to do
this,'' Ding said.
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (1 kg  &QC;  2.2 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
