<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0899 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0825-CO     08-24 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Scientists prove it's not the cheeseburgers; it's lack of sleep
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I will turn 45 in a few days. I am
alarmingly healthy, far more than I deserve, though I have the
normal aches and pains, as well as that male thickening of the
middle. Nothing terribly gross, but I'm carrying 10 pounds extra
that just won't go away. I go through spasms of exercise and good
resolutions. Lately, I've been walking two miles early most
mornings, doing 175 situps, only eating one cheeseburger a week,
drinking light beer and staying out of the breakfast to-go line at
McDonalds on consecutive days. What can I say? I'm a health nut.
</P>
<P>
   It has had absolutely no effect on the dun-loppin', as my late
father-in-law called it, because the belly roll lops over your
belt. I suppose brisk exercise makes me feel better, though I can't
really tell because I'm too sleepy at 6 a.m. And it sure does make
me hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a story in the Journal of the American Medical Association
says the belly roll is not my fault. It's because I don't get
enough sleep. I am going through the change of life.
</P>
<P>
   A medical study of 149 healthy men showed that as they enter
mid-life, most lose the ability to sleep deeply. That means they
generate a lesser amount of growth hormones, which leads to reduced
production of muscle and an increase in fat.
</P>
<P>
   The scientific term is somatopause, the male version of
menopause. And the age at when all this hormonal weirdness kicks in
is, you guessed it, 45. I can't wait for the hot flashes.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that as I've gotten older, I don't sleep as long or
as well, though it doesn't particularly bother me. Six or seven
hours of sleep is plenty most days. It is also true that I thrash
around in my sleep, wake up several times a night and have been
banished to the couch on many occasions because I allegedly snore
like a freight train. This is an allegation I've never been able to
confirm since I'm asleep while snoring, though there are a number
of earwitnesses.
</P>
<P>
   And given my modest stature, it's quite obvious that my growth
hormones quit working at about the age of 13, when I had my final
growth spurt to hit five-feet, six inches. As I head down the back
side of middle age, I will begin to shrink so that by the time I'm
90, assuming I'm still around, I'll be sitting on telephone books
to see over the steering wheel. At the rate it's going, I will be
as wide as I am tall and will do a lot of yawning by my ninth
decade.
</P>
<P>
   The wire story from which I got this information says doctors
are developing medication that induces deep sleep, which in turn
allows the body to produce the growth hormone. I'm going to get
this stuff, being a firm believer in better living through
chemistry. It's entirely possible that, besides actually being able
to sleep for more than four straight hours, these miracle drugs
could induce a growth spurt in me. By age 50 I could be
six-feet-tall, which means I would be nearly as tall as the rest of
the people in my house, also known as the land of giants. And a
modest 10 pounds of extra weight doesn't show up as much on someone
who's six-inches taller than me.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I really don't want to be taller. After more than 30
years of viewing the world from the same height, I'm not interested
in changing my perspective. That is the same reason I don't have
surgery so I wouldn't have to wear glasses. I know many people
who've had the surgery and swear by it. But I am so used to wearing
glasses that not having to do so would drive me nuts. I would not
know what to do with my hands, which now occupy spare moments
pushing glasses back up my nose and polishing the lenses.
</P>
<P>
   There's something peaceful about lying down in bed and taking
off your glasses. The world suddenly becomes blurry and indistinct
and retreats into the background, as if you've turned down a dimmer
switch and draped gauze over everything. It's a peaceful feeling.
I'm convinced sleep would come even harder if I could actually see
without glasses, because the world would remain in sharp focus, far
too close for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, then I would be able to find my way to the refrigerator
for a midnight snack, and that certainly wouldn't help the weight
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
