<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Friday, August 25, 2000 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I will turn 45 in a few
days. I am alarmingly healthy, far more than I deserve, though I
have the normal aches and pains, as well as that male thickening of
the middle. Nothing terribly gross, but I'm carrying 10 pounds
extra that just won't go away. I go through spasms of exercise and
good resolutions. Lately, I've been walking two miles early most
mornings, doing 175 situps, only eating one cheeseburger a week,
drinking light beer and staying out of the breakfast to-go line at
McDonalds on consecutive days. What can I say? I'm a health nut.
(Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ His daddy taught school before
going to Congress, Democrat Al Gore told the Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles last week. His mom worked her way through
law school waitressing. ``When I visit a school and see a
hard-working teacher trying to change the world one child at a
time, I see the face of my father,'' Gore said. ``When I see a
waitress working hard and thanking someone for a tip, I see the
face of my mother. ``And I know: for that waitress carrying trays
or a construction worker in the winter cold, I will never agree to
raise the retirement age to 70 or threaten the promise of Social
Security. It's not fair to them, and I won't do it.'' He'll stand
up to ``big tobacco, big oil, the big polluters, the pharmaceutical
companies, the HMOs.'' It's about populism, stupid. (McNeely,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ I've known many porch cats. They
are drawn to the hedge at our home and the fact that it generally
doesn't take too much wheedling for some cat chow and water to make
it out the front door.
</P>
<P>
   Porch cats come and go, some nameless. Then there were others:
Oopsie, with one eyelid that didn't work right. Snowball, who
became a fat farm cat when we found a family with a barn for her.
There was skinny Spice, a veritable teen who gave birth to three in
a discarded box in our driveway. When fire ants stormed, we hustled
the mom and newborns inside. Two of the kittens have stayed to this
day. (John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED.
</P>
