<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maintain proper tire air pressure to beat the heat
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Unless you have been under a rock or on a deserted
tropical island, you have heard of Firestone's tire recall.
Hopefully, regardless of what brand of tire your vehicle wears, you
have heeded warnings to maintain the proper air pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling across many Southern states this summer, I have
noticed a marked increase in the population of interstate
alligators _ you know, those carcasses of big truck tires in the
middle of the road. I blame the increase on one thing: heat.
</P>
<P>
   So why is proper tire inflation so important in the summer heat?
</P>
<P>
   An underinflated tire actually drags across the road surface,
and that builds up heat. You may have seen a slow-motion replay of
a dragster's rear tire when it is going through its burnout
process. You will notice that the tire side wrinkles as the tire
rotates.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what the driver is trying to do. Hot tires become
soft and gluelike for the driver's less-than-10-second run.
</P>
<P>
   Extensive heat on passenger-car tires also makes them soft, but
for more prolonged driving, that means tire failure.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us don't take the road surface temperature into
consideration when it comes to our tires. We should. Go to a NASCAR
race on practice and qualifying day, and you will see tire
engineers probing the tire's tread surface and the racetrack
surface as well to determine their temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for the track surface to exceed 130 degrees
when the air temperature is in the low 90s. With many areas now
facing summer heat near the three-digit mark, it is safe to assume
that our road surfaces are much hotter.
</P>
<P>
   Speed also increases tire temperatures. The faster tires rotate
against the road surface, the more heat they build up.
</P>
<P>
   So what can we do help protect ourselves from tire failure
during these hot summer months?
</P>
<P>
   We can't control the weather, and road surface temperatures are
out of our control, but we can consider slowing down and
maintaining our tires' proper air pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey conducted for the AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety,
experts determined that some 82 percent of American drivers claim
to check their tire pressure regularly. That is good.
</P>
<P>
   What is bad is that most of them don't know what the proper
inflation is. Some 46 percent cited the tire pressure marked on the
sidewall of their tire as the proper pressure. But that number
indicates the tire's maximum pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Your tires should be inflated to the vehicle manufacturer's
recommendation printed on the driver's side door sill placard or in
the owner's manual.
</P>
<P>
   It is very important that you always check when your tires are
cold, after the vehicle has been sitting for at least a few hours.
Checking air pressures on hot tires will give you false readings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
