r f BC-THE-MECHANIC0825-C0X     08-24 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC0825-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sparkling shop a mechanic's paradise
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A natural extension of my job as an automotive service
technology instructor is to match the student to a position that
will provide an advantageous union between the student and the
employer.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the shortage of qualified auto mechanics, this might
seem an easy task. I find it just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Our office receives several phone calls a week with pleas from
prospective employers to send them students. Unfortunately, many of
them have unreal expectations of the skills and recourses
(primarily tools) an automotive tech student possesses.
</P>
<P>
   The constraints of a six-quarter automotive program provide
barely enough time to cover the theories and repair techniques. To
achieve continuity in training, system training aids _ such as air
conditioning training units, engines on stands and fuel injection
boards _ are incorporated into shop instruction practices, with
only limited exposure to live work on real cars.
</P>
<P>
   Can students explain how a system works and diagnose it? Yes.
Can they find these components on several makes and models of
vehicles? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the majority of the job offers are full time, requiring
the student to withdraw from the automotive program before
completing it.
</P>
<P>
   The students, on the other hand, are often appalled by the
``less than fast food'' starting pay offered by some of these
repair shops because of their apprentice-level status.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, I often find myself seeking workable, and
hopefully long-lasting, employment arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago I had the opportunity to check out
iMotors.com's new auto reconditioning facility. My tour of the vast
establishment enabled me to get a pretty good picture of the
mechanical side of its operation.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco-based iMotors.com is a used-car brokerage service.
The company takes orders over the Internet for used cars, then
buys, reconditions and delivers them. The Stockbridge facility is
one of its reconditioning centers.
</P>
<P>
   As the foreman walked me through the mechanical/body and
paint/trim shop, he explained that the company only deals with 1-
to 5-year-old vehicles. Vehicles with major problems (engine,
transaxle, drivetrain, frame, body or interior) are rejected. If
only minor repairs are needed (maintenance, brakes, door dings,
upholstery, trim), the vehicle is moved to the next phase.
</P>
<P>
   The repair/reconditioning building is a huge arena of bright
shop lights reflecting off spotless floors. The top-notch
diagnostic and repair equipment is supported by environmentally
friendly parts-cleaning and chemical use/recycling stations.
</P>
<P>
   I could only think that after years of working in shops with
poor to barely adequate lighting and equipment in various phases of
degradation, I'd entered a mechanic's paradise. From a mechanic's
perspective, the shop and the company's approach to vehicle repair
are phenomenal. The atmosphere provides incentives for recruiting
and retaining skilled service personnel. The working conditions are
certainly conducive to employee contentment, a key element to
instituting a team focus. The technicians are not paid flat rate,
where speed takes precedence over quality.
</P>
<P>
   Master technicians work with and train the less experienced
people. The goal is to achieve a right approach. What more could a
teacher ask than to be able to find a working environment that
echoes her own philosophy?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
