A0904 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0825-COX     08-24 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wiggy's first storm
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I've known many porch cats. They are drawn to the
hedge at our home and the fact that it generally doesn't take too
much wheedling for some cat chow and water to make it out the front
door.
</P>
<P>
   Porch cats come and go, some nameless. Then there were others:
Oopsie, with one eyelid that didn't work right. Snowball, who
became a fat farm cat when we found a family with a barn for her.
There was skinny Spice, a veritable teen who gave birth to three in
a discarded box in our driveway. When fire ants stormed, we hustled
the mom and newborns inside. Two of the kittens have stayed to this
day.
</P>
<P>
   So it was not unusual a few weeks ago to see a new set of eyes
in the hedge. The eyes? Well, OK, unusual: one powder blue, one
tan.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all that is strange. The kitten is snow-white except
for this: A black toupee-like swath combed back from his forehead,
parted perfectly down the middle. He also has a black hyphen right
below his nose. He looks like Oliver Hardy with all the air taken
out, and minus the derby hat.
</P>
<P>
   We're on a first-name basis now. Our youngest son named him
Wiggy. But our interaction has been fleeting. As with most American
families, we don't spend that much time on the porch.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggy is probably a summer old, all ears and tail. Legs astound
him, particularly his own. Truly, spring is in his step. Startle
him with a door and he bounces around like one whose pogo stick
won't stop.
</P>
<P>
   This cat having composure that brims over at half tea-cup, I was
curious how Wiggy might react the other night when Waco got its
first bonafide storm in a century, or at least in a summer.
</P>
<P>
   Natural commotion
</P>
<P>
   Storms are sensitive subjects at our house, particularly in our
back yard. Thunder is our dogs' least favorite subject.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the dogs came inside with the first drum roll. The
air heaved and sweated. The trees made ``come over here'' gestures.
The rain came.
</P>
<P>
   I stationed myself on the porch. Wiggy emerged from the hedge.
</P>
<P>
   I watched to see if the kitten would react to the thunder and
the flash of sabers rattling above. Nope. He was watching me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look. Rain,'' I pointed out to Wiggy. He looked at my hand
instead and climbed in my lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lay some of that skin on me, man,'' he said in body language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, kitten,'' I gestured. ``Check it out. There's nothing
like that first real storm in months, the smell, the spray, the
earth worms gargling.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE THE MERRIER
</P>
<P>
   Momentarily my wife came out. Wiggy bounced over. ``It's a
party,'' he gestured.
</P>
<P>
   Becky checked out the storm. Wiggy checked her out.
</P>
<P>
   Her hands unnaturally idle, my wife grabbed a broom to sweep the
porch. Wiggy knew this diversion was meant for him alone. He
grabbed and gnawed, sliding and scampering as he chased the broom's
bristles, or vice versa. At the edge of the porch he hid under a
skateboard and pawed at the broom.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly my son Robert appeared. Robert checked out the storm.
Wiggy checked out Robert.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggy pawed at Robert's shoe laces a while. Then Rob unfurled a
draw string from an old pair of trousers. The kitten leaped after
it and danced on hind legs. The kid laughed.
</P>
<P>
   The rain kept pouring. Becky gathered the kitten into her arms
and remarked that his fur was misted. What do you think, cat? Wait
'till you sample raindrops on roses.
</P>
<P>
   It was a porchful of us for several minutes, all looking up.
Then the storm subsided, to where the only clatter was from the
gutters. Robert and his mom went back in. He left the draw string
on the porch for the kitten's amusement.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggy was occupying himself with it when I went inside. I think
Wiggy thinks rain is a great concept.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
