<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0921 &Cx1f; tab-z
u c BC-SIKORSKY-ADV02-NYTSF     08-24 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIKORSKY-ADV02-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV02 
 FOR RELEASE SAT., SEP. 2, 2000 
 DRIVE IT FOREVER
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's DRIVE IT FOREVER column. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of DRIVE IT FOREVER _ contact one of the New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text. 
 By BOB SIKORSKY 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Dear Bob: You genuinely have an appreciation for the care and
feeding of automobiles, so here's my story.
 &HT;    When I leave for work in the morning, I coast my 1986 Ford truck
down the hill from my house to the highway three-quarters of a mile
away, and then 6 miles to the freeway. So, after a cold start, my
truck gets a bonus of a no-load situation to the highway, followed
by 6 miles at 55 mph, and 60 mph on the interstate to my
destination. I never have the vehicle idling in the garage, since I
can idle down the hill.
 &HT;    I also religiously change oil in all my vehicles. I plan on
keeping them for a long time to come.
 &HT;    _ Chris Aiken, Spokane, Wash.
 &HT;    A: All well and good. For sure, going down a hill in the morning
might be considered a bonus as far as engine work and cold-engine
fuel economy are concerned. But you should NEVER coast and idle
down any hill. Freewheeling or coasting (vehicle in neutral, engine
idling) is dangerous because no engine braking is available.
 &HT;    It doesn't matter whether you are idling in your garage or while
coasting down the hill, cold idling is still one of the most
wear-intensive engine operations.
 &HT;    You'd be much better off, and safer too, by simply placing the
truck in gear and letting it go down the hill with the engine under
high vacuum. This is much more fuel efficient and lubricates the
engine much better than if the truck were just idling.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Dear Bob: I own a 1988 Mercury Grand Marquis with 88,000 miles.
I bought it new but since then I've gone through four gas tanks.
 &HT;    The first one went at about 40,000 miles, the second at 57,112
miles, and the third at 77,580 miles. I don't have the mileage for
the fourth.
 &HT;    Something is causing this problem as the leak is always in the
same place _ over the exhaust pipe.
 &HT;    Clearly, Ford should find out why I have had to replace so many
tanks but they refuse to look into the causes.
 &HT;    I have written the Highway Traffic Safety Administration and my
congressman, but with no luck.
 &HT;    What else can I do?
 &HT;    _ Carmen Orlando, Methuen, Mass.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A. I talked to a Ford safety representative who in turn
consulted the company's experts on fuel systems and tanks, and all
insist they'd never heard of such a problem. It is not something
Ford has seen on any of their vehicles, so they think it must be
specific to your vehicle only.
 &HT;    If you care to have the matter investigated further (AND I
assume you do), you can call Mike Vaughn at Ford Motor Co.
(313-337-2786) and supply him with your vehicle's identification
number (VIN) and your name and address. Ford will check into the
vehicle's history of repairs and take it from there. Let me know
what happens.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Dear Bob: An owner of a Volvo 760 Turbo wondered why the
air-conditioner fan cut off when the engine was under load. You
advised him it was normal for his car as it uses a cutoff switch to
disengage the AC during heavy acceleration. I would also suggest
the vacuum system be checked for a missing or improper connection.
 &HT;    Many of your readers will remember vacuum windshield wipers that
would quit during acceleration due to lack of engine vacuum. Some
of today's cars use engine vacuum to operate various dampers that
route hot or cold air to the defroster, dash and floor vents.
 &HT;    When the engine is under load and the vacuum is low, the vents
close but resume functioning again when engine vacuum returns to an
appropriate level.
 &HT;    _ Jack Reefer, Harrisburg, Pa.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A. Thanks for your input. AC cutoff switches, by stopping the
cold air, ease the load on the engine and promotes better fuel
economy when accelerating or going up a hill.
 &HT;    But, your vacuum suggestions have merit. Readers who have cars
without the AC cutoff switch should keep them in mind. This
on-again-off-again (depending on the amount of engine vacuum
available) cold air routine may simply be normal for their vehicle.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Bob Sikorsky, a national-award-winning journalist who has
written several best-selling automotive books, is a consultant in
that field and a member of the Society of Automotive Engineers and
of the Society of Tribologists and Lubrication Engineers. Questions
or comments of general interest should be addressed to Bob
Sikorsky, care of this newspaper. Bob Sikorsky regrets that he
cannot answer questions individually.) 
 &HT;    
