r e BC-RAMBLIN'-JACK-REVIEW-     08-24 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMBLIN'-JACK-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE OF A RAMBLIN' GUY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a wonderfully telling scene toward the end of ``The
Ballad of Ramblin' Jack'' where folk legend Ramblin' Jack Elliott
tries to take his daughter to the house where she grew up. Driving
around Mendocino backroads in his beat-up RV, Jack eventually gives
up, saying the house must be there somewhere, but finding it will
have to wait until another day.
</P>
<P>
   That Ramblin' Jack couldn't find his old house doesn't come as
much of a surprise given how seldom he hung his cowboy hat there.
That his only daughter, Aiyana, barely knew him is kind of a given,
too, and that gulf between father and child is at the heart of this
compelling documentary. Aiyana Elliott, a New York University
graduate making her directorial debut here, has crafted an
extraordinary portrait of an American original as well as a
beautiful story of a daughter trying to come to terms with her
distant father.
</P>
<P>
   Ramblin' Jack isn't known to many people outside the folk music
scene, but his influence on popular music is substantial. He's an
unlikely cowboy, being born Elliott Charles Adnopoz, the son of
Jewish doctor in Brooklyn. But Jack, as we can clearly see from
early home movies, was born with the spirit of wanderlust, and at
15, he ran away from home to join the rodeo. Thus began a lifetime
of living up to the nickname he gave himself.
</P>
<P>
   When Jack was 19, he heard Woody Guthrie on the radio for the
first time and soon determined to meet the legend. He visited
Guthrie's Coney Island home and quickly became a member of the
household. Jack loved Guthrie's honest sound and working-man spirit
and began emulating his hero, causing Guthrie to observe, ``Jack
sounds more like me than I do myself.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, after becoming one of the folk music scene's
most influential figures, it was Jack's turn to become the teacher,
mentoring a young Bob Dylan. Now Jack was the subject of imitation,
with Dylan being billed as ``the son of Jack Elliott'' before his
first concert at Gerde's Folk City in New York.
</P>
<P>
   These triumphs, along with the singer's long periods of
obscurity, are shown through an amazing wealth of archival footage.
Jack's love for freedom and spontaneity served him well, but came
with a price _ four broken marriages and a perpetual state of
financial disarray. As friend Kris Kristofferson notes: ``The story
of Jack's life is other people having hits for things he was
responsible for.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Ramblin' Jack'' is more than a straight biopic. As
daughter Aiyana spends two years traveling with her father, she
comes to the disturbing realization that proximity does not equal
intimacy. And watching her father glad-hand and befriend every
stranger he comes across, Aiyana becomes frustrated, complaining
that she's ``never had an actual conversation'' with him, even
though she's his daughter !ital!and she's making a movie about him.
This conflict _ and its ultimate resolution _ gives ``Ramblin'
Jack'' a universal poignancy and makes it one of the best
documentaries of the year. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``The Ballad of Ramblin' Jack; (unrated; suitable for all
audiences). &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Aiyana Elliott; written by Aiyana
Elliott and Dick Dahl. Released by Lot 47 Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 45 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1246EDT &QL; 
