<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-REGIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAU REGIS
</HEADLINE>
  Everyone's crazy about a sharp-dressed man 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Sidebar to `Looks like a million.' Short fact box below. Art
available.) 
By BARBARA De WITT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an exclusive interview, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
host Regis Philbin talked about his sudden fame as a fashion plate,
his new line of Regis shirts and ties by the Van Heusen Company,
and his off-camera style.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have single-handedly changed the shirt-and-tie business,
and men of all ages want to dress like you on your game show. Is it
a little frightening to suddenly be a fashion idol pursued by the
fashion press or are you loving every second?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not frightening _ it's terrifying. I'm no fashion icon.
I just got lucky with a television show that's running three or
four nights a week on prime time. I couldn't have foreseen it and I
couldn't control it, but here it is, my collection, and I'm proud
of it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you make a conscious effort to look different than you do
on your morning talk show? Or to set yourself apart from other game
shows?
</P>
<P>
   A: The monochromatic look was the dress code for the original TV
show in Britain. However, my staff on `Live' comes in to review
what I wore the night before on `Millionaire,' and they usually
like what they see but once in a while an odd color will spark a
revolt. (For instance) I was requested not to wear the gold tie.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Among your monochromatic shirt-and-tie ensembles worn on
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' which is your favorite color and
why?
</P>
<P>
   A: I like the dark blue ensemble the best ... and think darker
colors look best on me. And I feel most men would feel the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you were in the contestant's seat, which color do you
think would be the luckiest for you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Again, it would be blue. Blue is traditionally considered the
best color to wear on television. And I notice most men in the hot
seat wear blue.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do contestants ever ask (or show up) in your shirt-and-tie
ensembles? Are they allowed to copy your look or do the fashion
police keep their dress casual?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think they are encouraged to be casual, but once in awhile
someone slips through in full regalia. I like to see that. Why
should I be the only one wearing a shirt and tie?
</P>
<P>
   Q: How would you describe your personal fashion stance away from
the studios? Are you a khakis kind of guy? Is there a cowboy hat in
the closet, or is the elegant `Millionaire' look really you?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm a khakis kind of guy, but I like the formal
(`Millionaire') look a lot and wear it in my personal life on
numerous occasions. But there's no cowboy hat in the closet (he
chuckles).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know Van Heusen approached you about having your own line
of shirts and ties and that you give a lot of input, from the
collar points to the amount of sheen in the ties, but who provides
those elegant pinstripe suits and dark three-button jackets?
</P>
<P>
   A: For the past 10 years, Beau Brummel, a store in the Soho area
of New York, has been providing my wardrobe for both shows. I rely
on them to tell me where fashion is going, and we consult. So as
fashion changes, so may the `Millionaire' look. It's a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you admit fashion is always changing, and so might your
wardrobe. Will we ever be wowed with Reege in plaid or maybe a
blazer and ascot? Or black leather?
</P>
<P>
   A: In a word, no.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think the success of your new show and image will give
casual Fridays a kick in the pants?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it will encourage men to dress better and if they do,
I think they'll feel better. I never realized it myself, but I'm
glad the dressier look came along because it does make a
difference. &QL; 
---Want Regis Philbin's suit, too? Call the Beau Brummel store at
(212) 219-2666. Those pin-striped designs he favors are priced from
$995 to $1,295. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
