<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-OF-KILLING-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF KILLING: IT'S BASIC MATH  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF AUG. 24, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By ANIL ANANTHASWAMY  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist/RBI Magazines Ltd.  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most predatory animals are elementary mathematicians it seems. A
Japanese scientist suggests that math can explain how stalking
predators, from cheetahs to jumping spiders or praying mantises,
maximize their chances of a kill by attacking at just the right
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Shigeo Yachi from the Center for Ecological Research at Kyoto
University in Otsu, wondered how predators decided when to attack,
considering that each day the same animal may have to hunt
different kinds of prey, in groups of varying sizes, across
ever-changing types of vegetation cover.
</P>
<P>
   According to his mathematical model, predators follow a basic
rule at each step of the hunt: they simply weigh the merits of
getting closer to the prey against losing the element of surprise.
When the risk of being noticed by prey outweighs the advantage of
proximity, the predator attacks. ''Using this simple rule to make
decisions the predator can cope with diverse hunting situations,''
says Yachi, whose research will appear in a forthcoming issue of
Evolutionary Ecology Research.
</P>
<P>
   How long an animal has been stalking _ whether it's hours or
seconds _ does not affect its decision to attack or hold off. This
minimizes the information a predator has to process during the
hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The model's predictions fit the results of earlier experiments
done on jumping spiders, Yachi says. Jumping spiders attack an
adult house fly from afar, presumably to maintain the element of
surprise. But they get a lot closer before attacking a house fly
maggot, which naturally enough is less likely to bolt. And under
camouflage, the spiders get closer to their prey before attacking.
</P>
<P>
   According to Yachi, more support for the model comes from the
behavior of scale eaters, predatory fish that dart in to snatch the
scales of other live fish. The scale eaters are smaller than their
prey and if noticed they escape rather than attack, a behavior that
the model again predicts.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few exceptions to the rule though, says Yachi. ''The
model cannot be applied to coursing predators, such as wild dogs,
wolves, and hyenas, because their hunt does not rely on the merit
of surprise.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
