r a BC-BAY-MURDERS-HNS &LR;      08-24 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAY-MURDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA TRIO FACES MURDER CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB and MATTHEW YI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINEZ, Calif. _ Prosecutors have filed murder charges against
two men and a woman suspected of killing three others and tossing
their dismembered bodies into the Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta.
</P>
<P>
   The 8-page criminal complaint filed by Contra Costa County
authorities Wednesday accuses brothers Glenn and Justin Helzer and
their housemate, Dawn Godman, of killing Ivan and Annette Stineman
and Selina Bishop, daughter of blues guitarist Elvin Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors listed 21 ``overt acts'' linking the Helzers and
Godman to the crimes, including a written plan of action.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint also gives the dates and locations of a
cross-county shopping spree for the items allegedly used to extort
money from, kill and ultimately dismember their victims.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, prosecutors say the Helzers and Godman took
stepping stones and rocks from their own back yard to weigh down
the duffel bags filled with body parts that were deposited in the
delta.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, after Glenn Helzer was arrested, prosecutors say he
tried to sell his story for $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Justin Helzer's lawyer asserted for the first time
that his client was innocent of murder, and that brother Glenn
Helzer might have suffered from a ``severe mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Harold Jewett said he had not
decided whether to seek the death penalty in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly . . . anybody who was directly involved with the
brutal murders and desecration of the victims' bodies would deserve
to be considered for the death penalty,'' Jewett said.
</P>
<P>
   The Helzers and Godman also have been linked to the shooting
deaths of Jennifer Villarin, Selina Bishop's mother, and James
Gamble, her mother's boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Contra Costa County prosecutors linked the defendants to those
deaths in their criminal complaint, but have not filed murder
charges in those cases.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities believe the Stinemans were killed in a $100,000
extortion attempt, and that Bishop, Villarin and Gamble may have
been killed to cover up the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Helzer, 30, was the Stinemans' former stockbroker.
</P>
<P>
   Villarin and Gamble were found shot dead Aug. 3 in Selina
Bishop's studio apartment in Woodacre, in western Marin County. The
dismembered remains of the other three victims were discovered in
nine duffel bags in the Mokelumne River in the Sacramento-San
Joaquin Delta a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   The Helzers and Godman were arrested Aug. 7, charged with auto
theft and a few drug offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's office Wednesday added 13 more counts _
three counts each for murder; two counts for robbery and false
imprisonment; and one each for conspiracy, extortion, residential
burglary, auto theft, possession for sale of the drug known as
ecstasy and possession of a hallucinogenic mushroom.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Helzer's lawyer, Bill Veale, said that Glenn Helzer had
developed a ``severe mental illness,'' and that his client was
innocent of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin Helzer has never killed anybody, hurt anybody or
(stole) from anybody,'' Veale said. ``I think we will establish
that in court.'''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Helzer's lawyer, Suzanne Chapot, did not comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
