<HEADLINE>
FOR STADIUM NAMES, IT'S A NEW ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We know what you are thinking: What kind of name is CMGI Field?
</P>
<P>
   Sports stadiums should be named after beer companies or car
companies or airlines, businesses with names you recognize that
make products you can touch and understand.
</P>
<P>
   Well get over it. This is a new century, and we have a new
economy. This is the way it is going to be from now on.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI joins a growing list of technology companies that have
their name on sports facilities: Qualcomm, PacBell, Ericsson, and
our personal favorite, PSINet Stadium in Baltimore. Compared to
PSINet Stadium, CMGI Field practically sounds like poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Like their old-economy counterparts, the new guys on the block
want the recognition and the branding benefits that come with
sticking their logos on something as tangible as a sports arena. In
fact, for the new guys, who compete in crowded, cutthroat markets,
the chance to become household names may well be worth the $5
million or $7 million or $10 million a year they are spending for
naming rights.
</P>
<P>
   And these guys have the money. Do they ever.
</P>
<P>
   Pop quiz: Name the two Massachusetts companies with the greatest
stock market value. Answer: EMC Corp. and Sycamore Networks.
</P>
<P>
   EMC, a Hopkinton, Mass. company that makes computer storage
systems, is currently worth more than $200 billion. Sycamore, a
Chelmsford, Mass. start-up that makes telecommunications gear, is
worth $40 billion. Never mind that Sycamore has been a public
company for less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a 70 percent decline in its stock price this year, a
reflection of the market's skeptical view of Internet businesses,
CMGI is worth $11 billion. At that level, it is worth more than
Raytheon or Staples or most of the other traditional companies you
can name.
</P>
<P>
   When CMGI's stock was at its peak, chief executive David
Wetherell was personally worth about $5 billion. Today, his net
worth is down to $1.4 billion. We're betting he'll still be able to
afford a seat and a hot dog at the new CMGI Field.
</P>
<P>
   You may say: Hold on a minute. These stock market values are
insane. CMGI has lost $730 million in the last three quarters.
These companies can't possibly be worth this much. And you may be
right. But the stock market looks to the future, not to the past,
and investors are betting that the race to the future will be won
by some of today's technology leaders, including CMGI.
</P>
<P>
   Call us old-fashioned, but we will miss some of the old-economy
names that used to dominate the sports world. When Gillette
sponsored the Friday night fights or Budweiser sponsored your
city's baseball team, you knew what you were dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   How many of us know what PSINet or Qualcomm actually do? Even by
new-economy standards, CMGI is a tough company to figure out. With
investments in more than 70 separate companies, CMGI has more
affiliates than the Patriots have players.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how CMGI describes itself:
</P>
<P>
   ``CMGI represents the largest, most diverse network of Internet
companies in the world, including both CMGI operating companies and
synergistic investments made through its venture-capital affiliate,
CMGI (at)Ventures. CMGI leverages the technologies, content and
market reach of its extended family of companies to foster rapid
growth and industry leadership across its network and the larger
Internet economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Got all that?
</P>
<P>
   The old-economy giants also had a stability you could count on.
Gillette has been making razors in South Boston since the turn of
the 20th century. Budweiser is as durable as a Clydesdale.
</P>
<P>
   Will we be able to say the same about CMGI? The company has been
around in its current form only since 1994. In that time it has
bought and sold companies, changed strategies, and moved with
Internet speed to take advantage of shifting tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone say for certain that CMGI will even be around in
2002, when CMGI Field is slated to open? Technology companies can
have short shelf lives. They can be bought by domestic or foreign
competitors. Their technology can become obsolete. Remember Digital
Equipment? Or they can run out of cash. We're not making any
predictions about CMGI, merely pointing out some of the risks
involved in making a deal with a new-economy partner.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, all of us will learn to live with CMGI Field, just
as we have learned to live with the FleetCenter. As far as we know,
the Patriots will still play football the same way on the same fall
afternoons, and you will still be able to scream and cheer and
drink beer.
</P>
<P>
   Last time we checked, no one had yet figured out a way to
deliver beer over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
