</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FLEETBOSTON HIRED GUN WILL RUN INVESTMENT GROUP FROM N.Y. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FleetBoston Financial Corp. is making a high-stakes bet that a
Wall Street veteran can spice up performance and growth in its $125
billion investment group _ from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Keith T. Banks, 44, joins Fleet after 16 years at white-shoe
investment house J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., where he last served as head of
US equities. He will be CEO and chief investment officer at the
newly renamed Fleet Asset Management. And his pay package will
rival FleetBoston CEO Terrence Murray's.
</P>
<P>
   The hire, after a difficult 18-month search, shows the lengths
to which banks and other second-tier players in the investment
business must go to attract senior talent.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Fleet is not asking Banks to move to Boston. He
will spend much of his time here, however, particularly at the
outset, as he gets to know some 1,000 employees in the department,
from research analysts and traders to portfolio managers. The group
manages money for two mutual fund families, Galaxy and Columbia,
plus about $50 billion for institutions and wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Banks has a temporary office on Sixth Avenue in New York. By
January, he will assume offices in the IBM Building near Central
Park, when Fleet's investment banking unit, Robertson Stephens,
moves to larger quarters.
</P>
<P>
   He will be paid $20 million to $25 million over the next three
years, industry sources said, probably including stock awards.
That's substantially more than his predecessor, Tom O'Neill, was
making at that job, according to Fleet's latest proxy statement.
And it's not far from the $5 million that Murray, the CEO, earned
in 1999, plus $15 million in restricted stock that vests over three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty darned substantial,'' Alex Thomson, an executive
recruiter with Whitehead Mann Pendleton James in Boston, said of
Banks' pay package.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet is clearly looking to get a big bang for its buck.
Investment management revenue in the first six months of this year
rose 8 percent from a year ago, to $480 million. Faster-growing
fund groups, such as Putnam Investments and MFS Investments, are
growing by double-digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This business has enormous growth potential,'' said Charles K.
Gifford, Fleet's president. ``We absolutely intend to be a top-tier
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks indicated the business could grow substantially from this
point, with the right product lineup and performance. He wants to
beef up research and consider more aggressive equity products,
including sector funds, analyst-run funds, and hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now everything is on the table,'' said Banks, who
started with J.P. Morgan in 1984 as a chemical and textile analyst.
``First and foremost, I'm an investor.''
</P>
<P>
   A thin lineup of growth options has hurt Fleet's Galaxy family
of mutual funds over the last few years, as investors have flocked
to high-risk, high-return portfolios, according to an analysis by
Financial Research Corp., a Boston consulting firm. ``The
combination of the lack of aggressive growth product offerings and
the continuing merger activity at the corporate level have made
sales growth difficult for the firm,'' FRC said in its second
quarter report. what about 1784 funds?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Banks takes the top job at the investment group after
more than a year of upheaval. Fleet's purchase of BankBoston led to
many staff changes and to the elimination of BankBoston's former
1784 funds, which were merged into Fleet's Galaxy funds. Fleet's
five broker-dealers were reorganized under its Quick &AMP; Reilly
brokerage unit. The bank is also integrating its Columbia
Management fund unit, in Portland, Ore., into the asset management
group.
</P>
<P>
   While Fleet Asset Management's headquarters is still officially
Boston, Banks cleary plans to go talent hunting in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not fish in the whole pond?'' Banks said, noting that,
``There is an absolute war for talent.'' While Boston is a hub of
investment management, it's not easy, Banks admitted, for banks to
go up against the likes of Fidelity Investments and Putnam when it
comes to recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can be pretty effective in New York at attracting
people,'' he said. On top of providing strong investment
performance, he said, the best way to attract customers is,
``having the highest quality people and (the most) recognized
people you can get.'' Competitive pay is important, he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, who previously ran investments at Fleet, left the
company to run his own Navigator hedge funds, a highly lucrative
business. Hedge funds are unregulated funds that can invest with
fewer restrictions than mutual funds. Managers typically pocket 20
percent of the returns they reap for clients.
</P>
<P>
   This job will be a challenge for Banks, industry watchers said.
At Morgan, he oversaw $85 billion of equity assets. Now he'll be in
charge of a larger pool of money, three offices and all the
operations of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Banks appears confident that he can deliver results for Fleet
shareholders and customers. And he'll be eating his own cooking, he
said. Though it wasn't a requirement of the job, he said, he'll be
moving a portion of his own assets into Galaxy funds. ``Much to the
chagrin of that fund manager,'' he joked.
</P>
</TEXT>
