<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TECH-WOMEN-$ADV27-COX     08-24 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-WOMEN-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GENDER IMBALANCE HURTS THE TECH INDUSTRY, FEMALE EXECS SAY
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Aug. 27.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASPEN, Colo. _ Despite the astonishing growth of high-paying
jobs in the tech world, the number of young women entering
computer-related careers is small _ and shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   While women now account for slightly more than half of U.S.
Internet users, they are barely visible in the ranks of computer
scientists, engineers and programmers.
</P>
<P>
   But does it matter to the economy, or to society, if women sit
out the tech revolution? Would anything be different if women held
half of the tech jobs available?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes'' was the emphatic answer from a pair of the tech word's
leading female executives, who last week joined a sea of white guys
at the Aspen Summit, an annual conference on the digital revolution
sponsored by the Progress &AMP; Freedom Foundation, a non-profit
research group.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that if women played a larger role in the
technology-driven sector of the economy, it would be much
healthier, with more stable companies, fewer labor shortages, lower
costs and higher sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``My political side says women are no different (from men), but
they are,'' said Esther Dyson, chair of the Internet Corporation
for Assigned Names and Numbers, a new international agency charged
with setting policy for the Internet's infrastructure. ``Whether
it's nature or nurture, they have different concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   And because of their different perspectives, women would help
stabilize an industry that has become too chaotic, Dyson said. For
example, she said, one of the top concerns of many young male
techies is to become a chief executive officer as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at how this industry works right now, there are
too many companies where some guy just decided he wanted to be CEO,
so he went out and did something that was redundant,'' she said,
referring to the wild proliferation of dot-com businesses in the
late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many of those me-too companies are collapsing, dragging
down the tech stock market and vaporizing capital. ``It's great to
see the outpouring of entrepreneurship, but at the same time, there
is this arrogance that says 'I'm going to do it,' as opposed to
saying, ``Gee, someone is already doing it _ let me help them do it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   A more female-influenced industry also might be better at
understanding consumers' needs, said Julie Shimer, a vice president
for 3Com Corp. and general manager of its consumer business. ``The
engineering pressure right now is very technology-gee-whiz focused,
but there's not much on 'Why would I want to do this? How would I
use it responsibly?','' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If half of all engineers were female, ``I think technology would
be easier to understand, and it would be targeted more at women and
children,'' Shimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson said ``friendlier'' products also could reduce business
costs because companies ``might spend less money on tech support,''
she said, referring to the legions of workers who answer customers'
questions about puzzling products and services.
</P>
<P>
   But female perspectives are lacking because, outside of the
National Football League, few enterprises are as male-dominated as
the tech world.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Commerce Department estimates that while women
represent 51 percent of the population, they make up only 26
percent of the computer scientists and 9 percent of the engineers
working today.
</P>
<P>
   But even those ranks soon will thin as the pipeline of female
tech majors dries up. Only about 25 percent of computer science
bachelor's degrees will go to young women this year, down from 37
percent at the peak in 1984, according to the American Association
of University Women (AAUW). And at the high school level, girls
represent only 17 percent of the computer science ``advanced
placement'' test takers.
</P>
<P>
   While women's participation in computer science has been
decreasing, many girls a master's degrees in business
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, women are swarming over U.S. campuses, where they now
outnumber males 56 percent to 44 percent, according to the U.S.
Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   So why are they shunning the tech world?
</P>
<P>
   An AAUW study found that girls regard computer-related jobs as
``boring'' and ``lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyson said that perception is fostered by the entertainment
media, which tend to use ``geeky guys'' to portray lonely computer
workers. ``Girls get a wrong message,'' Dyson said. ``Programmers
often work together and trade ideas. It's some of the more
interesting work because they are solving problems. You're not
doing the same thing again and again. It's very creative.''
</P>
<P>
   The AAUW study found that girls also say teachers make computers
seem boring by focusing on the technical properties of hardware,
rather than on innovative uses of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the AAUW study showed girls are turned off by idea of
working extremely long hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the computer industry, ``some people do work a lot,'' Dyson
said. ``But I think that, frankly if you had more women in it,
you'd have more people to hire and nobody would need to work quite
so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if more young women were entering tech fields, the
industry would be better able to restrain its runaway labor costs.
A survey of nearly 5,000 college students last spring found that of
those planning to graduate with a bachelor's degree in computer
science or engineering, 51 percent expect a starting salary offer
of between $51,000 and $70,000 a year, according to CollegeHire, an
Austin, Texas-based high-tech recruiting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of focusing solely on paying higher salaries, tech
executives would do well to concentrate on making the workplace
friendlier to people who want to maintain a home life, Dyson said.
Such changes would also help the industry attract more young men,
who also have started avoiding computer-related fields.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of U.S. undergraduates earning computer and
information science degrees declined from a high of 41,889 in 1986
to just 24,768 in 1997. The Information Technology Association of
America says technology-driven companies have about 800,000 jobs
now open or projected to be open through the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   For a quick fix to the labor shortage, the industry has been
hammering Congress to nearly double the current cap of 115,000 on
the visas that allow high-skilled foreigners to work here for up to
six years.
</P>
<P>
   But long-term, a better solution would be to make the computer
lab feel less like a stay-up-all-night fraternity house. Providing
more humane working hours, child-care help and vacation time would
attract far more people, both male and female, to the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're hot and you're growing, you don't need to do that,''
Dyson said of the tech industry of the 1990s. ``But when you lose
your sex appeal, you need to start treating people right.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Women in Technology International Foundation, www.witi.com
</P>
<P>
   Progress &AMP; Freedom Foundation, www.pff.org
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
