<HEADER>
A1044 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DRUG-PRICING-BOS &LR;      08-24 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-PRICING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDERS' EFFORT LEADS TO DRUG PRICING LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 25 seniors from Maine weren't thinking revolution when they
boarded a Greyhound bus in Portland two years ago. They didn't have
a political agenda as they made the five-hour trip to Montreal. And
they certainly didn't give presidential politics a thought as they
made a mad dash to a Canadian pharmacy the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   They just wanted cheaper prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saved almost $100 that day,'' said Viola Quirion, 77, of
Waterville, as she recalled the adventure in which she and others
took advantage of Canada's regulated prescription drug industry.
</P>
<P>
   Their bus ride bolstered a movement that ended with Maine
becoming the first state to enact a drug price control law, which
went into effect last week. The law made national headlines and
unleashed a political storm. Similar bills are developing in many
states, waiting to emerge during the winter legislative season.
</P>
<P>
   Drug pricing is a powerful issue affecting the pocketbooks and
the health of about 13 million seniors without prescription drug
coverage. Annual spending on drugs for each American senior grew
from $559 in 1992 to $1,205 in 2000, a 116 percent increase,
according to a national study. By 2010, that figure is expected to
jump 133 percent, to $2,810.
</P>
<P>
   Most people never feel the cost of drugs because their health
insurance handles it. But Medicare, the federal program that
insures the elderly, does not cover prescriptions. And those
without insurance _ an estimated 40 million people _ must pay or go
without.
</P>
<P>
   But going without can be painful, especially in old age.
Prescription drugs are playing an increasingly vital role in health
care, keeping in check dozens of chronic conditions that, left
untreated, could ruin the quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, presidential candidates Al Gore and George W.
Bush have promised to tackle the issue, and their different
approaches could influence elderly voters in the presidential
election. Five bills on the issue have been introduced in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, drug companies are making record profits, but their
marketplace is growing increasingly competitive. Most ideas for new
drugs fail in the laboratory. A single blockbuster drug, like
Prozac or Lipitor, can make or break a company. The companies argue
that current prices are justified by the billions of dollars they
spend on research. But even they support some forms of drug
coverage for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   So how did this political snowball start in Maine? Blame it on
Canada, which sets drug prices at levels it considers fair to
patients and pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Quirion's band of bus riders were, in fact, latecomers to
cross-border drug shopping. Maine and Canada share almost 800 miles
of border, and along it are dozens of paired towns, like Calais in
northeast Maine and St. Stephen in New Brunswick. Residents of
Calais have long made the short, easy trip to pharmacies in St.
Stephen.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main factors behind why Maine was first is our
proximity to Canada,'' said Maine's governor, Angus King, an
Independent. ``When you live in Kansas you can't drive 50 miles to
get cheaper prescriptions like we can. You don't notice the price
differential there.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the issue came up, Mainers took to it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The law that King signed in May allows the state to gather the
325,000 residents without drug coverage, to group them with Maine's
200,000-person Medicaid population, and to negotiate drug prices
with pharmaceutical companies. The companies regularly give
discounts to high-volume purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Maine law gives the state a big stick in negotiations.
If officials do not get the discounts they are looking for, they
can set the prices they want after July 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The law angered drug makers. The pharmaceutical giant SmithKline
Beecham announced this month that it would no longer ship pills to
Maine. A week later, a coalition of drug makers filed suit against
Maine, asserting that the law is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   King, whose administration is preparing to negotiate drug prices
in the fall, is undeterred. ``Maybe they don't want to talk except
in court, and that's unfortunate,'' he said. ``But if this is
successful, every state in the union is going to do it in, like, 18
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Quirion did not hear of the Canadian option from her fellow
Mainers. It was a group of elderly Minnesotans visiting Waterville
for a conference on aging who let her in on the secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us about how much money they saved,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Quirion had worked for 40 years in quality control at a Maine
shirt factory before retiring nine years ago. Her income is largely
Social Security, about $1,000 a month, and her health insurance is
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   She takes a drug called Prilosec, which keeps her chronic
stomach problems in check. Without it she cannot digest food. And
she takes Relafen for her arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, a three-month supply of the drugs costs about $600.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, it costs about $400.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very good thing,'' Quirion said. ``So we decided to
do it once a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of the trip spread. On the second run, last year, the
seniors had their own bus, donated by local unions, and 35 seniors
from other parts of New England. They also had a special guest.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wallace, a reporter for the CBS News show ``60 Minutes,''
had heard of the trip, and decided to bring a television camera
crew along. When the show hit the airwaves, the reaction was
immediate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got telephone calls and mail from all over,'' Quirion said.
</P>
<P>
   Maine state Senator Chellie Pingree, a North Haven Democrat,
took note. She had fallen into the issue accidentally. During her
second term, the Republicans had taken control of the Senate and
had relegated her to a legislative graveyard shift, a subcommittee
on health care.
</P>
<P>
   Pingree noticed that when she mentioned the issue of high drug
prices, pharmaceutical lobbyists were at her door the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys just don't move,'' she said in an interview last
week from the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles, where
the knitting store owner was something of a minor star.
</P>
<P>
   But she saw the groundswell of interest as presidential
contenders and academics began raising the issue last year.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of group purchasing intrigued her. Why not gather
all the people without insurance to form a big buying block? The
idea had been around for decades. Most HMOs, government agencies,
and large companies get discounts because they buy so many drugs
for their group members.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than negotiate with companies, Pingree decided to
calculate the savings a big buying group would deserve and to fix
the prices by law. The bill passed the Maine House on April 14 and
the Senate two weeks later. But the governor had concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am generally more sympathetic to market-based solutions,''
King said.
</P>
<P>
   But he knew a hot issue when he saw one. So rather than veto the
bill, he convened a rare negotiating session with Pingree and her
colleagues. What emerged was a plan to form a Maine buying block
and negotiate prices with the drug companies rather than set the
prices outright.
</P>
<P>
   Pingree and her colleagues insisted on a backup plan. If the
companies did not play fair, the state would set prices. King
signed the bill, and Maine found itself a national leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say there's a great deal of interest. I've talked
to governors all over the country,'' King said, noting that the
chief executives of New Hampshire and Connecticut have a strong
interest.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry filed suit against the law three
days before it went into effect. It argued that the law violates
the Constitution's commerce clause, which prohibits states from
regulating business that crosses state lines. The companies are
asking a federal judge in Maine to suspend the law until the
constitutional issues are resolved. With several other states
likely to attempt to pass similar laws soon, the industry is
anticipating a multifront legal war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that a number of states are considering bills
modeled on Maine's. It would be a bad decision for other states,''
said Marjorie Powell, assistant general counsel for Pharma, the
pharmaceutical trade group that filed the suit.
</P>
<P>
   But all the talk of constitutional battles and presidential
elections does not move Quirion. She thinks more about her fellow
Mainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people in central Maine who lost their jobs.
They have no insurance and don't have any prescription drug
benefits,'' she said. ``We're fighting for them, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1045 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-WOMEN-$ADV27-COX     08-24 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-WOMEN-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GENDER IMBALANCE HURTS THE TECH INDUSTRY, FEMALE EXECS SAY
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Aug. 27.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASPEN, Colo. _ Despite the astonishing growth of high-paying
jobs in the tech world, the number of young women entering
computer-related careers is small _ and shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   While women now account for slightly more than half of U.S.
Internet users, they are barely visible in the ranks of computer
scientists, engineers and programmers.
</P>
<P>
   But does it matter to the economy, or to society, if women sit
out the tech revolution? Would anything be different if women held
half of the tech jobs available?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes'' was the emphatic answer from a pair of the tech word's
leading female executives, who last week joined a sea of white guys
at the Aspen Summit, an annual conference on the digital revolution
sponsored by the Progress &AMP; Freedom Foundation, a non-profit
research group.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that if women played a larger role in the
technology-driven sector of the economy, it would be much
healthier, with more stable companies, fewer labor shortages, lower
costs and higher sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``My political side says women are no different (from men), but
they are,'' said Esther Dyson, chair of the Internet Corporation
for Assigned Names and Numbers, a new international agency charged
with setting policy for the Internet's infrastructure. ``Whether
it's nature or nurture, they have different concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   And because of their different perspectives, women would help
stabilize an industry that has become too chaotic, Dyson said. For
example, she said, one of the top concerns of many young male
techies is to become a chief executive officer as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at how this industry works right now, there are
too many companies where some guy just decided he wanted to be CEO,
so he went out and did something that was redundant,'' she said,
referring to the wild proliferation of dot-com businesses in the
late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many of those me-too companies are collapsing, dragging
down the tech stock market and vaporizing capital. ``It's great to
see the outpouring of entrepreneurship, but at the same time, there
is this arrogance that says 'I'm going to do it,' as opposed to
saying, ``Gee, someone is already doing it _ let me help them do it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   A more female-influenced industry also might be better at
understanding consumers' needs, said Julie Shimer, a vice president
for 3Com Corp. and general manager of its consumer business. ``The
engineering pressure right now is very technology-gee-whiz focused,
but there's not much on 'Why would I want to do this? How would I
use it responsibly?','' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If half of all engineers were female, ``I think technology would
be easier to understand, and it would be targeted more at women and
children,'' Shimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson said ``friendlier'' products also could reduce business
costs because companies ``might spend less money on tech support,''
she said, referring to the legions of workers who answer customers'
questions about puzzling products and services.
</P>
<P>
   But female perspectives are lacking because, outside of the
National Football League, few enterprises are as male-dominated as
the tech world.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Commerce Department estimates that while women
represent 51 percent of the population, they make up only 26
percent of the computer scientists and 9 percent of the engineers
working today.
</P>
<P>
   But even those ranks soon will thin as the pipeline of female
tech majors dries up. Only about 25 percent of computer science
bachelor's degrees will go to young women this year, down from 37
percent at the peak in 1984, according to the American Association
of University Women (AAUW). And at the high school level, girls
represent only 17 percent of the computer science ``advanced
placement'' test takers.
</P>
<P>
   While women's participation in computer science has been
decreasing, many girls are flocking to other fields that require
intensive study of math and science. For example, women now make up
about 40 percent of students pursuing medical degrees and master's
degrees in business administration.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, women are swarming over U.S. campuses, where they now
outnumber males 56 percent to 44 percent, according to the U.S.
Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   So why are they shunning the tech world?
</P>
<P>
   An AAUW study found that girls regard computer-related jobs as
``boring'' and ``lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyson said that perception is fostered by the entertainment
media, which tend to use ``geeky guys'' to portray lonely computer
workers. ``Girls get a wrong message,'' Dyson said. ``Programmers
often work together and trade ideas. It's some of the more
interesting work because they are solving problems. You're not
doing the same thing again and again. It's very creative.''
</P>
<P>
   The AAUW study found that girls also say teachers make computers
seem boring by focusing on the technical properties of hardware,
rather than on innovative uses of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the AAUW study showed girls are turned off by idea of
working extremely long hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the computer industry, ``some people do work a lot,'' Dyson
said. ``But I think that, frankly if you had more women in it,
you'd have more people to hire and nobody would need to work quite
so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if more young women were entering tech fields, the
industry would be better able to restrain its runaway labor costs.
A survey of nearly 5,000 college students last spring found that of
those planning to graduate with a bachelor's degree in computer
science or engineering, 51 percent expect a starting salary offer
of between $51,000 and $70,000 a year, according to CollegeHire, an
Austin, Texas-based high-tech recruiting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of focusing solely on paying higher salaries, tech
executives would do well to concentrate on making the workplace
friendlier to people who want to maintain a home life, Dyson said.
Such changes would also help the industry attract more young men,
who also have started avoiding computer-related fields.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of U.S. undergraduates earning computer and
information science degrees declined from a high of 41,889 in 1986
to just 24,768 in 1997. The Information Technology Association of
America says technology-driven companies have about 800,000 jobs
now open or projected to be open through the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   For a quick fix to the labor shortage, the industry has been
hammering Congress to nearly double the current cap of 115,000 on
the visas that allow high-skilled foreigners to work here for up to
six years.
</P>
<P>
   But long-term, a better solution would be to make the computer
lab feel less like a stay-up-all-night fraternity house. Providing
more humane working hours, child-care help and vacation time would
attract far more people, both male and female, to the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're hot and you're growing, you don't need to do that,''
Dyson said of the tech industry of the 1990s. ``But when you lose
your sex appeal, you need to start treating people right.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Women in Technology International Foundation, www.witi.com
</P>
<P>
   Progress &AMP; Freedom Foundation, www.pff.org
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
