<TEXT>
<P>
   HOW MEN AND WOMEN COMPARE IN THE INFORMATION AGE
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN MAKE UP THE MAJORITY OF INTERNET USERS
</P>
<P>
   People using the Internet: 50.4 percent female, 49.6 percent
male
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN DOMINATE ON CAMPUS
</P>
<P>
   College students in 1998: 56 percent female, 44 percent male
</P>
<P>
   AND WOMEN LIKE SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   College students majoring in biological and life sciences: 53
percent female, 47 percent male
</P>
<P>
   BUT WOMEN ARE A SMALL MINORITY IN THE TECH WORLD
</P>
<P>
   Recipients of engineering-related degrees: 9 percent female, 91
percent male
</P>
<P>
   Computer science ``advanced placement'' test takers in high
school: 17 percent female, 83 percent male
</P>
<P>
   Professionals in all jobs within the information technology
industry: 20 percent female, 80 percent male
</P>
<P>
   THE LACK OF WOMEN IN TECH FIELDS PULLS DOWN WAGES FOR WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   Median earnings for people with bachelor's degrees: $35,408 for
women, $49,982 for men.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Media Metrix, U.S. Commerce Department, American
Association of University Women.
</P>
