<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1052 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-LINUX-ART-B     08-24 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-LINUX-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A USER-FRIENDLY FACE-LIFT FOR LINUX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Linux is not pretty _ at least not in its
natural state. But lately the upstart operating system has been
getting a facelift, and Nat Friedman likes the look of it.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman and his colleagues at Helix Code Inc. are performing
the surgery. Their Helix Gnome software masks the drab, complex
text interface of Linux behind rich and colorful images that let
users control Linux by clicking a mouse, just as they do with
Microsoft Corp.'s Windows software.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-million people have already downloaded Helix Gnome
from the company Web site since it was released on the Internet in
March. Among the small but influential clique that runs Linux
software on their personal computers, Helix Gnome is on its way to
being the gold standard.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not bringing in any gold. Like Linux itself, Helix
Gnome is free.
</P>
<P>
   ``The software itself is a commodity,'' Friedman says. ``We hope
to make no money off the software.''
</P>
<P>
   As with other Linux firms, Helix Gnome expects to get users
hooked on a variety of add-on services to bring in some bucks.
Quite a lot of bucks, says Will Roseman, cochairman of Linux Global
Partners, a New York venture capital firm that has invested $2.2
million in Helix Code. Roseman predicts quarterly earnings in the
$30 million range by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing new about any of this technology,'' says
Friedman with refreshing candor. After all, Gnome's been around for
a couple of years, the brainchild of a team of programmers led by
Mexican software designer Miguel de Icaza. Nor is Gnome the only
effort to create a user-friendly interface for Linux. Its
best-known rival is the KDE Project, launched by programmer
Matthias Ettrich in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   De Icaza began Gnome in 1997, largely because the KDE Project
originally contained some ``closed'' code that belonged to a
commercial software company. This code has since been removed, but
the change came too late for de Icaza.
</P>
<P>
   A disciple of the Free Software Foundation in Cambridge, de
Icaza rejected on principle the idea of giving any commercial firm
control over the contents of a Linux system. All the code, he
believed, should be ``open,'' freely available in its raw form for
anyone to modify. This was the guiding principle of the Free
Software Foundation's GNU project to create open software programs.
(GNU stood for GNU's Not Unix). De Icaza made his new interface
part of the GNU project, and named it the GNU Network Object Model
Environment, or Gnome.
</P>
<P>
   De Icaza's devotion to open software doesn't mean he's opposed
to making money. He even interviewed for a job at Microsoft Corp.,
when MIT computer science student Friedman was working there as a
summer intern. De Icaza didn't get the Microsoft job, but he and
Friedman hit it off, and decided to found a company to improve upon
and commercialize Gnome.
</P>
<P>
   Helix Code was incorporated in October, and began by staffing up
with top Linux coders. ``We knew everyone in the Gnome community,''
Friedman says. ``So recruiting and hiring for us was just a game .
. . we hired the best developers from a community of thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   The team set to work, adding a number of sophisticated new
applications to the basic Gnome interface. One of them, Evolution,
may raise a few eyebrows at Microsoft headquarters. It's a dead
ringer for Microsoft's popular Outlook personal information manager
_ only it's free.
</P>
<P>
   Another top priority at Helix Code is built-in software that
will connect a user to the company's Internet servers. That way, a
user can automatically download bug fixes, code updates, new
features, and more.
</P>
<P>
   A whole lot more, if Friedman gets his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The updater for us is sort of the seed for the beginning of
service offerings,'' he says. Once you get people regularly logging
in to a Helix Code server for upgrades, you get regular
opportunities to sell them stuff.
</P>
<P>
   How about an add-on that lets you order airline tickets from
inside your Evolution program, with arrival and departure times
automatically loaded into your schedule?
</P>
<P>
   Or you could dump your new digital photos onto your hard drive,
click a button, and have the pictures relayed to a photo processing
firm that would print them on glossy paper and mail them to
Grandma.
</P>
<P>
   You could also have the server send you a message the next time
Courtney Love is playing in town. The concert date would
automatically appear in your schedule. Friedman figures people
might pay $5 a month for such a service.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible revenue stream could flow from customized
versions of Helix Gnome, tailored to the needs of specific
businesses. And of course, there's the model of Linux firms like
Red Hat, which make their money by providing service and support
for users.
</P>
<P>
   All these profit options depend on getting Helix Gnome on as
many Linux desktops as possible. The company got good news on that
front at last week's LinuxWorld trade show in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the nation's top computer makers, including Compaq
Computer Corp., Hewlett-Packard Co., IBM Corp., and Sun
Microsystems Inc., have joined with Helix Code in a new consortium
to support continuing development of Gnome. The deal doesn't mean
these companies have specifically endorsed Helix Gnome, but it
furthers the goal of making Gnome the standard user interface for
Linux computers.
</P>
<P>
   And not just Linux. Sun Microsystems plans to use Gnome on its
Unix-based computers, the most popular Unix machines in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It's dirt cheap and relatively easy to switch from standard
Gnome to Helix Gnome. So expanding the universe of Gnome users is a
boost for Helix Code's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Helix Gnome is a hit with the Linux cognoscenti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every conference I go to, people are using it,'' boasts
Friedman. ``So there's a kind of immortality there.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, immortality is more fun when there's money in it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
