<HEADER>
A1053 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-SCOTSMAN-BOS &LR;      08-24 1723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SCOTSMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYAL SCOTSMAN: STATELY HOME ON RAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURGH, Scotland _ Would I succumb to claustrophobia? I'm the
sort who can't comfortably get through the catacombs, or even climb
the Bunker Hill monument. The confined space thing creeps me out.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, I recently signed on for a four-night trip on the
Royal Scotsman, an ornate train that meanders through the Highlands
of Scotland. The ``State Rooms'' measure 10 1/2-by-6 1/2 feet and
the shower stalls are so small that my elbows bumped the sides as I
was trying to wash my hair. No chance of falling over in the shower
if the train lurched.
</P>
<P>
   Space is a luxury. It's about the only one the Royal Scotsman
doesn't have. The service is superb, as is the food, which is a
near-miracle given the conditions under which it's created. The
train's decor is opulent, dominated by plaid _ no surprise in the
land of tartan. The staff wear plaid pants or pleated skirts.
Certain nights on the trip, designated as formal, give gentlemen
guests the chance to wear plaid, too: They're requested to don
either dinner jackets or kilts. My Jewish husband, lacking a clan
tartan, threatened to have a kilt made up in a Star of David
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The train is essentially a British country house on wheels:
Think ``The Shooting Party,'' without the bedroom-swapping
hanky-panky. (Or maybe I just missed that.) ``Murder on the Orient
Express'' also came to mind. Although the crime rate on the train
was nil, the delicious sense of possibility was there.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Scotsman experience starts before you board the train,
in the elegant Balmoral Hotel next to Edinburgh's Waverley Station,
from which the train departs. Sitting in a dark, clubby,
leather-and-mahogany lounge, you fill out forms that ask about
personal preferences. Under the ``Food and Beverage'' category, I
wrote ``as much champagne as possible,'' which turned out to be no
problem on board, although there's probably a nationwide shortage
of bubbly now.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I tried to walk from the hotel to the train, and
were gently informed that we'd be driven in a procession of proper
British black taxis instead, even though the walk would have taken
two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want you to become accustomed to the way you're going to be
treated for the next four days,'' said our guide, a Mary Poppins
nanny type. The pampering continued as a kilted piper played while
we trod on a red carpet to board the garnet-colored train. We were
directed by a Jeeves equivalent to the observation car, which was
graced with giant bouquets including thistles, a traditional symbol
of Scotland. There were also overstuffed sofas whose ends sprouted
tiny triangular tables on which to place drinks: The car is so
narrow that coffee tables are out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century style of the Scotsman conjures up Queen
Victoria tootling up to her beloved Balmoral on her royal train.
The modern version is richly outfitted with brocades and velvets,
mostly jewel-toned, and wood-paneled walls with ornate inlaid
moldings outlining panels of pale golden burl. Coved ceilings in
the public rooms are covered in embossed white paper; ceiling fans
whir overhead, the only form of air conditioning on the train and
all that's generally needed in the cool Scottish climate. Windows
in the train actually open. I'm so used to hotel windows that don't
that this in itself was impressive, and went a long way toward
alleviating any sense of being cooped up. Besides, the Highland air
is wonderfully breathable.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of peace and privacy prevails as you watch the rugged
countryside go by, with its ruined castles and fields of wild
lupine and gorse. On the tour I took (there are several different
ones), the route was essentially a giant loop around Scotland's
most picturesque parts, beginning and ending in Edinburgh. The
train stables at night, so no movement disrupts guests' sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling alone with nature, I was standing stark naked one
morning, looking out of the window, when suddenly the train pulled
up at a village station and there were fully clothed people looking
back at me.
</P>
<P>
   The individual cabins (20, to accommodate 36 travelers) are
cleverly designed to maximize space and minimize the effects of the
moving train. As soon as you unpack, your luggage is whisked away
by the staff so it's not in your way. Built-in twin beds have
storage drawers underneath, in between, and overhead. There's an
armoire as well. There actually is enough room for the wardrobes of
people who never wear the same thing twice. All the doors have
hooks at the top to secure them in either open or shut positions,
so they don't swing or sway when the train does. Shelves are all
boxy compartments, so nothing falls off. The rooms have no phones;
I found the absence of constant ringing and voice mail a relief.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the train's general manager, Stephen Coupe, is part
baronet-type host, part butler. He acknowledges that passengers
cede a certain control on board: ``We're telling you what you have
to eat and drink, and what your schedule is, and you have to like
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He makes sure you like it. I found not having to make decisions
quite relaxing. Coupe, while outwardly serene at all times, can't
have relaxed for a second. Various airlines had lost the luggage of
several passengers, and Coupe spent hours on the phone (he's got
one) tracking it down. When one guest lost an earring on the floor
of a cashmere shop during one of the daily off-train excursions, he
tracked that down, too, and had it forwarded to the London hotel
where she would be staying next. He oversees the annual
redecoration of the train during the off-season: The Scotsman
doesn't run in winter. The tab for last year's refurbishment was
$500,000, but Coupe dreams of spending even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like mixer taps in the bathrooms,'' he says wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   We all need a Coupe in our lives, I started to think, a
major-domo who makes things run smoothly. ``Service is our number
one priority,'' he says, and the service behind the scenes is as
impressive as what you do see. Take bath towels. There are fresh
ones for every passenger, every day. With no laundry facilities on
board, I wondered where the dirty ones were stashed. (In the
luggage area underneath the Royal Scotsman bus that takes guests on
their daily excursions, it turns out.) The towels are washed only
when the Scotsman returns to Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain theatricality to this travel experience, the
illusion that you're journeying on your own private train. The
staff of 20 eager-to-please young people don't wear name tags, just
as they wouldn't if they were working in your own stately home.
There are no bills to sign for meals or drinks; even the champagne
is included in the hefty price of around $1,000 a day per person.
There is just one sitting at meals, so no one's ever waiting,
everyone can linger, and the dining rooms don't feel like
restaurants. Even the toiletries in the bathrooms are on a
residential scale: Eight-ounce shampoo bottles instead of dinky
little hotel-size ones.
</P>
<P>
   The limited space of the cabins encourages orderly living. Two
people getting dressed in the cabin at the same time requires
choreography as intricate as a tango. If you don't hang up your
clothes or fold them in a drawer, they start piling up on the floor
like snowdrifts. There's no room to walk around. If I had the
money, I'd send my teenage son on the train, just to teach him what
a closet is for.
</P>
<P>
   Some people prefer spas for their self-indulgence, and there is
an advantage in that a spa gives you a shot at losing weight, which
the Scotsman certainly doesn't. The food is sublime, turned out by
two chefs who work in a tiny kitchen with a window onto the
corridor, so guests can watch them toil. (There used to be three
chefs, but there wasn't room for them all to maneuver in the small
space at the same time.) The chefs bake bread twice a day, and
create such extravagant dishes as roast sea bass with Jerusalem
artichokes, foie gras parfait, and roast squab with asparagus, all
complemented by excellent wines selected by Coupe. For an American,
the train's breakfast is actually the most adventurous meal, with a
different smoked fish each morning along with lamb kidneys and
black pudding, which is pig's blood sausage. (Nearly every other
breakfast-like substance is also available, and there were people
on my tour who opted for the yogurt and muesli.)
</P>
<P>
   Daily excursions in the luxuriously equipped bus (drinks, fruit
baskets, restroom) tended to be food- and drink-centered, too.
There was a private tour and tasting at the Strathisla Distillery,
where you learn how single malt Scotch is made. There was a visit
to the Inverawe Smokehouse, whose jolly owner, Robert
Campbell-Preston, gave a fish-smoking demonstration and then
invited us into his gabled manse for wine and samples of smoked
venison and eel, as well as the traditional salmon. (We were able
to consume only about half of this lavish buffet. I asked what
happened to the leftovers. They go, it seems, to the
pets-in-residence, Vietnamese pot-bellied pigs.)
</P>
<P>
   There was a visit to Kinloch Lodge on the Isle of Skye, where
Claire Macdonald, Scotland's version of Julia Child and the wife of
Lord Macdonald of Macdonald, the 34th high chief of Clan Macdonald,
offered one of her famous cooking demonstrations. Giving out
recipes for rack of lamb with pinhead oatmeal and cracked black
pepper crust, she also cheerfully gave us a piece of her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need full-fat foods in your diet,'' she said adamantly,
advocating exercise to offset them. ``People eating reduced fat
diets are leading pathetic lives. You can't look a cow in the eye
if you buy skim milk. It's filthy stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   For four delightful days, I followed Lady Macdonald's advice. I
don't know if I gained weight. There aren't any scales on the Royal
Scotsman. There isn't room.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information on Royal Scotsman trips or to book one, call
Abercrombie &AMP; Kent International at 800-323-7308. The e-mail
address is info(at)abercrombiekent.com, and the Web address is
www.abercrombiekent.com. The train also has its own Web site,
www.royalscotsman.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
