<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      08-24 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIBERGLASS INSULATES EVEN WHEN IT'S WET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am having my attic and the house insulated. What is better
to use: fiberglass or cellulose?
</P>
<P>
   R.D., North Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Both fiberglass and cellulose are good insulators, with
cellulose having a slightly higher R factor, which is a measurement
of the ability of the insulation to stop the loss of heat. The
higher the number that goes with an R factor, the better the
insulation.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think that it is a matter of what is the better
insulation, but one's personal preference. The handyman prefers
fiberglass, whether it is blown in the walls or laid on the attic
floor. Fiberglass is inert, and once it is secured in the walls or
on the floor, it does not pose a health hazard. It is fire
resistant, although any kraft paper that is used with the
insulation as a vapor barrier is not. Fiberglass doesn't lose its
insulating ability if it gets wet, and when it does, it tends to
dry out faster than cellulose.
</P>
<P>
   Cellulose, while a good insulator, is organic, and loses some of
its value when it gets wet and takes a long time to dry out. It is
treated with chemicals to make it fire resistant, but no one has
proved to me how long those chemicals are effective.
</P>
<P>
   The only time cellulose is superior to fiberglass is when it is
wet-blown. This is usually done only in commercial applications.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My kitchen cabinets are a white painted metal, 60 years old.
I would like to paint them a different color. Is that practical?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN BABOIAN, Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is definitely practical, and while new paint will perk up
the kitchen, new handles can, too. The handyman did this with some
steel cabinets (they were all the rage shortly after the war) in
Connecticut nearly 40 years ago. I can't say how long the paint
lasted, but it stood up nicely for me for some years.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, do not paint the interior of the cabinets; they
probably don't need it and you can save yourself a lot of tedious
work. Do paint both sides of the doors, however.
</P>
<P>
   Take off the hardware if you can, although the hinges might be
riveted instead of screwed or bolted on. Sand all surfaces to be
painted to reduce gloss and roughen the finish. Wash with a strong
solution of detergent and water.
</P>
<P>
   When painting, always apply thin coats. Apply a prime coat of
latex enamel undercoater, finish with two coats of a semigloss
latex enamel. Or, for a high shine and top durability and
washability, two coats of a semigloss or high-gloss oil-based,
indoor-outdoor enamel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I like the new vinyl lattice, but I can't find it in dark
brown. It only comes in white, dark green, light brown, and gray.
These colors would not work on my house.
</P>
<P>
   BARBARA SILBERMAN, Gloucester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know if any company makes dark brown lattice. You can
paint vinyl lattice and vinyl everything else, but I would not; it
would be iffy, and if it started to peel or chip, you'll have a
pretty ugly mess. I suggest this: Buy pressure-treated lattice and
stain it with a dark brown semitransparent stain. Just one coat is
needed and you can repeat, with one coat, in five years or so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We love our new smooth-top electric range, but there are two
problems: It has a stain that nothing seems to take out. I used the
special cream that comes with the stove for cleaning, without
success. What can I use? Also, the pots do not stay flat on the
smooth top, resulting in uneven heating. What can I do about that?
</P>
<P>
   ZELDA SOKAL, Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That's interesting. The handyman and his wife just got a
smooth-top range, and while we also love it, we have had problems
similar to yours. We did not have a stain that would not come out,
but that may be due to the fact that the handyman has taken off all
stains, some of them very stubborn, with careful use of Brillo or
SOS pads (not too heavy, of course, but not too light, either.)
There may be a taboo on using Brillo and other steel-wool products,
but that is mainly because we Americans tend to do a job with
maximum power and no holds barred. A moderately restrained
steel-wool cleaning will not hurt the glass.
</P>
<P>
   The second problem is typical with people who get new smooth-top
stoves: Their old pots and pans, no matter what quality, are
slightly warped and do not have full contact with the glass. The
only answer is to buy new kitchen ware, heavy-duty and of high
quality. You do not have to replace all the kitchen wear, just
enough to do good cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman's wife lucked out. Our kitchen wear was of high
quality, a wedding gift from her grandmother back in 1956. After
some years, it did get a bit distorted, but Mrs. Handyman inherited
a larger, heavier sauce pan from her mother. This one has stayed
flat and works perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   I am thinking of putting a metal trivet on the burner area and
the distorted pan on that, but this would reduce efficiency and
would tend to scratch the glass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
