<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1056 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-CAR-PETTY-HNS &LR;      08-24 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PETTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PETTYS' NASCAR STREAK NEARS AN END 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LEE SCHEIDE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As streaks go, not even Cal Ripken had a chance to touch this
one.
</P>
<P>
   When NASCAR was born in 1948, Lee Petty was one of the founding
members, coming out of the North Carolina backwoods to win three
driving titles in 15 years, along with the first Daytona 500 in
1959.
</P>
<P>
   He passed the torch to son Richard, who became the most prolific
NASCAR Winston Cup driver in history, winning seven championships
and 200 races.
</P>
<P>
   During Richard's reign as ``The King,'' his son, Kyle, joined
the family business, keeping the streak alive. And when Richard
retired after the 1992 season, Kyle was left to carry the family
banner into battle each week in Winston Cup ovals around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Though not as dominant on the track, Kyle brought his own flair
to the series, his pony-tailed hair reaching the middle of his
back, the earring catching the eye. His own man, Kyle drove for the
famed Wood Brothers and then Felix Sabates before returning to the
roost in 1997 to run his own team _ and to prepare the world for
the next generation, his son Adam.
</P>
<P>
   Always smiling like his father, Adam had the desire of his
grandfather, and those in the inner circle of NASCAR knew that a
contender had just stepped into the ring. After all, he'd already
found his way to Victory Lane, being hoisted on grandfather
Richard's shoulders at less than a year old after Richard won the
1981 Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Groomed through go-kart, American Speed Association and Busch
Grand National Series races, Adam attempted and qualified for his
first Winston Cup race in April, at Texas Motor Speedway.
Ironically, father Kyle couldn't make the field for his son's first
race, putting him in the unfamiliar role of observer.
</P>
<P>
   Had he known then the price his family was about to pay, no
price tag would have been too high to get Kyle into a car that day.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, on April 5, Lee Petty died, several weeks
after stomach surgery. The patriarch of the family had been ill, so
his death, while sudden, wasn't unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's, on May 12, in New Hampshire, knocked the family to its
knees.
</P>
<P>
   As Kyle and Adam's sister, Montgomery Lee, were flying to Europe
for an equestrian event, Adam's car hit the Turn 3 wall at full
throttle, causing severe head trauma that killed the 19-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   The town of High Point, N.C., rallied around Kyle; his wife,
Patti; Montgomery; and their other son, Austin. NASCAR circled its
wagons, protecting the entire Petty family during its time of
grief. Sprint, the chief sponsor on Adam's Busch car, parked its
car until Kyle was ready to put another driver in the seat.
</P>
<P>
   But Kyle wasn't ready to put anyone else in his son's seat
except himself. So when the team returned to the track, Kyle was
behind the wheel, sitting in Adam's seat, finding ways to keep
Adam's memory alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance for me to stay close to him,'' Kyle has said
time and again.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night at Bristol, Kyle will drive the Sprint car in the
Busch race, then hopefully pilot the Hot Wheels car Saturday
evening in the Winston Cup race. He's done it hundreds of times,
but Saturday's race is significant, because when the checkered flag
drops on the winner, it also will signal the end of Kyle's Winston
Cup season for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The next weekend, at Darlington, Steve Grissom will drive the
Hot Wheels car, making it the first start in NASCAR history that a
Petty, while healthy, hasn't been in a race. That's 2,172 races
over 52 years of competition.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Kyle will honor the memory of his son by driving the
remaining Busch Series races, then moving the Sprint car up to
Winston Cup competition next year. The plan had been for Adam to be
driving in 2001; now his father will take his place.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Petty Enterprises, headed by Kyle, will field three
Dodge Intrepids, with John Andretti in the familiar No. 43, and a
new driver and sponsor for the No. 44. Kyle will pilot the No. 45,
backed by Sprint, starting a new streak for the Pettys. But things
can never be the same for the Pettys _ or NASCAR _ who had hoped to
use Adam's infectious smile and youthful attitude to drive into the
next two or three decades.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Lee Scheide by e-mail at lscheide(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
