<HEADLINE>
LEARNING TO WEASEL WITH EASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I called Jeanne Martinet, author of ``Artful Dodging:
Painless Techniques for Avoiding Anyone Anytime,'' she said she
couldn't talk or she'd be late for her massage.
</P>
<P>
   This particular ploy, the massage dodge, can be found on page 66
of ``Artful Dodging'' (St. Martin's Griffin, $11.95). As Martinet
pointed out before she hung up, it's a good dodge because just
about anybody would drop whatever they're doing in favor of getting
a massage.
</P>
<P>
   Martinet promised to call back, and she did. Not calling back is
one of the Seven Dodging Sins, set forth in chapter one, The Ethics
of Evasion. Even dodgers have their standards, sort of. (There are
ways to get credit for calling back yet manage to avoid actually
speaking with the person in question. See chapter nine,
Telecommunication Tricks).
</P>
<P>
   Martinet believes that dodging is the grease that makes the
squeaky wheel of life move a bit more smoothly. Unfortunately, the
little white lie, which, she writes, ``used to be an accepted sign
of good breeding and a sensitive nature'' is now in disrepute. For
many people, the word ``dodger'' evokes the image of ``a sniveling,
sneaking snake in the grass.'' But, as Martinet writes, most of the
world's dodging is done by nice, normal people, even if they don't
like to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   Martinet has written several books on social interaction,
including, ``The Art of Mingling,'' a popular handbook that has
earned its author the nickname Miss Mingle. That book gave her the
idea for ``Artful Dodging,'' because, she said, ``Most people
seemed to think the most interesting part of it was about how to
escape people.''
</P>
<P>
   She also felt that the knack of the graceful dodge was in danger
of dying out. ``People know how to say no, they just don't know how
to say no nicely,'' she said. ``They think it's almost spiritual to
be totally honest and direct, but that is so selfish. Sometimes you
have to sacrifice your own need to tell the truth to avoid hurting
someone else's feelings. Tell me a lie even if I can't believe it.
At least it means you're trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodging isn't serious lying. It's not inflating your resume or
failing to RSVP or breaking promises, all of which are dodging
no-nos's in Martinet's book. Artful dodging is done for good
reasons, among them self-defense, face-saving, protecting your
privacy, avoiding boredom, saving time, preserving what remains of
your sanity.
</P>
<P>
   The dodge can be as simple and classic as claiming to be sick,
or saying you were stuck in traffic or using your kids as an excuse
(``The baby-sitter canceled at the last minute.''). Martinet
provides an encyclopedia of excuses, ranging from semi-standards
like the doggie dodge (`I'd love to come but my dog is sick''), to
more inventive gambits like nihilism (``I'm sorry, I just don't see
the point of anything anymore''), and UFO sightings (``You may not
believe this, but I saw this huge group of people by the side of
the road looking up at the sky . . .'').
</P>
<P>
   The really ambitious may work their way up to daredevil dodging.
These are advanced techniques that require a lot of nerve and
energy, such as offensive dodging, in which you try to make
yourself so obnoxious that the other person will want to avoid you,
permanently. Martinet writes that offensive dodging isn't her
style, but that some people like it. ``It's proactive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinet's dodging days may be over since she wrote this book.
``Nobody ever believes a word I say anymore,'' she said. ``I can't
get out of anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
