<SLUG> BC-BOOK-OMERTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUZO'S FORMULA HAS A FEW TWISTS, TURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
OMERTA 
By Mario Puzo. 
Random House, 316 pp., $25.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early reviewers have given scant respect to ``Omerta,'' the
final novel by Mario Puzo, author ofone of the great American
myths, ``The Godfather.'' That hasn't stopped Hollywood from
snapping up the film rights, nor has it kept the book off the
bestseller lists. And reviewers should have been more cautious _
``Omerta'' is full of examples of what happens to people who don't
show respect. A bought judge is sent a ribboned box suitable for
holding a pair of long silk gloves; inside is a pair of severed
arms. Retribution is swift, fatal, final, and merciless. Readers
begin ``Omerta'' at their own peril:They should not plan to
accomplish anything else until they finish it.
</P>
<P>
   Puzo died in July 1999, leaving behind the manuscript of
``Omerta,'' which he had been working on for three years. Random
House is publicizing the book as the concluding volume of a ``Mafia
Trilogy'' that began with ``The Godfather'' and continued with
``The Last Don.'' On the second page, there is a reference to the
Mafia families of the earlier two books; this book presents a
third, the family of Don Raymonde Aprile, and at a different moment
in the American history of the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   The RICO anti-crime legislation has been passed, and Don
Raymonde realizes that his time is over. He has gradually divested
himself of the overtly illegal aspects of his business and intends
to concentrate on banking. But there are interests that do not wish
him to do so, and they resort to extreme measures _ Don Raymonde is
assassinated on the steps of St. Patrick's Cathedral. His children
inherit his 10 private banks, but also the enmity of those who want
the banks for their own purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The only person who stands between Don Raymonde's children and
an unhappy fate is Astorre Zeno, brought up by Don Raymonde as a
brother to them. Astorre is a merchant in macaroni, with a singing
voice turned a little goofy by a neck wound imperfectly concealed
by a thick gold chain and medallion. Don Raymonde's children don't
know that their childhood playmate's father was one of the great
dons of Sicily, and that Astorre has been brought up in the old
ways, which he must now adapt to a new set of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   There are many twists and turns in the plot, which moves between
past and present, from California to New York, Washington, D.C.,
and Sicily; the bad guys include a drug lord, a rival don, corrupt
police, a pair of assassins who are identical twins, and, of
course, an FBI that is all too eager to cooperate with its target
and enemy. There are many ingeniously satisfactory executions and
murders more elaborate than a curious offstage one Puzo mentions,
in which an overambitious mobster apparently commits suicide in the
trunk of his own car. And there are some alluring and dangerous
females _ Don Raymonde's daughter is a newer stereotype, a feisty
feminist lawyer opposed to the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   To say more about the plot would be unfair; the end is
predictable, and so are some of those twists and turns _ Puzo
sometimes helps himself to some of his best earlier ideas _ but
there are also some new climbs and drops on the road, and some
scary chasms off to the side.
</P>
<P>
   The story in ``Omerta'' is complete, but the book doesn't feel
finished; parts of it read like an outline Puzo intended to fill in
later. Puzo tells a perfectly serviceable story, but the book keeps
suggesting ways it could easily have been further developed. Puzo
sets situations up to give the story resonance and then doesn't
really use them _ one of Don Raymonde's sons, for example, is
stationed at West Point; another is a television executive. Both
circumstances contribute to the machinery of the plot, but the
younger Puzo would have made something of the parallels, and the
divergences, between the Mafia, the media, and the military.
</P>
<P>
   Too much of the dialogue is stiff, artificial, and preachy, and
the narrative voice isn't consistent either, but there is still
some zest in the telling; a delight in the sights, sounds, tastes,
and smells of Sicily; and a clearly communicated belief in honor.
Occasionally Puzo reminds you that he was once a novelist with
literary ambitions and accomplishments; even ``The Godfather''
wasn't primarily intended to be a commercial venture. ``Omerta''
touches on themes that are bigger than it is and that Puzo didn't
have the time or the stamina to realize.
</P>
<P>
   But even when he falls back on formula, it's a satisfying
formula. After all, he invented it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
