<HEADLINE>
ATLANTIC MONTHLY GETS A NEW LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not conjure up the jaggy Gen-X sensibility of ESPN The
Magazine or Wired, but the September issue of The Atlantic Monthly
doesn't evoke images of a tradition-bound New England literary
journal either. Charles C. Mann's cover story on the war over
Internet music piracy (or more egalitarian distribution, depending
on your view) is garnished with a colorful, eye-catching
techno-graphic of ``The Heavenly Jukebox . . . From Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Michael Kelly's magazine. The political columnist and
former New Republic editor, who became The Atlantic's editor after
David Bradley bought it from Mort Zuckerman last fall, is reshaping
a magazine that in recent years was more respected than read. This
week, he's preparing to show advertisers a 32-page prototype of a
major redesign slated for January. He's hired Robert Vare, formerly
of The New Yorker, as senior editor to ride herd on the magazine's
longer pieces. And on Sept. 1, Benjamin Schwarz, former executive
editor of World Policy Journal, joins the staff to edit an expanded
``back of the book'' section on literature and arts.
</P>
<P>
   Relying liberally on his Rolodex (he is still editor-in-chief of
The National Journal), Kelly has also secured Atlantic Monthly
commitments from a number of high-profile writers, including:
Weekly Standard senior editor David Brooks; author Richard Ben
Kramer; former New Republic executive editor Margaret Talbot;
Washington Post reporter Hanna Rosin; National Journal White House
correspondent Carl Cannon; National Journal media critic William
Powers; and Alan Wolfe, director of the Center for Religion and
American Public Life at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a concern when Kelly took the helm from William
Whitworth, it was that he might re-route The Atlantic toward
politics, transforming it into a New Republic with longer word
counts. Thus, an eyebrow or two was probably raised by James
Fallows's July cover story on Al Gore's pit-bull debating
technique, highlighted by a striking illustration of Gore with an
ominously bared fang. (Before Kelly was fired at The New Republic,
his view of Gore didn't exactly jibe with that of his boss and
longtime Gore friend, Marty Peretz.)
</P>
<P>
   But thus far, Kelly's remained true to his promise to edit an
``eclectic magazine.'' The May cover story challenged the idea that
it is girls, more than boys, who are at risk in our educational
system. The June cover piece took a look at Unabomber Ted
Kaczynski's strange college daze at Harvard, and August featured a
way-off-the-beaten-path piece on the beach in India where brave men
tear apart discarded sea vessels. Coming in October _ a Wolfe cover
story about the drive for higher educational standards at
evangelical colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only true serious weakness in Bill Whitworth's Atlantic
was the covers,'' says former Atlantic editor Robert Manning. Under
Kelly, ``there's been a definite change, an improvement in the
covers,'' he says. ``From what I've seen, he's off to a very good
start.''
</P>
<P>
   The January redesign should reveal whether Kelly's got a second
act as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the contenders to buy The (Quincy, Mass.)
Patriot Ledger and The (Brockton, Mass.) Enterprise is now a former
contender. Kirk Davis, president of Fidelity's Community Newspaper
Company, says it dropped out of the bidding as ``our focus has
shifted from acquisitions to product development and customer
satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   With final bids reportedly in, the remaining candidates are
thought to include Boston Herald publisher Patrick Purcell, the
Journal Register Co., and, according to a report in the Herald, a
Maryland company that publishes shoppers. None of the parties would
comment on their plans, including one potential suitor whose name
recently surfaced in the rumor mill, the Dallas-based Belo company,
which owns The Providence Journal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bosses at Boston magazine are apparently in no hurry to
anoint a new editor to replace Craig Unger. For one thing, the
trains are running on time these days under a makeshift management
team headed by former art director _ now newly named ``creative
director'' _ Joseph Heroun. (One former staffer who's just returned
is editor-at-large Sean Flynn.)
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that the magazine's planning process has been
sharpened under this unusual in-house leadership committee,
associate publisher Dan Scully says: ``If you're keeping score,
it's unorthodox method one, traditional method nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Detroit News editor and publisher Robert Giles may have
seen his successful candidacy for Harvard Nieman Foundation curator
become ensnared in controversy due to smoldering resentments over
the Detroit newspaper strike. But he's already demonstrating
impressive institutional clout in his new post.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation just announced that Ignacio Gomez, a Colombian
investigative journalist forced to flee to the United States in
fear of his life, has been added to this year's Nieman class,
thanks to Giles's former employer. Giles, a former senior vice
president of the Freedom Forum _ a foundation devoted to free press
and free speech issues _ convinced his old bosses to foot the
$35,000 bill for Gomez's stay at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Newspaper Guild local at the Boston Globe is helping Globe
columnist Jeff Jacoby contest his four-month suspension without pay
for using, without attribution, other accounts for a column on the
fates of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. Both union
president Robert Jordan and Globe spokesman Richard Gulla confirm
the filing of Jacoby's grievance, which is expected to generate
meetings soon between union and newspaper officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
