<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TONIGHT-ADV28-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV28
</HEADLINE>
   FOR RELEASE: Monday, AUG. 28, 2000 
 TV-TONIGHT COLUMN 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tonight at 8, Showtime debuts ``Bash,'' a nearly two-hour filmed
version of Neil LaBute's controversial 1999 stage trilogy, ``Bash:
Latterday Plays.'' Calista Flockhart (``Ally McBeal''), Paul Rudd
(``Reaching Normal'') and Ron Eldard (``ER'') star, but if you're
looking for light-hearted entertainment, you better skip this.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute is the writer of, among others, the caustic film ``In the
Company of Men,'' and his rather bleak view of humankind offers us
grim confessions of the suffocation of a baby, an affair between a
student and a teacher, and a fatal gay-bashing _ the latter by a
Mormon, no less. Like early Elvis Costello songs, LaBute focuses on
revenge and guilt, especially the latter, and his work can be an
acquired taste.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its grimness, this was also an acclaimed production,
compellingly acted. It's another bit of edgework for Showtime,
which is trying to get a bigger piece of HBO's turf as a cable
network that dares.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Battle at Bighorn: Tiger Woods vs. Sergio Garcia'' ABC at 8:
No ``Monday Night Football'' tonight, but this should actually be
more fun than most preseason NFL games. The made-for-TV showdown is
live from the Bighorn course in Indio, Calif. But the way Tiger's
been playing lately, it may not be as competitive as the network
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: The torment continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mysterious Ways,'' NBC at 8: Declain investigates a
separated-at-birth case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opposite Sex,'' Fox at 8: When alcohol cancels a field trip
for them, the kids spend a night loose inside the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moesha,'' UPN at 8: Moesha considers a life-changing offer
after a romantic disappointment. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of Queens,'' CBS at 8:30: Doug invites Arthur to a Mets
