<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ULSTER-LOYALISTS-BOS &LR;      08-24 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ULSTER-LOYALISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOYALIST VS. LOYALIST: THE DEPTHS OF AN ULSTER STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With the arrest of a Protestant paramilitary leader,
Johnny Adair, police in Northern Ireland hoped they had defused a
feud among rival pro-British loyalist groups that had left bodies
in the street over the past week and that had exposed a worrisome
consequence of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   While it was convenient to blame Adair, whose nickname is ``Mad
Dog'' and who has a reputation for popping steroids, for the surge
in violence in Belfast, the outbreak of shootings and street
fighting has its roots in a feud among Protestant guerrillas that
goes back 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, it is a turf war between the two main armed
loyalist groups, the Ulster Volunteer Force and the Ulster Defense
Association, over the spoils of criminal rackets in their
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But at a more fundamental level, the feud is an inevitable
result of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Loyalists, like Irish republicans, are sharply divided on what
the Good Friday Agreement of 1998 will bring. Most in the Ulster
Volunteer Force say the historic compromise means an eventual union
of Northern Ireland with Britain. Most in the Ulster Defense
Association assert that it has made a united Ireland inevitable _ a
prospect they dread.
</P>
<P>
   Irish republicans, especially the Irish Republican Army, are
similarly divided. While the bulk of republicans say politics is
the only way forward, a fundamentalist core still clings to the
dream of ending British rule in Northern Ireland by force. The
fundamentalists have been planting bombs in London and across
Northern Ireland trying to wreck the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Although loyalists have been killing one another for years over
petty rivalries and drug deals gone bad, it was not until they
torched Gusty Spence's house the other day that it became clear
just how bitter the internecine rivalry has become.
</P>
<P>
   Augustus ``Gusty'' Spence is the founder of the loyalist
paramilitaries. It was he who told a ragtag bunch of angry
working-class Protestants 35 years ago that they were the
successors to the original Ulster Volunteer Force, which took up
arms 80 years ago to resist the British government's inclination to
solve the Irish question by granting the island independence.
</P>
<P>
   Spence's recruits singled out and killed ordinary Roman
Catholics in Belfast to instill fear, and to quash talk of a united
Ireland. It was Spence who shot and killed John Patrick Scullion, a
28-year-old Catholic from West Belfast. Scullion's murder in 1966
is regarded as the first in what came to be known as the Troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Over the following three years, loyalists picked off other
Catholics here and there, their fury stoked by a civil rights
movement demanding equal rights for Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   It was their campaign of terror that brought British troops onto
the streets of Northern Ireland in August 1969. The loyalist
campaign also revived the IRA, which had laid down its guns a
decade before, saying its goal of driving the British from Northern
Ireland and uniting with the Republic of Ireland was hopeless. In
1969, the IRA was reborn as the protectors of Catholic
nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   How ironic, then, that it was the spiraling loyalist-on-loyalist
violence that brought British troops back onto the streets of
Belfast this week for the first time in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Under the peace process launched by the Good Friday accord,
nearly all paramilitary prisoners have been released over the past
two years. The loyalist prisoners returned to a community at war
with itself. Those who support the peace process and those who
don't are killing each other over their differences, as well as
over petty jealousies, rivalries, and who gets to shake down the
fish-and-chip shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committing hara-kiri,'' said David Ervine, who became
politicized in prison under Spence's tutelage and emerged
determined to find a political solution to the conflict he once
thought could only be solved by force.
</P>
<P>
   Ervine's colleague, Billy Hutchinson, has survived repeated
assassination attempts, the most recent a few days ago when shots
were fired at his house. On Monday night, after two loyalists were
shot to death in their car in West Belfast, Hutchinson acknowledged
that the feud has been simmering for years, but made it clear that
he blamed Adair for the recent surge.
</P>
<P>
   Adair, a shaven-headed man who revels in the ``Mad Dog'' moniker
bestowed upon him by the tabloids, is the Belfast commander of the
Ulster Defense Association. His group, while larger in numbers, has
never matched the Ulster Volunteer Force in discipline and
ideology, which fed an inferiority complex that has manifested
itself in murderous ways.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Adair took a previously undisciplined group
of gangsters and transformed them into one of the most ruthless
death squads ever seen in Northern Ireland. It was Adair's ability
to kill scores of Catholics, including many members of Sinn Fein,
the IRA's political wing, that many believe influenced the Irish
republican leadership to wind down the war and seek a political
solution.
</P>
<P>
   The police put Adair in prison on what even republicans consider
trumped-up charges, and there he soon established himself as one of
the leading loyalist proponents of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   But many now believe that was only a cynical tactic aimed at
securing his release from prison. Once on the street, police say,
Adair plunged back into the underworld of loyalist racketeering,
where the line is blurry between protecting and exploiting one's
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one man is the cause of all this trouble,'' said
Hutchinson, whose embrace of the peace process is often misread as
pacifism. ``You know the IRA is sitting back, laughing, watching
all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it is. On Monday night, a leading IRA man in Belfast
chuckled as he watched television coverage of the feud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loyalists have turned on themselves because they don't
know how to manage the peace process,'' he said. ``The bulk of
loyalism is scared, and in that vacuum a gangster like Adair will
prosper. Loyalists are scared because they know the game is up.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the situation is that Johnny Adair and his ilk find
themselves agreeing with the IRA that the process will lead to a
united Ireland. Hutchinson and the bulk of the Ulster Volunteer
Force believe the opposite: that the the Good Friday Agreement will
make Northern Ireland a more attractive place to live, so that even
the bulk of Catholics will want it to remain part of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Taking Adair off the street might help in the short term, as it
did a half-dozen years ago when the police arrested him, briefly
ending a series of sectarian murders. But another charismatic
loyalist, Billy Wright, stepped into the void and led a dissident
group of loyalists away from the negotiating table, murdering
Catholics in an attempt to goad the IRA back to war even after
Wright was murdered by republican dissidents in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Peace process or not, on the streets where Billy Hutchinson grew
up, scores are settled in the neighborhood, not in the courts to
which loyalists profess loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland has changed dramatically these last 10 years,
but old habits die hard _ as will more loyalists, on the mean
streets of Belfast and beyond.
</P>
</TEXT>
