<HEADER>
A1080 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-TV-TONIGHT-ADV29-NYTS     08-24 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TONIGHT-ADV29-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV29
</HEADLINE>
   FOR RELEASE: Tuesday, AUG. 29, 2000 
 TV TONIGHT 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   High-fives all around for the Fox Family Channel. The late,
lamented NBC series ``Freaks and Geeks,'' which lasted only one
season, pops up just a few months later on the cable channel, which
tonight at 8 debuts a weekly double-episode run.
</P>
<P>
   The show, created by Paul Feig, offers a terrifically real look
at high school life on the outside of social cliques, circa 1980.
The right music, clothes and attitudes ground the stories of sister
and brother Lindsay and Sam Weir, sensitively played by Linda
Cardellini and John Daley, two Michigan teens just trying to
survive high school. Lindsay is a brain who's started hanging out
with the freaks; Sam is just a geek, but a smart one. From this you
get an idea of what Feig's Michigan teen life was like; the series
draws very much on his experiences.
</P>
<P>
   If you liked ``The Wonder Years,'' in particular, but also
``That '70s Show'' or the movie ``Dazed and Confused,'' give this a
chance. Included in the run will be three episodes NBC never aired.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: On and on and on and on ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire,'' ABC at 8: Regis Philbin
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That '70s Show,'' Fox at 8: Really, you should be watching
``Freaks and Geeks'' (see above). You've already seen the one where
Eric and Donna get caught in an intimate encounter in the Vista
Cruiser, right? Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' ABC at 9: Greg's attempt to find himself
leads to a hot-sheet motel. Hmmm. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Source Hip-Hop Music Awards,'' UPN at 8: We're told the
show will go on, despite the massive brawl that ended last week's
taping with pepper spray and hospitalizations after only a few
awards had been handed out. Li'l Kim did perform, but still, if
this lasts two hours, it may be a shoo-in for next year's Emmy for
editing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just Shoot Me,'' NBC at 9:30: Victoria Principal guests as an
ex-wife of George Segal's Jack. These two old pros are fun to watch
together. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Open Tennis update, CBS at 12:35 a.m. From Flushing, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dog Skip,'' pay-per-view, various times: Frankie Muniz of
``Malcolm in the Middle'' stars in this PG-rated,
heartstring-tugging story of a boy and his Jack Russell terrier,
based on the Willie Morris book. Kevin Bacon and Diane Lane also
star.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Daria: Is It Fall Yet?'' MTV at 7:30: Excellent animated
series gets a 90-minute showcase for its mordant take on adolescent
life. Included is Daria's stint as a counselor at the ``It's OK to
Cry'' self-esteem summer camp, and that alone should make it worth
watching. But there's also a new twist. Daria is dating, and
actually has to cope with happiness. It's one thing she may not be
able to deal with in her usual sarcastic fashion. Good for teens
and their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Real World,'' MTV at 10: For once, the title is actually
deserved, as the roommates get a trip to South Africa bringing them
face to face with some realities of the apartheid era. Oh, and they
rappel down a cliff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beggars and Choosers,'' Showtime at 10: More satirical
intrigue behind the scenes of a fictional TV network. Tonight, a
hit show jumps ship.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Ricki Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Martin Sheen of
``West Wing.'' Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05 a.m.:
TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 1:05: Carmen
Electra, Stone Temple Pilots. (Note time after tennis.) Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Ethan Hawke,
Jerry Springer and band Supergrass. Rerun. &QL;
