<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Aug. 25:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak proposed
Thursday that if peace efforts fail, the rightist opposition party
Likud should join his government to help carry out his civil/social
reform plan. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RELIGION (Beijing) _ About 130 evangelical Christians,
including three visiting Americans on a religious mission, were
arrested in central China on Wednesday as they attended a revival
meeting, according to police officials and the arrested Americans'
pastor in California. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-U.S. (Washington) _ Mexican President-elect Vincente Fox
is scheduled to meet President Bill Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore on Thursday. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ A Norwegian admiral was quoted in a
newspaper Thursday as saying that he had nearly called off Norway's
efforts to rescue the crew of the Russian submarine Kursk because
of Russian officials' interference and misinformation. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-UNREST (London) _ Violence between Protestant guerrilla
groups claimed a third victim Thursday when a man was shot dead
overnight. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-IRAQ-ARMS (United Nations) _ Developments at the U.N.
meeting on plans for new arms inspections in Iraq. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TAXES (Washington) _ With a stunt of a farmer on a
tractor, congressional Republicans send the inheritance tax bill to
Clinton for a certain veto. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code
</P>
<P>
   GORE-PERCEPTION (Undated) _ A Political Memo: What a difference
a week makes. Al Gore's crowds are big and enthusiastic, he's
acting with confidence, the polls are up and his opponents seems a
bit defensive. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Miami) _ George W. Bush's campaign day. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Washington) _ Al Gore's campaign day. By Katherine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-PARKS (Anchorage) _ Former President Jimmy Carter said
his eleventh-hour decision in 1980 to protect millions of acres of
land in Alaska, doubling the national park acreage, was his
proudest achievement. Alaskans burned him in effigy. But Alaska has
changed and tourism is booming. With Carter here to celebrate the
20th anniversary of the Alaska Lands Act, the locals are welcoming
him warmly. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-EDUCATION-GAP (Washington) _ Test results show that the gap
in educational achievement between whites and blacks has remained
steady in the 1990s after narrowing in the 1970s and 1980s. The gap
has even widened for those with the most education. By Kate
Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   GA-JEW-LYNCH (Marietta, Ga.) _ The lynching of Leo Frank 85
years ago has cast a long shadow in this town. A play about the
case is being performed locally and a researcher has claimed to
have tied the lynching to some of the town's most prominent
families. Some non-Jews see this as a time to actively seek a way
to make amends. But while the town has changed a great deal,
longtime Jewish residents feel they still need to keep their heads
down. By Jane Gross.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIFE-ORIGINS (Undated) _ Experiments attempting to replicate
the hot, high-pressure conditions near deep-sea vents have
succeeded in synthesizing an obscure chemical that is a key to
several life cycles, supporting the view that life originated in
such places, and boosting the stock of a self-taught German chemist
who has been plugging the theory for several years. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVOR-RATINGS (Undated) _ CBS says the two-hour finale of
``Survivor'' drew 51 million viewers, more than expected, making it
the most-watched show for the 1999-2000 television season after the
Super Bowl. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly column: Looking at
decimalization. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   Editors, no Marketplace column on days with a Norris column.
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON (Undated) _ Developments following Verizon's settlement
with the last of its striking workers. Separately, Verizon
Wireless, the joint venture between Verizon and Vodafone files to
raise $5 billion in an initial public offering. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NINTENDO (Undated) _ Nintendo has become the last of
Japan's big game-machine makers to enter the competitive market for
next-generation consoles, saying that it will introduce its
Gamecube next year along with as a successor to the wildly
successful Game Boy.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TELECOM (London) _ On what happens to the smaller
companies in European telecommunications, like Royal KPN of the
Netherlands and Sonera of Finland, now that the big wireless
auctions are over. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI-RECALL (Tokyo) _ Looking at the impact of the recall
on Mitsubishi Motors. By Miki Tanikawa.
</P>
