<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1090 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-FLORA-LEWIS-AUGUST24-     08-24 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORA-LEWIS-AUGUST24-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGUISH OVER THE KURSK IS WIDELY SHARED  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 825-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of the FLORA LEWIS column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Flora Lewis  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   PARIS _ It is important for Russians to know, in their anguish
and anger, how much most everybody else sympathized over the
tragedy of the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   It was a warship, built to attack, but among the once and
perhaps still supposed foe, there was no gloating or sense of
superiority, which Moscow's military establishment seemed to fear.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, what disdain was felt in the west was for the
demonstration of the automatic way the old Soviet habits of lying
and secrecy still seem to dominate in a moment of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   It is evident that people in Russia feel the same way. Their
government has lost a great deal more by delayed reaction and
awkward cover-up than by the accident itself, still unexplained.
</P>
<P>
   What impact that may have on future Moscow behavior is hard to
foresee. It matters that at least on this painful occasion, there
is a common concern among Russians and westerners alike for the
right to know.
</P>
<P>
   We will probably never find out for sure whether a quicker
response, a willingness to accept foreign help from the start
instead of a proud rejection would actually have saved some lives.
</P>
<P>
   Neither fear of loss of face nor fear of loss of some kind of
military secret could have justified the refusal to rush all the
useful expertise available so long as there was any chance of
finding survivors.
</P>
<P>
   There was a shared agony of hoping and waiting for rescue and
need to be kept informed that showed how much people on two sides
of the shredded Iron Curtain now recognize they have in common.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days before the Kursk went down, the Concorde crashed
in flames outside Paris. Both represented modern marvels of
technology, tangible assertions of prestige that are not
particularly practical and prove, after all, not to be invulnerable
either.
</P>
<P>
   But an airplane accident, awful as it may be, happens in a flash
and there is time only to grieve afterwards. The submarine sat
there in the freezing sea, men pounding on the hull begging to be
saved and gradually gasping away life. There was time to feel the
terror.
</P>
<P>
   And it should leave a heightened awareness of what it means to
agree that the Cold War is over, that there is no longer any point
in maintaining the posture that what is bad for one side is good
for the other.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides need honesty from their leaders. It is
almost as much in the interest of the west as for the Russians that
a police state mentality doesn't manage to restore repression.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the need of making clear the human warmth of condolence
and the political requirement of valid information, there is the
problem of the result of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   It is normal and understandable that the relatives of those who
died would like the bodies recovered, though burial at sea is an
honorable old tradition. But whether that effort is made or not, it
is necessary to make sure the nuclear reactors are permanently
sanitized.
</P>
<P>
   At the relatively shallow depth of the submarine wreckage, there
is a risk of rusting containers releasing radioactivity. That is
already a serious danger in the area of the Kola peninsula, which
the Russians have long been using as a dumpling ground for old
nuclear engines to the grave distress of their Norwegians
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   It is time that more serious attention be paid to Norwegian
warnings. They do know what they are talking about because they
have been watching this as closely as still intense Russian secrecy
makes possible, and they have a great deal of underwater expertise,
as their divers demonstrated in opening the Kursk hatch, because of
maintaining North Sea oil rigs.
</P>
<P>
   The cost, the difficulty and the long dangerous delays in
dismantling the various components of nuclear warfare are not yet
widely understood. This is the aftermath of the nuclear arms race
and it is monstrous.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be kept in mind in considering the possibility of a
national missile defense as proposed in the U.S. provoking a new
arms race, partly with China, partly with Russian modernization.
</P>
<P>
   Disarming is not a simple matter of throwing away weapons. It is
an extremely intricate and expensive task, for which the U.S. is
wisely helping Russia a bit in financing, but there is a lot more
to do. It is urgent and can buy a lot more security per dollar
spent than some of the extravagant Pentagon ideas.
</P>
<P>
   With the new millennium, there has been a tendency to lose
memory of the lessons imposed by the Cold War and what a burden it
was. The disaster of the Kursk is a reminder that the opportunity
to work together for a peaceful world must be seized and that it is
normal for human emotions to be shared. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist
for The New York Times. She is the author of five books, including
``Europe: Road To Unity'' and ``Europe: A Tapestry of Nations.''
Her articles have appeared in the International Herald Tribune, The
New York Times Magazine, The Atlantic, The Economist, France-Soir,
Life, The London Observer, The New Yorker and many other
periodicals. Last year she won the Overseas Press Club's Award for
Lifetime Achievement.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the FLORA
LEWIS column and other features. &QL;
</P>
