<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-LARS-VON-TRIER-FAIRCH     08-24 1765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LARS-VON-TRIER-FAIRCHILD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARS VON TRIER: PRINCE OF DARKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By AARON GELL 
 (One color slide is available.) 
 From W magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    He may be the enfant terrible of the international film circuit,
notorious for his unguarded remarks, his crusade to put
overindulgent filmmakers on a creative austerity program, his
crippling phobias and, most of all, for his films themselves _
brutal, beautiful, shattering tragedies that tend to leave
audiences either sobbing or cursing his name.
 &HT;    But today, sitting in an office at Zentropa, his sprawling
film-production facility housed in a former army base on the
outskirts of Copenhagen, Lars Von Trier is in good spirits.
 &HT;    The primary reason is out in the parking lot: a spiffy,
cherry-red Alfa Romeo Spider convertible.
 &HT;    ``Ah, doesn't it look new!'' Von Trier remarks. Moments later,
we're flying down a nearby expressway.
 &HT;    ``I won't go very fast,'' promises the director as he nudges the
car into fifth and fumbles with the stereo, adding, ``It's just ...
the acceleration is so very nice.''
 &HT;    Overhead, the sun suddenly pushes its way through a thick carpet
of Scandinavian clouds, and the Beach Boys' ``I Get Around'' drowns
out the hum of the engine. Von Trier is beaming.
 &HT;    Given his well-known political leanings (he used to belong to
the Danish Communist party), to say nothing of his long history of
severe panic attacks, the Alfa Romeo is a bit out of character.
It's actually on loan as some sort of promotional gesture by the
automaker, which is apparently harboring a true subversive in its
marketing department.
 &HT;    ``My first wife would never have allowed this car,'' Von Trier
says. ``But my new wife is very nice. She thinks having a sports
car is a basic human right.''
 &HT;    So does Von Trier, who cheerfully tosses the keys to anyone who
asks to take it for a spin.
 &HT;    Besides, the director has earned a little fun. By all accounts,
the making of his latest picture, the Palme d'Or-winning musical
melodrama ``Dancer in the Dark,'' was an excruciating experience.
 &HT;    Like 1996's ``Breaking the Waves,'' ``Dancer'' centers on a
dreamily naive, willfully self-sacrificing young woman. Selma, a
Czech immigrant living in the Pacific Northwest in the late 1950s,
is losing her sight due to a hereditary disease. She works in a
factory, saving up for an operation that will protect her son from
the same fate. But after a friend betrays her and steals the money,
the world caves in on her: Selma winds up charged with murder.
Meanwhile, she daydreams of movie musicals.
 &HT;    It's operatic stuff by any standard, but as most everyone knows
by now, the real melodrama took place off-camera between Von Trier
and his lead actress, the Icelandic pop star Bjork, who very nearly
quit the film.
 &HT;    (At one point, she reportedly climbed a fence to escape the
experience and tore at her costume in a frenzy.)
 &HT;    ``We had some difficulties collaborating,'' Von Trier says
slowly. Asked what the trouble was about, he says, ``It was just
that for her it was extremely tough to do it. She felt trapped and
claustrophobic and betrayed and whatever.'' He adds that since
Bjork, who composed the film's music, is accustomed to having total
creative freedom, serving his vision proved difficult.
 &HT;    ``Usually, she's in charge,'' he says. ``But if she's in my
story, I have to stop her all the time. That's direction, that's
where the word comes from, right? I'm pointing the direction, and
this is not very pleasant if you go right and I want to point
left.''
 &HT;    Although it was her first role, Von Trier says, Bjork
immediately took to his improvisational approach.
 &HT;    ``She was so extremely good at it,'' he says. ``I felt like a
lion tamer, and she was my best lion. She could do all kinds of
tricks if she wanted, but otherwise, rraaarrgh!''
 &HT;    It seems that Bjork, who declined to comment for this article,
came to associate Von Trier with a different sort of creature.
After the film wrapped, she gave cast and crew members little
animal figurines as gifts. The director got a rat.
 &HT;    Von Trier sighs. ``I'm sure I've been an asshole,'' he says,
``but I've also been extremely pressed, right? This was a very big
production for us. At a certain point, if she had walked out, we
would have been extremely bankrupt. And my four children would have
had to sleep outdoors. This is something that is not really
artistic to talk about, but it's a fact of life.''
 &HT;    The resulting film, which caused a sensation at Cannes and
earned the elfin singer the Best Actress award, is like nothing
ever seen before, a gorgeous musical fantasy crossed with an almost
medieval tale of exquisite suffering. Von Trier says that as with
``Breaking the Waves,'' his aim was to bring a sense of
authenticity to the unfashionable genre of melodrama.
 &HT;    ``My mother and father were Communists and cultural radicals,''
he explains, ``so they thought a story like this was the worst _
opium for the people. Since this was so forbidden when I was young
and people became so angry, I thought there had to be some good
qualities there.''
 &HT;    People still get angry around Von Trier. Detractors accuse him
of cheap sentimentality, even misogyny for the tortures he inflicts
on his female protagonists. He doesn't seem to mind a bit.
 &HT;    Since he regards it as the artist's role in society to, as he
says, ``take you by the hand and lead you somewhere you didn't want
to go on your own,'' a bit of resistance seems only natural.
 &HT;    ``I have tried to see how far I could go with this,'' he says
when asked about the misfortunes that inevitably befall his
heroines. ``It's a matter of taste if you think it works, but I
haven't yet reached the limit. I still don't know how bad it can
get.''
 &HT;    Let's just say that for Selma, it gets uncommonly bad.
 &HT;    ``When you want to work with melodrama, then you have to find
some tools,'' Von Trier says with a shrug. ``The first tool was the
mother and child. And then a handicap is good, very good.''
 &HT;    The director's devotion to easy sentimentality coincided, oddly
enough, with his holy war on behalf of cinematic truth. Among other
things, signatories to the highly publicized Dogma 95 ``Vow of
Chastity,'' which Von Trier composed with his friend Thomas
Vinterberg, agree to work on location with hand-held cameras and to
shun special lighting and effects.
 &HT;    While ``Dancer'' is not officially a Dogma film, it aims for
that same honesty. The film was shot mostly on hand-held video, and
the musical sequences were performed in full takes, captured by 100
stationary cameras.
 &HT;    While many observers viewed the Dogma manifesto as an
attention-getting prank _ particularly its repudiation of the
auteur theory as ``bourgeois romanticism from the very start and
thereby ... false!'' _ the fact is that Von Trier, a child of
permissive hippie-intellectual parents _ simply wanted a few rules.
Dogma may have 10 points, but for him, it's a 12-step program.
 &HT;    It seems to be working, too. His later work seems almost to have
been made by a different person than the tormented genius behind
the meticulously controlled ``Element of Crime,'' ``Epidemic'' and
``Zentropa.''
 &HT;    ``They were technically brilliant, but there was a coldness,''
says Stellan Skaarsgard, who appeared in ``Breaking the Waves'' and
``The Kingdom II'' as well as ``Dancer.'' ``There was no real life
in them. But then he totally changed his way of working. He's a
control freak, like all directors, but now he knows he can control
even chaos.''
 &HT;    Von Trier says he hasn't seen his early films in years. ``I'm
embarrassed about them, really embarrassed,'' he offers. ``The guy
who made them was just so young, so irritating. Now I feel more
mature.''
 &HT;    ``You know,'' he adds, ``even now when I see drawings I did when
I was 3 or 4, I think, `Oh, I should never have given that to my
mother, because this little flower down here is completely wrong
...''
 &HT;    The need for control has been a constant motif in his life _
``that ghost again,'' he calls it _ and it is at the root of the
director's psychological ailments: compulsive perfectionism, bouts
of agoraphobia and hypochondria and a terror of hospitals and
airplanes. (As a result of the latter, he'll be a no-show at the
New York Film Festival in September, although ``Dancer'' is being
honored with the opening-night slot.)
 &HT;    It is perhaps in light of these disorders that ``The Idiots,''
his controversial and critically misunderstood 1998 film about a
cultlike group of young Danes who pretend to be retarded, is best
viewed.
 &HT;    For Von Trier, mimicking the mentally handicapped is not about
ridicule but envy; it's a fantasy of liberation from his own
tyrannical superego.
 &HT;    ``I've been a nervous wreck all my life,'' he acknowledges. ``At
a certain point, I couldn't even leave my room.''
 &HT;    He had years of therapy, but he credits Prozac with taking the
edge off his neuroses. He also practices a form of meditation,
leading himself on what he calls ``shamanic journeys'' into a sort
of Jungian spirit world.
 &HT;    ``It's really fantastic,'' he says. ``You have this drum sound
on the stereo, and you imagine that you go into this animal world.
You discover a lot.''
 &HT;    On these travels, he takes on the guise of an animal. ``I'm an
otter,'' he says.
 &HT;    Sort of like an auteur?
 &HT;    ``Oh!'' he punches the steering wheel. ``An auteur otter! Great.
Thank you. I never thought of that, but now I can never face my
otter again.''
 &HT;    Thank goodness for Bjork's rat.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
