<HEADLINE>
EYE SCOOPS! 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 Compiled by the editors of WWD, DNR and W magazine 
 (Color art is available.) 
 From WWD, DNR and W magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    HARD CELL
 &HT;    
 &HT;    LOS ANGELES _ When the fantasy thriller ``The Cell'' opened in
theaters recently, audiences will got another fashion statement out
of Jennifer Lopez.
 &HT;    This time, though, the actress traded in her Versaces for a
touch of ``Mad Max'' _ with the help of costume designer Eiko
Ishioka. Combining the outrageousness of the Paris couture with a
bit of quirky sci-fi futurism, Ishioka has turned ``The Cell'' into
a visual feast, with Lopez the inevitable muse.
 &HT;    ``I want to challenge the design vocabulary and weave it into
other aspects of film _ acting, lighting and directing,'' the
Japanese-born Ishioka says. ``Ninety percent of movie costumes are
based on reality or history. These were based on my imagination.''
 &HT;    On top of ``The Cell,'' Ishioka, who won an Oscar for her work
on ``Bram Stoker's Dracula,'' is coming out with a new book in
October. ``Eiko on Stage'' contains sketches and photographs of her
work for film, opera and the theater over the last 15 years.
Francis Ford Coppola, one of many admirers in Hollywood, wrote the
introduction.
 &HT;    ``I've been lucky to work with people who gave me creative
freedom,'' she says. ``Coppola is one of the few directors who
really adores design and its power. He is an ideal director for a
designer.''
 &HT;    Ishioka has equal praise for Tarsem Singh, who directed ``The
Cell,'' and the feeling is clearly mutual.
 &HT;    Upon meeting Ishioka for the first time, Singh, who had read her
first book, ``Eiko by Eiko,'' when he was still in art school, told
her, ``That was our bible and you were our goddess.'' So when ``The
Cell'' came around, he was prepared to give Ishioka complete
freedom to create a group of outlandish costumes for the film's
dream sequences.
 &HT;    ``In the movie's opening scene, I thought Jennifer should look
like a fairy tale,'' says Ishioka, who draped the star in a white
feather-trimmed gown. ``I liked the image of a bird in the middle
of a dry, golden desert. For her cape, I asked the research team
for feathers from all the white birds there were.''
 &HT;    ``Jennifer was very involved with her image in the film,''
Ishioka adds. In one scene, Lopez insisted that a Grecian peplum
dress be made with an open front. But occasionally the actress had
to sacrifice the comfort of standard-issue sex appeal.
 &HT;    ``When she becomes trapped by a serial killer,'' Ishioka
explains, ``she enters a world of torture and abuse _ she
essentially becomes a sex toy, so she had to look erotic and
uncomfortable at the same time. I gave her a sheer dress and a big
black-and-red wig and a bizarre hard collar made of plastic.
Jennifer asked me if I could make it more comfortable, but I said
`No, you're supposed to be tortured.'''
 &HT;    In another pivotal scene, Lopez wears a suit of molded leather
armor that Ishioka first sculpted in clay, then cast. ``Tarsem
didn't want to use typical metal. He wanted me to design something
erotic and special.''
 &HT;    Before working on ``The Cell,'' Ishioka, who moved to New York
in the mid-'80s, spent two years in Amsterdam designing costumes
for Wagner's Ring Cycle for the National Opera.
 &HT;    ``When Tarsem called me in Amsterdam, he said `The Cell'
costumes should be very operatic. I sent him a 60-page fax of
initial sketches.
 &HT;    ``Film costumes should be perfect from every angle,'' Ishioka
continues, ``because the camera shoots 360 degrees. In opera, the
audience watches from a distance so there doesn't need to be as
much detail _ but my Japanese heritage forces me to do it. If a
singer or actor is wearing a perfect costume, her spirit is rich
and beautiful. If not, she has no confidence.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SUITE DREAMS
 &HT;    
 &HT;    If you book yourself into Paris' latest hot hotel _ the newly
restored Meurice _ remember two secret numbers: 524 and 528. These
junior suites, nestled under the hotel's mansard roof, feature
dizzying views of Place Vendome and Montmartre and great bathrooms
with original stained-glass windows.
 &HT;    The oak-paneled dressing rooms are gigantic (there's space for
plenty of Vuitton trunks and Colette shopping bags) and feature
flattering golden lighting.
 &HT;    But if you're feeling as flush as the hotel's owner, the Sultan
of Brunei, reserve La Belle Etoile, the most expensive hotel suite
in all of Paris. The 3,000-square-foot complex includes a Belle
Epoque rooftop pavilion with a huge wraparound terrace. The views
alone may be worth the price of admission _ $8,400 a night.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MONUMENTAL HEADACHE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Giorgio Armani can't stand clutter _ whether it's on the runway
or in the piazza. The designer is lobbying to have a monument to
former Italian president and prime minister Sandro Pertini removed
from its home in the piazza next door to Milan's Grand Hotel,
because he thinks it's an eyesore.
 &HT;    Armani, who happens to be opening his Emporio Armani mega-store
in that same piazza in October, even has offered to foot the bill
for the transfer.
 &HT;    City officials are divided as to what to do; designer Gianfranco
Ferre is furious: ``Whether Giorgio likes it or not, that monument
is part of the city's cultural face,'' Ferre says. ``He only
noticed it now, because of the opening of the store.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    BABY TALK
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Supermodel Stella Tennant has been in the family way _ in more
ways than one. The supermodel, who just gave birth to a daughter,
is designing a baby line for Burberry called Tennant &AMP; Son,
handmade in her Scottish hometown by her own friends.
 &HT;    The collection will hit Burberry's 57th Street store in New York
in September.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    BATTLE ROYAL
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In the old days, British monarchs used to behead errant nobles;
today, Queen Elizabeth just sues them.
 &HT;    The queen has filed suit against the Duke of Westminster,
Britain's wealthiest man, over a mineral-rich quarry in Wales.
 &HT;    The duke is keen to mine the quarry, but the Crown Estate
Commission is seeking a court writ to keep his minions from
trespassing on the land, which it contends belongs to the queen.
 &HT;    Let's hope the spat doesn't upset the delicate balance of royal
social life _ in the past, the duke has been a regular dinner guest
at Buckingham Palace.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
