<SLUG> BC-MILLIONAIRE-SHOPPING-HABITS-ONLINE-FAIRCHILD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WANTS TO FIND A MILLIONAIRE? 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By IRA P. SCHNEIDERMAN 
 From WWD 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Internet may be a great equalizer, but new research shows
that the rich are different from you and me when it comes to the
online world.
 &HT;    A new study by Forrester Research Inc. indicates millionaires
research and buy everything from clothing and jewelry to airline
tickets and groceries online.
 &HT;    For the report, ``The Millionaire Online,'' Forrester surveyed
more than 2,000 affluent households (those with investable assets
of $1 million or more, not including the value of their primary
home).
 &HT;    ``Retailers and manufacturers that target the affluent often
adopt a defensive tone about the Internet,'' said Ekaterina O.
Walsh, an analyst at Forrester. ``But our research uncovered four
oft-cited misconceptions about affluent consumers: That they don't
like technology, don't go online, don't shop online and don't use
the Internet to manage their finances.''
 &HT;    To begin, Walsh reports 56 percent of affluent households are
online vs. 43 percent of the general population.
 &HT;    The report states the affluent actually like technology more
than other consumers. Almost two-thirds of the affluent score as
optimists, according to a technology-optimism scale, vs. slightly
more than half of the non-affluent.
 &HT;    From fax machines to writable CD drives, the affluent own more
technology products than other consumers. Not only do two-thirds of
the affluent have a home PC, but the average affluent household
owns two.
 &HT;    Moreover, the survey also found that the millionaires' primary
reason for using a PC is to go online. Half of them have been going
online for at least three years, while only one-third of
non-affluent wired consumers have that much experience.
 &HT;    The study refutes the idea that millionaires don't shop online.
Millionaires are 16 percent more likely than other Internet users
to regularly research products online.
 &HT;    They are also more likely to follow through on their search.
Across a wide range of categories, the affluent score high on a
``buy to look'' ratio that measures research to purchase
follow-through. Overall, the affluent buy-to-look ratio is 21
percent higher than other Internet users, Walsh noted.
 &HT;    The study found 21 percent of affluent respondents purchased
clothing, compared with 15 percent of non-affluent buyers.
 &HT;    Millionaires are also more likely to buy in every product
category online, except for entertainment items such as music,
videos and games. They also power through the online
retail-adoption cycle faster, graduating from buying convenience
goods to research items and replenishment products earlier than
other consumers.
 &HT;    The report declares: ``Armed with deeper pockets and an affinity
for e-commerce, millionaires spend more on almost every type of
product online. They spent almost $150 more online during the 1999
winter holiday season than other buyers. This year, affluent
Internet buyers expect to spend $100 per month online, which is
double the spending planned by other Internet buyers.''
 &HT;    The affluent may spend more, but they don't overlook value. Like
other consumers, most affluent online shoppers (58 percent) are
value-focused buyers who seek good prices without sacrificing
quality.
 &HT;    The remaining 42 percent are convenience-focused buyers who
would pay extra to get their shopping done quickly and have it be
hassle-free. But even these convenience-focused buyers don't ignore
value.
 &HT;    Nine out of 10 respondents pay attention to shipping fees, and
43 percent are likely to visit price comparison sites such as
MySimon or CompareNet.
 &HT;    Compared with the non-affluent, millionaires are more
brand-conscious, states the report.
 &HT;    ``The wired affluent would prefer to buy a Baume &AMP; Mercier watch
if they could find it online,'' Walsh observes.
 &HT;    She notes that almost half say they seek specific brand names
for everything they buy versus less than a third of the
non-affluent.
 &HT;    Millionaires are a much sought-after market for a whole host of
companies, from luxury retailers and private banks to charities. To
effectively target them, the study says marketers must: &HT;    Master the online channel. Almost 60 percent of young consumers
are online, so the Internet must be at the core of any strategy to
target them. With Internet penetration among the affluent almost as
high, winning their allegiance requires synchronized offline and
online channels.
 &HT;    Avoid ``affluent portals.'' Although many will try, portals
aimed at millionaires will fail. Having investable assets beyond
seven figures is not enough of a common bond to drive site traffic.
Instead, seek the affluent at the myriad sites where they'll go in
pursuit for their other interests.
 &HT;    Use the affluent to test and launch new products. An affinity
for novelty, opinion leadership, brand-consciousness, and
value-focus make the affluent ideal candidates for examining and
fueling market trends.
 &HT;    Target emerging affluent consumers. These younger, high-income
non-affluent consumers share many key characteristics with the
affluent: a dominant career motivation, a passion for technology
and a high tolerance for investment risk. c.2000 Fairchild
<TEXT>
Publications &QL;
<P>
