<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GETS-DEFENSIVE-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIDE TURNS FOR GORE AS GAFFE-PRONE BUSH FLOUNDERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...RESENDING from Aug. 23)   (This 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
domestic/general news, ``p'' political news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chasing each other across the key electoral states
of the Midwest, the two U.S. presidential contenders were Tuesday
forced for the first time to engage each other directly in a
pre-Labor Day foretaste of the autumn campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With no fewer than six opinion polls now registering the
Democratic National Convention as a resounding success for Vice
President Al Gore, the campaign of George W. Bush slipped into
defensive mode, pounding away at the safe issues _ for Republicans
_ of education and military spending.
</P>
<P>
   There was abundant evidence, however, of a new renewed vigor in
the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In Milwaukee Tuesday, Gore countered head-on Republican
accusations that the country's defenses had been neglected during
the past eight years, insisting that the U.S. armed forces were
``the best prepared, the most powerful, most modern military in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   He also cited his experience of war in Vietnam (albeit as an
army reporter) as proof of his superior qualification to be
Commander-in-Chief.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bush, nor his running mate, Richard Cheney, went to
Vietnam: Bush served in the Air National Guard in his home state of
Texas, while Cheney stayed in higher education and benefited from
perpetual deferments.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was addressing the annual convention of Veterans of Foreign
Wars, the main U.S. veterans association, just 24 hours after Bush
had used his address before the same audience to lament the
country's state of military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   The next president, Bush had said, ``will inherit a military in
decline,'' and he received a standing ovation for his pledge: ``I
will rebuild the military power of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting back Tuesday, Gore argued that the cuts in the defense
budget quoted by Bush dated not to the Clinton years, but to the
tenure of his father, George Bush senior, at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Only last year, Gore said, the administration signed into effect
a 4.8 percent military pay increase, the largest in a generation,
with another 3.7 percent to come this month.
</P>
<P>
   In a succession of post-convention interviews _ his first
unscripted encounters with reporters for weeks _ Gore appeared
buoyed by the poll verdicts on his convention speech, which were
unanimously positive.
</P>
<P>
   The last two post-convention polls _ the Washington Post-ABC
television out Tuesday and the Reuters-Zogby poll out on Monday _
both put Gore in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Although the leads of 2 and 3 points respectively (in
projections including the Reform and the Green parties) were within
the margin of error, this was the first time either poll had showed
Gore ahead since the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bush insisted that the tightening of the race was what
they had forecast all along, and observers noted that a realistic
indication of the state of play would emerge only around Labor Day
(Sept. 4), when the Democratic Convention was as far in the past as
the Republican Convention is now.
</P>
<P>
   They noted also that Bush had raised seven times as much money
in July as Gore, although more frugal spending has left Gore with
more in his war chest (an estimated 6.4 million dollars) than Bush
(4 million).
</P>
<P>
   A new hint of defensiveness could be detected in the Bush
campaign, however, as the two candidates approach their next big
test: the televised debates.
</P>
<P>
   The commission that organizes and sets the rules for the debates
made its proposals more than a month ago; but as Ari Fleisher,
Bush's senior adviser made clear this week, the Bush camp has still
not agreed either the number of the debates or their venue.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has proposed three presidential debates _ in
Boston, Raleigh and St. Louis _ and one vice-presidential debate,
in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   At least in public, the line of the Gore camp _ which regards
debating as one of their candidate's strengths _ is the more
debates the better.
</P>
<P>
   The post-convention polls have also brought a perceptible shift
in the approach of the U.S. media. After months of treating Vice
President Al Gore as the underdog, they are now looking at the two
campaigns through a different prism.
</P>
<P>
   It is Gore, with his Jewish running mate and passionate
wife-kissing, who has tweaked the imagination, while Bush faces new
questions of style _ about his mangled English _ and substance: the
generous retirement package awarded to his running mate, Cheney,
and his reluctance to cash in his company shares. &QL; 
