<P>
   HURRICANE-DEBBY _ Hurricane Debby fell apart over Hispaniola,
it's barely a tropical wave. As it moves west, it could
re-intensify. (O'Meilia, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   GORE-THEME _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore began sounding
a subtle new theme on the stump this week, aimed at countering the
political estrangement among young and middle-aged voters alike.
Campaigning in the Midwest, Gore asked voters to ``open your
hearts'' and ``allow yourself to believe'' and to ``break through
your disillusionment.'' In an interview, Gore said these were not
references only to the reaction against President Clinton's
behavior, but also to the disenchantment with politics in general.
(Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washngton and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory Politics.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-TRENDS _ WASHINGTON _ Today's average kids score
significantly better in math and a little better in reading when
they take the same tests that baby boomers did when they were kids.
The results in science are mixed: 9-year-olds do worse,
13-year-olds the same and 17-year-olds better than the baby boomers
did when they were that young. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH _ TEST-TRENDS-DATA for textbox or graphic
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory Education
</P>
<P>
   MONITOR _ ATLANTA _ Off the coast of Cape Hatteras, in the
graveyard of the Atlantic, time and tide are erasing the remains of
a naval legend. The USS Monitor, the icon of Civil War ironclads,
is surrendering to the natural forces and maritime mishaps that
have dogged it since it sank in a storm on New Year's Eve, 1862.
Like the H.L. Hunley, the Confederate submarine raised from
Charleston Harbor this month, the Monitor _ the first ship built
entirely of iron _changed the face of naval warfare and sounded the
death knell for wooden warships. Like the Hunley, the Monitor was
lost at sea for more than a century. And like the Hunley, it is the
object of a multi-million dollar effort to save as much of it as
possible for posterity. (Toner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   COX EDS: Story can be found on the Budget Tool with a rundate of
August 20.
</P>
<P>
   COTTON-PICKING-FRAUD _ The Georgia Bureau of Investigation plans
to arrest a Rochelle farmer today and charge him with burying his
cotton-picker, a 6-ton, 15-foot high piece of equipment, and then
reporting it stolen to collect insurance on it. Hope to be able to
develop info that the guy was desperately trying to save his farm.
GBI will provide art of digging up the machine. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
