<HEADLINE>
$ADV02
</HEADLINE>
  FOR RELEASE Saturday, Sept. 2, 2000 
 RIDIN' IN STYLE: PONTIAC AZTEK GT _ ODD STYLING, INTERESTING
EXECUTION 
 (World rights.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's RIDIN' IN STYLE feature. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of RIDIN' IN STYLE _ contact one of the New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 ART NOTE: Includes B&AMP;W photo and color slide of the Pontiac Aztek
GT. 
 By STEVE SMITH 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Hands down the most confounding vehicle of the new model year,
the Pontiac Aztek clearly hopes to serve multiple masters. Its
looks are undeniably distinctive _ somewhere between ``hideous''
and ``purposeful,'' depending on whom you ask. It resembles the box
a smaller sports utility vehicle came in.
 &HT;    Though it shares a platform with the mainstream Pontiac Montana
minivan, the designers of the Aztek have taken a radically
different route to achieve their objective, which ostensibly is to
combine the usefulness and comfort of a minivan, with the rugged
capability of an SUV.
 &HT;    As it is presently available, the Aztek is front-wheel-drive
only, though an all-wheel-drive system will be available late this
year. But even with all-wheel-drive, it won't be prepared to do any
serious off-roading. That system is comparatively light-duty,
designed to handle slippery pavement more than rocky, rutted mud
roads.
 &HT;    So what is the Aztek? Rather than an SUV, Pontiac is calling the
Aztek an SRV, for Sports Recreation Vehicle, coining yet another
variation on the sport-ute theme. In this case, it may be
appropriate, as Pontiac is targeting younger people with active
lifestyles.
 &HT;    The Aztek is designed to carry five people and a lot of toys to
the beach, on camping trips, spring break or to the Gulf Coast! Of
course, a relatively minute percentage of anyone's total driving
time is spent doing things like that, but Pontiac hopes the Aztek
makes owners think of its extracurricular capabilities.
 &HT;    Outside, the Aztek's angularity is startling, with multiple
sharp edges, even in the rear hatch, which uses two pieces of
glass, butted together at an angle. There is copious dark gray
plastic cladding the bottom of the body. The gas cap is exposed.
It's all sort of military.
 &HT;    Though the exterior of the Aztek is rightfully ripe for
criticism, some genuine out-of-the-box thinking went on during the
interior design. Buttons and switches are large and rugged-looking.
There are really big grab handles to help you get in and out.
 &HT;    Mechanically, the Aztek has the same 3.4-liter V-6 engine as the
Montana minivan; at 185 horsepower, it does a more than adequate
job of moving around the Aztek's weight _ more than two tons on the
all-wheel-drive version, but 200 pounds less than that for the
front-wheel-drive. The only available transmission is a four-speed
automatic, and it's nicely matched to the engine.
 &HT;    Though the Aztek rides on the same 108.3-inch wheelbase as the
Montana, the abrupt rear styling does not leave room for three rows
of seats. The Aztek accommodates two up front in bucket seats,
three in the rear on a bench-style seat. Though roomy, rear-seat
passengers sit quite low, with not much forward visibility over the
front seats.
 &HT;    From the driver's seat, the Aztek is not as peculiar looking as
it is from the outside, though the large dashboard and slanted hood
make it a bit difficult to perceive exactly where the front bumper
begins. With all the glass surrounding the cockpit, outward
visibility is excellent.
 &HT;    The test vehicle was a top-of-the-line Aztek GT, which came with
16-inch tires, better suited to this tall, fairly heavy vehicle
than the 15-inchers on the base Aztek.
 &HT;    Though the GT adds quite a bit of equipment as standard _
ranging from a trip computer to a standard traction-control system
_ it also adds to the price.
 &HT;    The GT starts at $24,445, and the test vehicle had a $2,415
option package that included an upgraded sound system, a power
driver's seat, a security alarm, leather interior trim and
puncture-sealing tires. It also included a ``head's up'' display,
which projects information such as the vehicle speed onto the
windshield in the driver's line of sight. Other options, including
a $365 trailer towing package that increases towing capability to
3,500 pounds, cranked up the price to $27,875.
 &HT;    I also drove a base-model Aztek and, though it lacked leather
and some of the other niceties, it listed at a total price of
$24,025. But it was still a very well-equipped vehicle, with
options that included a glass sunroof and a premium stereo.
 &HT;    Opt for the GT, though, and you can add some pretty interesting
equipment, as well as some trademark standard features. There's a
portable cooler that latches onto the console and can hold a dozen
12-ounce cans. The GT also has ``removable utility packs'' in its
front door trim for storage of items such as sunglasses and
cellular phones.
 &HT;    There's an optional pullout rear cargo tray that holds 400
pounds and makes loading sports equipment or home improvement
products easy. Indeed, practically everything behind the front
seats can be removed, folded or reconfigured _ quite ingenious.
 &HT;    And if you're a genuine outdoor type, there's a camping package
with a custom tent that fits over the open rear of the Aztek, and
an air mattress that can be inflated with an on-board compressor.
 &HT;    If all this interests you, and you can get past the exterior
design, the Aztek is a rolling platform of innovative concepts. But
if you can't, wait a year for the Buick Rendezvous, a more
civilized version of the Aztek that has a third row of seats, but
fewer of the young-lifestyle attributes.
 &HT;    Then, of course, there's the Montana minivan, which the Aztek is
at heart. Give Pontiac credit for trying something new, though _
odd as it is.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SPECIFICATIONS:
 &HT;    Name: 2001 Pontiac Aztek GT.
 &HT;    Base sticker price: $24,495.
 &HT;    Price of test vehicle: $27,835.
 &HT;    Powertrain: Front-engine, front-wheel-drive with 3.4-liter,
overhead valve V-6 with iron block and aluminum cylinder heads,
with a four-speed automatic transmission. 185 hp at 5,200 rpm.
Torque   210 lbs.-ft. at 4,000 rpm.
 &HT;    EPA-estimated mileage, city/highway: 19/26 mpg.
 &HT;    Fuel system: Electronically controlled multiport fuel injection.
 &HT;    Steering: Power assisted rack and pinion.
 &HT;    Brakes: Front disc, rear drum.
 &HT;    Curb weight: 3,780 lbs.
 &HT;    Length/wheelbase: 182.1 inches/108.3 inches.
 &HT;    Suspension, front: Independent with struts, coil springs and
stabilizer bar.
 &HT;    Suspension, rear: Trailing twist beam axle with coil springs and
stabilizer bar.
 &HT;    Cargo capacity: 45.4 cubic feet.
 &HT;    Tires: P215/70SR-16 radials on cast aluminum wheels.
 &HT;    Safety features: Front and side air bags, traction control,
remote locking, security system, antilock brakes, puncture-sealing
tires.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     NEXT WEEK: The Chevrolet Corvette Z06 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Steve Smith is the executive editor of Car and Driver
magazine.) 
 &HT;    
