<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MISS-SAIGON-ERA (New York) _ The musical ``Miss Saigon'' has
taken in more than $1.3 billion internationally at the box office
since its world premiere in London in September 1989. ``Saigon''
has been performed in the United States and six other countries,
and a new production will open in the Philippines next month. The
show's imminent departure from New York is significant because its
departure leaves just two in a crop of mega-musicals still running
on Broadway _ ``Les Miserables'' and ``The Phantom of the Opera'' _
suggesting that an era of theatrical spectacle may be at an end. By
Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2,3,4,5.
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-MUSEUMS (Washington) _ At the moment, the big museums
here aren't necessarily the main attractions. After you have seen
the smart, laconic Ed Ruscha retrospective at the Hirshhorn, you
may want to check out a few local art paths less traveled. By
Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PHOTOGRAPHY (New York) _ If you want to know how far afield a
serious photographer will go in this city, you can get some idea at
the Museum of the City of New York, where ``New York Now 2000:
Contemporary Work in Photography'' offers 130 photographs of New
York City and New Yorkers. By Vicki Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   AUSCHWITZ-ARTIST (Boston) _ When Charlotte Salomon and her
unborn child died at Auschwitz, Solomon left behind an astonishing
work of art that transformed her life into a poignant opera of
paintings, words and music. Owned by the Jewish Historical Museum
in Amsterdam, her work has since been shown in Germany, the
Netherlands, France, the United States, Israel and Japan. By Grace
Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WAR-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Art of War'': Christian Duguay,
director; with Wesley Snipes, Ann Archer, Donald Sutherland.
Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   BRING-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Bring it On'': Peyton Reed,
director; with with Kristen Dunst, Jesse Bradford, Eliza Dushku.
Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   MOTEL-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Bittersweet Motel'': Todd
Phillips, director; a documentary about the musical phenom Phish.
Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   CATFISH-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Catfish in Black Bean Sauce''
deals with adopted children being raised by parents of a different
race, but Chi Muoi Lo, the writer and director, plays around with
the idea in an unexpected way. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CHALK-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Chalk'': Rob Nilsson, director.
Reviewed by Dave Kehr.
</P>
<P>
   CREW-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Crew'': Michael Dinner,
director; with Burt Reynolds, Richard Dreyfuss, Dan Hedaya, Seymour
Cassel, Carrie-Ann Moss, Jennifer Tilly, Lainie Kazan, Jeremy
Piven. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTBALL-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Fast Pitch'': Jeremy Spear,
director; a softball documentary. Reviewed by Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``God's Army'': Richard Dutcher's
film about young, high-spirited Mormon missionaries. Reviewed by
Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Love and Sex'': Valerie Breiman,
director; with Framke Janssen and Jon Favreau. Reviewed by Lawrence
Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   MOST-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Most Terrible Time in My
Life, '' directed by Kaizo Hayashi, is a mildly amusing Japanese
appropriation of 1950s U.S. detective movies. Reviewed by Dave
Kehr.
</P>
<P>
   ORFEU-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Carlos Diegues' ``Orfeu'' is based
on the play by the Brazilian writer Vicinius de Moraes that also
inspired Marcel Camus' 1959 film ``Black Orpheus.'' With Toni
Garrido, Patricia Franca, Murilo Benicio, Zeze Motta. Reviewed by
A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   SMILING-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Smiling Fish and Goat on
Fire'': Kevin Jordan, director; with Derek and Steve Martini.
Reviewed by Dave Kehr.
</P>
<P>
   SOLOMON-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ The moment the star-crossed
title characters in Paul Morrison's somber love story ``Solomon and
Gaenor'' set eyes on each other, your heart sinks. It is
immediately obvious there is nowhere for these young lovers to
travel but down an awfully familiar path that could take any of
three twists. With Ioan Gruffudd, Nia Roberts. Reviewed by Stephen
Holden.
</P>
<P>
   SPENT-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Spent'': Gil Cates, Jr.,
director; with Jason London, Charlie Spradling, Richmond Arquette,
Barbara Barrie and Rain Phoenix. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS4KIDS (Undated) _ Assessing the current cinema for children
of different ages.
</P>
<P>
   AT-THE-MOVIES (Hollywood) _ News of the silver screen. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-IN-BRIEF (Undated) _ Capsule reviews by New York Times
critics.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEVIDEO (Undated) _ Short items on what's news in home video
and short reviews of what's new in home video. By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EYEWITNESS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In his new book on
presidential leadership, the veteran White House adviser David
Gergen laments the current state of politics, the ascendance of
spin and media manipulation and the tendency of politicians like
Bill Clinton to mistake campaigning for governance. Reviewed by
Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEEKEND (Undated) _ Ron Wertheimer spotlights the weekend
television fare: On HBO, a TV film, ``The Last of the Blonde
Bombshells.''
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-COLUMN (New York) _ The Antiques Column. By Wendy
Moonan.
</P>
<P>
   ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK (Undated) _ Spotlighting a new album.
</P>
