<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-REDISCOVERING-RVS-ART     08-24 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDISCOVERING-RVS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and l coding)  
 THE RIDE IS GETTING SUITE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ATTLEBOROUGH, Mass. _ On the right, we have Arthur Longa's
two-floor, colonial-style house. On the left, we have his Allegro
Bus diesel motor home.
</P>
<P>
   Quick quiz: Which one _ the house on the right or the RV on the
left _ has all-maple kitchen cabinets, leather couches, and tile
floors? Which one has two-zone heating and air conditioning?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: It's the recreational vehicle, worth $180,000 and 39
feet long. It also has a living room that expands 3 feet in width
at the push of a button, two televisions and a VCR, and a CD player
that holds eight discs. And on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Long considered the province of retirees, RVs are going upscale
and finding a younger, hipper following. Longa, a 40-year-old
father of two, is part of a groundswell of RV enthusiasm that is
putting a new face on a classic piece of Americana. In recent
years, 35- to 54-year-olds have for the first time surpassed the
over-55 crowd in ownership of RVs. And sales are at a 20-year high;
last year, manufacturers shipped $10.4 billion worth of RVs to
dealers, compared with just $1.2 billion in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   But the boom, enthusiasts say, is not just a product of the
high-flying economy. They see RV mania as a sign of a gathering
backlash against today's hyped-up, stressed-out lifestyle. An RV,
they say, represents a return to a slower, more relaxing mode of
travel, redolent of the byways and back roads of a gentler era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted my children to see more of America than a fly-in,
fly-out kind of a trip,'' said Longa, who rented RVs for several
years before purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Brunswick, Maine, is hosting the annual convention
of the Family Motor Coach Association, where manufacturers show off
the latest advances in mobile home technology and devotees swap
secrets of living the good life on the road. Organizers expected
6,000 RVs to make the pilgrimage. Consider it a show of force.
</P>
<P>
   It's an indication that, even in an age when air travel is
ubiquitous, when many families can afford expensive vacations,
Americans still find liberation behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only time in my life that I really feel free,'' said
Janet Smith, an RV devotee who rents and sells the vehicles at Trip
Makers Inc. in Walpole. She believes that many families are turning
their backs on ``jet-setting'' vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Longa's is one of them. ``The RV is very exhilarating and
free,'' he said. ``I don't have to pull into the airport and wait
for someone else to get me there. I can get there myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, parents who have bought or rented RVs say they
finally found a way to get away from the constant din of soccer and
piano lessons, bills, and leaky faucets. In an RV, they say, they
have managed to achieve family bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is very, very busy. This was a way to put a pause in the
sentence,'' said Joan Wallace-Benjamin, president of the Urban
League of Eastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace-Benjamin rented an RV a few years ago for a
cross-country trip with her two sons and husband, Milton Benjamin,
president of the Massachusetts Community Development Finance
Corporation. On long stretches of road, the family passed the time
with books-on-tape and conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good way for us to bond and get to know one
another,'' said Wallace-Benjamin, who added that her family would
love to go again next summer. ``In the process, we decided we
really do like our kids. We don't just love them; they're
interesting people.''
</P>
<P>
   And the children, separated from their friends and forced to
talk to their parents for days on end, apparently enjoy the time as
much as the adults. One mother, Karen Boynton of Plymouth, reported
that her 16-year-old son offered to pay for a weekend at a
campground out of his allowance.
</P>
<P>
   With the popularity of MTV's ``Road Rules,'' a long-running
reality show that features a Winnebago, RVs are gaining a certain
measure of cachet with youth. Mini Cost Auto Rental, a Newton
agency, rented 25 RVs to fans of the band Phish for a New Year's
Eve concert in Florida that generated a two-day traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   Younger renters and buyers are exactly what RV manufacturers
want. In the past three years, the Recreational Vehicle Industry
Association has spent $20 million in print and television ads
promoting their products, with much of the campaign aimed at baby
boomers and families with young children. The association has been
so successful that it is planning to double its spending for
another three-year campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The association says one of the best lures is gadgetry, which
can push the cost of an RV to the million-dollar mark. Of the motor
homes shipped in 1999 (separate from travel trailers and other
smaller RVs), 77 percent had at least one ``slide-out,'' a
mechanism that expands floor space at the push of a button. Other
options include satellite television, Internet access, and washers
and dryers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amenities are very important,'' said Jeffrey Gladstone,
37, a Boston investment analyst who lives in Franklin. ``I see
people miserably crawling out of their tents, and they look over at
me, drinking a cup of coffee and looking for the remote control.
That says it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladstone recently purchased a 27-foot travel trailer that
attaches to his pickup truck. He's planning to upgrade next year to
a full motor home, and perhaps drive cross-country.
</P>
<P>
   Gladstone, his wife, his 7-year-old son, and 10-year-old
daughter have gone away every weekend since they bought the RV in
April, including trips to Maine, Connecticut, and Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Unwinding at home is not good enough, Gladstone said. ``You have
to get away. If you sit on your lawn, you look down and you see
weeds, and then you get stressed out.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger, and often more affluent, market for RVs is also
influencing the camping options available across the country. Bay
View Campgrounds in Bourne, for example, has three swimming pools,
a video game parlor, and courts for tennis, basketball, and
volleyball, along with daily activities for children.
</P>
<P>
   These campgrounds make it appealing for families like
Gladstone's to take short weekend trips. And they sometimes serve
as surrogate neighborhoods. Ron Norfolk of Freetown, for example,
doesn't feel safe letting his children ride bicycles on the busy
street at home. But at Pinewood Lodge Campground in Plymouth, where
he spent last week, they can.
</P>
<P>
   Even high gasoline prices seem to have done little to dampen RV
enthusiasm. Shipments of the biggest vehicles _ Class A motor homes
_ are down 5 percent since last year, but are otherwise higher than
any time in the last two decades. Overall, RV sales are soaring to
record highs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch it suck up gas,'' Gladstone said, ``but I weigh the
enjoyment, and it's not really an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe correspondent Meadow Rue Merrill contributed to this report
from Brunswick, Maine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
