<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      08-24 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEARNING FOR THE MOVIE CAR _ UNTIL ANOTHER COMES ALONG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems so long ago, yet only two months have passed since I
fell in love with Eleanor in Los Angeles. I confess, there have
been others since.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor was the 1967 Shelby Mustang GT 500 KR that Nicholas Cage
drove in the movie ``Gone in 60 Seconds.'' She's history.
</P>
<P>
   First came the new 911 Turbo Porsche I drove in the Black Rock
Desert in Nevada. Fast and dangerous and edgy as you wanna be.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just this month, there was a brief fling with a 1962
Mercedes 300 SL roadster. This 3-liter straight-6 is the descendant
of the famous Gull Wings, which began as race cars in 1952 and went
street legal in 1954. It cranked out 215 horsepower, had a top
speed of 159 miles per hour, and, at $10,000 in 1962, was not a
cheap date.
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you this because, after Eleanor appeared in a column
about famous cars from movies and television, you readers swamped
me with mail. The cars I missed. The cars you've loved.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so much that you argued with my choices, among them
Steve McQueen's 1968 Mustang GT 390 from ``Bullitt,'' the 1974
Dodge Monaco 440 cop car that Aykroyd and Belushi drove in ``The
Blues Brothers,'' Paul Le Matt's 1932 Ford five-window coupe from
``American Graffiti,'' or Kowalski's 1970 Challenger R/T Hemi from
``Vanishing Point.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just that you had loves of your own; love built of
adolescent fantasy or adult yearning for that certain car.
</P>
<P>
   Your list seemed weighted toward the '70s era, one reader wrote,
but I give you bonus points for the Pacer from ``Wayne's World.''
(And to you, dear reader, a rousing chorus of ``Bohemian
Rhapsody.'') So you and your roommates improved on my list, adding
the A-Team's van, the T-Bird of ``Thelma and Louise,'' but warned
me, ``don't even get me started on James Bond.'' (Hey, I prefer
cars that start when it's wet.)
</P>
<P>
   Corvette Enthusiast wrote to say he was disappointed that no
'Vettes made the list and asked, how about the Corvettes that
rotated each season during the run of ``Route 66''?
</P>
<P>
   Good point and it reminds me I should have included the
Harley-Davidson Sportster from ``Then Came Bronson.'' ``Route 66''
with a motorcycle and no designated road.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader wrote to say his wife missed Suzanne Somers's
white Thunderbird from ``American Graffiti.'' If ever a car (and
its occupant) symbolized longing _ though I'm not sure if the
longing was for the car or the blonde at the wheel _ that
Thunderbird, I must agree, heads the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirty Mary &AMP; Crazy Larry'' another reader wrote after I
praised that film's 1969 Charger R/T 440, I thought I was the only
one who remembered that gem. Others to put on the list, he
continued: the 1954 Sunbeam-Talbot Alpine Roadster, predecessor to
the 1959-67 Tiger. Grace Kelly drove it in ``It Takes a Thief.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on this man's list: The 1964 Aston Martin from
``Goldfinger'' (somebody got him going on James Bond), Columbo's
1960 Peugeot 403 Carbriolet, and the three Mini Cooper S's from
``The Italian Job.''
</P>
<P>
   I was faulted for missing the 440 Six-Pack Barracuda that Ken
Wall drove on the ``Wise Guy,'' and Christopher George's Shelby
Mustang from ``The Immortal.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the Sunbeam Alpine that Maxwell Smart drove on
``Get Smart,'' asked another. Now there's a guy way ahead of his
time. Top down in a roadster, distracted, talking on the
predecessor to the cell phone, Smart's famous shoe phone.
</P>
<P>
   And so we fall in love, or like, with the cars we see on screen.
Sometimes it is because we want to own the car. Sometimes it is
because the car represents something far larger: escape, freedom,
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   But love is often in the air. Thelma and Louise, fleeing bad
marriages, loved each other all the way to the edge of the Grand
Canyon. I don't know if Maxwell Smart loved Agent 99, but I do know
that Columbo loved Mrs. Columbo and Paul Le Matt loved his
five-window coupe.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite love story from a reader? Dan Levin tells this tale:
</P>
<P>
   My favorite movie car is the steel-blue Austin Healey roadster
that Ava Gardner drove at the end of ``On the Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Atomic war had all but destroyed life on earth. Gardner's
husband, Gergory Peck, a submarine captain, is heading north with
his crew on a mission that spells certain doom. Gardner snakes the
Healey along a winding coastal road, top down, desperate for one
last and longing glimpse of the sub before it disappears forever.
</P>
<P>
   Grabbed Levin right by the heart strings, it is easy to see.
Healys became to Levin, he admits, the world's most beautiful cars.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but love can be fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   That love lasted, he writes, ``until that day I saw a 1963,
British racing green Jaguar XKE headed up Mt. Vernon Street with
its top down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sic transit gloria mundi, Dan writes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm no scholar of Latin, but I assume that means: Love 'em
and leave 'em.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
