<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT`S THE HONDA S2000 LIKE? IT'S AS GOOD AS IT SOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, what's it like?
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere I parked the Honda S2000, the high-revving, hunched,
hot sports car of the moment, somebody asked that question.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I'd say, it's like driving a motorcycle _ without the bugs
in your teeth.
</P>
<P>
   This is a magical machine. Consider: When you want horsepower,
you feed those horses from two sources, RPMs and torque. Honda's
response: We don't need no stinkin' torque. Instead, they are
cranking a remarkable 240 horsepower (and even that is limited by
emissions regulations) out of only 2 liters of engine. Torque? A
paltry 153 lb.-ft.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a screaming machine that's all howling horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   So thank God for the rainbow tachometer that spreads its
crescent across the top of the gauges behind the steering wheel.
Watch it climb, lightning fast, past 5,000 RPMs to 6,000, where the
engine takes on a more powerful tone, past 7,000, where it gets
downright guttural, and up to near 9,000, where it's screaming
again.
</P>
<P>
   Want to pass on the highway? Drop from sixth to third gear and
stomp it. Whatever you may have been listening to on the radio will
be lost in the whine, but the act of passing will take but seconds.
You swear this car asks to be abused because to be driven, its
engine must be wound out.
</P>
<P>
   Starting from stop, you have to be careful to wind the engine to
a healthy scream or you run the risk of stalling. Once it gets
rolling, however, the responsiveness seems without limit.
</P>
<P>
   And all this is tucked into what I consider a classic throwback
to the earlier days of sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   The engine is up front. It's rear-wheel drive. The body is
stiff. The short rear deck covers a trunk that has barely enough
room for two small travel cases. The sloping nose looks almost '60s
English until you look at the S2000 from the front and its bulging
fenders, not apparent from the side view, give it away as a modern
muscle roadster.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the seats are firm and legroom is ample. There's even a
dead pedal for the driver's left foot, though this car is so much
fun to drive, you find yourself using that foot for shifting up and
down just because you can.
</P>
<P>
   I loved the red Start Engine button located on the dash to the
left of the wheel, but was confused by the audio control setup. It
seemed strange that, in addition to controls on the audio system
itself _ at center dash _ Honda chose to put another set on the
dash to the left of the wheel. Either way is a reach, so what is
gained? If you're going for redundant audio controls, put them on
the steering wheel where they are more convenient and a boost to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you won't want to be distracted searching for audio
buttons when you're driving the S2000. You are fully involved if
you're driving it the way it is meant to be driven.
</P>
<P>
   Its stiff body is controlled by front and rear suspensions that
both incorporate unequal length control arms, coil springs, and
anti-roll bars. Steering is electric power assist rack-and-pinion.
Brakes are vented 11-inch discs all around.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a car that displays virtually no lateral roll, is
stiff and steady on straightaways, and is knifelike in sharp
corners. In fact, it cuts so sharp there is some sense of
understeer, though not in a disconcerting way. And with all those
RPMs and rear-wheel drive, you can induce oversteer if you want it
to play with, and sometimes, using the rear wheels to help steer
can be fun.
</P>
<P>
   And the tight, clicking six-speed shifter in the S2000 makes it
virtually impossible to not have fun driving this car. It is as
fine a shifter as I've ever used.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, however, is in learning to drive by sound. That's not
an uncommon trick. What is uncommon, is doing it to sounds you
likely have never heard coming from an automobile before (except at
certain race tracks).
</P>
<P>
   That's because the engine puts forth a furious wail and you
swear you are about to blow it up _ until you look at the arcing
rainbow and see you are only at 5,000 RPMs. It is not until you hit
Six Grand that the VTEC two-stage valve-timing system, with two
sets of exhaust and intake cams, kicks in for maximum boost and
you've reached into the heart of this remarkable four-cylinder
engine. Screaming around for more than a week, it delivered about
24 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   It's very loud. It's very quick. It's very stiff. And it's a
whole lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The soft ledges built into the front doors for elbows. If the
car isn't going to roll in the corners, you are. They give great
support in turns.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --The tonneau cover for the convertible top. I never could get
the whole thing snapped down. It stayed in the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The numbers &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $30,000 &QL; 
Price as tested: $31,500 (est.) &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 240/153 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 94.5 inches/162.2 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 68.9 inches/50.6 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 2,780 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 2 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
