<SLUG> BC-R-CHINA-RELIGION-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE AMERICANS ARRESTED IN RAID ON CHURCH IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Resending to fix garble.) 
(EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ One-hundred and thirty evangelical Christians,
including three visiting Americans on a religious mission, were
arrested in central China on Wednesday as they attended a revival,
according to a human rights monitor and the Americans' pastor in
California.
</P>
<P>
   The raid was part of a continuing pattern of arrests, fines and
other harassment of so-called house churches, mainly evangelical
Protestant groups that have quietly spread their faith to tens of
millions of Chinese while refusing to accept the authority of
official religious bodies.
</P>
<P>
   It came one day after a top leader of the government-sponsored
churches told an audience in Los Angeles that religion in China had
entered a ``golden age'' of freer expression.
</P>
<P>
   The detained Chinese are followers of the China Fangcheng
Church, which claims more than 500,000 members and is one of the
largest of many fervent Protestant groups that meet and evangelize
across the country without government approval. Such groups often
receive encouragement and financial aid from like-minded churches
in the United States, Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   American evangelicals say the beliefs and practices of the
Fangcheng Church fall well within the Christian tradition. But the
Chinese authorities have labeled it and several other similar
groups as cults and in December sent two Fangcheng leaders to
``re-education through labor'' camps.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the U.S. Embassy in Beijing said it had not
yet confirmed with Chinese officials that three citizens were in
police hands but that it was sending a consular officer to the
area. Under an agreement, China must inform the embassy within 96
hours when an American is detained for any reason.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, when an American supporter of the outlawed
Falun Gong spiritual group was detained she was quickly deported.
</P>
<P>
   The mass arrests were first reported by the Hong Kong based
Information Center for Human Rights and Democracy. On Thursday, a
police officer in the township where the raid occurred,
Dawangzhuang, in Henan province, confirmed that a large number of
worshipers were being held but would not say where.
</P>
<P>
   Often in such cases, most of those detained are soon released,
but leaders sometimes face stiff fines or imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   The detention of the three Americans, all of them Taiwan-born
immigrants, was confirmed Thursday by a pastor of their church, the
Chinese Vinyard Church Fellowship in Los Altos, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans _ Henry Chu, 36; his wife, Sandy Lin, 28; and
Patricia Lan, 25 _ traveled to China on Aug. 13 for a two-week
mission in support of China's beleaguered Christians, said the
pastor, who spoke by telephone on condition that his name not be
used.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chu, who has lived in the United States for 15 years, has an
engineering degree and also completed seminary school, the pastor
said, and volunteers much of his time to church work. Lin also
graduated from college and a seminary and is a paid employee of the
Vinyard Church Fellowship. Lan is a third-year seminary student.
</P>
<P>
   All three have made similar trips to China, the pastor said,
adding that his church alone, with some 300 members who are mainly
ethnic Chinese from Asia, annually sends four or five small groups
to China.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign missionary work is illegal in China, though informal
outside aid to churches is sometimes tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fangcheng Church is not a cult,'' the pastor said. ``They
are moderate and sound Christians. ``Its members are very faithful
and fearless, and they want to save everyone for Jesus. That's why
we want to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   The government-recognized leaders of China's five approved
religions _ Protestant Christianity, Catholicism, Buddhism, Islam
and Taoism _ arrived in the United States this week to take part in
a world summit meeting of religious leaders at the United Nations
in early September.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in Los Angeles on Tuesday, Fu Tieshan, bishop of the
official Chinese-Catholic Church, which does not accept the
authority of the Vatican, said religion in China is entering a
``golden age,'' with the number of believers growing and less
official interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religious believers and non-believers respect each other, are
united and have a harmonious relationship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Fu, reflecting the government's concern about the spread of
uncooperative religious groups, also warned that too many of the
people newly attracted to religion are poorly educated, and hence
susceptible to heretical teachings and to cults.
</P>
<P>
   By government estimates, about 4 million people take part in the
official Chinese-Catholic Church, but outside experts say that
another 4 million to 8 million attend so-called underground
Catholic churches, led by priests loyal to the pope, and that they
are sometimes detained or fined.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 million people attend the official,
non-denominational Protestant Church, but tens of millions more _
no one has good numbers _ are believed to be active in the dynamic
``house church'' movement, named for its informal meeting places.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, these unapproved churches do not operate in
secret, and the police may tolerate them if they do not too openly
proselytize. But in some regions, including Henan province,
assertive house church leaders have been harshly suppressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1515EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
