<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-US-NIGERIA-0825-COX     08-24 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-NIGERIA-0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON VISIT AIMS TO BOLSTER NIGERIA'S ROLE AS KEY DEMOCRACY
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In the two years since President Clinton pointedly
snubbed Nigeria's former dictators during a tour of Africa, the
sprawling country has changed from international pariah to
America's great democratic hope.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen months ago, Nigeria installed its first civilian
government since 1983 headed by President Olusegan Obasanjo, a
63-year-old former general with a reputation as an honest democrat
and hard worker. The change provided the United States a
much-needed friend in Africa, where war and economic stagnation
have conspired to dim prospects that raised hopes in the mid-1990s
of a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will spend the weekend in Nigeria as part of a brief
African tour trying to bolster Obasanjo's support and reward his
country with a clear expression of America's approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``If democracy takes root in Nigeria, it will lift up an entire
region,'' Clinton said last week.
</P>
<P>
   He will be the first American president to set foot in Nigeria
since Jimmy Carter _ who also visited Obasanjo, the country's
military leader from 1976 to 1979. Obasanjo ceded power to a
civilian government, which was pushed out of power in 1983,
beginning a long and draining run of military dictatorships not
broken until 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office, Obasanjo has held the fledgling democracy
together despite the many unsettling forces that sometimes seem on
the verge of pulling Africa's most populous country apart.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the relationship between the United States and
Nigeria has flourished. At the same time, Nigeria's importance to
American foreign policy has risen radically.
</P>
<P>
   The once stabilizing countries Clinton visited in 1998 _
Ethiopia, Eritrea, Uganda and Rwanda _ have fallen into war with
each other. Surprisingly, Nigeria has been reborn as a bright spot.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Rice, the assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, said earlier this week that the Clinton Administration is
working overtime to support Obasanjo. ``Across the spectrum, we are
cooperating with and coordinating with Nigeria in a way that is
unprecedented,'' Rice told reporters at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view Nigeria as an indispensable partner to pursue our
shared goals of democracy and stability and conflict resolution,
not only in West Africa and on the African continent but
globally,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its size and location, Nigeria could be a key in
containing the violence that has crippled Africa's attempts to
develop, the administration believes. The government recently
announced plans to assist in training and equipping up to five
Nigerian battalions for service in peacekeeping, particularly in
Sierra Leone. The first American trainers arrived in Nigeria
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. policymakers also take note of Obasanjo's ambitions of
doubling Nigeria's oil output to 4 million barrels a day. The
country, an OPEC member, already produces about twice as much crude
oil as Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Wednesday that oil prices would be on the agenda
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also has dramatically increased its aid to
Nigeria _ from $7 million in assistance restricted to humanitarian
groups in 1998 to about $109 million this year _ the largest amount
in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   However, after years of neglect and outright theft from public
coffers by Nigeria's military leaders, this may be a drop in the
bucket.
</P>
<P>
   For 17 years this vast country - which is about the size of
Texas, Georgia and Florida combined _ was ravaged by military
juntas that despite its oil wealth wrecked the economy,
impoverished the people and depleted the national treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria developed the reputation of being perhaps the world's
most corrupt country. (In 1998, Transparency International rated
Nigeria No. 2 among corrupt nations, trailing only neighboring
Cameroon.)
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Sani Abacha, who ruled from 1993 until he died in office in
1998, is accused of personally stealing more than $4 billion. With
the assistance of friendly governments _ including the United
States _ Obasanjo has located several hundred million. But much of
the money may never be recovered.
</P>
<P>
   And by most measures, Obasanjo has made an auspicious start.
Immediately after taking office, he summarily retired from the
government crooked military officers, pushed an ethics agenda and
has labored to repair the country's dreadful reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo also has been willing to extend his efforts beyond
Nigeria, teaming with South African President Thabo Mbeki on an
number of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Despite many small victories, the economy remains weak but at
least stable.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian leaders say it will be impossible for them to address
the major infrastructure problems hindering the country's
development as long as they are burdened with about $31 billion in
debt to the industrialized world. Clinton has told them that he
supports their position and has pledged to lobby for debt relief.
Only about 4 percent of the debt is owed to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest threat to Obasanjo now is a bloody conflict
between Muslims in the north and Christians, who dominate the
south. Muslim leaders have imposed sharia _ a strict set of laws
based on a literal interpretation of the Koran _ in a half-dozen
northern states, creating a conflict that has claimed the lives of
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo has been criticized for reacting too slowly and
indecisively. Politicians from both religions express concerns that
Nigeria will disintegrate if Obasanjo cannot gain control of the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is a feeling among ordinary Nigerians, intellectuals
and business leaders that the change is irreversible.
</P>
<P>
   For many, Clinton's visit represents Nigeria's return to the
fold of civilized nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visit by President Bill Clinton further underscores the
reality of our country's re-emergence into international
respectability,'' Babatunde Fadun, a businessman and politician,
wrote in the Nigerian Guardian newspaper Thursday. ``After several
years of self-imposed isolation, Nigeria returns to the world stage
in a positive light.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ngrguardiannews.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.allnigeria.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.infoplease.com/ipa/A0107847.html
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
