<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1192 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN25-CO     08-24 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A funny thing can happen on the way to the polls
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Politics is a funny business, and getting
funnier all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's looking like we're going to have a horse race of an
election after all, as opposed to a coronation fit for a king by
the name of George II.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent round of polls is giving Vice President Al Gore
a slight edge over Texas Gov. George W. Bush, whose lead only a few
weeks earlier was in the double digits.
</P>
<P>
   Polls, of course, can be funny, too.
</P>
<P>
   These are nationwide popularity polls. Never mind that the
presidential election is neither a nationwide nor a popular vote.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents are voted on in individual state elections, each with
its proscribed number of electoral votes according to population,
and it's the electoral college vote that officially counts.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where it can get tricky for the polls:
</P>
<P>
   George Bush and Dick Cheney may be ahead in Texas by as many as
4 million votes, while Al Gore and Joe Lieberman are the favorites
in New York by only a few hundred thousand.
</P>
<P>
   But whether a candidate wins a state by a split-hair decision or
by a landslide, it's winner-take-all for that state's electoral
votes, making it mathematically possible to lose the popular vote
nationwide yet still be elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Because Texas is so big and so lopsided in favor of Bush, the
overall polling figures are easily skewered. That being the case,
Gore may be in even better shape than it appears.
</P>
<P>
   Another curious aspect of the electoral college: Electors are
prohibited from casting a vote for a president and vice president
from the same state; such was the provision written into law by the
Founding Fathers to prevent Virginia from totally dominating the
executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-Cheney ticket, in effect, will do exactly that for
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, though a legal resident of Wyoming, has been making a
living -- and a very nice one, at that -- as CEO of Halliburton Oil
Co. of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   He went to work in Dallas, he ate his meals in Dallas, he slept
in Dallas, and when he took a shower he took a shower in Dallas.
For all practical purposes, he lived in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that the Republicans have come up with a two-Texan
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   I can't imagine that it would be contested in court, but if it
were, and if the challenge were successful, might we end up with
Bush as president and Lieberman as vice president?
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder how that ticket would do in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the best advice about polls -- and most often quoted
by the candidate who is behind in the polls _ goes something like
this:
</P>
<P>
   The only poll that counts is the one taken inside the polling
place on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm still figuring it will be Bush. Write that down
as my prediction.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I'll go even further:
</P>
<P>
   I predict that Bush will be a one-term president, that through
no fault of his own, a faltering economy -- and we're about due for
a serious downturn -- will cost him re-election in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   It will be history repeating itself, just like his daddy in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Because if there's anything funnier than politics, it's history.
History has a hilarious sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
