<SLUG> BC-FILM-CREW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE RETIRED, BUT `THE CREW' STILL WANTS RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B-  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What happens to old mobsters when they trade in their rods for a
retirement home? Just call them ``Goodfogies.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dreyfuss narrates as Bobby Bartellemeo, the former
lieutenant of an old Jersey gang of wiseguys now graying retirees
in Miami, whose social highlights are senior special dinners and
strip clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Director Michael Dinner reigns in Dreyfuss' usual jittery,
high-strung delivery but has less success with Burt Reynolds, who
mugs his way through the film as ``Bats,'' an enforcer on a
pacemaker. Dan Hedaya and Seymour Cassel round out the group as,
respectively, ``Brick,'' the thick-headed softy with a sentimental
streak, and ``Mouth,'' the tightlipped ladies man and arsonist.
</P>
<P>
   The script, by ``Kingpin'' co-writer Barry Fanaro, spoofs
``Goodfellas'' while it follows the old boys getting back into the
game. They execute a neat little bit of mobster theatrics to scare
off the young, rich tenants from their suddenly upscale apartment
house and drive prices back. Flush with success, they flaunt their
new confidence with sports cars, flashy jewelry and flashier women.
</P>
<P>
   But their plan backfires and soon they're up to their toupees in
a blackmail scheme, a murder for hire, a homicide investigation by
a cop who just may be Bobby's long-lost daughter (Carrie-Anne Moss)
and a mob war with a Hispanic drug lord (Miguel Sandoval, who
underplays the bedeviled mob boss to quiet perfection).
</P>
<P>
   Dinner is a smooth, smart director with a great sense of comic
timing, but his strengths are character humor and understatement,
where Fanaro's leering sexual humor and outrageous gags are like a
senior citizens version of a teen sex farce. It's an odd mix with
an even odder undercurrent of romanticism.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner makes this quartet of former killers a cute and cuddly
bunch of snappy-dressing codgers who couldn't harm a flea if they
wanted to, yet he thinks nothing of the gang war they inadvertently
set off on the streets of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner made his reputation on TV, directing and producing
episodes of ``The Wonder Years,'' ``Chicago Hope'' and many others.
The film is slick and handsome, showing none of the visual
clumsiness many TV transplants let get in the way of the drama, but
Dinner instills it with a sweetness that bespeaks of his years
directing for families.
</P>
<P>
   It loses all potential for black comedy as a result, but in its
place is a good-natured movie that (criminal roots aside) explores
the way the elderly lose their dignity in their later years and
celebrates the strength of four guys who draw on their skills,
their courage and their spirit to take their dignity back.
</P>
<P>
   THE CREW
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Michael Dinner
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Barry Fanaro
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Richard Dreyfuss, Burt Reynolds, Dan Hedaya, Seymour
Cassel, Carrie-Anne Moss, Jennifer Tilly, Lainie Kazan
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 98 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: PG-13 for non-explicit violence and sexual content
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1534EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
