<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1196 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-BRINGITON-SPI &LR;      08-24 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BRINGITON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING NEW IN BANAL `BRING IT ON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing is sacred any more _ not even the cheerleader's
energetic, virginal appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm a Cheerleader'' and ``American Beauty'' challenged the
fresh-faced, chaste view of this optimistically iconic American
dream queen and the extreme sport cheerleading odyssey ``Bring It
On'' accentuates the fall by giving its angelic faces foul mouths
that would make a sailor blush.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the abundance of swearing and obscene gestures, there's
hardly a shred of fresh material in the film, which straddles turf
that was already getting a bit soggy more than a decade ago after a
flood of smarter teen comedies by John Hughes (``Sixteen Candles,''
``The Breakfast Club,'' ``Ferris Bueller's Day Off'').
</P>
<P>
   What this almost enjoyably bad comedy will do is provoke and
titillate every teenage boy's not-so-secret fantasy life. ``Bring
It On'' might shield its wallop of T&AMP;A taste in a shroud of
win-at-all-costs acrobatics, yet this squad of nimble, agile girls
and boys will stop at nothing to win the national championship
trophy for the sixth year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   After a new student named Missy (Eliza Dushku, from TV's
``Buffy, the Vampire Slayer'') enrolls at San Diego's Rancho Carne
High (Rancho Carne translates to ``fresh meat,'' by the way), the
Toro's cheerleading team discovers its cache of award-winning
cheers and choreography has been stolen for the rival East Compton
Clovers.
</P>
<P>
   New team captain Torrance (Kirsten Dunst) is caught between
saving face and doing the right thing. And Missy, her new best
friend, has an bad-boy brother Cliff (Jesse Bradford), who loves
the punk group The Clash. When he takes a shine to Torrance, well,
her whole peppy world is about to go postal!
</P>
<P>
   You've got to wonder what charismatic actors such as Dunst,
Dushku, Bradford (who began his film career with promise as the
young hero in Steven Soderberg's ``King of the Hill'' and who is
given so little to do here that it hurts) and Gabrielle Union are
doing slumming in a movie that's so lacking in everything except
spiffy footwork and abundant energy.
</P>
<P>
   Every other aspect of this story is predictable and surprisingly
confusing in its ultimate message _ its characters sway between
modern day empowerment and punishment by a '50s puritan ethic. That
in itself could have been a great theme but, in the end, even
Hughes better captured the false bravado and the sense of
insecurity that lingered beneath the cool facades of his teenage
protagonists _ and with resonant humor.
</P>
<P>
   So while 2, 4, 6, 8, ``Bring It On'' ain't so great, I wonder,
1, 2, 3, 4, why can't Hollywood give its teenage audience more?
</P>
<P>
   BRING IT ON
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Peyton Reed
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Jessica Bendinger
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Kirsten Dunst, Eliza Dushku, Jesse Bradford, Gabrielle
Union
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: PG-13 for language
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1535EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
