<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BUYING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COUNTIES, CITIES TO SAVE ON COMPUTER PURCHASES
 &HT;    Moving in the (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four major computer makers joined Thursday in a
one-size-fits-all bulk purchasing program for local governments
that promises to save the nation's cities and counties $50 million
over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is a win-win contract for us and for our
customers,'' said David Forsythe, vice president and general
manager of state and local government sales for Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program,'' Forsythe told a press conference here,
``allows us to save time, resources and money because we do not
have to re-bid to every local government. And this increased
efficiency translates into savings that we can then pass on to our
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer sales will build on a little-known government
cooperative program, in place since 1997, that allows both tiny
rural hamlets and large urban areas to qualify for a discount of as
much as 70 percent below a manufacturers' list price.
</P>
<P>
   The direct-sales participants in the program, in addition to
Dell, are IBM, Gateway and Micron. Two technology re-sellers,
Comark and Software Spectrum, have also joined in the bulk
purchasing plan, which pools the purchasing power of local
governments to achieve volume discounts.
</P>
<P>
   An umbrella group known as the U.S. Communities Government
Purchasing Alliance sponsors the plan. The consortium is composed
of National Association of Counties, the U.S. Conference of Mayors
and the National Institute of Governmental Purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   Their new program is expected to generate $100 million in sales
this year and more than $500 million in sales over the next three
years. This will represent a savings to local governments of more
than $50 million within a two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, one large jurisdiction agrees to seek bids on
specific technology products. Then any county, city or other local
government can purchase the same products at the greatly reduced
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the alliance maintains more than 10,000 active
accounts in some 5,500 public jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   It already offers an office supply program through Atlanta-based
Office Depot that saved local governments $35 million last year.
Office Depot reported program sales of about $16,7 million in 1997,
$35.4 million in 1998, and $75.8 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Hague, president of National Association of Counties and a
member of the King County (Wash.) council, said the program ``helps
local officials do more with less, exactly what our taxpayers are
demanding. We are doing it in a 21st century way, using technology
of course.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.naco.org
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
