u e BC-IVOR-OLYMPICS-MASSACR     08-24 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-OLYMPICS-MASSACRE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUNICH OLYMPICS MASSACRE RELIVED IN OSCAR-WINNING DOCUMENTARY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's IVOR DAVIS HOLLYWOOD STARS feature service.
For more information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of IVOR DAVIS HOLLYWOOD
STARS _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 ART NOTE: Includes two B&AMP;W photos: 1) director Kevin MacDonald; and
2) a group shot of the 1972 Israeli Olympic team. 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 c.2000 Ivor Davis 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sydney Summer Olympics will unfold in September with the
tightest security ever seen at the quadrennial event.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, that was not the case back in September l972 when the
Olympics took place in Munich, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Loose security resulted in eight Palestinian members of the
Black September Movement sneaking into the athletes' village in the
early hours of Sept. 5, killing two Israeli athletes, and over the
next 21 hours torturing and eventually slaying nine other members
of the Israeli team.
</P>
<P>
   During the last hours that the horrible drama was playing itself
out in the very heart of the Olympic village, Olympics organizers
debated whether to suspend the Games. Meanwhile, close to the
apartment where the athletes were being held and tortured, members
of other teams practiced, trained, sat at cafes or simply relaxed
in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   With our minds about to focus on the Olympics that open Sept.
13, HBO has chosen Sept. ll to air the powerful Oscar-winning
documentary, ``One Day in September.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Kevin MacDonald recalled the background and events that
lead to the making of the film:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only 28 years since the end of World War II and the
Germans, because of their history, were worried that if they
cracked down too hard they would be perceived as Teutonic
dictators,'' he explains. ``They were trying to live down the
reputation they had for militarism and for being overly strict. So
they went to the other extreme and were completely lax.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, for the Games, unarmed German cops donned sky blue lycra
outfits. ``They wanted to show the world that they were a
democratic country, not the fascist state they used to be,'' adds
the young Scottish filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   So how did the terrorists get in? The film shows that they just
climbed over the fence around the village at about 4:30 a.m. ``They
were actually helped over by some drunken American athletes who
thought they were competitors, like themselves, trying to get back
to their dormitories without going through officials at the front
gate and having their passes checked,'' says MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were a lot more naive about security then,'' he points
out. ``It was easy come, easy go. And it wasn't uncommon for
athletes to go to parties and smuggle themselves back into the
village by climbing the fences.''
</P>
<P>
   The terrorists were also helped, says producer Arthur Cohn, by
the delegation from East Germany, who were quartered on the floor
above the Israelis. ``They passed crucial information to the
terrorists,'' adds MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, narrated by Michael Douglas, is often tough to
watch. The filmmakers' greatest coup was to track down the last
remaining member of the Palestinian terrorist squad, now hiding
with his family somewhere in Africa, and to persuade him to do an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the assassins died in a hail of bullets at the airport.
Two were eventually hunted down and killed by the Israeli secret
service, Mossad, which also disposed of a dozen other Palestinian
leaders believed to have been involved with the planning of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald says Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak was at that
time head of one of the anti-terrorist squads that carried out the
reprisals. ``In the most famous incident, Barak dressed up as a
woman _ with grenades literally in his bra _ and with a dozen other
commandos got into central Beirut from the beach and killed three
senior members of the PLO. That was in direct revenge for Munich.''
</P>
<P>
   The surviving Palestinian terrorist, Jamil Al Gashey, who was
also the youngest, appears in the film in disguise. In shadowy
lighting, with his face masked with glasses and a moustache and
hidden by a baseball cap, he gives a version of how the terrorists
planned the attack.
</P>
<P>
   They originally intended only to take hostages in exchange for
Palestinian prisoners held abroad, he maintains. ``We had no orders
to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Gashey, who has survived several attempts on his life, expresses
absolutely no regret for what he did.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn, the six-time Academy Award winner whose triumphs include
``The Garden of The Finzi-Continis'' (1971) and ``Central
Station,'' (l999) explains: ``Gashay said he would do it again
because it presented an opportunity to let billions of viewers
around the world know the political aims of the Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   Though criticized in some Israeli circles for giving Gashey a
platform, the filmmakers say most Israelis, including Mossad, are
happy with the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided from the very beginning,'' says Cohn, ``that in
order to have an evenhanded document, to have a believable and
authentic story, we needed the protagonists of that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an uphill battle to get all the others to appear. We
had, for the first time, the head of the Mossad, Zvi Zamir. We had
the German interior minister, the Munich police chief, the head of
the Olympic Village and all the other principals at Munich.''
</P>
<P>
   Because families of the Israeli athletes were upset at the
graphic photographs of their slain loved ones, the pictures were
``softened'' in the film. But, Cohn says, ``I continued to insist
that a film against terror must show terror.''
</P>
<P>
   The other great revelation of the film is the incompetence of
the infamous German officials, who not only had no anti-terrorist
squad but also had no special-services group whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   When they did try to mount an attack on the terrorists, who were
holed up with their victims in the dormitories, machine-gun toting
police dressed as athletes planned to get in through the roof's
ventilation shafts. But as they assembled there, TV cameras were
watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really the first satellite Olympic Games and the whole
world was watching _ along with the terrorists,'' MacDonald
recalls. ``It became this incredible drama unfolding in the living
rooms of viewers around the world. In some way we tried to
re-create that sense in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extraordinary to see the footage, throughout that day, of
the negotiations going on, the terrorists coming out on the
balcony, the bus with the terrorists inside, and they and the
hostages leaving in helicopters for the airport. Today the media
would be kept two miles away and wouldn't see a thing,'' he notes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, having come up with a clever plan to grab the
terrorists at the airport, the German police could not follow
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five policemen disguised as flight crew were to be hidden in
the jet waiting at Fuerstenfeldbruck air base to fly the terrorists
and their nine hostages to Libya,'' recalls Cohn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their plan was to capture or kill the terrorist leader when he
inspected the plane, and the chances would have been excellent that
his subordinates would then have given up or been overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the police assigned to the job rejected the plan as being
a suicide mission,'' exclaims Cohn. ``Even now I find this attitude
absolutely incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, German security officials eventually opted to storm
the terrorists as they arrived in helicopters at the airport for
their plane to freedom. In blazing gunfire, five of the terrorists
perished _ but not before they tossed a grenade, blowing up the
copter carrying the nine remaining Israeli hostages.
</P>
<P>
   And the Games went on ...
</P>
<P>
   (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``One Day in September,''
consult the HBO web site at www.hbo.com. And check out The New York
Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on Hollywood Stars and other features. &QL;
</P>
