<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1222 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-MARINO-TRIBUTE0824-CO     08-24 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINO-TRIBUTE0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dolphins fans get chance to honor their hero
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Dan Marino stood on the stage, licking his
lips just like he used to before taking a snap with the final
seconds clicking off the clock. Only it was clear that in many
ways, this situation was tougher. He took a deep breath. He put a
hand on his chest. He blinked hard.
</P>
<P>
   The fans cheered louder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' he said, his voice cracking. ``I'll never forget
it in my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   His family came to his side. The band played. And so ended a
tribute at Pro Player Stadium that felt like the final night of a
political convention _ thousands gathering for the same cause, some
waving signs, some wearing funny hats, some getting choked up while
watching sentimental videos, all cheering at every drop of a name.
</P>
<P>
   Marino.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the applause didn't crank up every time someone
talked about what the featured speaker would do in the future. It
came whenever any of the warmup acts _ from former coach Don Shula
to the other five quarterbacks in the Class of '83 _ talked about
what Marino did in the past. And what some in the crowd clearly
wished he was still doing.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours before the final speech, Marino had bounded on to
the stage wearing a short sleeve black shirt, tan pants and
loafers. The fans rose to their feet and gave him an three-minute
ovation. With the Tina Turner song ``Simply the Best'' blaring over
the loudspeakers, Marino blew kisses and mouthed the words ``thank
you'' to the 52,000 people who had snatched up all the $2 tickets
in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the cheering started to fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan,'' moderator Tony Segreto began, ``for 17 years . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   The fans interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more year!'' they chanted. ``One more year!''
</P>
<P>
   Marino hadn't been on this field since Dec. 27. That Monday
night _ actually it was 12:18 on Tuesday morning _ he trudged off
the field after a 38-31 loss to the Jets, grass stains smeared
across the No. 13 on the front of his jersey. Before entering the
tunnel, he raised his head for a moment, glanced into the stands,
found his children and waved.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be part of a rough farewell year. There were
the clashes with Jimmy Johnson, the injury that forced him to miss
five games and, finally, the sight of him standing alone on the
sideline in Jacksonville _ a self-imposed benching in what turned
out to be his final NFL game.
</P>
<P>
   He waited two months, seriously considering an offer to play for
the Minnesota Vikings, before calling a news conference to say,
``It's time.''
</P>
<P>
   If that was a sad day, then this was a happy night.
</P>
<P>
   While much of America watched the final episode of ``Survivor,''
the anchor for the CBS affiliate in Miami told everyone in the
stadium how fortunate they were to have other plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a night if you don't get a lump in your throat,''
Segreto said, ``you don't have a pulse.''
</P>
<P>
   It was night for jokes, for gushing testimonials, for photos
from childhood, for footage from record-breaking games, for a clip
from ``The Simpsons'' that included Marino's voice, for a $104,000
donation by the Dolphins to Marino's charity, for appearances by
Terry Bradshaw, Don Shula, Mark Clayton, Mark Duper, Don Strock,
Nat Moore and many more.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was Marino throwing three more passes _ hard passes _
to former targets Clayton, Duper and O.J. McDuffie.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the cheers. Maybe it was the jeers: for any footage
that included Jimmy Johnson, for the introduction of Jim Kelly, for
any reference to Dolphins owner Wayne Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   When the fans booed Huizenga, Marino defended the man who helped
orchestrate the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not right,'' Marino said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not rush to Kelly's defense when the former Bills
quarterback teased the fans, saying that in Buffalo they used to
refer to the Dolphins' home field as ``Rich Stadium South.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boo if you want,'' Marino said.
</P>
<P>
   And the fans did _ until Kelly praised them for years of making
it hard to run the no-huddle offense.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the highlight was Hootie and the Blowfish playing ``Only
Wanna Be With You'' _ the 1995 song that led to a video featuring
Marino and other athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Before the tribute, Darius Rucker, the band's lead singer
explained that, despite growing up in South Carolina, he had become
a Dolphins fan at age 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived and died with Dan Marino for 17 years,'' he said.
``He's affected my moods. He's affected my relationships. He's
affected everything in my life. And to be here on a day like this,
I could never even begin to tell you what it means to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the crowd apparently could relate.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours before the start of the tribute, cars already lined
up on the roads around the stadium _ including the recently newly
renamed Dan Marino Boulevard. The elaborate production went off
smoothly, despite a few glitches. Joe Namath had ``transportation
problems'' and didn't make it to the stadium in time for his
planned tribute to Marino's Pittsburgh's roots. Instead, the
program moved on to another Pittsburgh quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw, now an analyst on Fox's pre-game show, told a few
stories about Marino's youth and gave him a little advice for his
future job with HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be yourself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, that might have been the highlight. Marino being
himself. After hearing the fans break into the one-more-year chant
again at the end of the night _ ``Believe me,'' he said, ``I would
like to play one more year, but I can't'' _ Marino licked his lips,
regained his composure and made a request.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's have some fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he led the way, showing a side of himself that his fans
rarely saw. He danced. He sang. He relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
