<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WYCLEF JEAN CD IS FEARLESS AND FUNNY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You want audacious?
</P>
<P>
   Within the first four cuts of ``The Ecleftic _ 2 Sides II A
Book,'' Wyclef Jean has: enraged Columbia Records bigwig Tommy
Mottola for not delivering a new Fugees record; rapped over Kenny
Rogers (yes, that Kenny Rogers) doing a revamped version of ``The
Gambler;'' and performed a moving song about street players and
Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the mock Mottola phone call is a put-on. But it does point
the way to the rest of this bracing, sometimes magnificent
reggae/hip-hop/rock CD. Jean, one-third of the multimillion-selling
Fugees, has established himself as one of the most ecleftic
(ecleftic _ get it?) of hip-hop superstars, and he rarely loosens
his grip here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ecleftic'' is a shape-changing stew of straight-up hip-hop,
reggae-hop, balladry, old-school '70s funk _ witness the lovely
``Runaway,'' done with help from Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire _ and several
nods to classic rock. And within all that, Jean turns his lyrical
concerns from everyone bugging him about the next Fugees CD
(''Where Fugees At?'') to the joys of marijuana (''Something About
Mary'') to the infamous Diallo shooting.
</P>
<P>
   And it ends with a hip-hop version of _ brace yourself, classic
rockers _ Pink Floyd's ``Wish You Were Here,'' which grows out of
``Bus Search,'' a skit about a redneck searching his band's tour
bus for illegal drugs. Does the ``Here'' cover work? Against all
odds, yes (although the guitar intro could have been better).
</P>
<P>
   And like the hilarious reworking of ``The Gambler'' _ the track
is called ``Kenny Rogers _ Pharoahe Monch Dub Plate,'' it shows
just how fearlessly Jean is traveling. An amazing balancing act,
``Ecleftic'' hits all the targets it aims for, from ``911,'' a soul
duet with Mary J. Blige, to the brisk feminist hip-hop of ``Perfect
Gentleman,'' from the hilarious ``It Doesn't Matter'' (which
features a cameo by wrestler The Rock) to ``Diallo,'' a mournful
reggae-ish cry of sorrow and agony. ``He didn't have no piece
sir/But now he rests in peace sir/In the belly of the beast sir''
Jean sings over and over, and it's as gripping as any number of Bob
Marley's finest moments.
</P>
<P>
   Jean is one of the few high-profile rappers successfully
balancing Marley's tradition of mixing social protest with sweet
love songs even if, occasionally, his hubris gets the best of him.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, ``Ecleftic'' is one of the best urban CDs of the
year, an endlessly wide-screen look at the man's personal issues
and those of society at large. That it's sometimes extremely funny
only adds to its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
