brides, even caskets_virtual therapy is still considered
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two-thirds of people with diagnosable mental health
problems don't seek treatment, according to a 1999 report of the
U.S. surgeon general. A third of those who do manage to make a
first-time appointment fail to keep it, says the American
Psychological Association in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   E-therapy, proponents argue, knocks down many of the barriers
that keep people out of therapists' offices: embarrassment,
inertia, cost.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics say there's no way to control the quality of care
on the Internet. It's experimental, and it's impossible to
regulate. Even when it's performed by knowledgeable, experienced
and ethical professionals, there is no research on whether or how
therapy by text, rather than face to face, works, the critics say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet more therapists and ``virtual clinics,'' where a credit card
gets you instant advice, are flooding online every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major objection to cybertherapy in the past has been the
lack of visual cues,'' Chechele said. These include how a client
dresses or sits_things that can tip therapists off to depression,
anxiety and lies. But Chechele, who has been practicing through his
Web site, www.cybertherapy.com, since 1997, finds ``that there's
something special about lack of visual cues. E-mail therapies allow
some people to be more forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Maricle, for instance, found it easier to write e-mails at her
own pace rather than making and keeping appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just wonderful to give him a scenario when it was going
on at the time I was feeling it,'' she said. ``I didn't have to
wait until my 3 o'clock appointment on Thursday. I could go ahead
and write it right then.''
</P>
<P>
   And the lower cost helped her keep her mind on why she was in
therapy, instead of on the money she was spending to get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I started therapy again, I was looking at $75 to $150 per
hour. I couldn't afford it,'' Maricle said. ``It's hard to
concentrate when all you can think is, `How am I going to pay for
this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Chechele's charges are fairly standard: For $150 a month he'll
answer an unlimited number of e-mails. For $1.60 per minute, he'll
do chat or telephone sessions with a 45-minute minimum. By way of
comparison, his 50-minute in-office visit runs $85.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some mental health professionals have deep reservations
about what Chechele and others are doing. They say e-therapy poses
troubling ethical and legal dilemmas and may even be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for many consumers it's not dangerous, but for some it
could be,'' said Thomas Nagy, a licensed psychologist, Stanford
University professor and author of two books on ethics who helped
formulate the APA's code of ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone comes into your office every week and seems to be
becoming more panicky and dissociative,'' or starts talking about
suicide, it's possible to refer the patient for medication or, in
extreme cases, to hospitalize him or her involuntarily, Nagy said.
</P>
<P>
   And some serious disorders, such as borderline personality
disorder, aren't always readily apparent. Even when a therapist is
seeing someone face to face, it may take several meetings to reach
such a diagnosis, Nagy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're dealing with someone who's 1,000 miles away or in
another country, you really can't do this stuff,'' he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Online practitioners agree that e-therapy can't replace
traditional methods, so it's not for everyone. Most say they don't
take suicidal and seriously mentally ill patients. However,
Chechele admitted that no matter how carefully he screens them, his
online patients do from time to time become suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   He said he does for them what he would a local patient: makes
himself more available, makes contracts in which they promise not
to harm themselves or others, encourages them to tap their support
network and find local resources. Finally, if he feels a case is
outside his competence, he refers the patient to another mental
health professional.
</P>
<P>
   Confidentiality is another ethical concern. Skeptics worry that
e-mails or chat sessions, which are not usually scrambled, could be
intercepted and read, especially at work where such monitoring has
become routine. Chechele offers his patients a scrambling service
that costs $1 per month but finds that few use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously my neck's out there, way out there,'' Chechele said.
``I try to practice by the same mandates as I would in my office.
Legal and ethical issues, I try to uphold those as best I can in
this new medium.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Some cybertherapists say what they are doing isn't therapy.
Instead, they call their practices ``counseling'' or ``coaching,''
in hopes of dodging state licensing laws. Some also post
disclaimers.
</P>
<P>
   But psychotherapy by any other name is still the same, warns
Marlene Maheu, director of the Telemedicine Training Program at the
California School of Professional Psychology in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Maheu and co-author Barry Gordon report in an article to be
published in October in the APA journal Professional Psychologist
Research and Practice that some 10 percent of 42 U.S. online
therapists who took part in a 1998 survey said they were not
licensed.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that a majority of online therapists
described their services ``in terms other than providing
psychotherapy,'' said Gordon, a clinical consulting psychologist in
Petaluma, Calif. But when they were asked to list what kind of
diagnoses were being made, most were fairly serious.
</P>
<P>
   As of yet, very few complaints about online providers have been
made with state attorneys general and none has resulted in
convictions or enforcement actions, said Gerry Koocher, an
associate professor at Harvard University's Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of 42 state attorneys general due to be published in
the APA journal in October, Koocher found only seven states have
received complaints against therapists using electronic means to
carry out counseling. The only conviction involved telephone
counseling, not the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``duty to warn,'' Maheu said. Every state has
different standards for what therapists are legally obligated to
tell the authorities. Most states require that child and elder
abuse be reported, but beyond that, standards vary. In California,
for instance, therapists must tell the police when a client
threatens any third party. The Florida Supreme Court has ruled the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm dealing with someone from another state, am I still
obligated to report? If I'm obligated to report, is my obligation
to report in my own state_which doesn't care, 'cause the other
person isn't there_or do I call that other state where they're at?
And do I know where they are?'' Koocher asked.
</P>
<P>
   If an online therapist is sued for malpractice, it's unclear if
professional liability insurers will pay up. ``Professional
liability policies usually exclude coverage for illegal acts
committed by the practitioner. To the extent that an insured
practitioner is involved in unlawful practice under some state's
law, coverage under their professional liability policy may be
denied,'' Koocher writes in his upcoming journal article.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Some say the only way to address legal problems is to license
therapists nationally. That's not likely, said George J. Alexander,
professor of law at Santa Clara University and an expert in
telemedicine law.
</P>
<P>
   State licensing laws spring from the constitutional right states
enjoy to make laws protecting their own citizens. To solve the
problem of e-therapy crossing state lines, states have begun
issuing special ``telemedicine licenses,'' but Alexander said
that's not much better. Therapists would still need to be licensed
in every state where they practice, and keep track of each state's
applicable laws.
</P>
<P>
   Others say that, given the worldwide reach of the Internet, even
federal licensure would be inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible jurisdictional nightmare. The first time
you try to control it, you'll have someone in Pakistan pop up and
say, `I can help you out there in Southern California,''' said
Storm King, past president of the Internet Society for Mental
Health Online and a doctoral candidate in clinical psychology at
the Pacific Graduate School of Psychology in Palo Alto, Calif. King
would rather see international, self-regulating organizations set
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said the legal tangle is keeping some of the best
therapists off the Internet. ``The problem is that even though
there is virtually no enforcement, it scares a lot of ethical,
thoughtful people from doing (online therapy). It doesn't scare the
charlatans,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that there's little research on cybertherapy. That
means practitioners don't know what's effective, nor do they have
widely recognized standards of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a vicious circle,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   But even professionals with deep concerns about delivering
mental health services through the Internet don't think that it
shouldn't be done. Most would simply rather see therapists take a
more cautious and incremental approach.
</P>
<P>
   That seems unlikely. After years of chafing under the
restrictions of managed care, some practitioners see cybertherapy
as a way to access a wider pool of patients paying cash. Others
fear that the Internet will become just another cost-savings
vehicle for HMOs as online clinics like Lifescape.com and
myTHERAPYnet.com proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at some of the larger online therapy companies
getting started out there, the people who are helping them out and
putting the most venture capital into them are the managed care
companies,'' said David Nickelson, director of technology policy
for the APA. ``I can't imagine that the value system that comes
with some of managed care isn't going to be infused into those.''
</P>
<P>
   His fear? Picture answering 25 questions on your HMO's Web site
before you can be authorized to see someone online. ``If it's
really bad, maybe you'll get an in-person session, but they cost
more and the overhead is much higher than hooking you up online.''
</P>
<P>
   One saving grace, said Russ Newman, the APA's executive
director, is that people may not yet be as interested in online
therapy as many companies think they are.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 60 million adults, some 68 percent of all American
Internet users, looked for health information on the Web, a January
Harris Poll found. Some 40 percent of those researched mental
health care topics.
</P>
<P>
   In its own December poll, the APA found the same high level of
interest in mental health information_for which about 66 percent
were willing to go online. However, only about 23 percent of
respondents said they would consider engaging in an online dialogue
with a mental health professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that says the public is not yet willing to jump up on
this thing with both feet,'' said Newman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
