<HEADLINE>
$ADV04 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI 
 JOHN C. MCGINLEY MENACES AGAIN IN `SOLE SURVIVOR' 
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., SEPT. 4, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI feature service. For
more information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI _
contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives
listed at the end of the text.) 
 &HT;    (Includes a color slide and black-and-white photo of John C.
McGinley in ``Dean Koontz's Sole Survivor'')
 By IAN SPELLING 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) &QC;
<P>
   John C. McGinley sent chills up the spines of viewers as serial
killer Edgler Vess in the top-rated 1997 miniseries version of
``Intensity.'' And on Sept. 13 and 14, McGinley elicits sick laughs
in ``Dean Koontz's Sole Survivor,'' a Fox thriller with a sci-fi
twist.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do `Intensity,' I had to go and visit whatever demons I
could possibly dredge up,'' McGinley, 41, says by telephone from
his home in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''`Sole Survivor' is more of me doing Alan Rickman (from `Die
Hard') or John Malkovich (from `In the Line of Fire') type
things,'' he says. ``I get to put some air underneath the role and
prance a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My character isn't even in the book. As developed in the
teleplay by Richard Christian Matheson, son of sci-fi writing
legend Richard Matheson, he's an amalgamation of three different
characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to the set, they said, `Dude, you can do what you
want and go wherever you want,''' he laughed, adding, ``When you
give me that kind of license, just call `Action' and get out of my
eye line!''
</P>
<P>
   McGinley co-stars in ``Sole Survivor'' as Victor Yates, a
merciless guy whose task it is to kill Rose Tucker (Gloria Reuben),
who just may be the only survivor of a recent plane crash. That
crash claimed the wife and daughter of Joe Carpenter (Billy Zane),
an former crime reporter out to speak with Tucker and unravel the
true cause of the deadly incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is really Dean's exploring some supernatural, sci-fi
and spirituality issues,'' says McGinley, whose 50-plus credits
include ``Platoon' (1986), ``Highlander 2: The Quickening'' (1991),
``Seven'' (1995) and ``Any Given Sunday'' (1999).
</P>
<P>
   ``Between the scenes, between the lines, if you care to see it,
Dean is doing some spiritual wrestling with what this 'life' all
adds up to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit about miracles, a little bit about screwing
around with nature. Dean usually writes about arbitrary killing and
death, and here he took a beat and said, `I want to explore
something different.' And Fox said, `We'll do it with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   The actor says he and Koontz spoke a couple of times by
telephone, but adds that the author did not visit the ``Sole
Survivor'' set in Vancouver, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   McGinley describes protagonist Yates as a purely black-hat
villain. ``He comes on the scene when there's a problem and handles
it, whatever `it' is, almost always with a smirk and a cruel, witty
line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if he removes the trash,'' the actor says. ``Tennessee
Williams wrote a play called `Camino Royale,' and there were
characters in it referred to as the street sweepers. Anytime
something goes wrong or there's a dead body somewhere, the street
sweepers come and just take it away like so much other trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guy is of the same ilk. `OK, Billy Zane needs to be
eliminated? Let's go. No big deal.' Billy just happens to crash
into an intersection, but it's my intersection and now he's got to
be disposed of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this guy Yates. I think he's hysterical. He's having a
great time at everybody else's expense, and that's exactly how I
played him.''
</P>
<P>
   While shooting ``Sole Survivor,'' McGinley made time to join
Mickey Rourke to play the villains in Sylvester Stallone's next
feature, a remake of ``Get Carter.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also due soon in ``Highway,'' a drama about a dope dealer
who, on the weekend of Kurt Cobain's suicide, hitches a ride to
Seattle with two vigil-bound young men; and ``Summer Catch,'' a
baseball movie starring Freddie Prinze Jr. and Jessica Biel.
</P>
<P>
   McGinley doesn't know what's on tap after ``Catch.'' Given his
bravura performances in both ``Intensity'' and ``Sole Survivor,''
it seems likely that Koontz won't be able to conjure up future
villains without McGinley's mug rattling around in his head, thus
ensuring McGinley at least a few future gigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, if I get invited to another Dean Koontz dance once every
two or three years, it would take care of a lot of problems,'' he
says. ``I'll do anything to stay in the fraternity. It's pretty
sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; NEXT WEEK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kate Mulgrew talks about ``Star Trek: Voyager's'' seventh, and
final, season premiere.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on John C. McGinley in ``Dean
Koontz's Sole Survivor'' consult the Fox Web site at
www.foxnet.com. And don't forget to visit The New York Times
Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on Inside Trek and Sci-Fi and other features. &QL;
</P>
