<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1241 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-GOP-SWEEP-NNS &LR;      08-24 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-SWEEP-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF GOP SWEEPS ELECTIONS, EXPECT SOME CHANGES -- BUT NOT WHOLESALE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
THURSDAY, Aug. 24, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 By BILL WALSH  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans have controlled Congress for the past
five years, but Capitol Hill business lobbyist Bill Morley can only
think of what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Tort reform, tax cuts, measures to ease environmental
restrictions on business _ all have been blocked by congressional
Democrats or vetoed outright by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   However, Morley is suddenly salivating at the prospect of a
Republican clean sweep in November. Should Texas Gov. George W.
Bush win and the GOP keep its majority in Congress, it would be the
first time in nearly 50 years that the Republicans have controlled
both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of legislation that doesn't even come up
because you know it will be vetoed and you don't have the votes to
override,'' said Morley, who lobbies for the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce. ``You would be looking at a whole different situation
with George Bush in the White House. We would be looking for some
real change.''
</P>
<P>
   Political experts say that the type of radical dismantling of
government programs envisioned by the 1994 Republican revolution is
unlikely, but they agree that a GOP sweep in November would yield a
more prolific legislative output than any other election scenario.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, at least. Invariably, they say, single-party
domination is hampered by internal squabbling that can effectively
stall legislation on its own. The factions within the Republican
Party that have kept quiet during the 2000 campaign would likely
resurface, the experts predict, if the GOP won big in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would get more through with a clean sweep, there's no
doubt about it,'' said David Mayhew, a Yale University political
scientist whose book ``Divided We Govern'' argues that between 1946
and 1990 divided governments were as productive as unified ones.
``But give it three to four months and you would be hearing about
friction between Bush and (House Republican leader) Tom DeLay.''
</P>
<P>
   While the presidential contest is too close to call, members of
both parties say a Democratic sweep is unlikely. Political
oddsmakers give Democrats an outside chance of winning back the
House from Republicans, but not the Senate. A Republican sweep, by
contrast, is seen as a distinct possibility, although no one is
predicting that the party will significantly pad its majority in
either chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a Bush victory would clear a roadblock that has stalled
many a Republican initiative: the presidential veto. This year
Clinton has vetoed the so-called marriage penalty tax that had won
approval from the Republican-dominated Congress, and he has
threatened to veto the estate tax repeal bill that landed on his
desk Thursday. Those two items would likely be signed into law by
Bush, experts say. Clinton also has vetoed a ban on partial-birth
abortions, a bill Bush said he would sign as soon as it hit his
desk.
</P>
<P>
   Under a Bush administration, experts also would expect
significant increases in military spending and speedier deployment
of a national missile defense system, a program the Clinton
administration has balked at.
</P>
<P>
   Stripped of the veto, the most powerful tool Democrats would
wield during an era of Republican control would be the Senate
filibuster. They could tie up the chamber with endless speeches
until the Republican leadership met their demands.
</P>
<P>
   To shut off a Senate filibuster, the Republicans would need 60
votes, which has proven difficult even with the five-seat majority
the party has enjoyed for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans could skirt the Democratic talk-fest by using
what's known as the reconciliation process _ essentially cloaking
their proposals as budget bills, a legislative vehicle not subject
to filibuster. Some believe reconciliation is a route Bush could
use to pass legislation letting retirees invest a portion of their
Social Security taxes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under reconciliation, Social Security reform is very doable,''
said Daniel Palazzola, a political scientist at the University of
Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists see a Republican sweep as the worst of all
possible election outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Weiss, political director of the Sierra Club, predicted
that Bush would allow increased timber cutting on federal lands and
would roll back Clinton's conservation efforts. He speculated that
Bush would leave in place Republican-backed amendments, known as
riders, designed to chip away at environmental regulations. The
threat of a Clinton veto last year effectively derailed riders that
would have allowed oil companies to escape certain royalty
payments, undermined science-based management of the national
forests and weakened new regulations governing mining operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you combine George W. Bush with the current Republican
leadership on Capitol Hill, it will be an environmental disaster,''
Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the impact of single-party domination depends on the
size of that party's majority in Congress. Currently, the
Republicans have a 13-seat majority in the House, a paper-thin
margin that is not expected to grow significantly, even with a GOP
sweep. It has forced Republican leaders to reach out to Democrats
to get legislation passed.
</P>
<P>
   A group that would suddenly rise in prominence under a
Republican presidency, experts predict, is a coalition of moderate
Democrats known as Blue Dogs. Some experts said that especially if
Democrats were to regain the House, the Blue Dogs would be
vigorously courted by a Republican president to help get
legislation over the hump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Dogs would be an important swing group,'' said insurance
industry lobbyist Robert Rusbouldt. ``They have been reluctant to
take on a Democratic president. But you may see them forge certain
alliances to get things passed under a Republican administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the excitement in the Republican ranks about a possible
election sweep _ the first for the party since Dwight Eisenhower's
election in 1952 _ presidential scholars say that party domination
in Washington is no guarantee of legislative productivity.
</P>
<P>
   They point to Jimmy Carter's four years in the White House as
among the least active of any modern administration, even though
Democrats controlled Congress for the entire period from 1976 to
1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was at odds with Congress the whole time there,'' said J.
Bennett Johnston, a Democrat and former Louisiana senator who
served during Carter's term.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   While Bush is seen as more conciliatory than Carter _ or, for
that matter, Democratic candidate Al Gore _ experts predict he
would have his own intraparty problems to deal with. He has already
parted ways with the Christian conservative wing of the party over
the strongly pro-life abortion plank in the party platform, and
that rift is expected to remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have control, that's when the splits start to come
out,'' Johnston said. ``It's not easy being president with your own
party in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, presidents who have been paired with opposing
Congresses have, at times, posted prodigious legislative records.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable was Ronald Reagan's last two years as president
from 1986 to 1988. Although a lame duck, Reagan and a
Democratic-controlled Congress produced more major legislation --
including welfare and trade reform bills, a two-year budget
agreement and Medicare changes _ than at any other time of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The predictions were that nothing would get passed,'' said
Charles O. Jones, author of ``The Presidency in a Separated
System.'' ``Reagan wanted a legacy and the Democrats hoped to
regain the White House in 1988. It was all compromise legislation,
but a lot of it got through.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones sees a legislative stalemate if Gore gets elected and the
Republicans hold onto Congress. Other experts predict Gore would at
least have a honeymoon period during which he could push through
some of his top priorities, such as prescription drug coverage for
senior citizens and a patient's bill of rights. His own targeted
tax-cut proposals also would be expected to pass muster in a
Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones said that during eight years as vice president, Gore
has often played the role of attack dog for the Clinton
administration and developed a reputation for extreme partisanship.
Jones said it will be difficult for a Republican Congress to forget
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been quite partisan and that's the way the Republicans
on the Hill look at him,'' Jones said. ``If it's a Republican
Congress and a Democratic president, I see that as very tough for
getting much done. It could be a continuation of what we've been
seeing in the past couple of years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1619EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
