<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MISS-SAIGON-ERA-ART-3     08-24 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-SAIGON-ERA-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR `SAIGON,' THE LIGHT AT THE END 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photos NYT2,3,4,5 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They call it the Nightmare. That is how the crew
refers to the sequence in which the metal embassy fence drops in,
the helipad moves down, the sound of whipping blades intensifies,
and a life-size chopper descends.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 31, American troops will evacuate Saigon this way for
the last time on the stage of the Broadway Theater, bringing to a
close the musical ``Saigon,'' the sixth-longest-running show in
Broadway history. After nearly 10 years, the production, loosely
based on Puccini's ``Madama Butterfly,'' will have played 4,063
performances and gone through 1,218,900 pounds of dry ice, 89,386
scene changes and 812,600 light cues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saigon'' has taken in more than $1.3 billion internationally
at the box office since its world premiere in London in September
1989. The Broadway production, which opened on April 11, 1991, has
grossed more than $266 million and has been seen by nearly six
million people.
</P>
<P>
   The show spawned two U.S. touring companies and a Toronto
production. ``Saigon'' has been performed in six other countries,
and a new production will open in the Philippines next month,
starring Lea Salonga, who originated the title role on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The show's imminent departure is significant, and not only
because ``Saigon'' is the most technically complex show in Broadway
history, or because it broke several records during its phenomenal
run, like the largest advance ticket sale ($37 million) and highest
ticket price ever for a musical at the time ($100). With ``Cats''
scheduled to close next month, the departure of ``Saigon'' leaves
just two in a crop of mega-musicals still running _ ``Les
Miserables'' and ``The Phantom of the Opera'' _ suggesting that an
era of theatrical spectacle may be at an end.
</P>
<P>
   With musicals now costing $5 million to $12 million to mount,
many producers say they would not attempt a ``Saigon'' today. (The
show cost $10.9 million in 1991.)
</P>
<P>
   Written by Alain Boublil and Claude-Michel Schoenberg (who wrote
``Les Miserables''), with additional lyrics by Richard Maltby Jr.
and produced by the British impresario Cameron Mackintosh,
``Saigon'' is also a landmark in that it was the first successful
musical to deal with the sensitive subject of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the production originally engendered considerable
controversy when Sir Cameron clashed with the Actors Equity
Association over casting: the union insisted on an Asian actor for
the major role of the Engineer, a Eurasian pimp, while Sir Cameron
insisted on Jonathan Pryce _ initially canceling the production _
and ultimately prevailed. But ``Saigon'' has proved to be a source
of steady income for Asian actors, who often find work hard to come
by on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have been with the musical the longest say they are in
no position to mourn its passing. After all, most shows don't last
even a year on Broadway. And ``Saigon'' just kept on going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it was the last great blockbuster of the '80s, it had
all that sort of media-frenzied hype behind it,'' Sir Cameron said.
``Therefore, it wasn't until the dust had settled that actually the
audience decided to like it for itself. To this day it has its own
following.''
</P>
<P>
   While the production is best known for its special effects, it
is the poignancy of the love story between Kim, a Vietnamese waif
forced to work as a prostitute after witnessing the death of her
parents in the war, and Chris, an American GI compelled to leave
Saigon on the last helicopter out, that seems to explain why the
musical has run so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happened was, there was an appetite for what
opera has always done well,'' said Nicholas Hytner, who directed
the show, ``which is to dramatize large passions in some people set
against a sweeping historical background.''
</P>
<P>
   In his review of the show in The New York Times, Frank Rich
wrote, ``For all that seems galling about `Saigon' _ and for all
that is indeed simplistic, derivative and, at odd instances,
laughable about it _ this musical is a gripping entertainment of
the old school.''
</P>
<P>
   While audiences may be moved by the tale and its tragic ending,
they are also awed by the element of spectacle, with sets by John
Napier, lighting by David Hersey, sound by Andrew Bruce and
costumes by Andreane Neofitou and Suzy Benzinger. In addition to
the famous 1,700-pound helicopter (often derided as too
Disneyland), the show features an 18-foot fiberglass statue of Ho
Chi Minh and a real 1959 Cadillac, cut in half to fit backstage.
The crew is bigger than the cast, 55 to 46. There are 375 costumes,
206 props, 45 firearms, including handguns, M-16s and AK-47s. The
touring company that closed this month in Buffalo required 40
tractor-trailers.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Phantom' had been the largest automated show,'' said Jake
Bell, the show's production technical manager. `` `Saigon'
surpassed that by more than double.''
</P>
<P>
   Experiencing a matinee from behind the scenes offers a glimpse
into what it takes to make this monster of a show work its magic.
</P>
<P>
   Busy in the Wings
</P>
<P>
   The action begins a half-hour before the curtain goes up. The
last of the actors enter through the stage door, sign in and head
up to their dressing rooms to get into their wigs, makeup and
costumes.
</P>
<P>
   On the cool, cavernous stage and in the wings, the crew readies
the props and scenery. Set pieces that have been left on the stage
from the close of the show the night before _ like the runway for
the Moulin Rouge strip club in Bangkok, where the story moves in
Act II _ are moved into the wings and, in most cases, flown, which
means they are strung up on chain hoists to keep the limited wing
space as clear as possible. Act I sets and props are moved onto the
deck _ meaning the stage and wings _ including bicycles and details
for the wedding shrine: incense, candles and colorful hanging
unicorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like rotating stock in a store,'' said Andrew Douglas,
the assistant propertyman.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the tight space, large pieces of scenery must be
constantly moved around in the wings to allow others to get on and
off the stage. The towering Ho statue, for example, gets shifted
from side to side at the rear of the stage like a pendulum clock
throughout the performance. Then there are the five different beds
to keep track of: Kim 1 Bed, Kim 2 Bed, Kim 3 Bed, Kim 4 Bed and
Hotel Bed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition there are the smaller details to account for, like
the basket of lacquered vegetables (exactly what kind is a matter
of backstage debate: zucchini, okra, bitter melon?), stacks of fake
dollar bills, carts with hanging fish and trays of jewelry.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
