<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MISS-SAIGON-ERA-ART-2     08-24 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-SAIGON-ERA-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: of jewelry.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With so many sets rising and descending in the wings, backstage
can be a dicey place to be. ``Organized chaos,'' said Peter Wolf,
the first assistant stage manager. To make room for all of the
show's big bells and whistles, the theater first had to be
transformed. Jack Cennamo, 61, the head carpenter, who has been
with ``Saigon'' since it began, said he and his crew spent two
months tearing out walls, radiators and stairwells.
</P>
<P>
   During the performance, the stagehands are particularly
concerned with how the scenery moves on and off. ``It's routine,''
Cennamo said of running the show. ``But you have to pay
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 19 muslin blinds that look as if they were made of
rice paper and frame the stage. Behind them is black masking
through which scenery glides in and out on metal pylons that are
meant to evoke Vietnam. The rising of the blinds is carried out by
one of the show's three computers, which occupy a room of their
own. If a computer malfunctions and the blinds don't go up, the
pylons carrying the scenery rip through them and the stagehands
have a problem. It has happened, but not often.
</P>
<P>
   Girls Will Be Boys
</P>
<P>
   Coordinating all this, calling the cues, is Mark Dobrow, the
production stage manager, who has been with ``Saigon'' for five
years. Outside the office he shares with his assistant stage
managers _ Wolf and Lisa Buxbaum, the second assistant _ Polaroid
pictures cover the walls, featuring every cast member who has been
with the company, almost 300 over the years. Each of them signed
the show's coolie hat upon leaving.
</P>
<P>
   The role of Kim's son, Tam, has been played by 34 different 4-
and 5-year-olds, mostly girls. ``Boys, when they're 4, are not
mature enough,'' Dobrow said. ``They get bored really easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking after this child is a chaperone, or ``child wrangler,''
currently Suzanne Arnold, who stays by her charge's side throughout
the show. When Tam (played by Jenna La Salla and Gail Quintos, who
alternate performances) is offstage, Arnold entertains the child in
the dressing room with games, storybooks and toys. When Tam is
onstage, Arnold is nearby, out of sight of the audience. When, for
example, Tam is sitting on a bed (Kim 3 Bed) that is curtained off,
waiting to make her entrance, Arnold sits beside the girl, telling
her jokes or reading aloud.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is in charge of training the new Tams, who generally stay 3
to 10 months. Rather than explain the entire show to a 4-year-old,
Wolf has given each of Tam's scenes names. So when Tam first enters
by running from the bed to his mother, that is called the ``Tam Run
Game.'' When Kim shoots her cousin with a gun to protect Tam, that
is the ``Tam Bang Game.''
</P>
<P>
   The stagehands have developed joke names for some of the
grown-up scenes, too. The one in which the men enter wearing
sandals, for example, is called ``the flip-flop boys.''
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room under the stage before the show, the actors
playing soldiers get dressed in their Army gear, attaching their
microphones, draping dog tags around their necks. Ray Santos, one
of the original cast members who plays a Vietnamese customer in the
first bar scene, says he values this time the most. ``We make each
other laugh,'' he said, ``talk about things outside of the show.''
</P>
<P>
   All shows become families; this one has become a dynasty. Cast
members have left and come back, borne children, married one
another. Tams have grown up, and their younger siblings have become
Tams.
</P>
<P>
   `Here We Go Again'
</P>
<P>
   It is nearing 2 p.m.: showtime. Gradually actors wander onto the
stage to stretch and chat before the curtain goes up. Dobrow, the
stage manager, stands at his podium in front of a script with
marked cues, puts on his headset and announces in low tones:
``We're at places. Places, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he checks in with all the other departments on headsets:
automation, carpentry, electronics, sound, his fellow stage
managers, the house manager who monitors the audience. Robert
Billig, the show's musical director, who is conducting today and
visible on backstage infrared monitors, reports on the number of
substitutes in his orchestra, so the sound man knows what to
expect. ``Count is 12,'' Billig says of the subs. ``One cello, two
violins, an oboe, Asian flute ... .''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Harris, the house manager, reports, ``House is ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, the propertyman, says, ``Here we go again.''
</P>
<P>
   The show begins in Saigon, 1975, with a sequence the crew has
come to refer to as ``Dreamland,'' in which Kim and Chris meet for
the first time in a nightclub. Then the show moves to Kim's hut
(Kim 1 Bed), then on to Ho Chi Minh City, 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The actors onstage look sharp, as if they were performing these
songs and dances for the first time. But keeping it fresh is a
challenge, especially for those who have been with the show the
longest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's near impossible,'' said Alan Ariano, an
original member of the ensemble. ``I blank out sometimes and go on
automatic: `OK, did I do the laundry?' You catch yourself, have to
snap yourself out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ariano said he had supplemented his ``Saigon'' life with a
photography business, shooting theatrical head shots, and more
recently with a degree in computer graphics. Knowing that no show
lasts forever, and that there may not be another one immediately to
follow, he said he wanted something to fall back on. ``What's next
for me I don't know,'' he said. ``The nature of this business is
job insecurity.''
</P>
<P>
   The business is doubly insecure for Asian actors, who say they
must rely on productions like ``The King and I'' and ``M.
Butterfly'' to get work. In this light ``Saigon'' has been
something of a gold mine, employing actors of Filipino, Japanese,
Chinese, Vietnamese and Hawaiian descent as well as black and
Hispanic performers. ``Both the professional and the public view of
minority casting, nontraditional casting, colorblind casting has
taken a terrific leap forward,'' said Alan Wasser, the show's
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Ariano and Francis Cruz, two original cast members, attended the
same high school in Chula Vista, Calif. ``We've been part of an
elite group that's been able to work'' in the theater, Ariano said.
''I don't take that for granted.'' The Chopper Drops
</P>
<P>
   At intermission the crew prepares for the top of Act II, flying
all the scenery from Act I up on the chain hoists, bringing down
the Bangkok units. The act opens at a conference in the United
States, 1978. Then it moves to Bangkok. Then it flashes back to
Saigon when Kim remembers the American evacuation. In other words,
the Nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter is the sum of six separate automated effects. The
boom arm can swing from side to side; the cab can pitch up and
down, move side to side and rotate; the rotor on top is a nylon
rope with a rubber ball on the end that is ejected, creating the
illusion of a spinning blade. At the controls is Virgil, a robot
whose head turns as the helicopter lands.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1628EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MISS-SAIGON-ERA-3RDTA     08-24 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-SAIGON-ERA-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: helicopter lands.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the chopper settles on the helipad, it is up to Buxbaum,
one of the stage managers, to signal the live co-pilot (hidden on
the pad) to come through the helicopter, motioning the rest of the
soldiers to climb aboard. The 13 men who scramble into the
helicopter actually drop into the hollow box of the pad, lined with
two benches, handing off their rifles to a prop man as they
descend. Buxbaum holds a flashlight in her mouth to light their
way.
</P>
<P>
   Then Buxbaum reports, ``All clear'' into her headset, and the
helicopter rises into the eaves. ``It's really cool to be onstage
when the helicopter is coming down,'' said Eva Schegulla, Kim's
dresser. ``After four years I still get a kick out of it every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually this all goes smoothly. But there have been exceptions.
Like the time the helicopter didn't take off. Fortunately the
automation guys were able to run the machinery from a dial on the
encoder, as opposed to going through the computer, controlling each
effect individually. But there have been times when the helicopter
didn't work at all, and for such times there is Plan B, which
essentially amounts to blinding the audience with light and adding
a lot of smoke. Remarkably, audiences who have experienced Plan B
have apparently found it satisfying. ``They think they've seen
something,'' Dobrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially Hytner, the director, did not think the helicopter was
at all essential, though he now says he is glad it is there. ``I
thought, `Oh, we don't need this,''' he recalled. ``But it's not
necessarily about what you need.''
</P>
<P>
   Members Only
</P>
<P>
   Once the impact of the helicopter has receded, the show returns
to its human drama, as Kim encounters Chris' wife in a hotel room.
Downstairs in the green room, members of the cast settle in for the
matinee ritual of ``Asian Treat.''
</P>
<P>
   It started about 10 years ago when a dresser began bringing
fruit and drinks for the male cast members she attended to. This
mushroomed into an exclusive group of about 14 members who take
turns bringing snacks for the matinees. Only members can partake. A
sign nearby explains the rules of the Asian Food Treat Club:
``Anyone is welcome to be part of the club after having contributed
to the festivities and having passed the requirements specified by
the AFTC board of directors at the time of one's application _ just
kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   Today the menu includes crackers, brie and dip, and the members,
from the cast and crew, dive in while the non-members eye the
spread hungrily from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   A New Job
</P>
<P>
   In the hair room, John James, who has been hair supervisor for
seven years, is putting the female cast members into their blond
wigs for the ``American Dream'' number. Sparkly in their glittering
fringe and white fishnet stockings, the women congratulate Lisa
Yuen, an ensemble member, on her new job: she will be leaving
``Saigon'' to join the road company of ``The Scarlet Pimpernel.''
</P>
<P>
   This news is clearly bittersweet; cast members know they need to
figure out what to do next, and those landing jobs before the end
of the run feel lucky. But it also offers a sobering reminder to
the actors who remain that the end is near. On Nov. 2, a gala
featuring ``Saigon'' alumni will celebrate the show's 4,000th
performance. The New Year's Eve show will be the last.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're happy that she got another job, but sad that she won't
be there when it ends,'' said James. ``You can just feel that
people are pulling away emotionally, trying to find what to do next
and where to go next. Is there life after `Saigon'?''
</P>
<P>
   James said he was concerned about the future, too. ``I'm a
little worried,'' he said. ``This is the first time I've ever had
to face unemployment.''
</P>
<P>
   On to Heartbreak
</P>
<P>
   Onstage the ``American Dream'' number has its usual buoyant
effect on the audience, particularly because of the Cadillac _
carrying a woman in a Statue of Liberty crown that lights up _
which seems to float downstage on a cloud (read: dry ice). Maltby,
who collaborated on the lyrics, said that this showstopping number
goes to the heart of the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vietnam was a turning point in America's estimation of itself,
and the American dream, which hovers over the whole show, is what
was at stake,'' he said. ``America has never believed in the
American dream after that event. Prior to that we were always the
good guys, and we always won. Suddenly we were the bad guys doing
terrible things, and, worse than that, John Wayne didn't come
riding over the hill to save the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show in its essence is about that, about the American
inability to make the leap to Vietnam, to understand it and to
ultimately help.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's matinee moves to its heartbreaking conclusion,
accompanied by surging notes from the orchestra. Kitschy perhaps,
but some in the audience are crying. The cast comes on for its
curtain call, bowing between the billow and the bang of the heavy
red velvet curtain as it rises and falls. ``I think they loved
it,'' one actor quips as she comes offstage, ``and we should do it
again, tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two and half hours later _ the show runs more than two and
a half hours with intermission _ all of these people will be back
to do it all over again, almost exactly as they did it before. For
them this is work: what they wake up and do every day except
Sunday, sometimes twice a day, to feed their families, afford
vacations, pay the rent. They casually head out the stage door to
their dinner breaks, showing no trace of having weathered something
wrenching.
</P>
<P>
   The audience, on the other hand, emerges dazed, the way people
do coming out of a movie in the middle of the afternoon, taking a
moment to recover and re-enter their real lives, blinking in the
sunlight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Saigon'' is at the Broadway Theater, 1681 Broadway, at 53rd
Street, (212) 239-6200. Performances are Mondays, Tuesdays,
Thursdays and Fridays at 8 p.m.; Wednesdays and Saturdays at 2 and
8 p.m. Through Dec. 31. Tickets: $20 to $85 (last week of
performances, $47.50 to $90.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
