<HEADLINE>
`SMILING FISH AND GOAT ON FIRE': A LITTLE TOO DESPERATE TO BE
LIKED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By DAVE KEHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Directed by the newcomer Kevin Jordan, ``Smiling Fish and Goat
on Fire'' is a wistful little movie with big soulful eyes _ the
cinematic equivalent of a puppy dog. This independent production,
made on a thrifty $40,000 budget, is cute enough, but like a lot of
puppy dogs it seems a little too desperate to be liked.
</P>
<P>
   The soulful eyes in question belong to the Martini brothers,
Derick and Steven, who wrote the script with Jordan and star as
Chris and Tony Remi, siblings with radically contrasting
personalities. Chris, the elder, is sober and responsible _ an
accountant, inevitably _ whose fidgety temperament earned the
nickname Goat on Fire from his grandmother, who was half Italian
and half American Indian. ` Smiling Fish was grandma's name for
Tony, a carefree would-be actor who easily attracts women with his
lazy charm and sees no particular need to settle down.
</P>
<P>
   They live together in happy male squalor in the Los Angeles
house they inherited from their parents, passing their time with
affectionate roughhousing. But providence soon provides them with
two perfectly matched prospective mates.
</P>
<P>
   The jittery, retentive Chris becomes involved with Anna
(Rosemarie Addeo), a voluptuous, open-hearted Italian beauty who
works as an animal handler on film sets. Irresponsible Tony finds
himself unexpectedly cast as a potential head of household when he
falls in love with Kathy (Christa Miller), a single mom who has
moved to Los Angeles in hopes of finding a movie career for her
aggressively adorable daughter, Nicole (Heather Jae Marie).
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's direction emphasizes big bear hugs and heart-to-heart
conversations along with a few artificial crises to create a vague
sense of suspense. His main asset is Bill Henderson, a veteran bit
player who shines here in the somewhat stereotypical role of a
wise, elderly black sound engineer who instructs Chris in the ways
of love. It's left to Henderson to serve up the film's bromides
about romance and destiny (real love comes along only once, so
you'd better grab it), but he does his job with warmth and poise.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other American independent films, ``Smiling Fish
and Goat on Fire'' is a study in delayed development, in which
helpless, childlike men in their late 20s are rescued and redeemed
by domineering, motherly women. As romantic fantasies go, it's hard
to imagine anything more regressive.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Smiling Fish and Goat on Fire'' is rated R (Under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes strong
language and mild sex.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SMILING FISH AND GOAT ON FIRE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kevin Jordan; written by Jordan, Derick Martini and
Steven Martini; director of photography, Fred Iannone; edited by
Kevin Anderson and Ryan Rothmaier; music by Chris Horvath, Steven
Martini and Bill Henderson; produced by Derick Martini, Jordan and
Steven Martini; released by Stratosphere Entertainment. Running
time: 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Derick Martini (Chris Remi), Steven Martini (Tony Remi),
Christa Miller (Kathy), Amy Hathaway (Alison), Bill Henderson
(Clive Winter), Rosemarie Addeo (Anna) and Heather Jae Marie
(Nicole). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
