<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATFISH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CATFISH IN BLACK BEAN SAUCE': LOOKING AT ETHNIC IDENTITY WHILE
LOOKING FOR LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Catfish in Black Bean Sauce'' deals with adopted children
being raised by parents of a different race, but Chi Muoi Lo, the
writer and director, plays around with the idea in an unexpected
way. Full of twists, the film tries to exploit all the comic
streams running through its narrative, a gambit Lo isn't quite up
to seizing. (He has more ideas than he knows what to do with.) And
the movie isn't quite as much fun as it could be.
</P>
<P>
   In this case the Vietnamese-born Dwayne (Lo) and Mai (Lauren
Tom) have been brought up by African-Americans, Harold (Paul
Winfield) and Dolores (Mary Alice). Mai was 10 and her brother
considerably younger when they were taken in. The uptight Dwayne,
who feels more comfortable with his parents, is a rising star at
the bank where he works and has a beautiful African-American
girlfriend, Nina (Sanaa Lathan). He wants to propose but can't
quite muster the nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Mai has issues, as they say on daytime television; she is
consumed by the urge to find her birth mother; Mai was old enough
at their separation to remember her. Mai represents what the movie
is really about: the need to keep things real. She is constantly
searching for their mother and eventually finds her, which
complicates everyone's life, especially when Mai disrupts her
brother's proposal by breaking the news. And with ethnic emphases
in American culture shifting so quickly _ a shift ``Catfish''
recognizes _ what is real becomes more and more confusing,
especially for people like Dwayne, who doesn't know if he's coming
or going.
</P>
<P>
   Lo's mild comedy is moved along by the sanguine dignity of
Winfield and Alice. They're the kind of adoptive parents an orphan
would dream of, and they're as understanding as only screen
inventions can be. Winfield doles out generous helpings of his
chuckle, and Alice frets winsomely. Her Dolores has a mother-hen
instinct that keeps hovering and fluttering over her young.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of a race comedy outside the usual black-white
dynamic is inventive enough that the tremors of shock and
confrontation that rumble through the film do a little of the
director's work for him. He has managed an incredibly fine job of
casting. The performances by the actors playing the parents have an
air of authenticity and, in Winfield's case, authority.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie introduces farce complications so abruptly that
they seem to demand the oohs and surprised applause of a live
audience for a sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   A climactic dinner that tries to combine the ethnic cuisines of
both families is the kind of disaster that can make one feel
embarrassed for the actors; it's cringe-inducing. Yet Lo delivers
other comic points with a minimum of fuss, showing Asian youths
using hip-hop slang and the chasm that can exist between minorities
and is deepened when the wrong words are used. At times Lo relies
on a creaky mechanism to get his laughs, especially upon the
arrival of Thanh (Kieu Chin), the birth mother of Dwayne and Mai,
which comes as a big shock to Harold and Dolores.
</P>
<P>
   Dwayne is the movie's magnet for tension; he has gathered all of
it, which often seems to pull his shoulders up to neck level.
``Catfish'' is by no means a dumb movie, but it is in such a hurry
to get its laughs that it feels as stressed as Dwayne. Lo throws in
mix-ups with Dwayne's roommate, who may or may not be gay, and
racial tensions that emerge from a run-in with a policeman when he
and Nina are out. The issues are targets to be demolished, skeet in
the way of Lo's shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   He might have served his material better if he had not been
before the camera. It takes a lot of concentration to finish a film
under less arduous circumstances. But what he doesn't do is
sentimentalize any of this, a smart impulse.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Catfish in Black Bean Sauce'' is rated PG-13 (Parents
strongly cautioned). It includes profanity and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CATFISH IN BLACK BEAN SAUCE'
</P>
<P>
   Written, produced and directed by Chi Muoi Lo; in English and
Vietnamese, with English subtitles; director of photography, Dean
Lent; edited by Dawn Hoggatt; music by Stanley Smith; production
designer, Skyler Adler; released by Iron Hill Pictures and Black
Hawk Entertainment. Running time: 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Paul Winfield (Harold Williams), Mary Alice (Dolores
Williams), Chi Muoi Lo (Dwayne), Lauren Tom (Mai), Kieu Chinh
(Thanh), Sanaa Lathan (Nina), Tyler Christopher (Michael), Tzi Ma
(Vinh), George Wallace (James) and Wing Chen (Samantha).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
