<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUILTS,   SO COVETED   AND COLLECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By   WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a good man, a great antique quilt from Provence is hard to
find.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, a French antiques dealer spotted a fine old
quilt at a weekend market in Provence and tried to buy it _ just at
the very moment another man reached for it. The dealer courteously
yielded his claim. He told the man, ``You take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprised by the dealer's courtesy _ such antique French quilts
are scarce _ the man invited the dealer for coffee and introduced
himself: his name was Andre-Jean Cabanel, and he was an olive
farmer from Nimes. He invited the dealer to see his collection of
antique quilts from Provence.
</P>
<P>
   When the dealer visited Cabanel, he was the one to be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dealer told me it was the most incredible thing he'd ever
seen,'' said Ross J. Francis as he finished recounting the meeting.
Francis is the vice president for development at Brunschwig &AMP; Fils,
the American textile company that will reproduce some of the
patterns from Cabanel's quilts in its fall 2001 collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the farmer's house was filled with antique armories,
each stuffed with Provencal quilts,'' Ms. Francis said.
``Evidently, Monsieur Cabanel's mother had restored old quilts and
he had admired them when they were brought to the house when he was
a boy. He never married and had been collecting them for 40
years.''
</P>
<P>
   None were for sale, but word of their quality soon spread. The
Cabanel collection was exhibited this summer in Alsace, at the
Musee de L'Impression sur Etoffes de Mulhouse. The Museum of
Printed Textiles in Mulhouse spent the previous year and a half
restoring them. In November the show moves to the Musee de la Toile
de Jouy in Jouy en Josas, a town outside Paris near Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   Cabanel's quilts are also the subject of a book, ``Pique de
Provence'' (Edisud Publishers, 2000). One of the contributors to
the book is a dealer based in Washington, Kathryn Berenson, author
of ``Quilts of Provence'' (Henry Holt, 1996). Berenson helped to
catalog Cabanel's collection of 2,000 quilts.
</P>
<P>
   `` Cabanel is a passionate collector,'' she said. ``He even
trades truffles for quilts.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of antique quilts from Provence and neither
are like American antique quilts, which are pieced together from
scraps. The Provence quilts tend to be made of two large pieces of
whole cloth, either cotton or silk, that are sewn together with
some kind of filling element, like batting or cording, sandwiched
between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These quilts are intensely quilted and the quilting shows up
because the background is often a neutral or solid color,'' said
Laura Fisher, a Manhattan quilt dealer who owns Laura Fisher in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher specializes in American quilts, but currently she has
several 19th-century Provencal quilts for sale, at prices from $150
to $2,000 apiece. ``There was a strong needlework tradition in
Provence,'' Fisher said. ``It's like a three-dimensional sculpture
in thread.''
</P>
<P>
   Quilting goes back to prehistory. In medieval times quilted
cloth was used as insulation in winter garments as well as armor,
to protect its wearer from arrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``What distinguished the work of Provencal needle women was
their vision of the decorative possibilities inherent in these
lines of stitching,'' Berenson writes in her book. ``They developed
the ability to realize complex, minutely detailed patterns in
beautiful, well-proportioned motifs merely through the play of
light and shadow on the surface of a textile.'' Today, these quilts
are often called ``boutis.''
</P>
<P>
   In the18th and 19th centuries, Provencale women hand-stitched
their quilted bed covers with motifs inspired by the bounty of the
region: sunflowers, pomegranates, lavender, artichokes and olives
in patterns that completely fill the ground of the quilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French started printing imported cotton in about 1640,''
Berenson said. ``By the 1680s, the Marseilles women were producing
40,000 to 50,000 quilts a year for export to Germany, England,
Italy and Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that the Marseilles community was so proud of the
women's workmanship that it gave the quilts as gifts to royalty and
as tokens of appreciation. The French called these quilts
``confections'' or ``broderies de Marseille'' and refer to the
stitching as ``embroidery from within.''
</P>
<P>
   They should not be confused with pieces woven on machine-driven
looms to obtain a textured character.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan gallery Cora Ginsburg has an exceptional bouti for
sale at the moment. It is a 19th-century, all-white wedding quilt
from Marseilles, with flower baskets, artichokes, butterflies,
birds and grapes depicted on it. At 86 by 81 inches, it is also
unusually large. ``It's a museum piece,'' said Titi Halle, the
owner. The price is $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bagley Home, an antiques shop in Sag Harbor, N.Y., has a smaller
white wedding bouti, with perfect stitching. ``It has high
definition,'' Terry Bagley said. ``It's exquisite, lightweight and
warm.'' The price is $800.
</P>
<P>
   The more common bouti is a quilt made from gaily colored printed
cottons that are stitched in tight rows or diamond patterns. In the
early 17th century, the cottons were imported from India and
nicknamed ``Indiennes.'' They were hand-printed with colorful
flowers, mythic animals, exotic locales and scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Louis XIV did not want the French to import luxury goods and
drain the country's coffers, so he banned importation of Indiennes.
But he instructed his minister Jean-Baptiste Colbert to import the
best artisans and dyers to establish textile businesses in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``They produced French tapestries, laces, cottons, wools and
upholstery,'' said Berenson, who is writing a book on Colbert.
``Cardinal Mazarin is known to have had dozens of French quilted
bed covers.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding antique Provencal boutis is not easy. Berenson may have
the largest stock in the United States and can be reached by
e-mail: kwberenson(at)aol.com. In France, one of the best sources
is Michel Biehn, 7 rue des Quatre-Otages, L'Isle-sur-la-Sorgue, in
Provence (011-33-4-90-20-89-04).
</P>
<P>
   For those who fear the effects of daily wear and tear on an
antique bouti, there are now reproductions on the market. The store
Rue de France in Newport, R.I., sells contemporary French bouti
covered in a 19th-century-style cotton, which reverses from a
subtle floral pattern to a blue and tan stripe. The queen size
costs $695, and it can be machine washed and tumbled dried.
Information: (800) 777-0998, or on the Web at www.ruedefrance.com.
</P>
<P>
   The contemporary ones are very pretty, but nothing looks as
great as a bouti that has weathered 200 years of good Provencal
living.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1633EDT &QL; 
