<HEADER>
A1260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-PHOTOGRAPHY-NYT &LR;      08-24 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PHOTOGRAPHY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT MAKES NEW YORK `THE' CITY AND NOT `A' CITY? 
</HEADLINE>
   By VICKI GOLDBERG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 17th-century poet said that God made the first
garden and the first city. But as it turned out, humans gave up the
garden and were never quite so happy again. Eventually they moved
to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   By that time cities had a bad rap. Shelley thought hell was a
city rather like London. Not long after he said so, photography
came along and tried to save the sinking reputation of the urban
environment. Until late in the 19th century, when social reform
became a big issue, urban photography came mainly to praise rather
than to bury, and there was quite a lot of it around, pronouncing
black and white eulogies.
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows Manhattan has been photographed ad infinitum and
ad nauseam, from its towering buildings to its cowering homeless,
its intemperate subways to its decorous penthouses, Liberty to the
residents at Rikers. It's still going on. Tourists are focusing on
the Disney and Warner Brothers stores, professionals on everything
else.
</P>
<P>
   Everything. If you want to know how far afield a serious
photographer will go in this city, you can get some idea at the
Museum of the City of New York, where ``New York Now 2000:
Contemporary Work in Photography'' offers 130 photographs of New
York City and New Yorkers, taken by 41 photographers. The
exhibition was selected by Bob Shamis, curator of prints and
photographs, with the assistance of an advisory board, and is the
initial presentation of a new program ``embracing cutting-edge
approaches to creatively interpreting the distinctive urban
experience of the City,'' according to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Distinctively urban these photographs are, cutting-edge maybe.
They are more about cities than about ``the City,'' more about
photography than either. Wherever cities grow, architectural
geometries, ethnic types and rushing citizens like those on view
here will pop up. They may not be as bleached and blurred and oddly
cut off as those in the wide range of approaches in this show,
which includes photographs of collaged engravings, scenes
constructed with photographs of collaged engravings, scenes
constructed with mannequins, daguerreotypes and stereographs.
</P>
<P>
   A nice clutch of good pictures stands out here between the usual
numbers of boring ones, and a surprisingly large complement of
relatively unknown photographers is a bonus. Though the artistic
and experimental work here generally outclasses the documentary,
old-fashioned straight photography still delivers the old-fashioned
goods: Stanley Greenberg's film-noir image of a city tunnel; Andrew
Moore's morose interiors of old theaters; Jim Dow's opulent color
image of the University Club library; Mitch Epstein's color
photograph of two adults and two children, dwarfed and made pale by
an enormous, black and white billboard of a man reclining in his
Calvin Klein skivvies. Even that image, advertising being what it
is, might turn up someplace other than the glitzy, grungy, overripe
Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   New York is a problem (in more ways than one). So many
photographers have gotten drunk on this city's high-proof
distillation of urban experience that the subject ought to have
been used up long ago. But there are no used-up subjects (though
some are tired and some have become icons, and daunting); there are
only subjects that require rethinking and inventiveness.
</P>
<P>
   A few adventurous souls run clever riffs on the trite and true.
Thanks to Abelardo Morell's camera obscura, the upper part of the
Empire State Building and its spire lie upside down in a graceful
diagonal across a bed, while a broad swath of the city's skyline
hangs down from the top of the bedroom. Susan Wides even manages to
see the Flatiron Building with a fresh eye by paying off-kilter
homage to Stieglitz and Steichen. Both of them photographed,
memorably, the building's majestic triangular prow seen through a
bare-branched tree. Wides represents the Flatiron in strict and
nearly rectangular profile, in color, tilting crazily above a
scraggly clump of trees.
</P>
<P>
   One photographer, Katharina Bosse, finds a subject that will be
new to most people, if perhaps not unique to this city: rooms
rented to those who want to live out their sexual fantasies. One is
an operating room, entirely icy blue with rubber head masks and an
enema bag, and one a luxurious boudoir that the renters presumably
could not afford on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the photographers close in on details that might be
anywhere outside a rain forest, or liberally court blur that
effectively erases identity, or fiddle with the print till the
color wavers or the image swoons. Some of these photographs are
fine: Sophie Rivera's sharply composed, gritty viaduct painters;
Don Burmeister's pillars and sky in saturated oranges and
turquoise; James Fee's indistinct image of a blimp in a sky so full
of photographic imperfections it looks like the end of the world;
Vera Lutter's otherworldly camera obscura negative of a Pepsi sign;
Maria Theresia Litschauer's decaying buildings amid wrenchingly red
skies and rivers.
</P>
<P>
   These are urban all right _ not a hay wain in sight _ but they
don't look a lot like the New York or even the urban experience
that most people meet on the sidewalks. These and other
photographers in the show _ worried that New York has been done to
death, worried that photography has been done to death, threatened
by computers and impugned by philosophical types _ play around with
techniques, unusual composition and presentation in a dogged effort
to ``make it new.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have photographic subjects, some have photographic pretexts
_ in this case both of these are in New York _ and some are more
interested in what they can do to change, extend, disguise or
radicalize the medium. New York being close at hand, their cameras
blink at it.
</P>
<P>
   Photography has always had the dual ability to present an
equivalent to everyday experience or a camera experience that isn't
ordinarily encountered without a camera. Equivalents are the images
that make you think, ``Yes, that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   A camera experience, still dependent on what light, a lens and
film or electronic impulses deliver, is another way to look at the
familiar, a magnified detail, say, that no human eyes could see in
rectangular format, or an action stopped faster than the unaided
eye could manage. Both experiences can enrich accepted ideas by
making us suddenly recognize scenes, things, details that we hadn't
noticed before.
</P>
<P>
   There is a third kind of photographic experience that has been
around for some time and has become ever more common as
photographers grapple with the threats to photography's reputation:
a purely photographic experience, dependent on the method used
(camera obscura, for instance) or the process, or the darkroom, and
producing an image of something that doesn't quite exist outside of
the image itself. For that, any old reality will suffice, even New
York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
