<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bristol among the best tracks for excitement
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If NASCAR fans were allowed to go to only one race per year,
many would pick this weekend's night race at Bristol. It is the
hardest ticket to acquire in NASCAR, and provides an unmatched
atmosphere for racing.
</P>
<P>
   Bruton Smith's Speedway Motorsports Inc. purchased ``The World's
Fastest Half-Mile'' in 1996 and launched a massive expansion
program which increased seating and parking.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's marquee track might be Lowe's Motor Speedway outside
Charlotte, but Bristol is his little jewel tucked away in the
foothills on the Tennessee-Virginia border.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Thunder Valley,'' Bristol Motor Speedway thrills the
fans in seats totally encircling the track.
</P>
<P>
   Despite incredible lap speeds of more than 120 mph on this
high-banked, half-mile oval, the drivers still have enough room to
put on a side-by-side show.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Bristol, here are the best tracks in Winston Cup racing
for side-by-side racing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta: In November 1997, Geoffrey Bodine ran a lap of 197
mph to christen the new configuration and asphalt at Atlanta Motor
Speedway. Three years later, a ``second groove'' has developed,
allowing much better grip for the cars. March's race produced
constant wheel-to-wheel action, including 30 lead changes with 17
different drivers. Then there was the unforgettable 10-lap duel at
the end: Dale Earnhardt beat Bobby Labonte by a bumper in one of
the closest finishes in NASCAR history.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Martinsville: Opened in 1947 under the direction of Clay
Earles, this half-mile oval is one of the oldest tracks on the
circuit. It has become known for its tight racing through the
years. Rarely, if ever, does a car leave a Martinsville race
without a bunch of dinks and dents from trading paint with
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Richmond: This 0.75-mile, D-shaped facility has been called
the short track that ``thinks it's a superspeedway.'' As short
tracks go, this one is wide enough to allow an overload of
side-by-side racing. At times, you'll even see three-wide action on
the sweeping front stretch. RJR Sports Marketing thinks enough of
the track to put its ``Winston No Bull Million'' on the line at
Richmond on Sept. 9. Both Richmond events are at night, when the
cars glisten under the lights and appear to be moving faster than
they do in the day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Talladega: If NASCAR ran on tracks like Talladega and Bristol
each week, there would be consistent sellouts and double-digit TV
ratings. But NASCAR makes everyone involved settle for four visits
to these two facilities each calendar year. Even the most dull
Talladega race is better than most conducted on NASCAR's beloved
flat-track superspeedways. Despite the constant griping about
restrictor-plate racing, everyone still holds their breath watching
the unbelievable moves at Talladega Superspeedway during the two
500-milers each season.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the worst tracks in Winston Cup for side-by-side
racing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Daytona: History proves there is no way Daytona should be
ranked as one of the toughest tracks for passing. Based on the two
points races and the Twin 125s _ which had zero lead changes _ a
case can be made that NASCAR's ``shock package'' was a disaster at
their crown jewel facility in Florida. Both Daytona races, most
notably the season-opening 500, were extremely dull. Changes must
be made.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Indianapolis: The Brickyard provides plenty of history, and
that came in handy for the 350,000 fans that filled the 2.5-mile
layout earlier this month. They had plenty of time to reminisce
about past events. Those memories, and the engine noise, were about
the only things to keep a collective snore from engulfing
Indianapolis. The ``race'' featured Rusty Wallace leading 110 of
160 laps and Bobby Labonte driving away into the sunset _ or
raindrops _ in the last 15 laps.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Homestead: NASCAR loves superspeedway flat tracks. They must
because they still schedule races at Homestead, Loudon, and
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pocono: When asking drivers about the toughest tracks for
passing, many, including Jeff Gordon, say the infamous Pennsylvania
tri-oval needs to be nuked. Ironically, Pocono had two of the most
exciting races of the season: Jeremy Mayfield bumping Dale
Earnhardt out of the way in the first event, and Mayfield blowing a
tire with a half-lap to go and being passed by Rusty Wallace. The
same excitement, however, wasn't there for the other 199 laps in
each race.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Road courses: Get the hook. The only side-by-side action
you'll see at Sonoma or Watkins Glen is when a driver is being set
up to be passed. There is no way to run a competitive, door-to-door
lap at either of these tracks. Drivers who lose their patience
often end up in the ``kitty litter'' or ``gravel pit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
