<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fights few on circuit amid pressures to achieve
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the recent argument between Tony Stewart and Jeff
Gordon, NASCAR drivers seem to have fewer confrontations than other
professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 12 months, there have been four major confrontations
between Winston Cup drivers _ three involving Stewart. By all
accounts, with the countless bumps and wrecks, there should've have
been more.
</P>
<P>
   John Andretti, who drives for Petty Enterprises, explained some
of the reasons for non-confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it's a very emotional sport, we don't represent
just ourselves,'' Andretti said. ``We represent the companies that
are involved, from the people who sponsor our cars, to the cars we
drive, to the tires we're on _ you name it. So for starters, we
represent a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``But above and beyond all that, we also have a lot of people
who follow this sport, and I think because of that, our goal should
be to make racing like the ultimate role model.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti earned rave reviews at Martinsville last September by
maintaining his composure when he was wrecked by Stewart while
racing among the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the same race, Stewart had twice spun out Irwin, who
got revenge by bumping the No. 20 Pontiac into the wall. Stewart
slowly climbed out of the mangled car, and waited for Irwin to
circle the track. Stewart threw a series of left-handed jabs toward
Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Stewart has had separate run-ins with Gordon and
Robby Gordon. The other major argument came last May between Steve
Park and Joe Nemechek after The Winston all-star exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR will race this weekend at Bristol, where Dale Earnhardt
bumped leader Terry Labonte out of the way with a half lap to go.
There was no confrontation between the drivers after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the guys realize it's easier to talk about it than it is
to fight about it,'' driver Rick Mast said. ``Most everybody has
come through the ranks of the Saturday night bullrings, and you've
been through that stuff. You've learned how to control your
emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who has been criticized by fans, finally is talking
this week about Watkins Glen. He claims he has no anger toward
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't agree with what happened, but I'm not mad about
it,'' Stewart said. ``You can't dwell on things like that in our
sport and retain a competitive edge on everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, Labonte return to the scene of `the bump'
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Carvell
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   The most talked-about event of the 1999 season was last August's
Bristol race, where Dale Earnhardt Sr. bumped leader Terry Labonte
out of the way with a half-lap to go. The crowd, which had cheered
heartily for ``The Intimidator'' only several laps earlier, turned
on Earnhardt when he climbed out of his car in victory lane. He was
showered with a loud chorus of boos for several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Fans shouldn't expect to see a duel between the two drivers
again on Saturday night. Labonte is just getting used to steering a
car again after missing two races with vertigo. Labonte was asked
about last year's finish this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bristol is always an exciting place to run at,'' Labonte said.
``Last year didn't turn out quite as good as I'd hoped it would for
me, but we had a great run and a good car. I hope our car will be
as good this year as it was then.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can do that and be in the position to win, that's what
we're hoping for. And yes, I heard 'em (boos for Dale Earnhardt)
like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's predicting the Winston Cup champ for 2000
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Carvell
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   With 12 races remaining in the 2000 Winston Cup season, it's
time to start looking at which driver has the best shot at winning
the championship. Here's our attempt at handicapping the chase for
the Winston Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1. Bobby Labonte: Labonte, who drives the No. 18 Pontiac, has
been nearly bullet-proof during the first two-thirds of the season.
But history suggests that he is due bad luck, and it could come
Saturday night at Bristol, the half-mile facility nestled in the
Appalachian Mountains on the Tennessee-Virginia border. Odds on
winning Winston Cup, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  2. Dale Jarrett: Jarrett, the defending Winston Cup champion,
slowly has crept back into contention for his second title. Dale
Earnhardt's first-half success was a blessing in disguise. It
deflected much media attention away from his title defense. He has
one victory this year _ the Daytona 500 _ but don't bet against him
winning at least one more race and possibly his second title in
November. Odds on winning Cup, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3. Dale Earnhardt: Earnhardt, a seven-time Winston Cup
champion, looks like he's starting to run out of steam. He can look
back on two races that have derailed his hopes of sitting at the
head table at the Waldorf-Astoria in December. At Pocono last
month, he blew a tire while running second; at Watkins Glen, he
crashed on his own while again running second. Odds on winning Cup,
15-1.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  4. Jeff Burton: When Burton gets on a roll, it means serious
trouble for the competition. But Burton seems to be streaky, rather
than consistent. Remember how he had the field covered early at
Atlanta in March only to demolish his No. 99 Ford while leading?
You know he'd love to have that race to run again. Odds on winning
Cup, 20-1.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  5. Rusty Wallace: Wallace will break out a new Ford Penske
chasis on Saturday evening with the Harley Davidson paint scheme.
He hopes to ``hog'' the top spot on the leaderboard at his favorite
track, Bristol. He is the real sleeper in the title chase and has
huge momentum. A Bristol victory, coupled with bad luck from Bobby
Labonte, could propel this Missouri native closer to the title.
Odds on winning Cup 15-1.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  6. Tony Stewart: Stewart and Wallace are the only three-time
winners in 2000. But the early wreck at Michigan last Sunday put a
dent in Stewart's title hopes. This temperamental driver will now
race to win and let the chips fall where they may. Odds on winning
Cup, 50-1.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  7. Ricky Rudd: It is very difficult for a first year team to
compete for a title, much less win a race. Rudd has come very close
to winning. He and crew chief Michael McSwain seem to be meshing.
Look for Rudd to win a race and have an outside shot at a top-5
finish in the points race. Odds on winning Cup, 125-1.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  8. Ward Burton: At midseason, Ward Burton looked like a
serious title contender after a solid top-10 run at the Pepsi 400
in Daytona. But the team has hit the skids after being second or
third in points for a good portion of the first half of the year.
Burton won at Darlington in March and would love another victory to
stop the free-fall. Odds on winning Cup, 200-1.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  9. Mark Martin: Many consider Martin, a Daytona Beach, Fla.,
resident, the best active driver to not own a Winston Cup
championship. He'll have to wait until 2001 for another shot. An
unlikely victory at Martinsville appeared to have him set for a
title run, but that was followed with inconsistent finishes
including consecutive 43rd place results at Pocono and Indy. He is
clinging to the top-10. Odds on winning Cup 250-1.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  10. Jeff Gordon: It doesn't take a genius to realize that the
chemistry between Gordon and new crew chief Robbie Loomis isn't
there yet. Many forget that his original Rainbow Warrior pit crew
members bolted during the 1999 offseason and jumped to the No. 88
team. Gordon is looking ahead to 2001 as he finishes his
disappointing season. Odds on winning Cup 300-1.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte puts focus on each race, not trophy
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Carvell
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte remains the leader of the Winston Cup points
standings, but he is in no mood to celebrate. Labonte says that
will only happen if he is still No. 1 after the season-ending NAPA
500 on Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to every weekend not worrying about (the
championship),'' Labonte said. ``We worry more about that race each
weekend. We don't bring it up at the shop or around my house until
we get to the racetrack, and everybody around us brings it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``One bad day is going to make it bad for us, so we can't think
about it like that. We just think about trying to make every race
as good as possible. It's not at the point that we get down to '13,
12, 11, 10' (races to go). It's going to get down to '3, 2, 1' and
maybe the last one, so we're just concentrating on each weekend and
looking forward to every race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know if we have those great days and finish in the top five
(every week), we should be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte is taking the same low-key approach of contending for
Winston Cup title as his older brother, Terry Labonte, a two-time
circuit champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just kind of taking it one race at a time and going
out and doing the best that they can,'' Terry said about his
brother. ``I think they're really approaching the thing right, and
they're having to run hard because it's close.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't gotten to a position where they can ease back and
take it easy and be cautious. They've got to go out and run hard
every week. That's what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Craftsman Truck update
</P>
<P>
   Greg Biffle has a commanding 190-point advantage in the
standings of the Craftsman Truck Series with five races remaining.
Each event, Biffle will have to choose between chasing after the
checkered flag or driving safely for points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be smart about what we are doing,'' Biffle said.
``Our goal as a team and mine as a driver is to win the
championship. That doesn't mean that we aren't going to still try
and win races.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we really have to think about every decision we
make as a team and as a driver.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the remaining races on the 2000 Craftsman Truck Series
season:
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 27 _ Chicago 175, Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 7 _ Richmond 200, Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 22 _ Dover 200, Dover, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 13 _ O'Reilly 300, Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 28 _ California 200, Fontana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
