<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1263 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-TAO-STEVE0825-     08-24 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TAO-STEVE0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ladies man's patter boosts film
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Listen closely and feel free to take notes at
``The Tao of Steve,'' in which a pudgy, philosophy-spouting, pot
smoker reveals his secrets for becoming a chick magnet. Who says
movies can't be entertaining and educational?
</P>
<P>
   The Steve of the title does not refer to the movie's unkempt,
underachieving Zen master, whose name is Dex. It refers instead to
his pop icons of cool _ Steve McQueen, Steve McGarrett (''Hawaii
Five-O'') and Steve Austin (''The Six Million Dollar Man'') _ who
attract woman with their haughty air of indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Dex (the teddy bear-like Donal Logue, padded out to
Falstaffian proportions) has lardered on the pounds since high
school and made little of his life, he still has his way with the
opposite sex. The problem is he has never been in love. It has no
place in his philosophy, you see, and when it strikes, he is
knocked for a seismic loop.
</P>
<P>
   His troubles begin, or perhaps his good fortune, at his 10-year
high school reunion, when he is introduced to Syd (Greer Goodman,
who also co-wrote the script). She resents the fact that he does
not remember her, and we later learn that they had a one-night
stand in college while Dex was in an alcoholic haze. Still, from
the way they verbally spar, can quote from the same books and
continue to get on each other's nerves, even a Stu _ the nerdy
opposite of a Steve _ could tell they have a future together.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Dex-Syd scenes, which form the heart of the movie,
``The Tao of Steve'' is at its best dawdling with Dex and his
circle of slacker friends. They play Frisbee, golf and poker and
vegetate, all the while listening to Dex's mantras for success in
sexual conquests. The remarkable thing is that this exploration of
the arrested development male psyche comes from first-time
filmmaker Jenniphr Goodman, who fortunately directs a lot better
than she spells.
</P>
<P>
   She also wrote the film with sister Greer and Duncan North, the
real life model for Dex. The writing is better than the execution,
which has a few too many awkward moments and amateurish edits.
Still, the character of Dex and his cerebral, if misguided, patter
are enough to make this otherwise standard romantic comedy stand
out from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The story is set in Santa Fe _ Syd is there as a guest set
designer for the renowned Santa Fe Opera _ and the visual beauty of
the area is captured as well as possible on an independent film's
budget. At one point Syd invites Dex on a hiking and camping
expedition in the New Mexico hills. Gamely, then ruefully, he
agrees, and even when the movie veers into sitcom shtick, it has a
point to make and leads to a new plateau in their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Syd must necessarily come off as more mature than Dex _ who
wouldn't? _ but that leaves Goodman stiffer and less at ease than
the relaxed, Buddha-like Logue. Whether he is anything like Dex, he
wears the character as comfortably as he wears his shabby wardrobe,
while Goodman frequently looks like she is acting. Nevertheless,
however improbable the match, you will probably be rooting for the
two of them to get together by the fade-out, and that is all ``The
Tao of Steve'' asks of you.
</P>
<P>
   Those that want to take home more can scribble down bits of
Dex's philosophy (''Women want sex 15 minutes after men do. Hold
out for 20 minutes. She'll chase you for five.'') You might even
give it a shot, but its success is only guaranteed in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   THE TAO OF STEVE
</P>
<P>
   2 _ 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   Rated R: Language, drug use, sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 28 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An amiable romantic comedy stands out from the
crowd for its comic philosophical dialogue and a big teddy
bear-like performance from Donal Logue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
