<HEADER>
A1267 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-OPPORTUNISTS08     08-24 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-OPPORTUNISTS0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WALKEN IN SENSIBLE SHOES: Fine performances save would-be caper
flick
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It has been such a long time since
Christopher Walken has played anything close to a mentally balanced
character, that we watch and wait now for the expected signs of
psychosis whenever he is on screen.
</P>
<P>
   In the gritty working-class Queens drama ``The Opportunists,''
he isn't creepy or crazy, just a decent guy named Vic Kelly, who
tries to escape his criminal past and fails miserably at it.
</P>
<P>
   This is a satisfying change of pace for Walken, given the
opportunity to flex different acting muscles, but his vehicle
sputters and lurches just like the cars Kelly tries unsuccessfully
to repair.
</P>
<P>
   The problem seems to lie with first-time feature director Myles
Connell, who wrote a credible, involving, if naggingly familiar
screenplay, but never establishes a filming rhythm that would
propel the story forward with dramatic tension. Not every heist
picture has to move with the velocity of ``Gone in 60 Seconds,''
and ``The Opportunists'' does dawdle productively on some
well-observed character details. Nevertheless, a little more
momentum would have helped the movie a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Take it as a character study masquerading as a caper flick.
Kelly is an intriguing, deeply flawed figure who plied his break-in
skills once too often, then turned himself in and did prison time.
He voluntarily gave back the stolen money after his family left him
because, as he puts it, he no longer had anyone to spend it on.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 20 years later, he is trying to mend his relationship with
his grown daughter (Vera Farmiga), support his aged aunt (Anne
Pitoniak) in a Catholic nursing home and do the right thing by his
adoring girlfriend Sally (Cyndi Lauper). But Vic is an inept auto
mechanic, falling behind in rent payments and starting to bounce
checks. As he begins to realize, ``the regular citizen thing is not
going so well,'' and one more heist looks inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card in this particular deck is Michael (Peter
McDonald), a scrappy Irish bloke who turns up claiming to be Vic's
distant cousin, yearning to become an apprentice criminal under his
tutelage. Impetuous and impatient, he proves even more of a
screw-up than Vic and the combination of the two of them is
disasterous.
</P>
<P>
   Dilligently, Vic gets back his safe-cracking skills, training to
shave time off his tumbler manipulations to beat the alarm at a
shady security operation where two nervous acquaintances work as
guards. The race against the clock of the break-in does briefly
quicken the pulse, but those looking for a full-fledged caper
thriller had better look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   It works far better as a morality tale of second chances and
redemption, sold by Walken's somber performance as the likeable
reluctant crook. He underplays with such seeming effortlessness,
even as he gives some truly eccentric line readings. Still, it is
refreshing to be reminded what a skilled actor he is after so many
years of off-the-wall scenery chewing.
</P>
<P>
   Dubliner McDonald lends the tale just the right edginess,
helping to keep the caper's outcome in doubt, and Farmiga (of the
unpersuasive ``Return to Paradise'') has some appealing moments
here, even though her character is frustratingly sketchy. Even
Lauper comes off well in her first dramatic role, so perhaps
Connell deserves some credit for drawing so many fine performances
from his cast.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is enough to keep ``The Opportunists'' from being
ignored remains to be seen. It has an intriguing, fragile human
quality, even as it dashes most expectations of the genre it seems
to want to be mistaken for.
</P>
<P>
   THE OPPORTUNISTS
</P>
<P>
   Rated R: Language, minimal violence
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 29 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A morality character study masquerading as a caper
flick, with one of Walken's best, most normal performances in
years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
