<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ In a clear warning to the
Palestinians to compromise on Jerusalem and other issues, Prime
Minister Ehud Barak said Thursday that he was prepared if the peace
talks fail to invite the right-wing Likud party to join in a
national unity government and even to appoint Ariel Sharon, the
hawkish former army general who is Likud's leader, as foreign
minister. A month after the Camp David peace talks ended with wide
differences over Jerusalem between Barak and Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, Barak's suggestion appeared to be putting
Arafat on notice that Israel could back away from its offer of a
limited foothold in Jerusalem for the Palestinians and establish a
government that, with Likud at its heart, would almost certainly
put a break on any peace deal that involved major concessions to
the Palestinians. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RELIGION (Beijing) _ One hundred and thirty evangelical
Christians, including three visiting Americans on a religious
mission, were arrested in central China on Wednesday as they
attended a revival, according to a human rights monitor and the
Americans' pastor in California. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
