<P>
   RACE-EDUCATION-GAP (Undated) _ A 30-year gap between test scores
of black and white students that had begun to narrow in the 1980s
has continued to widen in the past few years, according to new
national test results released Thursday, dealing a discouraging
blow to increasing efforts across the country to raise the
achievement of minority students. Most perplexing, officials said,
is that the gap has opened the widest among children of the most
well-educated parents, where average scores by white students
remained relatively steady while those of blacks fell back toward
the lower achievement of the late 1970s. By Kate Zernicke.
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-PARKS (Anchorage) _ Former President Jimmy Carter said
his eleventh-hour decision in 1980 to protect millions of acres of
land in Alaska, doubling the national park acreage, was his
proudest achievement. Alaskans burned him in effigy. But Alaska has
changed and tourism is booming. With Carter here to celebrate the
20th anniversary of the Alaska Lands Act, the locals are welcoming
him warmly. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
