<HEADER>
A1270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CREW-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-24 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREW-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CREW': THE CRIME OF THE ANCIENT MARINARAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Ju know what I ang? A clee-tchay.'' So says Raul Ventana
(Miguel Sandoval), the Hispanic drug kingpin who is the designated
heavy in Michael Dinner's slapdash, hyperactive new mobster comedy.
``Ju know what happens to clee-tchays?'' Ventana asks his minions,
who look grateful to be back at work after the long hiatus of
``Miami Vice.'' ``They die.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, amigo. ``The Crew,'' with morbid relish, takes
defibrillator paddles to pop-culture archetypes and situations that
should have been allowed to expire peacefully long ago. The
inexplicable success of ``Analyze This'' and the unlikely, richly
merited triumph of ``The Sopranos'' seem to have illuminated dim
light bulbs over the heads of Barry Sonnenfeld and Barry Josephson,
the film's producers, and the good people at Touchstone Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ventana delivers his commentary, we have seen a
parade of dark suits, fedoras and cigars, strippers doing pole
dances, bodies in the trunks of cars, and a cascade of ethnic
stereotypes as vivid as third-generation photocopies of an old Don
Rickles routine.
</P>
<P>
   A carefully edited one, to be sure. ``The Crew'' pokes fun at
Latinos, Italian-Americans, Jews and the elderly but leaves blacks
and gays alone; or rather, it tries to have affectionate fun with
the ways its selected target groups have been made fun of in past
movies and television shows. And some of it is, I'll admit, pretty
funny.
</P>
<P>
   The script was written by Barry Fanaro, screenwriter of the
Farrelly brothers' ``Kingpin,'' which will someday be acknowledged
as a masterpiece of 1990s neo-lowbrow American cinema. ``The Crew''
occasionally pops to life with a priceless throwaway line (as when
the Brothers Grimm are referred to as ``a couple of Nazi goniffs'')
or an inspired set piece (like the sequence in which Ventana's
senile and extravagantly wrinkled father breaks out of the nursing
home, or the ``Goodfellas'' parody in which geriatric mobsters try
to bribe their way into the early-bird special at a Miami
delicatessen).
</P>
<P>
   But Fanaro also wrote more than 100 episodes of ``The Golden
Girls,'' which is more to the point. Like that redoubtable show,
``The Crew'' aims to be a piece of genial old-timers' slapstick. It
follows a gang of New Jersey wiseguys _ seen in their prime in an
opening sequence set in 1968 _ into unhappy, impoverished and
sexually frustrated old age. Except for Bobby Bartellemeo (Richard
Dreyfuss), who delivers a voice-over narration studded with
``mooks,'' ``fahzools,'' and ``fuhgeddaboudits,'' each member is
defined by a colorful wiseguy nickname and a single personality
trait. Bats (Burt Reynolds) has a violent temper; Mouth (Seymour
Cassel) never talks; and the Brick (Dan Hedaya) is, as Bobby puts
it, ``about 10 Lucky Strikes short of a pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedaya deserves credit for bringing his dingbat character to
comic life, the way he did as Nick Tortelli, his recurring
scuzzball on ``Cheers.'' And Dreyfuss works hard to be both wiseguy
and mensch, though his trademark intelligence is stymied by the
dumbness of the script.
</P>
<P>
   But what in creation possessed the filmmakers to cast Reynolds
as a mafioso, other than the fact that once, before much of the
current film audience was born, he was hailed as the next Brando?
In any case Reynolds, who has often mistaken lack of effort for
effortlessness, sits around looking bored, except when he is
knocked unconscious. The gag is that when he wakes up, Bats hatches
the gang's next brilliant scheme. The movie seems to have been made
by a similar method.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Crew'' is cobbled together in desperate obedience to the
widespread Hollywood fallacy that the more plot a movie has, the
more people will like it. Thus in addition to nonsensical capers
involving phony rub-outs, the accidental crossing of Raul Ventana,
and the crew's entanglement with a buxom stripper named Ferris
(Jennifer Tilly), there is the sentimental contrivance of Bobby's
search for his lost daughter and some tired banter between two
Miami detectives (Jeremy Piven and Carrie-Anne Moss) who are also
ex-lovers, one of whom just happens to be ...
</P>
<P>
   Just forget about it, OK?
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``The Crew'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes lecherous shots of women in bathing suits,
some relatively tame gangster profanity and violence that tries to
remain within the bounds of silliness.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE CREW'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Dinner; written by Barry Fanaro; director of
photography, Juan Ruiz-Anchia; edited by Nicholas Smith; music by
Steve Bartek; production designer, Peter Larkin; produced by Barry
Sonnenfeld and Barry Josephson; released by Touchstone Pictures.
Running time: 88 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Richard Dreyfuss (Bobby Bartellemeo), Burt Reynolds (Bats
Pistella), Dan Hedaya (the Brick Donatelli), Seymour Cassel (Mouth
Donato), Carrie-Anne Moss (Detective Olivia Neal), Jennifer Tilly
(Ferris Lowenstein), Lainie Kazan (Pepper Lowenstein), Miguel
Sandoval (Raul Ventana) and Jeremy Piven (Detective Steve
Menteer). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
