<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1271 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-CENTAM-$ADV27-     08-24 1523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CENTAM-$ADV27-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: in 2nd to last graf, corrects name to read 'Corado'
 &HT;    MEXICO SEES FLOOD OF CENTRAL AMERICAN IMMIGRANTS HEADING FOR
AMERICAN DREAM
 &HT;    (1100&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With chart information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Tapachula is a city in
Mexico's southern Chiapas state, about 18 miles from the Guatemalan
border.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAPACHULA, Mexico _ Baby-faced Sonia Marlene Lopez, 15, said she
was willing to do anything if she could just get to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wash dishes, clean hotel rooms, take care of babies,'' the
teenager from El Salvador said earnestly, her eyes as wide as
saucers.
</P>
<P>
   But Lopez never made it to her dream cities of Houston or El
Paso. Instead she, her sister and a cousin _ all high school girls
_ were unceremoniously dumped just inside Mexico by a smuggler
they'd paid to take them north. And it wasn't long before
immigration authorities in Chiapas, Mexico's southernmost state,
picked them up and put them in a detention center here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parents knew we were doing this. Our grandmother gave us
money,'' said Claudia Lopez, 16, who huddled nervously with the
other girls inside a cell, waiting for deportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going somewhere where with jobs we could
afford to buy food,'' Claudia said. ``We didn't know this would
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   While United States officials wage their own battle against
illegal crossings, Mexican officials in Chiapas _ which borders
Guatemala _ say they're grappling with a 30 percent surge in
seizures of Central Americans and other illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   More than 54,000 migrants were caught just in Chiapas here
between January and June, compared to about 37,700 during the same
period last year. The vast majority are Central Americans on their
way to the United States to escape low wages and societies still
devastated by civil war and 1998's Hurricane Mitch, according to
Javier Jimenez, regional director of the Mexican National Migration
Institute here, in this a city on the Guatemalan border.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a sense of urgency about them,'' Jimenez said. ``The
U.S. economy is what offers them hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Smugglers charging thousands of dollars are getting into the
action, leading migrants on increasingly perilous journeys in their
quest to reach the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In April, seven people died after 250 migrants were found locked
inside suffocating train cargo holds in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   In May, authorities found 309 illegal immigrants jammed inside a
convoy of four trucks traveling from Chiapas to Matamoros, on
Mexico's northern border. The migrants, ten of whom had to be
hospitalized, said their goal was to reach Brownsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On July 22, Guatemalans bound for the United States, including
two children, drowned when a motorboat they were in capsized off
the coast of Oaxaca, another southern Mexican state.
</P>
<P>
   A greater number of South Americans are also traveling through
southern Mexico en route to America.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere in the United States,'' was the dream destination of
Luis Cayano, a 23-year-old Peruvian who'd been locked inside a
one-room holding cell here for more than a month, awaiting news on
who would pay for him to be deported to Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Cayano, who has some college education, said he spent several
thousand dollars on bus fare and bribes to corrupt officials in
various countries as he made his way north. His mother had used her
house as collateral for a loan from a bank and he felt responsible
now to somehow get to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a dream of going to the United States, you have to
give it a go,'' Cayano said. ``We are willing to risk a lot to get
there, even our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Among the Central Americans flooding Mexico, Salvadoran
Francisco Antonio Ramirez wanted to get to Los Angeles, where he
heard he could make more money than he ever imagined. Mexican
officials caught him at a bus station near Tapachula.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do a cost-benefit analysis, it's probably worth more
for me to try to get to the United States than stay at my job in El
Salvador,'' the 26-year-old father of two said.
</P>
<P>
   On the verge of tears, he said he'd saved and borrowed about
US$900 for his journey from his home in San Miguel, El Salvador.
Back home, in a country rife with crime, he was earning the
equivalent of US$110 a month repairing highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pittance,'' he said. ``We lived through a terrible war.
And now what little you earn gets stolen by criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Honduran Carlos Castillo, 18, said he earned so little at a
T-shirt assembly plant back home _ about US$40 a week _ that his
family also thought it worth him trying his luck at getting to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad situation in Honduras,'' said Castillo, a
fresh-faced youth who was placed in the holding cell with the
startled look of a deer caught in headlights.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was hoping to join his uncle somewhere in Texas, but
he couldn't remember exactly where. He was supposed to call and get
the name of the city once he had traveled deeper into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch, which hit Central America almost two years ago,
left its worst path of destruction in Honduras, Castillo's
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 people were killed and 70-to-80 percent of
agricultural production was destroyed, along with 33,000 homes. The
U.S. government offered more than $103 million in emergency food
and disaster recovery. About 10 percent of another $291 million to
rebuild roads, health infrastructure and businesses was spent by
this June, according to the U.S. Agency for International
Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tragedy. We endured non-stop rain and wind. People
went for days without food. All that left big losses. You have to
look hard for ways to survive. So the hurricane had a huge impact
on us,'' Castillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the migrants waiting to be shipped back home,
Castillo shrugged when asked if he would attempt the trip again.
</P>
<P>
   Most Central Americans caught in Chiapas are deported over the
border to Guatemala, where they travel freely without visas under a
multilateral agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Those crossing illegally into Mexico sometimes walk through
tropical terrain or pay to be ferried across the Suchiate River,
which divides Chiapas from Guatemala. Once inside Mexico, the
migrants take buses or jump on trains heading north, climbing on
top of boxcars or hanging off the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials man roadblocks near the southern border to
check travelers' documents, and patrol the banks of the Suchiate
River. But because of shortages in manpower, the Suchiate appears
in some places to be a virtual no man's land.
</P>
<P>
   An astonishingly bustling trade is carried out daily on the
river, whose banks are lined on both sides with shacks selling food
and goods.
</P>
<P>
   Just a football-field away from an international checkpoint in
Hidalgo, Chiapas, a couple dozen rafts crafted from inner tubes and
wooden planks ply the river, carrying people and loads of
groceries. Guatemalans use the rafts so they can avoid having to
pay tariffs on their purchases at an official checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican customs' officials appear unable to stop the illegal
crossings. About the most they do is watch with binoculars and try
to stop drug shipments from coming in, said Neri Corado, one of the
reed-thin men and boys who push the rafts through the river with
long poles.
</P>
<P>
   In an impoverished region where everyone is fighting to survive,
tolerance prevails.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sacred river provides a source of work for us,'' said
Corado. ``Imagine what we would do if it were not here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
