u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-640&AMP;     08-24 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-640&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AND NORWEGIAN WORKERS ACCUSE RUSSIA OF HAMPERING RESCUE
EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Norway almost called off its rescue efforts for the
sunken submarine Kursk because of Russian officials' interference
and misinformation, a Norwegian admiral was quoted Thursday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
   Rear Adm. Einar Skorgen said in an interview with the Norwegian
newspaper Nordlandsposten that he told the Russians that his
deepsea divers would not be able to continue their work unless the
Russians became more cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times there were so many wrong details and disinformation
from Russia that it was close to endangering the divers,'' Skorgen
said. ``We couldn't rely on the information we were getting.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, he said, Russian officials said wrongly that
undersea currents were too strong for rescue work, that the escape
hatch was too severely damaged to allow a rescue minisubmarine to
attach to it and that the Kursk's hull was cracked.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The admiral's complaints ran counter to President Vladimir
Putin's assurances in a half-hour television interview on Wednesday
night that accusations of incompetence in the Russian rescue effort
were unfounded. Both Putin and the Russian navy have come under
attack from critics who say the rescue was too slow and poorly
managed, and that Putin recognized the scope of the incident only
belatedly.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Putin said he believed that Russian military
officials moved swiftly and efficiently when the Kursk exploded and
sank to the bottom of the Barents Sea on Aug. 12. Putin also said
that a much-criticized delay in accepting Norway's offer of aid was
because of unidentified ``technical parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   Skorgen said that the Norwegian rescue effort only gained ground
when he used a military hotline to reach the commander of Russia's
northern fleet, Vyacheslav Popov, a colleague from earlier days of
Norwegian-Russian military contacts.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Skorgen called Popov three times, and each time the Russian
bureaucracy yielded, he said. A team of four Norwegian and eight
British divers later pried open an escape hatch and confirmed that
the 118 seamen inside the Kursk were dead.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a senior Russian military official disputed a
second complaint, from one of the British divers, that his team had
been barred from using a sophisticated minisubmarine specially
designed for undersea rescues.
</P>
<P>
   That diver, Paddy Heron, said in an interview with British
Broadcasting Corp.-Scotland television that ``any arrangement or
proposed operation that they spoke about was rescinded, gone back
on, altered or countermanded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If life was still extant,'' he said, ``undoubtedly lives were
then lost by the fact that we sat doing nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Col. Gen. Valery Manilov, the deputy chief of the Russian
military general staff, called that accusation groundless at a news
conference on Thursday. Manilov said the minisubmarine was not
needed after it was proved that the Kursk's crew was dead. He also
insisted that the submarine's escape hatch was too severely damaged
for the submersible to dock with it.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the recriminations, families of some of the
crewmembers gathered Thursday in the military town of Vidyayevo to
lay a cornerstone for a memorial to the seamen, and later to sail
to the site of the sunken Kursk to toss flowers and wreaths onto
the waters.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin, which has been stung by criticism about the
sailors' scant pay and their families' dilapidated housing, said it
had collected enough in donations to give each of the 118 families
an additional $27,000 beyond the $7,000 in pay already awarded
them.
</P>
<P>
   And in Murmansk, near the Kursk's home port, Russian prosecutors
opened a criminal inquiry into the two explosions that sank the
submarine. They gave no indication that a specific individual or
group is suspected of causing the blasts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Prosecutor-general Vladimir Ustinov said investigators will seek
first to establish the cause of the explosions and that the course
of the inquiry will be set by the evidence they find.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Federal Security Service, Nikolai Patrushev,
confirmed earlier reports that the submarine carried two Dagestani
men who were not members of the regular crew, and said they were
``specialists from a certain Caspian enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Their presence was notable because the Russian region of
Dagestan borders Chechnya, where separatist guerrillas are waging
war against the Russian army, thus raising the prospect that the
Kursk was sunk by a terrorist act. But Patrushev said that his
intelligence service has no information to support that theory.
</P>
</TEXT>
