<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SOLOMON-FILM-REVIEW-N     08-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLOMON-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOLOMON AND GAENOR': A FABRIC PEDDLER WHO SOLD HER A BILL OF
GOODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The moment the star-crossed title characters in Paul Morrison's
somber love story ``Solomon and Gaenor'' set eyes on each other,
your heart sinks. It is immediately obvious there is nowhere for
these young lovers to travel but down an awfully familiar path from
clandestine ecstasy to pariahhood to tragedy that could take any of
three final twists, all equally predictable. Surrendering yourself
to this well-acted film is never a question of wondering when the
last shoe will drop, but one of how much you'll allow yourself to
identify with its likable but foolish lovers, who break the strict
social rules of their claustrophobically dingy community and pay
the usual price.
</P>
<P>
   That community is an impoverished Welsh coal mining village in
1911. Solomon (Ioan Gruffudd) is the eldest son in a devout
Orthodox Jewish family that has recently migrated to Wales from
Russia and has set up a pawnshop that doubles as a drapery
business. One of Solomon's tasks is to go from door to door of the
miners' cottages across the hill, peddling swatches of cloth that
can be made into dresses. One day he stops at the door of Gaenor's
strict, churchgoing family. She answers his knock, and a spark is
lighted.
</P>
<P>
   To the film's considerable credit, the young lovers don't
exactly conform to the Romeo and Juliet stereotype of celestial
innocents crushed by a cruel and envious world. Solomon, the more
morally culpable of the two, is a flagrant liar whose courtship of
Gaenor involves adopting a non-Jewish pseudonym, Sam Livingstone,
and making up a nonexistent Gentile family. As enraptured as
Solomon appears to be during the first throes of their passionate
affair, he never broaches the subject of marriage, which for a time
she assumes is his intention.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Gaenor (Nia Roberts) proves easily seduced. Once
Solomon has given her a pretty red dress he has sewn himself, she
is a goner. She hurls herself into a sexual relationship with
Solomon while hardly knowing him. Neither one seems to have the
slightest awareness of the possibility that she might become
pregnant. Which she does, of course, discovering the pregnancy just
around the time she has given up hope of Solomon's proposing
marriage or even of meeting his family.
</P>
<P>
   Although its storytelling includes a number of small glitches,
the movie does an almost dismayingly good job of conveying its
characters' grim, bare-bones existence and the stultifying sexual
and religious taboos that the lovers flout. And without dwelling on
anti-Semitism, it evokes the tensions between Jews and Gentiles,
which explode into vandalism, arson and looting after a strike
imperils the miners' precarious existence and they take out their
resentment on the local Jewish merchants.
</P>
<P>
   The most emotionally harrowing scenes show the pregnant Gaenor's
brutal denunciation and expulsion from church when her pregnancy is
revealed during a service, and Solomon's rapidly crumbling
relationship with Gaenor's loutish older brother, Crad (Mark Lewis
Jones), who is suspicious of the young stranger from the start
because of his uncallused hands.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has a good performance by Gruffudd, whose Solomon
becomes obsessed with Gaenor only after she has rejected him. But
it is Roberts (making her debut) who walks off with the film. Her
understated, beautifully layered performance suggests the spark of
defiance under Gaenor's prim exterior and fans it into a reckless
impulsiveness that eventually deepens into an enfolding womanly
passion containing just a touch of fanaticism.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Solomon and Gaenor'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes nudity and
sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SOLOMON AND GAENOR'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Paul Morrison; in English, Welsh and
Yiddish, with English subtitles; director of photography, Nina
Kellgren; edited by Kant Pan; music by Ilona Sekacz; production
designer, Hayden Pearce; produced by Sheryl Crown; released by Sony
Pictures Classics. Running time: 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Ioan Gruffudd (Solomon), Nia Roberts (Gaenor), Sue Jones
Davies (Gwen), William Thomas (Idris), Mark Lewis Jones (Crad),
Maureen Lipman (Rezl), David Horovitch (Isaac) and Bethan Ellis
Owen (Brownwen).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
