<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1275 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WOMENHEALTH0825-COX     08-24 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENHEALTH0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You're tired, your throat hurts. It must be cancer. Or maybe
lupus. Why do women do this to themselves?
 &HT;    By Sharyn Wizda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There it is again, the twinge, just a little
critch in the back of your throat.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably just all that talking I did today, nothing but
meetings, you think to yourself, lying in bed trying to get to
sleep. Maybe get up and get some water and I'll be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes pass. The little voice pipes up again.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I have a cold. Maybe I'm getting sick. Well, just get a
lot of sleep and you'll be fine.
</P>
<P>
   The dark suddenly seems darker, more ominous.
</P>
<P>
   What if it's something else? I've been kind of tired lately.
What if that has something to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   And so on, and so on, until you've gone with a few twists of the
psyche from being a reasonably healthy person to imagining how you
will cope with the inevitable news from your doctor that you have
cancer. Or chronic fatigue syndrome. Or lupus. (Will I be one of
those brave women that I read about in the magazines? Is this
destined to teach me a valuable lesson about the meaning of life _
but too late?)
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about hypochondria, which typically involves a
good six months of obsessing despite visits to the doctor and
tests. This is something . . . different. Harder to explain, harder
to pinpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, I know that I'm an intelligent person and I know
that I'm not crazy,'' says Stacy Miles, 27, an undergraduate
adviser in the University of Texas' Spanish and Portuguese
department. ``I do know that I'm a rational person. But sometimes I
feel irrational in the fears that I have about things that may be
wrong with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, I had the flu one time and so I was reading this
self-diagnosis book. My glands were swollen and I managed to
diagnose myself with lymphoma. I really convinced myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles did eventually go to see a physician _ she really did have
the flu. (She never mentioned lymphoma: ``Of course, I didn't want
to go to the doctor and look like an idiot.'')
</P>
<P>
   See, somewhere in the back of your mind you're pretty sure you
don't have anything major wrong with you. But that twinge or that
exhaustion just has to have an explanation, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``You read about some new illness and you think, `Ohhh, is that
why I'm tired all the time?' '' says Ursula Acker Parks, 32, a
budget analyst for the state. ``Those are the ones that get me:
`Oh, maybe that will explain my lethargy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I would much rather believe it was a disease or syndrome of
some sort,'' quips Parks. ``Anything that would not require me to
change my lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   What's causing this millennial wave of worry among women? Well,
for starters, we're all tired. (This goes for men, too, though it
seems that men don't think anything's wrong with them until, say, a
bone is broken. And even then they'll just walk it off.) So maybe
none of us is thinking too clearly to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the reams of information available to us,
more and more all the time. A seemingly endless parade of magazine
and newspaper articles and television stories _ all with comment
from a stricken person saying something to the effect of, ``If I
had just checked it out earlier . . .'' There's the Internet, with
its unfiltered information and quizzes and danger signs. Even the
HMOs are sending us medical manuals, designed to help us avoid the
doctor's office and figure out what we have ourselves. (Call these
the Big Books Of Very Terrifying Things.) Is it any wonder that
what used to be called ``medical students' disease'' has become an
equal-opportunity scare-fest?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those type of health Web sites where you can look up symptoms
for things can be discouraging. You put s and women say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have breast pain I tend to think in those moments of
irrationality, `What if it's breast cancer?' '' says Leslie
Strickland, 28, a pre-med student at the University of Texas. ``A
lot of it is just because the publicity is so high about checking
yourself . . . I tend to think that I'm pretty strong _ I lived in
Africa for 2 1/2 years and got exposed to everything from leprosy
to cholera. But even though it's normal to have pain in your
breasts _ that's the only thing that causes me a scared moment,
where I think, `Oh my gosh, I want to not get that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Youngkin, an obstetrician/gynecologist, said many of
his female patients have worries that mirror Strickland's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are very worried about breast cancer, and with good
reason,'' Youngkin says. ``But 10 times more women die from heart
disease than from breast cancer . . . There is a concern that women
have about breast cancer that overwhelms the statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's totally normal, common behavior,'' says
psychotherapist Lisa Mersky. ``With some diseases, the symptoms are
so common . . . fatigue or lack of energy, we all have that because
of modern life.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Both Williams and Mersky, our resident experts,
also confessed to having such thoughts on occasion. But both also
suggest trying to focus on the rational thoughts and facts in your
mind, to repeat those over and over rather than, ``How will I deal
with chemo?''
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to understand that we have lots of control over
our thoughts. Our thoughts are not imposed on us externally,''
Mersky says. ``So if we remind ourselves that we are in control of
what we are thinking and think about why we are thinking this _ and
decide to stop if you really do want to. This isn't a judgmental
reaction _ `What's wrong with me? This is ridiculous. Why am I
worrying about this?' _ but a lively, curious thing _ `Why do I
need to worry about this?' ''
</P>
<P>
   What's also worth paying attention to is whether these thoughts
are really masking something else _ something you're avoiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who tend to be worriers can have a very creative
imagination, and it may be that they want as many distractions from
the reason that they're really worried as possible,'' Mersky points
out. If there are deep-seated issues _ anything from being
dissatisfied with a job or relationship to something as serious as
childhood abuse _ that a person is troubled by, one way of coping
is to transfer all that worry into something physical. A disease
could be a life-and-death issue, after all _ it has to take
precedence over everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Barring that, breaking your thought patterns could involve
something as simple as going to the doctor and not being afraid to
voice those fears bullying you in the middle of the night. That's
one way Strickland dealt with her concerns about breast cancer: ``I
just recently went to the doctor and talked to her and that really
allayed a lot of my fears.''
</P>
<P>
   Or it could be even easier: Confess to your friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I see a TV show or read something (about a disease)
that's when I start to think about it a little bit more,'' says
Miles, who admits she's worried about skin cancer and
obsessive-compulsive disorder, among others. ``But then when I sit
down with my friends and we laugh about it _ it's not serious: `Oh,
I self-diagnosed myself with OCD the other day.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And it just doesn't seem real anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EYEWITNESS-BOOK-REVIE     08-24 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYEWITNESS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``EYEWITNESS TO POWER'': MASTER OF SPIN PUTS HIS CRAFT TO WORK FOR
HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes at end of review) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his new book on presidential leadership, the veteran White
House adviser David Gergen laments the current state of politics,
the ascendance of spin and media manipulation and the tendency of
politicians like Bill Clinton to mistake campaigning for
governance. ``The 1980 contest for the White House was the last
truly good one the country has had,'' he writes, ``because all
three candidates _ Carter, Anderson and Reagan _ provided clear
choices for the electorate. They said exactly what courses they
intended to pursue if elected, didn't blur their differences, held
down the mud slinging, and didn't sell their souls to their
pollsters and handlers.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Gergen himself is one of the people who
helped create this sorry state of affairs; he has effectively made
a career out of playing the role of the little man behind the
curtain in ``The Wizard of Oz,'' helping to orchestrate the auras
of the great and powerful. It was Gergen who helped institute
``spin patrol'' during the Reagan years, using his mastery of
leaking, damage control and sound bites to package and promote that
administration's policies. And it was Gergen who was later enlisted
by an embattled Clinton White House _ which had reviled many of
Reagan's conservative stands _ to help shore up its operations and
public image.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, Gergen's easy transit from being a Republican
helpmate to being a Democratic one, from being a White House
spinmeister to being a journalistic one (he is currently
editor-at-large for U.S. News &AMP; World Report and a regular analyst
on ``The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer'') underscores the pragmatic _
some would say mercenary _ ethos of a political era that
increasingly values expertise over conviction, style over
substance. Gergen's description of himself as a ``pro-choice, high
safety net man'' did not keep him from working for Ronald Reagan,
just as his ``hard-line'' views in international affairs did not
keep him from working for Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Eyewitness to Power'' Gergen tries to spin his own image,
repudiating the consequences of the very processes he helped set in
motion. ``How could we have taught a younger generation of public
officials the wrong lessons about governance?'' he asks. ``Where
had we gone wrong? While officials since the beginning of the
republic have been cajoling the press, one of my deepest regrets in
public life is a feeling that I have contributed to this
deterioration. Spin has spun out of control and we need to put it
back in its box.''
</P>
<P>
   In much the same way that his former Reagan colleague James
Baker 3rd tried in his memoirs (``The Politics of Diplomacy'') to
put his reputation as ``The Velvet Hammer'' behind him and reinvent
himself as a statesman, so Gergen tries in this volume to put his
reputation as ``The Sieve'' behind him and reinvent himself as a
Washington wise man. ``Eyewitness,'' which recounts Gergen's
experiences working with Richard Nixon, Gerald Ford, Ronald Reagan
and Bill Clinton, is at once a hypocritical mea culpa and a series
of talking points designed to insure the author's reputation as the
insider's insider.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gergen's public persona, familiar to readers from his many
television appearances as both a pundit and a White House
spokesman, this book is low-key and conciliatory in tone, almost
every criticism balanced with a compliment. President Clinton,
whose service Gergen left after 18 months, feeling ``angry'' and
``used,'' receives the harshest treatment; he is repeatedly
criticized for his lack of self-control, his poor management style
and his reliance on his wife as a political partner.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally a faint whiff of ``I told you so'' creeps into the
book's pages. Had President Ford put a strong chief of staff in
place from the start as Gergen wished, it is suggested, his
administration might have avoided many of its early and
debilitating stumbles. Had Clinton listened to Gergen and others
who advised him to make a full disclosure of Whitewater documents
from the start, ``we would have punctured the growing pressure for
an independent counsel'' and the whole ensuing melodrama with
Kenneth Starr and Monica Lewinsky might well have been avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing heavily on Gergen's own reminiscences _ as well as such
works on leadership as Garry Wills' ``Certain Trumpets'' and Howard
Gardner's ``Leading Minds'' _ ``Eyewitness to Power'' sifts through
the record of recent administrations to give future would-be
presidents some tips on how to be an effective leader. Though
Gergen's analysis of individual presidents is often shrewd, many of
his tips are little more than the sort of common-sense
recommendations one might find in a self-help book: i.e.,
``leadership starts from within,'' or surround yourself with
``strong, prudent advisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Other observations will be self-evident to anyone familiar with
recent history. Gergen points out that the Nixon White House went
too far in ``trying to manage the news'' and that Clinton shared
Nixon's intelligence, obsession with spinning, tendency to polarize
and compulsive need to win.
</P>
<P>
   In Gergen's opinion, Clinton's failure to take control of the
health care initiative was connected to his unwillingness to
challenge Hillary Rodham Clinton in the wake of reports alleging
that he had used Arkansas state troopers to procure women. ``Might
we have passed a bipartisan reform plan,'' Gergen asks, if the
shadow of Bill Clinton's past ``had not hung over his relationship
with his wife?''
</P>
<P>
   Though Gergen frequently mentions the importance of character
and goals in this volume, most of his advice revolves around
strategy and stagecraft and the best way to play the game. The
focus tends to be on presentation and perception, not morality or
vision. For instance, in the case of Ford's pardon of Richard
Nixon, Gergen writes, ``it was in the execution of his decision _
not the decision itself _ that the new president stumbled.''
Instead of simply springing the pardon on an unsuspecting country,
he argues, Ford should have carefully laid the proper groundwork
first.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Eyewitness to Power'' Gergen also devotes a large amount of
space to drawing lessons in communication from Reagan's speeches:
keep it short and brisk, he advises, ``use the language of the
living room,'' ``look for catchy facts,'' ``use the occasional
prop,'' ``be positive,'' ``anticipate the critics'' and ``have a
good closer.'' Gergen argues that historical allusions can lend a
leader ``an aura of distinction,'' and he emphasizes the
importance, in the first 100 days, of establishing a positive
narrative in the public's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing more important to the success of an actor, it
is said, than his performance in his first scene and in his last,''
Gergen writes. ``One shapes his character for the entire play, the
other the memories that the audience carries from the theater. The
same applies in politics and in other fields of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The analogy between actors and politicians is no accident: in
the spin-driven world Gergen has helped create, the line between
the two has become increasingly blurry, with handlers like himself
cast in the ever more visible role of director.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EYEWITNESS TO POWER: The Essence of Leadership, Nixon to
Clinton'
</P>
<P>
   By David Gergen
</P>
<P>
   382 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
