<HEADLINE>
MISADVENTURES ON THE ROAD TO `LOVE AND SEX' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``First love is the most powerful because nobody's been hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Love is a minefield.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in relationships. Mine just happen to be short
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women like to turn men into weirdos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer you're with the same person, the more annoying
they'll become.''
</P>
<P>
   That is but a sampling of the wit and wisdom that Valerie
Breiman has managed to pump into her slight but bright and charming
romantic comedy, ``Love and Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Breiman, this film tracks the
misadventurous road to love taken by Kate Welles (Famke Janssen)
from her girlhood playground passion to her loss of virginity to
her high school French teacher to _ one hopes _ a happy ending with
Adam Levy (Jon Favreau), the artist who shamelessly spirits her
away from a standup comedian at an exhibition of his latest
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Kate herself is a writer for one of those trendy women's
magazines where orders from her demanding boss to come up with
2,500 happy, perky words by the end of the day on how to find and
keep that perfect man prompt her to ponder the flashback-inducing
question: What makes a relationship last forever?
</P>
<P>
   Although Kate's relationship with Adam starts off happily and
progresses in stages to sex and other intimacies, living together,
cute arguments over tastes in films, and eventually to pregnancy,
it descends into sexlessness, annoyance, resentment over past
affairs and a decision to part company.
</P>
<P>
   While Kate and Adam remain in touch, she is soon partying with a
young man described as a perverted basketball player obsessed with
her derriere, followed by a torrid affair with the not-too-bright
but hunky star of topless Ninja movies who picks her up while she
is shopping in a store specializing in devices for the enhancement
of sexual pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love and Sex'' is occasionally too cute for its own good, but
it is packed with recognizable situations. Janssen and Favreau
provide enjoyably consoling company for those still dating their
way through life.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LOVE AND SEX'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Valerie Breiman; director of
photography, Adam Kane; edited by Martin Applebaum; production
designer, Sara Sprawls; produced by Timothy Scott Bogart, Martin J.
Barab and Brad Wyman; released by Lions Gate Films. Running time:
82 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Famke Janssen (Kate Welles), Jon Favreau (Adam Levy), Noah
Emmerich (Eric), Cheri Oteri (Mary) and Ann Magnuson (
Steinbacher).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
