<HEADLINE>
THE COMPUTERS OF THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: This story is being transmitted to entertainment and
lifestyle wires) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe inspiration strikes simultaneously, but a couple of
magazines have trotted out their visions of the ultimate computer
in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Such exercises by serious computer geeks are fun to ponder
because of what such dream machines say about where the rest of us
will be in a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Maximum PC put together a maximum machine that's pretty amazing.
Then again, it better be: It costs a shade under $12,000, which
would buy either an excellent used car or about 13 of the perfectly
satisfactory Dell Dimension L computers advertised on the
magazine's back cover.
</P>
<P>
   At $899, the Dell features a sturdy 667-Mhz Pentium III
processor, smallish 7.5 gigabyte hard drive and 15-inch monitor,
speakers and decent CD-ROM drive. It's pretty good and a reliable
enough buy for anyone with modest computing needs.
</P>
<P>
   But ``pretty good'' isn't what interests the Maximum boys. So
what ate the cash?
</P>
<P>
   Well, three superfast hard drives, including a 75-gigabyte IBM
device that looks like a bargain for serious space needs; a fast
Pioneer DVD drive; two very fast Plextor CD-rewritable drives
!ital!and a Plextor CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   It has two 256-megabyte memory modules (at $990 apiece, where
one is double what most people need), and not one but two
1-gigahertz Pentium III processors (at $1,100 each, again more than
double most people's needs), to make everything go, in Steve Jobs'
words about his own company's dual-processor Power Macs, ``wicked
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maximum machine has other little goodies, like a Creative
Labs Live Drive II that provides connections to and from all kinds
of audio devices and Sigma Designs' Real Magic Hollywood Plus,
which lets you play DVDs at high quality on your computer or
television.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the components are cheap, such as the Hollywood Plus
($70) and the Logitech First Mouse Wheel ($20). Others are
reasonable, like the fine $250 Klipsch ProMedia v.2-400 speaker
set. To Maximum PC's credit, the magazine also suggests
budget-priced alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   PC Upgrade magazine put together a more modest super machine
specifically for gamers, centered around a 1-gigahertz AMD Athlon
processor.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Maximum machine, this is a box with a purpose: to
play high-end games. That focus reduces the need for lily gilding
(such as Maximum's dual recordable CD drives), cutting costs to a
more reasonable (ha!) $3,199 (or three Dells plus copies of Diablo
II and Deus Ex to get started playing).
</P>
<P>
   To make pretty pictures, they relied on Hercules' 3-D Prophet
DDR-DVI graphics card, which takes a big load off the computer's
brain in generating all the demanding surfaces, lighting and
shading of top-quality games. The Prophet is one of several
graphics cards out there that uses the industry-leading GeForce
chips from nVidia, combining two of them along with lots of
dedicated memory.
</P>
<P>
   They recommend Logitech's Wingman mouse ($99) and Mad Catz's
Panther DX joystick ($39) to control the games, and ELSA's 3-D
Revelator glasses ($59). So what does any of this supertech have to
do with writing a letter to Grandma or checking your e-mail? Not a
lot.
</P>
<P>
   But truth is, these machines are where we're going, with
powerful electronics capable of handling increasingly sophisticated
entertainment of many kinds, supplanting or combining many of the
devices we have lying around the house already. Consider these
dream machines a peek at our reality, in a few years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0825-COX     08-24 1915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore gains in four states
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore has caught George W. Bush in Michigan, taken a lead in
Minnesota and New Jersey and slightly increased his lead in
California, according to state polls taken after the Democratic
convention. The surveys, released today, are generally in line with
other polls that have shown Gore getting the benefit of a
post-convention ``bounce'' that presidential candidates often
receive. California, with 54 electoral votes, Minnesota with 10,
New Jersey with 15, and Michigan with 18 together account for more
than one-third of the 270 needed for election in November. While
such bumps in the polls can be a temporary phenomenon, they could
rearrange the state-by-state landscape in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   HERE'S WHERE ONE TAX CUT WOULD GO . . .
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush campaigned in Louisiana today with a family he
said would benefit greatly from his proposals and not at all from
rival Al Gore's. Upon landing at the airport in New Orleans, Bush
presented local residents Andrew and Margaret Bechac as a family
with two children that would receive a 77 percent reduction in
their federal income taxes under his plan. ``I want to put a face
on the current tax relief package,'' Bush said with the Bechacs at
his side. Earlier in the week, he said he needed to do a better job
explaining his $1.3 trillion proposal in the face of criticism from
Gore, who has offered a $500 billion plan.
</P>
<P>
   . . . BUT GENERAL DIRECTION IS QUESTIONED
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman, in a pointed critique of George W. Bush's tax-cut
plan, says Bush is having a hard time explaining it because it's
not fair. Seizing on Bush's acknowledgment that he needed to do a
better job of explaining his plan to cut income taxes across the
board, Lieberman asserted: ``The problem isn't explaining the tax
cut; the problem is the plan itself. It benefits the wealthy, not
the hard-working families of America.'' Lieberman said there's
``nothing wrong with being rich _ in America, we all want to be
rich. The point is who needs the tax cut, who needs the help.''
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN POLICY AND EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore showed off his international and domestic sides today,
meeting with Mexico's president-elect before heading to the nearby
University of Maryland to plug his proposal to make college tuition
tax deductible. Gore highlighted his foreign-policy experience in
the meeting with Vicente Fox at the vice president's official
residence at the U.S. Naval Observatory. Gore says his proposal for
a college tuition tax credit would save most families about $2,800
a year and assure that college would not ``be limited to families
of wealth and means.''
</P>
<P>
   CHECKERED TEACHING CAREER
</P>
<P>
   Ezola Foster, Pat Buchanan's running mate on the Reform Party
ticket, collected workers' compensation payments for a year for a
mental disorder she now says she did not have. The disability claim
was contested by her employer, the Los Angeles Unified School
District. Foster applied for workers' compensation in 1996, shortly
after refusing to return to her job as a typing teacher at Bell
High School. The reason she could not return to work, she told the
Los Angeles Times, was that her outspoken opposition to illegal
immigration had made her a target of what she claimed was
hatemongering and physical threats at an overwhelmingly Latino
school. Foster is African-American.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ABOUT THE SHAPE OF THE TABLE?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush may be chuckling over the debate about
presidential debates, but his staff is serious about shaping this
year's encounters to be favorable for their candidate. The Boston
Globe reports that Bush opposes the podium-and-panelist method that
has dominated recent presidential debates. Instead, Bush wants a
more intimate roundtable discussion like the primary debate in
February where he, John McCain of Arizona and Alan Keyes sat
face-to-face with CNN's Larry King before a live audience. Bush's
advisers say the traditional debate format features ``gotcha''
questions from reporters who serve as panelists.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER BIG CONCERT BOOKED
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee will invade New York's Radio
City Music Hall for the sequel to a convention-ending fund-raising
gala that raised $5.1 million. The lineup for the Sept. 14 event
rivals the concert schedule at any summer venue. It includes
Crosby, Stills and Nash; Jimmy Buffett, Sheryl Crow; Bon Jovi;
Lenny Kravitz; Bette Midler; Macy Gray; Don Henley and Glenn Frey.
Comedian John Leguizamo will serve as M.C. Ticket prices: $125 to
$10,000.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM BALLOT BATTLES
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the Reform Party's national convention was
supposed to choose a nominee, the battle continues between Pat
Buchanan, the former Republican, and John Hagelin, the Natural Law
candidate embraced by supporters of Reform Party founder Ross
Perot. Iowa election officials drew Buchanan's name from a glass
bowl today after a raucous hallway exchange between party factions
fighting for a spot on the state's November ballot. Hagelin was the
winner in a film-can drawing in Montana. In California, Buchanan
had been briefly listed, but was pulled from the ballot today at
the request of party leaders, said Alfie Charles, a spokesman for
the secretary of state there.
</P>
<P>
   COMPENSATION QUESTIONED
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times report questioned whether Dick Cheney is worth
the the multimillion-dollar retirement package he got from
Halliburton, the oil services company where he had been CEO. Cheney
presided over a merger between Halliburton and Dresser Industries,
a deal that led to several money-losing ventures, including a South
American pipeline project that lost $100 million. Halliburton's
stock price rose sharply in Cheney's first years as CEO, but has
stagnated in the past year and a half. The board of directors
withheld bonuses last year from Cheney and other top execs for
missing financial targets for 1998 and 1999. And the company also
has faced fines for missed deadlines and unsatisfactory work in
North Carolina and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   THE KOSHER ELVIS
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman campaigned like a rock star in a predominantly
Jewish retirement community. But the policy message about
prescription drug prices and elder care was nearly drowned out by
the in-house band's rendition of ``Hava Nagila.'' There were shouts
of ``Joe! Joe! Joe!'' at the sight of the Orthodox Jewish veep
candidate. One small, silver-haired woman left a red lipstick
imprint on the back of Lieberman's hand and gushed, ``It's like
kissing the Torah, kissing you.'' By the way, Al Gore was there
too.
</P>
<P>
   KARENNA IN FOR AILING MOM
</P>
<P>
   A post-convention flu has felled Tipper Gore, so her eldest
daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, is taking her place on the campaign
trail this week. Al Gore's Nashville-based presidential campaign
announced that his wife was too ill from the nonstop campaigning
around last week's Democratic convention to keep her dates in
Pittsburgh and Erie, Pa., today. Tipper Gore is scheduled to join
her husband Monday on a trip to Tallahassee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   THAT OLD CALIFORNIA CONFIDENCE
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney is predicting that he and George W. Bush will take
California on Election Day. ``This is an absolutely essential state
in this election,'' Cheney told about 70 Republican elected
officials and supporters after flying in to Santa Barbara for two
fund-raisers. ``Governor Bush was here last week; I'm here this
week,'' he said at the airport. ``We're both going to be back a lot
between now and November 7 because on November 7 we're going to
carry California.'' Cheney sounded a family values theme, noting
that he and wife Lynne have been married 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS SCUTTLE AD
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party abruptly dropped plans to air a TV ad
questioning the veracity of Al Gore and President Clinton, fearing
a backlash if moderate and independent voters viewed the spot as a
reference to the Monica Lewinsky scandal. Officials with George W.
Bush's campaign and at the Republican National Committee also
apparently objected on grounds that the ad used an outdated Gore
interview and conflicted with Bush's promise to soften the tenor of
American politics. The TV spot had been scheduled for broadcast in
Texas as early as today.
</P>
<P>
   SHORT SPEECHES, SHORT DAYS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush recently cut short a day of running for president
to make time for his 3-mile run back home in Texas, ordering his
entourage to leave Memphis _ the site of his only event that day _
several hours early. It was just the latest example of Bush
maintaining a mix of down time in his campaign schedule after the
primaries, when he increased his appearances in an effort to beat
back the challenge by John McCain. Since then, his preference for
early bedtimes and short campaign swings have prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   IF NOT RELIGIOUS, THEN MILITARY VALUES
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, a former secretary of defense, met with uniformed
Junior ROTC students to praise the values taught in the officer
training program and the military. Flanked by future troops, Cheney
emphasized that public schools should build character by teaching
traditional values. ``Nothing is more essential to education than
character,'' he told students, teachers and parents at Bakersfield
High School in California. Cheney said he favored a more prominent
role for prayer in public schools, but that care must be taken to
maintain the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   HONEY, I SHRUNK THE MILITARY
</P>
<P>
   The shrinking of America's military, now decried by George W.
Bush as one of the Clinton administration's biggest sins, was
pushed by running mate Dick Cheney as Bush's father's defense
secretary a decade ago. After the fall of the Berlin Wall _ and
with a Congress hungry for a ``peace dividend'' _ Cheney in 1990
proposed a gradual 25 percent reduction in the military:
withdrawing tens of thousands of troops from Europe, canceling
weapons programs, and removing 442,000 men and women from the
military over five years. ``I've got a 10-pound defense program and
a 6-pound defense budget. Somehow we've got to squeeze one down so
it fits,'' he said in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION DEFICIT DISORDER
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and George W. Bush would love to have the voters'
undivided attention, but they're not going to get it. The
presidential race is about to be overtaken by a big wave of
diversions and distractions, forcing the candidates to compete with
the Summer Olympics; the U.S. Open tennis tournament, the start of
football, basketball and hockey seasons; major league baseball
playoffs and a World Series stretching into late October.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING A READ ON IT
</P>
<P>
   Since the Democratic convention ended last week, Amazon.com saw
sales for books about Al Gore expand their lead over sales for
books about George W. Bush. Gore book sales are leading now, with a
54-46 percent edge. That's up from 51-49 percent last week.
Bush-related books had held a strong lead since the index was first
posted last month. You can keep up with the book race at
www.amazon.com/election2000. The index is updated weekly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
