<HEADER>
A1313 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-THEME25-COX     08-24 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-THEME25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE REACHES OUT TO VOTERS TURNED OFF BY POLITICS
 &HT;    620&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore has begun emphasizing a
subtle theme on the stump, aimed at countering the political
estrangement among young and middle-aged voters alike.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in the Midwest this week, Gore asked voters at
nearly every stop to ``open your hearts'' and ``break through your
disillusionment'' and ``allow yourself to believe that we can do
the right thing'' as a nation.
</P>
<P>
   When he begins this portion of his stump speech, ``I see the
heads start to nod out there'' in the crowd, Gore said in an
interview following his trip down the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his words referred not only to the reaction against
President Clinton's behavior, but also to the disenchantment with
politics in general.
</P>
<P>
   Gore traces this disillusionment to the assassination of
President John F. Kennedy in 1963, followed by the Vietnam War, the
assassinations of Martin Luther King Jr. and Robert F. Kennedy in
1968, and the Watergate scandal that led to President Nixon's
resignation. It has been exacerbated in recent years, he said, by
the country's sometimes painful transition to an information
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a reference to the last two years _ it's a reference
to the last 35 years or so,'' Gore said. ``There really are a lot
of people who feel like they've been burned, not by Clinton's
activities _ or maybe that, too _ but mainly it's because of the
cynicism and the ironic detachment, the feeling that politics is
not worthy of smart people, committed people getting involved,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know, to hell with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``open your hearts'' portion of Gore's stump speech usually
comes at the end, soft and earnest, a somewhat jarring transition
from the fiery populist attacks on ``Big Oil, Big Tobacco and
HMOs'' that make up most of the speech.
</P>
<P>
   It is most often directed to ``the young people'' in the
audience, the teenagers and twenty-somethings that are the least
likely to vote in presidential contests, but who helped swell the
turnouts for such political mavericks as Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., and Gov. Jesse Ventura of
Minnesota, a third-party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   During Gore's just-completed boat trip down a 400-mile stretch
of the Mississippi, his appeal captured the imagination of not only
these elusive voters, but also some of Gore's fellow baby boomers
and those of President Kennedy's generation, who wistfully recall
the promise of the New Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Seeing him got me all revved up,'' said Shirley Chaney, 49,
in Hannibal, Mo., where Gore's trip ended Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``He's catching the attention of people who could care less
about politics,'' said Chad Rentz, a middle-aged restaurant owner
in Bellevue, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``He talks the way my father does,'' said 27-year-old Jennifer
Hedrick of Sparta, Wis., who turned out for one of Gore's riverboat
stops in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``He's for the average guy,'' said Harry Haldeman, 77, of
Jesup, Iowa, who grew up in the coal mining areas of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining his idealistic appeal, Gore said, ``I think for at
least 35 years we've had a series of traumas to the political
system, to our self-government, without an uninterrupted period of
healing to restore the level of confidence and good feeling that's
necessary for a healthy democratic process. But I know that if you
decide to push past that and get involved, you really can make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said if you scratch the surface of a cynic, you'll
find someone wanting to believe that the world is good and we can
make a difference,'' he said. ``That's what I'm trying to do _
scratch the surface of cynicism.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his theme was born in the open meetings he held in
Iowa and New Hampshire during the nominating contest with Bradley.
At one meeting, he met someone who reminded him of himself in the
early 1970s, after a series of alienating events that included the
national tragedies of the era and his father's loss of his U.S.
Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I encountered somebody _ I can't even remember who or where _
who reminded me of myself at that time; and I said to that person,
`Look, you've got to let yourself believe that we can really do the
right thing, and you've got to push past this disillusionment and
cynicism','' Gore recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after that, I stood up in front of some group and it
just came out that way. Several people came up to me afterward and
said, 'That really had an impact on me, and you ought to say that.'
``
</P>
<P>
   That message was soon set aside, however, after Gore defeated
Bradley and began a series of attacks on Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, his Republican rival.
</P>
<P>
   Gore began sounding the anti-cynicism theme anew in the weeks
just before the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles last
week, and it was part of his acceptance speech, widely hailed for
its non-combative tone.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
