<HEADER>
A1315 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-TIMEREGAINED25     08-24 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TIMEREGAINED25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Familiarity with Proust helps decipher `Time Regained'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unless the names Gilberte, Odette, Albertine and Saint-Loup stir
associations in your mind like the taste of a madeleine dipped in
tea, you'll be bewildered by ``Time Regained.'' The lush, hushed
adaptation of the last volume of Marcel Proust's ``Remembrance of
Times Past'' is a summing up of the writer's immense meditation on
time, memory, snobbery and tortured passions. It's like the climax
of a sumptuous soap opera _ but if you haven't tuned in to the
previous episodes, you won't have a clue.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Raoul Ruiz's elegant film unfolds largely in a
series of sumptuous rooms and corridors. Their doors open, like the
mind, onto different places and times as Marcel (played by
look-alike Marcello Mazzarello) wanders through the sprawl of his
own life, a socially connected man of Paris in the late 19th and
early 20th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   It's a game of free association, as the clink of a spoon in a
teacup transforms into the peal of church bells, launching us into
Proust's memories of being 10 in the fictional village of Combray.
Or a withered old duchess at a gossipy salon is suddenly replaced
by her younger, beautiful self. In a way, the movie is a ghost
story, a catalog of the dead and dying brought back to life,
through Proust's memory, and in particular by his writing.
</P>
<P>
   Like memory, the film swings between specific sensual
impressions and events viewed in isolation from their full context.
We see young Marcel and Gilberte first meet as children, then again
as adults after Gilberte (Emmanuelle Beart) has married Robert
Saint-Loup (Pascal Greggory). When we encounter journalist-musician
Morel (Vincent Perez), he is already engaged in a suggestive
relationship with Saint-Loup, and a vague feud with Saint-Loup's
wealthy uncle, the Baron de Charlus (John Malkovich).
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Regained'' doesn't fill us in on the backstories as it
shuffles through time. That's because what the characters do to one
another is less important than what time does to all of them. When
Marcel withdraws to a sanitorium for his health, he returns to
society to find familiar faces have altered, lives have turned
better or worse. These changes appear full-blown _ the Baron now a
limping old man, Gilberte an embittered, scorned widow. Even
without Marcel around, time keeps busy making its changes. Only
Odette (Catherine Deneuve), the famed, slightly scandalous beauty,
remains untouched.
</P>
<P>
   What tangible plot there is concerns the onset of World War I,
as Saint-Loup blusters heartily toward the front, while Morel
becomes a deserter. But what really drives ``Time Regained'' is its
background of romantic obsession. This is a world of sexual
fluidity in which everyone seems capable of sleeping with (or has
already) everyone else. Robert and Morel, Morel and the Baron,
Gilberte and Robert, Gilberte and Albertine, Albertine and Marcel.
It's like a very polite, bisexual template for ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   Though playwright Harold Pinter wrote a fascinating, but still
unproduced, screenplay tackling the whole work, Proust's six-part
novel is famous for being considered unfilmable. ``Time Regained''
proves this partly true and partly false. Ruiz constantly shifts
from naturalistic direction to touches of surrealism, letting
inanimate objects swell into the forground, or gliding furniture
(and sometimes his actors) around the sets on dollies and
turntables. In the end, it's more of a kaleidoscope than a
traditional movie, which calls for a beginning, middle and end.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately it's designed for Proust readers, who are likely to
love and loathe it in equal parts for its attempts to give concrete
form to his work. It's like a gorgeous silk tapestry shrouding a
statue meant to memorialize decay and regret and ineffability _ a
statue that can't really be seen in its entirety with the naked eye
(or the camera lens).
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Regained''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Catherine Deneuve, John Malkovich and Emmanuelle Beart.
Unrated but contains sexual situations. At Lefont Plaza. 2 hours,
45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A beautiful and serious adaptation that will
flummox anyone without a handle on Marcel Proust.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
