r e BC-BURNING-SPEAR25-COX     08-24 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNING-SPEAR25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reggae granddaddy Burning Spear still carries plenty of fire
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After three decades of making reggae music, recording 34 albums
and winning his first Grammy Award, Burning Spear says it's time to
start thinking about retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Not actually retiring, mind you. Just thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on my mind because I know it's going to take place one
day,'' says Burning Spear, aka Winston Rodney, who will be
appearing at the Tabernacle on Saturday night. ``Everyone must
retire at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   But the point of Burning Spear, for now at least, is to keep
playing the ``conscious'' music that has kept his career aflame and
set him worlds apart from other popular reggae artists.
</P>
<P>
   While some old-school artists are slowing down, Spear and his
Burning Band are in the midst of a 50-state tour. At each stop,
they've been performing a marathon mix of classics from his
earliest recordings, such as ``Man in the Hills,'' as well as
tracks from his most recent album, the 1999 Grammy-winning
``Calling Rastafari.''
</P>
<P>
   During his long career, Burning Spear's music has evolved. It
has become more melodic, and the instrumentals of the band are
crisper and more refined. Despite his longevity _ or maybe because
of it _ his voice seems smoother and more energetic than ever.
</P>
<P>
   What hasn't changed is his message. His stage name is the
moniker of the late Kenyan President Jomo Kenyatta. And as an
artist, Burning Spear has been a longtime proponent of black
nationalist Marcus Garvey, for whom three of his albums were named.
</P>
<P>
   His latest release stays true to his social message, without
becoming heavy-handed. And Spear promises a show that, like the
album, will keep fans' heads bobbing while giving them something to
think about long after the concert ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think them will feel the music 'pon a different level in
terms of lyrics and melody,'' Spear says in a gravelly Jamaican
patois. ``There are many social messages we a deal with. The real
message inna de music.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the songs he plans to perform is ``Statue of Liberty,''
which gives voice to the struggles of West Indians and other
immigrants who come to the United States seeking to improve their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about equal rights and justice,'' says Spear of
the album tracks he counts among his favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us come to better our education and do honest work
and are not treated properly. I've been through that. I've seen
that.''
</P>
<P>
   While younger artists battle lyrically for the title of ``don
dada'' _ Jamaican slang for the uncontested ruler of the reggae
landscape _ Burning Spear has inherited the unofficial mantle of
the genre's granddaddy.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one years ago, Rodney was working as a mechanic and
laundryman in a rural section of Jamaica when he had a chance
meeting with a young Bob Marley, sans Wailers. Marley suggested
that Rodney audition for his producer, Coxsone Dodd, who eventually
went on to help launch Burning Spear's career.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, other members of reggae's royal family have died,
including Marley, Peter Tosh and most recently Dennis Brown.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Burning Spear as one of the few grown-ups on the
reggae scene. And like many grown-ups, he's concerend about the
younger generation of reggae artists _ and their fans.
</P>
<P>
   He is especially critical of dance hall performers whose
fast-paced, hard-edged lyrics have been slammed for glorifying gun
violence and raunchy sex and vilifying homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fan of dance hall,'' Spear says bluntly. ``Dance
hall is just generating fas' money; it has no morals. It seems
young people nah care what them listen to. I'm not condemning
anything, by why dem a listen to something they can't gain anything
from? Music should change your ways and your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Although dance hall music has been topping the reggae charts for
years, Spear predicts it will fade away. In the meantime, he's
considering the long haul. There are at least two more Burning
Spear albums planned, including a collection of love ballads, and
an overseas concert tour in the works.
</P>
<P>
   So forget about gold watches and rocking chairs. Burning Spear
still figures he has a gold record left in him, and the only
rocking he'll be doing is when he gets onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This music still has a long way to go,'' he says. ``Me can't
retire just yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More about Burning Spear:
</P>
<P>
   www.burningspear.net
</P>
<P>
   More about reggae: www.niceup.com
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
