<HEADER>
A1317 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DICKEY-BETTS25-COX     08-24 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICKEY-BETTS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Betts: `They don't want me back'
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stories conflict, but it's become apparent that drugs and
alcohol _ long-running problems for the Allman Brothers Band _ have
driven another wedge between the surviving members of the group
that used to happily live together in Macon. As a result, guitarist
Dickey Betts says he has little expectation of ever rejoining the
group he was part of for 32 years before being ignominiously sent
home from a tour three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want me back,'' says Betts, 55, who'll bring his
new band to Variety Playhouse on Sunday. ``So I don't have a choice
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The band originally said ``creative differences'' were the
reason Betts was dumped from the summer tour in mid-May. But Gregg
Allman, who was not available for comment for this article, later
said it was because Betts had addiction problems and ``when it
starts to affect the music, something has to be done about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Betts, speaking from his home in Sarasota, Fla., counters that
he's ``not strung out on drugs, and I don't have an alcohol
problem. I've got an eight handicap at the golf course, and you
can't do that if you've got drug or alcohol problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Betts has said that he checked into a crisis intervention center
for treatment of depression June 3 at his wife's request but denies
Allman's charges that he was arrested. The Boston Globe reported
that a Sarasota County Sheriff's Office report said that ``a
husband and wife'' were having problems that night and that the
husband broke a television, overturned a couch, left and the wife
then asked for help in finding him. Chuck Lesaltato of the
sheriff's office confirmed for rollingstone.com that Betts was the
husband and that he was taken to a crisis intervention center for a
psychiatric evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a lot of tough press from Gregg, who somehow feels
the need to justify what they did to me,'' Betts says. ``I called
Gregg a couple of times and he hung up on me, so I got my attorneys
to force them to meet with me, and when we did, I got different
stories from each guy. I just wished them well. I'd like to see the
band come together for a farewell tour and go out gracefully. ...
I'm grateful for the time I spent in that band.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Betts says he's happy with the seven-piece band he's
put together for his mini-tour opening Saturday in Myrtle Beach,
S.C., and scheduled to end Sept. 22 at Asbury Park, N.J. ``This is
not a throw-together project,'' Betts says, adding that sets will
include tunes from his solo career and from the Allman Brothers
songbook. ``A lot of work has gone into this,'' Betts says. ``I
auditioned players at my house, and now we've been putting in seven
hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The musicians are guitarist Mark May, vocalist Matt Ziner,
bassist Dave Stoltz, saxophonist Chris Jenson, drummer Mark
Greenberg and percussionist Junior Ortiz. ``I've had a lot of bands
since I was 18 years old, but I've never been a guy who wanted a
backup band,'' Betts says. ``With me being more of an
instrumentalist than a vocalist, I enjoy putting guys together and
showing them off. By the time people leave the show, they'll get to
know these guys, because we'll spotlight each guy as we go along.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: Boston Globe, Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more about Dickey Betts, the Allman
Brothers Band: www.allmanbrothersband.com
</P>
<P>
   Russ DeVault writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
