<HEADER>
A1324 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-YOUTH-VOTE- &LR; ADV27-HNS     08-24 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-VOTE- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YOUTH GROUPS REACH OUT TO CAPTURE YOUNG VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
 ADV27-HNS  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, August 27)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND   
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alarmed by the fact that most 18- 24-year-olds
don't vote, national youth and civic groups are mounting a massive
campaign to entice young adults to become politically involved.
</P>
<P>
   After young adults aged 18-20 were given the right to vote in
1972 by the 26th Amendment, the voting rate of 18- to 24-year-olds
fell from 43 percent that year to 28 percent in 1996, according to
the Committee for the Study of the American Electorate, a group
that studies voting trends.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the voting rate among all population groups
declined from 55 percent to 49 percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   As they get older, many young adults are retaining their
nonvoting habits, reversing an earlier pattern in which they began
voting once they started collecting such middle-aged trappings as
mortgages and children. For example, voter participation among 25-
to 34- year-olds dropped from 54 percent in 1972 to 39 percent in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we start doing something about the whole political
culture, the rates of voter participation are going to continue to
decline,'' said Curtis Gans, director of the committee and a
leading analyst of voting behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Younger adults are not apathetic _ in fact, they are the most
activist generation in history, says Steven Culbertson, president
of Youth Service America, an umbrella group for more than 200
national, state and local organizations.
</P>
<P>
   He says young people are choosing to perform volunteer work
instead of voting.
</P>
<P>
   A 1999 survey by the University of California at Los Angeles and
the Higher Education Research Institute of 383,815 students at 668
universities and colleges showed a record 74 percent volunteered
for community service, up from 62 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is that if you volunteer but don't vote, 20 years
from now your kids are going to be cleaning up the same dirty
rivers and tutoring at the same mediocre schools,'' Culbertson
said. ``The large-scale impact doesn't take place until you go to
the ballot box.''
</P>
<P>
   Culbertson said young adults complain that politicians ignore
their concerns. Politicians, in turn, admit overlooking young
adults because they don't vote.
</P>
<P>
   To break this cycle, the group's Servicevote 2000 campaign is
planning six political forums this year at college campuses and
community centers around the country in which young people can ask
questions of federal and state candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Another effort _ this one by Doug Bailey, founder of the
Hotline, a popular politics newsletter _ is working through school
systems by contacting principals around the nation, hoping they
will register 15 million high school students to vote on-line in a
late October mock election.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said the two goals of his Youth-e-Vote program, launched
in January, are ``to turn today's students into tomorrow's voters _
to start them early,'' and ``to facilitate the teaching and
learning of civics.''
</P>
<P>
   The students also will vote on issues such as education and
criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have in this country is a situation where there is
less and less civics taught in the schools and at least 50 percent
(of youths) live in homes of parents who do not vote,'' Bailey
said. ``This is simply an effort to try to re-instill'' voting
habits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Scaggs, a former six-term congressman from Colorado, now
executive director of the democracy and citizenship program at the
Aspen Institute, a nonpartisan research group, is trying to spur
new adults to vote by training political candidates to better
address the concerns of the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get candidates willing to think differently, it's
probably not going to make a lot of progress,'' Scaggs said.
</P>
<P>
   Scaggs has compiled a ``tool kit'' for candidates trying to
reach the estimated 30 million young adults who don't vote.
</P>
<P>
   The kit was distributed last month to 2,400 state and federal
candidates and campaign managers around the nation. It includes
tips such as dressing casually and warns against imitating the
language of youths. ``The phoniness detectors of this age group are
very finely tuned,'' Scaggs said.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates also lose youth audiences when they talk about
``bridging the digital divide'' instead of making sure schools have
computers, or when they refer to ``universal access'' instead of
health care for everyone, said Sharon Bassett, who works with
Scaggs.
</P>
<P>
   Scaggs said many politicians ``tend to have a stereotype of this
age group as cynical and turned off by politics.'' That image ``is
wrong and it feeds into the `why-pay-attention-to-them' frame of
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Scaggs said most young people don't vote because they aren't
familiar with the issues or are intimidated because they don't know
how to push a lever in a voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more a reluctance to do something foolish than a
kind of attitude against politics,'' he said. ``This age group is
not walking around with a negative attitude. It's much more an
attitude of humility and ignorance and not wanting to make a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Youth Vote 2000, a coalition of more than 60 national groups, is
planning a series of debates for state and federal candidates, with
the job of moderator being held down by young journalists aged 18
to 30.
</P>
<P>
   John Dervin, 26, political director for the group, said he
expects questions from young adults will include queries about how
to pay for higher and continuing education and how to pay for
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Dervin said Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic nominee for
president, has agreed to participate in a youth-moderated
presidential debate, but the group hasn't heard from Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Youth Vote 2000 also teamed with the World Wrestling Federation
to seek out younger potential voters. Last month, the partnership
registered thousands of new voters at a Madison Square Garden
match. During the Republican convention in Philadelphia earlier
this month, a 28-year-old wrestler known as ``The Rock'' publicly
signed up to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew Charitable Trust, a private foundation that supports
nonprofit efforts to solve public problems, has in the 1999-2000
election cycle shelled out an unprecedented $4.3 million to boost
young adult voting. The Pew money was used to fund such
vote-related programs as a Project Vote Smart web-site for youth
issues. Pew also paid for students at the Medill School of
Journalism at Northwestern University to report on the presidential
campaign for college campus newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   MTV, which reaches 77 million households, also is working to
boost younger voter participation.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Friedman, vice president of public affairs for the
24-hour cable music video service, said MTV's web site,
www.rockthevote.com, already has registered more than 70,000 young
people to vote so far this year, compared to 42,000 for 1996.
</P>
<P>
   MTV's ``Choose or Lose'' campaign, responding to surveys showing
youths listen best to their peers, employed a ``street team'' of
four young TV reporters to report on issues of concern to young
people at the national political conventions. In another special,
the young reporters interviewed politicians to find out what they
were doing at age 22.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   Judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
