<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1326 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TEST-TRENDS25-COX     08-24 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-TRENDS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TODAY'S KIDS GET HIGHER TEST SCORES; BUT MINORITIES SLIP
 &HT;    600&AMP;adds. With TEST-DATA.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ National test scores are higher for today's
students, but some of the progress in closing the gap between the
races slipped away in the 1990s, said a report issued Thursday by
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Baby Boomers who took similar tests 30 years ago,
today's students of all races have average scores that are
significantly higher on math tests and a little higher on reading
tests.
</P>
<P>
   The results on science tests taken three decades apart were
mixed: 9-year-olds do worse, 13-year-olds do about the same, and
17-year-olds do better than the baby boomers did when they were
that young.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1970 and 1988, the gains by blacks and Hispanics were
even greater than the gains among whites. That narrowed the scoring
gap between whites and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But some ominous trends were confirmed when career researchers
from the National Center for Education Statistics (NCES) looked at
what has happened in the last 10 to 12 years of that 30-year span:
</P>
<P>
   _ Among white students, math and science scores rose more
slowly, and reading scores remained flat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among black students, scores stayed flat in all three
subjects. That wiped out about half of their previous gains in
closing the gap. By 1999, the average math scores of black
17-year-olds and white 13-year-olds were the same.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among Hispanic students, scores were flat, except for gains by
13-year-olds in reading and 17-year-olds in science and math. On
balance, the gap by which their scores trail those of whites
remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Kati(cq) Haycock of the nonpartisan Education Trust, a
Washington-based reform advocacy group, glumly described the more
recent trend as ``disappointing, especially for students of color
and their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCES researchers examined scores on special national tests
given to samples of up to 17,000 students aged 9, 13 or 17 every
two to three years. The tests began in the 1973 school year for
math, 1971 for reading and 1969 for science.
</P>
<P>
   They said that their lengthy, nuanced, and apolitical report
showed what happened, rather than why.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report shows a mixed picture of good news and bad news, of
gains and then of gaps narrowing and widening again,'' said Michael
Nettles, the black scholar from the University of Michigan who is
vice chair of the National Assessment Goals Board, the independent,
bipartisan body that oversees the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually all the reduction in the gaps between whites and
blacks took place (in the 1980s), and since then the gaps have
widened,'' Nettles said. ``This is a depressing reversal of gains
made over the previous two decades.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The average scores of Hispanics are slightly higher than those
of blacks,'' Nettles said. ``In the past decade, the gaps between
whites and Hispanics have fluctuated _ some narrowing, some
widening _ but over all, little has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said minority students have virtually caught up with white
students of their age in learning basic skills, but ``when you move
up to more complicated work the differences appear to be wide.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why that happened, Nettles suggested several
possibilities, but cautioned, ``The only honest answer is that we
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Haycock said she thinks minorities lag because they are less
likely than whites to take advanced math and science courses, and
more likely to attend schools in which those who do take advanced
courses are taught by a teacher who didn't major in that subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their teachers are less qualified and their course-work is
less rigorous,'' she said. ``Put those factors together and, of
course, you get lower test scores.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some evidence for her view was offered by Michael Casserly,
executive director of the Council of the Great City Schools, which
consists of 60 urban school districts that educate 35 percent of
the blacks and 30 percent of the Hispanics in the nation's public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing teachers, particularly math and science
teachers, to higher-paying suburbs,'' Casserly said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, average scores ``have not fallen significantly in any
category'' in the 1990s, said Education Secretary Richard Riley. He
said a slump would have been expected, because weaker students are
less likely to drop out nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, today's schools teach ``a group of students
that is larger and more diverse than ever before _ with higher
percentages of test-takers with disabilities and a higher
percentage whose home language is not English.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the test rules excluded all students who were
identified as having either learning disabilities or
English-language problems judged to be serious enough to affect
their scores.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that ``we have a persistent gap in
achievement and we must work to close it while lifting achievement
for all,'' Riley added, ``In several categories, blacks and
Hispanics are scoring better than ever _ and that is good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the tests fell into nine categories (three age
groups in math, three in reading and three in science), Riley
pointed out that in 1996 or 1999:
</P>
<P>
   _ White children and black children tied or exceeded their
highest scores in six of the nine categories.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hispanic children tied or exceeded their highest scores in
seven of the nine.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Summaries, extracts and the full report are online
at
nces.ed.gov/nationsreportcard/trends/trnd(underscore)results.asp.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
