<SLUG> BC-FILM-TAOOFSTEVE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TAO' MAY BE TOO COOL FOR ITS OWN GOOD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dex (Donal Logue), the protagonist of this indie effort, is the
guy who comes up with the film's title. An overweight Santa Fe
slacker, Dex concocted and practices the ``Tao of Steve,'' a
philosophy of cool detachment based on such macho heroes as Steve
McQueen and ``Hawaii Five-O's'' Steve McGarrett, as a way of
scoring with women.
</P>
<P>
   As Dex explains it, you can't just act uninterested when you're
with a woman; you've got to be uninterested, and then she'll become
so intrigued that she'll want to sleep with you. The camera pans
across Dex's bookshelves, showing rows of philosophy books. But he
seems to have a copy of ``The Rules'' stashed there somewhere as
well, and he simply reversed the genders. Whatever he's doing, it
works. Ten years out of college and passing his time as a
kindergarten teacher, Dex is still quite the ladies' man despite
being, by his own reckoning, 50 pounds heavier since graduation.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins at a college reunion, where Dex meets Syd
(co-screenwriter Greer Goodman), a down-to-earth set designer for
the Santa Fe Opera. Syd quickly challenges Dex's faith in the Tao _
which appears to have more to do with Peter Pan than with Eastern
philosophy _ and he finds himself falling for her. But he still
wants to mess around; it's as if he's in a triangle with Syd,
himself and his own immaturity.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which was directed by Goodman's sister Jenniphr, was
an audience fave at Sundance and has gathered some good prerelease
buzz. It has its moments, and Logue's easygoing frat-boy manner
makes it worth seeing. But the screenplay is a little too
self-consciously offbeat and clever for its own good; you can
figure that out by checking out the lead characters' occupations
and listening to the philosophy-major dialogue. It'll probably be
an art-house hit _ and it's tough to get past the feeling that it
was schemed out that way all along. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
