A1331 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-BRINGITON-TEX     08-24 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BRINGITON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A CHEERLEADING MOVIE, THIS IS PRETTY DISPIRITED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest teen comedy is sort of like ``The Replacements''
turned inside out; instead of being about the lame football team,
it's about the good cheerleading squad that's working its way to
the big game ... er, competition. But it's not even as good as
``The Replacements,'' which has a rowdy affability that makes its
formula construction forgivable. Despite the fast-lane-paced
dialogue, the short-attention-span editing and the frequent rah-rah
scenes, ``Bring It On'' is a little dispirited.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Dunst plays the chirpy new cheerleading captain of an
award-winning San Diego squad. She discovers, with the help of
incongruous newcomer Eliza Dushku, that the team's
competition-winning routines were stolen from a squad in East
Compton, Calif. Dunst and Dushku.MDNM/ lead a likable cast, but
director Peyton Reed seems unable to light a fire under anybody. In
fact, he appears to have been busy extinguishing sparks; anyone who
promises to steal the movie is quickly reined in.
</P>
<P>
   Dushku enters the movie, Gothed-out and dreadlocked, with the
same bird-flipping attitude she had as Buffy's nemesis on the WB's
``Buffy The Vampire Slayer,'' but she's almost as sunshiny as Dunst
before the movie's over. Jesse Bradford, who plays Dushku's brother
and Dunst's love interest, makes an impressive entrance but is soon
enough reduced to reactive crooked smiles from the Freddie Prinze
Jr. school. Gabrielle Union has some edge as the head East Compton
cheerleader, but she's not in the movie nearly enough to make a big
impact.
</P>
<P>
   The elements for a good movie are here, considering the stress
that must go into a real cheerleading competition, but the
impatient editing makes it impossible to appreciate the stunts in
the climactic competition, and the movie is aimless even though you
always know exactly where it's headed.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
