<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1332 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-HAWAII-POPULARITY-100     08-24 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAWAII-POPULARITY-1000(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK BEYOND THE KITSCH AND HULA DANCERS, YOU'LL SEE SOMETHING
WONDERFUL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ We don't talk much on the hike to the top of Diamond
Head, the peak of dry volcanic ash that looms nearly 800 feet over
Waikiki Beach. Even though we had started in the cool hour just
after dawn, the trek requires some exertion, especially at the
brisk pace we're keeping, trying to beat the heat and the crowds
for a clear, panoramic view of the Oahu coast.
</P>
<P>
   But this had been billed as a nature hike, so on the way down,
after she'd pointed out the sprawling beach estate shared by the
Hawaii cast of MTV's ``The Real World,'' our guide begins
explaining the island's unique flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>
   A landscape that seemed lush and colorful and typically Hawaiian
_ macadamia and avocado trees, brilliant hibiscus and plumeria,
tropical songbirds _ had once been even more exotic, she tells us.
Developing in a vacuum, more than a thousand miles from other land
masses, hundreds of species of plants and animals found nowhere
else had evolved on Hawaii. But the humans who settled the islands,
first the Polynesians and then Europeans, brought pigs and chickens
and goats, plus plants such as breadfruit and papayas. Rapidly,
many of the endemic birds, flowers and trees died out, replaced by
the interlopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What took millions of years to evolve on Hawaii, humans
basically destroyed in only a few hundred years,'' she says
soberly, as we pick our way downhill, single file.
</P>
<P>
   Until I'd seen the view from the top of Diamond Head, I had been
formulating a similar thought: Had we tourists had the equivalent
effect in just two generations?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if I had expected Hawaii to be an undiscovered
tropical paradise. The islands have been the American dream of a
vacation destination for at least 40 years, a magnet for
honeymooners and families since before Gidget went Hawaiian or the
Brady Bunch used it as the setting for a Very Special Episode. And
the destinations I had chosen _ three nights in Honolulu, four on
Maui, on the stretch of beach known as Kaanapali _ were the most
visited of all.
</P>
<P>
   But I was traveling with my parents, both in their early 80s,
and the itinerary had been something of a compromise, allowing them
to leisurely revisit sites, like Pearl Harbor, that they had
enjoyed on earlier visits, and giving me a first-timer's overview
so I'd know where I'd want to return to later. I reasoned that I
really just looked forward to spending time with them; it didn't
matter that our schedule would be heavy on touristy sites I might
not choose on my own. And surely, Hawaii was beautiful everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in my first 36 hours in Hawaii, I had been shocked at
its, well, schlockiness. We had sipped weak $7.50 mai tais at a
poolside bar overlooking Waikiki Beach, which was slightly gray and
packed end-to-end with beach towels bearing sunbathers. Honolulu
had struck me as a nondescript city that existed largely to provide
a setting for cheap sushi bars and souvenir shops selling coconut
purses, pearl necklaces and loud print shirts; it looked, in the
words of a well-traveled friend, ``like Oklahoma City with a beach
stuck on the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   And, most horrifyingly, we'd spent a long, hot, endless day at a
Polynesian theme park, staffed by well-meaning students from
Brigham Young University's Hawaii campus. Women and men alike wore
pretty flowered sarongs, danced the hula enthusiastically if not
authentically, and insisted on shouting ``Alo-HA!'' at the
slightest provocation. It was as if we'd found the Hawaiian version
of Branson.
</P>
<P>
   But the trip turned around just before 5 a.m. on my second full
day in Oahu, when I awoke to meet the van transporting us to
Diamond Head.
</P>
<P>
   Early morning is my favorite part of day in almost any new
place, and I was delighted to see streets free of the usual tour
buses, their parking spaces taken by delivery trucks double-parked
in front of restaurants as workers delivered cases of papayas,
pineapples and freshly caught fish. Here and there, shopkeepers
were sweeping sidewalks in front of stores that looked more
inviting minus the crowds; the occasional bicyclist or jogger
crossed our path, taking advantage of the cool early morning.
</P>
<P>
   The sun was a pale pinkish-orange circle, still low in the sky,
as our group of eight pulled into the parking lot at Diamond Head,
so named because British sailors who spotted it in 1825 mistook its
sparkling calcite crystals for precious stones. The peak is
actually a tuff cone, formed of the ash left over from a long-ago
volcanic explosion.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   The summit and the surrounding crater have been used for many
things over the years: Early Hawaiians called it Leahi and crowned
it with a temple, possibly used for human sacrifices. The U.S. Army
built a fort at the edge of the crater, starting in 1909; at the
summit, it added a series of tunnels, bunkers and observation
points. The crater, which in the '60s and '70s was the site of big
rock concerts, now contains a National Guard encampment, picnic
tables and restrooms, and other facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But most people come here to get the view from the top. It is
not as easy a hike as it first appears; the gently sloping path
quickly turns steep and narrow, and just before the peak, there are
a series of stairs and two dark tunnels, the Alcatraz-like remnants
of the old military base.
</P>
<P>
   After less than 40 minutes, however, we're rewarded for our
early start _ we are among the first few of the day to take in the
grand view. It's a clear day, so we can see it all, from the
Waianae Mountains of the leeward coast, to the homes and hotels and
the Waikiki Shell lining the beach, to the lighthouse and the
sailboats and a few hardy surfers in the bay below.
</P>
<P>
   The view is spectacular, and I've enjoyed the walk and the
company of my fellow hikers so much that I feel guilty back in the
van, when I admit to one of them that this was the first thing on
the island I'd really enjoyed. She had been to Hawaii before, and
she hadn't found a part she couldn't love; she warned me gently
against making such a quick judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give it time,'' she said. ``You haven't really seen anything
of Hawaii yet.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Maui,'' my father, who is not usually given to
superlatives, tells the man seated next to him at the Old Lahaina
Luau, a lavish spread on the beach at the edge of Lahaina, the old
whaling seaport on the west coast of the island. We are all
drinking rum punch and wearing fresh-flower leis; our plates are
loaded with roast pig and mahi-mahi and coconut pudding and fresh
tuna and sweet Hawaiian yeast bread. In a few minutes, traditional
hula dancers will take the stage, lit by rows of glowing tiki
torches and featuring a traditional dugout canoe.
</P>
<P>
   It could not be more traditionally ``touristy.''
</P>
<P>
   And I couldn't agree with my dad more.
</P>
<P>
   We have been here for two days, having settled into a spacious
condo just steps from the beach and about 10 minutes from Lahaina,
a village that was built more than 150 years ago to support the
whaling industry and now is largely populated by tourists and the
shops and restaurants that serve them. There is a mall there, in
what used to be a pineapple cannery, and several smart shops and
galleries, selling traditional, gorgeous Hawaiian quilts, oil
paintings with island themes, and sculptures carved of native koa
wood.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was inevitable that Maui was where I'd really learn to
love Hawaii. The second-most recognizable site in Hawaii, after
Waikiki, Maui has been voted the best island destination in the
world four years running by the well-traveled readers of Conde Nast
Traveler. Though it is rife with development _ huge resorts, many
with manicured golf courses and multilevel swimming pools attached,
stretch for miles on its western and southwestern coasts _ it still
seems more laid-back than bustling Honolulu, which is, after all, a
major city that just happens to have a world-class resort attached.
</P>
<P>
   We'd originally planned to visit Maui to see the whales _ it is
a prime winter playground for humpback whales, and whale-watching
is such a popular pastime from January through April that traffic
jams, and accidents, are sometimes caused by carloads of tourists
suddenly braking to peer at the great creatures playing just
offshore.
</P>
<P>
   But our schedules hadn't worked out, so we'd missed whale season
by more than a month. Freed of that major objective, we found
ourselves with a much more flexible schedule than we'd adhered to
on Oahu, giving us plenty of time to shop, eat, sightsee, swim,
walk on the beach, and generally put ourselves on island time.
</P>
<P>
   Our first afternoon on Maui, we wandered into a casual seafood
restaurant on a prime stretch of Front Street, which, as its name
implies, fronts the ocean. A friendly waiter beckoned us to a table
on the wooden deck perched on the edge of the water, and we
lingered for hours, feeding morsels of bread to seabirds and
watching rowers in long canoes glide past, training for an upcoming
race. Other diners were in no hurry, either; we all talked
companionably as we staked out tables to watch the sunset. The
setting was so scenic and cozy we wouldn't have even cared about
the food, but it was wonderful _ barely seared, perfectly cooked
ahi, or tuna (plucked from the Hawaiian waters less than 24 hours
earlier, our server told us proudly).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was just the jet lag finally wearing off, but the
relaxing evening seemed to set the tone for the rest of the trip.
The days quickly developed an easygoing rhythm: Wake just before
dawn, take a freshly brewed cup of coffee to the beach and sit on a
low rock wall, watching the sun rise and talking to my fellow early
risers, like the couple from North Carolina who liked to sculpt
sand castles before the day's waves, and crowds, could destroy
them. Then back to the room to plan the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   One day, it was nothing more taxing than swimming and sunning on
the wide white-sand beach, eating fish tacos at a picnic table that
overlooked the ocean, then saving up for the Lahaina luau, so
authentic in its food, music and dancing that even locals sometimes
attend. (Tourist-centered though it might be, I was fascinated by
the lump of a ``kalua'' pig roasting in a pit and by the carved
bowls, koa-nut necklaces and other crafts being made right on the
grounds by local artisans.)
</P>
<P>
   Another day, we took a circle tour of the island, driving past
pineapple fields, the occasional stray nene, or black-faced
Hawaiian goose, and a flower farm where we stopped to admire dozens
of varieties of brilliant protea, orchids and bromeliads. We got
caught in a sudden rainstorm at the lush Iao Valley, a sharp
counterpoint to the dry western shores; the valley, punctuated by
the soaring rock known as the Iao needle, is a bona-fide rain
forest, with gentle streams, a waterfall and hiking trails amid all
the tropical plants.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   The high point of the tour _ literally, as it turned out _ was
the trip to the top of Haleakala, the world's largest dormant
volcano. The smooth road to the top takes more than two hours to
drive, rising more than 10,000 feet in less than 40 miles of road;
more than a million tourists make their way there annually. The
Hawaiian word for House of the Sun, Haleakala offers the best
vantage site on the island; on clear days, you can see all the way
to the Big Island.
</P>
<P>
   Another morning, after bird-watching on our terrace overlooking
the beach, we decided to go for a drive. The winding, narrow road
to Hana on the east coast, taking more than four hours to traverse
one way, was too much for one day, we decided, so we took off
instead for the little-visited northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few miles north of our condo, the clusters of hotels and
shopping centers began to thin out and the road narrowed. We drove
for miles, only passing another car every five or 10 minutes. Every
few miles, there would be a wide turnout, filled with cars parked
every which way; just below would be a beach, sparsely populated
with sunbathers and swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   The view at every stop was just like a postcard: cliffs tumbling
to the water, waves crashing against white sand beaches and jagged
black rocks, a lone yacht anchored in the bay. No wonder I loved
Maui; this was what I had dreamed of, when I thought of Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, with the benefit of hindsight, even Honolulu came to
grow on me.
</P>
<P>
   I'll remember sitting in the beachside dining room of the Royal
Hawaiian, the big pink hotel that was one of Waikiki's first,
watching the sunset and sipping a Blue Hawaiian (a strong one, this
time) as islanders tied up their catamarans and windsurfers for the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   I'll remember Pearl Harbor: the survivor of the bombing who,
wearing a cap and name tag marking him as a veteran, proudly told
of how he'd fought back that day. The silent ride out to the
memorial at the sunken Arizona, where the names of the dead were
etched on the wall. The oil bubbling up around the floating
memorial, leaking from the battleship entombed beneath, as if the
sea itself were still weeping.
</P>
<P>
   I'll remember the USS Missouri, and standing on the deck where
the Japanese surrendered, and hearing for the first time that my
stepmother's brother had been aboard the ship that day, a witness
to history.
</P>
<P>
   And I'll remember standing on the peak of Diamond Head,
surveying the island spread out below me as the sun rose on another
day in paradise. It was a very good reminder that sometimes,
destinations become popular with tourists for a very good reason.
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
