<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1341 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TAMMYFAYE-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      08-24 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMYFAYE-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-TAMMYFAYE-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    A TRUE LOOK AT TAMMY FAYE'S MAKEUP(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drug abuse. Sex scandals. Vicious backbiting. Missing millions.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, the life of a TV preacher can be pretty rough.
</P>
<P>
   So says (beginitalic)The (enditalic)(beginitalic)Eyes of Tammy
Faye(enditalic), a compelling documentary about life behind the
pulpit that examines the rise and fall of PTL, one of the most
successful television ministries in history.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers Fenton Bailey and Randy Barbato combine old footage,
interviews and an innovative style to produce a stunning portrait
of the so-called ``electric church.''
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Faye, of course, used to be Tammy Faye Bakker. She was
married to televangelist Jim Bakker, who built PTL from nothing,
only to see it destroyed by the Jessica Hahn sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Tammy Faye Bakker Messner has been little more than
a (beginitalic)Saturday Night Live (enditalic)joke. Because of her
garish makeup - the movie includes a hilarious tour of her makeup
bag - and squeaky speaking voice, the mainstream media made her out
to be a clownish loon, little more than an amusing sideshow to
Jim's fall from grace.
</P>
<P>
   In a sympathetic portrait, the film shows the other side of
Tammy Faye, who comes off surprisingly candid and quite sane. If
we're to believe the producers, Tammy Faye is a victim, a
well-meaning Christian entertainer done in by her husband's hubris
and the ambition of fellow TV preacher Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   Narrated by RuPaul, the film notes that Tammy Faye was one of
the first religious figures to openly embrace those who were
rejected by other churches: gays, AIDS victims and drug addicts.
She also survived bouts with drug addiction and cancer, along with
the foundering of her marriage and career.
</P>
<P>
   The film also points out that Tammy Faye was a tireless
entertainer, sometimes doing TV shows for hours at a time with no
script. It's also clear that she has a good singing voice, which
she used to produce dozens of albums.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the movie offers a fascinating look into the early
days of televangelism, which is rooted in the work of old-time
traveling preachers, such as Oral Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   It includes priceless footage from Jim and Tammy's early days,
when they created hand puppets to entertain children on one of the
first Christian TV shows. Their partner was none other than Pat
Robertson, who later became well-known as the host of
(beginitalic)The 700 Club(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   After several false starts, Jim and Tammy struck gold with the
Charlotte, N.C.-based PTL (Praise the Lord) network, which produced
Las Vegas-style shows and eventually was on 24 hours a day. At the
height of their success, the pair built Heritage USA, the world's
first Christian theme park, which, at one time, was third in
attendance behind Disneyland and Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it all came tumbling down after it was revealed that
Jim had had a tryst with Hahn, a young church employee. According
to Tammy Faye, Falwell used that news to leverage the Bakkers out
of PTL. Falwell, for his part, said he assumed control of PTL at
Jim Bakker's request.
</P>
<P>
   The film also takes some shots at (beginitalic)The Charlotte
Observer(enditalic), which won a Pulitzer Prize for its coverage of
the PTL scandal. In one of the film's most poignant moments, Tammy
Faye confronts the reporter who wrote the stories.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he asks for her autograph.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
