<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Aug. 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Lower humidity will return to the Northeast on Friday as light
breezes bring drier air south from Canada. Patches of early fog
will yield to plentiful sun, boosting readings to seasonal levels
by the afternoon. Farther south, scattered showers will accompany a
front plodding south through the Middle Atlantic States. Meanwhile,
partial sunshine and seasonably high humidity will cover the
Southeast with isolated thunderstorms erupting during the heat of
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Oppressive heat will persist in much of the Plains. Amid sunny
skies, daytime highs will near 100 degrees from central Kansas to
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will shroud parts of the Pacific coast, especially in the
Northwest where onshore winds arrive. Most of the West will be dry,
but spotty thunderstorms will form near some mountain peaks in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THE DEMISE OF DEBBY
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, satellite images showed a delicate swirl, the eye
of the storm, emerging from beneath the cluster of clouds that
surrounded Hurricane Debby. The tempest was being torn apart. The
demise of the storm began when part its circulation encountered the
mountains of Hispaniola. As the hurricane weakened, brisk winds
from the east in the lowest 5,000 feet of the atmosphere drove its
low-level circulation away from the tops of the tall thunderstorms
that had been essential to the storm's heat engine. By Thursday,
the swirl had vanished and with it so had the storm called Debby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
