<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SPENT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     08-24 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPENT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPENT': ODDS ARE THIS GAMBLER'S GOT PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Spent'' Max (Jason London) is such an inveterate gambler
that he leaves everything to chance. He picks his sports bets by
writing team names on a piece of paper, then carefully tearing it
up and flinging the scraps into the air. He bets on the teams whose
names are on the pieces he grabs. It's as imaginative a way to play
out a gambling addiction as has been seen in the movies in a long
time. This crazy character moment comes early enough in the picture
to make the audience believe there is going to be more such
characterization ahead. There isn't, though. ``Spent'' coasts on
that gesture and then finally runs out of steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spent'' is essentially a movie about people unable to
communicate, which in this film is synonymous with denial. That
point is made clear by the opening, a montage of motivational
speakers from infomercials bellowing into the camera, admonishing
viewers about wasting their lives and potential.
</P>
<P>
   Max's roommate, Grant (James Parks), has a crush on him but
refuses to admit he is gay. And there are scenes like the one
featuring the of Max's girlfriend, Brigette (Charlie Spradling),
and her parents at brunch. Brigette, who has a drinking problem, is
downing one chardonnay after another. Her mother clicks away with
castanets to make herself the center of attention, and her father
stares obliviously into space.
</P>
<P>
   The writer and director, Gil Cates Jr., is trying to make a
movie out of of grand, memorable sequences like Max's flinging the
bits of paper, and his future, into the air. But much of the rest
of the picture rings hollow and imitative: for example, the glib,
self-mocking chatter between Max, an unemployed actor, and his
show-biz hanger-on friends Doug (Phil Lewis) and Nathan (Erin
Beaux), which reaches at wit and succeeds only in showing the
strain.
</P>
<P>
   The main story, such as it is, involves Max's not coping with
his addiction, persisting in gambling long after it has left him
teetering on personal and financial ruin. A subplot about a script
Doug has written for Jack Nicholson _ a script about a movie star
obsessed with his floor seats for the Lakers _ is too obvious to
get the laughs it's after.
</P>
<P>
   Cates' material feels autobiographical; he must have lived many
of Max's moments, and the pathetic self-absorption of the losers on
the periphery of the movie business has an ache that is often real.
``I got a residual from that `Silk Stalkings' episode,'' Max says
to explain what he's living on. Cates is from a successful show
business family, and he probably grew up knowing the kind of
aimless guys who, in the backs of their minds, always knew they had
money to fall back on. (His father is the well-known television
director Gil Cates; his uncle Joe gets an executive producer credit
on ``Spent,'' and his brother Jonathan is its editor.)
</P>
<P>
   Max is also good at sifting through his options, shifting loans
and debts like chess pieces, and scamming family friends like the
naive Walsh (Barbara Barrie) into keeping him afloat. He gets a
charge from being just barely a step ahead, and the sick look on
his face when he loses a bet shows how deeply he has sunk into his
gambling addiction. But ``Spent'' lacks the junkie's rush, the
juice that keeps gamblers going. Cates wants to set up a mirror,
making Max self-righteous about Brigette's alcoholism. The whole
thing feels minor, though, and the troubles seem only skin deep:
``The Days of Whine and Roses.''
</P>
<P>
   In trying to give all of its characters face time, ``Spent'' is
spread so thin that what narrative thread there is dissipates.
There's an unwieldy attempt to graft farce onto the mingy
melodrama. By the end the most vivid figure on the screen is the
lovable doggie, who goes wherever dangling fingers are waiting to
give the happy pooch a scratch.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SPENT':
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Gil Cates Jr.; director of photography,
Robert D. Tome; edited by Jonathan Cates; produced by Rena Joy
Glickman, Jordan Summers and Gil Cates Jr.; released by Regent
Entertainment. Running time: 91 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Jason London (Max), Charlie Sprad-ling (Brigette), Phill
Lewis (Doug), Erin Beaux (Nathan), James Parks (Grant) and Barbara
Barrie ( Walsh).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHALK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     08-24 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHALK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHALK': A DOWN-AND OUT TALE OF A POOL HUSTLER AND A $10,000 BET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By DAVE KEHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Filmed in 1993 by the members of a San Francisco theater group
for the homeless, ``Chalk'' may be more interesting for what it
represents than for the disappointingly generic down-and-out tale
it relates.
</P>
<P>
   The film is the work of Rob Nilsson, one of the originators of
the contemporary American independent film. (His ``Northern
Lights,'' made in Minnesota, dates back to 1978.) In 1991 Nilsson
moved into the Tenderloin district of San Francisco with the
intention of writing a screenplay about the area's inhabitants. As
part of his preparation he founded a free acting workshop, the
Tenderloin Action Group, open to any resident of a San Francisco
shelter. Although the original project never got off the ground,
Nilsson discovered a number of promising performers and wrote
``Chalk'' with the help of his longtime collaborator, Don Bajema,
around the talents of the nonprofessional actors.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the movie takes place in a harborfront pool hall called
the Crab Tree _ actually a Bay Area warehouse fixed up by Nilsson
and his crew _ where the wily, ailing owner, Earl Watson (Edwin
Johnson), urges on the sibling rivalry between his unsuccessful
son, Jones (Johnny Reese), who is half-Korean and half-black, and
TC (Kelvin Han Yee, a professional actor), an Asian-American whom
Watson took under his wing when he was a child and developed into a
world-class pool hustler. Jones urges TC to take on the legendary
pool shark Dorian James (played by the wiry Bajema) for a $10,000
bet, secretly hoping that his brother will lose and his father's
affection will return to him.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson's affection for the work of John Cassavetes is apparent
in every dark, smoky frame of ``Chalk,'' which strives to capture
the grit and authenticity of Cassavetes' 1976 ``Killing of a
Chinese Bookie.'' But Nilsson doesn't have his elder's sense of
structure _ apparently improvised, Cassavetes' films were actually
tightly scripted and carefully composed _ and much of ``Chalk''
feels aimless and repetitive.
</P>
<P>
   A former shipyard worker who became a drifter after the death of
his wife, Johnson is cool and convincing as Watson, a character who
combines Don King and King Lear. But many of the other
characterizations suffer from excessive sentimentality _
revelations of soft interiors beneath tough exteriors _ and the
film finally fails to escape the conventions of the Hollywood
cinema it so proudly deplores.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years after its making, ``Chalk'' still has not found a
national distributor and is being released theater by theater by
members of the Tenderloin Action Group. In New York it opens Friday
at the Two Boots Pioneer Theater in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `CHALK'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rob Nilsson; written by Don Bajema and Nilsson;
director of photography, Mickey Freeman; edited by David Schickele;
music by Tim Alexander; produced by Rand Crook and Ethan Sing;
released by Tenderloin Action Group/Pacific Rim Media. Running
time: 135 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Edwin Johnson (Watson), Johnnie Reese (Jones), Kelvin Han
Yee (TC), Don Bajema (Dorian James), Denise Concetta Cavaliere
(Lois), John Tidwell (Johnnie) and Destiny Costa (Wanda). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
