<HEADLINE>
ONE-THIRD LESS IN BAY STATE WITHOUT HEALTH INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' robust economy helped cut the number of
people without health insurance by almost a third, giving 158,000
more people access to regular medical care than in 1998, according
to a state report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that the number of uninsured children was
reduced by half, leaving only 2.8 percent of Massachusetts kids
without coverage.
</P>
<P>
   At time when the uninsured population in the United States
continues to swell, state officials said the finding was a
testament to the unique, medically-focused, political climate here,
where a Republican governor and private businesses were among the
driving forces behind the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the medical and public health capital of the world,''
said state Department of Public Health Commissioner Howard Koh.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that about 1 in 20 state residents were without
health coverage in 1999. The national figure is 1 in six, or 44
million people. Only 1 in 50 children here were uninsured, the
study found, compared to more than 1 in 10 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci trumpeted the report at the Boston
Medical Center Thursday, where a crowd of doctors and
administrators gathered in the hospital's lobby to hear him
proclaim that the state's uninsured population had ``fallen
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing better than the nation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report did contain one troubling finding, said Celucci: The
number of blacks without coverage was double that of whites, and
the number of uninsured Latinos tripled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unacceptable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But overall the increase in insurance coverage represents a
significant advance in the quality of life for state residents,
said health experts. Those with coverage are more likely, though
regular check-ups, to diagnose and treat health problems before
they become serious. And they have access to prescription drugs,
which have become crucial in keeping chronic health problems in
check.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the uninsured are the working poor, according to
the report. More than two-thirds of the uninsured had jobs. Of
those, about 70 percent had employers that elected not to offer
health coverage for economic reasons, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Massachusetts employers were more likely to offer
insurance than their counterparts in most other states, said health
policy experts. In 1999 Massachusetts had 2.1 percent unemployment;
the number of employers that refused to offer coverage dropped to 7
percent, from 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been a culture here among employers of
providing coverage,'' said Rick Lord, president of the Associated
Industries of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Lord sounded the only discordant note of the day when he
attacked a universal health care proposal that will appear on the
November election ballot. If passed, it would mandate universal
government-provided health coverage. Lord said such a measure
``would dismantle the HMO system'' because patients might be able
to select any doctor they desire.
</P>
<P>
   Lord and the 5400 companies he represents are in the midst of
developing a fall ad campaign aimed at defeating the ballot
question, under the banner of ``No On Five.'' They believe it would
increase health care costs in general and put HMOs out of business.
They prefer the approach championed by Cellucci, which seeks to
slowly chip away at the uninsured population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incremental approach is working,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those increments is the state's Children's Medical
Security Plan, which offers coverage to every child in the state.
The only obstacle to covering all of them, said officals, is
informing parents of the program's existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been beating the doors down,'' said Cellucci, promising
to continue the effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
