<HEADLINE>
`BITTERSWEET MOTEL': LOVE PHLOWS BETWEEN PHISH AND PHANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sheer niceness is not a quality you expect to find in a rock
concert film. But niceness is precisely the ambience of
``Bittersweet Motel,'' Todd Phillips' bland, unrevealing
documentary of the hugely popular cult band Phish on tour in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This rock quartet is one band for whom the standard equation of
sex, drugs and rock 'n' roll hardly applies. Instead of sex, think
hugs and naked fans innocently romping outdoors. Instead of drugs,
think soy milk strained through homemade oatmeal cookies. Or the
Grateful Dead with the mystical psychedelic burners turned on low.
</P>
<P>
   True, Phish's redheaded lead singer, Trey Anastasio, is shown
drinking beer, and in one scene he might be a tiny bit tipsy. But
guzzling beer is something even the squarest college Joes like to
do on a Saturday night. Another scene observes some teen-age
parking attendants at a Phish concert discussing the chemistry of
marijuana, but the members of Phish itself aren't shown smoking or
snorting anything.
</P>
<P>
   As for sex, one scene finds Anastasio amiably fending off an
enthusiastic but inarticulate female fan who might possibly have
designs on him. If she does, he seems not to notice. Instead of
exuding any macho Dionysian charisma or sartorial flash in concert,
Phish prefers to convey the bonhomie of superannuated collegiate
nerds. (The band members are all in their mid-30s.)
</P>
<P>
   Of the four, Anastasio has by far the most screen time. He muses
affably about a bad review that accused Phish of artistically
``urinating on the audience'' and expresses pride that over the
years, the members have remained friends. He was born in New Jersey
and describes himself as a child of the '70s in his eclectic
musical tastes. The quartet's other members _ its keyboardist, Page
McConnell; its bassist, Mike Gordon; and its drummer, Jon Fishman _
remain politely in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Phish's very first gig, at an ROTC dance in the mid-80s,
Anastasio recalls, was not a success, and the students tried to
drown out the band's version of ``Proud Mary'' by turning up the
volume on Michael Jackson's ``Thriller.'' But Phish improved and
developed an ever-widening fan base, largely through word of mouth
and more recently through the Internet. The group eventually became
America's most popular band to sustain a following while remaining
largely under the radar of the mass media. Phish's albums have sold
in the millions without the benefit of hit singles or MTV
promotional buzz. Like the Dead, to whom Phish is inevitably
compared, the group is known for marathon concerts that are never
the same and draws the same kind of nomadic hordes who follow the
band from gig to gig.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bittersweet Motel'' includes quite a bit of music, but not
nearly enough to show the band's range of musical interests or its
ability to create wonderful free-floating jams. Its essential style
is an upbeat, improvisatory folk-rock, reminiscent of the Dead's,
that often rides on a cheerfully chugging beat. Like the Dead,
Phish lacks a polished lead singer, and the group's homegrown vocal
harmonies are frequently out of tune. But that's part of its folksy
charm.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic event in the movie is an outdoor concert near
a small town in Maine at which the fans were invited to take off
their clothes and lie down in a circle. Glimpsed from afar, the
spectacle of 1,200 naked bodies scrunched together resembles
nothing so much as a huge stack of freshly caught fish baking in
the sun. Or is that baked Phish?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BITTERSWEET MOTEL'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Todd Phillips; director of photography,
Elia Lyssy; edited by Alan Oxman; music by Phish; released by
Stranger Than Fiction Films. At Cinema Village, 22 East 12th
Street, Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Phish: Page McConnell, Trey Anastasio, Jon Fishman and
Mike Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 80 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
