<P>
   CLINTON-NIGERIA (Washington) President Clinton heads for Africa
Friday, hoping to spotlight the fragile new democracy in Nigeria as
an example for the rest of the continent to follow. He'll meet
Nelson Mandela in Tanzania and discuss the peace process in
Burundi, Rwanda, and Congo. By John Donnelly. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BUSH (New Orleans) _ After admitting he has not done a
good enough job selling his $1.3 trillion tax-cut proposal, George
W. Bush trades complicated arithmetic for the testimonial of a
smiling family of four as proof his plan would help working
Americans and not just the wealthy. By Glen Johnson and Jill
Zuckman. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOLPHINS-WHISTLES (Undated) _ Dolphins use ``signature
whistles'' to recognize individuals, much as humans rely on the
recognition of faces. Research shows they will imitate the
signature whistle of another dolphin to address that individual. By
David L. Chandler. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-INSURE (Boston) _ The number of people without health
insurance in Massachusetts dropped dramatically over the last year,
a product of a booming economy and state efforts to get more people
into Medicaid. The development bucks the national trend, and
leaders from both sides of the political spectrum praise it as a
significant advance in quality of life. By Raja Mishra. 700 words.
</P>
