<SLUG> BC-MOST-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MOST TERRIBLE TIME': PRIVATE EYE   AVENGING   SOME PUBLIC
THUGGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By DAVE KEHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A mildly amusing Japanese appropriation of 1950s American
detective movies, ``The Most Terrible Time in My Life'' relates the
life and crimes of a Yokohama private dick named Maiku Hama. Say it
fast four or five times and the hidden reference to Mickey
Spillane's notably brutal character Mike Hammer grandly emerges.
</P>
<P>
   Hama is played by Masatoshi Nagase, the dyspeptic, terminally
bored-looking young man Jim Jarmusch recruited to play a lethargic
Japanese tourist in his 1989 ``Mystery Train.'' At first, it's
surprising to see how little Nagase appears to have aged in 11
years. It turns out that ``The Most Terrible Time,'' which opens
Friday, was actually made in 1993 and has since been patiently
awaiting American distribution.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, America has probably not been awaiting ``The Most
Terrible Time in My Life,'' patiently or otherwise, since this
nation is fully capable of producing mildly amusing detective
spoofs all on its own. The director, Kaizo Hayashi, incorporates
the references, standard since Jean-Luc Godard's ``Breathless,'' to
the Bogart myth and the gangster films of the big hat, pin-stripe
suit era. But where Godard was revealing the unstable existential
underpinnings of the Bogart legend, Hayashi offers a far more
naive, romantic version of the material. It often feels like little
children playing dress-up, and indeed the film was said to have
started a fad for private detective gear among Japanese teen-agers
when it was released.
</P>
<P>
   Nagase does look sharp in his pork pie hat and sunglasses,
particularly when he hops behind the wheel of his lustrously
polished 1954 convertible. Maiku Hama keeps his office in a heavily
symbolic location, just off the upper balcony of a run-down
neighborhood movie theater where ``The Best Years of Our Lives'' is
playing to small groups of Yokohama film buffs. (The Japanese
characters on the marquee flip over to reveal the title of
Hayashi's film.) But his work comes to him in the storefront
gambling parlor where he spends his lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   He rescues a Taiwanese busboy from a savage beating by local
Yakuza thugs, losing his little finger in the process. When the
busboy, Yang Haitin (the actor uses his own name in the part),
wants to reward Hama for his efforts, he offers to pay him to find
his brother, De Jian (Hou De Jian), who has disappeared into the
Japanese underworld and taken on a Japanese name.
</P>
<P>
   The film finds its only resonance here, in the theme of mainland
immigration and the prejudice that Korean immigrants in particular
experience in Japan. ( Hayashi was born to Korean parents in
Kyoto.) The brother is actually a big-time hood who is organizing a
group of fellow newcomers into a brutal new gang, which he calls
the New Japs; it's a development that adds a deepening darkness and
violence to the film's final reels.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a film more about look and attitude than about
social issues. Its outstanding feature is the soft-edged,
black-and-white wide-screen images contributed by Yuichi Nagata.
They almost perfectly recapture the look of Japanese underworld
films of the 1950s and '60s, like Mikio Naruse's ``When a Woman
Ascends the Stairs'' and Akira Kurosawa's ``High and Low.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Most Terrible Time in My Life'' was a hit in its home
country and inspired two sequels, one of which, the garishly
colored ``Stairway to the Distant Past,'' is given a preview at the
end of this film. More patient waiting appears to be in store. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE MOST TERRIBLE TIME IN MY LIFE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kaizo Hayashi; written (in Japanese, with English
subtitles) by Hayashi and Daisuke Tengan; director of photography,
Yuichi Nagata; edited by Nobuko Tomita; music by the Meina Co.;
production designer, Takeo Kimura; produced by Shunsuke Koga,
Hayashi and Yu Wei Yen; released by Viz Films/Tidepoint Pictures.
Running time: 92 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Masatoshi Nagase (Hama Maiku), Kiyotaka Namba (Hoshino),
Shiro Sano (Kanno), Yang Haitin (Yang Haitin), Hou De Jian (Hou De
Jian) and Kaho Minami (Bai Lan).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
