<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Aug. 25 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ In a clear warning to the
Palestinians to compromise on Jerusalem and other issues, Prime
Minister Ehud Barak said Thursday that he was prepared if the peace
talks fail to invite the right-wing Likud party to join in a
national unity government and even to appoint Ariel Sharon, the
hawkish former army general who is Likud's leader, as foreign
minister. A month after the Camp David peace talks ended with wide
differences over Jerusalem between Barak and Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, Barak's suggestion appeared to be putting
Arafat on notice that Israel could back away from its offer of a
limited foothold in Jerusalem for the Palestinians and establish a
government that, with Likud at its heart, would almost certainly
put a break on any peace deal that involved major concessions to
the Palestinians. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-U.S. (Bogota) _ As President Clinton prepares to visit
Colombia next week and turn on the spigot of military aid,
Colombia's neighbors are expressing growing concerns that an
escalation of the fighting here could cast coca growing, drug
trafficking, refugees and even fighting across their borders. The
Colombian conflict has already led to guerrilla incursions into
Panama and Venezuela for safe haven. U.S. military officials warn
that one Colombian rebel group already exerts influence over Indian
dissidents in Ecuador, and new Colombian plantings of coca and
poppies have been reported in Peru. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-OUTLOOK (Biala Rawska, Poland) _ Urszula Malinowska is a
symbol of Poland's new market economy, the active boss of one of 2
million small and medium-sized private enterprises in a country of
42 million people. But like many Poles, she's not especially happy
with the way things are, and she is likely to vote for the reformed
Communists in parliamentary elections expected next spring, dumping
the more conservative Solidarity alliance. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT16 sent Aug. 23, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-AD (Washington) _ On the decision, supported by George W.
Bush, to drop plans to air a Republican Party TV ad questioning Al
Gore's veracity and featuring an old videotape of the vice
president. (Summary from wires) By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-POLITICS (Lummi Indian Reservation, Wa.) _ Mention the
name Slade Gorton in this far corner of Indian Country and some
people will talk about Slade Gorton the senior senator from
Washington who helped to secure $15 million this year to replace a
decrepit tribal school. But most people will think of Slade Gorton
the Indian fighter, the better-known and much-feared figure, a
72-year-old Republican who has spent much of his public life
battling the Lummis and other tribes on everything from fishing
rights to the power of governing their own affairs. In all the
years that Gorton has feuded with American Indians, he has never
suffered a strong political backlash from the tribes. But this
year, flush with money from casino gambling operations, Indians
across the country say they are going to make him pay. By Timothy
Egan.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT10,11, and a map.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-BUYERS-CLUBS (Undated) _ After decades of ceding control
over their care to cost-conscious health plans, consumers appear
ready to reclaim at least some of the decision-making authority
that they had in the years before managed care. Now, a number of
new companies are setting up shop, often on the Internet, to offer
people with little or no health care discount medical services,
cheaper prescription drugs and reduced rates on everything from
dental care and chiropractics to eye care and acupuncture. The new
companies, many of which operate like buyers' clubs like Costco,
are intended to let consumers and their doctors, decide which
medical services they need rather than deferring to case managers
at a managed-care companies. Customers pay for medical services
with cash or credit cards and typically pay a small annual fee to
belong to the plan. In exchange for the opportunity to get paid
immediately, doctors in the programs agree to serve consumers at
reduced fees comparable to those they receive from managed care
companies. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT11 sent Aug. 23, and a graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
