<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-CAPITAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABUJA JOURNAL: NIGERIA'S NEW AND NEUTRAL CAPITAL AWAITS CLINTON'S
VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria _ The street was wide open, with more lanes than
cars, on a quiet afternoon here in Nigeria's shiny new capital. But
somehow, Usman Muhammed, an excitable 28-year-old taxi driver, had
gotten into a fight with a Peugeot immediately recognizable as a
government-owned car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government drivers, they are useless! Criminals!'' Muhammed
yelled, nearly colliding his jalopy with the Peugeot. ``My friend,
why are you driving rough?''
</P>
<P>
   The Peugeot came to a stop at an intersection where Muhammed's
``friend'' promptly used his right hand to form the equivalent of
the Nigerian finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Abuja,'' Muhammed said, somewhat deflated, ``they are all
driving rough.''
</P>
<P>
   He perked up, though, on seeing a Toyota Corolla, which he had
long coveted. ``Once I buy that car,'' he said, ``I go marry my
wife.'' He would have it made, as he explained in Nigerian English:
``Big man don come.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of the big men, President Clinton, is to arrive on
Saturday in Abuja, a city that has long been home to government
rough drivers and ordinary Nigerians with big dreams. Nigeria
decided to move its capital from Lagos and create a new one a
quarter of a century ago. But it was only in the last decade that
the government moved here and Abuja grew from a town to be the
capital of Africa's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   The concentration of so many new government buildings, new
villas, new hotels and new cars on new roads in a country where
every other city seems to teeter on collapse has long fueled
visitors' imaginations, sometimes in unexpected ways. For example,
the troubles in the oil-producing Niger Delta were said to have
grown in recent years after youths from the region came here.
Gaping at the gleaming new capital that the country's oil had
built, they returned to their villages in the mangrove swamps with
a militancy that has since pushed the delta to the brink of civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos _ a city that many Nigerians regard with the same kind of
awe and loathing with which many Americans view New York _ was
abandoned as the capital because it was too crowded, too dangerous,
too closely linked to the Yoruba, the main ethnic group in the
area. In a nation riven with ethnic cleavages, a new capital in a
neutral zone, geographically in the center of the country, was
needed, a symbolic home for all Nigerians. Abuja, an African
Brasilia, was born.
</P>
<P>
   Still, telltale signs of dominance by Nigeria's Muslim
northerners dot Abuja. The new National Assembly building looks
like a mosque. A gold-domed mosque sits in the middle of the city,
not far from an unfinished church.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his two-day visit to Nigeria, Clinton will stay here
with his host, President Olusegun Obasanjo. U.S. officials rejected
visits to the north and south, partly for security reasons, partly
for political ones. Calls to the north and southeast would have
left out and angered those in the southwest. Any visit to a city
other than Abuja would have been a slight to Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   And so Clinton will remain stuck in the neutral zone that is
Abuja.
</P>
<P>
   In Lagos, whose residents look down on Abuja the same way New
Yorkers do on Washington, the news came as a shock. If Abuja knows
how to build beautiful roads, Lagos knows how to party. There is
fine pepper soup in every neighborhood restaurant, the best
musicians from the region, enough thrills to provide plenty of what
some English-speaking West Africans call ``life enjoyment.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much life enjoyment here in Abuja, which becomes a ghost
town on weekends when politicians leave to visit their villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``By leaving Lagos out of Clinton's itinerary, it's a big
mistake,'' said James Uloko, 39, who works in public relations in,
naturally, Lagos. ``From Lagos, you can see all the colors of life
in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   At a market here, Sylvester Ebere said he did not want any of
that color.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Abuja for security reasons,'' said Ebere, acknowledging
that he had never set foot in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   Ebere, 23, moved to Abuja two weeks ago, looking for job
opportunities he has yet to find. ``British trained,'' said Ebere,
who said he had worked as a gardener for a British-owned company in
Kaduna.
</P>
<P>
   For now he is living with his brother, Joel, 28. They were
marketing products like skin cream and tooth powder and share a $7
a month cubicle on the outskirts of Abuja.
</P>
<P>
   Housing was the hardest part of living here, said Tony Njoku,
42, a businessman, who paid about $300 a year for a two-bedroom
apartment, 45 minutes from Abuja. Something comparable in the city
itself could cost $2,500. ``No common man is able to rent here,''
said Njoku, who moved here in the late 1980s when Abuja's
population was around 15,000. Now it is an estimated 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1991 that Nigeria's former military ruler, Gen.
Ibrahim Babangida, formally transplanted the capital here, some
months after surviving a coup attempt in Lagos. Since then, in this
country whose economy still depends almost entirely on the
government, the center of gravity has shifted here.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim Muhammed, 55, a jobless man from the northern state of
Jigawa, said he had come to Abuja to support his two wives and 23
children back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually go to some big men from my area, who are in
government jobs, to ask for contracts,'' Muhammed said, explaining
that he then sold the contracts _ to clean a road here or to cater
some food there _ to a third party for a markup.
</P>
<P>
   ``But things are very difficult now,'' he said, adding that
Obasanjo's administration had cracked down on the freewheeling
spending of the past. ``The officials no longer want to see us.
They now prefer to give contracts to their girlfriends. You can
hardly see them inside their cars with dark tinted windows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
