<HEADLINE>
HOW ANIMAL INSTINCTS FIGURE IN FALL FASHION. (WITH PHOTO) 
BY LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
Not all the hides and skins for fall are showing up as clothing.
The accessories market is an easy and sometimes less expensive way
for women to update last year's wardrobe.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Check out a sampling of what's in store, clockwise from top
left: Blue-green snake pumps by Ferragamo, $390 at Neiman Marcus,
add a surprising note of color.
</P>
<P>
   A blue dyed rabbit tote bag, $295 at Saks Fifth Avenue, is lined
with a shocking color.
</P>
<P>
   Adrienne Landau's red fur fling, $415 at Neiman Marcus, adds a
touch of fur in warmer climates.
</P>
<P>
   Tip your hat to style with Eric Javits' python hat, $375 at
Neiman's.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not an optical illusion. These Emanuel Ungaro
stiletto-heeled pumps, $350 at Neiman's, are more python than
suede.
</P>
<P>
   Small leather goods are slithering into style with
python-embossed belts such as this blue snake, $80 at Neiman's, and
turquoise snake or tan pony cuffs, $155 and $80 respectively at
Neiman's.
</P>
<P>
   An itsy-bitsy bit of fur could set off an evening ensemble. This
pastel blue dyed rabbit bag is $125 at Saks.
</P>
<P>
   Think of this season's colorful suede and leather jackets as fun
accessories. This teal Emanuel Ungaro leather is $695 at Saks.
</P>
<P>
   X X XEND OF STORY
</P>
