<HEADER>
A1377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-FASH-ANIMALINSTINCTS-     08-24 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASH-ANIMALINSTINCTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEATHER, SUEDE, FUR AND OTHER ANIMAL INSTINCTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
In a season when political parties are bending over backward to be
politically correct, the fashion industry appears to be taking on
the entire animal population.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Designers followed a decade of converting leopard print to a
classic with a couple of seasons of toying with their favorite pony
prints. Then they moved on to zebras and tigers, and now pythons
and crocodiles, not to mention herds of leather and suede garments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see a cow anywhere, call us,'' said Judy Pryor, owner
of Pryorities boutique in Houston, Tex. ``There is so much leather
for fall we're afraid there's probably not a cow left.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet leather in the new millennium is not the same as leather in
the 1980s or '90s, but more a way to update all-neutral wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
   In the over-the-top '80s, leathers were hard-edged, executed as
entire suits or dresses with pleats, ruching and metallic trims.
Then when the fashion world emerged from grunge into the
minimalistic years, the look was a simple black leather jacket,
skirt or pant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black leather jacket especially has become a necessity,''
said Christina Kerford, public relations manager for Macy's. ``It's
a key piece for every wardrobe.'' With that in mind _ and in their
closets _ her customers are now moving on to color.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor said that this year her customers are combining leather
with lace and looking to buy metallic leathers and ruffled leather
skirts. For holidays, she will stock turquoise and violet leather,
but the looks are not garish.
</P>
<P>
   Designers are using leather and suede more like fabrics. This
year's soft, thin leather is drapey and sensual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think of fashion-forward things like this unlined, coral
suede jacket, with its fringed edges, as anything but an
accessory,'' Pryor said. ``It's lightweight, it's fun and it's
hip.'' And it has a price tag of $335.
</P>
<P>
   Leathers and suedes come in a wide range of prices, however, and
for those who want to spend even less, there is pleather, a sort of
``plastic leather.''
</P>
<P>
   Other less expensive lookalikes are moleskin, a polyester blend,
and washable suede.
</P>
<P>
   Many women may update their wardrobes with a python-print
blouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many animal prints have become classics,'' said Erin Carmack,
director of fashion presentation for Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Cows and snakes can thank their lucky stars for crocodiles and
alligators, whose popularity is on the upswing this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's new this season is not leopard but crocodile _ real,
faux or printed _ although python is still strong for fall and
winter,'' Carmack said.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar tile patterns of crocodile skins are being printed
on fabrics as thin as chiffon and embossed on thick leathers for
handbags and shoes. Real skins are around _ at a price.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein and Donna Karan are showing real crocodile clothing
that is cost-prohibitive for most women.
</P>
<P>
   ``A jacket can easily run $20,000,'' she said, noting that with
new technology, designers and manufacturers are achieving crocodile
prints as authentic-looking as the work achieved by the makers of
artificial wood flooring.
</P>
<P>
   Lane Bryant, retailer of plus-size fashions, is carrying
crocodile- and python-patterned pants and skirts in a thick
polyester faux leather.
</P>
<P>
   Not so more conservative dressers. In many stores, python has
reproduced faster than rabbits. It was the logical move after the
customer tired of leopard, with python's ability to shine in either
neutral or bright colors.
</P>
<P>
   In an astonishing turnaround, many, if not most of this fall's
fur accessories are real, not the popular faux.
</P>
<P>
   At Saks Fifth Avenue, for example, furs figure heavily in the
look called ``Neander girl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as the beginnings of life in fashion, the wild,
fun-sister side of this fall's ladylike, uptown dresser,'' senior
vice president Jaqui Lividini said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fur may be fake or real _ it doesn't matter,'' Lividini
said. ``It's all over the body, but it's not your mother's fur
coat. It's patched, trimmed, shearling, long-haired and colorful.
Color _ that's the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the must-haves for fall, she said, is fur neckwear, in
the form of a doughnut collar, shawl or cape. But seeing
full-length fur coats on the street again is not out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are fur bags at Saks, from itsy-bitsy fluffs for
luncheons or evening to tote-size bags in dulled-down shades of
red, green or blue rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   In most women's wardrobes, however, fur is an accessory, a bit
part, not a necessity like leather.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
