<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1378 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-FASH-PLAID-HNS &LR;      08-24 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASH-PLAID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOW YOUR STRIPES IN FUNKY PLAIDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
For fall, the ladylike side of the sportswear equation is tweed.
For the younger, hipper crowd, however, style equals plaid _ and
mothers may be jealous.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of these plaids look like ancestral tartans _
red-and-black, navy-and-green. Others are art-project explosions of
color. Picture rust with burgundy, fuchsia with lime green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plaid should be funky,'' said Lisa Spain, owner of Cotton Club
in Houston. ``We're using it with suede, leather, little cashmere
sweaters or just as plaid shoes. The look is very clean with only
plaid feet. We don't want our customer looking like a schoolgirl.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Spain doesn't want her youngest customers,
for whom she ordered plaid jumpers, looking too old.
</P>
<P>
   Today's interest in plaid began with the successful rejuvenation
of the house of Burberry. Under the leadership of Rose Marie Bravo,
former president of Saks Fifth Avenue, young designer Roberto
Menichetti moved from a British line of dowdy designs bought mainly
by tourists to high fashion sold around the world. Now Burberry
offers its signature plaid on bikinis.
</P>
<P>
   Plaids for fall look different for more than their colors,
ruffles _ yes, ruffles _ and pairings with animals prints. Some
designers, such as Tommy Hilfiger and Michael Kors, took an Op Art
look, morphing plaids into bold graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Others excelled by cutting plaid on the bias, meaning diagonally
across the fabric.
</P>
<P>
   With A-line skirts and dresses, bias cutting means more movement
and a more body-conscious garment. In looks, bias cutting equals
cute _ far from the school-uniform syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Plaid shows in prom and ball-gown designs, as well as in
feminine, scarf-neck blouses that might look great under a tweed or
leather jacket.
</P>
<P>
   But don't wear plaid head-to-toe. Mix with other mediums, such
as denim, leather and suede, and even other patterns, including
argyle, camouflage, leopard, tiger, ostrich, crocodile and python.
These are the funky looks to which Spain referred.
</P>
<P>
   Camel, the new neutral of fall, also mixes well with plaid. Just
a touch of plaid _ a shoe or a shirt _ is the modern way to update
last year's gray flannel suit.
</P>
<P>
   Or use it with a twist of embroidery or leather trim, or pair
plaid with a cashmere sweater or leather jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Plaids were last strong during the grunge period of the late
'80s, but wearing plaids today is more fun, not as contrived.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
