<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SENIORS-DANCING-ART-2     08-24 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORS-DANCING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WALLFLOWERS IN DANCE HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SANDEE BRAWARSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Frank Sinatra is singing ``Blue Skies'' as my
80-something cousin Ceil Merritt changes from her sensible street
shoes into a pair of metallic gold strappy heels. They could be
Cinderella's slippers. For in the next hour and a half she will be
transported from the world of a senior with her share of aches and
pains to that of a fairy princess, dancing waltzes, tangos and
rumbas with a series of princely partners.
</P>
<P>
   Ceil is a regular at the weekly ``Dance Evenings Elegante,''
held on Thursday nights in the social hall of an Upper East Side
church and on alternate Saturday evenings at the Roseland 2000
ballroom, a converted garage in Nutley, N.J. At these events, no
one stands on the sidelines hoping to be asked to dance, and no one
suffers partners who don't know a mambo from a merengue. With twice
as many female dancers as male dancers, the women dance every other
dance, with a chance to rest in between. For the women who
participate, this is dance heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The private dance parties are the invention of Stan Martin, a
magical dancer who began holding them in 1962. As a dance director
at a studio, he was frequently asked by students to continue their
lessons in dance clubs, at their expense. Happily married, he
turned them down, but he then consented to accompany two women at
once, and dance alternately with them. To the sounds of Guy
Lombardo and his orchestra at the Roosevelt Grill, the women had a
fabulous time.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, others asked to join, and Martin, whom everyone
calls Stan, approached another dance instructor about joining them.
The group multiplied quickly, maintaining its 2:1 ratio. When the
Roosevelt Grill closed, they moved to the Savoy Plaza, and when
that was slated for demolition, they tried the Manhattan Room of
the Hotel New Yorker, the Promenade at Rockefeller Center, the St.
Regis roof and the Hotel Taft.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we opened our doors, the hotels closed theirs,'' Stan
explained. For more than 30 years, with Peter Jones, also a former
dance-studio director, as his business partner, they ran the
evenings at Roseland on West 52nd Street. When the ballroom limited
its hours, they shifted to private clubs and then to their present
home at St. Jean Baptiste Roman Catholic Church in Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a high-ceilinged chamber on the church's lower level, the 20
or so women greet one another like old friends. Made up with care,
most wear dresses with color and flair. Adjacent to pillars at the
far end of the room, four tables are set with plastic tablecloths
and cups for water, with each woman's place marked with a small
envelope hand-lettered with her name, for the evening's fee. The
single artificial flower at the center of each table becomes a lush
bouquet as the music and dancing begin, and the makeshift dance
hall becomes a palace ballroom in the not-too-distant dreams of the
participants. Elegante, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the women are in their 80s, although the participants
ranged widely in age, with the youngest in her 30s. A lot of years
of dancing _ and a lot of stories _ percolate in the room. Some
women have been dancing all their lives, and others began recently,
perhaps after some family tragedy or a New Year's resolution to
learn to tango. ``I call this my mental health night,'' a nursing
supervisor said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the women are widows who found these evenings to be a
way to transcend their loss and solve the practical problem of
lacking a dance partner. One notes that her doctor suggested
dancing as exercise, and more than one mentions that her
psychiatrist sent her. A marketing executive in her 50's said that
dancing fed her soul; an author said that it engaged her mind. For
many, it is the highlight of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years the group has included songwriters, editors,
lawyers, a Rockette, wives of well-known men and a woman named Rose
who danced until she was 98 and was buried in her dance shoes.
Today, Eleanor Carlucci, 79, has the longest tenure, having danced
with the group for 35 years. She was Alfred A. Knopf's secretary in
the last years of his life and still works part time as the
librarian for Random House. She walks with a cane. But when the
music starts, the cane is on the sidelines, and she's in step and
in the swing.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' ages also vary, from the 20s to the 80s.
</P>
<P>
   (Some of the women and teachers will no sooner divulge their age
than have a woman lead.)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Vance, one of the youngest teachers, said that dancing
was ``ageless.'' One of the most senior, Johnnie Rossi, 76, a World
War II veteran, has had two replacements in one knee.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked one of the women to identify the music being
played, she said, ``You can always tell by looking at Johnnie's
hips.'' He moves with remarkable grace and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   For the teachers, all independent instructors, the parties offer
an opportunity to attract new clients, although they're not allowed
to solicit. Some give private lessons before and after the session,
which runs from 8 to 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing random about these evenings. The women at the
two tables on the left dance while those on the right sit out, and
then they switch. Always wearing jackets and ties, the teachers
come to collect their partners in the 10 seconds between songs _
taking their arm to lead them to the dance floor. They follow a
precise order of rotation, so that by the end of the evening, every
woman will have danced several times with every teacher, doing
different dances with each one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's my next gentleman caller?,'' Bel Kaufman joked, rising
to wait for her partner. Kaufman, the 89-year old author of ``Up
the Down Staircase,'' especially loves dramatic dances like the
tango and pasa doble, and dances with flourish. ``It can be
intimidating the first time,'' she said. ``We all look like we're
wonderful dancers. We're not. We dance with wonderful dancers. But
we're improving.'' She looks wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   People who happen upon the social hall and peek in are often
puzzled. Something about the dancers' mixed ages and appearances
suggest that these aren't married couples. Yet they waltz and
cha-cha with the familiarity of people who've known each other for
years, sometimes laughing and chatting, sometimes looking at each
other in a locked, silent gaze as they glide together with seeming
ease. It looks like a tea dance, reborn.
</P>
<P>
   On the polished dance floor of Roseland 2000, Stan's group
danced amid the New Jersey crowd, all their gestures reflected in
the mirrored wall. From 9 to 11 p.m. they follow their usual
rotating format. Without a doubt, Stan is the best dancer in the
room, and he makes whoever he is dancing with look splendid too. He
and his wife, Judie, had been a professional adagio team _ a dance
form where the man lifts the woman up high _ and performed
internationally but retired 10 years ago after an injury. With the
women in this group, he lifts only their spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of a Saturday session, Ceil is doing a variation
on the merengue with a bit of hustle, and her partner, George,
drops to his knees and dances around her. Not missing a beat, she
continues her steps, raising her arms and waving them to the music.
It is a tour de force; they are applauded as they conclude in an
embrace. ``Sometimes I like to show off,'' she admits later.
</P>
<P>
   One evening when there was a no-show and the teachers had a gap
on their dance cards, I was invited to dance. I demurred, saying I
didn't have the right shoes, but I was gently prodded to give it a
whirl. I did a tango with Peter, a mambo with Stan and then moved
through some stylish fox-trot quick and slow combinations with
Robert. Hey, I could do this. I was floating. But I was brought
down to earth when a regular guy asked me to dance at Roseland 2000
and our arms pretzeled instead of looping when we turned. So part
of the charm of this brigade of princes is that they lead
powerfully but don't make you feel as if they're propelling you
into place although, clearly, at times they are.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   About leading, Peter, who is 6 foot 3 and athletic-looking, and
the most professorial of the bunch, said, it was an ``imperceptible
art, like a magician's sleight of hand.'' He explained that he
``shifts gears'' for each partner. For some of the women, who are
totally in charge in their professional lives or have lived on
their own for so long that they're accustomed to making the rules,
learning to follow rather than lead is an acquired skill. ``To
suddenly think of myself as submissive is one of the hardest
things,'' a magazine publisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one of the reasons so many participants view ballroom
dance as healing is because of its quality of touch. It's one of
the few activities in which physical contact is permitted among
people who don't know each other well. But it's a touch that can be
tender and communicative without being intimate, even as the
partners hold each other and move as one. That distance provides a
layer of comfort and dignity that enable the women to lose
themselves in the dance.
</P>
<P>
   Ballroom dance is the rare fantasy that's easily lived out: with
stirring music and a talented partner, it's not much of a leap to
imagine being elsewhere, in another time, or being in love. To
watch these women dance is to feel the romance, the possibility,
the transformation and the fun of it all. ``When I arrive and
descend those steps, I hold onto the banister, aware of my age,''
Kaufman said. ``When I leave, I run up the stairs. I'm 18 again, no
matter how tired. I'm exhilarated.''
</P>
<P>
   When the evening's final song ends, the women complain about the
time going by too quickly. Most could have danced all night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
