<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AFRICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFF TO AFRICA TO BOLSTER TIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Clinton-Nigeria)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two years after his historic first trip to Africa,
President Clinton leaves Friday for the continent on a new
high-stakes mission that he can only hope will leave a more
enduring legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stops first in Nigeria, whose oil riches and influence
on other African nations make it arguably one of the most
strategically important nations in the world. There, he will
publicly praise the country's quick turnabout from dictatorship to
democracy and privately press for stability in petroleum prices.
</P>
<P>
   And then he travels for a day to Tanzania to recognize the
handiwork of one of the most influential people in his life, Nelson
Mandela, who has been presiding over a shaky peace deal among 19
parties in neighboring Burundi. Mandela hopes for a signing of the
work-in-progress treaty on Monday, but onlookers fear any deal
could easily unravel, sparking a genocidal fury.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential attention comes at a pivotal time for
sub-Saharan Africa, much of which was afflicted at the end of the
century by war, debt, disease and _ in the words of Harvard
University's Robert I. Rotberg _ ``venal leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   In Africa, there is great joy that a US president is coming. But
leaders harbor only modest expectations that Clinton's three-day
swing heralds significant relief for the continent's financial
burdens, either by forgiving billions of dollars owed to foreign
creditors or in the form of major assistance in coping with the
HIV/AIDS crisis.
</P>
<P>
   US critics of the administration's Africa policy doubt any
dramatic changes loom in the last four months of Clinton's tenure,
and instead expect much of his focus to be on a US domestic
concern: keeping down the price of oil. Nigeria, Africa's largest
oil producer, is a member of the OPEC oil cartel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get down to the brass tacks, what's still driving
American policy toward Nigeria is oil and stability defined by
oil,'' said Salih Booker, director of both the Africa Policy
Information Center and Africa Fund. ``The US wants to say it
supports democracy and wants to encourage the democratic process,
but my concern is that it's not really investing in that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of Africa's troubles stands the unsteady giant of
Nigeria, the most populous country that up to two years ago was run
by one of the most venal dictators of them all: General Sani
Abacha, said to have transferred $5 billion from the nation's
accounts to his own.
</P>
<P>
   Months after Clinton bypassed Nigeria in his first Africa trip,
Abacha died mysteriously, a transitional military leader took over,
and a multi-party vote in May 1999 elected President Olusegun
Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
   Senior US officials, who had done little pre-trip promotion,
described Nigeria as an anchor for all of Africa. The State
Department has listed Nigeria as one of four key countries to
closely monitor because democracy is either in transition or under
threat; the others are Indonesia, Colombia, and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a make-or-break transition, not just for Nigeria but
for Africa,'' National Security Adviser Samuel R. Berger said. ``If
Nigeria succeeds, this can help lift the whole region to prosperity
and peace. If it fails, it can swamp the whole region in turmoil
and misery.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Clinton's visit signaled ``our strong support for
the most important democratic transition in Africa since the
collapse of apartheid'' in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton toured Africa in 1998, he pointedly skirted Nigeria
because of Abacha's reign and instead singled out four other
leaders as examples of promise for the future. But to Clinton's
embarrassment, months later all four leaders were engulfed in two
wars, those along the Eritrea-Ethiopia border and the multi-party
conflict inside the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Obansanjo wears the American imprimatur of a promising
African leader, even though Nigeria remains extraordinarily
volatile. Internal troubles include separatist Islamic-led
movements and the brutal repression of environmental protesters in
the oil-rich Niger Delta.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans hope Obansanjo will inspire other democracies
and shoulder the weighty burden of peacekeeping responsibilities in
the region, especially the current United Nations mission in Sierra
Leone. In the last decade, Nigeria has spent $10 billion on
peacekeeping operations, yet it has expressed wariness to do more
because of the huge cost.
</P>
<P>
   The United States this week sent the first of about 200 military
advisers to Nigeria to train five batallions for peacekeeping
operations. But already Nigerian military officials are grumbling
that they are not being provided with new military hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continent of Africa is increasingly hanging by a thread,
and what happens in Nigeria is becoming increasingly decisive,''
said J. Stephen Morrison, director of the Africa program at the
Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington, and
until last January a senior State Department expert on Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Since the administration ``does not have a lot of success to
point to in its African policies, our approach to Nigeria is one
noteworthy achievement,'' Morrison said, noting that US aid to
Nigeria increased to $108 million this year, from $7 million two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Booker called that ``peanuts. It's less than a dollar per
person, and a lot of that new money will pay for American employees
at the new USAID office in Abuja. What Nigeria and other African
countries want to see is debt cancellation. The US should be
playing a leading role in that, cancelling its debt and leaning on
the Europeans to do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Smith, the National Security Council's senior director for
African Affairs, said the US was ``Nigeria's smallest creditor, at
only 4 percent of the total.''
</P>
<P>
   Four percent equals about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's trip marks the beginning of an intense international
agenda for the White House. After returning to Washington next
Tuesday, he makes a one-day visit Wednesday to Cartagena, Colombia,
to underscore his support for a $1.6 billion anti-drug package.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after Labor Day, he will spend at least two days at the
United Nations Millennium Summit in New York, which is expected to
attract more than 100 heads of state. There also is a chance that
Clinton could hold talks there between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to try to build on
this summer's collapsed Camp David negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a sprint to the finish line,'' said NSC spokesman P.J.
Crowley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
