<SLUG> BC-HOCKEYDADS-FIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE LAWYER SEEKS MEDICAL RECORDS OF DEAD HOCKEY DAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FARAH STOCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The lawyer for Thomas Junta, the Reading
father accused of killing a man in a disagreement over a youth
hockey game, Thursday filed a court motion to review the alleged
victim's medical records.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Thomas Orlandi said that he does not know if Michael
Costin had a pre-existing medical condition that might have
contributed to his death after a fight with Junta at a Reading ice
rink in July. But Orlandi said he wants to look over Costin's
records to see if such a condition did exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always look into that when there is an injury of this
magnitude,'' Orlandi said after Junta pleaded not guilty to a
manslaughter indictment in Middlesex Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Orlandi filed a discovery motion with Judge Maria Lopez seeking
the records.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer also said he plans to argue that Junta was acting in
self defense. Orlandi said Junta and Costin had confronted each
other in a seperate incident just before the fight and Costin had
kicked Junta in the leg with his ice skate.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez granted Orlandi's request to preserve Costin's ice skates
as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two sides to every story and we have evidence to
defend our side,'' said Orlandi after the brief court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   However, Denise Costin, the alleged victim's cousin, dismissed
the idea that a review of Costin's medical records might benefit
Junta's defense.
</P>
<P>
   She said Costin was ``completely healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no pre-existing condition,'' Denise Costin said.
``It was blunt blows to his head that killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Costin also rejected the claim that Junta could have been
acting in self defense against her cousin, who weighed 100 less.
</P>
<P>
   Junta, 42, was indicted two weeks ago for the July 5 death of
Costin, 40, a single father of four from Lynnfield.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors at an earlier hearing said ``unchecked rage'' led
Junta to smash Costin's head against the floor of the locker room
at Burbank Ice Arena in front of a crowd of adolesent boys, leaving
Costin with injuries that cut off the blood flow to his brain.
</P>
<P>
   At Junta's District Court arraignment, a judge ruled last month
that he was not a threat to society, and allowed him to be released
on $5,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Superior Court Judge Maria Lopez denied Junta's request
to reduce the bail. Lopez also ordered Junta to steer clear of the
victim's family or any potential witnesses, and suggested that
Costin's family do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Orlandi said he had been hoping to use the $5,000 bail money to
hire an expert to review Costin's medical records.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a family of means,'' Orlandi said, ``and they
could have used the money for experts.''
</P>
<P>
   The fatal fight began when Junta, a 275-pound truck driver,
quarreled with Costin for allowing too much rough play on the ice
while refereeing an impromptu game involving Junta's 10-year old
son and Costin's three sons, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   As their argument erupted into violence, other patrons at the
ice arena separated the two, and Junta left the rink. But after, he
returned and confronted Costin, who tried to punch him. Junta then
threw Costin to the floor and beat him. Outweight by 100 pounds,
Costin fell unconscious. He was hospitalized and pronounced dead
two days later, authorities said..
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Denise Costin reiterated her family's outrage at
Junta's freedom and the fact that he is only facing a manslaughter
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's fair,'' she said. ``I was actually at the
court room longer than he was in custody.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
