<HEADER>
A1385 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DOLPHINS-WHISTLES-BOS     08-24 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS-WHISTLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS `TALK' BY WHISTLING, RESEARCHER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other than humans, there are no land-dwelling mammals that are
capable of learning and imitating sounds they hear _ a crucial part
of the development of language, the most distinctly human of our
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   But dolphins share that capacity for imitation. When swimming in
the wild they keep in touch by uttering a ``signature whistle''
repeatedly. And now, new research being reported in the current
journal Science shows that one dolphin may address another _
whether for comradeship or conflict _ by immediately repeating the
other's distinctive whistle. In essence, they may call each other
by name.
</P>
<P>
   Birds can imitate sounds to some extent, but not with the kind
of specific individual signatures that dolphins produce. Dolphins
are remarkably adept at it _ they develop their unique signatures
within the first year of life, using sounds different from those of
dolphins around them, but related to noises in their environment.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of their signature whistles has been known for
about a decade _ first discovered by a team including biologist
Peter Tyack of Woods Hole (Mass.) Oceanographic Institution _ but
the new work is the first to show that these whistles are often
copied by different individuals within a few seconds of the
original.
</P>
<P>
   ``These results show that bottlenose dolphins use their learned
whistles in matching interactions, most likely to address each
other,'' Vincent Janik, a biology student at the University of St.
Andrews in Scotland, wrote in the new paper. Such ``addressing''
whistles might, he suggested, ``be either aggressive or
affiliative,'' or could ``signal alliance membership to third
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins in the wild are notoriously difficult to study: The
ocean is a very big place with limited visibility, and dolphins
move very fast. The breakthrough that made the new findings
possible was the use of an array of three underwater microphones
that, coupled with sophisticated computer software developed by a
Belmont, Mass. firm, Engineering Design, made it possible to
pinpoint the place where a given sound originated.
</P>
<P>
   Janik, currently working at the Woods Hole institute, placed the
microphones in a section of the Moray Firth on the Scottish coast
in 1994 and 1995, and recorded dolphin sounds over a period of 7
days as part of his thesis research.
</P>
<P>
   To count as a ``matching'' whistle, the second occurrence had to
happen within 3 seconds of the first, and be separated by a
distance large enough that a single dolphin could not have swum
that far in the interval. This ensured that the sounds really were
being made by two different dolphins, but it also meant that sounds
copied by dolphins swimming close together would not be counted.
Thus, ``it is possible that matching interactions are more common''
than the results indicated, Janik wrote.
</P>
<P>
   This discovery, Tyack wrote in an accompanying commentary, is
``important for anyone interested in comparative studies of the
evolution of vocal learning and labeling in animals.''
</P>
<P>
   From research with captive dolphins, researchers had already
found that they seldom use their signature whistles when they are
all close together. But as soon as one dolphin is separated from
the others, all of them immediately begin emitting their
signatures, suggesting that this is a way of keeping track of each
other and keeping the group together.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have also demonstrated that dolphins in captivity
will very quickly learn to associate a newly learned whistle with a
specific object _ a key part of the development of language. But
the new research, Tyack wrote, now extends that finding to show
that ``vocal labeling'' is also used by dolphins in their natural
habitat, as part of the process of social interaction.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Slater, a professor of natural history at St. Andrews and
supervisor of Janik's research, called the use of the technology
for pinpointing the location of sounds ``a great innovation. . . .
If you hear two identical sounds in a row, you might think it was
the same dolphin. But if they occur a few seconds apart and you can
tell that they are hundreds of feet apart, they must be different
individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, this method _ using microphones anchored to the
bottom _ avoids any disturbance of the dolphins' natural behavior,
which might occur with the use of boats or divers to observe their
behavior. In this research, the recordings were made from shore,
while a second researcher at a higher elevation was watching with
binoculars to monitor the number of dolphins and their movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you disturb them, they may behave in a different way,''
said Slater, a specialist in animal sounds. ``It's important to
extend our research out into the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, he said, the research on dolphin vocalizations is
``only scratching the surface of something that's probably very
complex.'' Dolphins are ``capable of all sorts of tasks, and they
presumably got all this intelligence for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   And by studying them, humans may learn something about our own
origins, Tyack suggests. ``There is a growing appreciation. . . of
the fascinating similarities in the ways that birds and mammals use
vocal imitation to interact with specific individuals,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``These similarities may provide an important comparative
perspective on how capabilities for imitation evolved in our
hominid ancestors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
