<HEADER>
A1389 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-BIGKISS-HNS &LR;      08-24 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGKISS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READ MY LIPS: THREE-SECOND SMOOCH MELTS GORE'S OLD IMAGE 
BY CLIFFORD PUGH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you wanna know if he loves you so,
</P>
<P>
   It's in his kiss.
</P>
<P>
   _ from the ``Shoop Shoop Song'' &QR;
</P>
<P>
   If Al Gore is elected president, pundits may be able to trace
where his fortunes first turned.
</P>
<P>
   It started with a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   On center stage at the Democratic National Convention, before
the most important speech in his political career, Gore laid a big
one on his startled wife, Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   In that one instant, he surprised a nation.
</P>
<P>
   Political pundits, etiquette experts and regular folks have been
buzzing about it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a quick peck on the cheek, Gore took his wife in his
arms and gave her a passionate lip lock that lasted a full three
seconds _ an eternity in political kissdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kiss,'' which some political experts believe did more than
anything to shed Gore's robotic image, had some etiquette experts
squirming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it was a high moment in their lives, but it just went a
little teeny bit over the line,'' Houston etiquette expert Annie
Cater said. ``My thought was what does he do when they're alone?''
</P>
<P>
   Letitia  &UR;  &LR; Baldrige, who served as first lady Jacqueline
Kennedy's social secretary and remains one of the nation's leading
etiquette experts, was put off by ``the kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a political gesture to show the world that this
marriage is not in trouble,'' Baldridge said. ``A normal couple
wouldn't have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garth Jowett, director of the School of Communication at the
University of Houston, believes such criticisms are silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a New York ball. This is politics where you let it
all hang out,'' he said. ``How many times have politicians gone
around kissing babies? They may as well go around kissing their
wives.''
</P>
<P>
   Early reviews indicate that much of the general public liked
seeing the Gores show such unabashed affection toward each other
after 30 years of marriage. His standing in the polls has shot up,
particularly among women.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative radio talk-show host Rush Limbaugh was so perplexed
by the turnaround that he invited women who had changed their minds
about Gore to phone in this week. A large majority of callers
thought the kiss was great.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of those little defining moments that can make or
break a campaign over time,'' said Jowett, who teaches classes on
pop culture. ``If Gore goes on to victory, the kiss will be
enshrined as part of political popular culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics maintain the kiss was a staged event. But in
interviews on all three network morning talk shows, Gore insisted
it had been ``completely spontaneous'' and was not part of an
attempt to reshape his image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said, `Are you trying to send a message?' I said,
`Actually, I was trying to send a message to Tipper,' '' he told
the CBS ``Early Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Houston first lady Elyse Lanier, who showed a remarkable
amount of public affection toward her husband, Bob Lanier, when he
was mayor, believes the Gores simply were showing their human side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a funny thing. People lose sight of the fact that
politicians are human. You don't get the other side of them so
often. We really have another side. We kiss each other. We kiss our
children. We hold hands. And if we don't like each other, we don't
get near each other,'' she said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier believes the public is smart enough to see through an
insincere display of affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything shows through on the camera, much more so than even
in person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One Houston political consultant who asked not to be identified
because he advises candidates across the spectrum likened the
Gores' public smooch to a kiss at a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to a wedding, it's public, but it's still sincere,''
he said. ``Unless you're an actor, it's hard to fake that kind of
thing. Anyone who sees them together knows they are real.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Crigler, professor of political science at the University of
Southern California, believes Gore's public display of affection
struck such a chord because it didn't seem to fit his image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone kisses their wife. It wasn't so hugely passionate
that it would have been surprising for some other people, but
because of Gore's reputation, it was surprising,'' she said. ``It
was new and different and told us about a side of him that we
hadn't quite realized. And it was reinforced both by his wife's
introduction and his speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Such nonverbal communication can be very effective in presenting
a message, said Crigler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald Reagan knew that. He would always have great visuals in
his media message, and the story would get out in a very positive
way. This is the same kind of thing. It's communicating a lot more
than words can communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts agree that the Gore kiss illustrates that passion is
more in fashion nowadays. Etiquette expert Cater links increased
public displays of affection with the trend toward dressing more
casually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more casual it gets, the more casual you get,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a generational thing, she believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men of a certain age _ 50, 60, 70 _ were brought up with a
different feeling about women and passion. The times they lived in
were a little bit more restrained. For younger people, it's not as
big of a deal. You see them necking at a ball game, for gosh sake.
And they probably don't even call it necking,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Politically speaking, Jowett jokingly suggests all the fuss over
the Gore kiss could open up a new way of politicking. Instead of
debates, ``politically we may end up with the `kiss-off' and see
who can kiss their wife (the best and longest),'' he said. ``That's
a good way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
