<P>
   EUROPE-TELECOMN-LI (Hong Kong) _ Li Ka-shing, the tycoon known
here as Superman, earned his nickname among investors by amassing
more wealth and influence than any other local businessman here
ever had. His flagship conglomerate, Hutchison Whampoa, reinforced
that reputation on Thursday when it reported earnings of $4 billion
in the first half of 2000. Most of Hutchison's profit, however,
came from a special one-time gain after the sale of its European
mobile phone operations. And the company's encore, an ambitious
plan to offer next-generation cellular services throughout Europe,
is in doubt. Last week, Hutchison unexpectedly gave up a coveted
license to offer advanced mobile services in Germany, saying it was
too costly. Thursday, even as Li and his lieutenants basked in the
glow of rich earnings, they had to explain why the German setback
had not scrambled their plans. By Mark Landler.
</P>
