<P>
   BOTTOM CENTER:
</P>
<P>
   DECIMAL-NORRIS-COLUMN (New York) _ On Monday, the New York Stock
Exchange and the American Stock Exchange will begin trading a total
of 13 stocks in dollars and cents, rather than using fractions.
Sometime next year, all stocks will be traded that way. That
change, in itself, is unimportant. Whether a price is quoted as a
quarter or as 25 cents is irrelevant. What is important is that
arbitrary limits on price competition are vanishing. In 1997, the
smallest change in price on the Big Board was cut in half, to
one-sixteenth of a dollar, or 6.25 cents. Now it will go to a
penny. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds., fyi, there is no Marketplace column on days with a Norris
column.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are tonight's columns, other features:
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   LAUNDRY-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Campaign season is usually a time
for airing dirty laundry. That is the case at Unilever's laboratory
in Edgewater, N.J., where filthy socks fetch $3 a pair and soiled
shirts are bought for $15 each _ all in service of a coming
marketing campaign to introduce a revamped old product. Unilever is
locked in a race with Procter &AMP; Gamble to reacquaint American
consumers with the laundry tablet, a product they have not seen
since the late 1970s. The repackaging effort is part of a strategy
to shed its more obscure, ancillary products and pour resources
into marketing Wisk detergent and other core brands. By Greg
Winter.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Bond prices were flat on Thursday after the
government reported a larger-than-expected drop in orders for
durable goods in July, suggesting that the Federal Reserve may hold
off raising interest rates again this year. By Robert Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8 p.m.)
