<HEADLINE>
FIVE FAVORITE KISSES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
The Air Kiss _ A favorite of the ladies who lunch because it avoids
messy makeup touch-ups since lips never brush the skin.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cheek-to-Cheek _ The preferred way of greeting in Europe with a
buss on both cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Peck _ A typical way of welcome in the South, but not
everywhere. When then-President Jimmy Carter greeted Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis at the John F. Kennedy Presidential Library in
Boston with a peck on one cheek, she visibly recoiled.
</P>
<P>
   The Smooch _ Lips on lips, but with a bit of a chaste feeling.
The kind of kiss your long-married parents do when you're watching.
</P>
<P>
   The Hubba Hubba _ The all-out, passionate ``I Love You'' kiss
like you see in the movies or in a heavy make-out session.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1393 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-BIGKISS-FAMOUS-HNS &LR;      08-24 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGKISS-FAMOUS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Great moments in kissing history 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
All-time great lip-smacking moments:
<TEXT>
<P>
   John C. Rice groomed his moustache and then lip-locked May Erwin
in a short silent film titled ``The Kiss.'' This first on-screen
kiss, filmed in 1896, shocked the public.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Kerr and Burt Lancaster kissed on the beach like there
was no tomorrow in the 1953 movie ``From Here to Eternity,'' a
scene that still sets the sizzling standard for a scintillating
screen kiss.
</P>
<P>
   An uptown cocker spaniel found true love over a bowl of
spaghetti with a streetwise downtown mutt in the 1955 Disney
classic ``Lady and the Tramp.''
</P>
<P>
   The comedy series ``Will and Grace'' delivered network prime
time's first smooch between two gay male characters this year. Jack
and Will smooched on the street in front of ``Today'' show
weatherman Al Roker to protest the fact NBC wouldn't air a gay kiss
on a fictional series.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II kisses the ground in every country he visits,
but his first visit as pope to his home country of Poland in 1979
evoked the most poignant memories.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years in the hit television series ``X-Files,''
Scully and Mulder finally shared a kiss as themselves in a 1999
episode set on New Year's Eve. They had kissed a couple of times
earlier in the guise of other characters. They also came close in
the ``X-Files'' movie before Scully got stung by a virus-carrying
bee.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most famous photograph involving a kiss is Alfred
Eisenstaedt's picture of an unidentified sailor and nurse
celebrating the end of World War II in New York City's Times
Square. Many men have claimed to be the sailor.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas A&AMP;M football games, every time a touchdown is scored,
an Aggie and his or her date get to share a kiss. It's one of the
university's most zealously guarded traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Corleone (Al Pacino) marked his brother for death with a
kiss in ``Godfather II.''
</P>
<P>
   Television's first interracial kiss between Capt. Kirk and Lt.
Uhura in a 1968 episode of ``Star Trek'' caused a furor. Thirty-two
years later, interracial kissing is such a non-factor that Ally
McBeal and her African-American doctor boyfriend never even mention
their different races.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
