 PERSONALS: The Egos and the Ids 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Footage of  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  doing The Walk, his entrance into the
Democratic National Convention, was shot on HDTV, says the New York
Daily News, because its format made him look thinner. Most
Americans don't yet have HDTV, and the chances are slim that its
benefits translate to garden-variety TV sets, but it couldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Boston Herald says the first thing ``Survivor'' champ
 &UR; Richard Hatch &LR;  did when he returned to Rhode Island from the island
was have liposuction. His agent,  &UR; Sherri Spillane &LR; , told the
newspaper that she didn't know. ``But if Rich did have liposuction,
good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Shakespearean scholar  &UR; Francis Rigney &LR;  calls Hatch
Richard IV, a warrior who followed in the footsteps of the Richard
before him:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am determined to prove a villain,'' says Gloucester, who
became Richard III, ``and hate the idle pleasures of these days./
Plots have I laid, inductions dangerous,/ By drunken prophecies,
libels and dreams,/ To set my brother Clarence and the king,/ in
deadly hate the one against the other. . . . I am subtle, false and
treacherous.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Michael Bolton &LR;  said he sang ``When a Man Loves a Woman'' by
request at the president's Hollywood party for  &UR; Hillary &LR; 
 &UR; Clinton &LR; 's Senate campaign. The request, says Us Weekly, was from
Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; John Waters &LR;  is auctioning memorabilia from ``Cecil B.
DeMented'' _ including  &UR; Melanie Griffith &LR; 's costumes _ on
Amazon.com to benefit the Prisoners Aid Association of Maryland
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unlikely bumperfellows:  &UR; Ruth Jacobs &LR;  saw a pickup truck with
a ``National Pest Control Association'' bumper sticker adjacent to
``There's no excuse for domestic violence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; STRIKE SCORECARD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Screen Actors Guild, which has been on strike, forwards a
list of movers and shakers who have been supporting and not
supporting the action.
</P>
<P>
   Pro, and up-front about their position:  &UR; Brad Pitt &LR; ,  &UR; Donald &LR; 
 &UR; Sutherland &LR; ,  &UR; John Elway &LR; ,  &UR; Mike Piazza &LR; ,  &UR; Dan Marino &LR; ,  &UR; Lance &LR; 
 &UR; Armstrong &LR;  and the Dixie Chicks.
</P>
<P>
   Anti:  &UR; Ridley Scott &LR; ,  &UR; Tiger Woods &LR; ,  &UR; Michael Johnson &LR; , the
 &UR; Bush &LR;  campaign and football players  &UR; Terrell Davis &LR;  and  &UR; Kurt &LR; 
 &UR; Warner &LR; .  &UR; Colin Powell &LR;  shot a nonunion public service announcement
for America's Promise, a nonprofit organization, in May. A couple
of years ago, the union says, America's Promise asked SAG for help
in gathering support among the union's members.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMINGS AND GOINGS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The late journalist and film reviewer  &UR; Penelope Gilliatt &LR; 
always referred to New Yorker editor  &UR; William Shawn &LR;  as Bill,
writes  &UR; John Gregory Dunne &LR;  in a letter to the editor commenting on
a New York Review of Books article about the New Yorker. ``I cannot
attest whether she called him by his diminutive in private, but
then Penelope was on such familiar terms with the universe that I
expect that when she arrived at the gates of heaven in 1993 she
greeted the Holy Ghost as `Holy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WHO SAID WHAT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``There is no other teen actor quite like her: a mesmerizing _ &LR; 
 &UR; at times disconcerting _ screen presence, a woman-child who &LR; 
 &UR; combines intensely analytical intelligence and sophistication &LR; 
 &UR; with a dewy face and voluptuous body. Sobieski is on the fast &LR; 
 &UR; track to inherit the Jodie Foster mantle but exudes more warmth &LR; 
 &UR; and humor; with a dash of Streepish gravitas, she's got the heft &LR; 
 &UR; to shoulder heavyweight roles. ... She's an accomplished &LR; 
 &UR; painter, a passionate poet, and, oh yes, she wants to direct. &LR; 
 &UR; ... Her bloodlines and education are privileged. Sobieski's &LR; 
 &UR; great-great- &LR; 
 &UR; great-great-uncle was King Sobieski of Poland (for whom the &LR; 
 &UR; bagel was invented).'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Leelee Sobieski &LR; , 18-year-old scion to a baked goods muse,
and the greatest thing since sliced bread, as described in a Los
Angeles magazine profile.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
