<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1397 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-SUBMARINE-B     08-24 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SUBMARINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S ANGUISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beyond the human loss Russia has suffered with the sinking of
its nuclear submarine stands the injury to national pride. Russia's
submarine fleet, which once numbered 180 craft, is a shadow of its
former self in the wake of the fiscal shambles that followed the
breakup of the Soviet Union. The rest of the world, both out of
sympathy for the 118 lost lives and wish for Russian stability, may
have a positive role to play in the aftermath of the tragedy if it
is done delicately.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military leaders and President Vladimir Putin have been
blamed both at home and abroad for failing to ask quickly for
assistance from other countries in attempting to rescue the crewmen
trapped on the submarine Kursk 400 feet deep in the Barents Sea.
Military leaders in any country give high priority to security, and
the Kursk was one of the newest of Russia's submarines. Russian
officials may not have relished the idea of Western experts pawing
over it. Conversely, the Russians may have been reluctant to invite
outsiders to see the low estate to which their prized possessions
have fallen because of inadequate funding for maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   They may have genuinely believed that they would be able to
reach the submarine with their own equipment in time to save some
lives, although the subsequent discovery of the damage from an
apparent explosion suggests that any crew members who survived the
initial catastrophe died before British or Norwegian rescue teams
could have arrived under the best of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   That the Russians did ultimately accept British and Norwegian
assistance stands to their credit. Their hope to recover bodies
from the submarine, and perhaps the submarine itself, evidently
depends on additional foreign assistance. This would particularly
involve Norwegians, who have had extensive experience in waters of
comparable depths. The process would be slow at best because
Norwegians are worried about the condition of the hull and interior
of the vessel. They might even decline the challenge, given the
risks involved.
</P>
<P>
   This increases the likelihood that there will be efforts to
recover the Kursk by raising it from the ocean bottom and moving it
either to a Russian port or to shallower waters, where it might be
easier for divers to work. It would be a herculean task, but one
for which Americans may be equipped.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, a great deal of coordination will be required,
and it is essential that the mission be conducted in a spirit of
mutual interest. Russia's difficulties are serious, but the loyalty
and persistence of so many individuals in the face of those
difficulties have to be admired. In the long run, the interests of
Russians, Americans, and many others will be served best by
increased cooperation rather than intense competition, and
cooperation can be based only on a willing spirit among all
parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0306 </DOCNO>
