<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Face to Face on Rushmore
</P>
<P>
   In the late '50s, MGM assigned Alfred Hitchcock and the
screenwriter Ernest Lehman to make ``The Wreck of the Mary Deare,''
a project of zero interest to either of them. Hitchcock had no
fully developed alternative to suggest, but he told Lehman that he
wanted to make something that had a chase across the presidential
faces on Mount Rushmore. He also envisioned a scene at the United
Nations in which the speaker on the podium would declare, ``I
refuse to continue until the delegate from Peru wakes up.'' The
delegate, of course, is dead.
</P>
<P>
   By December 1958 Hitchcock and Lehman had incorporated these
situations into ``North by Northwest,'' to be issued on Tuesday by
Warner in a new edition on videocassette and DVD. With DVDs of new
films ever more loaded with features generated by current directors
and production companies, it is interesting to see how well a
famous old film can be represented when many of the major players
aren't around to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock died in 1980 and Cary Grant, the film's primary star
in the role of Roger Thornhill, in 1986. But a new documentary,
available on the tape as well as on the disc, warmly and gracefully
recreates an experience from more than 40 years ago. Eva Marie
Saint, Grant's co-star, introduces the film. Martin Landau, a heavy
in ``North by Northwest,'' gives his Hitchcock imitation, but the
major recollections are provided by Lehman, the screenwriter, who
also contributes an audio commentary on the disc.
</P>
<P>
   As is usual on better discs, the pleasure is in the details.
Grant charged 15 cents for autographs. Jessie Royce Landis, who
plays Thornhill's mother, was younger than Grant. Ever the
eccentric, Hitchcock, or so it is said in the documentary, never
called actors cattle; he only said they should be treated like
cattle. In any case he is remembered as a likable tyrant,
respectfully obliging to cast and crew.
</P>
<P>
   As Eve Kendall, Saint, now 76, received three instructions:
lower your voice, keep your hands still and always gaze into
Grant's eyes. ``With Hitchcock you got the sense you were the only
one who could do it because you were there and he thought you
could,'' she said in an interview. She added that she wasn't sure
what he saw in her that landed her the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``His eyes always followed beautiful women,'' Patricia
Hitchcock, his daughter, says in the documentary. He liked white
gloves and beige clothes. Saint wore both to an introductory lunch
where everything but the script was discussed. That bothered her,
she said, because Eve Kendall didn't appear until page 58.
</P>
<P>
   In his commentary, Lehman lauds Hitchcock's way with lighting
and his genius with little touches, but he is more than a little
put out that everybody lionizes Hitchcock but never him, the
screenwriter. Saint agreed. ``What do they think _ Hitch made it
up?'' she said in the interview. But one never doubts their
feelings for the director. ``Funny and dear,'' Saint said. ``A
class act.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Princess Mononoke
</P>
<P>
   Forces of man and nature battle in Hayao Miyazaki's sumptuously
animated and exotically beautiful action film, set during the
Muromacho period in Japan (A.D. 1392-1573). Sent into the forest to
find the demonic forces that have contaminated him, young Ashataki
finds himself caught in a running battle between a ruthless
iron-mining baroness, Princess Eboshi, and woodlands creatures led
by Princess Mononoke, herself part human and part wolf. Permeating
all, the spirit of the forest appears as an elk by day and a
diaphanous divinity by night. While gods and demons struggle, Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times, a moral universe is created in
a ``sweeping, ambitious version of the comic-book storytelling that
engendered it.'' _ 1999. Miramax. $103. 135 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: Aug 29. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I Dreamed of Africa
</P>
<P>
   Reaching for the grandeur of ``Out of Africa,'' Hugh Hudson's
film never rises above an epic travelogue. Packing up her young
son, Kuki (Kim Basinger) goes to live in Kenya with her new
husband, a bounder named Paolo (Vincent Perez). Cue the lions and
elephants for predictable crises. Trying to take flight with poetic
profundities, Basinger manages only lifeless recitations as she and
Perez remain seriously miscast as ``adventure-seeking dilettantes
who have wandered far beyond their depth to indulge in an expensive
lifestyle experiment'' (Stephen Holden). _ 2000. Columbia Tri-Star.
$105.77; DVD, $29.95. 114 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. Release
date: Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Simpatico
</P>
<P>
   Trying to sketch in information that Sam Shepard's play omits,
Matthew Warchus' offbeat, gawky adaptation thrives with gripping
performances and a screenplay that skillfully imitates the
playwright's language. Horse racing is the metaphor for the
adrenaline-pumped American dream as a corrupt breeder (Jeff
Bridges) and his wife (Sharon Stone) tangle with a hard-drinking
eccentric (Nick Nolte) who threatens to expose some slippery
dealings over a high-priced steed. At least the film has integrity.
``Far from being a typical Hollywood desecration of a difficult
play, it stays true to the work's quirky, renegade spirit''
(Holden). _ 1999. New Line. $107.37; DVD, $24.95. 106 minutes.
Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Kahuna
</P>
<P>
   Staking out a hotel room in Kansas, three salesmen scheme to
unload a lot of product. Phil (Danny DeVito) is the showy type, but
Larry (Kevin Spacey) is the big kahuna, dominating Phil and Bob
(Peter Facinelli), a fresh-faced young Baptist. Based on Roger
Rueff's play ``Hospitality Suite,'' John Swanbeck's film airs
tired, secondhand truths in an exercise ``so transparent you could
wrap sandwiches with it'' (Elvis Mitchell). _ 2000. Universal.
$107.37; DVD, $26.98. 91 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a theater
release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in earlier
editions.  &LR;  LONGITUDE. Adapted from Dava Sobel's international best
seller, Charles Sturridge's film tells the parallel stories of John
Harrison (Michael Gambon), the 18th-century carpenter, clockmaker
and musician whose nautical timepieces attempted to solve the
complexities of longitude at sea, and Rupert Gould (Jeremy Irons),
the World War I Royal Air Force veteran who rescued Harrison's work
from oblivion. With plenty of political intrigue stirred in, Julie
Salamon wrote in The New York Times, ``the film surprises, much as
the book did, by taking what might seem a worthy but dull subject
and making it sparkle.'' 2000. A&AMP;E. $59.95, four cassettes; DVD,
$39.95. 200 minutes. Release date: Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   HOROWITZ: THE LAST ROMANTIC and VERDI: REQUIEM. The first of two
new DVDs features the pianist Vladimir Horowitz's performances of
Bach-Busoni's Chorale in G minor, Mozart's Sonata in C, Schubert's
Impromptu in A flat and Chopin's Mazurka in A minor. Filmed at the
Alte Oper in Frankfurt, Germany, Verdi's Messa da Requiem is
performed by the European Symphony Orchestra and the Neubeuren
Choral Society. 2000. Pioneer. DVD, $29.98 each.
</P>
<P>
   I CLAUDIUS. A new DVD edition of the acclaimed BBC production,
which stars Derek Jacobi, John Hurt, Patrick Stewart, Sian Phillips
and Sheila White, includes a 71-minute documentary, ``The Epic That
Never Was,'' about Alexander Korda's ill-fated 1937 screen
adaptation of Robert Graves' novel. Image Entertainment. $89.99,
three discs. 740 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
