<HEADLINE>
ANGRY INDIANS TAKE AIM AT SEN. GORTON OF WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wash., Ariz.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT10, 11 are being sent to NYT photo clients. A
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUMMI INDIAN RESERVATION, Wash. _ Mention the name Slade Gorton
in this far corner of Indian Country and some people will talk
about Slade Gorton the senior senator from Washington who is
helping to secure $15 million this year to replace a decrepit
tribal school.
</P>
<P>
   But most people will think of Slade Gorton the Indian fighter,
the better-known and much-feared figure, a 72-year-old Republican
who has spent much of his public life battling tribes like the
Lummis, who live two hours north of Seattle, on everything from
fishing rights to the power of governing their own affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In all the years that Gorton has feuded with American Indians,
he has never been subjected to a strong political backlash from the
tribes. But this year, flush with money from casino gambling
operations, Indians across the country say they are going to make
him pay.
</P>
<P>
   And because Gorton controls Indian-program purse strings in the
Senate, the stakes are high _ creating tension among tribal members
who say they are afraid that their challenge to Gorton will
threaten the paternal role of government that bonds most tribes,
uneasily, to the other Washington. This year, many tribal leaders
say they are so upset at Gorton that they are willing to take the
risk.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Indians have pooled money and are mounting a
campaign directed against a specific candidate, rather than a
single issue, as Indians have done in successful ballot initiatives
in California. The tribes say they have raised nearly $500,000 of
what is planned to be a $2 million independent campaign to deny a
fourth term to Gorton, who has fared poorly in recent polls even
though the Democrats will not select their nominee for almost a
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, members of Congress and senators should think
twice before trying to undermine tribal authority,'' said Ron
Allen, vice president of the National Congress of American Indians
and the leader of the campaign to raise Indian money against
Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how politics works. And until now, we've never played
the game,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Indians contributed a record $1.3 million in
so-called soft money, mostly to Democrats, but with no specific
target. This year, the tribes are on pace to surpass the 1996 mark,
and Gorton is the sole target _ or ``public enemy No. 1,'' as the
Native American Rights Fund, the largest Indian legal support group
in the nation, has labeled him.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally of the national Indian congress several months ago,
leaders urged tribes from around the country to contribute to the
First American Education Project, the fund set up to run issue
advertisements against Gorton here in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   The television and radio advertisements started running this
month and may follow Gorton all the way to Election Day, said Russ
Lehman, managing director of the fund. They feature a telegenic
tribal leader talking to children about the environment, then segue
to images of a large proposed mine in north central Washington,
which Indians have opposed and Gorton has championed.
</P>
<P>
   But Gorton is using the campaign against him to generate money
of his own, citing ``Indian tribes flush with gambling dollars,''
in a fund-raising letter to supporters. And he has used his
position as chairman of the Senate subcommittee that controls
federal funding for the tribes to counter the impression that he is
anti-Indian.
</P>
<P>
   Here on the Lummi Reservation, for example, the tribe is
desperate to replace its cluster of dilapidated modular buildings
where children from kindergarten to high school are educated.
Gorton has helped to ensure that next year's budget includes money
for a new school.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the feud between the tribe and Gorton over
Indian control of water and property of non-Indians living on the
Lummi reservation has escalated. A few years ago, Gorton threatened
to withhold half of the tribe's federal funding if it did not
buckle to the wishes of private developers seeking more water for
building non-Indian homes on the reservation. The dispute
continues, causing a rift within the tribe as members have tried to
win federal money for the new school.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Lummi people, this has become personal,'' said Darrell
Hillaire, a Lummi tribal council member. ``The needs of our
children come first, and Sen. Gorton has helped us there, and we
respect him for that. But on all these other issues, it seems like
it's racial with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Jones, the Lummi tribal chairman, said the tribe was not
sure how active it would be in the campaign to defeat Gorton _
because the school funds came first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stand up for our children,'' said Jones. ``But we
also have to make a stand for our rights. The Indian tribes are
finally learning how to use the system, and this is the test
case.''
</P>
<P>
   But others fear a backlash, should the effort fail. ``Tribes
pooling their resources together in an effort to defeat a senator
is a recipe for disaster,'' said Tom Keefe, a Democrat running for
Congress in eastern Washington state, who is married to a Nez Perce
Indian. ``What if the tribes pour millions of dollars into the
campaign and Sen. Gorton wins re-election?''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, with 29 federally recognized tribes, most of them
based near urban areas around Puget Sound, has long been at the
center of modern-day disputes between Indians and non-Indians.
Gorton's battles with the tribes date to the mid-1970s, when, as
Washington's attorney general, he opposed the treaty rights of
Indians to take up to half of the annual runs of salmon and
steelhead. He carried the fight to the Supreme Court and lost.
</P>
<P>
   As a senator, he proposed a bill to curtail Indian fishing
rights. Five years ago, he tried to cut nearly 25 percent of the
Bureau of Indian Affairs financing that goes directly to tribal
governments. And two years ago, he introduced measures that tried
to knock out tribal immunity from certain civil lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In support of the last measure, Gorton held a hearing in the
Seattle area that drew hundreds of people carrying anti-Indian
slogans and waving American flags.
</P>
<P>
   All of the proposals failed to gather support in the Senate, and
were fiercely opposed by Republicans, including Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., who received more political donations from Indians than
any presidential candidate ever had.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gorton says non-Indians do not have adequate constitutional
protections on reservations. He supports Indian self-government,
but says tribal rule should not extend to non-Indians who live on,
visit or have businesses on Indian land. This year, he points to
his effort to increase Interior Department spending on tribal
schools by $143 million as an example of his support for basic
Indian needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I drafted the Interior bill this year, one of my top
priorities was to dramatically increase federal dollars for tribal
schools,'' said Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   But many Indians say Gorton's school support is designed to
divert attention from a quarter-century of public battles with the
tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's election year window-dressing,'' said Brian Cladoosby,
chairman of the Association of Washington Tribes, and head of
Swinomish Indian Tribal Council, based just south of here. ``People
remember what he has done over the years. This year, we are trying
to make him an example. And so, even if we don't defeat him, it
will send a message: We can no longer be ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last two months, Allen, who is chairman of the Jamestown
S'Klallam tribe on the Olympic Peninsula of Washington, has been
visiting some of the wealthier tribes around the country, trying to
raise money against Gorton. Indians gambling is generating more
than $8 billion a year in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The wealthiest of the casino-enriched tribes, the Mashantucket
Pequots of Connecticut, are now considering donating to the fund,
even though some of the tribal leaders are Republican, as is Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been substantial and continuous attacks on Indian
Country from Gorton,'' said John Guevremont, the director of
national affairs for the Mashantucket Pequots, who said he was a
Republican. ``The tribes have a long list of grievances against him
and now have the means to try to defeat him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
