<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      08-24 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Cinefondation, in last graf, is cq.) By DAVE KEHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Toronto International Film Festival is about to enter its
25th year, having shown 5,790 features and shorts, by actual count,
since its inception in 1976. This year's edition, which runs from
Sept. 7 to 16, will add about 300 titles to that figure.
</P>
<P>
   In those years the festival has grown from a strictly local
event, organized by a group of Toronto businessmen, into one of the
primary stops on the international festival circuit, the North
American counterpart of Cannes, Berlin and Venice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no one year when we incrementally grew,'' said Piers
Handling, who joined the festival's staff in 1982 and has been its
director since 1994. ``It was year by year, adding 10 films one
year, 10 more the next. There have been no massive leaps, no huge
shifts in terms of artistic direction. It's a festival that has
valued its continuity and as a result has grown organically. It
hasn't had to deal with outsiders. It was all insiders who were
promoted into the key jobs, so there was nobody who came in and
thought they had to change the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto has grown into a festival that combines public support
with a large professional presence, which means that visiting
critics and distributors see movies alongside a huge and famously
responsive local audience. (By contrast, festivals like Cannes and
Sundance are attended almost exclusively by industry types.) It's a
chemistry that creates the crucial festival commodity called buzz,
the sense of excitement that grows around unknown films.
</P>
<P>
   For example Jean-Jacques Beineix's ``Diva'' had already flopped
in France when David Overbey, a programmer, took it to the 1981
festival, where it became a word-of-mouth smash and was picked up
for distribution. That year the festival also fielded the North
American premiere of an untested British feature, ``Chariots of
Fire,'' which went on to win the Oscar for best picture.
</P>
<P>
   ```Chariots of Fire' put us on the map and legitimatized us in
the eyes of the industry, that a film like that could play here and
break out into major awards,'' Handling said. ``Festivals were
always perceived as events for art films, for cinephiles. The
studios were afraid of their films' being described as festival
films. But Toronto is a large public festival. It's very inclusive,
it's noncompetitive; it has something for everybody. That's been
its philosophy since it was founded. We will show anything from
experimental cinema and documentaries to films from foreign
cultures to studio films.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thread that runs from `Chariots of Fire' to
`American Beauty,''' he continued, referring to the most recent
Oscar winner to have had its premiere in Toronto. ``When you can
actually prove to the studios that there is commercial value in
their film coming to your event, then they won't be afraid of
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the high-profile films that will premiere at this year's
festival are ``Almost Famous,'' a comedy about a teen-age rock
journalist directed by Cameron Crowe (``Jerry Maguire''); Kathryn
Bigelow's erotic thriller ``The Weight of Water''; and the military
drama ``Men of Honor,'' with Robert De Niro and Cuba Gooding Jr.
</P>
<P>
   And for unrepentant cinephiles, there will be new offerings from
the directors Tom Tykwer (``Run, Lola, Run''), Wong Kar-wai
(``Chungking Express'') and Stephen Frears (``My Beautiful
Laundrette''). The schedule, along with ticket-ordering
information, can be found at the festival's Web site,
www.e.bell.ca/filmfest.
</P>
<P>
   A MASTER RECALLED
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mr. Kurosawa I knew was like a little boy,'' says Emi
Wada, who won an Academy Award for designing the costumes for
``Ran,'' by Akira Kurosawa. ``He was gentle, shy and truly an
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ran,'' a transposition of ``King Lear'' to 17th-century Japan,
is generally considered the last great film of Kurosawa, the
Japanese master who died in 1998. First released in 1985, it is
being reissued nationally by Winstar, both theatrically and on DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions by fax from her home in Tokyo, Wada
recalled her collaboration with Kurosawa. They ``met for the first
time at a party to celebrate the completion of his film `Dersu
Uzala' in 1974,'' she wrote. ``There I learned that he was planning
to make a film based on Shakespeare's `King Lear.' In 1983, when
`Ran' was about to start filming, I went to see Mr. Kurosawa. I
talked to him about my ideas, and he decided to hire me on the
spot. And at that moment the title `costume designer' first came to
existence on a Kurosawa film.''
</P>
<P>
   Wada went on to design the costumes for movies including
``Prospero's Books,'' by Peter Greenaway, and Nagisa Oshima's
``Gohatto,'' which had its premiere at this year's Cannes
International Film Festival, as well as for numerous operas and
theater pieces in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the preparation of `Ran' began, Mr. Kurosawa and I drew
numerous sketches,'' Wada recalled. ``If all those pieces of
drawing paper were piled up, it would come to about 20 centimeters
high or more. He would continually say to me, `This design is
marvelous, but can you come up with something better?' I would work
on it some more, add things or sometimes change the idea
completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the costumes of `Ran' I was thinking of the theatrical,
symbolic, stylized costumes of Noh, focusing on the fabric with a
static silhouette. These costumes were more suitable for the film
than costumes in the actual period style.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the main characters I decided on the colors first, and
then the patterns, and then the material that would make the most
out of all those elements. For example, the costume of the leading
character, Lord Hidetora, started with a pure white and ended with
a thoroughly soiled white. For the three brothers I decided on
yellow, red and blue as the main colors, and I changed the
intensity of the colors depending on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``After working six months like this, finally he approved the
designs, and I started weaving them. Mr. Kurosawa entrusted me with
creating the fabrics, from selecting the threads to deciding on
their thickness, the dye and how they should be woven. When the
first woven cloth was done, I showed it to Mr. Kurosawa. He
congratulated me that I made something better than he aimed for.''
</P>
<P>
   AMERICANS IN PARIS
</P>
<P>
   Two New York University film students, Caran Hartsfield and
Peter Sollett, have been chosen to participate in a new program,
the Cinefondation Residence, sponsored by the Cannes Film Festival.
In October they will join four other students in a five-month
residency in Paris, where they will develop projects for their
first feature films under the guidance of French film
professionals. Oliver Assayas, who wrote and directed ``Irma Vep,''
led the selection committee. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 1947EDT &QL; 
