<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-BENZIGER-WINE-A     08-24 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BENZIGER-WINE-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WINEMAKING FAMILY TRIES A HIGH-TECH OPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By   TED APPEL   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLEN ELLEN, Calif. _ Returning to their first love after a brief
but expensive fling in the beer business, the Benzigers will open a
high-tech winery this week in the Sonoma Valley on the site of
their failed microbrewery.
</P>
<P>
   Never ones to think small, the Benzigers hope to make their new
Imagery Estate Winery into a must-see stop on Highway 12 with an
array of tourist-friendly attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The winery, which opens Friday for weekend visits, features an
art gallery with more than 125 paintings that have adorned the
labels of Benziger's ultrapremium Imagery wines for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   An ``Appellation Trail'' winds through the 20-acre property,
offering visitors a walking tour of Sonoma County's diverse
viticultural regions. And the winery is planning a new exhibition,
``Wines Through Civilization,'' to showcase the role of wine
throughout history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make it an educational tour, where people can
relax, have fun and learn something about wine,'' the winemaker Joe
Benziger said as workers buzzed around putting the final touches on
the winery.
</P>
<P>
   And what a winery it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We designed it with the latest and greatest in wine
technology,'' Benziger said.
</P>
<P>
   Benziger can monitor and operate the winery from anywhere in the
world, using a laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   Steel tanks can be heated or cooled to maintain precise
temperatures during the fermentation process. The specially
designed tanks can handle large or very small volumes of grapes,
allowing Benziger to make wines in small lots without blending
grapes from different vineyard blocks.
</P>
<P>
   A computer records every step in the viticultural and winemaking
process, creating an electronic archive that allows Benziger to
track changes from vintage to vintage.
</P>
<P>
   The new winery, which can process 3,000 tons of grapes, is twice
the size of the Benziger Family Winery on London Ranch Road. For
the first time in years, the Benzigers will be able to produce all
their wines in house, rather than renting space at other wineries.
</P>
<P>
   It is a homecoming of sorts for the Benziger family.
</P>
<P>
   The family created the fastest-growing segment of the wine
business in the 1980s, marketing a line of inexpensive varietals
under the Glen Ellen brand. The Benzigers sold the label in 1993 to
Heublein and focused on a line of higher-priced wines sold under
the family name.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Benzigers branched out into the beer business,
ripping out several acres of prime merlot vineyards to make room
for the Sonoma Mountain Brewery. The family pulled the plug on the
$4 million brewery early last year, saying it never turned a profit
in 18 months of operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw no light at the end of the tunnel,'' Benziger said.
``We made a business decision to get out early on.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the brewing tanks and iceboxes filled with kegs. The
Benzigers sold the brewing equipment to a beer maker in France,
recouping some of their investment. Now, the brewery is filled with
grape presses and steel fermentation tanks for wine.
</P>
<P>
   The winery will serve as the home of the Benzigers' Imagery
brand. The label focuses on unusual grape varietals like malbec,
cabernet franc, petite sirah, viognier and barbera, produced in
small lots. This winter, Benziger will debut a new line of
single-vineyard cabernet sauvignons under the Imagery label.
</P>
<P>
   The Benzigers plan to double production over the next five
years, from 5,000 cases to about 10,000 cases. The ultrapremium
wines, which retail for $20 to $50 a bottle, will be sold
exclusively in the winery's tasting room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be able to sell every drop out of there,'' Benziger
said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the new winery will be used to make the family's core
Benziger brand, a 175,000-case label with wines that retail for $10
to $40 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the tasting room will be greeted with a free glass
of wine at the door _ although a fee will be charged for additional
tastings _ and encouraged to browse through the art gallery. The
collection, valued at more than $1 million, features original art
commissioned for the Imagery label.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Bob Nugent, an art professor at Sonoma
State University, the winery has commissioned more than 100 artists
over the last 17 years to create paintings that adorn its labels.
Artists are given free rein over the content of their creations,
with one caveat _ all must include a depiction of the Parthenon,
the ancient Greek temple in Athens that has become the winery's
signature.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the paintings were exhibited at the Benzigers'
original winery, most of the collection has been crated up in
storage, until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The art collection is very special,'' Benziger said. ``We
wanted to keep it all in one place.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
