<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1411 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-HEALTH-BUYERS-CLUB-AR     08-24 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BUYERS-CLUB-ART-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOUNT CLUBS FILL THE GAPS IN HEALTH INSURANCE COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich., Texas, Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 was sent Wednesday to NYT photo clients. A
graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A variety of new companies are beginning to offer below-market
prices on prescription drugs and services like doctor, dental and
eye care and medical tests.
</P>
<P>
   Like buyers' discount clubs, including Costco and Sam's Club,
the new companies attract people looking for a better price, in
this case because they have no health insurance or because their
health insurance does not cover the treatments they want.
</P>
<P>
   Individual patients sign up, often on the Internet, and agree to
pay for medical services with cash or a debit or credit card. They
usually pay a small annual membership fee, and get an
identification card that is accepted by a network of doctors,
drugstores and other health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   The drugstores and other providers join the plans _ and accept
the lower prices _ to reach more customers. And doctors, eager to
avoid the payment delays and the restrictions on diagnostic and
treatment choices they experience when patients are using
insurance, accept reduced fees comparable to those they receive
from managed-care companies.
</P>
<P>
   Because the services are so new, there are no firm statistics on
how many people have signed up, or how many thousands of doctors
are involved. But many self-employed people with little or no
insurance find the new discounters particularly useful.
</P>
<P>
   Adria Firestone, a mezzo-soprano who lives in Jersey City, N.J.,
said her union health plan got so expensive that she could no
longer afford full coverage. So when she needed bifocal contact
lenses before a concert in Italy, she showed her card from a
company called Medisavers to a participating Manhattan optometrist.
As a Medisavers member, she paid $306.68 instead of the $475 retail
price.
</P>
<P>
   David Wallen, a free-lance entertainment writer in Los Angeles,
saw a Web site operated by a company called HealthAllies soon after
it began offering doctor services in May. There was no charge to
sign up. ``They negotiated rates for me with the internist and
eye-ear-throat doctor I was already seeing,'' he said. ``It saved
me half on my medical bills. It's great for people without health
insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients with insurance are using the new services as well.
Anyone trying to see a doctor outside his managed-care network, or
looking for a medical service his insurance does not cover, like
acupuncture or cosmetic surgery, may now be able to find a lower
price for what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a real phenomenon,'' said Gail Wilensky, a
health care economist and former White House official. ``People are
going to be able to shop and choose'' from a variety of medical
services including ``individual providers and services they want.''
</P>
<P>
   The new programs are not aimed at people of limited means who do
not qualify for Medicaid, those often referred to as the working
poor. But they can stretch the buying power of people who can
afford to pay for medical care _ including the one in 10 uninsured
people who earn $50,000 a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   Making discounts on health care widely available ``is clearly a
method for making the market work better,'' said Judith Lave, a
professor of health economics at the University of Pittsburgh. ``We
are clearly better off with them than without them.'' But she said
the services would mainly attract patients who were relatively well
off, so the discounts would not solve ``our macro problem,'' the 45
million people without insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Limited alternatives to employer-sponsored medical plans have
existed for some time. AARP, formerly the American Association of
Retired Persons, has long had a mail-order pharmacy for its
members, for example. But the new companies can help people who do
not have an employer or an organization to negotiate the lower
discounts that are typically provided to groups.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent, HealthMarket, a startup in Wilton, Conn. headed
by Stephen F. Wiggins, the former chief executive of Oxford Health
Plans, began listing doctors in the program on its Web site in late
July and plans to add hospitals, dental and vision care and
alternative medicine next month.
</P>
<P>
   Other small companies starting up or expanding discount medical
services include HealthAllies, based in Glendale, Calif.;
MedAdvantage of Southfield, Mich.; AmeriPlanUSA, based in Dallas;
and Medisavers, which also offers health plans to a number of New
York unions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Larger companies are entering the business as well. In June, the
Reader's Digest Association joined with Medco to advertise
drugstore discount cards and mail service to 50 million customers
of Digest magazines, books and records, and says it may eventually
offer other medical services as well.
</P>
<P>
   People who join YourxPlan, the Reader's Digest-Medco program,
pay $25 a year, or $40 annually for a family, to get promised
savings averaging 18 percent on brand-name drugs by mail, and 11
percent at 40,000 participating pharmacies. Members can also check
on prices or order refills on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas O. Ryder, chairman of the Reader's Digest Association,
said it started the business after conducting a survey of customers
of its magazines, books and records. ``We discovered that around 20
million did not have drug coverage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other people find the new services through professional
organizations. Melissa Wahl, executive director of the National
Association for Female Executives, said the organization was
recommending HealthAllies to its 135,000 members, many of whom run
small businesses with limited insurance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new medical service companies hope to grow
substantially if the tight employment market eases, and if big
employers begin to remodel health benefits the way they did when
they replaced pensions with 401(k) plans. If employers make that
change, employees would receive a set amount of money for their
health care needs instead of the relatively open-ended coverage
they have now, and they would spend their own money if their costs
exceeded the set amount.
</P>
<P>
   Already, employees are shouldering more of their health care
costs. The percentage of employees with fully paid health coverage
has dropped sharply under managed care. In 1998, 26.6 percent of
Americans had fully paid care, compared with 45.5 percent in 1983,
said James L. Medoff, a Harvard University economist who studied
the trend for the Center for National Policy, a nonprofit research
organization in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Even the covered services in managed care are disappointing many
patients. ``Health plans have so frustrated consumers that some of
them are ready to reach in their pocket and spend money,'' said
Karen Donelan, a public opinion expert at the Harvard School of
Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody hates the current system,'' said Bill McGahan, a
health care industries investment banker at UBS Warburg.
``Employers don't like it, physicians don't like it, employees
don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-pocket spending on health care services is exploding,
especially for drugs. Americans spent $199.5 billion of their own
money on health care in 1998, by the government's latest count, up
38 percent since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Of that amount, consumers spend $30 billion annually on
alternative medical treatments like acupuncture, said Regina
Herzlinger, a health care expert and professor at the Harvard
Business School.
</P>
<P>
   Donelan said a recent survey by Harris Interactive found that 15
percent to 20 percent of Americans who have health insurance were
already spending their money for extras, including alternative
care.
</P>
<P>
   To capture some of that spending, the online discount health
plans offer services and products that many health plans do not
cover, including expensive, heavily advertised drugs like Claritin
for allergies, lifestyle products like Viagra for male impotence,
and laser surgery to correct nearsightedness.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The new companies are spurring some established health insurers
to expand their offerings. The three biggest managed-care drug
companies, Merck-Medco, PCS and Express Scripts, are inviting a
broader public to try the discounts that they provide to employers
and health maintenance organizations, their main customers.
</P>
<P>
   As for AARP, the group recently waived a $15 annual fee for the
PCS cards it gives to 3.3 million members who buy the
organization's health-related insurance. And in February, the
association began offering member discounts on eye exams, glasses
and contact lenses.
</P>
<P>
   Express Scripts said it was adding more than 500 members each
week to several new drug card programs it started this summer with
groups like Seniority America, which sells services to people over
50.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As with much of what is available on the Web, the information
provided by the new medical companies is not always screened for
reliability or accuracy. The Web sites provide only limited
information about the doctors in their programs, and many rely on
outside organizations that have been approved by the National
Committee for Quality Assurance to vet doctors' credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers on their own looking for quality information about
doctors are at a real disadvantage,'' said Barry Scholl, a
spokesman for the quality assurance committee, whose main function
is to set standards and accredit managed-care plans. On Thursday,
legislation in California that would have regulated the discount
companies was defeated. Consumer advocates and some medical groups
said the law would have been too lax.
</P>
<P>
   At one startup company, HealthAllies.com, the listings on
doctors include their addresses, fees, the number of patients they
see each day, and whether they are board-certified in their
specialties. The company promises savings of 10 percent to 50
percent on ``the things insurance doesn't cover.''
</P>
<P>
   On HealthMarket, Wiggins' startup, consumers can get
information, including professional profiles of doctors, fees and
full charges for dozens of treatments. Individuals pay $29 a year
and families pay $49, plus a transaction fee for each service used.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said they liked the prompt hassle-free payments and
increased patient flow. Dr. Stephen B. Meisel, a radiologist who is
chief executive of Medfocus, a national chain of 1,800 medical
imaging centers, said the direct-to-consumer services were ``a
great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we sign up with insurance companies or employers,'' he
said, ``we give them a good value because they provide patient
volume. We offer the same range of fees for HealthAllies.com. The
patients are getting a big break.'' For example, he said, a
magnetic resonance imaging scan, or MRI, in New York City would
cost ``50 percent off the retail price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
