<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1426 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DAVIS-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      08-24 0306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMG AND CLIVE DAVIS START NEW LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: No byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a stormy public relations battle over his leadership
succession at Arista Records, Clive Davis has formally fashioned a
deal with BMG Entertainment to head a new label with a roster that
includes up-and-coming young artists and Q-Tip, the rapper.
</P>
<P>
   The new label, which will be called J Records, is a joint
venture between BMG and Davis, who founded Arista in 1975 and was
replaced in July as chief executive by Antonio Reid. That
succession was marked by tensions between BMG's top executives and
Davis, 67, who issued public statements attributing his departure
to the imposition of a general retirement policy by BMG's corporate
parent, Bertelsmann AG.
</P>
<P>
   That retirement standard applies only to top executives at the
media conglomerate, which required its previous chief executive,
for example, to step down at age 60. But even so, a number of
artists on contract with Arista criticized the corporate power
shift. They said they believed Davis was ousted because of his age
despite a banner year at Arista, which included Carlos Santana's
commercial comeback.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the struggles of the past were not mentioned in the
news release issued by BMG and Davis, who had been talking with
other music companies about starting a label. Davis will be
creating J Records with a team of some familiar faces from Arista
including Charles Goldstuck, former executive vice president and
general manager at Arista.
</P>
<P>
   The first recordings from the company are expected as early as
this October. One person close to the negotiations said that J
Records' new roster will feature Deborah Cox, LFO, Shannon Curfman,
Alicia Keys, Jim Cozier and O-Town, a boy band that is the subject
of a television series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-SURVIVOR-RATINGS-A     08-24 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-RATINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS LOOKS AHEAD TO SUPER BOWL, SUPER `SURVIVOR' AND SUPER SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: also moving in `f' category) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final episode of the CBS series ``Survivor'' reached an
audience of more than 50 million viewers Wednesday night, eclipsing
every show of any kind on television in the last year except the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour double episode of ``Survivor,'' which reduced four
finalists to a single winner, Richard Hatch, beat every episode of
series television over the last year, including ``ER'' the biggest
regular-season hit on the networks, and even topped last April's
broadcast of the Academy Awards, which in every other season is
second in audience only to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The finale even beat every night of Olympic broadcasts over the
last three Olympiads. It was, CBS said, the 11th most-watched
episode of a series in the history of television.
</P>
<P>
   Just as impressive for CBS, a network with a reputation for
rarely reaching the young adult viewers most advertisers prefer,
``Survivor'' was strongest among viewers between 18 and 34 years
old. The finale reached more than 60 percent of the viewers in that
age group tuned in to television from 8 to 10 p.m. Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The success sets CBS up for some enormous payoffs, starting with
the second edition of ``Survivor'' set to start in January, which
CBS' top sales executive, Joseph Abruzzese, predicted would attract
the highest per-commercial price of any series on television in the
coming season. ``Survivor II'' will begin the night of Jan. 30,
immediately after the Super Bowl, which CBS will broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that's going to be the most profitable night in the
history of television,'' said Leslie Moonves, the president of CBS
Television.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl always attracts the highest prices for
commercials every television season, but the game comes with an
expensive fee of hundreds of millions of dollars for rights from
the NFL. ``Survivor'' has a budget of less than $1 million an
episode and CBS owns the show with its executive producer Mark
Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Survivor II'' following the Super Bowl, CBS expects to
charge record prices for advertising for the entire evening. David
F. Poltrack, executive vice president for research at CBS, even
suggested that having ``Survivor II'' follow the game ensured that
viewers would stay tuned even if the game became lopsided. ``We may
have found the only programming with the potential to actually
benefit the Super Bowl,'' Poltrack said.
</P>
<P>
   Abruzzese said that advertisers, who had traditionally used the
Super Bowl to introduce products and ad campaigns, were already
talking about extending that strategy into the first new episode of
`'Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   The network is also predicting a ``Survivor'' bounce for its new
lineup of fall prime-time series, all of which were heavily
promoted during the 13-week run of ``Survivor.'' Poltrack said that
CBS' tracking studies showed that the new CBS shows were far ahead
of any upcoming show on any other network in terms of audience
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves declined to predict that CBS could become the leading
network in prime time in the next year, but he did say, ``I think
we're going to make it a very interesting season.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other statistics racked up by ``Survivor'' were a total
audience _ viewers who watched some portion of the show Wednesday
night _ of 72 million. The average audience figure for the entire
telecast was 51.7 million. It was by far the most-watched network
broadcast in the summer since Nielsen Media Research initiated its
People Meter Rating System in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The entire 13-episode run of the series was an extraordinary
success. It averaged a 17 rating and 30 percent share of the
audience. That would have ranked the show second among all series
in television's regular season, behind only ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Poltrack pointed out that ``Survivor'' undoubtedly had more
viewers than officially counted. ``About 20 percent of the people
in America are on vacation in the months of June, July, and August.
Those people were surely watching in motels and hotels but they
weren't being counted.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS saw some additional immediate advantages from its enormous
night. The CBS local station in New York, WCBS, saw its late news
ratings soar by almost 200 percent. The network's late night star
David Letterman brought on the 16 ``Survivor'' contestants for a
Top 10 list _ featuring Hatch going naked _ and scored his
third-highest rating this year.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves also said CBS hoped to begin cashing in on an extensive
merchandising effort, selling ``Survivor''-related products,
everything from hats and T-shirts to camping equipment. The network
has already released an e-book and will soon release a conventional
book based on the show, along with a board game from Mattel and CD
of music from the show.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the cast members have also made deals for themselves but
Hatch is obviously in the best position. In a telephone interview
Thursday he declined to discuss what deals he had made, though he
acknowledged that he was considering writing his own book.
</P>
<P>
   The other biggest winner from the show's spectacular success is
the producer, Burnett. Moonves said Thursday that the ownership
deal on the show was ``extremely complicated,'' but that Burnett
was entitled to a portion of the advertising revenue from
`Survivor,'' both for this edition and future ones.
</P>
<P>
   Abruzzese said that Burnett helped sell the show to the list of
nine sponsors who signed on before it began, including Reebok
shoes, Budweiser Beer, Target stores and Ericsson phones. ``They
got one of the best deals ever, tremendous bang for their buck,''
Moonves said.
</P>
<P>
   But once the show became a hit, CBS began selling an additional
minute of advertising in the show each week, mainly to movie
companies. CBS extended the finale from one hour to two hours and
had the whole second hour to sell at new prices, which reached as
high as $600,000 for a 30-second commercial. The network also sold
the hourlong discussion show that followed at lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett shared in all that new advertising revenue. ``He got
half and we got half,'' Abruzzese said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Burnett is definitely becoming a very wealthy man,''
Moonves said.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
