<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1430 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-24 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A REALITY-TELEVISION CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If George W. Bush were a ``Survivor'' contestant, he would have
been Kelly, who made it to the finals with her ability to recall
the details of her former teammates' family histories.
</P>
<P>
   Really, the man can run into somebody he met 15 years ago for
five minutes in a hotel lobby and you'd have thought they roomed
together at prep school. This may not be the most important talent
in the universe, but it's surprisingly rare in the male of the
species.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea what your wife's name is. Isn't that
interesting?'' exclaimed Richard, the eventual ``Survivor'' winner,
to another contestant with whom he had spent 39 long, intense and
occasionally naked days.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Richard went home with the $1 million has caused
many Americans to question the existence of a benevolent deity, and
we will not be so cruel as to suggest that if Al Gore had been on
the island, he would have been Richard. But Gore did tell the
Democratic convention that he was not concerned about being
lovable. This came after four days of continuous effort to convince
the nation that the vice president was adorable as all get-out, and
was therefore a very Richard thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Many people seem to feel they have gotten a real education in
the downside of the human character from ``Survivor.'' The show
didn't have an equivalent to Nick Bateman, the archvillain of the
British version of ``Big Brother,'' who attempted to win the
support of his fellow contestants by telling them that his
nonexistent wife had been tragically killed in a car crash. The
tabloid press urged that helicopters be used to drop leaflets
warning the housebound competitors about the viper in their midst.
When ``Nasty Nick'' was evicted for cheating last week, The Sun,
which had led the campaign against him, swiftly hired him as a
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   But we digress. The subject at hand is whether the ``Survivor''
mania can teach us any lessons about the current presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   There were some similarities. The ``Survivor'' finale went on
way too long, much like this political season, which seems to
stretch back to the Battle of Hastings. The ``Survivor'' jurors all
wound up protesting that they hated both the candidates and didn't
want to vote for anybody, which certainly sounds familiar.
</P>
<P>
   And weirdly, as the show wound down, the contestants began
talking a little like Bush. The people on the island had the
advantage of some careful editing, but you still couldn't help
noting that a lot of them tended to rush verbally forward,
stringing words together without much concern for where the trail
was taking them. (One convoluted rationale by a Richard supporter
concluded with the announcement that ``Kelly was more
double-faced.'')
</P>
<P>
   Like Kelly, Bush has had a not-great week. Gore is rising in the
polls. There's a growing suspicion that the public is never going
to embrace the $1.3 trillion tax cut that sits like a great wart in
the middle of the Bush agenda. And on Monday, the candidate
delivered a speech that connoisseurs of Bushian malapropisms
regarded as a four-star keeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot let terrorists and rogue nations hold this nation
hostile or hold our allies hostile,'' he told an Iowa fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   He also promised to ``work to end terrors _ tariffs and
barriers,'' and to bring an end to ``four years of Clinton-Gore.''
His attempts to defend the tax cut were marred by an unfortunate
tendency to mix up billions and trillions. As a finale, Bush
assured the audience that victory was theirs because ``we're
talking about issues in a way the American people can understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after vowing to do a better job of explaining the tax cut
to average voters, he proceeded to give a disquisition that even
the above-average national correspondents on his press plane found
bewildering.
</P>
<P>
   Tired politicians always tend to mess up their syntax.
Unfortunately, Bush's Iowa speech came after he had taken a day off
the trail to return to Austin, for a schedule in which the word
``nap'' figured prominently.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Bush can turn all this to his advantage. The babbling
thing seems to be spreading, and Americans may prefer a president
who would not look down on them if they forgot to insert verbs in
their sentences. They might conclude that at least he's not, you
know, like, double-faced.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
