<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ALASKA-PARKS-ART-NYT &LR;      08-24 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-PARKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKA, FLUSH WITH TOURISM, CHANGES ITS OPINION OF CARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE. Alaska _ On a visit Wednesday to the state where his
legacy is larger than that of anyone since the man who bought
Alaska from Russia for 2 cents an acre, former President Jimmy
Carter again had to pass through a knot of people shouting his name
and waving placards in his face.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of burning Carter in effigy and shouting obscenities
as Alaskans have done in past visits, the crowds that greeted him
in the twilight of summer hailed Carter as a hero and visionary for
what has been called the greatest conservation act in American
history.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, just weeks before handing the presidency to
Ronald Reagan, Carter signed a bill that protected an area of
Alaska equal in size to California. The Alaska National Interest
Lands Conservation Act declared 104 million acres as national
parks, wildlife refuges and wilderness. It more than doubled the
acreage in the national park system and tripled the amount of
public land that cannot be developed.
</P>
<P>
   The Lands Act, which Alaska's political and business elite saw
as a betrayal of the state and a blueprint for economic ruin, has
helped to spur a $1 billion annual tourist economy.
</P>
<P>
   Carter used his triumphant return to Alaska this week to urge
President Clinton to settle an issue left unresolved when the act
was passed: whether to allow oil and gas development in the Arctic
National Wildlife Refuge. The refuge is a summer range for more
than 100,000 caribou and untold numbers of birds, but it also holds
what is believed to be the biggest untapped oil fields in the
nation, perhaps as much as 10 billion barrels, which would be
second only to the output now flowing from Alaska's North Slope.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Carter called on Clinton to declare the
refuge a national monument, an act that would infuriate many
Alaskans because it would almost certainly prevent development. The
president does not plan to declare the area a monument, his aides
said Thursday, but they did not rule out the possibility that he
might change his mind during the waning days of his presidency,
especially if Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican nominee, is
elected.
</P>
<P>
   For the business interests that have never gotten over the
passage of the Lands Act, the prospect of new protections is
unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what Alaskans fear the most,'' said Carl Portman,
deputy director of the Resource Development Council, which
represents major businesses in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The question of what to do with the Arctic refuge, which has
been largely overlooked outside of Alaska, could be the biggest
environmental decision by the next president. Bush favors opening
the refuge to oil and gas development, while Vice President Al
Gore, the Democratic nominee, says it should be protected, although
he has not come out for designating it as a monument.
</P>
<P>
   History has been kind to Carter's act, the former president said
this week, and some prominent Republicans in this state grudgingly
agreed with him. In December 1980, a month after he was voted out
of office, Carter signed a bill that had been fought over, in one
version or another, since Alaska was made a state in 1959. It has
been called the biggest zoning act in history, designating 10 new
units to the National Park system and protecting nearly a third of
the state from development. Carter ranks it among the biggest
achievements of his career.
</P>
<P>
   But at the time, it looked like Carter would never be able to
set foot in this state. At the Alaska State Fair, he recalled, he
was a bigger villain than the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, as
people lined up to throw bottles at his image. Just months after
Carter left office, he stopped in Anchorage on his way to Tokyo,
and the Secret Service urged him not to leave the air base for fear
of what angry Alaskans might do to him.
</P>
<P>
   One National Park Service plane was burned at Wrangell-St.
Elias, the biggest national park in the nation, and the cables were
cut on another plane. The governor of Alaska at the time, Jay
Hammond, a Republican, said he would sue to stop the act, calling
it a ``de facto repeal of statehood.'' Alaska's Congressional
delegation vowed to undermine it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of predictions were made that Alaska would go to hell if
this much land was taken away from gas and oil development,''
Carter said in a speech here Wednesday before 600 people that drew
five standing ovations. ``But Alaskans have done well. Tourists
come here to find a solitude, a beauty, sites that are not
available to a Georgian or someone from Ohio or Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska has become one of Carter's favorite places. He has heard
the thunder of caribou herds as they migrate out of the Arctic
Slope, he has seen a brown bear up close, and he has caught a
31-inch rainbow trout on a very small fly. This week he planned to
fish at Lake Clark National Park, one of the parks created by the
Lands Act.
</P>
<P>
   More than three million tourists a year visit the new parks,
refuges and monuments created by Carter. In Seward, the town named
for Secretary of State William Seward, who bought Alaska for $7.2
million in 1867, a multimillion-dollar industry has developed
around ships that take visitors to the bird rookeries and glaciers
of Kenai Fjords National Park. The town rescinded a 20-year-old
resolution opposing Carter's action.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond, the former governor, has also had a change of heart.
Seated at the dais with Carter on Wednesday, he said most Alaskans
now favored the act for which Carter was so vilified.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Alaska's Congressional and business leaders no
longer talk of overturning the Lands Act, they say it has blocked
access to many areas and stifled needed development in rural
communities. Many people want snowmobiles, new roads and airstrips
in the parks and monuments. They say small-time miners, the
archetypal sourdoughs of Alaska, have been shut out of the lands.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's critics believe the interests of Alaska were overlooked
by a leader far removed from the state.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, chairman of the Appropriations Committee,
opposed the act 20 years ago and still says it was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Thom, a spokesman for Rep. Don Young, a Republican who has
been Alaska's Congressional representative for more than 20 years,
said, ``Signing the act was one of the darkest days in Alaska
history, a travesty of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   None of Alaska's congressional leaders were at the anniversary
luncheon for Carter on Wednesday, nor was Gov. Tony Knowles, a
Democrat. But for the overflow crowd, it was a celebration that had
a ``told you so'' air to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember what Morris Udall, the congressman most responsible
for the act, said when he came back to Alaska in the mid-'80s,''
Deborah L. Williams, executive director of the Alaska Conservation
Foundation, said at the celebration. ``He said, `Just like in the
'70s, everyone waves at me, but this time all five fingers are
extended.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
