<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES FLAT AS ORDERS FOR DURABLE GOODS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices were flat Thursday after the government
reported a larger-than-expected drop in orders for durable goods in
July, suggesting that the Federal Reserve will hold off raising
interest rates again this year.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day, the price of the 10-year note rose 1/32, to
105 9/32, and its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from
the price, fell to 5.71 percent from 5.72 percent on Wednesday. The
30-year bond rose 8/32, to 108 16/32. Its yield fell to 5.66
percent from 5.67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 12.4 percent plunge in durable goods orders last month was
the largest on record and surpassed economists' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Maury N. Harris, chief economist at PaineWebber, said the
``orders data are consistent with our forecast for GDP growth to
slow in the third quarter to 3.3 percent at an annual rate after
5.2 percent growth in the second quarter.'' He said the numbers
were consistent with forecasts that the Federal Open Market
Committee, which next meets on Oct. 3, would keep interest rates
static indefinitely. ``Nevertheless, one should not overreact to
the weakness in these numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Fleming Asset
Management, said, ``Signs of a moderating economy, coupled with
faster productivity growth that is helping to suppress inflationary
tendencies, has given the Fed some breathing room in its quest to
maneuver the economy into a soft landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furthermore,'' Fine said, ``the proximity of the presidential
election makes it highly unlikely that any change in policy would
be instituted at the Oct. 3 FOMC meeting. Thus, if the Fed should
deem additional tightening necessary, a clearly debatable point
both inside and outside the FOMC, the Nov. 15 meeting would appear
to be the earliest conceivable date for further action.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed is still very sensitive to the potential for
inflation in a vibrant economy with a 4 percent unemployment rate,
Fine said, the Fed will not raise interest rates for a while unless
economic growth picks up or inflationary pressures become
threatening, or both. He says neither appears imminent.
</P>
<P>
   With the Fed expected to adhere to an unchanged monetary policy,
bonds are likely to trade in a range, Fine said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pugliese, senior vice president and director of the
fixed-income department at the J.W. Genesis Financial Corp. in Boca
Raton, Fla., also saw the bond market's lack of reaction to
Thursday's data as a sign that it was trading well ahead of itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this economic slowdown is not as strong as what
Treasury rates are telling us,'' he said. ``You just can't put a
pen to paper to justify the current rates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
