<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITCHBLADE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT THE GOOD WITCH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' refers to Sun., Aug. 27) 
Our rating: 1 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Witchblade'' is obviously based on a comic book, but it's hard
at times to tell which one. It's about a tough-babe cop who, thanks
to some mystical mumbo-jumbo, gets this goofy-looking metal arm
that deflects bullets just like Wonder Woman's wristbands and pops
out villain-skewering daggers similar to the knuckle-bound cutlery
of the X-Men's Wolverine.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Pezzini (Yancy Butler, who takes this role more
staggeringly seriously than anyone could ever imagine) is haunted
by memories of a dead-dad cop and an iced estranged pal.
Surrounding her are a partner (William Yun Lee), who's around just
long enough to mention the wife and kids before the inevitable
happens; a moony, hunky cop (David Chokachi) who takes time from
his Tommy Hilfiger photo shoots to provide snippets of exposition;
and a zealously murderous evil genius (Conrad Dunn) of the sort
that exist only in really stupid movies.
</P>
<P>
   There are also a couple of mysterious figures who disappear
whenever there's a convenient break in the editing _ and, given
Norman Buckley's MTV-on-speed cutting and ``Matrix''-on-a-budget
visual effects, that's fairly often _ who are tied in some fashion
to an ethereal goofball named Irons (Anthony Cistaro). Irons
studies up on this sort of thing so he can tell Sara, ``The
Witchblade has a way of slipping from its wearer's grasp just when
it is needed most'' _ kind of like common sense in this movie. It
gets worse _ the gizmo is ``a mystery wrapped in a riddle and
cloaked in a conundrum.'' Even though this is clearly designed to
spin off into an equally dumb TV series, Irons sums it up for us
when he says, ``You've disappointed me, Sara.''
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
The show: ``Witchblade.'' &QL; 
What: Action flick/potential pilot for a TV series based on a comic
book about a crime-fighting dame with a magical metal arm. &QL; 
The stars: Yancy Butler, Anthony Cistaro, Conrad Dunn, David
Cokachi, William Yun Lee, Eric Etebari. &QL; 
Where: TNT. &QL; 
When: 8, 10 and midnight tonight; also Tuesday, Wednesday, Saturday
and Sept. 4. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
