<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASKELL, TRAVERS COULD PRODUCE CHAMPION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to selecting a champion 3-year-old colt at the end
of the year, summertime races such as the Haskell Invitational and
the Travers Stakes don't mean much.
</P>
<P>
   At least that has been the case each of the past three years in
thoroughbred racing. Since 1997, horses that haven't even competed
in the Haskell, Travers and Breeders' Cup Classic have been
selected the champion 3-year-old colt.
</P>
<P>
   The list of those horses that have won the races, but lost the
championship, isn't bad. Touch Gold won the Haskell _ he even won
the Belmont Stakes _ but he missed being 3-year-old champion in
1997. Coronado's Quest won more big stakes races than any
3-year-old in '98 _ including the Haskell and the Travers _ yet he
was no champ. And Lemon Drop Kid won the Travers last year, then
Cat Thief was the Breeders' Cup Classic winner, and both of those
horses got little mention when it came time to pick a champion.
</P>
<P>
   If those horses didn't stand out, there is something that stood
out about each of those seasons. There was a 3-year-old that pulled
the Kentucky Derby-Preakness Stakes double and almost won the
Triple Crown in the Belmont: Silver Charm in '97, Real Quiet in '98
and Charismatic last year. All were selected champion even if they
took the rest of the year off.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen this year.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus hasn't raced since
the Preakness, though trainer Neil Drysdale smugly suggests that he
will in the fall. And Preakness winner Red Bullet is out for the
year because an X-ray revealed the start of a crack in his left
front cannon bone.
</P>
<P>
   So, maybe it's time for the spotlight to fall back upon the
Haskell and the Travers. If that's the case, it could be the start
of a championship run for Dixie Union. The colt is co-owned by
Gerald J. Ford of Dallas, whose name adorns the new SMU football
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Union already has won the Haskell, and he'll be the
favorite in the Travers because Arkansas Derby winner and Jim Dandy
Stakes winner Graeme Hall will miss the race because of an injured
knee.
</P>
<P>
   Just going on his Haskell victory, Dixie Union is special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had every right not to run well in that race,''
trainer Richard Mandella said. ``He got pinched going into the
backstretch. He came close to clipping heels. He lost three lengths
within a jump.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more. Dixie Union finished fifth in the Breeders' Cup
Juvenile last year and had to miss the Triple Crown because a bone
chip had to be removed from a knee. Before the injury, Dixie Union
won four of five races and defeated the likes of Exchange Rate,
High Yield, Captain Steve and eventual Breeders' Cup Juvenile
winner Anees.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he can pull off the Haskell-Travers double, Dixie Union
will have to do something special later this year. After
second-place finishes in the Preakness and Belmont in '96, Skip
Away won the Haskell and finished third in the Travers. Then his
special moment came: He beat Cigar in the Jockey Club Gold Cup, and
he was chosen champion 3-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   If Dixie Union can't find his special moment in the weeks after
the Travers, the champion 3-year-old will be Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   LATE SCRATCHES REMATCH, AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Heritage of Gold has jumped to the top of the older female ranks
by virtue of her two victories this year against defending champion
Beautiful Pleasure. But she'll be tested again Friday, because both
horses are entered in the Grade I $400,000 Personal Ensign Handicap
at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   It's a 11/4-mile race, and both horses carry equal weights and
have to spot 11 to 12 pounds to the other three horses in the race.
But trainer Tom Amoss is confident after Heritage of Gold erased a
seven-length deficit to beat Beautiful Pleasure by a length in the
Grade I Go For Wand last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was more relaxed and more professional last time out than
she's ever been,'' Amoss said.
</P>
<P>
   GOLD NUGGET RESTS
</P>
<P>
   After finishing third at odds of 30-to-1 in the Grade I Eddie
Read Handicap on July 30 at Del Mar, the next start for Gold Nugget
is up in the air. According to owner Leland Cook, Gold Nugget was
lined up for the Fourstardave Handicap _ with Pat Day getting the
riding assignment _ Saturday at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he didn't come out of his last workout Sunday on his toes
like he did before the trip to Del Mar,'' Cook said. ``So, we're
going to pass for now.''
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming starts for Gold Nugget, champion turf horse at Lone
Star Park at Grand Prairie this year, could be either the Grade III
Bay Meadows Handicap on Sept. 23 at Bay Meadows, the $50,000 Sport
City Handicap on Sept. 4 at Louisiana Downs or the $100,000 Texas
Hall of Fame Stakes on Oct. 7 at Retama Park.
</P>
<P>
   LONE STAR SALE
</P>
<P>
   The Fasig-Tipton Texas Summer Yearling Sale is offering 400
horses at its auction Monday and Tuesday. The start time is noon
each day at the sales pavilion at Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   Among the horses scheduled for auction are siblings to these
horses: former TTA Futurity winners I'm Allthat and Louetta;
Middleground Stakes winner Superpave; Independence Handicap winner
Jest In Orbit; and Grade III Round Table Handicap winner Slew O
Mink.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON: BOB BAFFERT
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert's jokes sometimes fall short. In fact, the more he
forces them, the more they fall short. And he forces them with
increasing frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert trains General Challenge and River Keen, who both are
entered in Saturday's $1 million Pacific Classic at Del Mar
(televised 5:30-6:30 p.m., TVG). So, Baffert's chance to crack a
joke came at the post position draw.
</P>
<P>
   When Baffert was informed by a television reporter that River
Keen and General Challenge had drawn the two inside post positions,
Baffert joked that the draw had been fixed because people were
conspiring against him.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert had no quick reply when the reporter asked him how there
could be a fix against his horses when John Mabee, who owns General
Challenge, is the longtime chairman at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   Post position is unlikely to make much difference in a race with
the distance of 11/4 miles and only seven horses in the starting
gate. Baffert finally admitted it later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to have my two horses together,'' Baffert said. ``But
we're just happy to be in the race and that the horses are doing
well. That's more important than post position in a mile and a
quarter race.''
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge is the 9-to-5 favorite. River Keen is 15-1.
The rest of the field from the inside post out is Euchre (8-1),
Tiznow (5-1), Skimming (5-2), Ecton Park (7-2) and Forty One Carats
(12-1).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVERS TOPS PACIFIC CLASSIC
</P>
<P>
   Both the Travers Stakes in New York and the Pacific Classic in
California offer purses of $1 million and will be contested
Saturday. The Travers (ESPN, 3-4:30 p.m.) is restricted to
3-year-olds and the Pacific Classic is open to horses 3 years old
and older. It would make sense that the Pacific Classic would
produce horses that would be more successful later in the year in
the Breeders' Cup Classic, but the statistics don't support that
notion:
</P>
<P>
   {Travers Pacific Classic} Number of horses to the Breeders' Cup
Classic 179 153 Average finish in Breeders' Cup Classic 5th 6th
Best finish in Breeders' Cup Classic 1st 2nd {Note:} Concern (1994)
and Cat Thief (1999) won the Breeders' Cup Classic after competing
in the Travers the same year. Twilight Agenda (1991) and Bertrando
(1993) finished second in the Breeders' Cup Classic after competing
in the Pacific Classic the same year. Paseana won the Breeders' Cup
Distaff (1992) after competing in the Pacific Classic.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
