<HEADER>
A1461 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-STEPMOMS-HARRISO     08-24 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-STEPMOMS-HARRISON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MYTH OF THE EVIL STEPMOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Friday, Aug. 25, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By KATHRYN HARRISON    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's report of three studies showing that children raised
by stepmothers are likely to receive less food, health care and
education than children raised by their biological mothers should
not have come as much of a surprise _ especially to mothers.
However impolitic it may be to ask, who really believes that
stepmothers can possibly replicate the care of the original mother,
notwithstanding the moist optimism of movies like ``Stepmom,'' in
which the earnest efforts of Julia Roberts are enough to secure a
stepchild's happy future?
</P>
<P>
   Mothering, be it by way of the womb, marriage or adoption, is
relentless, even under the best of circumstances. Despite the
cultural myth that mothers have an endless capacity to give, their
means of expressing love _ their time, energy and material assets _
are finite.
</P>
<P>
   And stepmothers, no matter how devoted, may be hampered by a
combination of factors unique to their situation: a lack of basic
factual knowledge about the child, the complicating presence of the
biological mother, the hostility of stepchildren traumatized by
divorce, the father's unwillingness to interfere, and their own
sense of alienation from the tribe of the original family.
</P>
<P>
   The new studies, while in no way suggesting that stepmothers are
wicked or consciously negligent, oddly dovetail with our culture's
traditional suspicion of them. Portrayed in fairy tales, the
stepmother is a grasping woman who favors her own offspring, no
matter how ill-deserving, over those of an earlier, presumably
dead, wife.
</P>
<P>
   As the stepchild's fortunes unfold in the original Grimm's
version of Cinderella, it's not the stepmother who dresses the
unloved stepdaughter for the prince's ball and thus vouchsafes her
future in the castle, but a magic hazel tree growing above the
grave of Cinderella's own dead mother, a tree inhabited by a
ministering white bird _ her mother's hovering spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Case, the Princeton economist who was the chief researcher
in the three studies, was surprised to find that contact two or
three times a month between the stepchild and his or her biological
mother was sufficient to raise the child's health care status to
the same level as that of those children who live with both
biological parents. But if the biological mother of the stepchild
is dead? Basic health care _ measured as a medical checkup within
the last year _ plummeted, she found.
</P>
<P>
   Stepmothers in fairy tales derive from a harsher agrarian epoch,
when resources were scarce and life, especially childbirth, a much
dicier proposition. If we can ignore their tendency to represent
good and evil unalloyed, such stories remain pertinent as
repositories of the human dynamic in our own post-industrial
society, when motherhood is increasingly nonbiological, though not
for reasons of morbidity.
</P>
<P>
   In Grimm's ``The Juniper Tree,'' a stepson is sacrificed to
safeguard the fortunes of his half-sister. Resurrected as a many
colored bird, he flies from the branches of the tree that bears his
mother's spirit. With eyes like stars and a song whose verses
enumerate the injustices he suffered, the brother ultimately
restores order to the family.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we can use studies like the ones from Princeton to that
same end: to reveal inequality and achieve a finer balance. More
than half of today's children will live apart from at least one
biological parent by the time they reach 18. The stories of their
families will point up not only how hard it is to be a stepchild,
but how complicated and challenging is the role of the stepmother.
</P>
<P>
   (Kathryn Harrison is the author, most recently, of ``The Binding
Chair: Or, A Visit From the Foot Emancipation Society.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
