s f BC-INVEST-401-PLANS-$ADV     08-24 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-401-PLANS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIREMENT SAVINGS PLANS: SOMETIMES, ALL YOU HAVE TO DO IS ASK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 27) 
 By SANA SIWOLOP    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Workers at the 15 retail stores of the Tile Shop do not receive
many of the perks that many a new-economy employer may dish up to
attract talent. They get no stock options, no nap rooms and
certainly no on-site pet care.
</P>
<P>
   But the company does offer a big lure for new hires: Instead of
waiting months or years to be eligible to join the 401(k)
retirement savings plan, workers at Tile Shop can join as soon as
they walk in the door.
</P>
<P>
   As job-hopping has become common in many industries, employers
say that the traditional waiting periods for benefits have become
an obstacle to recruiting. Qualified workers who already have
benefits are loath to do without them, even temporarily, to take a
new job.
</P>
<P>
   So more employers are reducing or eliminating the probationary
periods for savings plans, vacation time, profit sharing and
sometimes even medical insurance coverage, benefits experts say.
And companies that have not formally changed their waiting periods
are increasingly willing to waive them if a potentially valuable
new employee asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the current job market, this is a highly desirable thing to
offer,'' said Dallas L. Salisbury, president and chief executive of
the Employee Benefit Research Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Hard statistics are scant, but many companies say they see
anecdotal evidence that when benefits are available quickly,
vacancies are filled faster and turnover among new employees is
lower.
</P>
<P>
   The short-wait or no-wait approach seems to spreading fastest
for retirement savings plans. According to surveys by the
Profit-Sharing/401(k) Council of America, a nonprofit organization
that includes both sponsors and providers of plans, 40 percent of
companies let new employees join 401(k) plans within their first
three months in 1999, up from 32 percent the previous year. And 18
percent made them eligible for profit-sharing plans that quickly,
up from 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Liberto, a vice president at Segal Advisors, the
investment consulting unit of the Segal Co., a benefits consulting
firm based in New York, estimated that over the last year, at least
one-third of his company's clients have shortened or eliminated
waiting periods for 401(k)'s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing clients moving away from one-year eligibility to
either immediate eligibility or eligibility the month following the
beginning of employment,'' he said. ``Companies see it as a
competitive issue. Allowing people to come into a plan immediately
doesn't penalize them for coming from another job.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a tight labor market is at work. Federal rules
governing 401(k) plans oblige employers to enroll as many middle-
and low-paid workers as possible, to ensure that the plan is not
deemed to unfairly favor highly paid workers, though recent rulings
have eased some of the restrictions. Companies can now enroll
workers automatically, and the Internet has made benefits
administration easier for employers.
</P>
<P>
   But recruiting is the primary motive. Pearson Inc., the American
arm of Pearson PLC, the media conglomerate based in London,
eliminated its three-month wait for medical benefits in January
1999. A year later, it trimmed the wait for 401(k) plan eligibility
fromas long as six months to no more than 30 days, depending on
the date of hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten positive feedback that this has been an effective
recruiting tool,'' said Randall Keller, senior vice president for
human resources.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tile Shop chain, based in Plymouth, Minn., executives
were also concerned about retention; Minnesota, after all, has an
unemployment rate of just 2.5 percent. Historically, turnover in
the company's sales and manufacturing divisions ran to 80 percent a
year, and personnel officers found themselves having to fill the
same jobs every few months. Scrapping the 90-day wait to join the
401(k) has given new workers a greater stake in staying, said
Dianna Kincade, the human resources director at the company.
</P>
<P>
   Immediate eligibility for medical plans, however, is not yet as
common, but it, too, is spreading. Kenneth Jacobsen, who leads the
national health practice at Segal, said many more companies were
shortening the wait for medical coverage from 90 days to 30.
``We're seeing this trend in mid- to large-sized companies, and
we're seeing it at a pace that is three to four times higher than a
year or two ago,'' Jacobsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all waiting periods appear headed for the out box. Employee
stock ownership plans, for example, still tend to have one-year
eligibility requirements, because they are explicitly intended to
reward longevity, said Corey Rosen, director of the National Center
for Employee Ownership in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Experts caution that ``immediate eligibility'' can mean
different things at different companies. Prospective employees
should check the fine print to make sure that they understand a
company's rules. ``It might be the first day of earnings, or it
might be the first day of the first month after you start work, or
even the first day of the second month,'' said David Wray,
president of the Profit Sharing/401(k) Council. The variations
sometimes reflect differences in how quickly companies process a
new employee's paperwork, he said. Knowing when coverage will
start, of course, helps job changers decide whether to extend their
former employers' medical coverage under the federal Cobra law to
cover any gap.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whether they kick in immediately or almost immediately,
accelerated benefits are making a difference. Carl Randazzo, a
regional manager at the Tile Shop, said turnover had dropped
sharply at the five stores he manages since his company eliminated
the waiting period for its 401(k) plan. The change, Randazzo added,
is also making a big difference in hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are looking at two job offers, this benefit can
cinch it so that they go with us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
