<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-780&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      08-24 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, BUSH PUTS THE FOCUS ON TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)  (See also BUSH-AD) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Gov. George W. Bush sought to seize the offensive
Thursday on the issue of tax cuts, charging that Vice President Al
Gore's plan was so narrow and complicated that it would fail to
lower taxes for many middle-class Americans.
</P>
<P>
   To make his case, Bush expanded his previously arranged schedule
to include two events where he introduced families whose taxes, he
said, would be lowered significantly under his own plan, but very
little, if at all, under Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The so-called `targeted' tax cut means that some are targeted
out of tax relief,'' Bush said at an airport event in New Orleans,
referring to Gore's plan.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the example of the man standing beside him, Andrew
Bechac, a high school teacher and football coach who supports a
wife and two young children on $40,000 a year. Bush said that if
his tax cut was enacted, Bechac would pay the federal government
$475 a year _ about $1,600 less than he now does.
</P>
<P>
   In a later speech, Bush returned to the example of the Bechacs,
making a more concrete pitch for his tax-cut proposal than he was
able to muster earlier in the week, when he stumbled over some
numbers and then conceded that he had to do a better job of selling
his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under my opponent's plan, he gets no tax cut,'' Bush said of
Bechac. ``He gets no tax cut. I ask you, I ask Americans, to look
at the facts in these tax plans.''
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, when Bush arrived in Miami, he introduced yet
another family that he said would benefit under his plan.
</P>
<P>
   With these events and examples, which Gore's aides derided as
selective and misleading, Bush was clearly trying to recover from
his earlier missteps. At the same time, he sought to make light of
those fumbles, which threw him off the education message that he
had said he would be focusing on this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I didn't explain what I was trying to explain very
well,'' he told reporters aboard his campaign plane, a smile on his
face. Asked if he wanted to take another crack at it, he said,
laughing, ``Yeah, exactly, let me start over.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was also signaling that he was not going to back away from
his sweeping proposal to cut taxes by about $1.3 trillion over the
next decade, which many polls suggest may not be in line with the
priorities of most American voters. Gore has proposed a more
limited tax cut of $500 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush was confronting head on two of the principal obstacles
to selling a big tax cut: Many voters' belief that politicians are
not really going to deliver the goods, or that the total savings
would ultimately be pocket change.
</P>
<P>
   Bechac, a man with a history of activism in the Republican party
in Louisiana, said during the airport event that $1,600 ``will go a
long way for us each year.''
</P>
<P>
   But while ush presented Bechac as a typical example, Gore's
aides said he was an aberrant one. ``They finally found one working
family that does better under the Bush plan than the Gore plan,''
said Ron Klain, a senior adviser to Gore. ``While Governor Bush can
play games with particular examples, he can't change the truth that
most working families do better under Gore than Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign quickly released an analysis that it said
showed that if the Bechacs did some of the things that trigger tax
breaks under the vice president's plan _ like paying for day care
for their children, taking a standard deduction instead of
itemizing, putting money in certain kinds of savings accounts _
they might get an even bigger tax cut than the $1,600.. The Bush
campaign said that none of that was relevant to the Bechac family.
Bush's plan cuts the income tax rate for all taxpayers in all
income brackets, including the wealthiest Americans, who would get
by far the most money back in simple dollar terms.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan does not cut rates, but rather provides breaks for
people who incur expenses for particular needs, like child care,
elderly care and school tuition, or who are saving money for
retirement or college. Those reductions in taxes apply, for the
most part, only to families with combined incomes of less than
$100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said Thursday that because Gore's plan has an
income ceiling and pivots on certain conditions, about 50 percent
of taxpayers _ about 50 million people _ would not see their taxes
lowered.
</P>
<P>
   Klain said that only about 30 million taxpayers would not
qualify for Gore's tax cuts, and that most of those people have
family incomes exceeding $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The back-and-forth over taxes suggested how large the issue
could loom in this election. Gore and his aides have asserted that
Bush's tax cut would gobble up surpluses and endanger prosperity.
Bush and his aides have levied the same accusation about Gore's
spending proposals, which are larger than Bush's.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Texas governor had previously employed the strategy of
showcasing middle-class people and the kind of tax breaks they
would get during his battle in the Republican primary against Sen.
John McCain of Arizona. Like Gore, McCain complained that Bush was
lavishing too much of his tax cut on wealthy Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that Bush would continue throughout the coming weeks
to introduce families like the Bechacs. But he had not, at the
start of the week, intended to do that Thursday, when he was also
unveiling a new education proposal.
</P>
<P>
   It calls for $437 million more in federal financing over five
years for historically black colleges and universities and an an
additional $166 million for similar institutions that have
primarily served Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Even before his plane had left Austin, Texas, Thursday morning,
Bush was talking about tax cuts, saying that his belief in them was
impervious to polls. ``That should speak volumes about me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the New Orleans airport, Bechac, 33, held his 4-year-old
daughter, Meredith, while Margaret Bechac, 29, held the couple's
1-year-old, Camille.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Bechac, Bush said, ``Somebody asked me today on the
plane, `You know, the polls said people, hard-working people, don't
want tax relief.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I mentioned that,'' Bush added, ``and I think your
reaction was to laugh out loud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
