<SLUG> BC-DOG-DAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT SUMMER'S END
</HEADLINE>
  Rent a movie! Watch a movie being made! Be in a movie! 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's late August, most kids aren't back in school yet, the
parade of visiting friends and relatives from out of town is
continuing and the thought of listening to ``It's a Small World''
one more time is more than you can stand.
</P>
<P>
   We feel your pain.
</P>
<P>
   For these dog days of summer, there are still some entertainment
options out there. Some are new, some may be new to you, others may
be ones you've forgotten about. Here are a few attractions _ and
distractions _ to consider during summer's last steamy gasp.
</P>
<P>
   _Going through ``Survivor'' withdrawal already? Bored with
``Millionaire,'' ``Big Brother'' and reruns of reruns? The
offerings on the tube may be passe, but don't forget we live in TV
Land. Most networks' fall premieres are weeks away but those new
episodes are in production right now. Audiences Unlimited in
Universal City (818-753-3470) and Audience Associates on Melrose
Avenue near Gardner (323-653-4105) have free tickets to tapings of
popular returning comedies such as ``Everybody Loves Raymond,''
``The Drew Carey Show,'' ``Just Shoot Me'' and ``3rd Rock From the
Sun'' and newcomers like ``The Geena Davis Show'' and ``Bette.''
They also offer game shows such as ``The Price Is Right,''
``Hollywood Squares'' and ``Wheel of Fortune'' or late-night fare
like ``Politically Incorrect With Bill Maher'' and ``The Dennis
Miller Show'' _ the HBO one, not the ABC Monday Night Football one.
</P>
<P>
   To get into ``The Tonight Show With Jay Leno,'' line up at NBC
Studios, 3000 W. Alameda Blvd. in Burbank, by 4 p.m. the day of the
telecast. (If there's a big star or a hot musical guest on the
bill, plan on getting there early in the morning.) Tickets are
given on a first-come, first-served basis, with a limit of two
tickets per person. For more information, call (818) 840-4444 and
ask for audience services.
</P>
<P>
   There are standard rules to most television tapings: Leave those
cameras, video recorders and cellular phones behind, along with
children under the show's minimum age. And keep in mind most shows
hand out more tickets than the studio has seats to assure a full
house, so arrive early unless you want to feel like the loser in
musical chairs.
</P>
<P>
   _Universal Studios Hollywood still has its famous features
including ``Jurassic Park: The Ride,'' ``Back to the Future'' and
the year-old ``Terminator 2: 3D,'' but it also has a few
attractions added this summer, among them the ``Rugrats Magic
Adventure!'' stage show; The Klumps, a special effects production
built around Eddie Murphy's ``Nutty Professor'' sequel; and the
``Chicken Run'' maze featuring clay animation models from the
movie. And now through Sept. 5, Universal is displaying all 27 real
Emmys (without winners' names, of course) that will be handed out
Sept. 10 at the 52nd annual Primetime Emmy Awards. It is the first
ever public display of the TV academy's winged statuettes.
Universal's Studio Tour tram ride recently underwent a face-lift,
with the addition of on-board monitors that show movie scenes
filmed in the backlot locations pointed out by the guide. For more
information, call (818) 622-3801.
</P>
<P>
   _Universal isn't the only studio offering tours. It's just the
one with the biggest advertising budget. Paramount (5555 Melrose
Ave., Hollywood), Warner Bros. (Hollywood Way and Olive Avenue,
Burbank) and NBC welcome the public for an inside look at the
movie- and TV-making process. Prices vary: $7 for a 70-minute
stroll around NBC (818-840-4444) with peeks at the ``Days of Our
Lives'' and ``Tonight Show'' sets; Paramount (323-956-1777) gives
escorted two-hour walks for $15 per person; and Warner Bros.
(818-954-1744) charges $32 for two hours, part on foot and part in
golf carts. Most tours set a minimum age, and tickets are given out
on a first-come, first-served basis except for groups' advance
reservations. There's no guarantee you'll see real movie stars or
get into busy soundstages; these are working lots and their first
priority is making movies and TV shows, not catering to the
curious. But tours offer a great opportunity to see how movie magic
is made.
</P>
<P>
   _If you've seen all the summer's best movies _ or should we say
``both''? _ head to the neighborhood video store and walk right
past that new releases section. Instead try the foreign language
aisle for an Akira Kurosawa epic such as ``The Seven Samurai'' or
his melodramatic ``Rashomon,'' Mexican director Alfonso Arau's
bittersweet ``Like Water for Chocolate'' or wonderful comedies such
as Jacques Tati's ``Mon Oncle'' or ``Mr. Hulot's Holiday.''
Although Italy's ``Life Is Beautiful'' is available dubbed in
English, it's only right to see it in the language that helped
writer-director Roberto Benigni earn his best-actor Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a total aversion to subtitles, there are many gems
hidden in the mainstream comedy, drama and action aisles. Consider
a few hot stars of the moment and look for one of their early
films, such as Tom Cruise's ``Risky Business,'' Minnie Driver's
``Circle of Friends'' or Martin Sheen's ``Badlands.'' There are
videos out there for nearly everyone. Ever appear in a community
theater production and laugh at yourself in the process? See
Christopher Guest's mockumentary ``Waiting for Guffman.'' Going
through home construction or remodeling hell and need
commiseration? Watch Cary Grant and Myrna Loy in the 1948 comedy
``Mr. Blandings Builds His Dream House.''
</P>
<P>
   _Dodgers got you blue? Try an alternative sport once in a while,
such as polo at Will Rogers State Park, home field of the Will
Rogers Polo Club. There are games every weekend through Sept. 24 in
Pacific Palisades, with matches running 2-5 p.m. Saturdays and 10
a.m.-1 p.m. Sundays. And it's a bargain among L.A. sports _ just $3
per carload. Call (310) 573-5000 for schedule details, or (310)
454-8212 for other information.
</P>
<P>
   _It's hard to beat a beautiful summer evening at the Hollywood
Bowl, unless it's a beautiful summer day there watching a rehearsal
for free. The Los Angeles Philharmonic practices mainly Tuesday and
Thursday mornings, and there's a jazz soundcheck usually on
Wednesday afternoons. On Friday mornings you usually can catch the
Hollywood Bowl Orchestra rehearsing, more often than not with the
weekend headliner. While you're there, stop in at the museum to see
photos, videos and interactive displays of the landmark's history.
There is no admission charge for daytime rehearsals or the museum.
Parking on the grounds is free until 4:30 p.m. For more information
call (323) 850-2000.
</P>
<P>
   _Of course, in Los Angeles entertainment is not merely a
spectator sport. In addition to tapings tickets, Audience
Associates (323-653-4105) also can get fans in front of the camera
through its aptly named Big Crowds business. You may be needed to
play a screaming groupie in a concert scene, a football fanatic or
a loyal party member cheering a candidate's speech. These are
unpaid extra positions but Cash Oshman of Audience Associates/Big
Crowds say they sometimes lead to paid assignments and membership
in the Screen Extras Guild. Oshman said groups of 50 or more can
use one of his assignments to raise money for their favorite
non-profit organization while working on a real film or TV shoot.
No promises that you won't be left on the cutting room floor, or
even that your face will be caught on camera, but at least you can
say you worked on a movie. That could be a good bragging point when
it comes time to rehash what you did on your summer vacation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
