<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-REALTOR-PROFILE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECLIMBING THE REAL ESTATE CHARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 27) 
 By KATE MURPHY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ His hair is thinner, though still tinted red, and his
posture is slightly bent, but certainly not bowed. Harold Farb, the
flamboyant Houston apartment developer who gained national
attention for his excesses before he fell hard in the 1980s, is
back.
</P>
<P>
   Farb, 77, has spent the last 15 years selling office buildings
and trimming his apartment portfolio by 90 percent, in order to pay
off $455 million in debts from real estate deals that went bad when
the price of oil hit the skids and took the Texas economy with it.
He has also put behind him such costly indulgences as a supper
club, where he headlined as a lounge singer, and a glossy magazine
catering to Texas' rich and self-absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Farb is putting the finishing touches on a $25 million,
372-unit apartment complex in the suburban Kingwood section of
Houston _ his first project in a decade and a half. This time
around, Farb said, he will keep his business on a firmer
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Like many developers who lost their French-cuffed shirts when
the Texas real estate market crashed in 1983, Farb has become more
cautious. Gone are the days when he built 1,000-unit apartment
buildings and office towers as if he were playing with Legos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned I'm not invincible,'' said Farb, who before the
real estate collapse made the Forbes 400 list of the wealthiest
people in America with an estimated net worth of more than $200
million. Yet, he added, ``I'm not running scared, either.''
</P>
<P>
   A cinema buff who has financed five albums of himself singing
show tunes, Farb has named his latest venture the Paramount, in
honor of the studio that made many of the films he enjoyed watching
as a boy in his father's two Houston movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The new apartment complex was built using the same builders,
landscapers, finance officers, accountants and lawyers whom Farb
hired in his heyday. But now, he said, they are contract workers,
not employees. Farb was also more selective about the location.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kingwood is zoned,'' he said, ``so I know there isn't going to
be a lot of junk going up around the property, like pawn shops and
liquor stores,'' which would diminish its value.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Inselmann, president of the American Metro/Study Corp., a
Houston company that compiles and analyzes housing data, said Farb
is emblematic of most developers in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took the Texas market getting sucked down the drain before
we started seeing a more studied and restrained approach to
building,'' Inselmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, at the slightest hint that the Houston market was
going soft, new building permits started to tumble. They are
projected to fall to 4,000 this year from 20,000 in 1998, Inselmann
said. And the decline has come despite surging oil prices that have
buoyed the local economy and forecasts that 60,000 jobs, mostly
unrelated to energy, would be created this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone would prefer to be safe than sorry,'' he said, adding
that Farb's new development could cash in on local builders'
overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   Farb said he couldn't be happier about his timing or about his
return to the apartment business. He is looking to develop more
residential properties in Houston as well as in Atlanta.
``Apartments are what I know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is staying away from office buildings and ventures like the
supper club and magazine that Farb said got him into ``trouble with
a capital T.'' (He is not as shy about marriage, despite his highly
publicized divorce in 1983 from his second wife, the socialite
Carolyn Farb, which cost him a reported $20 million, though he
disputes that figure. He has married four times since then,
including three separate ceremonies with his current wife, Diane
Lokey.)
</P>
<P>
   In focusing on apartments, he is playing to his strength. After
all, Harold Farb apartments were once the hip places to live in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were young and single and upwardly mobile in the 1970s,
you lived in a Farb,'' said Liz Dantone, a project manager for the
Friendswood Development Co., a former Exxon subsidiary that has
built several residential communities around Houston. ``He's still
a master at branding.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike apartments owned by an anonymous real estate investment
trust, Farb's have always been identified with their owner, with
his name and logo (showing him holding a rolled-up blueprint)
plastered all over the place. Comment cards addressed ``Dear Farb''
are in every manager's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landlords have such a negative image,'' Farb said. ``I've
always let my tenants know who I am and how they can get in touch
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, Farb personally answers complaints written on those
cards. He also visits his four properties daily, making
inspections, talking with maintenance men and striking up
conversations with tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone back to my roots of providing people with a nice
place to live at an affordable price,'' Farb said. Even while
charging cut rates _ his credo is ``rent $10 below market'' _ he
pays extra for amenities like resort-quality pool furniture and
high-end exercise equipment. ``I want it to be a poor man's country
club,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pool at the Paramount will be graced with a 7-foot-high
statue of Minerva, the Roman goddess of wisdom, that he salvaged
from his defunct marble-and-mirrored supper club, the Carlyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paid $50,000 for that statue and now I have a place to put
it,'' he said, pleased with his thrift. ``My daddy told me to
always eat hot dogs, even if you can afford steak,'' Farb said.
That way, a reversal of fortune will not seem as severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still eat hot dogs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
