u w BC-CONGRESS-TAXES-NYT &LR;      08-24 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS PRESS AHEAD WITH BILL TO REPEAL ESTATE TAX 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Shrugging off a veto threat, Republican
congressional leaders revved up a red tractor Thursday and
dispatched a Montana cattle rancher to ride from Capitol Hill to
the White House to deliver their latest tax-cutting proposal _ a
bill to repeal the federal estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill would phase out the tax over the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   But there is as much political symbolism in the bill's passage
as in the tractor ride through busy Washington streets.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's proponents say it will help those families who pass
down their farms and small businesses from one generation to the
next.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton is expected to veto the legislation in the
next few days on the ground that it will benefit mostly the rich,
not farmers and owners of small businesses. The estate tax is
levied on about 2 percent of all estates _ usually those worth more
than $675,000, but provisions of the tax code lift the threshold to
$1.3 million for family-owned farms and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say they prefer smaller, more focused tax cuts that
preserve more of the budget surplus for other proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people learn about the dangerous exploding nature of
this tax plan, the less they like it,'' said Jake Siewert, a White
House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown over tax cuts comes just as the presidential and
congressional campaigns kick into high gear, giving Democrats and
Republicans a classic issue they can take to voters to underscore
their differences. ``It draws the contrast between: `What do you do
with the surplus?' '' said Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va. ``Republicans want
to give the surplus back and Democrats want to spend it. Since we
can't agree, it goes to paying down the debt.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, who spent
the day discussing his overall tax-cutting plan, supports repeal of
the estate tax. His Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore,
prefers a narrower retooling of exemptions to benefit farmers and
small-business owners.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at a farmers market in South Carolina, House
Speaker Dennis Hastert appealed to Clinton to ``listen to the
farmers and small businesses of our country'' and not veto the
repeal of the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``This unfair tax is so steep that sometimes the deceased
owner's children must break up a farm or sell a business just to
cover the tax,'' said Hastert, R-Ill. ``Your children should not
have to sell what you worked your whole lives to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the ranking Democrat on the
House Ways and Means Committee, said Democrats empathize with
farmers and would like to offer them a tax break. But the tax break
should not be geared toward the rich, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican leaders aren't really interested in getting
anything enacted that benefits the family farmer or small-business
owner,'' Rangel said. ``All they want is an excuse to hold more
political stunts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert spearheaded a strategy this year that chopped up a
larger Republican tax cut package, which Clinton vetoed last year,
into smaller chunks. The estate tax bill is one of them. That
approach has made it more difficult for Democrats to oppose the tax
cuts, which are popular with voters, and it has allowed Republicans
to fend off accusations that they dominate a do-nothing Congress.
</P>
<P>
   To override a veto, a two-thirds majority is needed in the House
and the Senate. But the bill is not expected to pull that many
votes in the Senate, and perhaps not in the House, either.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Clinton vetoed another Republican tax cut proposal,
one aimed at married couples. Republicans are expected to try to
override that veto as well.
</P>
<P>
   If the estate tax bill is also vetoed, Republican leaders could
hold votes to override the two vetoes soon after Labor Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
