<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1477 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-AD-880(2TAKES)-N     08-24 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-AD-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the backlash.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   West also said Gore should be careful in how he attacks. ``Gore
has the risk of coming across as an attack dog just because people
seem to like him a little less personally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has to be especially careful about advertisements that
attack Clinton because _ as the Republican Party found in the 1998
congressional campaign _ attempts to revisit the Lewinsky scandal
and others that have roiled the White House can backfire.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Bush campaign does, the Republican Party intends to
run tough commercials against Gore. ``We will have ads that raise
questions about Al Gore's credibility and integrity,'' said
Clifford D. May, the party's communications director, ``because
there are plenty of questions to be raised.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party commercial, which was never broadcast,
suggests that Gore, in saying Clinton has not uttered an untruth,
was not acknowledging Clinton's misstatements about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky. But the advertisement was based
on an interview in which Lisa Myers, a correspondent for NBC News,
asked Gore about an attack he made on Oliver North, who was then
running for Senate from Virginia. The exchange about North was
edited out of the advertisement, which had the tag line, ``The tag
line: ``Think Al Gore will say anything?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he objected to the commercial because ``it had nothing
to do with the affairs of the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   While the advertisement was pulled, clips of it were broadcast
on national television, including ABC News and NBC News programs,
as parts of stories about the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But even William Daley, the chairman of the Gore campaign, said
he did not think the Republicans were behind a plot to get free
publicity for the advertisement _ while making Bush look virtuous
by objecting to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a little Machiavellian,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
