<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1480 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DEECEE-MUSEUMS-3TAKES     08-24 1688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-MUSEUMS-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS RUNS   THROUGH MORE   THAN CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The 3rd take is a 250-word information box.) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This town tends to generate hot air of one kind or
another year round, and the weather can get spectacularly toasty,
even in a coolish summer like this one. Luckily, the city
compensates with acres on acres of air-conditioned museum space,
and a lot of very good art to fill it.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the big museums aren't necessarily the main
attractions. The National Gallery of Art is focused on an Art
Nouveau blockbuster to open in the fall. The much-traveled Norman
Rockwell survey is at the Corcoran but will be heading to New York.
So, after you have seen the smart, laconic Ed Ruscha retrospective
at the Hirshhorn, you would do well to check out a few local art
paths less traveled by.
</P>
<P>
   My vote for most far-out show of the moment goes to ``Amazons in
the Drawing Room: The Art of Romaine Brooks'' at the National
Museum of Women in the Arts. The museum itself, two blocks from the
White House, is a trip, architecturally speaking. It was built in
1908 as a Masonic temple and later did active duty as an X-rated
movie theater. Its outstanding architectural feature is a soccer
field-size atrium with oddly disposed galleries running off it on
different levels. This unorthodox layout is actually well suited to
the art and life of Romaine Brooks (1874-1970), an expatriate
American painter who in a series of memorable portraits of women
succeeded in establishing a lesbian visual presence in
early-20th-century art.
</P>
<P>
   Born Beatrice Romaine Goddard in Rome, Brooks was a daughter of
wealthy Americans. She had a dreadful childhood. Her father
deserted the family soon after she was born. Her unstable mother
alternated between sadistically punishing and ignoring the
children. (There was another daughter as well as a boy, St. Mar,
who died insane.) The artist worked for years on an
autobiographical account of her youth. She titled it ``No Pleasant
Memories.''
</P>
<P>
   She lived mostly in New York until 1896, when she went to Italy
to study art. On the island of Capri, she found a resort favored by
upper-class Europeans and Americans, with an extensive gay circle.
One of its members was John Ellingham Brooks, to whom she was
briefly married. She also met Somerset Maugham and Charles Lang
Freer, founder of the Freer Gallery of Art here. Freer may have
introduced her to the art of James McNeill Whistler, whose somber
palette she emulated.
</P>
<P>
   When her mother died in 1902, Brooks became rich and
independent. She settled in Paris, where she was an integral part
of the city's artistic haute monde. Her career flourished. Her
first one-person show was at the renowned Durand-Ruel Gallery and
was made up almost entirely of paintings of women.
</P>
<P>
   In 1910 she had a fling with the Italian poet and politician
Gabriele D'Annunzio. The romance was brief, but they remained soul
mates, and his proto-fascist ideology had a lasting effect on her
thinking. (She painted a portrait of him as a kind of martyred Mr.
Sensitive; it's in the show.) They were also rivals for the
affections of the dancer Ida Rubinstein, a star of the Ballets
Russes. Brooks won the contest. Rubinstein became her lover and the
subject of a series of sensually zany portraits.
</P>
<P>
   In one morbidly erotic, Symbolist-tinged piece, Rubinstein
floats nude and dead pale on an Art Nouveau swirl of white paint
that suggests a bird's wing or a shroud. In another, she's dressed
in the uniform of a Red Cross nurse, with a starchy wimple. For
this patriotic image, painted during World War I, Brooks was
awarded the French Legion of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   The affair with Rubinstein was soon over. In 1915 Brooks met the
Paris-based American writer Natalie Barney, with whom she began a
nearly lifelong relationship. Possibly as a result of Barney's
forthright Sapphist views, Brooks' portrait style became more
realistic and more intent on shaping a new concept of femininity.
</P>
<P>
   She tried various approaches. In a brash 1924 portrait of the
British aristocrat Una Troubridge, the companion of the novelist
Radclyffe Hall, her subject wears mannish clothes and a monocle
that contrast with her girlish bob and lipstick. Troubridge's prize
Dachshunds are by her side. Brooks, who had mixed feelings about
Hall, later hinted that she had meant the portrait as a joke, but
whatever her intentions, it's a groundbreaking, gender-bending
image.
</P>
<P>
   She could also be tender, as she is in ``Peter, a Young English
Girl,'' a portrait of the androgynous-looking British artist Hannah
Gluckstein, who went by the name of Peyter Gluck. Her well-known
1920 portrait of Barney, titled ``The Amazon,'' is done mostly in
soft gray-lavenders and furlike textures against a background of
falling snow.
</P>
<P>
   The two women came to lead a strangely insular existence in a
rapidly changing Europe. They were ahead of their time in their
attitudes about sexuality and gender. But as the art historian
Whitney Chadwick suggests in the exhibition catalog, they
subscribed to an ideal of a social, sexual and even racial elite
that led them to view Nazism favorably.
</P>
<P>
   Their insularity is also reflected in Brooks' art. Although she
lived in Paris during an epoch of exhilarating aesthetic
experimentation, she stayed, as many other artists did, with the
figurative style of an earlier day, branching out only slightly
with a series of automatist drawings in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is no artist like her. In a 1923 self-portrait,
she presents herself, at age 49, with close-cropped hair, wearing a
top hat and a black hacking jacket, the scarlet Legion of Honor
ribbon in its lapel. Her pallor is intense: she has applied white
paint as if it were stage makeup, and her eyes are half-hidden by
the hat brim. Alert, glittering, self-possessed, they're barely
visible in reproductions, so it's a bit startling to see them when
faced with the picture itself in the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks has carefully set up that reaction. One of the points of
the picture is that she's watching you before you get close enough
to look at her. She's not passively inviting your approach; she's
deciding whether you're worth bothering with. Chances are, you're
not, at least not if you're approaching with the conventional
notions of what male and female mean. Whereas in the Troubridge
portrait, Brooks is still separating out signs of gender (pants,
lipstick), here she has created a new kind of being,
uncategorizable and unitary, in total control of her own identity.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks also took control of her artistic legacy. Although she
lived most of her life in Europe, she left nearly two dozen of her
best portraits to the Smithsonian's American Art Museum, formerly
the National Museum of American Art, and they make up about half of
this show, which was organized by Joe Lucchesi, professor of art
and art history at St. Mary's College of Maryland. Whatever one's
quarrels with Brooks' unconscionable politics, her outspoken
lesbian presence in don't-ask-don't-tell Washington is a stroke of
poetic justice.
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR M. SACKLER GALLERY
</P>
<P>
   The intersection of politics and art is also an underlying theme
of three very different modest-size shows at the Freer and Sackler
galleries, adjoining museums that house the Smithsonian's
collection of Asian art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heroic Past: The Persian `Book of Kings,''' organized by
Massumeh Farhad at the Sackler, is a visual essay on the
quasi-mystical role that kingship played in the culture of Iran.
Among the earliest items here is a superbly wrought fourth-century
Sasanian silver-and-gilt plate with an image of a ruler, probably
Shapur II, in the muscle-flexing pose of cosmic hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Then, leaping centuries, come manuscript paintings of scenes
from the ``Shahnama,'' or ``Book of Kings,'' the Persian royal
epic. The poem is endless _ some 50,000 verses _ but every newcomer
to the throne felt compelled to commission a freshly illustrated
version of it, as a symbolic seal of legitimacy for his reign.
</P>
<P>
   This is nice for the viewer, because the vivid narratives
frequently brought out the best in court artists. A page from one
of the greatest of such books, produced in Tabriz around 1525,
shows the heroic warrior Rustam being saved from a lion by his
horse, Rakhsh. In this case, the perilous encounter is turned into
an exotic ballet with a Leon Bakst set, gilt and baby blue, with a
lion as sweet as a kitten.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier painting of a battle scene, the sprightly and the
grisly are balanced. The Persian king Kay Khusraw may have the
benign face of an overgrown baby, but he is slicing off an enemy's
arm with his sword. Beneath him lies the corpse of a soldier, cut
in half and gushing blood. He's been placed in the margin of the
page, outside the picture itself, as if to push the realities of
war into the reader's sphere.
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely the intention of the work in a second Sackler
exhibition, ``A Well-Watched War: Images From the Russo-Japanese
Front, 1904-1905.'' The Japanese woodblock prints gathered here by
James Ulak, along with paintings by British magazine illustrators,
were designed as journalistic reports on the struggle between Japan
and Russia for the possession of Port Arthur, a warm-water harbor
in northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures are pure propaganda and sometimes almost as
fanciful as the ``Shahnama'' paintings: military leaders striking
valiant poses, enemies cut (or in this case blown) to bits.
Accuracy is blocked out by wishful thinking. One woodblock print
shows a Russian ship being attacked and destroyed by Japanese
torpedoes; but apparently the face-off never happened, or happened
differently; the ship was seen later intact and afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Many photographs of the war were taken, but the medium was still
regarded with suspicion, as either too realistic for public
consumption or not realistic enough. Instead publishers and
audiences alike favored cushioning, interpretive hand-wrought
images that turned war into an operatic spectacle.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   FREER GALLERY OF ART
</P>
<P>
   At the Freer, political realities run, however subtly, through
``Brushing the Past: Later Chinese Calligraphy From the Gift of
Robert Hatfield Ellsworth,'' a showcase of 20 works of late-18th-
through 20th-century calligraphy selected from the 260 given to the
museum by Ellsworth, a well-known New York collector, dealer and
historian.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Joseph Chang, the show is a modern history in a
nutshell of this most revered of Chinese art forms. Stylistic
currents are clearly traced. So is an organic, discursive pattern
of lineal descent, with artists taking cues from their immediate
forebears but also rummaging through the past, rejecting and
rediscovering and always extending the thread of tradition.
</P>
<P>
   This process was rocky in the later 20th century, particularly
during the Cultural Revolution, with its manic swings between
denunciation and approval of traditional forms. But resilient
voices persevered, and the Freer show, which comes with an
excellent catalog, is like an intimate party of mature, quietly
forceful personalities who seem young beyond their years.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM OF AFRICAN ART
</P>
<P>
   Parties are also in progress at the National Museum of African
Art. The livelier of the two is titled ``A Concrete Vision: Oshogbo
Art in the 1960's'' and highlights the work of a group of artists
in the town of Oshogbo, a Yoruba commercial and religious center in
southwestern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Oshogbo was celebrated for its theater and dance
troupes. Then local visual artists joined forces with a few
European residents, notably Ulli and Georgina Beier, to explore
styles that combined African and modern Western elements. (Jacob
Lawrence lived and taught here in 1962.)
</P>
<P>
   Much of the work is figurative and refers to Yoruba myths and
beliefs, appropriate for a town that is a pilgrimage site for
Oshun, the goddess of waters. Of the 11 artists in the show,
organized by David Binkley, the best known is the man who calls
himself Twins Seven-Seven. (He was the only surviving child of
seven sets of twins.) He came to Oshogbo as a dancer, met the
artists and started to draw. He eventually settled on a format of
paint and ink on plywood with which he depicts spirits and
fantastic animals in intricate nets of color and line. He remains
active in the town today in art, music and local politics.
</P>
<P>
   A second exhibition, ``Trans-Atlantic Dialogue: Contemporary Art
in and Out of Africa,'' organized by Michael Harris, also deals
with cultural interaction, specifically between African-American
artists who have spent time in Africa and African-born artists who
have come to the West.
</P>
<P>
   There seem to be affinities between the decorative paintings of
Skunder Boghossian from Ethiopia and those of the American artist
Jeff Donaldson, and between the puzzlelike geometries of certain
pieces by John Biggers and those of the African-born Moyo Okediji.
But the most dynamic pairing by far is in a compact room of
paintings by Jean-Michel Basquiat and the Nigerian-born Ouattara.
They met in Paris in the 1980s, by which time Basquiat had been to
Africa, and were friends in New York. Seen side by side, their
works generate a mutual energy that goes beyond a mere sharing of
motifs.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the show feels tepid by comparison. This has to do
partly with the art, but the disjointed installation, which
straggles over two large rooms, has to take some of the blame. This
museum consistently exhibits contemporary work, which is great, but
it is still in search of an effective way to present it. The
pressure-cooker effect of the self-contained Basquiat-Ouattara
hanging may suggest a solution.
</P>
<P>
   TEXTILE MUSEUM
</P>
<P>
   For a last look at the intricacies of cultural sharing, head
away from the Mall for the Textile Museum, on a leafy street near
Dupont Circle. Founded 75 years ago by the businessman and
collector George Hewitt Myers, it occupies a pair of brick town
houses that retain signs of their domestic origins. The museum has
some 16,000 textiles and carpets, a substantial research library
and permanent and temporary exhibition spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Its current show, ``Tribal Traditions: Village and Nomadic
Weaving of Anatolia,'' which opens Aug. 25, is drawn mostly from
the permanent collection and adds up to a rich little primer in the
flat-weave rug styles that have emerged around four cities in
Anatolia _ Bergama, Konya, Malatya and Erzurum _ in the last two
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the designs, assertive and brightly colored, originated
in nomadic cultures and were meant to be clearly readable from a
distance. When nomads were forced to settle in one place, to
facilitate taxation by the Turkish government, rug patterns came to
be associated with particular villages. Some of these connections
are intact, though with more and more work done for commercial
markets, certain motifs have floated free for general use.
</P>
<P>
   Sara J. Wolf, the curator, manages to throw a light on all
aspects of this complex dynamic. In one inspired installation, six
prayer rugs seem suspended in mid-air: they represent the
distinctive and almost unvarying rug style perpetuated by a single
village group. By contrast, a rug completed just last year by a
village weaver named Hediye Ustun, in a region around the city of
Konya, is based on a motif borrowed from a neighboring village and
turned into a different, virtuosic variations-on-a-theme design.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to get absorbed in this fascinating material, but be
sure to see ``Considering Excellence: Great Works From the Textile
Museum's Collections,'' the small show upstairs, through Nov. 5. It
includes a gorgeous tapestry-weave Peruvian poncho, a gold-threaded
Indian shawl and a sheer gauze-weave summer coat of yellow silk
from China. Perhaps most fetching of all, though, is an Iranian
prayer cloth from the 18th or 19th century: all white,
handkerchief-size, embroidered with minute silk flowers, it looks
as light and cool as a perfect summer day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   CAPITAL TREASURES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Details about visiting the Washington museums in Holland
Cotter's art review:
</P>
<P>
   FREER GALLERY OF ART, Smithsonian Institution, Jefferson Drive
at 12th Street S.W., (202) 357-2700. ``Brushing the Past: Later
Chinese Calligraphy From the Gift of Robert Hatfield Ellsworth,''
through Jan. 2, 2001. Hours: Daily, 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL MUSEUM OF AFRICAN ART, Smithsonian Institution, 950
Independence Avenue SW, (202) 357-2700. ``A Concrete Vision:
Oshogbo Art in the 1960s,'' through Oct. 22, and ``Trans-Atlantic
Dialogue: Contemporary Art In and Out of Africa,'' through Sept. 3.
Hours: Daily, 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL MUSEUM OF WOMEN IN THE ARTS, 1250 New York Avenue NW,
(202) 783-5000. ``Amazons in the Drawing Room: The Art of Romaine
Brooks,'' through Sept. 24. Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 10
a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 5 p.m. Admission: $3; $2 for
students and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR M. SACKLER GALLERY, Smithsonian Institution, 1050
