<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1483 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-POLAND-OUTLOOK-1STLD-     08-24 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-OUTLOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-700(2TAKES)-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLES TRADE COMMUNIST-ERA WORRIES FOR THE PROBLEMS OF PROSPERITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 2nd Take to clarify grafs 2, 4 and 12; graf 12, bgng `Even
so, Polish...')  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT16 was sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIALA RAWSKA, Poland _ In the past 10 years, Urszula Malinowska
and her husband have transformed their lives, turning a tiny farm
and orchard into a wood-processing factory that employs 35 people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after failed farming ventures, they bought a used
American machine to cut timber, a Wood-Mizer, and created a
business of making timber into lumber for the construction boom
that has transformed this area near Mszczonow, some 35 miles
southwest of Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they have $500,000 a year in revenue, produce their own
power and heat from the waste wood and sawdust and are planning a
more modern plant to work on more expensive woods for higher-profit
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Ursula Malinowska, at 48, could be a billboard for the new
market economy that has taken hold in Poland, the largest and most
successful country in central Europe in this transformation. She is
the active boss of one of 2 million small and medium-sized private
enterprises in a country of 42 million people.
</P>
<P>
   But like many Poles, she is not especially happy with the way
things are, and she is likely to vote for the reformed communists
of the Democratic Left Alliance in the parliamentary elections
expected next spring, dumping the more conservative Solidarity
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   To Malinowska, the changes have come with mixed blessings. ``The
great satisfaction is that we've built something new, and without
permission from anyone,'' she said, as her workers took large pine
logs and began to turn them into lumber.
</P>
<P>
   ``As owners, there is a great feeling of responsibility, and we
work from 6 to 6,'' she added. ``But there is a sense of achieving
one's goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said, `` There are lots of problems.'' Small
businesses do not get much help from the state; the tax laws are
complicated and contradictory; there is an effective state monopoly
on the supply of lumber, given the difficulties of trade with
Russia, Ukraine and Belarus; and with Poland still outside the
European Union and membership probably four years away, she feels
that ``our Western partners take advantage of our weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The sourness is widely felt by Poles, whose rapid progress is
nonetheless falling behind their own expectations. While young
people are full of confidence, many Poles still have a deep fear of
being marginalized, of falling behind, both as individuals and as a
nation striving to join the rest of Europe as an equal, said Jacek
Kucharczyk, deputy director of the Institute of Public Affairs, an
independent Polish research organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poland is a country doing better than it feels _ it's doing
better than it thinks it's doing,'' Kucharczyk said. Surveys show
that more than 50 percent of Poles think theirs is a better country
than it was 10 years ago, and only 30 percent disagree, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But change is still frightening to those who are over 40. And
the current Solidarity government's biggest undertakings _ to
decentralize and streamline health care, education, pensions and
provincial administration _ have caused enormous anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   With more to lose, there is also a growing concern about
personal safety and crime, and a feeling that the police are not
keeping up with the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Even the prospect of joining the European Union has raised
considerable fear _ not just among the many farmers who fear
European competition, but also among those who worry that Poland
will give up some of its precious identity, after centuries of
struggle to shape and preserve it.
</P>
<P>
   What is the Polish nightmare? ``To be the Mexico of Germany:
proud, important, too big to fail but deeply unbalanced next to a
neighbor that is too rich and too big,'' one European ambassador
said.
</P>
<P>
   Poles are more pessimistic these days, said Halina Binczak,
economics editor of the respected daily newspaper Rzeczpospolita.
In polls, only about 8 percent of Poles think the reforms are going
well. Five years ago, she said, 60 percent of households had
trouble making ends meet. Today, it's some 40 percent. ``Yet five
years ago, people were more optimistic than now,'' she said. ``Our
aspirations are rising faster than our possibilities. People are
less satisfied with what they have, even though they have more.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Yet the signs of new prosperity are everywhere in Poland. In
Mszczonow, a small town of some 6,000, there are scores of new
shops _ bakeries, groceries, hardware stores, hairdressers _ that
did not exist 10 years ago. The town has streetlights now, put up
four years ago. Farmers are growing a special kind of apple that
feeds good, tart concentrate into blended juices. There is one
large industrial park, Europark, already in operation, with another
soon to open.
</P>
<P>
   On this main route near Warsaw, there are hundreds of trucks
from all over Europe and the former Soviet Union. Servicing them
are large gas stations, looking like modern palaces, with cafes and
small grocery stores attached. (And in a sign of the increased
traffic, numerous prostitutes line up at intervals along the
roadway.)
</P>
<P>
   The roads are crammed with new cars. Poles have bought more than
500,000 new cars each year for the last four years, reflecting the
prosperity and an explosion in consumer credit, but posing dangers
for more inflation, already at 11.6 percent in July, a two-year
high.
</P>
<P>
   And they use their cars to shop at huge supermarket complexes in
the suburbs, where Ikea rubs up against KFC and McDonald's and
Carrefour and Geant superstores.
</P>
<P>
   But for all this wealth, the infrastructure lags far behind.
Warsaw traffic is bad, and there is barely a subway system, with
only one short route. The telephone system, reluctantly changing
from a state monopoly, is inefficient, compared with the Czech
Republic's or even Romania's, and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   There are few highways, and the two-lane roads _ effectively
three-lane, with expensive cars zooming around buses, trucks and
the little old Polski Fiats that can't go much over 60 miles an
hour _ are often seamed and channeled, with heavy traffic punishing
roadbeds built for less booming times.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Road fatalities are consequently a major issue, with large green
and black signs displaying the number of dead and injured at
particularly bad spots. A billboard campaign shows wrecked cars
with large, one-word slogans: ``Autoagresja'' and
``Autodestrukcja.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Like its roads, Poland's politics are messy and crowded, still
driven by the ideologies of the battle, 20 years ago, against
communism: Reformed communists versus the Solidarity coalition,
which itself is a very broad group of some 30 parties. Although its
roots are in a trade union, Solidarity is center-right in politics.
Some of the best-known intellectuals associated with Solidarity,
like the historian and former Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek,
formed the Freedom Union, further to the right. And then there are
farmers' parties and some Roman Catholic parties that veer toward
ultranationalism, exemplified byRadio Marya, a radio station
supported by a vocal minority of Poland's priests.
</P>
<P>
   But as everywhere in the former Soviet-bloc countries, patronage
and corruption still play too large a role in politics, with
parties and ministers often getting kickbacks from businesses and
lobbyists for contracts or favors.
</P>
<P>
   The Polish government itself asked the World Bank to look into
corruption last year, and was told that the main problem is graft
among legislators, ministers and judges.
</P>
<P>
   Economically, everyone agrees, Poland's biggest problem is the
deficit in the current trade account _ with imports, fed by new
prosperity and credit, growing more rapidly than exports. The gap
is now almost 8 percent of gross domestic product, said Binczak of
Rzeczpospolita. The government has to do more, she said, to support
exporters with credits and tax breaks or risk a currency crisis and
a reduction in foreign capital flows that finance the budget
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Polish exports have at least quadrupled in the past
decade, with more than 70 percent of exports going to countries of
the European Union and only 10 percent now going to Russia, said
Witold M. Orlowski of the Independent Center for Economic Studies.
The economy has grown an average of about 5 percent a year over the
past several years, and the government estimates $12 billion this
year in foreign direct investment, after last year's record $8
billion _ a serious vote of confidence by hardheaded foreign
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats and analysts are concerned that the minority
Solidarity government, facing likely elections in the spring over
the 2001 budget, will increase the budget deficit too much with
populist spending, to try to fight slowly rising unemployment,
estimated at 13.5 percent this year. But Binczak and others believe
that the fundamentals of economic policy are set, in part by the
markets and the pressure to join the European Union, and that the
politicians will not want to disrupt them too badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming sense is that the Poles are going in the
right direction,'' a Western ambassador said. ``This is no longer a
grimy little East European country trying to keep its head above
water, but a country taking its place in Europe.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Agriculture remains the biggest structural challenge to a
modernizing Poland _ and to its entry into the European Union. Some
25 percent of Poland's work force lives in the poorer countryside,
many of them on small farms. But of the country's 2.1 million
farms, only half sell significant amounts to the market. The other
half are subsistence farmers whom no one wants to suddenly move
into the cities. The European Union will help, but wants to contain
the size of the subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, protected by socialism, are the ones most concerned by
the new Poland, which they see as a land of high taxes, falling
farm prices and rising prices for fertilizer, fuel, seeds and
machinery.
</P>
<P>
   In Skorzec, a tiny village about four miles south of
Ciechanowiec, two farmers, Czeslaw Bojar, 59, and his neighbor,
Kazimierz Murowski, 64, stopped work to chat and complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I bought my first tractor, under communism, it cost 27
pigs,'' Murowski said. ``Today, it costs 100 pigs.'' He stopped to
scratch. ``It's not that we liked communism, but life was better
for us then.''
</P>
<P>
   Bojar has six sons and worries that his farm, roughly 25 acres,
will not be big enough for all of them and that some will find
themselves in the cities, unemployed. As for the European Union, he
said: ``I can't know the future, and people disagree. But when we
join the E.U., it will be like a bulldozer and break down all the
walls, and then who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Murowski said everything was comparative. ``I remember how it
was after the war, with everything destroyed and nothing to eat,''
he said. ``Well, it's better to be poor in peace than rich in
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the farmers have cars, heat, telephones and television, a
big change from 15 years ago, they admit, and their neighbors, with
a new roof and siding on their house, are off working in Belgium,
earning good money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were a communist country, they said we'll be in heaven
one day, and now they say it'll be even nicer that we're not
communists anymore,'' Bojar said. ``And we, we still hope it will
be better than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Karol Szyndzielorz, a former journalist turned businessman, put
it simply. ``Poles cannot believe it, but it's true,'' he said.
``Poland is now a lucky country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
