<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1486 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NIGERIA-HNS &LR;      08-24 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;    Clinton to laud Nigeria for transition from ``pariah to
partner'' &HT;    By MICHAEL HEDGES
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After snubbing Nigeria's military dictatorship two
years ago, President Clinton will visit the sprawling African
nation Saturday and laud its dramatic transition from ``pariah to
partner'' when he meets with its democratically elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visit to Nigeria signals our strong support for the most
important democratic transition in Africa since the collapse of
apartheid,'' national security adviser Sandy Berger said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It underscores opportunities opened by Nigeria's shift from
pariah to partner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While there is promise in the three-year shift to democracy by
Africa's most populous nation led by President Olusegun Obasanjo,
there are also reasons for caution, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nigeria is still in really deep political trouble,'' said
Larry Diamond, a senior analyst at Stanford University's Hoover
Institution. ``I'm not certain the Clinton administration realizes
how deep that trouble is.''
</P>
<P>
   The theme of Clinton's trip is democracy, but pragmatic foreign
policy, economic and business items also appear on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian official hope the visit will signal relief from the
country's crushing international debt of about $32 billion. While
U.S. officials said agreements on debt relief are not expected
during the visit, Clinton will likely increase U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
   The president will also offer help on combating AIDS and other
infectious diseases, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton will push Nigeria, a member of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Counties, to increase its oil output from the 2
million barrels a day it now produces.
</P>
<P>
   At least 11 trade and business agreements will be signed during
the visit, according to U.S. officials. That includes deals with
private companies for everything from sugar to telecommunications,
as well as some government-to-government accords.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit coincides with the arrival this week of the
first of 400 U.S. troops who will train Nigerian soldiers as
peace-keepers in neighboring Sierra Leone. But Berger said Clinton
is not expected to meet with any of the U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   After two days in Nigeria, Clinton will journey to Tanzania at
the request of former South Africa President Nelson Mandela. There,
Clinton and Mandela hope to witness the signing of an initial
agreement aimed at ending a war between Hutus and Tutsis in
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago, Clinton leapfrogged Nigeria while on a tour
of Africa, a snub designed to express displeasure at the brutal
dictatorship of Gen. Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, four of the nations visited by Clinton _ Ethiopia,
Eritrea, Rwanda and Uganda _ have embroiled eastern and central
Africa in war, while Nigeria has stunned some analysts by taking
the first shaky steps toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials vigorously made the case this week that Nigeria
represents ``our best chance to save western Africa,'' as one State
Department expert said.
</P>
<P>
   Berger and others have credited President Obasanjo with trying
hard to restore order, bind ethnic wounds and heal the country's
critical-list economy.
</P>
<P>
   But Diamond, the Hoover Institution analyst, noted that Clinton,
for security reasons, is only going to Abuja, a sterile capital in
the center of the country, far away from the turmoil in its south,
north and east.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it say when the Secret Service feels that the
president shouldn't even leave Abuja?'' Diamond said.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria's transformation began in early 1998 when Abacha
mysteriously died, paving the way for a return to power of
Obasanjo, who had briefly ruled in the 1970s but had later been
thrown in prison during one of the country's intermittent military
coups.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha ``stole more than $5 billion from the state, protected
drug cartels and crime syndicates, arrested his adversaries,
including Obasanjo, and murdered others and turned Nigeria into the
poorest oil-rich country in the world,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   The political and social upheaval unleashed during the
dictatorship has not diminished in the past two years of Obasanjo's
government, even by the most optimistic assessments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obasanjo is sitting on an extremely chaotic situation,'' said
Diamond. ``The country is being pulled apart by religious groups in
the north and by people in the south who feel they should have more
control over the oil in that region.''
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International and other groups have criticized Obasanjo
for human rights abuses. Earlier this year he ordered a town of
insurgents destroyed in the oil-rich Niger Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption remains widespread in both the private sector and
among government officials, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
   Religious differences threaten to split the country.
Christianity is practiced in much of Nigeria. But in eight northern
states which are predominantly Muslim, Shariah, or fundamentalist
Islamic law, has been declared the legal code by local governors.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this ``years of neglect of the people, poor governance
and corruption and you don't fix that overnight,'' said Jerry
Kepes, a director at the Petroleum Finance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Kepes said a failure to distribute Nigeria's profits from its
immense oil reserves _ the country sells 2 million barrels of
high-grade crude oil a day _ have led to horrific episodes where
locals puncture pipelines to steal gasoline, leading to fireballs
that have incinerated hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   But, Berger insisited, ``for the first time in 20 years the
people of Nigeria are aggressively addressing these challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are enormous for Africa, and high for the rest of the
world, Berger said. With an estimated 120 million people and
billions of barrels of oil, Nigeria could become a stabilizing
influence on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   But the nation remains crushingly poor, with a per capita income
measured in hundreds of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a make or break transition,'' Berger said, ``not just
for Nigeria but for Africa. If Nigeria succeeds, this could help
lift the whole region to prosperity and peace. If it fails it could
swamp the whole region in turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamond agreed with the stakes. ``We badly need Nigeria to join
South Africa as an anchor of stability in Africa,'' he said. ``I'm
just not sure the Clinton administration appreciates the depths of
the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxxx
</P>
