<HEADER>
A1487 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-LIFE-ORIGINS-NYT &LR;      08-24 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LIFE-ORIGINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEMICAL EXPERIMENT SUPPORTS MAVERICK THEORY ON ORIGINS OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)   By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A maverick theory about the origin of life has received striking
support from an experiment that mimicked the violent interactions
of deep seated rock and common gases during the Hadean epoch, the
days when the earth had just formed as a planet.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found to their surprise that even in these hellish
conditions they created a chemical known as pyruvate, which is
crucial for the metabolism of living cells.
</P>
<P>
   Pyruvate is the fuel for a universal energy-producing process
known as the citric acid cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The work, by George D. Cody and his colleagues at the Carnegie
Institution of Washington's Geophysical Laboratory, is being
reported Friday in the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   The new finding does not explain how or where life began but it
supports a theory that proposes a new way of looking at this long
intractable problem. The theory, proposed by a German patent
attorney, Guenther Waechtershaeuser of Munich, holds that the
origin of life should be sought by looking for a metabolism, some
repeated cycle of chemical change, that may have taken place on the
early earth and that may then have built itself up into more
complex molecules and organisms.
</P>
<P>
   This contrasts with the conventional approach, which is to take
familiar parts of today's cells, like nucleic acids, and try to
figure out the conditions in which they may have formed
spontaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Waechtershaeuser dismisses the latter approach as the broth
theory because even when a researcher has found conditions under
which the individual chemical ingredients of life may have been
formed, it is hard to explain why they should then assemble
themselves into living cells.
</P>
<P>
   He calls his own proposal the iron sulfur world theory because
he believes that the metallic surfaces, particularly those of the
common mineral iron sulfide, would have been promising
facilitators, or catalysts, of the chemical reactions that created
the precursor chemicals of living cells.
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual for amateurs, even qualified chemists like
Waechtershaeuser, to contribute to the specialized worlds of modern
science. And his ideas, being only theoretical, did not arouse much
enthusiasm until 1997 when he showed that an iron sulfur surface
could promote the conversion of carbon monoxide to a two-carbon
chemical important in biochemistry of living cells.
</P>
<P>
   To biochemists, his finding had particular resonance because at
the center of many enzymes are iron and sulfur atoms that transfer
electrons in ways vital the cell's energy requirements. The idea
that living cells result from some primitive chemical cycle that
got going on an iron sulfur surface is to them not so alien.
</P>
<P>
   Cody and his colleagues decided to use a special high pressure
apparatus to explore how Waechtershaeuser's proposed system might
work in locations like the volcanic vents in the deep ocean. This
kind of chemistry is a dangerous pursuit since at high pressures
water becomes a violent acid and carbon monoxide eats through
steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set out to explore the ability of minerals to catalyze
reactions that would be important in a primitive metabolic sense,''
Cody said. Putting iron sulfur, a source of carbon monoxide, into
their reaction tube, ``we came across an unanticipated result,'' he
said, referring to the large amount of pyruvate formed. The tube
also contained a hydrogen sulfidelike chemical to mimic the
hydrogen sulfide produced by volcanoes.
</P>
<P>
   Pyruvate consists of three carbon atoms linked together, and is
an obvious building block from which sugars and the other
carbon-based molecules of life can be constructed.
</P>
<P>
   Waechtershaeuser believes the origin of life lies in a process
known as autocatalysis, the emergence of some natural chemical
process, like the pyruvate-producing one, in which the products
help the reaction go faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evolution is better and better autocatalysis,'' he said in a
phone interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If one of these autocatalytic processes started to generate the
class of fatty chemicals known as lipids, these might form a bubble
around the system, and the first cell would be generated. The cell
would have left the surface on which it was generated. And later,
it would have developed, as a byproduct, the elaborate
information-storage system embodied in today's DNA molecules.
</P>
<P>
   Michael W.W. Adams, a biochemist at the University of Georgia
who studies early life, said Waechtershaeuser had developed a very
reasonable and testable hypothesis for the origin of organic
material relevant to life. ``It makes so much sense to have metal
catalysts involved at the dawn of life, especially metal sulfides,
because these are essential to most energy conserving processes,''
Adams said. ``I very much think he is on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written commentary on Cody's report Waechtershaeuser said
that, with the creation of pyruvate, all of the eight sequential
steps needed to make peptides from carbon monoxide had now been
shown to be chemically possible. Peptides are short chains of amino
acids, the components of the protein molecules that are the
workhorses of the living cell.
</P>
<P>
   The new results ``greatly strengthen the hope that it may one
day be possible to understand and reconstruct the beginnings of
life on Earth,'' he wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
