<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Lasting Problems Seen for Mitsubishi in Japan
</P>
<P>
   Despite the public humiliation that it had concealed customer
complaints about defects for more than two decades, Mitsubishi
Motors, Japan's fourth-largest carmaker, is not likely to suffer a
significant loss in sales or damage to its brand image in Japan,
analysts say. For one, analysts said, both Fuji Heavy Industries,
the maker of Subaru, and Daihatu Motors were forced to recall cars
in the late 1990s, with little effect on sales. And despite the
deception in Mitsubishi's case, there was no evidence that the
defects had caused any fatal or otherwise serious accidents,
further limiting potential public reaction to the recall of 620,000
cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Medical `Buyers' Clubs' Crop Up
</P>
<P>
   Some new companies are beginning to offer below-market prices on
prescription drugs and services like doctor, dental and eye care
and medical tests. Like buyers' discount clubs such as Costco, the
companies attract people looking for a better price.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo Announces New Console
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo offered the opening gambit in what is certain to become
a bitter battle of new technology and cost-cutting in the home
video game industry. It announced both a new home console based on
an IBM PowerPC chip and a new version of its handheld Gameboy
system. Neither system is scheduled to arrive in the United States
market before next year. The American depository receipts of
Nintendo fell 25 cents, to $21.75.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Up on Good Corporate News
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose as Wall Street cheered upbeat corporate news and
signs that interest rate increases may be coming to an end. The Dow
Jones industrial average rose 38.09 points, to 11,182.74, while the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index edged up 2.34 points, to
1,508.31. The Nasdaq composite index gained 42.27 points, or 1.05
percent, to 4,053.28.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Fund Manager Charged in Fraud
</P>
<P>
   Michael Berger, who managed the Manhattan Investment Fund, was
charged with defrauding 300 people who invested about $575 million
while losing about $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Rejects Broader Tire Recall
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor officials lashed out at plaintiffs' lawyers suing the
automaker and Bridgestone/Firestone, accusing them of endangering
public safety by calling for a broader recall of tires and of
distributing Ford documents out of context to journalists. ``A
broader recall is wrong,'' said Helen Petrauskas, a Ford executive.
``It's wrong because many good tires will be delivered and used to
replace good tires _ and people who have tires which should be
replaced will have to stand in line and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   No Rush Seen on Fuel Economy
</P>
<P>
   A government report to be released as early as today reaches few
conclusions about the effects of tightening federal fuel-economy
regulations for cars, making it virtually certain that the rules
will not be changed by Congress before the end of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
