<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN PRESIDENT-ELECT WARMLY GREETED IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM WEINER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vicente Fox, the next president of Mexico _ a land
he envisions far closer to the United States, with borders no more
than lines on a map _ started laying out his vision to the present
and future leaders of the United States Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who takes office on Dec. 1, met with President Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore; he is to meet Gov. George W. Bush in Texas
on Friday. At the White House, the State Department and the vice
president's residence, he was congratulated for winning the fairest
election in Mexican history on July 2, defeating the ruling party
and ending its seven decades of often authoritarian and corrupt
government.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the Mexican leader's victory ``a truly historic
affirmation of genuine democracy.'' A measure of good will _ rare
among many of the two men's predecessors _ appeared to flow between
Clinton and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're walking on clouds,'' Clinton told Fox during their
private meeting, according to aides. The thorniest issues dividing
the two nations _ drugs, migration, trade disputes _ were
discussed, but not debated, aides on both sides said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's vision of a future in which people and their possessions
can move far more freely across the 2,000-mile border is not shared
by official Washington, or by either presidential contender. That
frontier has become a battle front, as the United States fights its
long and often unsuccessful war against drug traffickers and
illegal immigrants heading north.
</P>
<P>
   Gore found the idea of open borders ``clearly problematic,''
said his national security adviser, Leon Fuerth, and Bush repeated
Thursday that he thought ``we ought to enforce our borders.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said much the same thing. ``Obviously, we have borders
and we have laws that apply to them and we have to apply them, and
so do the Mexicans,'' he said. ``But I think over the long run, our
countries will become more interdependent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has become the United States' second-largest business
partner (Canada is No. 1, Japan No. 3). Trade between the two
nations is expected to exceed $240 billion this year. And Fox
believes that a growing economic integration will inexorably erode
the border _ and the development gap _ in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, he says, can develop in the next two or three decades
from a client trading with a superpower into a full-fledged
partner, if it can answer questions like those he posed today:
``How can we narrow the gap on income on both sides of the border?
How can we in the long term equal the levels of development between
our countries so that we become real friends, real partners and
real neighbors?''
</P>
<P>
   If the economy of Mexico grows stronger, if living standards and
wages rise _ per-capita income is barely $5,000 a year, and 40
million Mexicans are poor by any standard _ then, Fox argues, there
will be far less incentive for illegal immigration, which has risen
to perhaps 150,000 cases a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we build up the opportunities in Mexico so that our
kids, 12- , 14-year-olds, don't have to leave home, don't have to
move to the United States looking for opportunities?'' he asked.
Not by beefing up border patrols, he said, but building up Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton expressed concern that the 1994 North
American Free Trade Agreement, or NAFTA, which reduced crossborder
trade barriers dividing the United States, Mexico and Canada, had
not raised real wages in Mexico. And they said that Gore had asked
Fox's help in building support for free trade among environmental
and labor groups, which have often viewed NAFTA as a malevolent
force.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Fox spent an hour talking, Fuerth said, touching on
trade, the environment, human rights, democracy and two interwoven
problems confronting Mexico: The international traffic that fills
the enormous demand for drugs in the United States, and the
official corruption that smooths the flow of the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Fox pledged to ``attack corruption profoundly within
government,'' beginning with Mexico's police and security agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1502 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     08-24 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAPLER JUST SAYS YES TO DRUG-TESTING PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the record, Gabe Kapler swears he's not a steroid freak.
Never used them. Never will.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case you were wondering.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time the Texas Rangers' outfielder has
addressed that question and it likely won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never look myself in the mirror again knowing that I
cheated,'' Kapler said by phone Wednesday from the visiting
clubhouse at Yankee Stadium. ``I think they're unsafe. I think
they're unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult thing for a lot of people to talk about.
It's not difficult for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Good, because precious few others feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's dirty little secret is sneaking out of the closet
faster than a Mark McGwire blast can leave the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Is America's pastime overrun with steroid use? Is that the real
reason for the power explosion in the game? Is it the players who
are juiced, not the ball, as columnist Rick Reilly charged in
``Sports Illustrated'' last week?
</P>
<P>
   If it is, then baseball, the only major sport with no drug
testing program in place to protect its participants, has no one to
blame but itself. It is the single-most shameful omission in
professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers strength coach Mike Arndt told Reilly that ``15 to 22
percent'' of major-leaguers are on ``illegal substances,'' meaning
performance-enhancing steroids. Rockies strength coach Brad Andress
told the ``Denver Post'' it's even higher, maybe 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take Arndt's estimate and work with that. If 20 percent
are steroid users, that means one out of every five players is
doing it. Translation: The average team _ which eliminates the
Rangers, because they're not even average this year _ has five
players in the clubhouse using illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But let's get down to specifics. OK, Mike, how many Rangers
players are using steroids? Five? Six? More?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say I don't believe anyone on our roster is
using,'' said Arndt, in his first year as the Rangers' strength
coach. ``I can say that based on the relationship I've had with
these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some guys who are very adamant in their feelings
about it as far as anti-use. They're very vocal.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those is Kapler. But fate works in strange ways. At about
the same time that Reilly's column was raising eyebrows, ESPN was
showing a photo of Kapler on the cover of a fitness magazine during
its Sunday night telecast from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, he's not called ``Abs'' for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Here's the Rangers' strength coach talking about steroids
running rampant in baseball and here's Kapler's rippling physique
for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   Deduction? Well, you know where this goes and so does Kapler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe strongly that it stems from jealousy of some sort,''
Kapler said. ``It's also a compliment. It's someone saying, `you
can't look that way naturally.' It's frustrating, though, because
they don't understand the time and effort you put into this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Arndt, who came up with his percentages from talking to
strength coaches from other teams, to compile a list of Rangers
players he believes absolutely don't use steroids, and Kapler would
be right at the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the most vocal against it,'' Arndt said. ``Gabe
doesn't even like to drink coffee because he feels it hurts his
overall performance. He's very much against steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just don't know the work that Gabe puts in to have that
physique. It comes from a lot of hard work and good genetics.''
</P>
<P>
   Supplements? Sure, Kapler has tried more than a few. He's a big
believer in multivitamins. He has tried creatine, a supplement
that's usually blended like milkshake, that's supposed to build
muscle mass and stamina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to look at something that's found naturally in food,''
Kapler said. ``If they can condense and put it in a powder or
tablet form, I might try it.''
</P>
<P>
   It has never crossed general manager Doug Melvin's mind that
Kapler might be a steroid user. Not once.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an assumption that if you have a good physique, you
must be doing that,'' Melvin said. ``That's pretty unfair. Kapler's
been that way for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be more concerned if, in a short period of time, you saw
someone suddenly bulk up. If Darwin Cubillan comes to camp next
spring at 225, we might be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubillan is the slender right-hander who came to Texas in the
Esteban Loaiza trade with Toronto. On a good day, after three
double cheeseburgers, he might weigh 165 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that the Rangers haven't had players who used
steroids. There have been clubhouse whispers about this player or
that over the years. This guy's using. That guy has suddenly bulked
up and it's affecting his play.
</P>
<P>
   You could probably name them yourself. But it's all just rumor
and suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think Mike's assessment of the percentages is
way too high,'' Kapler said ``I know of just one (user) for sure.
The other ones, I could guess, but I don't even want to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do that to me. They think I'm obviously a user when I'm
not. I'm not going to make the same mistake and do that to other
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler would love to see baseball develop a comprehensive
testing program, to end the questions once and for all, as well as
provide more education on the subject for players.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, you should level the playing field and
everything should be tested for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd just like to make sure there's a level field of play
between the pitchers and the hitters,'' said Melvin, who also
believes baseball needs a testing program. ``Let the union do it if
that's what it takes, and they can reprimand the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's nothing to hide, then what's the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Union mouthpiece Gene Orza told Riley there is no evidence that
steroids ``alter the playing field'' or provide a health and safety
hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that Orza is (a) blind; (b) deaf; and (c) somehow
doesn't consider the increased risk of testicular cancer, heart
disease, stroke, depression and raging mood swings a health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guarantee you that Old-Timers' games are not going to be
``near'' as much fun,'' Riley zinged.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take it one step further. It's going to be difficult to
play Old-Timers' games at all if no one lives long enough to be an
old-timer. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
