<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KANSAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACK DEPTH NO CONTROVERSY AT KANSAS STATE
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-QBS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas State quarterback Jonathan Beasley started 11 football
games last season, of which the Wildcats won 10. In another, he
came off the bench to trigger a comeback victory against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   His reward, heading into Saturday's opening game of his senior
season, has been a spot in the Wildcats' lineup with a clear view
of the rearview mirror. In it, he sees redshirt freshman Ell
Roberson gaining favor each day in the eyes of coach Bill Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it heat, but there is competition,'' Beasley
said. ``It makes me better and it makes Ell Roberson better. He's
pushing me and I'm pushing him. If one goes down, the other is
capable of coming in and taking over the job.''
</P>
<P>
   To many Wildcats' fans, the lingering question is whether
Roberson _ already dubbed the team's ``quarterback of the future''
by Snyder _ can commandeer the starting job on his own merits
during a season that will begin with national championship dreams.
Kansas State, ranked eighth in The Associated Press' preseason
poll, plays Iowa at 1 p.m. Saturday in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley has earned the starting nod, Snyder said, based on
superior knowledge of the Wildcats' offense. But his status is not
etched in stone because coaches are intrigued with the progress of
Roberson, a former standout at Baytown Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gap has closed,'' Snyder said. ``We'll go into the season
with Jonathan Beasley as our No. 1 quarterback. But the position
will remain competitive, provided the quarterbacks make it so.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder is quick to praise Beasley, who completed only 44.3
percent of his passes last season, for his leadership skills and
veteran savvy. A team captain, Beasley is 10-1 as the Wildcats'
starting quarterback. But he lacks the mobility and arm strength of
Roberson, who has been compared favorably to Michael Bishop, the
Wildcats' starter in 1997-98 and winner of the 1998 Davey O'Brien
National Quarterback Award.
</P>
<P>
   As a high school senior, Roberson passed for 1,678 yards and
rushed for 1,123. He accounted for 28 touchdowns (10 passing, 18
rushing). He's been impressive enough in drills that Snyder plans
to play Roberson in nonconference games, like the one against Iowa,
to gauge his progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be remiss if we didn't find opportunities to play Ell and
make him the quarterback of the future. How soon that future comes,
I can't say,'' Snyder said. ``My thoughts are that he's an
extremely fine football player and a fine athlete. But he needs to
make an extremely firm commitment to make the progress he needs to
be the No. 1 quarterback at Kansas State. How soon he can
accomplish that, I can't tell you. It depends on that firm
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   From his perspective, Roberson said he is committed to expanding
his knowledge of the Wildcats' offense and mastering the
``intangibles'' that Snyder identified as the reason to keep
Beasley in the lineup. Beasely, who played much of last season
while nursing a sore shoulder, said he is not prepared to surrender
the starting job without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley said the offense ``didn't execute at times'' last
season, most notably during a 41-15 loss to Nebraska in which
Kansas State quarterbacks completed only 8 of 32 passes. Beasley
was 3 of 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still room for me to improve,'' said Beasley, who
passed for 1,805 yards and accounted for 22 touchdowns (14 passing,
8 rushing) last season. ``I need to make sure I always get us into
the right checks, so we can execute better. And the completion
percentage is something I need to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said he is optimistic Beasley will be more productive
this season because outsiders do not understand the physical
ailments he faced last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went a long time last year without disclosing the fact that
Jonathan's arm had been injured,'' said Snyder, whose policy is not
to discuss the status of injured players. ``He's far healthier now
than at any time last season. That will add to his assets.''
</P>
<P>
   But does he have enough assets to hold off Roberson?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jonathan Beasley is a better athlete than people realize,''
Snyder said. ``But he's been sandwiched between Michael Bishop and
Ell Roberson. Jonathan is not as athletic as those two. That's
accurate. But he's not a washout, in that respect. He's got a good
arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jonathan epitomizes what college athletics are all about, what
teamwork is all about. He's always willing to sacrifice for the
good of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The lingering question is whether Beasley will eventually be
asked to sacrifice his starting job for the good of the Wildcats.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
