<HEADLINE>
FOR NOW, EXPERTS DISCOUNT RADIATION PERIL FROM SUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use with RUSSIA-SUBMARINE, already moved)  
 By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two nuclear reactors in the sunken Russian submarine Kursk
should pose no immediate risk to the surrounding environment and
only a moderate risk in the coming decades, naval experts and
environmentalists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not high on the list to worry about,'' said Thomas B.
Cochran, director of the nuclear program for the environmental
group Natural Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   Measurements indicate no radiation leaks from the submarine at
present, the Norwegian Radiation Protection Authority said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the radioactive elements within the Kursk remain of
concern, because the submarine lies in relatively shallow water _
350 feet down _ in a rich fishing area. Should radiation leaks
occur, currents could spread the radioactivity over a large portion
of the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental group Greenpeace urged on Tuesday that the
Kursk be pulled off the ocean bottom if possible. ``It's not a
matter of if radiation will be released from the Kursk,'' said
William Peden of Greenpeace. ``It's a matter of when. We hope the
international community will spare no effort, spare no expense in
making the Kursk safe.''
</P>
<P>
   With apparently no immediate radiation danger, there is time to
first survey the Kursk before deciding what to do, said Thomas
Nilsen, a researcher with the Norwegian environmental group
Bellona. ``We could actually make things worse than it already is
by shaking the submarine,'' he said. ``We say we are in a hurry,
but we should not rush.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Kursk is so badly damaged that it might break apart
during a salvage effort, other options should be considered, such
as cutting out the reactor compartment or entombing the submarine,
Peden said.
</P>
<P>
   Including the Kursk, seven nuclear-powered submarines _ two
American, five Russian _ have sunk. So far, none appears to have
leaked nuclear fuel into the surrounding water. Submarine reactors
are sealed within thick steel walls, and most experts believe
decades or longer will pass before seawater corrodes through the
walls.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Navy has sent remote-controlled underwater vehicles to
the wreckage of the submarine Thresher, which went down in 1963 off
Cape Cod, and the Scorpion, which sank in 1968 off the Azores,
about six times each, collecting samples of sediment, water, and
plant or animal life around the wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done surveys at those sites and have seen very, very
little radioactivity coming out from the ships,'' said Jonathan
Kiell, a spokesman for the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The sediment within a few feet of the submarines contain
slightly raised levels of radioactivity, believed to come from the
reactor's coolant, and not the fuel. The coolant becomes slightly
radioactive through the normal operation of a nuclear reactor.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our surveys have shown there is no environmental threat
created from those two submarines,'' Kiell said.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian monitoring of the Russian submarine Komsomolets, which
sank in waters a mile deep in the North Atlantic, 300 miles off the
coast of Norway, also shows slight radiation leaks from the cooling
fluid, not the reactor core.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the dangerous radioactive elements in spent nuclear fuel
decay away within weeks and months. The two of most concern _
strontium-90 and cesium-137 _ have half-lives of about 30 years,
and will take about 300 years to decay away.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Nikitin, an environmental activist who was once an
engineer on a Russian nuclear submarine, has been the most
alarmist, saying that the Kursk will start leaking radiation within
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my mind, I'm sure about it, that in a month or two months,
the submarine will no longer be hermetically sealed,'' Nikitin said
in an interview through a translator.
</P>
<P>
   But even Nikitin said the radiation would come from the cooling
water, not the reactor fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be a major hazard,'' said Cochran of the
Natural Resources Defense Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
