u a BC-LEE-BAIL-900(2TAKES)-     08-24 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-BAIL-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.M.)  
 IN BLOW TO GOVERNMENT CASE, LOS ALAMOS SCIENTIST IS GRANTED BAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Saying the government case against the accused Los
Alamos scientist Wen Ho Lee ``no longer has the requisite clarity
and persuasive character'' needed to keep him in detention before
his trial, a federal judge Thursday ordered his release on bail.
</P>
<P>
   The order is a symbolic but humiliating blow for government
prosecutors, who have had Lee held in jail for more than eight
months under unusually harsh conditions on charges that he had
mishandled the ``crown jewels'' of the country's nuclear weapons
program and posed a grave threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
   Judge James A. Parker of U.S. District Court in Albuquerque,
N.M., said in his order Thursday that Lee would be required to post
$1 million in bail. Lee may remain in prison for a week or so while
the tough conditions the judge outlined, amounting to home
detention, are finalized. In addition, the government could attempt
to halt the order with an appeal and a request for a stay.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision represented a stunning turnaround in this
politically charged trial and was another in a string of recent
developments suggesting that, at least in some respects, the
prosecutors' case appears to be unraveling.
</P>
<P>
   At a bail hearing in December, Parker had agreed with the
government and found that Lee, a former scientist at the Los Alamos
National Laboratory, posed such a threat that he could not be
released under any condition before his trial, which is scheduled
for November.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the assistant U.S. attorney leading the prosecution,
George Stamboulidis, said that if Lee were released and managed to
hand over to a foreign power the secrets he had improperly
downloaded, ``It's of a caliber where hundreds of millions of
people could be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same hearing a senior FBI agent acknowledged that
earlier he had provided inaccurate testimony about Lee's supposed
deceptions on several critical issues, which the judge had cited in
his detention order in December.
</P>
<P>
   Also, two highly respected weapons experts appearing for the
defense contradicted several government witnesses and said that the
data Lee is accused of illegally downloading onto portable computer
tapes would not be of great use to another country and that most of
it had already been made public in scholarly journals and the like.
</P>
<P>
   While the judge did not detail his reasoning in the order,
released late Thursday, he clearly rejected the government's
assertions this time about the threat from Lee. In court last week,
Parker said he would not rule until he had read the full transcript
of the unusually long and detailed three-day bail hearing. But in
his decision Thursday, he wrote that he now felt able to render the
decision before the transcripts had been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're simply delighted,'' said Brian Sun, an attorney for the
family of Lee. ``I wish I could wax on further, but we're just
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's daughter, Alberta, 26, a fervent supporter throughout the
case, was highly emotional. ``I'm just thrilled that he will
finally be at home,'' she said in a telephone interview. ``I can't
wait to see my Dad and hug him.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I think it just means that the government's case is
crumbling.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Holscher, one of Lee's lawyers, said that the terms Parker
described in his order, while tough, were agreeable. The judge
scheduled a hearing for Tuesday to discuss and finalize the
conditions of Lee's release.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are gratified by the court's decision,'' Holscher said.
``Dr. Lee and his family are grateful to the scientists and members
of the community who have supported him. We have always indicated
to the court we would comply with any of its conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The only government response came from Patricia Chavez, a
spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney in Albuquerque. ``The court's
order is being reviewed,'' Chavez said in a written statement.
``The government will be responding in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker listed 12 conditions in a draft order for Lee's release.
In addition to requiring the large bond secured by his own assets
and the assets of family members and friends, they include his
being held in detention at his home in White Rock, near Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   His next door neighbors, Don and Jean Marshall, who also work at
the government lab in Los Alamos, would serve as third-party
custodians.
</P>
<P>
   Lee would be monitored electronically at all times and would
have but a single telephone in his house, with no computers or
other electronic communications devices. Officials would be able
immediately to block any phone calls that appeared to involve
sensitive information. The government would be able to inspect all
his mail, and he would be able to leave his house only with one of
his attorneys to work on his case or to go to a hospital for
emergency medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered that only Lee's wife, Sylvia, would be able to
reside at his home with him. She would be able to leave the house
only after notifying government officials of the time of her
departure, her destination and the purpose of the trip. Law
enforcement officials would have the right to search her on leaving
and re-entering the house.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's two children, his daughter, Alberta, and his son, Chung,
27, would be able to visit only in the daytime and only after
arranging the visits in advance with the government, which would
have the right to have a law enforcement official present in the
house during the stay.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, the terms represented a marked improvement from the
conditions under which Lee has been held since he was arrested and
indicted in December.
</P>
<P>
   He is held in something close to solitary confinement in a
prison in Santa Fe, N.M., had been shackled until recently for his
brief periods in an exercise yard, is shackled when he travels to
the courthouse to work on his case with his lawyers, and can see
his family for one hour a week, and then only with a law
enforcement official close at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government has insisted in several hearings that
Lee was engaged in what amounted to one of the most serious cases
of espionage since the dawn of the nuclear era, he is not actually
charged with spying in his 59-count indictment. He was investigated
for several years on suspicions that he passed secrets on a
sophisticated warhead to the Chinese government, but prosecutors
now say there is no evidence for this and that they will not raise
the matter at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is charged with illegally downloading a vast amount of
nuclear weapons secrets to an unsecure computer at Los Alamos and
then putting the information on 10 computer tapes, seven of which
are missing. Lee has indicated through his lawyers that he
destroyed the seven tapes after he was fired in March 1999, and he
offered to take a lie detector test on this question.
</P>
<P>
   The government has not taken him up on the offer, and
prosecutors have used the question of the tapes' whereabouts as a
critical issue in the three bail hearings that have taken place.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes are still unaccounted for, but new testimony was
provided at the hearing last week that clearly cast the
circumstances of Lee's actions in a far different light. Earlier,
FBI agent Robert Messemer said that Lee had lied to a colleague
whose computer Lee had used to complete the downloading. Last week,
Messemer said that had not been the case.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution has also said that Lee downloaded the
information to enhance his job prospects with several scientific
institutes in foreign countries like Australia, Germany and
Singapore. But last week Messemer said that though letters to those
institutes had been found on Lee's home computer, the government
had no evidence the letters had ever been sent or received.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, several government witnesses had
described the codes and other information Lee downloaded as the
``crown jewels'' of the nuclear weapons program, but several
respected scientists rebutted those assertions, apparently
undermining, at least in Parker's eyes, the need to continue
holding Lee in the kind of conditions reserved for the most
nefarious spies and criminals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
