u i BC-MEXICO-COURT-NYT &LR;      08-24 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-COURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO COURT MAKES HISTORY BY SIDING WITH CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In a ruling that justices described as a judicial
watershed, the Mexican Supreme Court ordered President Ernesto
Zedillo Thursday to turn over to Congress secret banking data
relating to questionable financing of Zedillo's 1994 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was the first in modern history in which the court,
the weak sister in Mexico's system of government, has ruled in a
constitutional dispute between two competing federal powers. The
court's decision to uphold a congressional challenge to
presidential powers marked a clear declaration of independence by
the court from the all-powerful executive branch, which has
dominated the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling in a suit filed by opposition lawmakers last year, the
court found that Congress had every right to demand full disclosure
by Zedillo's government about the dealings of Banco Union, a bank
that oversaw millions of dollars in donations to the president's
1994 campaign even as it was sliding into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Zedillo later intervened in Banco Union's case, turning
its liabilities into public debt and arguing that bank secrecy laws
barred any public accounting.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's ruling, the court gave Zedillo 30 days to turn
over to Congress a series of files from Banco Union. The court's 11
justices endorsed the order unanimously. In a statement hours
later, Zedillo's office pledged to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is a profoundly historic decision,'' Olga
Sanchez Cordero, the justice who presided over the previous
deliberations in the constitutional challenge, said at a news
conference. She said it marked the first time the high court had
refereed a dispute between two branches of the federal government,
and also because it limited bank secrecy laws here by stipulating
that they may not be used to shield potentially illegal
transactions in which taxpayers must pay for the reckless
management of private assets.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mexico's independence from Spain in 1821, its judicial
system has been hobbled by frequent presidential interference, and
three presidents in this century have simply dismissed the entire
high court. One was Zedillo himself, who in his first month in
office dismissed all 26 justices, installing the new 11-member
court.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the justices elected a new chief justice, Genaro
Gongora Pimentel, who has championed initiatives aimed at
increasing the judiciary's power and independence. Under his
influence, the court's powers to broker constitutional challenges
have been growing.
</P>
<P>
   It has ruled in constitutional disputes between two cities,
between cities and states, between states and the federal congress.
But it had never ruled in a dispute pitting the congress against
the presidency, Sanchez said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling comes eight weeks after Zedillo's governing party
suffered its first defeat in seven decades of presidential voting,
and some analysts suggested that the July 2 election of an
opposition candidate, Vicente Fox, had strengthened the court's
willingness to rule against Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Zedillo said he had already ordered the
treasury secretary and the president of the National Banking
Commission to turn over the Banco Union files requested by
Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
