<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-TELECOM-LI-ART     08-24 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-TELECOM-LI-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG'S MASTER TRADER STILL KNOWS WHEN TO SAY NO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In his hometown, Li Ka-shing, the tycoon known here
as Superman, still vaults tall buildings with ease. But in Europe,
where Li is just another mogul, he seems to have lost his
extraordinary powers.
</P>
<P>
   Li earned his nickname among Hong Kong investors by amassing
more wealth and influence than any other local businessman here
ever had. His flagship conglomerate, Hutchison Whampoa, reinforced
that reputation Thursday when it reported earnings of $4 billion in
the first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Hutchison's profit, however, came from a special
one-time gain after the sale of its European mobile phone
operations. The company's encore, an ambitious plan to offer
next-generation cellular services throughout Europe, is in doubt.
Last week, Hutchison unexpectedly gave up a coveted license to
offer advanced mobile services in Germany, saying it was too
costly.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, even as Li and his lieutenants basked in the glow of
rich earnings, they had to explain why the German setback had not
scrambled their plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't for a moment concede that we will be out of
Germany,'' Canning Fok, the group managing director of Hutchison,
said in an interview. ``But we have to be more creative about
getting into that market. To throw money around is not the way to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the great race to carve up Europe's electromagnetic spectrum,
Hutchison Whampoa has emerged as an unpredictable outlier.
Aggressive in bidding for a British license, abrupt in backing out
of Germany, Hutchinson Whampoa, a conglomerate that can trace its
roots to Hong Kong's early colonial days, has left many
telecommunications experts scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Fok insists that there is no mystery. The company could someday
buy back its share of the German license from its partners, Royal
KPN of the Netherlands and NTT DoCoMo of Japan. Even if it never
breaks into Germany, he said, Hutchison will create a valuable
cellular franchise in Britain, where it recently won a license, and
in other countries like Italy, where it is still in the running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each asset is valuable as long as you get it at the right
price,'' Fok declared. ``We haven't lost anything from Germany. I
won't say we've gained, but we haven't lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their qualms, most analysts are willing to give Li the
benefit of the doubt. Hutchison has become one of the most highly
valued companies in Hong Kong on the strength of its chairman's
ability to sniff out good deals and steer clear of bad ones. At a
price for the three partners of more than $7 billion, Hutchison
considered the German mobile license extremely expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hutchison is a company where pragmatism is very much the
watchword,'' said John Tysoe, a telecommunications analyst at the
investment firm WestLB Panmure in London. ``They avoid the mistake
that other telecom operators make, which is to fall in love with
their businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   By ceding Germany, however, other analysts say that Hutchison
has effectively abandoned its dream of building a pan-European
cellular network. Had the company been able to assemble such a
network, it would have been an enormously valuable franchise _
perhaps even more valuable than Orange, the British mobile network
that Hutchison sold last year to Mannesmann of Germany for $14
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason everybody owns Hutchison's stock is because they
expect Li Ka-shing to pull off another massive deal,'' said Anil
Daswani, a Salomon Smith Barney analyst. ``We were all expecting
them to build a European network, and then sell it off or spin off
part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison's recent attack of caution has deflated its
shareholders. The company's stock has declined 6.4 percent since
Aug. 18, when it gave up the German license. The shares fell 1.8
percent on Thursday, to 110.5 Hong Kong dollars, or $14.17, though
the earnings were released after the market closed.
</P>
<P>
   Those earnings show a generally healthy company, even
subtracting the one-time gain of $3.2 billion. Operating earnings
rose 32 percent, to $1.3 billion. Hutchison's container ports,
telecommunications and energy divisions turned in particularly
strong performances, while the results of its property group
remained lackluster.
</P>
<P>
   The company would have reported even greater profit if it had
not taken a $3.8 billion provision against fluctuations in the
value of its 3 percent stake in Vodafone AirTouch, the British
cellular giant. Hutchison picked up the stake when Vodafone
acquired Mannesmann earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say that Li's phenomenal record as a deal maker has
placed unreasonable expectations on the company. Last year, after a
previous round of blockbuster asset sales, Hutchison reported a
profit of $14.25 billion. On that basis, it made the company, whose
annual sales were around $7 billion, the most profitable in the
world, ahead of General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our shareholders have gotten accustomed to big numbers,'' Fok
said. ``We've done it for two years now. But I won't guarantee it
for every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Fok said Hutchison's investors recognize that no one can produce
an endless stream of $14 billion transactions. The trouble is, they
may have become spoiled: Li has pulled off more lucrative deals
since the sale of Orange.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison's earnings do not include the roughly $10 billion
profit it reaped last month when Deutsche Telekom agreed to acquire
Voice-Stream Wireless, a United States cellular company, for $53
billion. Hutchison began investing in Voice-Stream late in 1997. It
paid a total of $1.2 billion for a 23 percent stake, which is now
worth about $12 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If Hutchison's shareholders seem hungry for deals, it is because
they have been trained by Li. Since he took over the company in
1981, he has treated it more as a collection of assets than an
industrial empire. This reflects Li's background _ he came to Hong
Kong from mainland China in the 1940s and traded his way up from
selling plastic flowers to building skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   But it also reflects Hutchison's roots in the mutable world of
Hong Kong. Founded in the 1860s as the Hong Kong and Whampoa Dock
Co., it built dry docks and ship-repair yards on the South China
seacoast when Hong Kong was a young British colony. Over the years,
it cobbled together a disparate array of assets, ranging from
drugstores and supermarkets to container ports.
</P>
<P>
   By 1980, Hutchison was losing money and was ripe for the picking
by Li, the most aggressive of a new generation of Chinese
entrepreneurs eager to supplant the British. Under Li, Hutchison's
reach expanded beyond Hong Kong and into new industries like
telecommunications. But its trading mentality never changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a strategy to dominate the world,'' said Simon
Murray, a British investor who was managing director of the company
in the 1980s and still sits on the board. ``Hutchison always moved
forward on an add-on basis, accumulating assets, building on the
bricks we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the company's telecommunications holdings have
accounted for its multibillion-dollar asset sales, they contribute
only 6 percent of the operating profits. Hutchison has made much
more money selling telephone networks than running them.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its retreat in Germany, Fok said Hutchison was ready to
``go for it'' in bidding for a third-generation license in Italy.
He said the company would also consider investing in such networks
in the United States, when Washington begins auctioning the
airwaves.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Further down the line is China, which is still building its
first generation of mobile phone networks. Hutchison has a $400
million stake in China Unicom, the second-largest telephone
operator nationwide. Fok said, however, that Hutchison would not
expand its presence there until the rules on foreign investment in
the telecommunications industry became clearer.
</P>
<P>
   For all his prudence, Fok seems exuberant when discussing the
prospects for third-generation mobile service. With its emphasis on
data transmission, Fok says this technology has more in common with
the Internet than with traditional cellular service. The German
pullback notwithstanding, he says the scramble for licenses in
Europe is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to seize a dominant
position in a new industry in a single year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like there is a piece of triple-A land available for
development in every major city in the world at the same time,''
Fok said. ``When do you see that? You don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
