<HEADER>
A1515 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-P1FOX-HNS &LR;      08-24 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-P1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 FOX-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Fox finds warm reception for U.S. visit, not ideas &HT;     &HT;    By JOHN C. HENRY
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton praised Mexican President-elect
Vicente Fox's aggressive plan to reshape Mexico's economy Thursday,
but his proposal to open the U.S.-Mexico border got a less than
neighborly response.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have borders and we have laws that apply to them, and we
have to apply them. And so do the Mexicans,'' Clinton said,
standing alongside Fox during a Rose Garden press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's cautious response was echoed by Vice President Al Gore
and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the two leading candidates to
succeed him in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Fox met early Thursday with Gore, who characterized the open
border proposal as ``very problematic in the U.S.,'' said Leon
Fuerth, the vice president's national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is scheduled to meet with the new Mexican leader
(FRIDAY) today in Dallas, was more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's fully explained open borders,'' Bush said.
``As you know, I believe we ought to enforce our borders.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, an undaunted Fox predicted that free movement across the
2,000-mile border will come within a decade when Mexico's standard
of living more closely resembles its northern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on PBS' The NewsHour, Fox said the gap in
salaries and income between the United States and Mexico can be
significantly reduced in 10 years. Then, he said, ``we can open up
the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's forecast came during his first visit to Washington since
winning election last month and ending the Institutional
Revolutionary Party's, or PRI, 71-year grip on power in Mexico.
Fox, a member of the pro-business Action National Party, or PAN,
takes over from President Ernesto Zedillo Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it was ``a great honor'' to meet with Fox, Clinton said
his election was a ``truly historic affirmation of democracy'' in
Mexico. The election ``is an example to people who are friends of
freedom everywhere in the world,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime advocate of closer ties with Mexico's northern
neighbors, Fox told reporters after his meeting with Clinton that
they ``explored solutions'' to the surging number of Mexican
migrants in the United States, currently estimated at about 7
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solutions have to do with economic development, with growing
the Mexican economy at rates of 7 percent, which will give us the
opportunity of building up 1.35 million new jobs,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox wants the United States to allow more legal migrants from
Mexico, and in exchange his government would do more to limit
illegal border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has called for a European Union-style partnership involving
Mexico, Canada and the United States, an economic integration that
Clinton and Gore said is not coming soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, you will see growing interdependence in our
hemisphere, and I think the Canadians will be a part of that, and I
very much hope our friends in Central America and South America and
the Caribbean will be a part of that,'' said Clinton, who leaves
office in January. ``I regret that I won't be around for a lot of
it, but I think it's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   During an hourlong visit to the vice president's official
residence at Washington's Naval Observatory, Gore and Fox discussed
his plan for expanding the Mexican economy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore adviser Fuerth said the vice president at one point in the
conversation said full implementation of Fox's ideas would take 25
to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident President-elect Fox will be a strong partner of
the United States,'' Gore said in a statement released by his
office.
</P>
<P>
   In a rambling news conference, Fox touched on plans to invest
heavily in education and infrastructure, creating an economic
climate favorable to small businesses and ending official
corruption and fighting drugs. He said the Mexican government needs
to do more to draw Mexicans out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the United States' and Canada's obligation _ it is
ours _ to better the quality of life and the living conditions in
Mexico,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
