<SLUG> BC-NY-AIRPORT-DELAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA GUARDIA AIRPORT, WHERE UNLIMITED DEMAND MEETS A LIMITED
INFRASTRUCTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anthony D. Layne, the terminal duty manager at La
Guardia Airport, looked through his van's swishing windshield
wipers and sized up the traffic jam of jumbo jets idling before him
on the taxiway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' he said, in a nice bit of understatement, ``that
things could get a little hairy out here today.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a summer Friday, one of the busiest days at La Guardia.
Yet as summer Fridays go, this one was relatively tame. In the
terminal, flight information screens flashed only a few delays. The
Mimlitsches of Colorado Springs, Frank and Martina and their three
children, were not even particularly upset about the long line at
the American Airlines counter. They made it up to the ticket agent
in nine minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not so bad,'' Mimlitsch said.
</P>
<P>
   While there was no air rage raging inside the airport, no
teeming of crowds familiar to the veteran La Guardia traveler,
there was a whole airport's worth of angry people teeming somewhere
else: out on the tarmac, in their respective planes, which by early
afternoon were lined up 25 deep waiting to take off. This situation
meant that although most airplanes pushed away from the gates on
time that Friday, it was at least an hour, and sometimes more,
before they were airborne.
</P>
<P>
   It also meant that untold numbers of connections to final
destinations were missed, dozens of gates at other airports were
kept idle waiting on those late planes, dozens of other flights at
those airports were delayed as a result and so on around the
country, like a bad echo.
</P>
<P>
   None of this was a result of anything extraordinary, just a few
minor storms hovering near the New York region and a volume of
flights that meant even the slightest delays quickly became big
delays. All this happened on a day of only average traffic: 846
takeoffs and landings on La Guardia's two runways, which on a very
busy day handle 1,200.
</P>
<P>
   But to spend a day at La Guardia, in Queens County, is to
examine through a magnifying glass the factors that have converged
to make this summer the worst for airline delays in history, not
only here but around the country, provoking a debate about whether
the nation's air transportation system is overloaded.
</P>
<P>
   La Guardia is a good case study not necessarily because of the
way it is run or because of its delays, though it does often rank
among the worst in the country for delays and long taxi times. It
is a good example, instead, because it is probably the most extreme
case of what many experts say is a chief cause of air travel
problems: an airport infrastructure that has not kept pace with the
increase in air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of La Guardia, this is because it is hemmed in
between Flushing Bay and the Grand Central Parkway, with little
room to grow. Two oversized photographs hanging in the airport's
Port Authority operations office tell this story better than any
statistics can.
</P>
<P>
   One picture is from 1964, when the airport's new main terminal
opened. The other picture is an aerial view of the airport a few
years ago, showing a virtually unchanged setting: a crescent with
four arms stretching out behind it for jet gates; a tangle of
taxiways; the same two runways, now slightly longer.
</P>
<P>
   There is one big difference. In the 1964 photo _ taken when
there were about 200,000 takeoffs and landings a year at the
airport _ a couple dozen jets are parked at gates or moving toward
the runways. In the recent photo, taken when the number of takeoffs
and landings were more than 350,000 a year, it seems as if nearly
every square inch of tarmac is covered with jets.
</P>
<P>
   Because La Guardia serves so many airlines, which fly to so many
cities, it is like a finely calibrated instrument that can be
thrown into disarray by the smallest disruption _ bad weather here
or anywhere else, late arrivals, air traffic control glitches or
bunching, when airlines schedule too many flights at once.
</P>
<P>
   A $340 million renovation, which is nearing completion, has made
the terminal more comfortable and modern, adding food courts and
enlarging the lower baggage area. Taxi space has also been improved
but there is no room to add what is most needed _ more runways _ so
congestion has become more common.
</P>
<P>
   Layne has seen tarmac traffic jams so many times that they no
longer faze him much. One recent Friday, the culprit was what Layne
calls popcorn storm cells, small clusters of turbulent weather,
which were north of the city, causing only light rain at the
airport, but forcing air traffic controllers to space out takeoffs
slightly. Layne pointed toward the radio in his van, which was
tuned to the channel used by the officials who direct traffic to
the runways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why you hear those long periods of silence on
there,'' he said, `is because nobody's moving out here. They don't
have anything to tell anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the United Airlines concourse that Friday, Stephanie
Black, a church secretary from Ossining, N.Y., had put her
9-year-old son, Daniel, on a flight by himself back to Denver to be
with his father. The jet pushed away at 11:29 a.m., a minute early.
As she waited, it did not take off. Thirty minutes passed. Then
forty-five. Black needed to go back to work. At 12:20, the jet
thundered down the runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he's in there tearing his hair out,'' said Black, 29,
``probably asking the pilot if he can fly it himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason that La Guardia makes an interesting laboratory
for viewing flight delays is that it is one of the few airports in
the country whose traffic is still limited by the Federal Aviation
Administration's high-density rule, which was created in 1969 to
prevent overtaxing the air traffic control system. The rule, which
now has many exemptions, basically means that no more than 1,224
flights are supposed to take off and land during La Guardia's peak
hours, from 6 a.m. to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the exemptions and a steady increase in the
number of flights being scheduled by major airlines, the flight
limit has not prevented the growth of traffic at La Guardia,
especially in the last few years. A chart of all La Guardia
aircraft movements _ those of big jets, commuter jets, private jets
and propeller planes _ shows that last year, for example, there
were 371,000 takeoffs and landings, up from 358,157 in 1998 and
345,647 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, President Clinton signed a law intended to expand
service between New York and smaller cities by creating more slots
for small regional jets, those that hold up to 71 passengers, to
come into and leave La Guardia.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the law, including Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and
officials in Queens, have sued to try to stop the addition of
slots. They contend that the measure could add as many as 500
flights a day to the airport, swamping it, causing more delays,
clogging traffic and creating more noise.
</P>
<P>
   David Z. Plavin, the president of the Airports Council
International, a trade association representing major airport
operators, said that La Guardia was among 22 national airports
classified by the federal government as severely congested, meaning
that they have 20,000 hours or more of delays a year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing outcry from passengers about those delays,
the chances for La Guardia, or many of the other airports, to ever
get off that list remain dim. In large part, this is because demand
for air travel is expected to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines respond to that demand, Plavin said, not only with many
more flights, but also with smaller planes, which are more
economical for the airlines, yet mean more takeoffs and landings
for the same number of people. ``What I think we're seeing is a
tension in the system of people wanting to have more frequency to
places they want to fly and airlines obliging, but the system not
being able to handle that as efficiently as we need it to,'' Plavin
said. ``It used to be that you had two flights a day between some
major cities, and now there are maybe 10 or 20 or 30 by the same
airlines. It's not just a matter of insufficient hardware and
facilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
