<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WILSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIL WILSON, 44, TENOR WHO SANG A MEMORABLE `WERTHER' AT THE MET 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Neil Wilson, a tenor who sang at the Metropolitan
Opera from 1988 to 1993 and was particularly admired for his
portrayal of the title role in Massenet's ``Werther,'' died on
Monday. He was 44 and had homes in New York and Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was kidney cancer, said his manager, Neil Funkhauser.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was born in Lubbock, Texas, and received degrees at
Southwestern University in Georgetown, Texas, and at Oklahoma City
University. He began his operatic career in 1980 in a performance
of Verdi's ``Falstaff'' at Wolf Trap.
</P>
<P>
   He also appeared in the early 1980s in performances with the
Opera Orchestra of New York at Carnegie Hall and at the
Wuerttembergische Staatsoper in Stuttgart, Germany. In 1988, he
made his Metropolitan Opera debut as Macduff in Verdi's
``Macbeth.'' Other roles he sang with the company were Rodolfo in
Puccini's ``Boheme'' and Werther, both of which included broadcast
performances, and Alfred in Verdi's ``Traviata.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he was selected as a leading tenor at the Komische Oper
in Berlin, and over the last decade he gave more than 150
performances in leading roles, both in the house and on tour.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies with which he sang in recent seasons include the
Vienna Staatsoper, the Salzburg Festival, the New Israeli Opera,
the Canadian Opera Co., the Washington Opera, the Los Angeles
Opera, and Glyndebourne.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson won several vocal competitions and prizes, including the
Baltimore International Operatic Competition, the Rosa Ponselle
International Competition, and a contest sponsored by the Gerda
Lissner Foundation. In May, he was awarded the Wagner Prize by the
Liederkranz Foundation, and performed in a concert that the
foundation presented at Alice Tully Hall.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Linda Mungia; his mother, Shirley W.
Nease, of Abilene, Texas; two sisters, Nancy Fisher and Nora Del
Bosque, both of Austin, Texas; and two brothers, Noel Nease, of
Littleton, Colo., and Nathan Nease, of Abilene, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
