<HEADER>
A1532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-24 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LASORDA HAS HIGHER CALLING
</HEADLINE>
  By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  When he was managing for the O'Malley family, Tom Lasorda used to
preach that his blood was Dodgers blue. It was a great shtick that
earned him considerable television time in his early years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But now Lasorda is talking red, white and blue, and his
perennial bluster is muted as he talks proudly about patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father used to sit at the head of the table and tell us,
`You ought to thank God you were born in the U.S.,''' Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   He invokes the memory of his father, Sabatino, born in a little
town in the Abruzzi, the hardscrabble region to the east of Rome,
over toward the Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father fought for Italy in World War I, and came over when
he was 21,'' Lasorda said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Not needing to footnote that Italy wound up on the other side in
World War II, Lasorda recalled how ``the Germans put all these guns
up in the hills in Tollo, where my father came from, 12 miles from
Pescara. The Americans came in and leveled the place.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Lasorda family, then living in the Philadelphia area,
there were no ambiguities. They were Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would tell us in his broken English, `You may be called on
to serve your country. You may be called on to fight. You may be
called on to give up your life,''' Lasorda recalled. ``He said it
would be an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda calls himself fortunate that he never had to bleed for
his country. It is no sacrifice at all for him to manage the U.S.
baseball team in the Summer Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bigger than the World Series! Bigger than Major League
Baseball! Bigger than the Dodgers!'' shouts Lasorda, whose speech
demands to be defined by exclamation points.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda will have no Garvey, no Fernando, no Dusty, but he
expects nothing less than a gold medal from these prospects and
journeymen. He will surely reprieve the old gall and bluster he
used on his Dodgers in the 1980s, acting as if they were
participating in Grade B war movies.
</P>
<P>
   When Lasorda tried to replace Cpl. Jay Johnstone on defense
during a September game, Johnstone growled, ``Nuts to you, Tommy, I
ain't coming out,'' and bolted back to the outfield as Lasorda
chortled.
</P>
<P>
   When Pvt. Mickey Hatcher led cheers like a UCLA pompom girl,
Capt. Lasorda swelled with blue Dodger pride.
</P>
<P>
   And when the bureaucrats suspended one of his best men, Lasorda
rallied the troops. The other day, he recalled a pivotal moment,
when the future of the world _ or at least Chavez Ravine _ hung in
the balance.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled how his best relief pitcher, Jay Howell, was
detected using pine tar, a substance that gives the ball an extra
(and illegitimate) spin, during the 1988 championship series
against the Mets. Howell was tossed out of the game and ultimately
busted for two more games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my guys, `We're not gonna let the loss of one guy
determine this series,''' Lasorda recalled. ``I said, `We're all
gonna have to dig in.' That was when Hershiser closed for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Late the next night, Spc. Orel Hershiser, deceptively
bespectacled and mild-mannered, volunteered to come out of the
bullpen in the 12th inning, saving the Dodgers' stunning Game 4
victory, and sending them toward a world championship. Lasorda had
already nicknamed him Bulldog.
</P>
<P>
   He will surely have nicknames for his mix-and-match assortment
that will not have it easy in Sydney. He will try to drag
flashbacks from retreads like Pat Borders and a few others who have
had a taste of the majors.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans, who won the first two gold medals, in Barcelona and
Atlanta, will be back. Japan may bring as many as eight players
from their two major leagues, including the hot young pitcher
Daisuke Matsuzaka of the Seibu Lions. And South Korea is closing
down its pro league the way the NH L did for the 1998 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you right now, we're not gonna go 6,000 miles to
lose,'' Lasorda said over the telephone, so emphatically that one
could envision his index finger jabbing the air.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an immigrant from the Abruzzi can appreciate the
links between nations.
</P>
<P>
   Like Looie Carnesecca, the ambassador of basketball from St.
John's University, Lasorda has gone back to his ancestral homeland
to teach his sport. The Italians have learned well, and are one of
the eight qualifying nations for these Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play Italy on Sept. 22,'' Lasorda said. ``Olympic Stadium!
What an honor! It's my birthday!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
