<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS, PISTONS SET FOR LAETTNER TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Dallas Mavericks hope to complete a trade for
Christian Laettner by Monday, owner Mark Cuban said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would send Cedric Ceballos, John Wallace and Eric
Murdock from the Mavericks to Detroit for Laettner, a former
All-American at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Monday is the earliest the trade can be made.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks acquired Wallace and Murdock on June 28, the day
of the NBA Draft, from New York and the Los Angeles Clippers,
respectively. NBA rules state that after a player is traded, a team
must wait 60 days to trade him again, and the waiting period for
the Mavs ends Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up Laettner, who is going into the last year of his
contract, gives the Mavs needed depth at center and power forward.
The eight-year veteran has played for three teams _ Minnesota,
Atlanta and Detroit _ and has averaged 15.7 points and 7.6 rebounds
over his career. He scored 12.2 points with 6.7 rebounds in 82
starts for Detroit last season.
</P>
<P>
   Drafted third overall by Minnesota in 1992, Laettner scored a
career-high 18.2 points per game, grabbed 8.7 rebounds and made the
all-rookie team that season. With Atlanta in '97, he averaged 18.1
points and a career-best 8.8 rebounds. Laettner starred on two
national championship teams at Duke, was selected collegiate player
of the year in '92 and played on the original Dream Team at the '92
Olympics, earning a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   The trade would drop the Mavericks' roster to 15 players with
more changes possible. Cuban has told guard Dana Barros, acquired
last week in a four-team deal that netted point guard Howard
Eisley, that the team is trying to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos, a 6-foot-7, 10-year veteran, averaged 16.6 points and
6.7 rebounds last season in mainly a reserve role. Despite starting
only 25 times, Ceballos was third on the team in scoring. But with
the team in the market for a backup to center Shawn Bradley,
Ceballos is the Mavericks player most often mentioned in trade
rumors this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Murdock, who missed 42 games last season because of tendinitis
in a knee, is not completely healthy and would have been hard
pressed to make the Mavs' final roster. Wallace, a 6-9 forward,
played sparingly with the Knicks last season. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
