u f BC-MITSUBISHI-RECALL-NYT     08-24 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITSUBISHI-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS SAY MITSUBISHI'S PROBLEMS SHOULDN'T LINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKI TANIKAWA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Mitsubishi Motors has had perhaps its worst week in its
history. On Tuesday, the company acknowledged that it had concealed
customer complaints for more than two decades, and in a scene that
was televised nationally, its president profusely apologized to the
transportation minister. Its stock has dropped more than 6 percent
this week.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the admission, the company recalled 88,000 cars and
trucks, adding to a recall of 532,000 vehicles announced last
month. But despite the public humiliation, Mitsubishi, Japan's
fourth-largest car manufacturer, is not likely to suffer a
significant loss in sales or damage to its brand image in Japan,
analysts here say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The direct impact from the recall is negligible,'' said Koji
Endo, an automobile analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   For one, analysts said, Fuji Heavy Industries, the maker of
Subarus, and Daihatu Motors were forced to recall cars in the late
1990s, with little effect on sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese consumers' attention tends to go to new car models,''
said Seiji Sugiura, an analyst with Nomura Securities in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the admitted deception, ``in Mitsubishi's case,
there were injuries involving one vehicle out of 600,000 to 700,000
recalled,'' Sugiura said, further limiting potential public
reaction to the recall.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the matter of Mitsubishi's powerful name. The
Mitsubishi cluster of companies, or keirestsu _ which includes
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries _ has a work force that numbers in the
hundreds of thousands, and many of those workers can be expected to
be loyal customers.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Mitsubishi, which makes models like the Montero
sport utility vehicle, the Galant sedan and the Mirage compact, has
already been suffering from weak sales in Japan and abroad.
Mitsubishi Motors' domestic car sales fell by more than 3 percent
for the six months ended in June, while Honda Motor's sales rose
9.7 percent, and Toyota Motor's gained 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Motors is also plagued by huge debt. To survive, the
company has sought an alliance with DaimlerChrysler, which has
agreed to take a 34 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi has estimated that the cost of the recall, which
involves replacement parts and repair work, will be about 7.5
billion yen _ or about $70.2 million, based on current exchange
rates _ an amount that is not expected to significantly add to the
company's projected net loss of 70 billion yen, or $655 million,
for the fiscal year ending March 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The loss is largely a result of insufficient funds for
liabilities stemming from pension and retirement payments.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cost of the recall could ultimately swell to nearly
10 billion yen, ``that could be offset by selling plants, stocks or
land,'' Endo of First Boston said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi also faces a possible criminal prosecution for
failing to report defects to the government. The Tokyo police said
Thursday that they were considering an investigation. But the
maximum penalty under Japanese law is a fine of 4 million yen, or
$37,500. The true punishment is ``the social sanction for getting
penalized,'' said Yukikazu Komiyama, an official with the Ministry
of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   But pride in the Mitsubishi name may offset any such sanction.
``People who work for Mitsubishi group companies will shore up
sales of Mitsubishi cars,'' Endo said. ``There might even be a
campaign to buy a Mitsubishi.''
</P>
</TEXT>
