<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OATES IS LOSING PATIENCE AS PERISHO LOSES AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One-third of the Texas Rangers' experiment with young
pitching is coming to a conclusion. Matt Perisho is just about out
of chances to win a spot in the Rangers' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   That has become increasingly apparent with each start, and
manager Johnny Oates all but confirmed it Thursday. Perisho,
despite being given a 4-1 lead, gave up eight runs in three-plus
innings and lost to the New York Yankees, 8-7, at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho is 2-7 with a 7.34 earned-run average. It's no
coincidence that Ryan Glynn began his medical rehabilitation
assignment by starting Thursday night for Triple-A Oklahoma. Glynn,
a youngster inserted in the rotation along with Perisho and Doug
Davis, could be ready to pitch Tuesday, when Perisho's spot comes
up again. Oates said he hasn't made up his mind who will start
Tuesday but said there's a reason why Glynn started Thursday night.
Oates said much depends on what kind of report he gets after Glynn
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But Oates added, ``Ryan Glynn is going to pitch in the starting
rotation. Whose spot, I don't know. But he's earned that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his assessment of Perisho's performance, Oates said:
``Consistent. Consistent with what I've seen most of the year. Not
good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he's done evaluating Perisho, Oates said, ``I don't
know if it's accurate, but I've got an idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Perisho has given up 18 runs in his past two starts and is
winless in his past 11 starts. Even he seems to believe that he's
running out of chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can do about it,'' said Perisho, a 15-game
winner in Triple A last year who has yet to build on that success.
``I'm not concerned about that. I'm more worried about getting
people out at this level. No matter where I'm at for the next 45
days, all I'm trying to do is figure out how to get people out. No
matter if it's the rotation or the bullpen, I've got to get people
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Perisho did not lose to the defending world champions. This was
not the same team that finished off the Atlanta Braves in Game 4 of
the World Series last year. Shortstop Derek Jeter, third baseman
Scott Brosius and catcher Jorge Posada, who got a rare start at
first base, were the only ones in the lineup Thursday who started
Game 4 of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Missing were Bernie Williams, Tino Martinez, Paul O'Neill,
Darryl Strawberry (yes, he's technically still a Yankee) and Chuck
Knoblauch. All are either injured or, in Strawberry's case,
suspended. Their starting left fielder from Game 4, Ricky Ledee,
started for the Rangers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers met a team banged up as much as they were and still
lost. The Yankees did have 15-game winner Andy Pettitte on the
mound, but the Rangers got five runs off him in the first four
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see the best team in baseball,'' first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro said. ``They have a lot of guys sitting out, and
their pitchers were not at the top of their game. Come playoff
time, you'll see a different team playing at a different level. We
should have taken advantage of it, but they were able to piece it
together to win three out of four.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were the sloppy team early, and the Rangers took
advantage of a couple of errors to forge a 4-1 lead. But Perisho
couldn't hold it. The Yankees put together five hits, a walk and a
couple of Rangers defensive mistakes to score five in the third.
The Rangers got one back in the fourth, but Glenallen Hill finished
Perisho with a two-run home run in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make a good pitch, they hit a single,'' Perisho said. ``If I
make a bad pitch, they hit a home run. All I need to do is to keep
going out there and learn. Whether it's this year or next year or
in two years, I'm going to get balls that are hit at people and
make pitches that are popped up instead of hit for home runs.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
