<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNUSUAL LINEUP MAKES FOR BAD BASEBALL BUT A GOOD VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
  By RAFAEL HERMOSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ball was launched hard off the bat and appeared
headed for center field. Chad Curtis thought he had led off the
Texas Rangers' ninth inning with an exclamation, until pitcher
Mariano Rivera raised his glove and denied Curtis a leadoff single.
The ball knocked Rivera backward, leaving him with an expression
somewhere between a smile and a grimace.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to get any uglier than that, so it might help
him out a little,'' the New York Yankees' Jorge Posada joked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for the game. Fielding a lineup that
turned a few heads, the Yankees ended a messy homestand with a
sloppy 8-7 victory over the Texas Rangers Thursday at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The last week has lacked aesthetics. The Yankee bullpen blew its
third lead of the homestand on Wednesday night before the team
rallied in the ninth for a victory. In all, the Yankees won five of
eight games at the Stadium and now will travel to the West Coast to
play Oakland Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had their share of highlights Thursday, from
Glenallen Hill's love-in with the fans in the bleachers to Andy
Pettitte's persistence to Jose Canseco's footwork to Jason
Grimsley's two hitless innings of relief. But the Yankees and the
Rangers also combined for three errors and numerous mental blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good game to win, because we definitely didn't play a
good ballgame,'' said Pettitte (16-6), who won his seventh straight
game.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup was less than a thing of beauty. With Bernie Williams
(sore rib cage) and Paul O'Neill (hip pointer) resting injuries,
manager Joe Torre started an outfield of Hill, Clay Bellinger and
David Justice, who returned after missing three games with a sore
neck. Posada played first with Chris Turner catching. Jose Vizcaino
started at second base.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees had Pettitte and his knack for run support on
their side. The team is averaging 7.48 runs in Pettitte's 25
starts, including 11.17 in his previous six starts. Torre joked
that other pitchers were jealous and said before the game, ``If it
happens today with the little bit of a skeleton lineup we have,
then you know Andy Pettitte has an angel on his shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   That angel could have sprouted horns when Pettitte fell behind
by 4-1 in the third inning as his teammates appeared out of sync.
Posada closed his glove too soon on a throw to first in the first
inning for an error, and then he started an unusual sequence in the
third. Ricky Ledee's grounder bounced off Posada's glove and to
Vizcaino, who threw the ball past Pettitte at first base, allowing
one run to score. Curtis, who had stopped running at third, jogged
home unimpeded when Turner chased the ball to the backstop.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Pettitte was confident that his team would score off the
Texas starter Matt Perisho.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees batted around for five runs in the third on the legs
of Canseco. With Posada on first and Canseco, who has a sore left
heel, on second, and three runs already in during the inning,
Turner laid down a sacrifice bunt. Canseco raced to third and beat
Perisho's throw.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Bellinger hit a grounder to third with the bases
loaded and one out, Canseco looked like a tight end as he rambled
home. He saw Texas catcher Robert Waszgis casually standing behind
the plate. Third baseman Scott Sheldon threw home. That startled
Canseco, who saw that the catcher was out of position, and
apparently Waszgis, who was straddling the plate and failed to get
the forceout. The Yankees led, 6-4, but Texas scored once in the
fourth inning. Then, in the bottom of the inning, Hill punctuated
the afternoon with a mammoth two-run home run. The ball caromed off
the front of the center-field bleachers as Hill just missed
reaching the black seats for the second time in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Hill is batting .429 since his trade from the Cubs on July 20,
with 12 homers in 70 at-bats. He batted .455 with six homers on the
homestand and extended his career-high hitting streak to 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to the ballpark every day and the ball flies off the
bat, but usually that happens in batting practice,'' Hill said.
``It feels good to have it happen in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre says the team now expects every ball Hill hits in the air
to carry for a home run. ``That's crazy,'' the manager said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making this ballpark look like Enron Field or Coors
Field,'' Pettitte said.
</P>
</TEXT>
