<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NEWMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTHUR NEWMAN, 92, A BARITONE HEARD IN 50 ROLES AT CITY OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arthur Newman, a baritone who sang with the New York
City Opera in the 1940s and '50s, died on Aug. 6 in Scottsdale,
Ariz. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, who was born in St. Louis, began his stage career in the
1930s as a member of the Missouri Theater Company. Although his
roles were primarily nonmusical, by the mid-1930s he began studying
voice and operatic roles, and in 1939 he joined the St. Louis Grand
Opera Association. In four seasons with the company, he sang
secondary roles in ``Otello,'' ``Rigoletto,'' ``Traviata,''
Tosca,'' ``Manon'' ``Martha'' and ``Mignon.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman also became a featured singer at a St. Louis radio
station, KMOX, where for several years he and his wife, Helen
Wright, presented a weekly program of vocal duets. In the early
1940s, he also sang with the International Opera of Havana and with
the St. Louis Chamber Opera. His first performances in New York
were in a production of Offenbach's ``Vie Parisienne'' presented by
the New Opera Co.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the New York City Opera in the 1944-45 season and made
his debut as Schaunard in ``La Boheme'' in April 1945. He remained
on the company's roster until 1959 and is credited with more than
1,300 performances in more than 50 roles. Many were smaller, comic
roles like the Sacristan in ``Tosca'' and Antonio in ``Nozze di
Figaro.''
</P>
<P>
   He also sang Masetto in ``Don Giovanni,'' a handful of roles in
``Der Rosenkavalier'' and Escamillo in ``Carmen.''
</P>
<P>
   He also sang small roles on several recordings for RCA,
including Arturo Toscanini's recordings of ``Otello'' and ``La
Traviata.'' When he left the City Opera, he took a professorship at
Wichita State University in Kansas, where he taught until his
retirement in 1973. Among his students were the bass Samuel Ramey.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a daughter, Frances Sandoval, of Fountain
Hills, Ariz.; two sons, Frank, of Oak Hill, Va., and Greg, of
Silver City, N.M.; and a sister, Bertha Siteman, of St. Louis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
