<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
 BRIEFS-NYT   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  THE POLLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   A BOOST FOR GORE
</P>
<P>
   New polls show Vice President Al Gore has enjoyed a significant
post-convention boost in four crucial big states, overtaking Gov.
George W. Bush in Minnesota and perhaps in Michigan and increasing
his lead in New Jersey and California. Ralph Nader, the Green Party
nominee, slipped in all four states.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, an EPIC-MRA poll showed Gore ahead of Bush by two
points. That lead was within the poll's margin of sampling error of
plus or minus four percentage points. In a pre-convention poll, he
trailed Bush by eight points.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, a Mason-Dixon poll gave Gore an eight-point lead
over Bush. A July Mason-Dixon Poll had Bush ahead of Gore by three
points.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey poll, conducted by Quinnipiac University, gave
Gore a 12-point lead. A New Jersey poll taken just before the
Republican convention had Gore ahead by only four points.
</P>
<P>
   In California, a Field Poll had Gore leading Bush by 13 points.
The previous Field Poll, in June, had him ahead by 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   A BIG FUND-RAISING NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore pulled in more than $1.25 million
Wednesday night in a pair of fund-raising dinners in Washington for
the Democratic National Committee. The first dinner drew 30 people,
most of them Indian-Americans, who paid $5,000 each. With other
contributions, the dinner yielded $250,000. The host of the dinner
was Ramesh Kapur, owner of a medical technology firm in Winchester,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The second dinner drew about 20 people, most of them friends of
Gore's running mate, Sen. Joe Lieberman, who also attended. They
each paid or raised $50,000, for a total of $1 million. Both
dinners were served at the Mayflower Hotel, but the second was a
Glatt Kosher meal, the pure form of Kosher food, blessed by a rabbi
and provided by a restaurant, Dahan of Washington. Its host was
Marvin Lender, who once ran his family business, Lender's Bagels,
and is now an executive with M&AMP;M Industries, based in Woodbridge,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES:
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Austin, Texas
</P>
<P>
   DICK CHENEY: No public appearances
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: No public appearances
</P>
<P>
   JOE LIEBERMAN: Claymont, Del.
</P>
<P>
   RALPH NADER: Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   PAT BUCHANAN: No public appearances
</P>
</TEXT>
