<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRIGLEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS READY FOR RETURN TO WRIGLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Call it the 16th parallel, the line separating players
from fans along the right field bullpen at Wrigley Field. It's
impacted the Dodgers season perhaps more than anything else, and
today they return to the scene of the alleged crime.
</P>
<P>
   More than three months ago many of Dodgers players spilled into
the Wrigley Field stands to fight with fans, and from the incident
16 players were originally suspended and fined. Because of that May
16 fiasco, the Chicago Cubs modified their security approach to
ensure such incidents don't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   The revamped security measures, which include plain-clothed,
off-duty police officers sitting in the stands, could get its most
stringent test today. The Dodgers and Cubs play a doubleheader,
giving fans plenty of time to kick back and enjoy a beer, or four.
Many of those involved in the original melee said alcohol
consumption played a major role.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rathje, director of stadium operations for the Cubs, said
additional security has been added to the bullpen area. In
addition, a crowd-control person has been added, security now
checks every ticket in the area, other security guards had their
positions changed to better view the area and security personnel
are stationed adjacent to the bullpen bench and waist-high wall
throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
   Also, beer sales are cut off at 9:20 p.m. or after the seventh
inning for night games. Beer sales stop after the eighth inning of
day games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We changed a few things after that incident and pretty much
for the rest of the season we've been going with the plan,'' Rathje
said. ``Obviously, we're going to emphasize that area.''
</P>
<P>
   The altercation began in the bottom of the ninth when catcher
Chad Kreuter was allegedly struck in the back of the head and had
his cap stolen. Kreuter said he went into the stands to apprehend
the perpetrator because there was insufficient security.
</P>
<P>
   On his way back out of the stands, Kreuter said he was hit
several times. Teammates went to Kreuter's aid, with several
climbing into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   From it, 16 players, three coaches and an on-field assistant
were suspended for a total of 89 games and fined $77,000. After
appeals were filed, only five players, two coaches and bullpen
catcher Travis Barbary were suspended a total of 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be interesting to see the crowd's reaction,'' said
Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley, whose three-game suspension was
overturned. ``But from our standpoint, it's business as usual. For
me, it's passed, but we'll have to wait and see. I'm sure the fans
still remember and will exploit it. Obviously, we can't let that
happen again. And the Cubs better not let it happen. Security had
better do things better.''
</P>
<P>
   While many Dodgers say they have moved on, the issue isn't dead.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, left fielder Gary Sheffield will miss the first
three games of the series after dropping his appeal of a five-game
suspension Wednesday. Off the field, lawsuits could take time to
run their courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that (security) would be better,'' Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone said. ``Common sense would tell you
that it would be.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
