<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, AUG. 25 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-BRITAIN-SCANDAL-NYT (moved Tuesday, August 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, August 15
about new information on a 1960's sex scandal in Britain that
involved the Duchess of Argyll misattributed a lyric written for
``You're the Top,'' the Cole Porter song inspired by the duchess.
The lyric, with a reference to Mussolini, was written by P.G.
Wodehouse for the 1935 London production of ``Anything Goes.'' The
lyricist was not Porter.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-NYT (moved Friday, August 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, August 18
about the election for governor in the Mexican state of Chiapas,
and a related map, misspelled the name of a town where one
candidate held a campaign rally. It was Amatenango, not
Amen-tenango.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GORE-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
23 about a visit by Vice President Al Gore and Senator Joseph I.
Lieberman to a Jewish community center in Florida misattributed a
Yiddish greeting. It was Lieberman, not Gore, who said, ``Shalom
aleichem''; Gore said, ``Mazel tov.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-EDUCATION-COLUMN-NYT (moved Tuesday, August 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, August 8
about the progress of the Sisulu Children's Academy, a charter
school in Harlem, referred incorrectly to the business of its
founder, Steven B. Klinsky. He has negotiated buyouts of
corporations but is not a corporate raider who has engaged in
hostile takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
16 about a study showing that regular Internet users stay in
greater touch with family and friends than infrequent users
included incorrect figures from an author of the study. (The
study's conclusions were unaffected.)
</P>
<P>
   Daily Internet users in the study had, on average, 583 contacts
of all kinds per year with friends and relatives living within 30
miles, not 1,312. People who used the Internet one or two times a
year had an average of 396 contacts, not 471. Daily Internet users
had 266 contacts with more distant friends and relatives, not 997.
People who used the Internet once or twice a year had 99 such
contacts, not 75.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-VIDEO-E-MAIL-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
23 about video e-mail messages misidentified the company that used
the technology for a campaign promoting an Oracle Corp. conference.
The campaign was created by MindArrow Systems of Aliso Viejo,
Calif., not RadicalMail.
</P>
</TEXT>
