<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-BUSINESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY STRONGLY DEFENDS HIS WORK AT HALLIBURTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)   By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENTRAL POINT, Ore. _ Dick Cheney vehemently defended his work
in the oil services business Thursday, bristling at any suggestion
that he was less than successful as the chief executive of
Halliburton and insisting once more that as vice president he would
take steps to ensure that his retirement package did not pose a
conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from being a second-tier, second-rank energy services
company to being the biggest in the world,'' he told reporters. He
complained that a front-page article in The New York Times on
Thursday that characterized his record at Halliburton as mixed was
``a distortion,'' ``bad journalism'' and ``seriously flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By any measure you want to use, Halliburton has been a great
success story over the last few years, contrary to what your
colleagues at The New York Times reported,'' he said after
addressing members of the Future Farmers of America here at Crater
High School in southern Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's five years at the helm of Halliburton have drawn a
great deal of attention _ and criticism _ since he was tapped by
George W. Bush last month to be his running mate. Democrats
ridiculed the Republicans as the big-oil ticket, since Cheney and
Bush both worked in the oil industry in Texas. In addition,
Halliburton offered Cheney a retirement package that, as currently
structured, would leave him with stock options that are not
scheduled to vest until 2001 or 2002 _ meaning that as vice
president he would have a great personal interest in the price of
oil.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of Cheney's work at Halliburton that was
published in The Times on Thursday questioned the success of the
company's merger with Dresser Industries, the biggest deal he made;
found that while the company's stock rose, it still underperformed
most stocks in the industry; and described serious problems with a
subsidiary that builds roads.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who had earlier declined to be interviewed for the
article, criticized the prominence the article gave to the
company's problems with road construction, saying that the work
represented only a small part of Halliburton's business.
</P>
<P>
   He also sought to point out projects that he said the company
completed successfully, like Enron Stadium in Houston, an oil
platform that the company built for Exxon in a part of the Gulf of
Mexico that is nearly a mile deep, and a natural gas complex in
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney acknowledged that there had been problems with the
highway projects undertaken by Brown &AMP; Root, a unit of Halliburton,
and said many of them were exacerbated after the company got out of
the road- building business. ``We basically made a decision on my
watch to get out of the road-building business, and what you see
there is the residue,'' he said, adding that once the decision was
made many experts in road construction left the company.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he would find a way to handle his retirement package
so that it would not pose a conflict of interest if he was elected
vice president. ``There is no conflict until I'm sworn in, and by
the time I'm sworn in I'll have done whatever's necessary to make
sure there isn't,'' he said. ``I don't know what more I can say
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's business dealings have become a campaign issue. He
found himself questioned by reporters about rising oil prices at
several stops during a campaign swing through California and Oregon
this week. And when he was met by an enthusiastic crowd at the
opening of the new headquarters of the Kern County Republican Party
in Bakersfield, Calif., a Republican stronghold in the state, a
dozen protesters gathered across the street holding aloft signs
that said ``Cheney Oil'' and ``Halliburton: $39 million,'' a
reference to one estimate of the value of his retirement package.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
