u f BC-JAPAN-NINTENDO-NYT &LR;      08-24 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NINTENDO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO GAME GIANTS TO FIGHT BATTLE ROYAL IN UNITED STATES
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The home video game industry is about to embark
on what is certain to become a bitter and bloody year of new
technology and cost-cutting, which many people in the business say
will claim one or more victims.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo offered the opening move Thursday at the Spaceworld
video-game trade show in Tokyo, announcing both a new home console
based on an IBM PowerPC microprocessor and a new version of its
hand-held Game Boy portable system.
</P>
<P>
   Neither system is scheduled to arrive in the U.S. market before
next year. For this Christmas, the Sony Corp. will clearly dominate
the U.S. market with its highly promoted Playstation 2, scheduled
to go on sale in the United States on Oct. 22. It is a machine
based on a custom chip developed with a $1.3 billion investment
Sony made jointly with Toshiba.
</P>
<P>
   In the wings, the Microsoft Corp. is stalking the game industry
with its own Intel-based video-game system that the company says it
hopes will arrive for the Christmas 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the frenetic competition to dominate the game
console market has forced Sega to retool its strategy. On Sept. 7,
the company will bring out its Sega online game network. It will
also reportedly reduce the price of its Dreamcast video-game
system, which has trailed Sony's Playstation in the American
market.
</P>
<P>
   The next generation video game market is being attacked by giant
consumer electronics and software companies that have different
views of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like three giant planets colliding,'' said Greg Galanos,
a longtime software tool developer for the video game industry, who
is now managing director for Softbank Venture Capital in Mountain
View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the three giants, Sony is intent on creating a
round-the-clock home entertainment portal, Nintendo has focused on
a game-appliance strategy and Microsoft is bringing its PC-centric
strategy to a consumer electronics world, Galanos said.
</P>
<P>
   Sega is not as strong, he said. ``Sega is likely to end up as a
moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Sega, which industry reports say will soon cut the price of its
Dreamcast machine to $149, from $199, and bundle the price of the
machine into its new online game business, has been saying that the
Sony Playstation 2 does not have as large a technical advantage as
the Japanese consumer giant has claimed.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Sega executives are warning that a performance
war between the giants may ultimately damage the video game
industry. ``If Sony and Microsoft continue to outspec themselves,
they will kill each other and take the industry with them,'' said
Charles Bellfield, communications director for Sega of America
Dreamcast.
</P>
<P>
   Sony has made far-reaching performance claims for the
Playstation 2 and, as a result, is enduring some criticism from
game experts who have suggested that the first games available for
the new system have not matched the talk.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Microsoft is trying to market its machine as
more powerful than the Playstation 2, while saying that the company
is being careful not to ``overpromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that all of the video game makers, which generally
do about 80 percent of their business during the Christmas selling
season, could face stiff competition this year from other, new
intelligent consumer appliances that will be vying for attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Christmas, we're going to see big pushes from both Replay
and TiVo,'' said Nick Donatiello, president of Odyssey, a San
Francisco-based consumer electronics market research firm. TiVo and
ReplayTV are the leading brands of digital video recorders.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, he said, will be presented with a wide variety of
different choices this year. In addition to the new digital video
recorders, there will be hand-held gadgets like cell phones and
personal digital assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the game companies will be challenged to explain their
next generation products to consumers. All of the machines will add
features like network connections and the ability to play DVDs and
CDs, making them appear closer to interactive set-top television
boxes than dedicated gaming appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they're selling both floor wax and dessert topping,''
Donatiello said. ``How are they going to get the message across?''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Nintendo seemed intent on proving that its Gamecube could
compete head-to-head with Sony and Microsoft. The system will
include a proprietary 1.5-gigabyte optical disk storage system and
will have wireless game controllers.
</P>
<P>
   The system will go on sale in Japan in July 2001 and come to the
United States three months later.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will introduce its system, which will be manufactured
in Mexico by Flextronics, about the same time. The system will
include a 10 gigabyte or larger hard disk and an Ethernet
connection and will come without an operating system. The operating
system will be carried on each game disk and loaded when the disk
is inserted to play a game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
