<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY WAYS TO CALCULATE PROPOSED TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How big is George W. Bush's proposed tax cut? There is no single
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Over the first nine years that the program could be in effect
starting in the 2002 fiscal year, the first to begin after Bush
would take office, the tax cut is estimated by Congress'
nonpartisan Joint Tax Committee to reduce federal revenue by about
$1.3 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   But tax cuts are sometimes described in terms of their effect
not just on revenue, but on how much of the projected budget
surplus they would consume. The projections concerning the surplus
assume that all excess federal revenue would go toward reducing the
national debt. If any of the surplus is spent or used for tax cuts,
the debt would be reduced by a lesser amount. As a result, the
government would have to pay more interest on the debt than it
would if all the surplus had gone to debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of a $1.3 trillion tax cut, the government's
interest bill would be roughly $300 billion higher over nine years
than if there were no tax cut. So it would also be fair to say that
Bush's tax cut would use $1.6 trillion of the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a wrinkle. Major tax and spending programs are
usually described in terms of their costs over 10 years, not nine.
In the 10 years starting in fiscal year 2002, Bush's tax plan would
reduce revenue by about $1.6 trillion. If the interest effect were
added, the 10-year reduction in the budget surplus would be about
$1.9 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the same standards could be applied to Vice President
Al Gore's proposals. The Gore campaign describes his plan as a $500
billion tax cut over 10 years starting in fiscal year 2001. (For
the sake of argument, Gore assumes that his tax cut would start
next year, so the cost of the cut can be matched against the
current 10-year surplus projection.)
</P>
<P>
   If the interest component were included, it would be a $620
billion tax cut. But Gore has also proposed spending just over $1
trillion of the surplus. His campaign calculates that the overall
tax and spending plan would have an interest cost of $247 billion
over 10 years, meaning that Gore would use nearly $1.8 trillion of
the surplus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1677 &Cx1f; tad-z
b w BC-CLINTON-FOX-0825-1STL     08-24 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FOX-0825-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: in 10th graf, clarifies to read 'was elected president
last month . . . ' sted of 'last summer'
 &HT;    CLINTON, FOX PREDICT STRONGER U.S., MEXICO TIES
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton welcomed Mexican President-elect
Vicente Fox to the White House on Thursday, hailing his upset
victory in July elections as a ``historic'' landmark in the
development of democracy in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the ties that bind the United States and Mexico
will only grow stronger in the years to come, but he made it clear
that easing border restrictions, as Fox has espoused, is not in the
cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we have borders and we have laws that apply to them
and we have to apply them, and so do the Mexicans,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the United States,'' he told reporters at the
White House, ``I believe we have the most generous immigration
policy in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox emerged from an hour-long Oval Office meeting with Clinton
to say that narrowing the income chasm between the two neighbors is
the key to stemming the tide of illegal immigration by job-hungry
Mexicans seeking greener pastures north of the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   It marked a shift in emphasis for Fox, who has outlined in
Mexico in recent weeks a future of open borders between the two
countries, something along the lines of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we work on development, on job creating, on
education programs; as long as we can have in each rural community
in Mexico a school of high level, university or technological
school,'' Fox said, ``then we will not have migration as we are
having now.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving a bit further in that direction in remarks later in the
day, Fox said, ``Really, what we are proposing is an economic
convergence, a holistic view of the problems and the
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   There are roughly 7.1 million Mexican-born people living in the
United States _ far more than any other group of foreigners _ and
about 3 million are classified as illegal aliens. Controlling the
border, and dealing with illegal immigrants, has been a perennial
sore spot in U.S.-Mexico relations.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who travels Friday to Dallas to meet with Texas Gov. George
W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, was elected president
last month in a stunning win over the PRI, or Institutional
Revolutionary Party, which has controlled Mexico's government for
seven decades. He takes office Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton and Fox touched on a broad range of issues _
including the illegal narcotics trade and ideas for building on,
and perhaps eventually expanding the North American Free Trade
Agreement, or NAFTA, which wedded the economies of the United
States, Mexico and Canada _ the incoming Mexican leader made clear
that he was here as part of his transition preparations, not as a
Mexican official.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a working meeting, it's not a negotiating meeting or
anything like that,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, Fox received the sort of welcome here generally
reserved for heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   Much as he has hailed democratic leaders like Vaclev Havel of
the Czech Republic or Boris Yeltsin of Russia, Clinton praised Fox
for a victory expected to shift Mexico's political and bureaucratic
culture dramatically over the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have looked forward to this very much, for the chance to
congratulate him on his election, and all the people of Mexico on a
truly historic affirmation of genuine democracy in their country,''
Clinton said. ``I think it's an example to people who are friends
of freedom everywhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   That endorsement was part of an auspicious Washington debut for
Fox, a former executive with the Coca-Cola Co. While his visit was
an informal one _ PRI leader Ernesto Zedillo remains Mexico's
president for the next three months _ Fox was received pretty much
as Zedillo was when he visited Clinton earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Fox met with Vice President and Democratic presidential
candidate Al Gore Thursday morning, and was hosted for a formal
State Department luncheon by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Standing about two inches taller than Clinton, the charismatic
Fox, with his chiseled features and dark moustache, projected
confidence and an energetic vision for Mexico's future.
</P>
<P>
   He addressed the Washington and Mexican press corps three times,
alternating fluidly between his native Spanish and fluent English,
speaking extemporaneously and in complete paragraphs, seldom
glancing at notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between English and Spanish, I'll end up dizzy here,'' Fox
joked at one point during a 45-minute news conference at the
National Press Club, a traditional event for visiting heads of
state.
</P>
<P>
   In each appearance, Fox sounded the themes of reform and
decentralization near the heart of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He said state and local governments should assume a growing role
in areas where federal authority has been inefficient. He said job
growth must come from building a vibrant base of small and
medium-sized businesses, entrepreneurial in nature rather than the
hidebound behemoths that have long characterized industrial Mexico.
In addition, Fox said grassroots activism and so-called
non-governmental organizations _ both home-grown and foreign _ have
an important role to play in promoting human rights and sound
environmental practices, and combating poverty in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
