<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN AND REFORM RIVAL PLAY THE WHEEL OF FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Iowa, N.C., Mont., Mich., Calif., Kan.)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Iowa on Thursday, a government aide put a slip of paper
inside each of two black canisters. On one was written
``Buchanan-Foster;'' on the other, ``Hagelin-Goldhaber.'' After the
canisters were placed into a glass bowl on a stand outside his
office in the Capitol rotunda, Secretary of State Chester J. Culver
walked up, stirred the canisters around and lifted one out.
</P>
<P>
   And that is how Pat Buchanan and his running mate, Ezola Foster,
became the Reform Party presidential ticket in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   An odd way, perhaps, to pick a president, but it is the current
state of affairs in the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in Iowa and several other states this week is a
direct consequence of a fractious convention two weeks ago that
left the party split, with two candidates and their organizations
contending to be the rightful heir to state ballot designations in
November as the Reform Party ticket and $12.6 million in federal
campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   But the bickering at the convention was only a prologue to what
is going on now. Not only are the Buchanan and Hagelin factions
fighting over the money with the Federal Election Commission, they
are threatening lawsuits in various states over decisions that
leave one of them off the ballot as the Reform ticket, a
potentially fatal blow for the losing side. Only by winning 5
percent of the popular vote in November can the candidate and his
party qualify for federal money in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   John Duffy, a lawyer in Washington who represents Buchanan, said
flatly: ``We will go into court wherever necessary not to allow
anybody to identify themselves as the Reform Party candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Iowa was one of at least four states in which the
matter was addressed.
</P>
<P>
   In Montana, Secretary of State Mike Cooney followed his Iowa
counterpart by picking a name out of a ballot box that contained 10
canisters with ``Buchanan'' written on an index card and 10 with
``Hagelin.'' After Cooney plucked out a Hagelin, a lawyer for
Buchanan in Helena began drawing up papers seeking a temporary
restraining order from a state court to prevent Cooney from
certifying a ballot with Hagelin's name.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lippert, the lawyer, said the court would schedule a hearing
within 10 days to decide whether Cooney's selection should stand,
after which Lippert said, he expected that the losing party would
appeal the court decision to the Montana Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan Department of State's Bureau of Elections sent a
letter to the two campaigns, asking each to make a case for its
ticket, after which the bureau would decide. ``But if it's not
crystal clear who it should be, I could see us denying both
requests,'' said Brad Wittman, a spokesman for the bureau. ``Then
courts would have to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, the Board of Elections heard testimony from
the two sides for more than four hours Thursday, and then voted 3-1
to put the Buchanan ticket on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, two other states took other actions, and
perhaps nowhere else will the fight be more grueling than in
California, where the state Reform Party is operating as one
splintered organization. Late Wednesday, Secretary of State Bill
Jones withdrew Buchanan and Foster as the Reform ticket after the
state party chairman, Raymond O. Mills, a Buchanan ally,
acknowledged that the state party board of directors, which favors
Hagelin, had voted last week not to support a Buchanan ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Mills had told Jones last week that the state party recognized
Buchanan as the Reform nominee. But John H. Place, the party vice
chairman, told Jones in a letter that any communication with Mills
should be considered ``null and void'' without evidence of the
board's approval.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the state party has until next Thursday to affirm its
notify Jones of its choice.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas has taken another approach. On Tuesday, the state
rejected each side's claim to the ballot, advising the two to take
their complaints to the State Objections Board, which would sort
things out and pick one, leaving the loser to take matters into
court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
