<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FALLSTYLE-ETIQUETTE08     08-24 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLSTYLE-ETIQUETTE0827-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    u B5E11946EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Peggy Post confirms etiquette's back in style
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The good news, says manners maven Peggy Post, is
the definite resurgence of interest in etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   And although specific guidelines may change through the years,
she says the underlying principles of etiquette always remain the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a code of behavior based on being considerate and
practical,'' says Emily Post's great-granddaughter-in-law, who has
carried on the family mission. ``It helps us get along and gives
people a way of knowing what to do in certain situations. It gives
order to our world.''
</P>
<P>
   She says many rules of etiquette are simple and just a matter of
being considerate. ``If someone's right behind you when you're
walking into a building, don't slam the door in their face!'' she
says. ``And say `thank you' and `please.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dressing and fashion are topics that have always been addressed
in etiquette books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a decision about what's appropriate is a confusing
issue for people,'' explains Post, who adds that is especially true
today, when we have so many choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone asks me what `festive attire' means on an
invitation, I say, `Whatever your host or hostess has in mind,' ''
she says. ``I recommend you either ask other people who are going
what they're wearing or call and ask the hostess. It's all a matter
of feeling comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that we all need to look alike, Post says, but neither
should we ``pull out the shock too much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is not to offend other people. For example, when a
teen-ager is rebellious and wants to wear the wildest outfit to
grandparents' house for Thanksgiving dinner, at least tone it down
a bit. Wear a clean shirt so grandmom and dad don't feel upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Post says she's seen lots of interest in etiquette from parents,
children and teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that they understand just what it is we're
talking about,'' she says. ``Etiquette is for everybody, it's not
just stuffy, highbrow and formal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000824.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FALLSTYLE-INTRO0827-C     08-24 0293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLSTYLE-INTRO0827-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    u B5E11946EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Etiquette's in fashion
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Whatever happened to good manners?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question that's been asked often in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   About the time we all fell in love with blue jeans and sweats,
it seems we stopped minding our P's and Q's and began tossing our
etiquette books out the window.
</P>
<P>
   If you're one of those who mourns the loss, take heart. If this
year's fall fashions are any indication, significant changes are in
store.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't grungy or outlandishly dressed models who sauntered
down the New York runways in February showing off the newest fall
looks. Instead we saw elegant ladies and gentlemen looking polished
and sophisticated in luxurious cashmeres and tweeds.
</P>
<P>
   The word of the day is ``ladylike.'' And let's be honest, you
won't appear classy and refined if your decorum doesn't match your
outfit. So while we're not recommending a return to outdated and
rigid rules, the return to common courtesy sounds pretty
refreshing, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   So you won't be caught with your gloves off, we've assembled the
season's must-haves as well as ``must-do's.'' You'll get a chuckle
out of some of the historic etiquette we've uncovered (``The woman
always bows first when meeting men acquaintances on the street'')
and you may learn a few things about what's considered good manners
these days as well (``Do not tip the owner of a B&AMP;B, even if he
brings you breakfast'').
</P>
<P>
   We've taken our models to some of the most elegant locations to
illustrate just how much fun dressing up _ and behaving nicely _
can be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
