<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    u B5E11946EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Gentlemen look the part
 &HT;    By Luma Muhtadie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Men's fashions will complement their ladylike
counterparts. Designers have dipped into fashion's pool of
timeless, traditional pieces and updated them with crisp tailoring
and high-tech fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   The classic, polished look that emerges bridges the gap between
formal business dress and casual sportswear: Men will look smart
and sophisticated around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The resurgence of natural fabrics _ cashmere, refined wools,
tweed _ together with straight and narrow lines, creates a dressier
look than we've seen in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that American men search for comfort and
practicality even amid the dressiest clothing, and fabrics cannot
be too heavy, tightly binding, or vulnerable to wrinkling and
staining,'' says Jack Herschlag, executive director of the National
Association of Men's Sportswear Buyers Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The ``straight and narrow'' look in men's suits doesn't imply a
tight and constrictive fit. Many designers are adding a bit of
polyurethane (aka spandex) to fabric blends, which allows greater
freedom of movement. The 40-inch topcoat takes its proper place at
the top of the men's list of must-haves this fall. The ``topper'' _
long enough to be worn over a sport coat yet short enough to avoid
the trench-coat look _ is perhaps the season's biggest winner. It's
elegant and versatile.
</P>
<P>
   And the most enduring of classics _ leather _ comes on strong
again this fall. Leather has a strange versatility: It's one of the
most primitive fabrics, but with today's lustrous finishes it gives
it the impression of something high-tech.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
