<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    u B5E11946EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Prim, proper &AMP; polished
 &HT;    By Emily Rahimi
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Who says prim and proper can't be fun, or that
etiquette doesn't apply to teen-agers?
</P>
<P>
   Now that baggy jeans and chunky shoes are out of style,
polished, more sophisticated looks have taken center stage.
</P>
<P>
   For teens and collegians, that means this season's filled with
blouses, skirts and slacks. Though shapes are classic, they're
anything but boring.
</P>
<P>
   Bright colors (used in moderation) and animal prints (ditto) are
hot right now and can make a traditional look a lot of fun. Try
pairing a pewter sweater with a leopard print mini-skirt, or wear a
shiny, blue blouse with cropped wool slacks for a style that's
classy but still young.
</P>
<P>
   Leather is also a cool way to stay warm this autumn. The Gap
carries great pants, skirts and jackets in hues ranging from plum
to black. But don't think you need to break the bank to get this
look. Many stores also offer pleather pieces, which give you the
look of buttery leather at the price of plastic.
</P>
<P>
   If you just can't part with your
</P>
<P>
   T-shirts and jeans, check out items with more refined shapes and
colors. Try a rayon T-shirt with slim-fit, dark denim jeans and
matching jacket. You'll look clean, put together and
oh-so-well-bred. With so many options, why not go out and play with
convention?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to understand why so many otherwise attractive
people totally destroy their appearance by chewing gum like a cow
chewing a cud. Chewing gum, in itself, if it is done quietly and
unobtrusively, is not unattractive. But when one does it with
grimaces, open mouth, smacks, crackers and pops and worth of all
with bubbles, it is with the worst of taste.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Emily Post's Etiquette, 1997
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep your shoes on!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Etiquette for Dummies, 1999
</P>
<P>
   It is the impulse of all young persons to try to be as exactly
like each other as biscuits in a pan. During the war, groups of
teen-age girls across the country have taken to the sloppiest of
over-sized boys clothes worn in the sloppiest way.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long will it be before a new craze _ perhaps for extreme
loveliness _ takes its place, no one can say. It can only be hoped
that the behavior that goes with pants and shirttail out will not
have been found ineradicable.
</P>
<P>
   _ From Etiquette by Emily Post, 1945
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO A: UMBRELLA SHOT
</P>
<P>
   ``If two people are sharing an umbrella, the taller person _
usually the man but not always _ should hold it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From Etiquette for Dummies by Sue Fox
</P>
<P>
   TAKE COVER: On her: caramel ribbed cotton sweater ($48),
short-sleeved-graphic T-shirt with floral overlay ($15.50), khaki
trooper skirt ($36). On him: Cotton hooded jacket with adjustable
cuff, double-entry sleeve pocket and drawstring hem ($64), cotton
pants with cargo pockets, adjustable side tab, button-through cargo
pockets and kick-pleat hem ($39). All from American Eagle
Outfitters. Photographed at the downtown fountain in Troy.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO B: KIDS IN LINE FOR POPCORN
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . Try not to hold up the people behind you by lingering
over the decision of what to eat.'' _ From Amy Vanderbilt Complete
Book of Etiquette by Nancy Tuckerman and Nancy Dunnan
</P>
<P>
   SNACK TIME: From left, multicolored striped wool sweater ($69)
and red corduroy pants ($49) by Esprit, olive moleskin shirt by DCC
($29.99), white crewneck long-sleeved knit top ($14.99), chinotwill
flare pant by l.e.i. ($27.99), red ribbed top by Anxiety ($19.99),
khaki corduroy skirt ($39). On him: denim jacket ($59.99),
Silvertab long-sleeved T-shirt ($16.99), Silvertab crew jeans
($39.99), all by Levi's from Elder-Beerman. Photographed at the
Mayflower Theater in Troy, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO C: KIDS AT MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to the movies in some theaters is like going to the zoo.
There is so much talking and hooting, so much popcorn flying, so
much soda spilling down the aisles, you wonder why you bothered.
Tempting as it may be, don't talk to the person you're with. Clean
up your refuse at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Amy Vanderbilt Complete Book of Etiquette by Nancy Tuckerman
and Nancy Dunnan
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE PRESENTATION: (Back row, left to right) Stretch sweater
($38) and khaki pant ($44); paprika varsity sweater ($44), low-rise
khaki cords ($38), brown slip-on shoe with elastic inserts ($49).
(Front row) On her: amber track and field 3/4-sleeve T-shirt ($29),
putty journey vest ($42) and camel-colored squadron pants ($42). On
him: khaki expedition sweater ($48) and workwear utility jeans
($38). All from American Eagle Outfitters.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO 4: KIDS AT COFFEE SHOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional rule that the man always pays has been
replaced by greater equality. In general, however, when it comes to
a first date, the person who issues the invitation picks up the
tab.'' _ From Etiquette for Dummies by Sue Fox
</P>
<P>
   COFFEE BREAK: On him: blue/gray reversible vest ($34.99),
sweater ($34.99) and black relaxed foil jeans ($34.99). All from
Union Bay. On her: pleather pants ($27.99), black and silver knit
top ($19.99), from ILU. All from Elder Beerman. Photographed at
Winan's Chocolates and Coffee House in Troy.
</P>
