<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1692 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GATECH-FRIEDGEN08     08-24 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-FRIEDGEN0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aide in name only
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As his tenure as graduate assistant wound down at
Maryland in 1972, Ralph Friedgen looked for a job as a football
coach. He sent out more than 100 letters to colleges and another 40
to high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first letter I got back was from (Alabama coach) Bear
Bryant,'' said Friedgen, Georgia Tech's offensive coordinator. ``He
turned me down. He said he already had too many coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar replies followed. In fact, he was rejected across the
board.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the Maryland assistants, a guy named Bobby Ross, was
interviewing for the top job at The Citadel. ``Bobby told me he
thought he had a good chance at The Citadel job and said if he got
it he wanted me to come as the offensive coordinator. I told him,
`Let's wait and see if you get it, and then we'll talk.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen was making $150 a month when Ross called him in, along
with fellow graduate assistant coach Frank Beamer, and offered both
jobs as full-time coaches at The Citadel.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer eventually became head coach at Virginia Tech, the Yellow
Jackets' opponent Sunday. Meanwhile, Friedgen has held assistant
jobs with William &AMP; Mary, Murray State, Maryland, Georgia Tech, the
San Diego Chargers and Georgia Tech again.
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen is considered one of the top offensive football minds
in the country. Last year, he won the Broyles Award as the nation's
top assistant. He won it for directing the NCAA's most prolific
offense, as Tech led the nation with 509 yards per game and scored
40.7 points.
</P>
<P>
   No other college assistant can match his salary of more than
$200,000. He has achieved the rare double of directing offenses for
a college national champion, Tech in 1990, and a Super Bowl
participant, San Diego in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   So, why hasn't Friedgen been hired as a head coach, particularly
in this high-pressure, win-at-all-costs age of college football?f+t
</P>
<P>
   f-t ``Ralph is caught in a time when people are going with
flashy, movie-star images who are good with the media,'' Tech
running backs coach Bill O'Brien said. ``They don't look at
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen is a man of substance, both intellectually and
physically. In this day of sound bites and slick, Armani-suited
coaches with $200 coiffures, Friedgen doesn't fit the mold.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if Friedgen might get his dream job and go back to
his alma mater, Maryland, in 1997 after the Terps fired Mark
Duffner. In fact, Friedgen was set up for a telephone interview
with athletics director Debbie Yow and the Maryland search
committee when the announcement came that Ron Vanderlinden, a
Northwestern assistant for Gary Barnett, had been hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bitter at the time,'' Friedgen says now. ``I'm not
bitter anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary is amazed that Friedgen isn't
a head coach. ``I hope he has the opportunity,'' he said. ``Ralph
and I are so much alike. It's scary how much we think alike.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary and Friedgen have been friends since Friedgen was Ross'
assistant at Maryland and O'Leary was an assistant at Syracuse.
They first met on the road recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a bigger per diem out on the road, so I used to buy him
lunch,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen is more than just an offensive coordinator, O'Leary
said. The two confer on virtually all aspects of the game. ``He's
detailed beyond belief,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been studying his offensive system and playing in it for
three years,'' said Jon Muyres, Tech's starting flanker. ``You
could take any class at Tech for three years and you could master
it, but not Coach Friedgen's offense.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said: ``He took something from all the offenses he's
ever run _ the wishbone, split-backs, the `I' formation, two-backs,
one-back, no-backs_ and incorporated them. He's the most
knowledgable coach I've ever been around. . . . He's a professor of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen and his wife Gloria recently bought some property on
Lake Oconee, close to O'Leary and Beamer, and started building
their dream house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pulling out all the stops,'' Friedgen said. ``Isn't the
way it usually goes, as soon as you build a house, you get another
job?''
</P>
<P>
   You got the feeling he wasn't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
