A1693 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HURRICANE-DEBBY0825-C     08-24 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-DEBBY0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    u B7D1AD97Little Debby valuable as `teaching tool'
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Think of the late, unlamented Hurricane Debby
as a test.
</P>
<P>
   Not a fierce enough threat to galvanize emergency operations
into full alert, activate evacuations or force the temporary
shutdown of South Florida civilization.
</P>
<P>
   But keen enough to persuade procrastinators to buy batteries,
bottled water and plywood and to prompt emergency managers to begin
planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd keep everything that's not perishable,'' said Palm Beach
County Emergency Management Director Bill O'Brien. ``We're still
moving into the height of the hurricane season.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead of hunkering down with cans of cold soup behind
aluminum shutters while 100 mph winds test roof construction, South
Florida residents will endure just another late summer weekend of
temperatures in the upper 80s and lower 90s, sweat-inducing
humidity and a good chance of afternoon thunderstorms Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Those storms won't be Debby's doing. ``There's no longer
anything such as Debby and any remnants will be south of Cuba and
far from us,'' said meteorologist Tom Warner of the National
Weather Service in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   There's little chance that the storm, now a mere tropical wave,
can revive itself because of the same high level southwest winds
that sheared it apart as it tried to cross the Windward Passage
from Hispaniola to Cuba Wednesday night and Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   If Debby had been stronger then, it may have moved northwest
along the north coast of Cuba and become a threat to South Florida.
But the high terrain of Hispaniola had already begun shredding the
thunderstorms from the low level center, said hurricane specialist
Robert Pasch of the National Hurricane Center. Low easterly winds
pushed it south of Cuba instead.
</P>
<P>
   The north coast track was the official forecast but several
computer models predicted the move south of the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't totally pleased with our track models,'' Pasch
said. ``As I look at the errors in our (computer) predictions, they
are about average. But average is still not good when the storm
comes so close to millions of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm caused some flash flooding in mountainous Haiti but
eastern Cuba welcomed the rain. One man died in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Keys officials cancelled an evacuation of non-residents
early Thursday, but school will remain closed today because many
teachers evacuated. State and national parks re-opened Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dry run like this is a good teaching tool'' for emergency
officials, O'Brien said. ``It enhances the level of professionalism
because most of the people involved are not full-time emergency
management people. They get a better understanding of the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Debby's threat raises public awareness, Pasch said. ``We really
hope it made people think about their vulnerability and what they
need to do when a storm approaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
