<P>
   BILINGUAL-AMERICA _ CHICAGO _ ``Welcome. We speak Spanish,''
said the sign in Spanish beckoning customers to get a haircut at a
suburban Chicago salon. But somewhere along the way, former
employees allege, the Regis Hairstylist Salon decided that Spanish
spoken among employees made its English-speaking customers
uncomfortable. The sign disappeared and employees were ordered to
speak only English. Several hairstylists allege that they lost
their jobs for speaking their native tongue. As immigrants from
non-English-speaking countries flow into the United States,
businesses and institutions increasingly face a foreign-language
test: How best to cope with new workers and new customers whose
first language is not English. (Holmes, Cox News Service) WITH
PHOTOS.
