<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COTTON-PICKING-FRAUD0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Farmer buries cotton picking machine to claim insurance money
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A 58-year-old South Georgia farmer has been charged
with burying his cotton picker _ a 20-foot-high, multi-ton piece of
machinery _ to collect insurance on it.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Donald Keene of Abbeville reported his cotton picker
missing in February, according to the GBI. Cotton States Insurance
executive Tom Bengtson said the company paid $95,000 on Keene's
claim.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, unnamed informants spotted patches of John Deere
green peeking through a hillside on Keene's son's farm, said Gary
Rothwell, agent in charge of the GBI's Perry office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They reported it to Wilcox County Sheriff Stacy Bloodworth,
and he asked us to investigate,'' Rothwell said. The sheriff is
related to Keene.
</P>
<P>
   Rothwell said agents are investigating Kenne's finances.
</P>
<P>
   The farmer, charged with filing a fraudulent insurance claim and
making false statements, was free on bond Thursday. The GBI and
Cotton States had the machine exhumed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Rothwell said agents believe heavy equipment was used to bury
the machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was on a slope,'' Rothwell said. ``He dug out a cavern,
drove the thing in and covered it up. The keys were still in the
ignition.''
</P>
<P>
   New cotton pickers cost $200,000 to $250,000, according to an
agent for John Deere farm equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Bengtson said Keene's cotton picker was ``several years old,''
and he did not know how much the company could salvage from it. It
was severely damaged by its long interment.
</P>
<P>
   The burial of a massive piece of farm equipment, Rothwell said,
is new in his experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually in cases of insurance fraud,'' he said, ``they burn
the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
