<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1699 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-KINGS25-COX     08-24 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He's the `King' behind the curtain
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to catch Chet Brewster's name in the credits of the
hit movie ``The Original Kings of Comedy,'' try not to blink.
</P>
<P>
   And although the 36-year-old Lithonia resident briefly appears
on-screen with comedian Steve Harvey, his cameo probably won't make
him a household name.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't faze Brewster, who served as technical supervisor
on ``Kings'' and for the past three years was director of the
wildly successful traveling stand-up comedy stage show on which the
movie is based.
</P>
<P>
   While the comics kept the audience in stitches, Brewster was in
charge of keeping the freewheeling show from coming apart at the
seams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the man behind the curtain,'' he explains. ``When
something goes wrong, I was the first person everybody looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with four R-rated comedians, Brewster's job required him
to act as the unseen straight man: cueing the music when pleasingly
plump Cedric ``The Entertainer'' dances onstage, or getting a
close-up of a bug-eyed Bernie Mac poking fun at an outrageously
dressed audience member.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike typical comedy shows consisting of a guy with a
microphone telling jokes, Brewster's stage production used multiple
cameras and huge screens, turning it into a high-tech event. It
felt intimate even when it played sold-out venues as large as
Atlanta's Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I did the show, no matter where you were in the arena,
everybody had a good seat,'' Brewster says. ``Basically, I took a
comedy show and turned it into a rock concert.''
</P>
<P>
   So when MTV Films, Paramount and show creator Walter Latham
agreed to take ``Kings'' to movie theaters, Brewster figured he'd
be a shoo-in as director. Instead he got spiked, as in Spike Lee,
the Oscar-nominated director who eventually got the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt Chet is very good at what he does,'' says
Latham, who produced the film. ``But we needed someone with a lot
more prestige and a lot more experience.'' (``Kings'' was shot in
February during concert performances in Charlotte.)
</P>
<P>
   Brewster, who worked closely with Lee on the set, says he wasn't
soured by the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a strange feeling after working on the show for so
long, but I understand why they wanted Spike's name attached to it.
I wish they had given me the opportunity, but Spike was really
cool. Working with him was a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the success of the recent ``Kings'' concert tour and
movie (in metro Atlanta last weekend, ``Kings'' earned twice as
much at the box office as the nation's No. 1 film, ``The Cell''),
producer Latham says he's planning a sequel called ``The Kings and
Queens of Comedy.'' It's a traveling stage show that's expected to
come to Atlanta this fall. When it does, Brewster says he plans to
be there, working quietly in the background, as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind being a small fish in a big pond,'' he says.
``And it's a great job. Even though I've heard some of the jokes
thousands of times, working with these comedians still cracks me
up.''
</P>
<P>
   f+bTHE CHET BREWSTER FILEf-b
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  f+bAge:f-b 36.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  f+bResidence:f-b Lithonia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  f+bHometown:f-b Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  f+bMarital status:f-b Engaged.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  f+bEducation:f-b Emerson College.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  f+bCareer:f-b After college graduation, landed an entry-level
job at CNN. Later formed his own production company, DavenStar. Has
done music videos and stage productions with artists ranging from
Puff Daddy to Bachman Turner Overdrive. Has also shot an unreleased
movie with comedian Richard Pryor that mixes live action and
animation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
