<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-CREW-WISEGUYS0825-COX     08-24 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREW-WISEGUYS0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    u B5CCB505Wise guys deliver consistent comedy in `The Crew'
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Move over, ``Space Cowboys,'' there's a new
quartet of senior wise guys in town.
</P>
<P>
   Literally ``wise guys'' in this case, for the foursome of
Michael Dinner's ``The Crew'' are aged lower echelon New Jersey
mobsters. Now reduced to sitting out their sunset days on the porch
of their South Beach old age home, they reminisce as they watch the
suddenly trendy area get yuppified around them.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they will find themselves drawn into one last caper, but
otherwise this spry, smart-mouthed comedy is fresh, funny and
surprisingly savvy about the eccentricities of South Florida. In
fact, former ``Golden Girls'' staff writer Barry Fanaro's script
brings to mind the regional nuttiness of an Elmore Leonard or a
Carl Hiaasen novel, in which all roads lead to the local, inept
underworld.
</P>
<P>
   When Joey ``Bats'' Pistella (Burt Reynolds), Mike ``The Brick''
Donatelli (Dan Hedaya), Tony ``Mouth'' Donato (Seymour Cassel) and
Bobby ``No Nickname'' Bartellemeo (Richard Dreyfuss) fake a murder
in the lobby of their retirement hotel, it is just their bad luck
that the corpse they steal from the morgue was the father of a
vindictive Hispanic drug lord. From there, the problems escalate.
</P>
<P>
   They are then forced by a buxom hooker named Ferris (Jennifer
Tilly) to fake another killing. The would-be victim, Ferris's
stepmother, turns out to be Pepper Lowenstein (Lainie Kazan) of Sol
and Pepper, proprietors of Miami Beach's Rascal House deli. (As
Pepper used to say in commercials, with her best trophy wife
delivery, ``Slice the lox, Sol, I want to go shopping.'')
Complicating matters further is homicide detective Olivia Neal
(Carrie-Anne Moss), who Bobby suspects is the daughter he abandoned
30 years ago for mob life.
</P>
<P>
   As you may recall with a wince, Reynolds also was in
``Striptease,'' the only Hiaasen yarn to be filmed so far. His
appearance here subliminally links the two movies and underscores
how much ``The Crew'' gets it right, from the depressingly dingy
condo bingo night to the young vultures and real estate yentas
circling to grab any dead geezer's South Beach digs to the early
bird lineup at the Rascal House. In one of Dinner's better
directorial flourishes, he takes us through the deli's kitchen and
halls, a witty spoof of ``Goodfellas'' sweep into the Copacabana.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner, whose work has mainly been in television, underscores
the early character introductions with cheap freeze-frame punch
lines, but he soon eases into the movie's wry, winning tone. Most
impressively, he juggles his sizeable ensemble cast, getting vivid,
quirky performances without letting any one actor dominate.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds plays a hot-tempered bully, embarrassed to be working
at Burger King and stubbornly unwilling to let customers have it
their way. Since his best schemes come to him when he is
unconscious, he periodically has to be knocked out for inspiration
to strike. Baby Boomer Dreyfuss is disconcertingly convincing as a
senior citizen, Hedaya scores with his trademark gruff, dumb
delivery and Cassel (who hails from the early days of independent
filmmaking with John Cassavetes) lends a twinkle to the obligatory
over-the-hill Romeo _ the equivalent of ``Space Cowboys'' Donald
Sutherland.
</P>
<P>
   Moss is underutilized, but projects a soft, sympathetic quality
that contrasts nicely with her hard-edged, break-out showcase in
``The Matrix.'' Jewelry-clad Kazan and Wonderbra-ed Tilly are both
cast strictly to type, but they add the right grace and graceless
notes in support.
</P>
<P>
   The most puzzling part of ``The Crew'' is its generic title,
which gives no sense of the offbeat comedy or the sun-baked South
Florida flavor. It has nothing to do with a rowing team or a
close-cropped haircut, but everything to do with an hour-and-a-half
of laughs.
</P>
<P>
   THE CREW
</P>
<P>
   3 stars
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG-13: Language, drug smuggling, gunplay
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 38 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Cuddly, quirky South Florida comedy of
senior-division ``Sopranos'' pulling off one more job and swiping
plenty of laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
