<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-24 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COLO-BEAR0825-COX     08-24 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-BEAR0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baby bear goes to town
 &HT;    By Gary Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Small lots, narrow streets, scraggly
trees, children playing in the streets, swing-shift-working dads
and stay-at-home moms, Wal-Mart in walking distance _ sure enough,
it's bear country.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least it was was on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A yearling black bear sow claimed the territory for her own that
day, only to be rudely chased about by a passel of police officers
and a brace of wildlife officers. To say nothing of a pack of
onlookers, may of them who knew the Grand Valley had been invaded
by many bears this summer, at least 18 in all so far.
</P>
<P>
   The bear was first spotted just east of Wal-Mart about 10 a.m. A
police dispatcher cracked that there must have been a special on
honey.
</P>
<P>
   Police technician Paula Bockman was one of the first to get a
good look at the bear as it loped west across the Wal-Mart lot and
into a stand of scrubby elm barely 20 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was adorable,'' Bockman said.
</P>
<P>
   The bear lingered only a short time, though, in the patchy
shade.
</P>
<P>
   Word crackled out from dispatch that the bear was on the move,
this time heading west.
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove its claim to legitimate residency, the bear
ducked into the open door of Crown Liquors, said Grand Junction
Police Lt. Mike Nordine. Apparently finding nothing to its taste,
it crossed the street and made back to the east, passing by an auto
parts store and a Chinese restaurant. The bear found itself a
comfortable watching place in the shade of a line of slender elm
trees stretching 150 yards or so and settled in.
</P>
<P>
   With trees behind and an open field in front, the bear had a
commanding view of its territory _ tiny, but indisputably its own.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, company arrived. Police officers, onlookers and
experts watched the bear with a mixture of awe, sympathy and
healthy respect. The bear watched back.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle Sidener, district wildlife manager for the Colorado
Division of Wildlife, parked about 75 yards away and studied the
bear.
</P>
<P>
   She was, Sidener estimated, a yearling that would go about 100
pounds. That was an estimate, he cautioned, saying, not for the
only time, ``It's not a perfect science.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bear seemed to be in good shape, especially in
comparison to the 18 bears so far this summer that have been
tranquilized between and replaced in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   The bear's mother recently booted it out to fend for itself,
Sidener said, and that probably was the first of several cuffings
the yearling received as it crossed other bears' territories in
search of a place it could call its own.
</P>
<P>
   A late freeze and a dry spring and summer left precious little
food in the high country, forcing bears to cover larger territories
and leaving less room for newcomers, such as this one, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad year to be a bear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Much as he might wish to leave it alone, this bear had already
crossed the street on at least three occasions, which suggested a
traffic hazard at the least, Sidener said.
</P>
<P>
   A hazard in town, and at a severe disadvantage in its normal
territory, the bear was out of place most everywhere, Sidener said.
</P>
<P>
   Sidener sent for a tranquilizer kit and gun _ which looks like a
super-hyped paintball weapon _ and settled in to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Looking like a stump sticking out of the grasses _ albeit one
with rounded ears _ the bear seemingly glowed in the sun. Part of
the glow, Sidener said, was the light tips on the bear's fur. ``It
almost looks like he got a bad dye job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When his tranquilizer gun arrived, Sidener prepared for what he
least wanted _ a shot at a bear on the ground. The drug could take
anywhere from five to 20 minutes to take effect and a bear on the
ground could cover a lot of territory in that time. He eyeballed
the bear to determine how much sleeping agent to inject and noted,
``It's not a perfect science.''
</P>
<P>
   With no trees capable of holding a yearling bear, Sidener had to
risk a shot at the bear on the ground. He took one shot from about
30 yards, to apparent effect, but the bear never drifted into
unconsciousness. The shot, it turned out, missed.
</P>
<P>
   As Sidener approached for a second shot, the bear suddenly
bounded up and ran east, into a thicket of elm and weeds. Police
and the wildlife officers followed behind, trying to turn it back
with shouts and handclaps.
</P>
<P>
   The bear made for the backlot of Grand Junction Nursery, filled
with trees and plants.
</P>
<P>
   From within the greenery, officers could only rely on shouted
instructions and glimpses of their quarry, as well as other humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a bear in there with you,'' called one to a nursery
employee. ``You might want to head in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've got to get this done,'' came the response.
</P>
<P>
   The bear turned to the north and bounded ahead, climbing an
8-foot fence in almost simian fashion and crossing another empty
lot before disappearing into the urban wilds.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, elementary school children were called in from the
playground as the bear rambled around his realm.
</P>
<P>
   Sidener and the officers retired back to their vehicles for a
road hunt _ one that lasted only minutes before the bear was
spotted again.
</P>
<P>
   Nordine was the first to arrive where the bear was treed in the
back yard of James and Susan Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Otis, a 2-year-old chocolate Labrador, did what dozens of
two-legged pursuers couldn't _ forced the bear into a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Otis ``nearly treed me,'' Nordine said.
</P>
<P>
   Perched above roofline in the weeping willow, the bear attracted
a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my gosh, how cute,'' said Shawna Mangum, who saw the bear
dash through her back yard and followed it to the neighbors'.
</P>
<P>
   The urban safari moved towards its end when Sidener pumped a
dart into the bear's backside 32 feet above the ground. Once shot,
the bear lurched to the top of the tree, where it clung.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officers, neighbors and passersby were recruited to
catch the bear in a tarp before it struck the wooden deck.
</P>
<P>
   A play-by-play rang out as the bear lost consciousness. ``He's
holding on by two paws. Now just the one. Now!''
</P>
<P>
   The bear tumbled down from the crown of the tree, crashed
against a limb and then hit with a heavy thud in the tarp, where
she was quickly gathered up and carried off.
</P>
<P>
   The bear was tagged and was to be relocated to the mountains
near Silt or on the Uncompahgre Plateau, Sidener said.
</P>
<P>
   In reasonably good health, Sidener said, the female wasn't as
heavy as he had anticipated, maybe 75-80 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he said, ``It's not a perfect science.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
