<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH0825-COX     08-24 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's tough on crime stance conflicts with record
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In 1994, when he was a baseball executive
running for governor, George W. Bush led off his television
campaign with an ad that hit hard on crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last three years 7,700 criminals have been released
early from prison,'' Bush said then. ``I will end early release of
criminals and end parole altogether for rapists and child
molesters.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years later _ as a governor running for president _ that
approach could come back to haunt Bush as state prisons near
capacity and his parole officials are issuing more and more
get-out-of-jail-early cards.
</P>
<P>
   With parole rates inching higher during Bush's presidential
campaign, the stakes could be huge. One high-profile crime by one
parolee can change the outcome of an election.
</P>
<P>
   f+b f-bAt Al Gore headquarters in Nashville, there was a swift
effort to make political hay out of the parole rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises questions in the minds of voters as to why
Governor Bush has been mostly silent about what he would do to
ensure the safety of American families,'' said Gore spokesman Jano
Cabrera. ``Governor Bush has tried to deflect attention from his
gun lobby-like record and has been mostly silent on what, if
anything, he would do on crime as president.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Bush campaign worked to separate parole and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a state function and the proper role of the Board of
Pardons and Paroles to address parole, with the public's safety
being a paramount concern,'' said Bush campaign spokesman Ray
Sullivan. ``The governor's appointees to the parole board have a
history of careful deliberation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has talked about crime on the campaign trail, but his web
site _ which includes his positions on 19 issues _ includes nothing
about crime.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, criminal justice experts say, politics and
parole would be as mixable as oil and water.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an area that should be taken out of the political
realm,'' said D'Ann Johnson, executive director of the Texas
Criminal Defense Lawyers Association. ``The executive branch ought
to be able to make a case-by-case determination based on the facts
presented to them about whether a person is ready for release.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the real world _ especially in a real-hot political year
_ politics and parole are as linked as Michael Dukakis and Willie
Horton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets back to the political situation,'' said criminal
justice professor Raymond Teske at Sam Houston State University.
``It looks good to say, `We are not paroling people and I'm the guy
that's keeping them in there.'''
</P>
<P>
   For years, that's been the approach for Bush, a politician whose
family is well-acquainted with crime as campaign issue. In 1988, a
group supporting the elder Bush for president scored heavily with a
TV ad detailing the 1986 weekend furlough of convicted
Massachusetts murderer Willie Horton, who fled to Maryland where he
abducted a couple and raped a woman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis _ the elder Bush's
1988 presidential opponent _ vetoed a bill that would have ended
the weekend furloughs.
</P>
<P>
   For current presidential candidate Bush, the worst-case scenario
would be anything resembling a repeat of the Horton case. Odds
against it seem good. Almost all the inmates now being paroled are
non-violent offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Hubbarth, a vice president of Justice for All, a crime
victims' group, said Thursday he is not concerned about the
increasing parole rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Parole Board Chairman) Gerald Garrett has done an
incredibly good job of allaying people's fears about the streets
being prowled by released predators,'' said Hubbarth, a former
assistant general counsel for the parole division.
</P>
<P>
   Current polls show a national electorate concerned about crime,
but not as much as it is concerned about other issues. A Portrait
of America poll conducted last week showed crime tied for sixth,
with Social Security and taxes, among the issues of concern to
voters. Sixty-seven percent of the respondents said crime is a
``very important'' issue, making it one of 12 issues deemed very
important by 60 percent or more of the respondents.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by Rasmussen Research, included responses
from 4,208 likely voters. The margin of error is four percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   For many voters, concern about crime translates into calls for
longer prison sentences for offenders. Criminal justice Professor
Teske said the increased parole rate in Texas is the inevitable
result of that mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They overreacted to the situation,'' he said of politicians
like Bush who responded to the tough-on-crime call. ``Now they are
in a bind again. And now they've got to let them out. They don't
want to, but they have to because they don't have room for them.
It's going to have to happen. They have to be selective about it
and people shouldn't blame (Bush) or anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when he was a candidate for governor, Bush was not shy
about assigning blame for increasing parole rates. One of his
can't-miss quips along the campaign trail involved a story, perhaps
apocryphal, about a young girl's curiousity about wanted posters in
a police station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't you keep them when you took their pictures?'' Bush
said the girl asked.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
