<HEADER>
A1705 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SPRINT0825-COX     08-24 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Sprint wireless tool to link e-mail, Net, company networks
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sprint on Thursday trotted out a new service aimed
mainly at wooing companies that want their mobile employees to have
access to e-mail, the Internet and corporate networks back in the
office.
</P>
<P>
   While sure to be challenged by rivals, Sprint means to help
shape the future of wireless tools, leaping ahead of the pack by
packaging functions now found on a personal digital assistant, a
pager and a phone, said Jay Highley, Sprint vice president. ``We
think we are 12 or 18 months ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Other wireless Net phones aren't capable of slipping a user
through a company's ``firewall'' to plug into the internal
corporate network from anywhere, he said. ``The world has been
looking for the wireless data killer app (application), and the
killer app is e-mail _ or anything behind the corporate firewall.''
</P>
<P>
   To make that connection, a user can plug the phone into a
laptop. Or the user can slide a small metallic card into the
computer. That card, which costs $400, is a wireless modem.
</P>
<P>
   Once phone and modem are purchased, a user can for about $65 a
month have both phone and card _ and two phone numbers _ permitting
a phone conversation while linking to company networks or the
Internet. But the phone itself can also link to the Net, sending
e-mail and updating addresses and appointments _ on a much smaller
screen with a touch-sensitive keypad.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is widely believed to be behind Japan and
Europe in wireless data. But in both places _ especially with NTT
DoCoMo in Japan _ the service is pitched to consumers with a
heavier accent on games and e-mail than on corporate uses.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint service, available in September, is an aggressive
push toward business customers, employers of an estimated 47
million people who often work outside the office.
</P>
<P>
   To lasso that market, Sprint hopes to take advantage of the
desire to centralize purchasing and simplify billing. For instance,
time used on all a company's phones can be pooled and counted
toward whatever total the company is paying for. Sprint also
expects companies to consolidate buying decisions about wireless,
something often left now to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals can be counted on to point out some vulnerabilities in
the service. For one thing, a user's use of wireless data will be
billed per minute, like a phone conversation. Also, the service may
seem sluggish to anyone accustomed to a truly high-speed connection
from a desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's new service is technically only a little faster than
its current 9.6 kilobits-per-second connection. But software on
both network and phone strips away some graphics to make the link
seem like 56 kbps, as fast as the quickest dial-up modem.
</P>
<P>
   But even that is far slower than the high-speed connections of
many desktops. It's about half as fast as Metricom's Ricochet, the
wireless modem that provides a continuous connection to the Net for
laptops. That service was recently launched in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel and Southern LINC each have phones with e-mail capacity _
as well as an ``instant conferencing'' feature that connects
designated users immediately. And, of course, there are pagers that
send e-mail as well as various wireless phones from BellSouth,
Powertel and AT&AMP;T, which also has a national network. Some of these
services are cheaper than Sprint's.
</P>
<P>
   As for PDAs, like the Palm Pilot, they come with hundreds of
customized applications that Sprint cannot match. The newest Palms
also do e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   But Highley said Sprint has a better combination of features, as
well as a national plan that counts a minute in Atlanta the same as
in Spokane. A Palm cannot access corporate networks, he said. ``And
besides, you can't talk over it.''
</P>
<P>
