<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GASOLINE EDICTS SHARE BLAME FOR HIGH PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The next time some politico wants to grab
some headlines by initiating an investigation into gasoline price
spikes, we'd all be better served if the probe's focus was on
government rather than the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   Details of how federal and state meddling contributed
substantially to this summer's soaring gas prices have been
revealed in dribs and drabs, but it fell to a journal well outside
the media mainstream to do the most comprehensive reporting job yet
on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   An article in this month's edition of ``The Intellectual
Activist'' by Jack Wakeland is by far the best media effort to put
the gas price conspiracy in proper perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state controls, he explains, worked in tandem to
turn back the economic clock to the days before gasoline
standardization. The Illinois situation became a textbook example
of how badly consumers are served by ill-advised government policy.
</P>
<P>
   When the Environmental Protection Agency's reformulated-gas
mandate took effect, Illinois was divided into four pollution
control zones. Each required three different grades of
ethanol-blended gas. To further complicate matters, Illinois
mandated use of ethanol fuel additives, which are derived from
corn, instead of the cheaper ethanol-based oxygenate used in most
reformulated gas.
</P>
<P>
   Wakeland calls these ``boutique fuels'' and says if local
inventories run low they cannot be rebuilt by borrowing reserves
from other regions. Thus, when a pipeline supplying refineries
producing reformulated gasoline ruptured, it set in place the
events that caused the soaring prices.
</P>
<P>
   While Kansas City wasn't affected directly, the
market-distorting ripple effect from all the combined developments
no doubt contributed to the price shocks that occurred in this
area.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the resulting consumer woe, the article revealed, was
the cavalier way government officials ignored how their regulatory
mandates would cause prices to surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were a conspiracy ... the real conspirators would be
the EPA and the state of Illinois,'' Wakeland surmised. ``They
ordered the oil industry to produce 12 different gasoline blends,
specified the precise chemical composition of each, and dictated
exactly in which territories it may be sold _ and then blamed the
refiners for the astronomical costs of complying with these
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   While the alleged conspiracy by Big Oil is a figment of its
detractors' imagination, Wakeland notes that ``there is real
evidence for (the) anti-oil industry conspiracy. A memo from an
energy secretary aide warned that the reformulated gas rule was the
main culprit in the gas price spike, but EPA officials refused to
grant waivers for Chicago and Milwaukee areas, which were hit worst
by soaring prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as surging gas prices became big news, it's worth
remembering that many pols and bureaucrats began making noises in
the media implying that the oil industry greed was to blame for the
price gouging.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Wakeland says, Big Oil's critics offered no facts or
analysis to substantiate such claims. Instead they sold the idea
using the same methods others use to claim the world is really run
by a cabal of bankers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
