<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME OF WEEK GOING RETRO, AND THEN SOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Do not adjust your television set Saturday
morning. Fox has control of it. Sit back, learn and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   During the Dodgers-Cubs national telecast at 10 a.m. PDT from
Wrigley Field, Fox has what's called a ``Turn Back The Clock''
special presentation that may look more like Major League Baseball
meets ``The Twilight Zone.'' What it amounts to is an ingenious way
to illustrate how far technical advances have come in TV coverage
of the game over the last 60-plus years.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it'll also wake someone up into realizing that more isn't
always better.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 26, 1939, no more than 500 homes in New York had access
to the first televised baseball game between the Cincinnati Reds
and Brooklyn Dodgers from Ebbets Field. Behind the mike, Red Barber
flew solo _ Vin Scully was more than a decade away from starting
his career with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, a black-and-white production, with two
stationary cameras _ one on ground level behind home plate for a
majority of the pitcher-batter shots and another in the upper deck.
And they didn't even know if it was technically possible to switch
back and forth between the two live shots.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the Fox telecast will open Saturday, 61 years to the
date of that game _ one announcer (Joe Buck, from a small wooden
table behind home plate), two wide-angle cameras and no replays.
</P>
<P>
   With each half-inning, they'll add more equipment to represent
what changes were made in that decade. Tim McCarver won't join the
broadcast as the second voice until the top of the second (the
color man first was introduced in 1957), and an attempt at a color
picture will go in the bottom of the second (which came in '61).
</P>
<P>
   By the fifth inning, the game will be at full 21st Century tilt,
a 15-camera complement with microphones in the bases, catcher
camera and all the noisy graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Kinda makes you already yearn for the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a gimmick quality, but with a Game of the Week
telecast we can do something fun like this and honor some of the
people who've done the work over the years and show some of the
things we take for granted,'' said Keith Olbermann, Fox's baseball
studio host. Olbermann will introduce each half-inning time-frame
dressed in period clothes and, with Steve Lyons, discuss the news
headlines from that era.
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann added that, for his segment, he steps into an
egg-shaped time capsule _ the company rented the one used in the
movie ``Austin Powers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just too bad that they couldn't find a way to incorporate
Scully into this time warp.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION OF THE WEEK: If it's called the Kickoff Classic,
signifying the kickoff to the college football season, why does it
come a day after the Pigskin Classic?
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who promote the Pigskin found out that the Kickoff
worked (coming first),'' said ABC's Keith Jackson. ``It's money.''
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, both games are sponsored by the National
Association of Collegiate Directors of Athletics and benefit the
College Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   For our benefit, Jackson will call the USC-Penn State Kickoff
contest only because he happens to be in New York for network
meetings and Brent Musburger is busy this weekend doing the Little
League World Series. Otherwise, Jackson, starting his 48th season,
will remain a West Coast entity for the network this season as per
his agreement to drop plans for retirement two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find as the years pile up I grow more lazy,'' said the
almost 72-year-old who spent part of his summer vacation hauling in
175 pounds of halibut and 102 pounds of salmon from British
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind saying that come Sunday night, I'll probably be
bone dog tired since I haven't done a game since last fall. When
you're my age, it's hard to concentrate for eight or nine hours on
a broadcast like this.''
</P>
<P>
   NO STATIC CLING: There will be no discernable changes in the
weekday lineup for all-sports KXTA-AM (1150), even though the
station has access to the entire new Fox Sports Radio Network that
launches Monday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Premiere Radio Networks boss Kraig Kitchin, whose
Sherman Oaks, Calif.-based company works with Fox on this endeavor,
1150 needs to find a new program director and get through some red
tape from a pending company merger before any decisions are made on
what content the station will use.
</P>
<P>
   He did confirm that by the middle of next month, the new flashy
studios will be ready near the corner of Sepulveda and Ventura,
where anyone walking by can watch the ensuing show hijinx, kind of
like NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bruno, who did some fill-in afternoon hosting on 1150 prior
to the Fox launch, will host the first show for the network from 5
to 9 a.m. PDT. For obvious reasons, 1150 should pick up his show
and immediately drop the ``Bob and Tom'' syndicated fiasco out of
Indianapolis, which former 1150 program director Mike Thompson
not-so-privately despised.
</P>
<P>
   One of the interesting twists to this new network is that Bill
Pugh, who runs the affiliate XTRA-AM (690) in San Diego, has been
an important sounding board for Premiere and Fox. Pugh's brother,
Dan Patrick (not his real name), is the cornerstone to the rival
ESPN Radio network. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
-- The same time ESPN's Chris Berman and Dan Patrick make the cover
story of the newest issue of Dads magazine, NBC's Bob Costas had
his image consultants allow him to be interviewed in the October
issue of Playboy. Berman and Patrick talk about what it's like to
be a high-profile sports dad. Costas rips on John Tesh for his
network performance on doing gymnastics at the 1996 Summer
Olympics. ``I think most reasonable people would say that, at
times, the gymnastics coverage was beyond parody,'' says Costas.
``He's a talented guy, but, oh man, those gymnastics.'' &QL; 
-- For ABC's coverage Saturday of the Little League World Series
title game, Orel Hershiser has been added as an analyst. Wouldn't
hurt if he tried to boost his confidence a bit by pitching some
batting practice to the tykes. But then again ... &QL; 
-- Documentary don't misses: ESPN's two-parter on a Pennsylvania
high school football team's pursuit of the 1999 state title
(produced by New York Times Television company), airs Monday (5 to
6:30 p.m. PDT) and Tuesday (5 to 6 p.m. PDT), and The History
Channel's two-hour production called ``Gridiron Generals: A
Hard-Hitting History of College Football,'' airing Monday at 9 p.m.
PDT. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
-- Did ya see the promo running on the FX Channel for new episodes
of the Howard Stern-produced ``Son Of The Beach'' sit-com? There's
one of a surfing competition with a shot of huge waves crashing
that gets the announcer to exclaim: ``Look at that set'' _ just as
a well-endowed bikini-clad babe walks in front of him. Get it? Oh,
the announcer in question is only Fox's clean-cut, do-it-all Bill
Macdonald. Oh, (ital)now(endital) we get it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tom Hoffarth can be reached at (818) 713-3661 or
tomhoffarthdailynews.com. &QL;
</P>
