<SLUG> BC-RAVIANT-CAPITAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAVIANT NETWORKS ATTRACTS $55 MILLION IN VENTURE CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ An Overland Park company that works with
telephone companies and Internet service providers to update their
telecommunications networks has received $55 million in venture
capital from two East Coast firms.
</P>
<P>
   The cash infusion will allow Raviant Networks to hire up to 75
engineers, project developers and other employees this year; move
into new offices in Leawood; and build a state-of-the-art
telecommunications laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The venture capital investment is one of the largest ever in a
Kansas City, Mo., area company. It brings total capital investment
in area companies to more than $223 million in the first eight
months of 2000 _ eclipsing last year's record of $143 million.
</P>
<P>
   Raviant Networks, which changed its name from Integrated Network
Solutions Inc., until recently was based in Cedar Rapids, Iowa. The
company has moved its focus from equipment provider to specialist
in telecommunications network design and consulting, concentrating
on the integration of voice and data networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our real momentum was coming from telecommunications
services,'' said Matt Cullen, chief executive of Raviant. ``Our new
identity reflects transformation, not only within our company but
throughout the telecommunications industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Raviant now has 74 employees, most in Kansas City, with small
offices in North Carolina, Texas and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Raviant works with telephone companies, Internet service
providers and large corporations to help them integrate new
broadband technologies into existing networks. The company's
clients include Sprint Corp., WorldCom Inc. and Birch Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   The company specializes in packet switched networks, which
transmit voices and data along the same path in high-speed bursts,
using network capacity more efficiently than traditional circuit
switching. Circuit switching opens up a dedicated circuit between
callers for the duration of a call.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to packet switching gives companies an opportunity to
offer new services _ and generate more revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows them to deploy a whole set of next-generation
services, some of which haven't even been thought of yet,'' Cullen
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's the hottest segment in the telecommunications market, and
finding financing to move the company forward wasn't difficult,
Cullen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money flow in this area is still solid,'' Cullen said.
``We had firms virtually begging us to take money from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Raviant has grown from $2 million in revenue in 1997 to more
than $30 million in 1999. Cullen projected growth of 10 percent to
20 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the launch of its new corporate name, Raviant is
leasing a 22,000-square-foot headquarters in Leawood, Kan. The new
office will include the Raviant Encubator, a telecommunications
technology laboratory where customers can design, build and test
complex network equipment before it's used in a company's own
network.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen said the facility also will be used to work with start-up
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for opportunities to work with early-stage
companies,'' he said. ``The difference between huge success and
rampant failure is time to market, and we can help with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The venture capital came from Apollo Management and Crest
Communications Holdings, both venture firms based in New York. Each
invested $27.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Mockenhaupt, a managing director for Crest, said the
investment was one of the venture firm's largest to date.
</P>
<P>
   Crest was attracted to Raviant because of the company's
diversity, Mockenhaupt said. Raviant has staff members who have
both ``science-type expertise and a quality-of-service attitude
that the telco world has,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
