<HEADLINE>
AVAX COMPLETES ACQUISITION OF FRENCH BIOTECHNOLOGY FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Avax Technologies Inc., a Kansas City
biotechnology company, said Thursday that it had completed its
acquisition of Genopoietic SA, a privately held French
biotechnology firm.
</P>
<P>
   Avax said it also had acquired from Pierre et Marie Curie
University the rights to university patents covering Genopoietic's
technologies and retained Genopoietic's exclusive agreement with
the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very excited to close this important transaction with a
company that we believe is at the forefront of cell and gene
research and development,'' said Jeffrey M. Jonas, president and
chief executive officer of Avax.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of this transaction, we are now a company with
operations on three continents, with one commercialized product,
and a pipeline rich with cell and gene therapies in various stages
of clinical development.''
</P>
<P>
   Avax is working on cancer treatments that use a patient's own
cancer cells. It reached a milestone recently when its M-Vax
vaccine for melanoma was made available for use in Australia, the
first country to which it has been brought to market.
</P>
<P>
   Avax is publicly traded and is listed under the ticker symbol
AVXT.
</P>
<P>
   Genopoietic specializes in the research and development of cell
and gene therapy aimed at cancer, autoimmune diseases and
orthopedics.
</P>
<P>
   Financial details of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
</TEXT>
