<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETSALES-RESTRUCTURE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETSALES LAYS OFF NEARLY ONE-THIRD OF ITS EMPLOYEES, SELLS UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ In a major corporate restructuring,
Overland Park-based NetSales Inc. on Thursday laid off almost a
third of its employees and sold off its software e-commerce
business.
</P>
<P>
   The moves come as the 5-year-old Internet company shifts its
focus to the business-to-business Internet market, where it builds
and maintains marketplace Web sites for midsize manufacturers and
distributors, said Robert Fraser, the company's founder.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Fraser is stepping down as chief executive of
NetSales to focus on planning and public relations. Jeff Reene,
NetSales' president, who left Cerner Corp. in 1999 to join the
company, will take on the added role of chief executive, Fraser
said.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials declined to be specific about the number of
people laid off but said it involved more than 60 employees.
Employees were told Thursday afternoon, and some employees said
more than 70 persons were laid off.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales previously had about 240 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet company signed a deal Thursday to sell its
software//technology sales division to Eden Prairie, Minn.-based
Digital River Inc. The two companies had been competitors in the
e-commerce market, where both built Web sites for e-commerce and
software companies.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, which included NetSales' portfolio of more than 500
software publishing clients, was an all-stock transaction valued at
about $6 million, based on the closing price Thursday of Digital
River stock.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales' comparatively new business-to-business division is
growing rapidly, and the company was losing focus, Fraser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford to have two businesses that are very different
and very distinct. B2B is the market we've chosen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating almost a third of the company he spent five years
building was a difficult decision, Fraser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of friends I'm saying goodbye to today.
These are all very good and, for the most part, highly skilled
people,'' he said. ``But with the sale of the business, there was
nothing else we could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those laid off were in sales, customer service,
operations and support, Fraser said.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser said the decision to step down as chief executive was
``recognition of what has already happened. I haven't been focused
on day-to-day operations for six to nine months. It makes sense to
have a single person at the helm.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser started NetSales in 1995, working with three employees.
The business plan then was to sell advertising to software
companies from a company-owned software review Web site.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales refocused in 1997, building and operating e-commerce
Web sites for small and midsize companies. At one time, the company
operated more than 1,600 storefronts on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser had hoped that working with publishers to allow consumers
to buy and download software on the Internet would allow the
company to expand even more rapidly. The market, which Digital
River dominates, hasn't developed as rapidly as expected.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales moved into the business-to-business market earlier this
year after receiving $32 million in venture capital from a
coalition that included Time Warner and two of the nation's largest
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser said NetSales is expecting a ``flood'' of new corporate
customers as a result of partnerships with Cisco Systems, Chase
Manhattan Corp. and Wells Fargo &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about one word: focus,'' Fraser said. ``NetSales
has succeeded because of that one thing, focus.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's focus now will be on what Fraser calls
e-marketplaces _ Web sites where corporations in the $100 million
to $1 billion range can sell to their customers online. NetSales
builds and maintains the site, charging $20,000 to $200,000 per
site, plus a transaction fee.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales last week unveiled a product that allows corporate
marketplaces to interact with large online marketplaces that can
include thousands of corporate buyers and sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The business-to-business market, where companies do business
with their suppliers and customers online, is expected to grow to
more than $1 trillion in less than 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing tremendous demand for B2B e-business solutions,
particularly among the midmarket supplier companies that NetSales
targets,'' said David Grossman, an analyst at Thomas Weisel
Partners. ``These companies want to participate in the e-commerce
boom and are looking for strategic partners like NetSales to take
them online in a way that makes business and financial sense.''
</P>
<P>
   For Digital River, the opportunity to purchase the NetSales
division was another sign of the consolidation taking place in the
Internet marketplace. The company has 7,500 clients in its
portfolio, and picking up a competitor will help the company grow,
said Al Galgano, vice president of investor relations for Digital
River.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice addition to the portfolio,'' Galgano said of the
purchase. ``We're very happy with the quality of the clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Digital River, publicly traded on Nasdaq, hit $43 a
share in December before falling to less than $6 a share this
month. The stock, traded under the symbol DRIV, closed unchanged at
$6 a share Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital River has been a fierce competitor of ours,'' Fraser
said. ``But we found we cannot afford to have even a great side
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-00 2349EDT &QL; 
