<SLUG> BC-BOEING-STOCK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING SEES RESURGENCE AMONG INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _
</P>
<P>
   PAUL NYHAN
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing Co. is enjoying a resurgence among investors, its
shares surging to a 28-month high Thursday and gaining more than 8
percent in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering through a succession of production problems and
a 40-day engineering strike, the company's stock is making a
significant recovery. And there are plenty of reasons, from a
healthy aircraft market, and a successful satellite launch, to an
improving defense sector and a generally healthy U.S. stock market,
financial analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are increasingly comfortable with the notion that
Boeing is working as a turnaround story,'' said Heidi Wood, who
tracks Boeing for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``It is sort of a
compounding of several events.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those events is a stronger-than-expected demand for new
airplanes. Together, Boeing and rival Airbus have landed almost 600
orders in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   During the next few years, Boeing is expected to produce roughly
500 airplanes a year, according to a report from Peter Jacobs at
Ragen MacKenzie Group Inc. While, the rate is down from last year's
record of 620 aircraft, it still represents a healthy pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is generally a more optimistic outlook for the
company as a whole as long as the company can continue to post the
improvement in earnings as most investors are expecting,'' Jacobs
said.
</P>
<P>
   Only two days ago, Boeing burnished its image by putting a Delta
3 rocket into orbit from Cape Canaveral, Fla. The company had
failed in two previous attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing isn't the only aerospace or defense concern posting
strong gains on Wall Street. Bellevue-based Esterline Technologies
Corp. shares rose 56 cents, or 3.5 percent, in trading Thursday to
close at $16.50. Aircraft supplier B.F. Goodrich Co. shares rose
$1.94 to close at $41.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing shares rose $3.06, or 6.06 percent, in trading Thursday,
closing at $53.62 in one of the stock's best days in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Some defense firms are also performing well in the financial
markets, which is good news for Boeing since it's the nation's
second-largest defense contractor, according to some financial
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest defense contractor, Lockheed Martin Corp.
rose slightly, 6 cents, in trading Thursday to close at $28.44.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Standard &AMP; Poor's Aerospace and Defense Index rose
25.17 points Thursday to close at 1,210.85.
</P>
<P>
   Only five months ago, Boeing was saddled with a stock price in
the 30s and a slowdown in airplane deliveries as executives
struggled to settle a 40-day strike by engineers and technicians.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also made great strides in improving its
once-troubled commercial airplanes division. In 1997, Boeing
attempted to boost production to record levels and created major
problems within its commercial operations.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also managed to rebound from a more recent loss.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, Boeing shares fell $2.25, or 4.55 percent, to
close at $47.25 after Boeing announced it would acquire aviation
data company Jeppesen Sanderson Inc. for $1.5 billion in cash. Some
observers worried about the price.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of review, investors appear more comfortable with
the purchase and with Boeing, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in Boeing's stock price came too late for some Boeing
employees this year. The vast majority of Boeing workers would have
received stock payouts if the company's average stock price had
traded at roughly $49 on June 30, under a special trust program.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, employees will have another opportunity on
June 30, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial analysts say Boeing's stock performance could
continue, while adding the usual caveats about the unpredictability
of the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Ragen MacKenzie's Jacobs has pegged Boeing shares with a
18-month to two-year price target between $68 and $82.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is also in the market with a continuing stock buyback
program, according to on financial analyst.
</P>
<P>
   While Boeing offered its investors strong returns this week, the
company also broke through a symbolic barrier, according to Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting through the $50 dollar barrier was kind of a big
psychological hurdle for some investors,'' Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   Information from Bloomberg News was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
