<SLUG> BC-BKW-LIBERTY-COMETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY FOLLOWS SCRIPT THAT'S TOO FAMILIAR
</HEADLINE>
  By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With 4 minutes 4 seconds to play in the opening game of the WNBA
finals Thursday night, the momentum and the whole history of the
league began to turn on its heels.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after four years of fighting the legend that is the
Houston Comets, the only champions the league has ever had, the New
York Liberty seemed poised to bring Houston down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty had climbed back within four points of the Comets in
the opener of the best-of-three series, the only game that will be
played in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the sellout crowd of 19,563 hoping for an upset,
Teresa Weatherspoon made two foul shots with 52.3 seconds remaining
to pull the Liberty to within 52-50. But history and talent were
just too much of a burden to overcome at the end, and the Comets
hung on for a 59-52 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The series resumes Saturday afternoon in Houston. If it does not
end then, a third and deciding game will be played there Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston's three-year reign, the WNBA championships have had
only one most valuable player: Cynthia Cooper. She played that way
again Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   With 26.4 seconds left in the game, Cooper drove through the
lane and banked in a layup, drawing a foul. She then made the free
throw to give Houston a 55-50 lead, and sealed the victory by
sinking two foul shots with 14.1 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Tari Phillips could not do it alone Thursday night for the
Liberty. She had 24 points and sparked the second-half comeback,
but no one else on the Liberty scored in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper had 20 points, and Tina Thompson added 15. Sheryl Swoopes
also scored 12 for the Comets.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
