<HEADLINE>
LAZIO DISTANCES HIMSELF FROM BUSH TAX CUT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick Lazio moved to distance himself from
Gov. George W. Bush's tax cut plan Thursday, offering his own
package of business and personal tax reductions that by his
campaign's calculation is nearly 40 percent smaller than the one
Bush has made a cornerstone of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's proposal for the use of a projected $4.4 trillion,
10-year surplus, which he outlined in a speech at the Chamber of
Commerce here, includes a call to allow taxpayers to deduct the
payroll tax from their federal income taxes, much the way state and
property taxes are now treated. His plan would affect the payroll
tax that finances the Social Security Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said that proposal, combined with a menu of tax cuts long
advocated by congressional Republicans _ like eliminating the
inheritance tax and the so-called marriage penalty _ would save the
average New York family about $3,000 a year in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed permitting parents to put aside up to $500,
free of tax, to pay for primary and secondary education in private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that the surplus ultimately belongs to the American
people is not conservative or liberal, it's not even Republican or
Democrat _ it's just common sense,'' said Lazio, the Republican
candidate for Senate. ``And if I'm senator, New Yorkers will get to
keep more of what they earn. My opponent believes there's no room
in a $4.4 trillion surplus for meaningful tax relief for New York
families. I believe simple fairness demands that we give taxpayers
a break.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's speech came in a week in which Bush has found himself
defending the fiscal prudence of his $1.3 trillion, 10-year tax
cut, in the face of attacks by Democrats and polling data
suggesting that the idea has not stirred much interest from voters.
And in New York, his opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, has
repeatedly sought to link Lazio to Republican tax cut proposals
that she has said are too broad and has described as a threat to
the nation's future prosperity. Lazio's response suggested some
concern in his campaign about that line of attack.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-minute speech by Lazio, of Suffolk County, signaled, as
well, a coming-to-life of a campaign that has been somewhat dormant
for much of the summer. One of Lazio's advisers said that he had
intentionally kept a low profile while campaigning in order to
raise money, give himself time to become acquainted with issues and
in the belief that he benefited from keeping attention off himself
and on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With Labor Day, the traditional start of the general election
campaign, less than 10 days away, Lazio is now moving into a new,
higher-profile phase of his campaign; Thursday's speech was the
first in what aides said would be a series of addresses intended to
flesh out his political portrait.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to invoking an issue that Republicans have seized on
in election after election over the past two decades _ tax cuts _
Lazio Thursday seemed to be making a definite effort to move away
from Bush's tax cut plan, if not the Republican presidential
candidate himself.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign press release put the cost of Lazio's tax cut at $776
billion over the next 10 years. ``By comparison,'' Lazio's campaign
said, ``George W. Bush's tax plan would cost $1.3 trillion over 10
years, and Al Gore's tax plan would cost around $500 billion over
10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lazio, in a news conference, was notably cool to Bush's tax
plan, which his opponent Clinton has repeatedly criticized as
excessive. ``I am comfortable with the plan that I have laid out
right now, in terms of raw size, the macro number,'' Lazio said.
``I'm going to keep my options open on what Gov. Bush's proposal is
until we see what kind of revenues come in next year. I just prefer
to make sure that we have a restrained approach that will allow a
pay-down of the debt, will allow us to invest in the prescription
benefit and will give us the ability to have some enhanced
investment in education at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers moved to tether Lazio to Bush's economic
policies. They asserted that his estimate of the cost of his tax
cut was grossly understated _ they put it at $1.24 trillion over 10
years _ and said it would hurt the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Lazio offers New Yorkers yet another reckless
trillion-dollar tax plan that simply doesn't hold up,'' said Howard
Wolfson, a spokesman for Clinton's campaign. ``The Republican tax
program would return us to the days of irresponsible budgets,
ballooning deficits, and high interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed a far more modest plan of tax reductions
that would total $496 billion, her aides said Thursday. They would
include a reduction, rather than elimination, of the marriage
penalty and inheritance tax, and tax credits for such things as
college tuition. She said that the nation's surplus first should be
used to pay down the country's debt and to shore up Social
Security.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The centerpiece, and most unusual aspect, of Lazio's plan was to
allow taxpayers to deduct the payroll tax from their federal income
taxes. Such proposals have been raised in Congress before, but
usually discarded, both because they would be hugely expensive and
would offer more of a benefit to wealthier taxpayers in
higher-income tax brackets.
</P>
<P>
   The payroll tax affected, the one that finances the Social
Security fund, is 6.2 percent this year for people on the first
$76,200 of income; employers put in another 6.2 percent. Lazio said
his proposal would cost the government $300 billion; Clinton's
aides put the figure at closer to $500 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Lazio's tax-reduction program is made up of a number
of more familiar Republican initiatives. Lazio called for cutting
the capital gains tax from 20 percent to 15 percent, increasing
allowable IRA contributions to $5,000 from $2,000, and eliminating
part of the tax on Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio used his speech Thursday to offer his own response to what
has been a political complication for Republicans running for
office this year: the state of the economy. Calling the country's
financial health ``a wave of economic prosperity unrivaled in human
history,'' the congressman disputed the Democrats' claims of credit
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lazio attributed the nation's economic well-being to,
among other things, tax cuts initiated by President Ronald Reagan
and actions by the Federal Reserve. And he reiterated his
opposition to the economic program pushed through by President
Clinton early in his presidency, which raised taxes to reduce the
nation's deficit. The president has repeatedly invoked that
legislation as a turning point.
</P>
</TEXT>
