<HEADLINE>
FORMER CHIEFS PLAYER CHARGED WITH WRITING BAD CHECKS TOTALING
$158,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE AND GLENN E. RICE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Jackson County prosecutors on Thursday
charged former Kansas City Chiefs player Andre Rison with four
felonies for writing $158,000 worth of bad checks to a Georgia
jeweler.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, Rison wrote the four checks between
June and December 1998 to pay for such things as a Rolex watch,
diamond jewelry and a $40,000 gold necklace with the word ``Dre'' _
Rison's nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Each count is punishable by up to five years and a $5,000 fine.
He was charged in Jackson County because the checks were drawn on a
Jackson County bank and some of the merchandise was delivered to
this area.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Rison are the latest in a series of recent
legal troubles he has faced. A week before the Chiefs unexpectedly
released him last week, police in River Falls, Wis., where the
Chiefs hold their training camp, cited Rison for allegedly giving
false information after a bar fight.
</P>
<P>
   Rison also faces legal problems in Johnson County, Kan., where
he has criminal and civil trials scheduled in September involving
allegations of felony theft and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   After his release by the Chiefs, Rison, 33, signed a contract
with the Oakland Raiders, a team that played Thursday night against
the Seattle Seahawks in Oakland. Rison could not be reached for
comment. Raiders officials declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Tucker, a friend of Rison who is his contract adviser,
suggested that the charges were largely the result of a
misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a lot of players do is write checks, and they don't know
whether the account is closed or not. Andre probably didn't,''
Tucker said. ``He does silly stuff sometimes, because he doesn't
pay attention to things like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any intent there,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird said Rison probably did not
know of the bad-check charges. Warrants were issued only for
Missouri and Kansas to avoid costly extradition from California,
Beaird said. He said he expected Rison to surrender in Jackson
County and post $10,000 bond within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does not surrender in a reasonable time,'' he said, ``we
will expand the warrant'' to include California.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four checks Rison allegedly wrote to Elif Fine
Jewelry of Decatur, Ga., were on Jackson County accounts that had
been closed, according to court records. Before joining the Chiefs,
Rison had played for the NFL's Falcons in nearby Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Aydin, the Georgia jeweler who told police he took the
checks from Rison, could not be reached for comment. After failing
to collect on the debt, officials said, Aydin notified authorities
in February.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said a representative from Elif had indicated that Rison
had agreed to make payments over a period of time. Tucker said he
didn't know the specifics of the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had to be some agreement with the jewelry people,''
Tucker said. ``Nobody can walk in there and write a check like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Johnson County, a judge has entered a $200,000 civil judgment
against Rison in a case brought by one of his Leawood neighbors.
The neighbor said Rison had failed to repay money she lent him.
</P>
<P>
   An additional claim of fraud in the woman's lawsuit is to go to
trial Sept. 18 in Johnson County District Court, according to the
woman's attorney, Tom McGraw.
</P>
<P>
   A criminal charge of felony theft is also pending against Rison
in Johnson County, involving recording equipment he rented from an
Overland Park, Kan., business and allegedly never returned.
</P>
<P>
   That case is set for trial Sept. 25, although Rison's attorney
has filed a request to withdraw from that case. A hearing on that
request is set for Aug. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
